ABACUS.d: A table or tray scattered with sand which was used for calculating or drawing.
ABACUS.e: From Late Middle English abacus, abagus, agabus (“abacus; art of counting with an abacus”), from Latin abacus, abax (“sideboard or table with a slab at the top; slab at the top of a column; counting board, sand table; board for playing games”) (compare Late Latin abacus (“art of ...

ABATIS.d: A means of defense formed by felled trees, or sometimes by bent trees, the ends of whose branches are sharpened and directed outwards, or against the enemy, and more recently fortified with barbed wire.
ABATIS.e: From French abatis, abattis (“mass of things beaten or cut down”), from abattre. See abate.

ABBACY.d: The dignity, estate, term, or jurisdiction of an abbot or abbess.
ABBACY.e: From Middle English abbathie, from Late Latin abbātia, from abbās, abbātis (“abbot”). Doublet of abbey and Opatija.

ABBESS.d: A female superior or governess of a nunnery, or convent of nuns, having the same authority over the nuns which the abbots have over the monks.
ABBESS.e: From Middle English abbesse, from Old French abeesse (French abbesse), from Late Latin or Ecclesiastical Latin abbatissa, feminine of Latin abbas, abbatis (“abbot”).

ABDUCT.d: To take away by force; to carry away (a human being) wrongfully and usually with violence or deception; to kidnap.
ABDUCT.e:
From Latin abductus, perfect passive participle of abduco (“to lead away”), from ab (“away”) + duco (“to lead”).
* (physiology): Back-formation from abduction.

ABJECT.d: Existing in or sunk to a low condition, position, or state; contemptible, despicable, miserable.
ABJECT.e:
PIE word
 *h₂epó
The adjective is derived from Late Middle English abiect, abject (adjective) [and other forms], from Middle French abject (modern French abject, abjet (obsolete)), and from its etymon Latin abiectus (“abandoned; cast aside”), an adjective use of the perfect passi...

ABJURE.d: To solemnly reject (someone or something); to abandon (someone or something) forever; to disavow, to disclaim, to repudiate.
ABJURE.e: From Late Middle English abjuren (“to give up (something); to recant or renounce (something) under oath”), from Anglo-Norman abjurer, Middle French abiurer, abjurer, and Old French abjurer (“to reject or renounce (something) on oath”) (modern French abjurer), and from their etymo...

ABLATE.d: To remove or decrease something by cutting, erosion, melting, evaporation, or vaporization.
ABLATE.e: From Middle English ablat (“taken away”), from Latin ablātus, past participle of auferō (“to remove”), see -ate (verb-forming suffix). First attested in the 1500s, it became obsolete by the early 1600s. Returned into use as a back-formation from ablation.

ABLAUT.d: The substitution of one root vowel for another, thus indicating a corresponding modification of use or meaning; vowel permutation, distinct from the phonetic influence of a succeeding vowel.
ABLAUT.e: Borrowed from German Ablaut (“sound gradation”), which is from ab- or ab (“down, off”), + Laut (“sound”). Ab is used here in the sense of “deviating, varying” as in Abgott (“god other than the true God”), Abart (“different sort, variety, anomality”).

ABOUND.d: To be full to overflowing; to bristle.
ABOUND.e:
* First attested around 1325.
* From Middle English abounden, abounde, from Old French abonder, abunder, from Latin abundāre (“overflow”), which comes from ab (“from, down from”) + undō (“surge, swell, rise in waves, move in waves”), from unda (“wave”).

ABOUTS.d: Plural of ABOUT: On the subject of; concerning.
ABOUTS.e: From Middle English aboute, from Old English onbūtan, from on + būtan (outside of).

ABOVES.d: Plural of ABOVE: In or to a higher place.
ABOVES.e: From Middle English above, from Old English abufan, onbufan.

ABRADE.d: To rub or wear off; erode.
ABRADE.e: From Latin abrādō (“scrape off”), from ab (“from, away from”) + rādō (“scrape”). First attested in 1677.

ABRUPT.e: First attested in 1583. Borrowed from Latin abruptus (“broken off”), perfect passive participle of abrumpō (“break off”), formed from ab (“from, away from”) + rumpō (“to break”).

ABSEIL.d: To descend a steep or vertical drop using a rope with a mechanical friction device or (classic abseil) by wrapping the rope around the body; to rappel.
ABSEIL.e: From German abseilen, from ab- (“down”) + Seil (“rope”).

ABSENT.d: Being away from a place; withdrawn from a place; existing but not present; (sometimes) missing.
ABSENT.e: From Middle English absent, from Middle French absent, from Old French ausent, and their source, Latin absens, present participle of absum (“to be away from”), from ab (“away”) + sum (“to be”).

ABSORB.d: To include so that it no longer has separate existence; to overwhelm; to cause to disappear as if by swallowing up; to incorporate; to assimilate; to take in and use up.
ABSORB.e: From Middle French absorber, from Old French assorbir, from Latin absorbeō (“swallow up”), from ab- (“from”) + sorbeō (“suck in, swallow”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *srebʰ- (“to sip”). Compare French absorber.

ABSURD.d: Contrary to reason or propriety; obviously and flatly opposed to manifest truth; inconsistent with the plain dictates of common sense; logically contradictory; nonsensical; ridiculous; silly.
ABSURD.e: First attested in 1557. From Middle French absurde, from Latin absurdus (“incongruous, dissonant, out of tune”), from ab (“away from, out”) + surdus (“silent, deaf, dull-sounding”). Compare surd.

ABULIA.d: Absence of willpower or decisiveness, especially as a symptom of mental illness.
ABULIA.e: From New Latin abūlia, from Ancient Greek ἀβουλία (aboulía, “irresolution”), from ἀ- (a-, “without”) + βουλή (boulḗ, “will”).

ABUSED.d: Past tense of ABUSE: Improper treatment or usage; misuse.
ABUSED.e: From Old French abus, from Latin abūsus (misuse), from abūtor (misuse, consume).

ABUSES.d: Plural of ABUSE: Improper treatment or usage; misuse.
ABUSES.e: From Old French abus, from Latin abūsus (misuse), from abūtor (misuse, consume).

ACACIA.d: A shrub or tree of the tribe Acacieae.
ACACIA.e: From Latin acacia, from Ancient Greek ἀκακία (akakía, “shittah tree”), either from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱ- (“sharp”) (compare ἀκή (akḗ, “point”)) or more likely a Pre-Greek word. First attested before 1398. Doublet of cassie.

ACARID.d: Any parasitic arachnid, such as mites and ticks, of the subclass Acarina.
ACARID.e: Circa 19th century; from New Latin Acaridae (“biological family”), from Acarus (“genus”), from acarus (“mite”), from Ancient Greek ἄκαρι (ákari, “mite”). By surface analysis, acar- + -id

ACCEDE.d: To approach; to arrive, to come forward.
ACCEDE.e: First attested in the early 15th century. From Middle English acceden, from Latin accēdō (“approach, accede”), formed from ad (“to, toward, at”) + cēdō (“move, yield”) (English cede). Compare French accéder. Unrelated to ascend, aside from the common ad prefix.

ACCENT.d: A higher-pitched or stronger (louder or longer) articulation of a particular syllable of a word or phrase in order to distinguish it from the others or to emphasize it.
ACCENT.e: From Middle English accent, from Medieval Latin accentus and Old French accent, acent, both from Latin accentus, past participle of accinō (“sing to, sing along”). The word accent had been borrowed into Old English already, but was lost and reborrowed in Middle English.

ACCEPT.d: To receive, especially with a consent, with favour, or with approval.
ACCEPT.e: First attested about 1380. From Middle English accepten, borrowed from Old French accepter, or directly from Latin acceptō, acceptāre (“receive”), frequentative of accipiō, formed from ad- + capiō (“to take”). Displaced native Old English onfōn.

ACCESS.d: A way or means of approaching or entering; an entrance; a passage.
ACCESS.e: From Middle English accesse, acces, borrowed from Middle French acces (“attack, onslaught”) or from its source Latin accessus, perfect passive participle of accēdō (“approach; accede”), from ad (“to, toward, at”) + cēdō (“move, yield”). Doublet of accessus. First attested in the ...

ACCORD.d: Agreement or concurrence of opinion, will, or action.
ACCORD.e: From Middle English accord, from Old French acort, from acorder (see verb below).

ACCOST.d: To approach and speak to boldly or aggressively, as with a demand or request.
ACCOST.e: From Middle French accoster, acoster, from Old French acoster (“to stand beside”) (whence Medieval Latin accostare), from Old French a- + coste (“side, flank”).

ACCRUE.e: First attested in mid 15th century. From Middle English acrewen, borrowed from Old French acreüe, past participle of accreistre (“to increase”), from Latin accrēsco (“increase”), from ad (“in addition”) + crēscō (“to grow”).

ACCUSE.d: To find fault with, blame, censure.
ACCUSE.e: First attested around 1300. From Middle English acusen, from Old French acuser, from Latin accūsō (“to call to account, accuse”), from ad (“to”) + causa (“cause, lawsuit, reason”). Akin to cause. Displaced native English bewray.

ACEDIA.e: From Latin acēdia. Doublet of accidie.

ACETYL.d: The univalent radical CH₃CO- derived from acetic acid.
ACETYL.e: From Latin acētum (“vinegar”) + Ancient Greek ὕλη (húlē, “substance”).

ACHENE.d: A small, dry, indehiscent fruit, containing a single seed, as in the buttercup.
ACHENE.e: From French achène and its source, New Latin achena, from Ancient Greek ἀ- (a-, “a-”) + χαίνω (khaínō, “to gape”).

ACHIER.d: Comparative form of ACHY: Suffering from aches, sore.

ACHING.d: present participle and gerund of ache

ACINUS.d: One of the small grains or drupelets which make up some kinds of fruit, as the blackberry, raspberry, etc.
ACINUS.e: Unadapted borrowing from Latin acinus (“grape, grape-stone”); the histopathologic sense comes figuratively from the fancied resemblance (on microscopy) of acinic cells (acinar cells) to bunches of drupelets, berries, or grapes.

ACQUIT.d: To declare or find innocent or not guilty.
ACQUIT.e: From Middle English aquī̆ten (“to give in return; to pay, repay; to redeem (a pledge, security), to make good (a promise); to make amends; to relieve of an obligation; to acquit, clear of a charge; to free; to deprive of; to do one's part, acquit oneself; to act, behave (in a cer...

ACTANT.d: That which acts; a source of action or activity.
ACTANT.e: Simultaneously coined in English and French by Bruno Latour from action + -ant

ACTING.d: Present participle of ACT: Initialism of the Australian Capital Territory: a federal territory of Australia.

ACTION.d: The effort of performing or doing something.
ACTION.e: From Middle English accioun, accion, from Old French aucion, acciun, from Latin āctiō(n) (“act of doing or making”), from āct(us) + action suffix -iō(n), perfect passive participle of agere (“do, act”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵeti. See also act, active. By surfac...

ACTIVE.d: Having the power or quality of acting; causing change; communicating action or motion; acting;—opposed to passive, that receives.
ACTIVE.e: From Middle English actyf, from Old French actif, from Latin āctīv(us), from agere (“to do, to act”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵeti. By surface analysis, act + -ive.

ACTORS.d: Plural of ACTOR: A person who performs in plays, films, or television.
ACTORS.e: From Latin āctor (doer), from agere (to do, act).

ACTUAL.d: relating to a person's acts or deeds; active, practical
ACTUAL.e: From Middle English actual, actuel (“active”), from Anglo-Norman actuel, actual, and its source Late Latin actuālis (“active, practical”), from Latin actus (“act, action, performance”), from agere (“to do; to act”) + -alis (“-al”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵeti, fr...

ACUITY.d: Sharpness or acuteness, as of a needle, wit, etc.
ACUITY.e: From Middle English acuite, acuyte, from Middle French acuité, from Medieval Latin acuitas, irreg., from Latin acuō (“sharpen”).

ACUMEN.d: Quickness of perception or discernment; penetration of mind; the faculty of nice discrimination; acuity of mind.

ADAGIO.d: A tempo mark directing that a passage is to be played rather slowly, leisurely and gracefully.

ADDEND.d: Addendum, any one of two or more numbers or other terms that are to be added together.
ADDEND.e: Short for addendum, by surface analysis, add + -end.

ADDICT.d: A person who is addicted, especially to a harmful drug.
ADDICT.e: Borrowed from Latin addictus, past participle of addīcō (“deliver; devote; surrender”), from ad- (“to, towards, at”) + dīcō (“say; declare”)

ADDUCE.d: To bring forward or offer, as an argument, passage, or consideration which bears on a statement or case; to cite; to allege.
ADDUCE.e: From Middle English adducen, from Latin addūcere, adductum (“to lead or bring to”), from ad- + dūcere (“to lead”). See duke, and compare adduct.

ADDUCT.d: To draw towards a center or a middle line.
ADDUCT.e: Borrowed from Latin adductus, past participle of adduco. See adduce.

ADHERE.d: To stick fast or cleave, as a glutinous substance does; to become joined or united.
ADHERE.e: From Middle English *adheren (suggested by Middle English adherande (“adhering, adherent”, present participle)), from Latin adhaerēre, adhaesum: ad (“to”) + haerēre (“to stick”). Compare French adhérer.

ADJOIN.d: To be in contact or connection with.
ADJOIN.e: From Anglo-Norman adjoindre, from Latin adiungō.

ADJURE.e: From Middle English adjuren, from Latin adiūrō (“beg earnestly”), from ad- (“near, at; towards, to”)' + iūrō (“swear by oath”).

ADJUST.e: From Middle English ajusten, borrowed from Middle French adjuster, or Old French, from Latin ad (“to, up to, towards”) + iustus (“correct, proper, exact”); Equivalent to ad- + just. Probably influenced in sense by Old French ajouster (cf. modern ajouter), from Vulgar Latin *adiux...

ADMASS.d: That part of society that is influenced by mass media advertising.
ADMASS.e: From ad + mass, coined by British novelist J. B. Priestley.

ADMIRE.d: To be amazed at; to view with surprise; to marvel at.
ADMIRE.e: From Middle English admyren, borrowed from Middle French admirer, from Latin admīror, from ad + mīror (“wonder at”).

ADMITS.d: Plural of ADMIT: To allow entry; to confess to be true.
ADMITS.e: From Latin admittere (to send to, let in).

ADOPTS.d: Plural of ADOPT: To legally take another's child as one's own.
ADOPTS.e: From Latin adoptāre (to choose for oneself).

ADROIT.e: Borrowed from French adroit, from French à (“on the; to”) (from Old French a (“to; towards”), from Latin ad (“to; towards”), from Proto-Indo-European *ád (“at; near”)) + French droit (“right”) (from Old French droit, dreit, from Late Latin drictus, syncopated form of Latin dīrect...

ADSORB.d: To accumulate on a surface, by adsorption.
ADSORB.e: From French adsorber, from Latin ad- (“to”) + sorbeō (“suck in”).

ADULTS.d: Plural of ADULT: A fully grown person or animal.
ADULTS.e: From Latin adultus, past participle of adolēre (to grow up).

ADVENT.d: Arrival; onset; a time when something first comes or appears; the time when it is approaching.

ADVERB.d: A word that modifies a verb, adjective, other adverbs, or various other types of words, phrases, or clauses.
ADVERB.e: From French adverbe, from Latin adverbium, from ad- (“to”) + verbum (“word, verb”), so called because it is used to supplement other words. By surface analysis, ad- + verb.

ADVICE.d: An opinion offered to guide behavior in an effort to be helpful.
ADVICE.e:
From Middle English avys, from Old French avis, from the phrase ce m'est a vis ("in my view"), where vis is from Latin visus, past participle of videre (“to see”). See vision, and compare avise, advise. The unhistoric -d- was introduced in English 15c. Doublet of aviso.
Mostly di...

ADVISE.d: To give advice to; to offer an opinion to, as worthy or expedient to be followed.
ADVISE.e: From Middle English avisen (“to perceive, consider, inform”), from Old French aviser, from avis, or from Late Latin advisō, from ad + visō, from Latin videō (“to see”), visum (“past participle of videō”). See also advice.

ADWARE.d: A software application that includes advertisements, which are displayed while the software is running. Developers use adware as a source of income and to keep the costs of the software down (usually making it free). Some adware programs can include spyware.

ADYTUM.d: The innermost sanctuary or shrine in a temple, from where oracles were given.
ADYTUM.e: Borrowed from Latin adytum, from Ancient Greek ἄδυτον (áduton, “innermost sanctuary; shrine”), inflected form of ἄδυτος (ádutos, “not to be entered”).

AEDILE.d: An elected official who was responsible for the maintenance of public buildings, regulation of festivals, supervision of markets and the supply of grain and water.

AERATE.d: To supply with oxygen or air.
AERATE.e: From Latin aer (“air”) + -ate. Compare French aérer.

AERIAL.d: Living or taking place in the air.
AERIAL.e: From Latin āeri(us) + -al, from Ancient Greek ἀέριος (aérios), from ἀήρ (aḗr, “air”) + -ιος (-ios). By surface analysis, aer- (“air”) + -ial.

AEROBE.d: Any organism (but especially a bacterium) that can tolerate the presence of oxygen, or that needs oxygen to survive.
AEROBE.e: From French aérobie. By surface analysis, aero- + -obe.

AFFAIR.d: Something which is done or is to be done; business of any kind, commercial, professional, or public.
AFFAIR.e: From Middle English afere, affere, from Old French afaire, from a- + faire (“to do”), from Latin ad- + facere (“to do”). See fact, and compare ado.

AFFECT.e: From Middle English affecten, from Latin affectāre, from Latin affectus, the participle stem of Latin afficere (“to act upon, influence, affect, attack with disease”), from ad- + facere (“to make, do”).

AFFINE.d: Assigning finite values to finite quantities.

AFFIRM.d: To agree, verify or concur; to answer positively.
AFFIRM.e: From Middle English affermen, from Old French afermer, affermer, from Latin affirmare, adfirmare (“to present as fixed, aver, affirm”), from ad (“to”) + firmare (“to make firm”), from firmus (“firm”).

AFFLUX.e: From Latin affluĕre, affluxum. See affluent.

AFFORD.d: To incur, stand, or bear without serious detriment, as an act which might under other circumstances be injurious; (usually after an expression of ability, as could, able, difficult) to be able or rich enough; to spare.
AFFORD.e: From Middle English afforthen, aforthen, avorthien, from earlier iforthen, iforthien, ȝeforthien, from Old English forþian, ġeforþian (“to further, accomplish, afford”), from Proto-Germanic *furþōną, from Proto-Germanic *furþą (“forth, forward”), equivalent to a- + forth. Cognate...

AFFRAY.d: To startle from quiet; to alarm.
AFFRAY.e:
From Middle English affraien (“to terrify, frighten”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman afrayer (“to terrify, disquiet, disturb”) and Old French effreer, esfreer (“to disturb, remove the peace from”) (compare modern French effrayer), from Vulgar Latin *exfridāre.
The second part of thi...

AFGHAN.d: A native or inhabitant of Afghanistan; a person of Afghan citizenship or nationality and their descendants.
AFGHAN.e: Borrowed from Classical Persian افغان (afġān, “Afghan”), from Bactrian αβαγανο (abagano), first attested in the fourth century CE, most likely a compound of *apāka- (“distant, faraway”), from Proto-Iranian *Hápa, from Proto-Indo-Iranian *Hápa (“away”), from Proto-Indo-European *h...

AFRAID.d: Impressed with fear or apprehension; in fear.
AFRAID.e: From Middle English affrayed, affraied, past participle of afraien (“to affray”), from Anglo-Norman afrayer (“to terrify, disquiet, disturb”), from Old French effreer, esfreer (“to disturb, remove the peace from”), from es- (“out”) + freer (“to secure, secure the peace”), from Fr...

AFTERS.d: Plural of AFTER: Following in time or place.

AGARIC.d: Any of various fungi, principally of the order Agaricales, having fruiting bodies consisting of umbrella-like caps, on stalks, with numerous gills beneath.
AGARIC.e: From Latin agaricum, from Ancient Greek ἀγαρικόν (agarikón, “a tree fungus (Phellinus pomaceus”)), from the country of Agaria, in Sarmatia.

AGEISM.d: The treating of a person or people, especially older people, differently from others based on assumptions, prejudices or/and stereotypes relating to their age.
AGEISM.e: From age + -ism. Coined by American academic Robert N. Butler in 1969.

AGEIST.d: Unfairly discriminatory against someone based on their age.

AGENCY.d: The capacity, condition, or state of acting or of exerting power.
AGENCY.e: From Medieval Latin agentia, from Latin agēns (present participle of agere (“to act”)), agentis (cognate with French agence, see also agent).

AGENDA.d: A temporally organized plan for matters to be attended to.
AGENDA.e: From Latin agenda (“things that ought to be done”), future passive participle (gerundive) of agō (“I do, act, make”).

AGHAST.d: Terrified; struck with amazement; showing signs of terror or horror.
AGHAST.e: From Middle English agast, agasted, past participle of agasten (“to terrify”), from Old English a- (compare with Gothic 𐌿𐍃- (us-), German er-, originally meaning "out") + gæstan (“to terrify, torment”): compare Gothic 𐌿𐍃𐌲𐌰𐌹𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽 (usgaisjan, “to terrify”, literally “to fix, to root...

AGNAIL.d: Torn skin near a toenail or fingernail.
AGNAIL.e: From Middle English agnail, from Old English angnægl, from ang- + nægl, from Proto-Germanic *naglaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃nogʰ-.

AGNATE.d: A relative whose relation is traced only through male members of the family.
AGNATE.e: Learned borrowing from Latin agnātus (“paternal kinsman”).

AGOUTI.d: A rodent of the genus Dasyprocta, similar in appearance to a guinea pig but having longer legs, mainly native to Central and South America.
AGOUTI.e: From French agouti, from Old Tupi akuti. The name of the acouchi is probably from the same source.

AGREES.d: Plural of AGREE: To have the same opinion; to consent.
AGREES.e: From Old French agreer (to receive with favor).

AHIMSA.d: A doctrine of non-violence, concerned with the sacredness of all living things and an effort to avoid causing harm to them.

AIDING.d: Present participle of AIDE: An assistant.
AIDING.e: Borrowed from French aide ("aid; assistant", as in aide-de-camp (“field assistant”)). More at aid.

AIKIDO.d: A Japanese martial art developed from jujitsu and making use of holds and throws.
AIKIDO.e: Borrowed from Japanese 合(あい)気(き)道(どう) (aikidō, “aikido”, literally “way of adapting the spirit”), from 合(あい) (ai, “together, unify”) + 気(き) (ki, “spirit; breath”) + 道(どう) (dō, “way”). Doublet of hapkido.

AIMING.d: Present participle of AIM: The pointing of a weapon, as a gun, a dart, or an arrow, or object, in the line of direction with the object intended to be struck; the line of fire; the direction of anything, such as a spear, a blow, a discourse, a remark, towards a particular point or object, with a view to strike or affect it.
AIMING.e: The verb is from Middle English amen, aimen, eimen (“to guess at, to estimate, to aim”), borrowed from Old French esmer, aesmer, asmer, from Latin ad- plus aestimare (“to estimate”), the compound perhaps being originally formed in Medieval Latin (adaestimare), perhaps in Old Fren...

AINHUM.d: A painful constriction of the base of the fifth toe, frequently followed by autoamputation, occurring predominantly in black Africans and their descendants.

AIRBAG.d: A protective system in automobiles in which when a crash occurs, a bag containing nitrogen, formed by the explosive decomposition of sodium azide, quickly inflates in front of the driver or passenger, preventing injury to the head. Side air bags, including the back seat passengers, also prevent injury.

AIRBUS.d: A subsonic jet airliner, especially a wide-bodied one.

AIRIER.d: Comparative form of AIRY: Consisting of air.

AIRING.d: present participle and gerund of air

ALARMS.d: Plural of ALARM: A warning of danger.
ALARMS.e: From Old French alarme, from Italian all'arme (to arms!).

ALARUM.e: From Middle English alarom, from Old Italian all'arme (“to arms, to the weapons”), from Latin arma, armorum (“weapons”).

ALBEDO.d: The fraction of incident light or radiation reflected by a surface or body, commonly expressed as a percentage.

ALBERT.d: A male given name from the Germanic languages.
ALBERT.e: From Old English Æþelbeorht, from Proto-West Germanic *Aþalaberht, a compound of *aþalaz (“noble”) + *berhtaz (“bright, famous”), or from Old French Albert, from Latin Albertus, itself from the Germanic name. Regardless of the exact route, it is a doublet of Ethelbert. It became ...

ALBINO.d: Congenitally lacking melanin pigmentation in the skin, eyes, and hair or feathers (or more rarely only in the eyes); born with albinism.
ALBINO.e:
Borrowed from Portuguese albino and Spanish albino.
* Portuguese albino is from Medieval Latin albinus, from Latin albus
* Spanish albino is diminutive of albo, from Latin albus (“white”).

ALBITE.d: A plagioclase feldspar, the first member of the Albite-Anorthite solid solution series.
ALBITE.e: From Latin albus (“white”), the common color of the mineral, + -ite.

ALBUMS.d: Plural of ALBUM: A book for photographs or stamps; a collection of recordings.
ALBUMS.e: From Latin album (white tablet for public notices).

ALCAIC.d: Pertaining to Alcaeus, a Greek lyric poet of around 600 BC; especially, of a verse meter in a four-line stanza which he supposedly invented.
ALCAIC.e: From Latin Alcaicus, from Ancient Greek Ἀλκαϊκός (Alkaïkós), from Ἀλκαῖος (Alkaîos, “Alcaeus”) + -ικός (-ikós, “-ic”). By surface analysis, Alcaeus + -ic.

ALCOVE.d: A small recessed area set off from a larger room.
ALCOVE.e: From French alcôve, from Spanish alcoba or Portuguese alcova, from Arabic القُبَّة (al-qubba, “vault, chamber with vaulted roof”). Doublet of qubba.

ALDOSE.d: Any of a class of monosaccharides having an aldehyde or hemiacetal functional group.

ALDRIN.d: An insecticide and persistent organic pollutant containing a naphthalene-derived compound.
ALDRIN.e: From Alder + -in. Named after German chemist Kurt Alder (1902–1958).

ALEXIN.d: A protective substance that exists in the serum or other bodily fluid and is capable of killing microorganisms; complement.
ALEXIN.e: Ultimately from German Alexine, coined by Hans Buchner in 1891 from the Ancient Greek ἀλέξω (aléxō).

ALIENS.d: Plural of ALIEN: A foreigner; a being from another world.

ALIGHT.d: To make less heavy; to lighten; to alleviate, to relieve.
ALIGHT.e: From Middle English alighten (“to descend from a place: to dismount, get off; to descend to a place: to arrive or stop (at a place); to land; to drop; to attack; of lightning: to strike; to leap on to, mount; to descend in rank; to cause (someone) to lose rank; to come forth, spr...

ALIGNS.d: Plural of ALIGN: To arrange in a straight line.
ALIGNS.e: From French aligner, from à ligne (into line).

ALKALI.d: One of a class of caustic bases, such as soda, soda ash, caustic soda, potash, ammonia, and lithia, whose distinguishing characteristics are dissolving in alcohol and water, uniting with oils and fats to form soap, neutralizing and forming salts with acids, turning to brown several vegetable yellows, and changing reddened litmus to blue.
ALKALI.e: From French alcali, from Medieval Latin alcali, ultimately from Arabic اَلْقِلْي (al-qily, “alkali, ashes of the saltwort”), related to قَلَى (qalā, “to roast in a pan, fry”).

ALKANE.d: Any acyclic saturated hydrocarbon (methane, ethane, etc.).
ALKANE.e: From German Alkan, formed as alkyl + -ane.

ALKENE.d: An unsaturated, aliphatic hydrocarbon with one or more carbon–carbon double bonds.

ALLEGE.d: To state under oath, to plead.
ALLEGE.e: From Middle English aleggen, perhaps from Old French alleguer, or from Anglo-Norman aleger, the form perhaps from Old French esligier (“to acquit”), from Medieval Latin *exlītigāre (“to clear at law”), from Latin ex (“out”) + lītigō (“sue at law”), but the meaning from Old French...

ALLELE.d: One of a number of alternative forms of the same gene occupying a given position, or locus, on a chromosome.
ALLELE.e: Borrowed from German Allel, shortened from Allelomorph, from English allelomorph. Ultimately from the Ancient Greek prefix ἀλληλ- (allēl-) from ἄλλος (állos, “other”).

ALLIED.d: Past tense of ALLY: To unite or form a connection between (people or things), as between families by marriage, or between states by confederacy, league, or treaty.
ALLIED.e: From Middle English allien, alien (“to form an alliance, associate, join; to become an ally; to introduce (someone) as an ally; to marry; to become related (to someone); to attack, engage in combat; to combine; (cooking) to combine ingredients, especially to bind them together”) ...

ALLIES.d: Plural of ALLY: To unite or form a connection between (people or things), as between families by marriage, or between states by confederacy, league, or treaty.
ALLIES.e: From Middle English allien, alien (“to form an alliance, associate, join; to become an ally; to introduce (someone) as an ally; to marry; to become related (to someone); to attack, engage in combat; to combine; (cooking) to combine ingredients, especially to bind them together”) ...

ALLIUM.d: Any of many bulbous plants of the genus Allium, including onions and garlic.

ALLOSE.d: An epimer of glucose found in some African shrubs
ALLOSE.e:
From all + -ose.
Chemist Emil Fischer is credited with the following mnemonic for the order of the configurations of the 8 aldohexoses (See Coordinate terms below.) about the chiral centers when ordered as 3-bit binary strings: All altruists gladly make gum in gallon tanks.

ALLOWS.d: Plural of ALLOW: To permit; to let happen.
ALLOWS.e: From Old French alouer, from Latin allaudāre (to praise).

ALLUDE.d: To refer to something indirectly or by suggestion; to invoke it by implication rather than mention.
ALLUDE.e: From Middle French alluder, from Latin alludere (“to play with or allude”), from ad + ludere (“to play”).

ALLURE.d: The power to attract, entice; the quality causing attraction.
ALLURE.e: From Middle English aluren, from Old French aleurer, alurer, from a (“to, towards”) (Latin ad) + leurre (“lure”). Compare lure.

ALMOND.d: The seed within the drupe of a small deciduous tree in family Rosaceae, Prunus amygdalus, considered a culinary nut.
ALMOND.e: From Middle English almond, almaund, from Old French almande, amande, from Vulgar Latin *amendla, *amandula, from Latin amygdala, from Ancient Greek ἀμυγδάλη (amugdálē), of uncertain origin. Influenced by amandus and by many European words of Arabic origin beginning with the Arab...

ALNICO.d: An alloy of aluminium, nickel and cobalt, sometimes alloyed with smaller amounts of iron, copper, titanium and used primarily in the manufacture of magnets.
ALNICO.e: From the chemical symbols Al, Ni and Co.

ALPACA.d: A sheep-like domesticated animal of the Andes, Vicugna pacos, in the camel family, closely related to the llama, guanaco, and vicuña.
ALPACA.e: Borrowed from Spanish alpaca, from Aymara allpaqa.

ALPINE.d: Of, relating to, or inhabiting mountains, especially above the timberline.
ALPINE.e: From Latin Alpīnus, from Alpēs (“the Alps”). Cognates include French alpin.

ALTERS.d: Plural of ALTER: To change; to modify.

ALUMNA.d: A female pupil or student (especially of a university or college).

AMAZON.d: A member of a mythical race of female warriors inhabiting the Black Sea area.
AMAZON.e: From Middle English, from Latin, from Ancient Greek Ἀμαζών (Amazṓn); perhaps Ionian Greek pronunciation of Old Persian *hamazan- (“warrior”), as the Amazon women were known warriors. A popular folk etymology, of Ancient Greek provenance, claims that the word derives from ἀ- (a-, ...

AMBLER.d: A slow-moving, comfortable horse or mule.
AMBLER.e: From Middle English amblere; equivalent to amble + -er.

AMBUSH.d: The act of concealing oneself and lying in wait to attack or kill by surprise.
AMBUSH.e: From Middle English enbuschen, from Old French enbuscier, anbuchier (verb) (whence Middle French embusche (noun)), from Old French en- + Vulgar Latin boscus (“wood”) (whence also bouquet), from Frankish *busk (“bush”), from Proto-Germanic *buskaz (“bush, heavy stick”). Compare am...

AMERCE.d: To impose a fine on; to fine.
AMERCE.e: From Anglo-Norman amercier, from Old French a (“at”) + merci (“mercy”), thus “at the mercy of”.

AMNION.d: The innermost membrane of the fetal membranes of reptiles, birds, and mammals; the sac in which the embryo is suspended.
AMNION.e: From Latin amnion (“membrane around a fetus”), from Ancient Greek ἀμνίον (amníon).

AMOEBA.d: A member of the genus Amoeba of unicellular protozoa that moves by means of temporary projections called pseudopodia.
AMOEBA.e: From Ancient Greek ἀμοιβή (amoibḗ, “change”), referring to constantly changing shape of these organisms.

AMORAL.d: Done without consideration for morality or immorality.

AMOUNT.d: The total, aggregate or sum of material (not applicable to discrete numbers or units or items in standard English).
AMOUNT.e: From Middle English amounten (“to mount up to, come up to, signify”), from Old French amonter (“to amount to”), from amont, amunt (“uphill, upward”), from the prepositional phrase a mont (“toward or to a mountain or heap”), from Latin ad montem, from ad (“to”) + montem, accusativ...

AMPERE.d: A unit of electrical current, the standard base unit in the International System of Units; colloquially amp. Abbreviation: amp, Symbol: A
AMPERE.e: Named after French physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836).

AMULET.d: A religious article, protective charm, or ornament, usually bearing cultural or magical symbols, worn for protection against ill will, negative influences, or evil spirits.
AMULET.e: From Middle French amulette, from Latin amuletum.

ANATTA.d: The idea that there is no separate self or soul; egolessness. One of the three marks of existence.
ANATTA.e: From Pali anattan, from Sanskrit अनात्मन् (anātman, “no soul”), from अन्- (an-, “non-, un-, a-”) + आत्मन् (ātman, “soul”).

ANCHOR.d: A tool used to moor a vessel to the bottom of a sea or river to resist movement.
ANCHOR.e: From Middle English anker, from Old English ancor, ancra, from Latin ancora, from (or cognate with) Ancient Greek ἄγκυρα (ánkura). The modern form is a sixteenth-century modification after the Medieval Latin spelling anchora. Doublet of ancora, anker, angora, and Ankara.

ANGELS.d: Plural of ANGEL: A spiritual being serving as a messenger of God.
ANGELS.e: From Latin angelus, from Greek ángelos (messenger).

ANGERS.d: Plural of ANGER: A strong feeling of displeasure.

ANGINA.d: Any of various kinds of pain, especially pain that is suffocative, spasmodic, and/or acute and severe (fulminant).
ANGINA.e: From Latin angina (“quinsy; strangling, choking”), from angō (“to press together, to choke, to hurt (cause pain)”).

ANGLED.d: Past tense of ANGLE: The space between two intersecting lines.

ANGLES.d: Plural of ANGLE: The space between two intersecting lines.

ANGORA.e: From the name of the city of Ankara in Turkey, from Ancient Greek ἄγκυρα (ánkura, “anchor”).

ANIMAL.d: Any member of the kingdom Animalia of multicellular organisms that are usually mobile, whose cells are not encased in a rigid cell wall (distinguishing them from plants and fungi) and which derive energy solely from the consumption of other organisms (further distinguishing them from plants).
ANIMAL.e: From Middle English animal, from Old French animal, from Latin animal, a nominal use of the adjective form animāle, neuter of animālis, from anima (“breath, spirit”). Displaced native Middle English deor, der (“animal”) (whence modern English deer; from Old English dēor (“animal”...

ANIMUS.d: The basic impulses and instincts which govern one's actions.
ANIMUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin animus (“the mind, in a great variety of meanings: the rational soul in man, intellect, consciousness, will, intention, courage, spirit, sensibility, feeling, passion, pride, vehemence, wrath, etc., the breath, life, soul”), from Proto-Italic *anamos,...

ANKLET.d: A piece of jewelry/jewellery, resembling a bracelet but worn around the ankle.

ANLACE.e: Possibly from Middle English anelas, from Old French alesnaz, from alesne (“awl”), from Frankish *alisnu, *alasnu (“awl”), related to Old High German alasna, Alemannic German Alesne, Alse (“awl”); compare also Old High German āla (“awl”).

ANNEAL.d: To subject to great heat and then (often slow) cooling, and sometimes reheating and further cooling, for the purpose of rendering less brittle; to temper; to toughen.
ANNEAL.e: From Middle English anelen, onelen, from Old English onǣlan (“to burn, ignite, set fire to, consume, heat, enlighten, incite, inflame, inspire, kindle”), from Proto-Germanic *ana (“on”) + Proto-Germanic *ailijaną (“to burn”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eydʰ- (“to burn”). The dou...

ANNUAL.e: First attested around 1382, borrowed from Late Latin annuālem, annuālis, related to Latin annālis, adjective form of annus (“year”). Used to categorize plants since 1710.

ANNULI.e: Learned borrowing from Medieval Latin ānnulī.

ANOINT.d: To smear or rub over with oil or an unctuous substance; also, to spread over, as oil.
ANOINT.e: From Middle English enointen, anointen, borrowed from Old French enoint, past participle of enoindre (“to anoint”). Doublet of inunct.

ANOMER.d: Any diastereoisomer of a sugar or derivative differing in configuration only at C-1 of an aldose or C-2 of a ketose.

ANOMIE.d: Alienation or social instability caused by erosion of standards and values.
ANOMIE.e: From French anomie, from Ancient Greek ἀνομία (anomía, “lawlessness”), from ἄνομος (ánomos, “lawless”), from ἀ- (a-, “not”) + νόμος (nómos, “law”). Popularized by French sociologist Émile Durkheim (1858–1917).

ANONYM.e: Coined or borrowed around 1812, from French anonyme, from Ancient Greek ἀνώνυμος (anṓnumos, “without name”).

ANORAK.d: A heavy weatherproof jacket with an attached hood; a parka or windcheater.
ANORAK.e:
* Borrowed from Greenlandic annoraaq.
* (person with obsessive interest): Originally referring to train spotters (because they would wear anoraks while looking out for trains).

ANOXIA.d: A condition in which a body tissue or an environment is severely or totally deprived of oxygen; severe hypoxia.
ANOXIA.e: From an- (prefix meaning ‘lacking, without’) + ox- (meaning ‘oxygen’) + -ia (suffix forming names of diseases).

ANOXIC.d: Suffering from a reduced supply of oxygen.

ANSWER.d: A response or reply; something said or done in reaction to a statement or question.
ANSWER.e: From Middle English answere, andsware, from Old English andswaru (“answer”), from and- (“against”) + swaru (“affirmation”), (from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ent- (“front, forehead”) and Old English swerian (“to swear”), from Proto-Indo-European *swer-), suggesting an original meaning...

ANTEED.d: Past tense of ANTE: A price or cost, as in up the ante.
ANTEED.e: Learned borrowing from Latin ante (“before”). Doublet of and.

ANTHEM.e: From Middle English anteme, from Old English antefn, antefen and Old French antiene, anteine, anteivne, from Latin antiphōna, from Ancient Greek ἀντίφωνα (antíphōna), from ἀντί (antí, “over against”) + φωνή (phōnḗ, “voice, sound”). Doublet of antiphon.

ANTHER.d: The pollen-bearing part of the stamen of a flower.
ANTHER.e: From French anthère, from Ancient Greek ἀνθηρός (anthērós, “flowery, blooming”), from ἄνθος (ánthos, “flower”).

ANTING.d: Present participle of ANTE: A price or cost, as in up the ante.
ANTING.e: Learned borrowing from Latin ante (“before”). Doublet of and.

ANTLER.d: A deciduous branching and bony structure on the head of deer, moose, and elk, normally in pairs, grown and shed each year. (Compare with horn, which is generally not shed.)
ANTLER.e: From Middle English auntelere, hauntelere, from Old French antoillier (“antler, horn”), from ante- (“in front of”) + oillier (oil (“eye”) + -ier (a suffix indicating location)), possibly from an unattested Latin *anteocularis (“before the eye”).

ANTRUM.d: A bodily cavity, especially one having bony walls, especially one in the sinuses.
ANTRUM.e: From Latin antrum, from Ancient Greek ἄντρον (ántron, “cave”). Doublet of antre.

ANURAN.d: Any amphibian of the order Anura; a frog, a toad.
ANURAN.e: From New Latin Anoura, Anura (“name of the order of amphibians”), or from French Anoures (“name of a family of amphibians”), from Ancient Greek ἀν- (an-, “lacking”)) + Ancient Greek οὐρά (ourá, “tail”) + -an.

ANURIA.d: A condition in which the kidneys do not produce urine.

ANUSES.d: Plural of ANUS: The orifice of the rectum in most mammals, teleost fish, and many invertebrates, through which feces and flatus are ejected.
ANUSES.e: First attested in 1658, borrowed from Middle French anus or its etymon Latin ānus (“ring, anus”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁eh₂no- (“ring”). See also anal, annular, annelid.

ANYONE.e: From Middle English eny on, ony one, equivalent to any + one.

AORIST.d: A verb paradigm found in certain languages, usually an unmarked form or one that expresses the perfective or aorist aspect.

APATHY.d: Lack of emotion or motivation; lack of interest or enthusiasm towards something; disinterest (in something).
APATHY.e: From French apathie, from Latin apathīa, from Ancient Greek ἀπάθεια (apátheia, “impassibility”, “insensibility”, “freedom from emotion”), from ἀπαθής (apathḗs, “not suffering or having suffered”, “without experience of”), from ἀ- (a-, “not”) + πάθος (páthos, “anything that befall...

APELIN.d: A peptide that is the endogenous ligand for the G-protein-coupled APJ receptor

APEMAN.d: A prehistoric man resembling an ape, especially one held to be a precursor to modern humans; a non-human australopithecine.

APEXED.d: Past tense of APEX: The highest or the greatest part of something, especially forming a point.
APEXED.e: Borrowed from Latin apex (“point, tip, summit”).

APEXES.d: Plural of APEX: The highest or the greatest part of something, especially forming a point.
APEXES.e: Borrowed from Latin apex (“point, tip, summit”).

APIARY.d: A place where bees and their hives are kept.
APIARY.e: 17th century, from Latin apiārium, from apis (“bee”).

APIOSE.d: A branched-chain sugar, 3-C-(hydroxymethyl)-D-glycerotetrose, that occurs in parsley and many other plants

APOGEE.d: The point, in an orbit about the Earth, that is farthest from the Earth: the apoapsis of an Earth orbiter.
APOGEE.e: From Middle French apogée, from Latin apogaeum, apogēum, from Ancient Greek ἀπόγειον (apógeion, “away from Earth”), from ἀπό (apó, “away”) + γῆ (gê, “Earth”).

APOZEM.e: From Latin apozema, from Ancient Greek ἀπόζεμα (apózema, “to extract by boiling”), from the root ζέω (zéō, “to boil, seethe”), q. v.

APPEAL.d: An application to a superior court or judge for a decision or order by an inferior court or judge to be reviewed and overturned.
APPEAL.e: From Middle English apel, appel (“formal accusation brought in court; a challenge to trial by combat; an appeal to a higher court or authority; plea (for mercy, protection, etc.); pealing (of bells)”) [and other forms], from Old French apel (“a call”) (modern French appel (“a cal...

APPEAR.d: To come or be in sight; to be in view; to become visible.
APPEAR.e: From Middle English apperen, aperen, borrowed from Old French aparoir (French apparoir), from Latin appāreō (“I appear”), from ad (“to”) + pāreō (“I come forth, I become visible”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂-s- (“watch, see”), s-present of *peh₂- (“protect”).

APPEND.d: To hang or attach to, as by a string, so that the thing is suspended
APPEND.e: From Latin appendere (“to hang up, suspend on, pay out”), via Old French apendre, appendre, via Middle English appenden; from ad (“on, upon, against”) + pendere (“to suspend, hang”), equivalent to ad- + pend. Compare with Old English appenden, apenden (“to belong”). See also pend...

APPLED.d: Past tense of APPLE: A round fruit with red, green, or yellow skin.

APPLES.d: Plural of APPLE: A round fruit with red, green, or yellow skin.

APPLET.d: A small program module that runs under the control of a larger application, typically a web browser.
APPLET.e: From app + -let, but perhaps also influenced by Apple (the term originated in AppleScript).

ARABIN.d: A carbohydrate, isomeric with cane sugar, found in gum arabic

ARABLE.d: Able to be plowed or tilled, capable of growing crops (traditionally contrasted with pasturable lands such as heaths).
ARABLE.e: From Middle English arable, from Middle French arable, from Old French arable, from Latin arābilis, formed from arō (“plow”) + -bilis (“able to be”). Cognate with earable (“arable”).

ARALIA.d: Spikenard and any of many related ornamental and food plants, of the genus Aralia, from Asia and the Americas.
ARALIA.e: From the genus name, New Latin Aralia.

ARAMID.d: Any of a class of strong, heat-resistant synthetic fibres, used in aerospace and military applications.

ARBOUR.e: From Middle English arbere, arber, an alteration of herber, erber (“pleasure garden; herb garden”) influenced by Latin arbor (“tree”).

ARCADE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French arcade, from Italian arcata (“arch of a bridge”), from Latin arcus (“arc”).

ARCANA.d: Specialized knowledge that is mysterious to the uninitiated.
ARCANA.e: From Latin arcānus (“hidden, secret”), from arcēre (“to withhold”), arca (“a chest”).

ARCANE.e: Borrowed from Latin arcānus (“hidden, secret”), from arceō (“to shut up, enclose”); cognate with Latin arca (“a chest”).

ARCHES.d: Plural of ARCH: An inverted U shape.
ARCHES.e: From Middle English arch, arche, from Old French arche (“an arch”), a feminine form of arc, from Latin arcus (“a bow, arc, arch”). Doublet of arc and arco. Displaced native Old English bīeġels.

ARCHON.d: A chief magistrate of ancient Athens.
ARCHON.e: From Ancient Greek ἄρχων (árkhōn), a noun use of the present participle of ἄρχω (árkhō, “to rule”).

ARCING.d: Present participle of ARC: That part of a circle which a heavenly body appears to pass through as it moves above and below the horizon.
ARCING.e: Inherited from Middle English ark, from Old French arc, from Latin arcus (“a bow, arc, arch”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂erkʷos (“bow, arrow”). Doublet of arch, arco, and arrow.

ARDENT.d: Full of ardor; expressing passion, spirit, or enthusiasm.
ARDENT.e: First attested circa 14th century as Middle English ardaunt, borrowed from Anglo-Norman ardent and Old French ardant, from Latin ardentem, accusative of ardēns, present participle of ardeō (“I burn”).

ARDOUR.d: British, Canada, and Australia spelling of ardor.

ARENAS.d: Plural of ARENA: A central area for sports or entertainment.
ARENAS.e: From Latin arēna (sand), referring to the sand-covered floor.

AREOID.d: The analogue of the geoid for the planet Mars; the Martian geoid. The gravitational and rotational equipotential surface for Mars. The surface that provides the datum line (the equivalent for sea level) for Mars.
AREOID.e: From areo- (“Mars”) + -oid (“like”). From Ancient Greek Ἄρης (Árēs, “Ares”), the Greek God of War, equivalent to the Roman God of War Mars (“Mars”), synonymous use for the Red Planet; and Ancient Greek -ειδής (-eidḗs, “-oid”) suffix. Coined in analogy to geoid, the equivalent for...

AREOLA.d: The circular, darkly pigmented area surrounding a nipple; the areola mammae.
AREOLA.e: Borrowed from Latin āreola (“small vacant space, garden”), diminutive of ārea. Doublet of areole.

AREOLE.d: Any of the smallest enclosures created by the veins of a leaf.
AREOLE.e: Borrowed from French aréole, from Latin areola: a small area. Doublet of areola.

ARGENT.e: From Middle English argent, from Old French argent m (“silver”), from Latin argentum n (“white money, silver”).

ARGOSY.e: Alteration of Italian ragusea (“a large ship”), after the maritime city of Ragusa, now Dubrovnik.

ARGUED.d: Past tense of ARGUE: To give reasons for or against something.
ARGUED.e: From Old French arguer, from Latin argūtāre.

ARGUES.d: Plural of ARGUE: To give reasons for or against something.
ARGUES.e: From Old French arguer, from Latin argūtāre.

ARGUFY.d: To argue without any aim; to dispute; to disagree.

ARGYLL.d: A former county of Scotland, now incorporated into Argyll and Bute.
ARGYLL.e: Borrowed from Scottish Gaelic Earra-Ghàidheal (“land of the Gaels”).

ARIDED.d: Past tense of ARID: Very dry.
ARIDED.e: From French aride or directly from Latin āridus (“dry, arid, parched”), compare its synonymous contracted form ardus. Originally from the verb āreo (“I am dry, I am parched”), akin to ārdeō (“I am on fire, I burn”).

ARILED.d: Past tense of ARIL: A tissue surrounding the seed in certain fruits such as pomegranates.
ARILED.e: 1785. From New Latin arillus (compare modern French arille and the English doublet arillus), from Medieval Latin arilli.

ARISED.d: Past tense of ARISE: To get up; to come into being.

ARISES.d: Plural of ARISE: To get up; to come into being.

ARMADA.d: A fleet of warships, especially with reference to the Spanish Armada.
ARMADA.e: Borrowed from Spanish armada (“fleet, navy”), from Medieval Latin armāta, from the feminine past participle of Latin armō, from arma. Doublet of army.

ARMFUL.d: The amount an arm or arms can hold.
ARMFUL.e: From arm + -ful (suffix forming nouns indicating as much as can be held by the noun to which it is attached).

ARMIED.d: Past tense of ARMY: A large, highly organized military force, concerned mainly with ground (rather than air or naval) operations.
ARMIED.e: From (1386) Middle English armee, borrowed from Old French armee (cf. modern French armée), from Medieval Latin armāta (“armed force”), a noun taken from the past participle of Latin armāre (“to arm”), itself related to arma (“tools, arms”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂er- (“to j...

ARMIES.d: Plural of ARMY: A large, highly organized military force, concerned mainly with ground (rather than air or naval) operations.
ARMIES.e: From (1386) Middle English armee, borrowed from Old French armee (cf. modern French armée), from Medieval Latin armāta (“armed force”), a noun taken from the past participle of Latin armāre (“to arm”), itself related to arma (“tools, arms”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂er- (“to j...

ARMING.d: present participle and gerund of arm

ARMLET.d: A band worn on the arm for ornamental or identification purposes.

ARMPIT.d: The cavity beneath the junction of the arm and shoulder.
ARMPIT.e:
From Middle English armpitt, arme-pitt, armput, equivalent to arm + pit.
(something unpleasant): Presumably a reference to underarm body odor.

ARRACK.d: An alcoholic drink distilled from coconut palm flowers in South Asia.

ARRANT.e:
A variant of errant, from Middle English erraunt [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman erraunt, from Old French errant, the present participle of errer (“to walk (to); to wander (to); (figuratively) to travel, voyage”), and then:
* from Vulgar Latin iterō (compare Late Latin itine...

ARRAYS.d: Plural of ARRAY: An impressive display; an ordered arrangement.

ARREAR.e: From Middle English arere, from Old French arere, from Vulgar Latin *ad retro (literally “to the rear”).

ARREST.d: A check, stop, an act or instance of arresting something.
ARREST.e: From Middle English arest (noun) and aresten (verb), from Old French areste (noun) and arester (“to stay, stop”, verb), from Vulgar Latin *arrestō, from Latin ad- (“to”) + restō (“to stop, remain behind, stay back”), from re- (“back”) + stō (“to stand”), from Proto-Indo-European ...

ARRIVE.d: To reach; to get to a certain place.
ARRIVE.e:
From Middle English arriven, ariven, from Old French ariver, from Early Medieval Latin adrīpāre (“to land, come ashore”), derived from Latin rīpa (“shore, river-bank”). Displaced native oncome, tocome.
For the semantic evolution, compare Old English ġelandian, ġelendan, lendan (“...

ARROWS.d: Plural of ARROW: A projectile shot from a bow.

ARROYO.d: A dry creek or streambed, a gulch which temporarily or seasonally fills and flows (after sufficient rain).

ARSINE.d: A compound of arsenic and hydrogen, AsH₃, a colorless and exceedingly poisonous gas, having an odor like garlic.
ARSINE.e: From ars(enic) + -ine (“suffix used to form names of chemical substances”).

ARTERY.d: Any of the muscular- and elastic-walled blood vessels forming part of the circulation system by which blood is conveyed away from the heart regardless of its oxygenation status; see pulmonary artery.
ARTERY.e: Late Middle English arterie, borrowing from Old French artaire and Latin artēria (“a windpipe; an artery”), from Ancient Greek ᾰ̓ρτηρῐ́ᾱ (ărtērĭ́ā, “windpipe; artery”).

ARTFUL.d: Characterized by, or performed with, cleverness or contrivance; clever, ingenious.
ARTFUL.e: From art (“skill that is attained by study, practice, or observation”) + -ful (suffix forming adjectives from nouns, with the sense of being full of, tending to, or thoroughly possessing the quality expressed by the noun).

ARTIER.d: Comparative form of ARTY: Inclined towards the arts.

ARTIST.e: From French artiste, from Late Latin artista, from ars (“art”). Doublet of artiste. Displaced native Old English cræftiga. By surface analysis, art + -ist.

ASCEND.d: To move upward, to fly, to soar.
ASCEND.e: From Middle English ascenden, borrowed from Old French ascendre, from Latin ascendō (“to go up, climb up to”), from ad (“to”) + scandō (“to climb”); see scan. Unrelated to accede other than common ad prefix.

ASCENT.d: The act of ascending; a motion upwards.
ASCENT.e: Formed from ascend on the model of descend/descent.

ASHIER.d: Comparative form of ASHY: Resembling ashes (especially in colour); (of a person’s complexion) unusually pale as a result of strong emotion, illness, etc.
ASHIER.e: From Middle English asshy, asky, equivalent to ash + -y.

ASHING.d: Present participle of ASH: Solid remains of a fire.
ASHING.e:
From Middle English asshe, from Old English æsċe, from Proto-West Germanic *askā, from Proto-Germanic *askǭ (compare West Frisian jiske, Dutch as, Low German Asch, German Asche, Danish aske, Swedish aska, Norwegian aske), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eHs-; see it for cognates.
The...

ASHLAR.d: Masonry employing flat and well-squared stone or brick, creating an appearance similar to wooden flooring.
ASHLAR.e: From Middle English assheler, acheler, etc., from forms of Old French esselier (“wooden support, traverse beam”), from Medieval Latin ascelāris and assellāris (equivalent to a diminutive of early forms of ais (“plank”)), variant of *axillāris (attested only after the Renaissance)...

ASHRAM.d: A secluded religious hermitage inhabited by gurus, or the population of such a hermitage.

ASIDES.d: Plural of ASIDE: To one side; out of the way.

ASKARI.d: A member of a local African military or police unit, usually one serving in a European colonial force.
ASKARI.e: From Swahili askari (“soldier”), from Arabic عَسْكَرِيّ (ʕaskariyy). Doublet of lascar.

ASKING.d: Present participle of ASK: To request or petition.
ASKING.e: From Middle English asken, axen, from Old English āscian, from Proto-West Germanic *aiskōn, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eys- (“to wish; request”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian aaskje (“to ask, demand, require”), West Frisian easkje (“to ask, demand, require”), Dutch eisen (“to ...

ASPECT.d: Any specific feature, part, or element of something.
ASPECT.e: From Middle English aspect, from Latin aspectus (“look, sight; appearance”), from aspiciō (“see; catch sight of; inspect”), from ad- (“to, towards, at”) + speciō (“look, look at, behold; observe”).

ASPIRE.d: To have a strong desire or ambition to achieve something.
ASPIRE.e: From Middle English aspiren, from Old French aspirer, from Latin aspīrō (“breathe on; approach; desire”).

ASSAIL.d: To attack with harsh words or violent force (also figuratively).
ASSAIL.e: From Middle English assailen, from Old French assaillir, assalir, from Late Latin assalīre, from Latin ad (“at, towards”) + salīre (“jump”). See also assault.

ASSENT.e: From Middle English assent (noun) and assenten (verb), from Old French assent (noun) and assentir (verb), from Latin assentiō.

ASSERT.d: To declare with assurance or plainly and strongly; to state positively.
ASSERT.e: From Latin assertus, perfect passive participle of asserō (“declare someone free or a slave by laying hands upon him; hence free from, protect, defend; lay claim to, assert, declare”), from ad (“to”) + serō (“join, range in a row”).

ASSESS.d: To determine, estimate or judge the value of; to evaluate; to estimate.
ASSESS.e: From Middle English assessen, from Old French assesser, from Medieval Latin assessare, originally the frequentative of Latin assessus, past participle of assidēre, from ad (“to, towards, at”) + sedeō (“sit; settle down”). Cognate with Spanish asentar (“to settle”).

ASSETS.d: Plural of ASSET: A useful or valuable thing or person.

ASSIGN.d: To designate or set apart (something) for some purpose.
ASSIGN.e: From Middle English assignen, from Old French assigner, asigner, from Latin assignō, from ad- + signō (“mark, sign”).

ASSISE.d: Two or more beds or strata of rock united by the occurrence of fossils of the same characteristic species or genera.

ASSIST.e: From Middle English assisten, from Old French assister (“to assist, to attend”), from Latin assistō (“stand at, bestand”, verb).

ASSIZE.d: A session or inquiry made before a court or jury.
ASSIZE.e: From Middle English assise, from Old French assises, feminine plural participle of Old French asseoir (“to sit”), from Latin assidere.

ASSORT.d: To sort or arrange according to characteristic or class.

ASSUME.d: To authenticate by means of belief; to surmise; to suppose to be true, especially without proof.
ASSUME.e: From Latin assūmō (“accept, take”), from ad- (“to, towards, at”) + sūmō (“take up, assume”).

ASSURE.d: To make sure and secure; ensure.
ASSURE.e: From Old French asseurer (Modern French assurer), from Latin ad- + securus (“secure”). Cognate with Spanish asegurar. Doublet of assecure.

ASTHMA.d: A long-term respiratory condition, in which the airways may unexpectedly and suddenly narrow, often in response to an allergen, cold air, exercise, or emotional stress. Symptoms include wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing.
ASTHMA.e: From Middle English asma, asme, from Medieval Latin asthma, asma, from Ancient Greek ἆσθμα (âsthma, “laborious breathing, asthma”). The spelling was changed to add -th- in the 16th century to match the Greek etymological roots.

ASTRAL.d: Relating to or resembling the stars; starry.
ASTRAL.e: From Late Latin astralis, from Latin astrum (“star”), from Ancient Greek ἄστρον (ástron, “star”).

ASYLEE.d: A non-citizen of a country who has been granted asylum in that country.

ASYLUM.d: A place of safety or refuge.
ASYLUM.e: From Latin asylum, from Ancient Greek ἄσυλον (ásulon).

ATAXIA.d: Lack of coordination while performing voluntary movements, which may appear to be clumsiness, inaccuracy, or instability.
ATAXIA.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek ἀταξία (ataxía, “disorder”), derived from ἄτακτος (átaktos, “disorderly”).

ATBASH.d: A simple substitution cipher in which each occurrence of the first letter of the alphabet is substituted with the last, second with next to last, and so on.
ATBASH.e: From the letters of the Hebrew alphabet aleph, tav, beth, shin.

ATOMIC.d: Of or relating to atoms; composed of atoms; monatomic.

ATONAL.d: Lacking a tonal center or key.

ATRIUM.d: A central room or space in ancient Roman homes, open to the sky in the middle; a similar space in other buildings.
ATRIUM.e: From Latin ātrium (“entry hall”), from Etruscan.

ATTACH.d: To fasten, to join to (literally and figuratively).
ATTACH.e: From Middle English attachen, from Old French atachier, variant of estachier (“bind”), derived from estache (“stick”), from Frankish *stakkā, *stakō (“stick”), from Proto-Germanic *stakô (“pole, bar, stick, stake”). Doublet of attack. More at stake, stack.

ATTACK.d: An attempt to cause damage, injury to, or death of an opponent or enemy.
ATTACK.e: Borrowed from French attaque, derived from the verb attaquer, from Italian attaccare (“to join, attach”) (used in attaccare battaglia (“to join battle”)), from Frankish *stakkijan (“to stick, stick to, attach”). Doublet of attach. Displaced native Middle English onresen, from Old...

ATTAIN.d: To gain (an object or desired result).
ATTAIN.e: From Middle English atteynen, from Anglo-Norman ataindre, from Old French, from Latin attingō. Doublet of attainder and attinge.

ATTEND.d: Senses relating to caring for or waiting on someone, or accompanying or being present.
ATTEND.e:
PIE word
 *h₂éd
From Middle English attenden, atenden (“to devote oneself (to a task, etc.); to pay attention to (something), to look after; to consider (something); to expect or look forward to (something); to intend to do (something); to help or serve (someone), attend upon; to...

ATTEST.d: To affirm to be correct, true, or genuine.
ATTEST.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
Borrowed from Middle French attester, from Latin attestor (“to witness to, bear witness”), from at-, combining form of ad (“to”) + testor (“to bear witness”), from testis (“a witness”).

ATTIRE.d: One's dress; what one wears; one's clothes.
ATTIRE.e:
The verb is from Middle English atyren, atiren, from Old French atirier (“to equip”), from a- + tire (“rank”), akin to German Zier (“ornament”) and Old Norse tírr (“glory, renown”).
The noun is from Middle English atir, from the verb.

AUBURN.d: A dark reddish-brown colour, often used to describe hair colour.
AUBURN.e: Early Modern English auburn (“brown, reddish brown”) from Middle English aubourne, abron, abroune, abrune (“light brown, yellowish brown, blond”), alteration (due to conflation with Middle English brun (“brown”)) of earlier auborne (“yellowish-white, flaxen”) from Old French aubo...

AUGITE.d: A variety of pyroxene, usually of a black or dark green color, occurring in igneous rocks, such as basalt.

AUGURY.d: A divination based on the appearance and behaviour of animals.
AUGURY.e: From augur + -y, or from Middle English augurie, from Old French augurie, from Latin augurium.

AUGUST.e: From French auguste (“noble, stately; august”) or Latin augustus (“majestic, venerable, august; imperial, royal”), from augeō (“to augment, increase; to enlarge, expand, spread”). Doublet of Augustus.

AUKLET.d: Any of several small seabirds in the genera Aethia, Cerorhinca and Ptychoramphus of the auk family Alcidae.

AUREUS.d: A gold coin, minted in the Roman Empire from approximately 100 B.C.E. to 309 C.E., equal to 25 denarii.
AUREUS.e: From Latin aureus (“golden; gold coin equivalent to 25 denarii”), noun use of adjective, from aurum (“gold”). Doublet of eyrir, öre, øre, and oyra.

AURORA.d: An atmospheric phenomenon created by charged particles from the sun striking the upper atmosphere, creating coloured lights in the sky. It is usually named australis or borealis based on whether it is in the Southern or Northern Hemisphere respectively.
AURORA.e: From Latin aurōra (“dawn”). Doublet of Eos.

AUTEUR.d: A creative artist, especially a film director, seen as having a specific, recognisable artistic vision, and who is seen as the single or preeminent ‘author’ of their works.
AUTEUR.e: Borrowed from French auteur (“author”). Popularised by François Truffaut in the 1954 essay “Une certaine tendance du cinéma français” (“A certain tendency in French cinema”) in the influential film journal Cahiers du Cinéma as the phrase “la politique des Auteurs”. Doublet of aut...

AUTHOR.d: The originator or creator of a work, especially of a literary composition; or, one of the creators of a collaborative work.
AUTHOR.e: From Middle English auctour, from Anglo-Norman autour, from Old French autor, from Latin auctor, from augeō (“to increase, originate”). The h, also found in Middle French autheur, is unetymological as there is no h in the original Latin spelling. God the creator . by authentic. D...

AUTISM.d: A pervasive neurological condition that is observable in early childhood and persists throughout the lifespan, characterised by atypical communication patterns (e.g., differences in body language or eye contact), delayed language development, and sensory processing sensitivities.
AUTISM.e: Borrowed from German Autismus, coined by Swiss psychiatrist Eugen Bleuler, first usage dated to 1907 attributed by Carl Jung as an alternative of his for "auto-erotism", although Bleuler himself differentiates the terms in his book Dementia Praecox, first published 1911. From Anc...

AUTOED.d: Past tense of AUTO: Clipping of automatic (of a gearbox/transmission).
AUTOED.e: From Ancient Greek αὐτός (autós, “self”), metanalyzed from auto- in words such as automatic, autopilot, and automobile.

AUTUMN.d: Traditionally the third of the four seasons, when deciduous trees lose their leaves, and temperatures and daylight hours decrease; typically regarded as spanning the months of September, October, and November in the Northern Hemisphere, and the months of March, April and May in the Southern Hemisphere.
AUTUMN.e: Inherited from Middle English autumpne, from Middle French automne, from Old French automne, autonne, from Latin autumnus. Some of the verbal senses are from Latin autumnāre.

AVATAR.d: An incarnation of a deity, particularly Vishnu.
AVATAR.e: First use appears c. 1784, in The Hindu Wife; or, The Enchanted Fruit, by William Jones. Borrowed from Hindustani अवतार / اوتار (avtār), from Sanskrit अवतार (avatāra, “descent of a deity from a heaven”), a compound of अव (ava, “off, away, down”) and the vṛddhi-stem of the root √त...

AVAUNT.d: Begone; depart; used in contempt or abhorrence.
AVAUNT.e: First used 1275–1325; Middle English, from Old French avant (“to the front”).

AVENGE.d: To take vengeance (for); to exact satisfaction for by punishing the injuring party; to vindicate by inflicting pain or evil on a wrongdoer.
AVENGE.e: From Middle English avengen, borrowed from Old French avengier, from a- (“upon”) + vengier, from Latin vindicō, vindicāre.

AVENUE.d: A broad street, especially one bordered by trees or, in cities laid out in a grid pattern, one that is on a particular side of the city or that runs in a particular direction.
AVENUE.e: Borrowed from French avenue, from Old French avenue, feminine past participle of avenir (“approach”), from Latin adveniō, advenīre (“come to”, from ad (“to”) + veniō, venīre (“come”)).

AVERSE.d: Having a repugnance or opposition of mind.
AVERSE.e: From Latin aversus, past participle of avertere (“to avert”).

AVIARY.d: A house, enclosure, large cage, or other place for keeping birds confined; a birdhouse.

AVOCET.d: Any of four species of wading birds in the genus Recurvirostra, with long, slender recurved bills, long legs, and webbed feet.
AVOCET.e: From French avocette, from Italian avocetta.

AVOIDS.d: Plural of AVOID: To keep away from; to prevent.

AVOUCH.d: To declare freely and openly; to assert.
AVOUCH.e: From Old French avouchier, from Latin advocāre. Doublet of advocate, advoke, and avow.

AVOWAL.d: An open declaration of affirmation or admission of knowledge.

AVOWED.d: simple past and past participle of avow

AVULSE.e: From Latin avulsus, past participle of avello: ab- + vellō.

AWAKED.d: Past tense of AWAKE: Not asleep; to stop sleeping.

AWAKEN.e: From Middle English awakenen or awaknen, from Old English awæcnan or awæcnian, from a- plus wæcnan or wæcnian.

AWAKES.d: Plural of AWAKE: Not asleep; to stop sleeping.

AWARDS.d: Plural of AWARD: A prize given for achievement.

AWNING.d: A rooflike cover, usually of canvas, extended over or before any place as a shelter from the sun, rain, or wind.
AWNING.e: 1615-25 (nautical sense only); from *awn + -ing, reduction of Middle French auvans (“sloping roof”), from Old French anvant (1180), from Gaulish *an(de)bannā (“eaves”) (compare Occitan ambans (“parapet”)), form of *ande- (intensive prefix) (compare Welsh an-, Old Irish ind-) + *b...

AXILLA.d: The armpit, or the cavity beneath the junction of the arm and shoulder.
AXILLA.e: Borrowed from Latin axilla (“side, armpit”). Doublet of axil.

AXISED.d: Past tense of AXIS: An imaginary line around which an object spins (an axis of rotation) or is symmetrically arranged (an axis of symmetry).
AXISED.e: Borrowed from Latin axis (“axle, axis”) in the 16th century. Via Latin cognate with ala, aisle, atelier. Via Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱs- cognate with inherited English axle and borrowed axo-, axon.

AXISES.d: Plural of AXIS: An imaginary line around which an object spins (an axis of rotation) or is symmetrically arranged (an axis of symmetry).
AXISES.e: Borrowed from Latin axis (“axle, axis”) in the 16th century. Via Latin cognate with ala, aisle, atelier. Via Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱs- cognate with inherited English axle and borrowed axo-, axon.

AZALEA.d: A plant of the obsolete genus Azalea.
AZALEA.e: From New Latin, from Ancient Greek ἀζαλέος (azaléos, “dry”), because it grows in dry soil; from ἄζω (ázō, “I dry up”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eHs-.

AZYGOS.d: In anatomy, a structure that is unpaired. This is relatively unusual, as most elements of anatomy reflect bilateral symmetry.
AZYGOS.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek ἄζυγος (ázugos, “unwedded, unpaired”).

BAAING.d: Present participle of BAA: The characteristic cry or bleating of a sheep.
BAAING.e:
Compare German bäh, mäh; an imitative word.
Notes on phonological development
The pronunciation /bɑː/ is perhaps a development from earlier /bæː/ reflecting the shift of /æː/ to /ɑː/ during the 18th and 19th centuries. Compare Early Modern English bae, bea, both "to baa", respect...

BABBLE.d: To utter words indistinctly or unintelligibly; to utter inarticulate sounds
BABBLE.e: From Middle English babelen, from Old English *bæblian, also wæflian (“to talk foolishly”), from Proto-West Germanic *bablōn, *wablōn, variants of *babalōn, from Proto-Germanic *babalōną (“to chatter”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰa-bʰa-, perhaps a reduplication of Proto-Indo-Eur...

BABIED.d: Past tense of BABY: A very young human, particularly from birth to a couple of years old or until walking is fully mastered.
BABIED.e: From Middle English baby, babie (“baby”), a diminutive form of babe (“babe, baby”), equivalent to babe + -y/-ie (“endearing and diminutive suffix”). Perhaps ultimately imitative of baby talk (compare babble).

BABIES.d: Plural of BABY: A very young human, particularly from birth to a couple of years old or until walking is fully mastered.
BABIES.e: From Middle English baby, babie (“baby”), a diminutive form of babe (“babe, baby”), equivalent to babe + -y/-ie (“endearing and diminutive suffix”). Perhaps ultimately imitative of baby talk (compare babble).

BABOON.d: An Old World monkey of the genus Papio, having dog-like muzzles and large canine teeth, cheek pouches, a short tail, and naked callosities on the buttocks.
BABOON.e: From Middle English babewin, baboin, from Old French babouin, from baboue (“grimace; muzzle”), of West Germanic origin, related to dialectal German Bäppe (“lips; muzzle”), Middle High German beffen (“to bark”), Middle English baffen (“to bark”). See also baff, baffle.

BACHES.e: Abbreviation of bachelor (or, in later senses, of bachelor pad).

BACKED.d: Past tense of BACK: At or near the rear.
BACKED.e:
From Middle English bak, from Old English bæc, from Proto-West Germanic *bak, from Proto-Germanic *baką, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeg- (“to bend”). The adverb represents an aphetic form of aback.
Compare Middle Low German bak (“back”), from Old Saxon bak, and West Fris...

BACONS.d: Plural of BACON: Cured meat from the back or sides of a pig.
BACONS.e: From Old French bacon, from Germanic bakō.

BADASS.d: A belligerent or mean person; a person with an unpleasantly extreme appearance, attitudes, or behavior.
BADASS.e: From bad + ass (“buttocks; one's self or person”).

BADDER.d: Comparative form of BAD: Of low quality.
BADDER.e: From Middle English bad, badde (“wicked, evil, depraved”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps a shortening of Old English bæddel (“hermaphrodite”) (for loss of -el compare Middle English muche from Old English myċel, and Middle English wenche from Old English wenċel), or at least relat...

BADDIE.d: A person of bad character, especially in a work of fiction.

BADGER.d: Any mammal belonging to the genera Meles, Arctonyx, Mellivora and Taxidea.
BADGER.e: From Middle English bageard (“marked by a badge”), from bage (“badge”), referring to the animal's badge-like white blaze, equivalent to badge + -ard. Displaced earlier brock, from Old English brocc.

BADMAN.d: A violence-prone man who has had run-ins with the law; especially one from the Old West days of U.S. history.

BAFFLE.d: To confuse or perplex (someone) completely; to bewilder, to confound, to puzzle.
BAFFLE.e:
The origin of the verb is uncertain; it is possibly:
* from French bafouer, baffoüer (“to abuse, revile; to confuse, baffle; to deceive; to flout; to scorn”), imitative of someone making a disdainful sound by expelling air quickly through pouted lips (compare Occitan baf (interje...

BAGFUL.d: The amount that fills a bag.
BAGFUL.e: From Middle English bage-ful, bage full, baggeful, bagg-ful; equivalent to bag + -ful.

BAGGED.d: Past tense of BAG: A soft container made out of cloth, paper, thin plastic, etc. and open at the top, used to hold food, commodities, and other goods.
BAGGED.e: From Middle English bagge, from Old Norse baggi (“bag, pack, satchel, bundle”) (whence also Old French bague (“bundle, package, sack”)); related to Old Norse bǫggr (“harm, shame; load, burden”), of uncertain origin.

BAGGER.d: Comparative form of BAG: A soft container made out of cloth, paper, thin plastic, etc. and open at the top, used to hold food, commodities, and other goods.
BAGGER.e: From Middle English bagge, from Old Norse baggi (“bag, pack, satchel, bundle”) (whence also Old French bague (“bundle, package, sack”)); related to Old Norse bǫggr (“harm, shame; load, burden”), of uncertain origin.

BAGMAN.d: A person who collects, transports, or distributes illicit money, especially for the purpose of bribery, extortion, or the making of other improper payments.

BAGNIO.e: From Italian bagno, from Latin balneum (“bath”). Doublet of bain, balaneion, and banya.

BAILEE.d: One who holds bailed property; one who takes possession of the property of another (called a bailor) in order to keep that property safe for the other.

BAILEY.d: The outer wall of a feudal castle.
BAILEY.e: From Old French baile (“palisade, enclosure”), from Latin bacula, plural of baculum (“stick, rod”).

BAILOR.d: One who bails property; one who places property in the hands of another (called a bailee) for safekeeping.

BAITED.d: Past tense of BAIT: Any substance, especially food, used in catching fish, or other animals, by alluring them to a hook, snare, trap, or net.
BAITED.e: From Middle English bayte, bait, beite, from Old Norse beita (“food, bait”), from Proto-Germanic *baitō (“that which is bitten, bait”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“to cleave, split, separate”). Cognate with German Beize (“mordant, corrosive fluid; marinade”), Old English b...

BAJADA.d: In the southwestern US, a slope, specifically part of a piedmont slope made of rocky detritus.

BAKERY.d: A place in which bread (and often other baked goods such as cakes) is baked and/or sold.
BAKERY.e: From bake + -ery (“place of”). Replaced earlier bakehouse. Originally “place for making bread”; as “shop where baked goods are sold”, it was noted as an Americanism by British travelers by 1832.

BAKING.d: present participle and gerund of bake.
BAKING.e: From Middle English bakynge; equivalent to bake + -ing.

BALATA.d: Manilkara bidentata, a large South American tree that yields latex and edible yellow berries.

BALBOA.d: The currency of Panama, divided into 100 centésimos
BALBOA.e: Named after Vasco Núñez de Balboa. See also Balboa.

BALDED.d: Past tense of BALD: Having little or no hair, fur, or feathers.
BALDED.e:
From Middle English balled, ballid, bald (“bald”), of uncertain origin. Probably formed from Middle English bal, balle (“ball, round object, knoll, head”). Compare Old Danish bældet (“bald”).
An alternate etymology has Old English bǣl (“fire, flame; funeral pyre”) (from Proto-Ger...

BALDER.d: comparative form of bald: more bald

BALEEN.d: keratinous material that makes up the plates in the mouth of the baleen whale (Mysticeti), which it uses to trap its food; formerly used in corsetry.
BALEEN.e: From Middle English baleyne, from Old French baleine (“whale, whalebone”), from Latin balaena (“whale”), from Ancient Greek φάλαινα (phálaina, “whale”).

BALING.d: Present participle of BALE: Evil, especially considered as an active force for destruction or death.
BALING.e:
From Middle English bale (“evil”), from Old English bealu, from Proto-West Germanic *balu, from Proto-Germanic *balwą.
Cognate with Low German bal- (“bad, ill”), Gothic 𐌱𐌰𐌻𐍅𐌴𐌹𐌽𐍃 (balweins, “torture”), Old High German balo (“destruction”), Old Norse bǫl (“disaster”).

BALKED.d: Past tense of BALK: An uncultivated ridge formed in the open field system, caused by the action of ploughing.
BALKED.e: From Middle English balke, from Old English balca, either from or influenced by Old Norse bálkr (“partition, ridge of land”), from Proto-Germanic *balkô. Cognate with Dutch balk (“balk”), German Balken (“balk”), Italian balcone (“balcony”).

BALLAD.d: A kind of narrative poem, adapted for recitation or singing; especially, a sentimental or romantic poem in short stanzas.
BALLAD.e: From French ballade, from Old Occitan ballada (“poem for a dance”), from Late Latin ballare. Doublet of ballade.

BALLET.e: Borrowed from French ballet, from Italian balletto (“short dance, ballet”), diminutive form of ballo (“group dance”), from Late Latin ballō (“to dance”).

BALLOT.d: A small ball placed in a container to cast a vote; now, by extension, a piece of paper or card used for this purpose, or some other means used to signify a vote.
BALLOT.e: Borrowed from Italian balota (obsolete), ballotta (“small ball, especially one used to register a vote”), from balla (“bale, bundle”) + -otta (suffix forming diminutive nouns); or from Middle French balote (obsolete), ballotte (“small ball used to register a vote”) (also compare ...

BALSAM.d: A sweet-smelling oil or resin derived from various plants.
BALSAM.e: Borrowed from Latin balsamum, from Ancient Greek βάλσαμον (bálsamon, “balsam”), of Semitic origin (Hebrew בושם (“spice, perfume”)); compare Old English balsam, balsamum (“balsam, balm”), Doublet of balm and desman. Not related to balsa.

BAMBOO.d: A fast-growing grass of the Bambusoideae subfamily, characterised by its woody, hollow, round, straight, jointed stem.
BAMBOO.e: Borrowed from Dutch bamboe, from Portuguese bambu, from Malay bambu, from Kannada ಬಂಬು (bambu), variant form of ಬೇವು (bēvu). Cognate with Malayalam വേപ്പ് (vēppŭ), Telugu వేప (vēpa), from Proto-Dravidian *wēmpu (“neem”).

BANANA.d: An elongated curved tropical fruit of a banana plant, which grows in bunches and has a creamy flesh and a smooth skin.
BANANA.e: Borrowed from Portuguese banana or Spanish banana, derived from a Niger-Congo language spoken in the Guinea region. Specific derivation is unclear. Possible ancestor or cognate languages include Wolof banaana, Eastern Maninkakan banana, and Vai ꕒꘌꕯ (ɓaana) or ꕒꕌꕯ (ɓaana), possibl...

BANDIT.d: One who robs others in a lawless area, especially as part of a group.
BANDIT.e: Borrowed from Italian bandito (“outlawed”), a derivative of Italian bandire (“to ban”), from Late Latin bandīre, an alteration (due to Gothic 𐌱𐌰𐌽𐌳𐍅𐌾𐌰𐌽 (bandwjan, “to signal”)) of Late Latin bannīre (“to ban”), from Frankish *bannan (“to ban”). Doublet of bandito.

BANGLE.d: A rigid bracelet or anklet, especially one with no clasp.

BANING.d: Present participle of BANE: A cause of misery or ruin.
