BANING.e: The noun is derived from Middle English bane (“person or thing that destroys life, murderer, slayer; person who destroys the soul; destruction of life, death, doom; poison”), from Old English bana (“person or thing that causes death, murderer”), from Proto-West Germanic *banō, fr...

BANISH.d: To send (someone) away and forbid them from returning.
BANISH.e: From Middle English banysshen, from Old French banir (“to proclaim, ban, banish”) and Old English bannan, from Proto-Germanic *bannaną (“curse, forbid”). Compare French bannir. Doublet of ban.

BANKED.d: Past tense of BANK: An institution where one can place and borrow money and take care of financial affairs.
BANKED.e: From Middle English banke, from Middle French banque, from Italian banca (“counter, moneychanger's bench or table”), from Lombardic bank (“bench, counter”), from Proto-West Germanic *banki, from Proto-Germanic *bankiz (“bench, counter”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeg- (“to turn,...

BANNED.d: Past tense of BAN: To summon; to call out.
BANNED.e: Inherited from Middle English bannen (“to summon; to banish; to curse”), partly from Old English bannan (“to summon, command, proclaim, call out”), from Proto-West Germanic *bannan; and partly from Old Norse banna (“to prohibit; to curse”), both from Proto-Germanic *bannaną (“to ...

BANNER.d: A flag or standard used by a military commander, monarch or nation.
BANNER.e: From Middle English baner, from Old French baniere (Modern bannière), of Germanic origin. More at band.

BANTAM.d: Any of several small chickens, especially of a breed that is a miniature version of another breed.
BANTAM.e: Borrowed from Dutch Bantam (Banten province in Java).

BANTER.d: Sharp, good-humoured, playful, typically spontaneous conversation.
BANTER.e: 1670s as verb, 1680s as noun. The origin is unknown, possibly from London street slang; ostensibly as *bant + -er (frequentative suffix). Possibly an Anglo-Gaelicism from the Irish bean (“woman”), so that "banter" means "talk of women."

BANYAN.d: An Indian trader, merchant, cashier, or money changer.
BANYAN.e: From Portuguese baniano, from Arabic بَنِيَان (baniyān), from Gujarati વાણિયો (vāṇiyo, “merchant”), from Sanskrit वाणिज (vāṇijá), from earlier वणिज् (vaṇíj, “merchant, trader”). The name appears to have been first bestowed popularly on a famous tree of this species growing near B...

BANZAI.e:
From Japanese 万歳(ばんざい) (banzai, “long live..., huzzah, hurrah”), from Middle Chinese 萬歲 (mjonᴴ sjwejᴴ), from Old Chinese 萬歲 (*mans s-qʷʰats, “10,000 years [of life]”, i.e. “immortality”), from 萬 /万 (wàn, “10,000”) 歲 /岁 (suì, “year (of age)”).
Compare Mandarin 萬歲／万岁 (wànsùi).

BAOBAB.d: A tree, Adansonia digitata, native to tropical Africa, having a broad swollen trunk and edible gourd-like hanging fruits.
BAOBAB.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin bahobab, from Arabic أَبُو حِبَاب (ʔabū ḥibāb, “father of many seeds”), from أَبُو (ʔabū, “father”) + حَبّ (ḥabb, “seed”).

BARBEL.d: A freshwater fish of the genus Barbus or other closely related genera.
BARBEL.e:
PIE word
 *bʰardʰéh₂
From Middle English barbel, from Old French barbel, from Vulgar Latin *barbellus, from Late Latin barbulus, diminutive of Latin barbus.

BARBER.d: A person whose profession is cutting the hair and beards of usually male customers.
BARBER.e:
PIE word
 *bʰardʰéh₂
From Middle English barbour, from Anglo-Norman barbour, from Old French barbeor, from barbe (“beard”), from Latin barba.

BARBET.d: Any of numerous arboreal birds of the families Capitonidae, Lybiidae, and Megalaimidae, within the order Piciformes.
BARBET.e: From French barbe (“beard; long hair of certain animals”).

BARFLY.d: A person who spends much time in a bar or similar drinking establishment

BARGEE.d: A crewman of a working barge.

BARHOP.d: To drink at a number of bars during a single day or evening.
BARHOP.e: From bar (“drinking establishment”) + hop (“move rapidly between locations”).

BARING.d: Present participle of BARE: Minimal; that is or are just sufficient.
BARING.e:
From Middle English bare, bar, from Old English bær (“bare, naked, open”), from Proto-West Germanic *baʀ, from Proto-Germanic *bazaz (“bare, naked”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰosós, from *bʰos- (“bare, barefoot”).
Cognate with Scots bare, bair (“bare”), Saterland Frisian bar (“...

BARITE.d: A mineral, barium sulphate, with the chemical formula BaSO₄.

BARIUM.d: The chemical element (symbol Ba) with an atomic number of 56. It is a soft, reactive, silvery alkaline earth metal.
BARIUM.e: Coined by British chemist Humphry Davy in 1808, from baryta + -ium.

BARKED.d: Past tense of BARK: To make a short, loud, explosive noise with the vocal organs (said of animals, especially dogs).
BARKED.e: From Middle English barken, berken, borken, from Old English beorcan (“to bark”), from the Proto-West Germanic *berkan (“to bark”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerg- (“to make a noise, growl, bark”), from *bʰer- (“to drone, hum, buzz”). Cognate with Icelandic berkja (“to bark, blu...

BARLEY.d: A cereal of the species Hordeum vulgare, or its grains, often used as food or to make beer and other malted drinks.
BARLEY.e: From Middle English barly, barli, from Old English bærlīċ (“barley-like”, adjective) (later referring to barley itself and grain crops of similar appearance), from bere (“barley”) (compare Scots bere (“six-rowed barley”)), from Proto-Germanic *baraz (compare Old Norse barr), from...

BARMAN.d: A man who works in a bar.

BARNEY.e: From either the Old English personal name Bera (genitive singular Beran) or from Old English beren (“growing with barley”) + īeġ (“island”).

BARONY.d: The domain of a baron or baroness, usually as part of a larger kingdom or empire.
BARONY.e: From Middle English baronie, baronye, from Old French baronie, equivalent to baron + -y.

BARQUE.d: A sailing vessel of three or more masts, with all masts but the sternmost square-rigged, the sternmost being fore-and-aft-rigged
BARQUE.e: From Middle English barke (“boat”), borrowed from Middle French barque, itself borrowed from Italian barca or a Medieval Latin equivalent, from Late Latin barca, from Vulgar Latin barica, from Ancient Greek βᾶρις (bâris) 'Egyptian boat', from Coptic ⲃⲁⲁⲣⲉ (baare, “small boat”), f...

BARRED.d: Past tense of BAR: A solid, more or less rigid object of metal or wood with a uniform cross-section smaller than its length.
BARRED.e: From Middle English barre, from Old French barre (“beam, bar, gate, barrier”), from Vulgar Latin *barra, of uncertain origin. Doublet of barre.

BARREL.d: A round (cylindrical) vessel, such as a cask, of greater length than breadth, and bulging in the middle, made of staves bound with hoops, and having flat ends (heads). The word is sometimes applied to a similar cylindrical container made of metal, usually called a drum.
BARREL.e: From Middle English barel, from Anglo-Norman baril, Old French baril, bareil (“barrel”), of uncertain origin. An attempt to link baril to Old French barre (“bar, bolt”) (compare Medieval Latin barra (“bar, rod”)) via assumed Vulgar Latin *barrīculum meets the phonological require...

BARREN.d: Not bearing children, childless; hence also unable to bear children, sterile.
BARREN.e: From Middle English bareyne, from Anglo-Norman baraigne, baraing (“sterile; barren”), of obscure origin; probably from a Germanic language, perhaps Frankish *baʀ (“bare; barren”), from Proto-Germanic *bazaz (“bare”). If so, a doublet of bare.

BARRER.d: Comparative form of BAR: A solid, more or less rigid object of metal or wood with a uniform cross-section smaller than its length.
BARRER.e: From Middle English barre, from Old French barre (“beam, bar, gate, barrier”), from Vulgar Latin *barra, of uncertain origin. Doublet of barre.

BARRIO.d: A municipality or subdivision of a municipality in Spanish America, and in Spain itself.
BARRIO.e: Borrowed from Spanish barrio, from Arabic بَرِّيّ (barriyy, “wild”).

BARROW.e:
From Middle English berwe, bergh, from Old English beorg (“mountain, hill, mound, barrow, burial place”), from Proto-West Germanic *berg, from Proto-Germanic *bergaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰérǵʰos, from *bʰerǵʰ-. Doublet of berg and bergh.
Cognate with Scots burrow (“mound, ...

BARTER.d: An exchange of goods or services without the use of money.
BARTER.e: Late Middle English, from Old French barater.

BARYON.d: A heavy subatomic particle created by the binding of quarks by gluons; a hadron containing three quarks. Baryons have half-odd integral spin and are thus fermions. This category includes the common proton and neutron of the atomic nucleus.
BARYON.e: From Ancient Greek βαρύς (barús, “heavy”) + -on. Coined by Dutch-American physicist Abraham Pais in 1953. Equivalent to baryo- + -on.

BASALT.d: A hard mafic igneous rock of varied mineral content; volcanic in origin, which makes up much of the Earth's oceanic crust.
BASALT.e: From Late Latin basaltes, a misspelling of Latin basanites, from Ancient Greek βασανίτης (basanítēs), from βάσανος (básanos, “touchstone”), from Egyptian bḫn (“a hard stone”), b-x:n-O39

BASHED.d: Past tense of BASH: To strike heavily.
BASHED.e: From Middle English *basshen, *basken, likely from Old Norse *baska (“to strike”), akin to Swedish basa (“to baste, whip, lash, flog”), Danish baske (“to beat, strike, cudgel”), German patschen (“to slap”)

BASHES.d: Plural of BASH: To strike heavily.
BASHES.e: From Middle English *basshen, *basken, likely from Old Norse *baska (“to strike”), akin to Swedish basa (“to baste, whip, lash, flog”), Danish baske (“to beat, strike, cudgel”), German patschen (“to slap”)

BASICS.d: Plural of BASIC: Forming an essential foundation; fundamental.

BASING.d: present participle and gerund of base

BASKET.d: A lightweight container, generally round, open at the top, and tapering toward the bottom.
BASKET.e:
From Middle English basket, from Anglo-Norman baschet, basket, bascat, of obscure origin.
One theory is that it derives from Late Latin bascauda (“kettle, table-vessel”), from Proto-Brythonic (in Breton baskodenn), from Proto-Celtic *baskis (“bundle, load”), from purported Proto-...

BASSES.d: Plural of BASS: Of sound, a voice or an instrument, low in pitch or frequency.
BASSES.e: A respelling of base under the influence of Italian basso (“low”).

BASSET.d: The edge of a geological stratum at the surface of the ground; the outcrop.
BASSET.e: From French bassette, from Italian bassetta.

BATBOY.d: A boy employed to watch over the bats, and assist the players in retrieving them during play.

BATEAU.d: A small, flat-bottomed type of boat.

BATHOS.d: Overdone or treacly attempts to inspire pathos.
BATHOS.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek βάθος (báthos, “depth”). Employed ironically following Alexander Pope's Peri Bathous, lampooning various errors in contemporary writers.

BATING.d: Present participle of BATE: To reduce the force of something; to abate.
BATING.e: Inherited from Middle English baten (“to abate”), an apheretic form of abaten, from Old French abatre (“to knock down”).

BATMAN.d: A servant or valet to a military officer.
BATMAN.e: From bat (“packsaddle”) + man. The element bat is from French bât, from Old French bast, from Late Latin bastum, possibly from Ancient Greek βαστάζω (bastázō, “to bear, carry, lift”).

BATTED.d: Past tense of BAT: Any flying mammal of the order Chiroptera, usually small and nocturnal, insectivorous or frugivorous.
BATTED.e:
Dialectal variant (akin to dialectal Swedish natt-batta) of Middle English bakke, balke, of North Germanic origin. Perhaps compare Old Norse (leðr)blaka (literally “(leather) flapper”), from leðr + blaka (“to flap”).
Compare Old Swedish natbakka, Old Danish nathbakkæ.

BATTEN.d: To cause (an animal, etc.) to become fat or thrive through plenteous feeding; to fatten.
BATTEN.e: The verb is derived from Middle English *battenen, *batnen, of North Germanic origin, probably from Old Norse batna (“to grow better, improve, recover”), from Proto-Germanic *batnaną (“to become better, improve”) (compare Old Norse bati (“advantage, improvement”), from Proto-Germ...

BATTER.d: To hit or strike violently and repeatedly.
BATTER.e: From Middle English batteren, batren, bateren, a frequentative of Middle English batten, baten (“to beat”), equivalent to bat + -er (frequentative suffix).

BATTLE.e: From Middle English batel, batell, batelle, batayle, bataylle, borrowed from Old French bataille, from Late Latin battālia, variant of battuālia (“fighting and fencing exercises”) from Latin battuō (“to strike, hit, beat, fight”), of uncertain origin. Possibly from a Gaulish or P...

BATTUE.d: A form of hunting in which game is forced into the open by the beating of sticks on bushes, etc.
BATTUE.e: From French battue, ultimately from Latin battere. Doublet of battuta, which arrived via Italian.

BAUBLE.d: A cheap showy ornament or piece of jewellery; a gewgaw.
BAUBLE.e: From Middle English bable, babel, babull, babulle, from Old French babel, baubel (“trinket, child's toy”), most likely a reduplication of bel, ultimately from Latin bellus (“pretty”).

BAWBEE.d: A coin originally worth six pennies Scots, and later three; held equivalent to an English halfpenny.

BAWDRY.d: The practice of procuring women for the gratification of lust.

BAWLED.d: Past tense of BAWL: To shout or utter in a loud and intense manner.
BAWLED.e: From Middle English baulen, from Old Norse baula (“to bellow”) and/or Medieval Latin baulō (“to bark”), both from Proto-Germanic *bau- (“to roar”), conflated with Proto-Germanic *bellaną, *ballijaną, *buljaną (“to shout, low, roar”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel- (“to sound, ro...

BAWLEY.d: A small fishing boat, equipped with sails, used mainly in the estuary of the Thames, England.

BAYING.d: Present participle of BAY: A body of water (especially the sea) contained by a concave shoreline.
BAYING.e: From French baie, from Late Latin baia, probably ultimately from Iberian or Basque badia. Partly displaced native Old English byht, whence bight.

BAZAAR.d: A marketplace, particularly in the Middle East and South Asia, and often covered with shops and stalls.
BAZAAR.e: From Middle French bazar or Italian bazar, from Ottoman Turkish بازار (bazar), from Persian بازار (bâzâr).

BAZOOM.e: A variant of bosom, influenced by zoom. Originally North American. Attested since the 1950s.

BEACHY.d: Pertaining to the material making up the edge of a seashore, as with pebbles, gravel, and sand.

BEACON.d: A signal fire to notify of the approach of an enemy, or to give any notice, commonly of warning.
BEACON.e:
From Middle English beken, from Old English bēacn (“sign, signal”), from Proto-West Germanic *baukn, from Proto-Germanic *baukną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeh₂u-, *bʰeh₂- (“to shine”).
Doublet of buoy. Compare West Frisian beaken (“buoy”), Dutch baken (“beacon”), Middle Low Ger...

BEADED.d: Past tense of BEAD: Prayer, later especially with a rosary.
BEADED.e:
From Middle English bede (“a prayer”), also “a bead for counting prayers” in a peire of bedes (literally “a pair of beads”), from Old English bedu, bed, ġebed (“a request, entreaty, prayer”), from Proto-West Germanic *bedu, *bed, *gabed, from Proto-Germanic *bedō, *bedą.
Cognate ...

BEADLE.d: A parish constable, a uniformed minor (lay) official, who ushers and keeps order.
BEADLE.e: From Middle English bedel, bidel, from Old English bydel (“warrant officer, apparitor”), from Proto-West Germanic *budil, from Proto-Germanic *budilaz (“herald”), equivalent to bid + -le. Cognate with Dutch beul, German Büttel. More at bid.

BEAGLE.d: A small short-legged smooth-coated scenthound, often tricolored and sometimes used for hunting hares. Its friendly disposition makes it suitable as a family pet.
BEAGLE.e: Inherited from Middle English *begel (attested in the plural begles), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Middle French beegueule (“one who keeps their mouth open”), whence modern French bégueule (“a colloquial insult said to women of low status and accused of stupidity, who alway...

BEAKED.d: Past tense of BEAK: A rigid structure projecting from the front of a bird's face, used for pecking, grooming, foraging, carrying items, eating food, etc.
BEAKED.e: From Middle English bec, borrowed from Anglo-Norman bec, Old French bec, from Latin beccus, from Gaulish *bekkos, from Proto-Celtic *bekkos (“beak, snout”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bak-, *baḱ- (“pointed stick, peg”). Cognate with Breton beg (“beak”). Compare Saterland ...

BEAMED.d: Past tense of BEAM: Any large piece of timber or iron long in proportion to its thickness, and prepared for use.
BEAMED.e:
From Middle English beem, from Old English bēam (“tree, cross, gallows, column, pillar, wood, beam, splint, post, stock, rafter, piece of wood”), from Proto-West Germanic *baum, from Proto-Germanic *baumaz (“tree, beam, balk”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰew- (“to grow, swell”).
...

BEANED.d: Past tense of BEAN: Any plant of several genera of the taxonomic family Fabaceae that produces large edible seeds or edible seedpods.
BEANED.e: From Middle English bene, from Old English bēan, from Proto-West Germanic *baunu, from Proto-Germanic *baunō (“bean”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰabʰ- (“bean”). Cognate with Scots bene, bein (“bean”), North Frisian buan (“bean”), Saterland Frisian Boone (“bean”), West Frisian be...

BEANIE.d: A cap that fits the head closely, usually knitted from wool.

BEARDS.d: Plural of BEARD: Hair growing on a man's chin and cheeks.

BEARED.d: Past tense of BEAR: A large, generally omnivorous mammal (a few species are purely carnivorous or herbivorous), having shaggy fur, a very small tail, and flat feet; a member of the family Ursidae.
BEARED.e:
From Middle English bere, from Old English bera, from Proto-West Germanic *berō, from Proto-Germanic *berô, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerH- (“brown”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Boar, Boare (“bear”), West Frisian bear (“bear”), Cimbrian, Mòcheno per (“bear”), Dutch beer (“be...

BEAUED.d: Past tense of BEAU: A man with a reputation for fine dress and etiquette; a dandy or fop.
BEAUED.e: From Middle English beau, beu, bew, bewe, from Old French beau, from Latin bellus (“beautiful”). Doublet of bello and boo.

BEAUTY.d: The quality of being (especially visually) attractive, pleasing, fine or good-looking; comeliness.
BEAUTY.e: From Middle English bewty, bewte, beaute, bealte, from Anglo-Norman and Old French beauté (early Old French spelling biauté), from Vulgar Latin *bellitātem (“beauty”), from Latin bellus (“beautiful, fair”); see beau. In this sense, mostly displaced native Old English fæġernes, wh...

BEAVER.d: A semiaquatic rodent of the genus Castor, having a wide, flat tail and webbed feet, native to the Northern Hemisphere.
BEAVER.e:
From Middle English bever, from Old English befer, from Proto-West Germanic *bebru, from Proto-Germanic *bebruz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰébʰrus (“beaver”).
Cognate with West Frisian bever, Dutch bever, French bièvre, German Biber, dialectal Swedish bjur. Non-Germanic cognates...

BECALM.d: To make calm or still; make quiet; calm.

BECKED.d: Past tense of BECK: A stream or small river.
BECKED.e:
From Middle English bek, bekk, becc, from Old English bæc, bec, bæċe, beċe (“beck, brook”), from Proto-Germanic *bakiz (“stream”).
Cognate with Old Norse bekkr (“a stream or brook”), Low German bek, beck, German Bach, Dutch beek, Swedish bäck, Doublet of batch. More at beach.

BECKET.d: A short piece of rope spliced to form a circle
BECKET.e: Compare Dutch bek (“beak”) beak, and English beak.

BECKON.d: To wave or nod to somebody with the intention to make the person come closer.
BECKON.e: From Middle English bekenen, beknen, becnen, beknien, from Old English bēacnian, bēcnian, bīecnan (“to signal; beckon”), from Proto-West Germanic *bauknōn, *bauknijan (“to signal”), from *baukn (“signal; beacon”). Cognate with Old Saxon bōknian, Old High German bouhnen, Old Norse...

BECOME.e:
A compound of the sources of be- + come.
From Middle English becomen, bicumen, from Old English becuman (“to come (to), approach, arrive, enter, meet with, fall in with; happen, befall; befit”), from Proto-Germanic *bikwemaną (“to come around, come about, come across, come by”), ...

BEDAUB.e: From be- (“thoroughly, extensively”) + daub, from Old French dauber (“to plaster, whitewash”), from Latin dealbō (“whiten over, plaster”).

BEDBUG.d: A small nocturnal insect pest of humans, of species Cimex lectularius (common bedbug) and Cimex hemipterus (tropical bedbug) that feeds on the blood of humans during sleep.

BEDDED.d: Past tense of BED: A piece of furniture, usually flat and soft, on which to rest or sleep.
BEDDED.e:
Inherited from Middle English bed, bedde, from Old English bedd, from Proto-West Germanic *badi, from Proto-Germanic *badją (“resting-place, plot of ground”).
Cognates
Cognate with North Frisian baad, beed, Saterland Frisian Bääd, West Frisian bêd, Low German Bedd, Dutch bed, Ger...

BEDDER.d: Comparative form of BED: A piece of furniture, usually flat and soft, on which to rest or sleep.
BEDDER.e:
Inherited from Middle English bed, bedde, from Old English bedd, from Proto-West Germanic *badi, from Proto-Germanic *badją (“resting-place, plot of ground”).
Cognates
Cognate with North Frisian baad, beed, Saterland Frisian Bääd, West Frisian bêd, Low German Bedd, Dutch bed, Ger...

BEDECK.e: From be- + deck. Compare West Frisian bedekke (“to cover”), Dutch bedekken (“to cover, coat, overlay”), German bedecken (“to cover, top, overlay”), Swedish betäcka (“to cover, shelter”). Doublet of bethatch.

BEDLAM.d: A place or situation of chaotic uproar, and where confusion prevails.
BEDLAM.e: From Bedlam, alternative name of the English lunatic asylum, Bethlem Royal Hospital (royal hospital from 1375, mental hospital from 1403) (earlier St Mary of Bethlehem outside Bishopsgate, hospice in existence from 1329, priory established 1247), since used to mean “a place or si...

BEDPAN.d: A pan used for urination and defecation while in bed, now usually for reasons of medical necessity or convenience.

BEDSIT.d: A form of rented accommodation consisting of a single room for use as both sitting room and bedroom; there may also be a small kitchen area and washing and toilet facilities, but these amenities are more commonly outside the room and shared by several tenants.

BEEFED.d: Past tense of BEEF: The meat from cattle or other bovines.
BEEFED.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
From Middle English beef, bef, beof, borrowed from Anglo-Norman beof, Old French buef, boef (“ox”) (modern French bœuf); from Latin bōs (“ox”), from Proto-Italic *gʷōs, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *gʷṓws. Doublet of cow.
Beef in the sense of “a grudge, ar...

BEEPED.d: Past tense of BEEP: The sound produced by the horn of a car, or any similar sound.

BEETLE.d: Any of numerous species of insect in the order Coleoptera characterized by a pair of hard, shell-like front wings which cover and protect a pair of rear wings when at rest.
BEETLE.e: From Middle English bitle, bityl, bytylle, from Old English bitula, bitela, bītel (“beetle”), from Proto-West Germanic *bitilō, *bītil, from Proto-Germanic *bitilô, *bītilaz (“that which tends to bite, biter, beetle”), equivalent to bite + -le. Cognate with Old High German bicco ...

BEEVES.d: Plural of BEEF: The meat from cattle or other bovines.
BEEVES.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
From Middle English beef, bef, beof, borrowed from Anglo-Norman beof, Old French buef, boef (“ox”) (modern French bœuf); from Latin bōs (“ox”), from Proto-Italic *gʷōs, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *gʷṓws. Doublet of cow.
Beef in the sense of “a grudge, ar...

BEEZER.e: Unknown, perhaps from Spanish cabeza (“head”), though the meaning “head” appears to somewhat postdate “nose” in English. First attested in 1908, originally apparently as American boxing slang. Various sources have suggested a borrowing, perhaps by American sailors or marines, fro...

BEFALL.d: To fall upon; fall all over; overtake.
BEFALL.e: From Middle English bifallen, from Old English befeallan, from Proto-West Germanic *bifallan, from Proto-Germanic *bifallaną; equivalent to be- + fall.

BEFOOL.d: To make a fool out of (someone); to fool, trick, or deceive (someone).
BEFOOL.e: From Middle English bifolen, equivalent to be- + fool.

BEFOUL.d: To make foul; to soil; to contaminate, pollute.

BEGGAR.e:
From Middle English beggere, beggare, beggar (“beggar”), from Middle English beggen (“to beg”), equivalent to beg + -ar.
Alternative etymology derives Middle English beggere, beggare, beggar from Old French begart, originally a member of the Beghards, a lay brotherhood of mendica...

BEGGED.d: Past tense of BEG: To request the help of someone, often in the form of money.

BEGINS.d: Plural of BEGIN: To start; to come into being.

BEGIRD.d: To bind with a band or girdle; to gird.

BEHALF.e: From Middle English bihalve (“nearby”), from Old English bī healfe (“by [his/her] side”), from bī (“by”) + healfe (“side, half”), equivalent to be- + half.

BEHEAD.d: To deliberately remove the head of; to cut off (someone's) head.
BEHEAD.e: From Middle English beheden, bihefden, biheveden, from Old English behēafdian (“to behead”), equivalent to be- (“off, away”) + head.

BEHEST.e: From Middle English biheste, from Old English behǣs (“vow, promise”), from Proto-West Germanic *bihaisi, from *bi- (“be-”) + *haisi (“command”), from Proto-Germanic *haisiz, from *haitaną (“to command”). Final -t by analogy with other similar words in -t. Related to Old English b...

BEINGS.d: Plural of BEING: Existence; a living creature.

BELATE.d: To impede; cause something to be late; delay; benight.

BELFRY.d: A tower or steeple typically containing bells, especially as part of a church.
BELFRY.e: From Middle English belfrey, bellfray, belfray, from Old French belfroi, berfroi, berfrey (changed to have an ⟨l⟩ by association with bell), from Middle High German bërcvrit or bërvrit (“defensive tower”) (modern German Bergfried), possibly via Late Latin berefredus, from Proto-G...

BELIED.d: Past tense of BELY: Obsolete spelling of belly.

BELIEF.d: Mental acceptance of a claim as true.
BELIEF.e:
From Middle English bileve, from Old English lēafa, from Proto-West Germanic *laubu from Proto-Germanic *laubō. Compare German Glaube (“faith, belief”).

BELIER.d: Comparative form of BELY: Obsolete spelling of belly.

BELIES.d: Plural of BELY: Obsolete spelling of belly.

BELLOW.d: The deep roar of a large animal, or any similar loud noise.
BELLOW.e: From Middle English belwen, from Old English belgan, bylgan, ultimately from the Proto-Indo-European *bʰel- (“to sound, roar”), whence also belg (“leather bag”), bellan (“to roar”), blāwan (“to blow”). Cognate with German bellen (“to bark”), Russian бле́ять (bléjatʹ, “baa, bleat”...

BELOWS.d: Plural of BELOW: At a lower level or position.

BELTED.d: Past tense of BELT: A band worn around the waist to hold clothing to one's body (usually pants), hold weapons (such as a gun or sword), or serve as a decorative piece of clothing.
BELTED.e: From Middle English belt, from Old English belt (“belt, girdle”), from Proto-West Germanic *baltī̆, from Proto-Germanic *baltijaz (“girdle, belt”), from Latin balteus (“belt, sword-belt”), of Etruscan origin. Cognate with Scots belt (“belt”), Dutch belt, German Balz (“belt”), Dan...

BEMIRE.d: To soil with mud or a similar substance.
BEMIRE.e: From Middle English *bemyren (possibly attested in Middle English bemyred), equivalent to be- (“all over”) + mire.

BEMOAN.e: From Middle English bemenen, bimenen, from Old English bemǣnan (“to bemoan, bewail, lament”); equivalent to be- (“about, concerning”) + moan. Alteration of vowel from Middle to Modern English due to analogy with moan.

BEMUSE.e: From be- + muse. In meaning, influenced by bemaze and later amuse.

BENDED.d: Past tense of BEND: To cause (something) to change its shape into a curve, by physical force, chemical action, or any other means.
BENDED.e:
From Middle English benden, from Old English bendan (“to bind or bend (a bow), fetter, restrain”), from Proto-West Germanic *bandijan, from Proto-Germanic *bandijaną (“to bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰendʰ- (“to bind, tie”).
Cognate with Middle High German benden (“to fette...

BENIGN.e: From Middle English benigne, benygne, from Old French benigne, from Latin benignus (“kind, good”), from bene (“well”) + genus (“origin, kind”). Compare malign.

BENNET.d: A surname transferred from the given name, a less common spelling of Bennett.
BENNET.e: From Benedict. See French Benoît, Norman Beneît. Doublet of Benoit and Benito.

BENUMB.d: To make numb, as by cold or anesthetic.

BENZOL.d: An impure benzene (mixed with toluene etc), used in the arts as a solvent, and for various other purposes.

BENZYL.d: The univalent radical C₆H₅-CH₂- related to toluene and benzoic acid

BESEEM.e:
PIE word
 *h₁epi
From Middle English bisemen (“to beseem”) [and other forms], from be-, bi- (prefix forming transitive verbs with a completive, figurative, or intensifying sense) + semen (“to seem; to be or see as appropriate; to be visible or apparent; to regard”). Semen is deri...

BESIDE.d: Next to; at the side of.
BESIDE.e: From Middle English beside, besiden, bisyde (also besides > besides), from Old English be sīdan, bī sīdan (“by the side (of), on the side (of)”). Compare Saterland Frisian biesiede (“aside”), German Low German bisied (“aside”), German beiseite (“aside, to one side”). Compare also...

BESTED.d: Past tense of BEST: superlative form of good: most good.
BESTED.e:
From Middle English beste, best, from Old English betst, betest, from Proto-Germanic *batistaz.
Cognates

BESTIR.d: To put into brisk or vigorous action; to move with life and vigor.
BESTIR.e: From Middle English bestyrien, bestirien, from Old English bestyrian (“to heap up, pile up”), equivalent to be- + stir.

BETAKE.d: To take over to; take across (to); deliver.
BETAKE.e: From Middle English bitaken, equivalent to be- + take. Cognate with Danish betage (“to take, deprive, cut off”), Swedish beta (“to take, deprive, cut off”).

BETHEL.e: From Hebrew בֵּית אֵל (beth el, literally “house of God”). See also Bethel on Wikipedia.Wikipedia.

BETONY.e: From Middle English betayny, betanie, from Medieval Latin betōnia (possibly through Old French), from Latin betōnica or ve(t)tōnica, from Vettones, a people in Lusitania. Compare French bétoine.

BETRAY.d: To deliver into the hands of an enemy by treachery or fraud, in violation of trust; to give up treacherously or faithlessly.
BETRAY.e:
From Middle English betrayen, bitrayen (“to commit an act of treason against”), equivalent to be- + tray (“to betray”).
further etymology information

BETTED.e: From 16th-century criminal slang, perhaps from Middle English bet (“something better, advantage, luck”), from Old English bet, bett (“better”, adverb); or, alternatively from abet, from Middle English abet, abette, from Old French abet (“incitement to evil”), from Old French abet...

BETTER.d: comparative form of good: more good
BETTER.e:
From Middle English better, bettre, betre, from Old English betera (“better”), from Proto-West Germanic *batiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *batizô (“better”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰed-rós, from *bʰed- (“good”).
Cognate with Sanskrit भद्र (bhadrá, “blessed, fortunate, happy, good”...

BEVIES.d: Plural of BEVY: A group of animals, particularly quail.
BEVIES.e: From Middle English bevey, of uncertain origin, possibly Anglo-Norman. Also modern Scouse variant spelling of bevvy.

BEWAIL.d: To wail over; to feel or express deep sorrow for.
BEWAIL.e: From Middle English bewailen, equivalent to be- (“over, about”) + wail.

BEWARE.d: To use caution, pay attention to (used both with and without of).
BEWARE.e: From Middle English bewar, be war, be ware, forms of Middle English ben ware (“to be on one's guard, be vigilant”, literally “be ware”), equivalent to be + ware or be + aware. Compare Old English bewarian.

BEZANT.d: A coin made of gold or silver, minted at Byzantium and used in currency throughout mediaeval Europe.
BEZANT.e: From Middle English besaunt, from Old French bezant, nominative bezanz, from Latin byzantius (“of Byzantium”).

BEZOAR.d: A mass, usually of hair or undigested vegetable matter, found in a human or animal's intestines, similar to a hairball.
BEZOAR.e: From Spanish bezoar and/or French bézoard, based on Arabic بَازَهْر (bāzahr), from Middle Persian pʾtzhl (pādzahr, “bezoar, antidote”), from a compound of words meaning “to protect” and “poison” (literally “killing thing”), thus a bezoar was “that which protects against poison”. ...

BHAJAN.d: A type of Indian devotional song.

From Middle French biais, adverbially ("sideways, askance, against the grain") c. 1250, as a noun ("oblique angle, slant") from the late 16th century.

BIASES.e:

BIBBED.d: Past tense of BIB: An item of clothing for people (especially babies) tied around their neck to protect their clothes from getting dirty when eating.
BIBBED.e: Originally verb sense “drink heartily”, from Middle English bibben, either from Latin bibō (“I drink”) or of imitative origin. Noun sense (clothing) presumably either because worn while drinking, or because the clothing itself “drinks up” spills.

BIBBER.d: Comparative form of BIB: An item of clothing for people (especially babies) tied around their neck to protect their clothes from getting dirty when eating.
BIBBER.e: Originally verb sense “drink heartily”, from Middle English bibben, either from Latin bibō (“I drink”) or of imitative origin. Noun sense (clothing) presumably either because worn while drinking, or because the clothing itself “drinks up” spills.

BIFFED.d: Past tense of BIFF: A sudden, sharp blow or punch.

BIGEYE.d: Any fish in the taxonomic family Priacanthidae, which have large eyes.

BIGGER.d: Comparative form of BIG: Of great size, large.
BIGGER.e: Inherited from Northern Middle English big, bigge (“powerful, strong”), possibly from a dialect of Old Norse. Ultimately perhaps a derivative of Proto-Germanic *bugja- (“swollen up, thick”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰew-, *bu- (“to swell”), in which case big would be related to...

BIGRAM.d: An n-gram consisting of two items from a sequence.

BIGWIG.d: A person of importance in a group or organization.
BIGWIG.e: First arose in the 1730s, from big + wig. Formerly, English men of authority wore wigs. Bigwig plays on the idea that higher authority is denoted by a larger wig.

BIKING.d: Present participle of BIKE: Clipping of bicycle.
BIKING.e:
Clipping of bicycle. First attested in 1882.

BIKINI.e: From French bikini, named after the place name Bikini, from English Bikini, the name of the atoll where the United States tested nuclear weapons in July 1946; it was reckoned that the bathing suit would cause as much excitement as a nuclear bomb. This name was originally from Ger...

BILKED.e: Uncertain; perhaps a variant form of balk.

BILLED.d: Past tense of BILL: A written list or inventory. (Now obsolete except in specific senses or set phrases; bill of lading, bill of goods, etc.)
BILLED.e: From Middle English bille, from Anglo-Norman bille, from Old French bulle, from Medieval Latin bulla (“seal, sealed document”). Doublet of bull (“papal bull; bubble”) and bulla.

BINARY.d: Being in one of two mutually exclusive states.
BINARY.e: From Late Latin bīnārius (“consisting of two”), from Latin bīnī (“two-by-two, pair”). By surface analysis, bin- + -ary.

BINATE.d: Double; growing in pairs or couples.
BINATE.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Latin binus (“two each, in pairs”) + -ate (adjective-forming suffix)

BINDER.e: From Middle English byndere; equivalent to bind + -er.

BINDLE.d: A length of cord, rope, twine, etc, used to bind something.
BINDLE.e: Unknown; compare Old English bindele (“a binding, a tying”) from bindan (“to bind”), and bundle. Additionally, compare mister from master.

BIOGAS.d: A mixture of methane and carbon dioxide, produced by anaerobic digestion of organic waste matter, used as a fuel.

BIOPIC.d: A motion picture based on the life (or lives) of a real, rather than fictional, person (or people).
BIOPIC.e: Clipping of biographical picture; synchronically bio + pic.

BIOPSY.d: The removal and examination of a sample of tissue, cells, or bodily fluid from a living body for diagnostic purposes.

BIOTIN.d: A sulfur-containing member of the vitamin B complex, 5-[(3aS,4S,6aR)-2-oxohexahydro-1H-thieno[3,4-d]imidazol-4-yl]pentanoic acid, found in liver, egg yolk, milk, and yeast, essential to the activity of multiple enzyme systems.
BIOTIN.e: Borrowed from German Biotin, from Ancient Greek βίοτος (bíotos, “life”) + the suffix -in.

BIRDIE.d: A bird; especially, a small and cute one.

BIREME.d: An ancient galley having two banks of oars, one above the other.

BIRTHS.d: Plural of BIRTH: The emergence of a baby from its mother's body.

BISECT.d: To cut or divide into two parts.
BISECT.e: From bi- (“bi-, two”) + Latin secāre (“to cut”).

BISHOP.d: An overseer of congregations: either any such overseer, generally speaking, or (in Eastern Orthodoxy, Catholicism, Anglicanism, etc.) an official in the church hierarchy (actively or nominally) governing a diocese, supervising the church's priests, deacons, and property in its territory.

BISQUE.e: Borrowed from French bisque, possibly from Biscaye.

BISTRO.d: A small casual restaurant or pub, typically serving French-style cuisine.
BISTRO.e: Attested from c. 1920, from the French bistro(t) with the original meaning "proprietor of a tavern" (1880s), of unknown origin, presumably regional French dialect. See the French etymology for more.

BITCHY.d: Spiteful or malevolent; catty; malicious; unpleasant.

BITING.d: present participle and gerund of bite

BITMAP.d: A series of bits that represents a rasterized graphic image, each pixel being represented as a group of bits.

BITTED.d: Past tense of BIT: A piece of metal placed in a horse's mouth and connected to the reins to direct the animal.
BITTED.e:
From Middle English bitte, bite, from Old English bita (“bit; fragment; morsel”) and bite (“a bite; cut”), from Proto-Germanic *bitô and *bitiz; both from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“to split”). More at bite.

BITTER.d: Having an acrid taste (usually from a basic substance).
BITTER.e: From Middle English bitter, bittre, from Old English bitter, biter (“bitter”), from Proto-West Germanic *bitr, from Proto-Germanic *bitraz (“bitter”), equivalent to bite + -er (agent noun suffix) used attributively. Cognate with Saterland Frisian bitter, West Frisian bitter, Low ...

BLACKS.d: Plural of BLACK: The darkest colour, opposite of white.

BLAMED.d: Past tense of BLAME: To hold responsible for a fault.

BLAMES.d: Plural of BLAME: To hold responsible for a fault.

BLANCH.e:
From Middle English blaunchen, from Old French blanchir, from Old French blanc (“white”), from Early Medieval Latin blancus, from Frankish *blank, from Proto-Germanic *blankaz (“bright, shining, blinding, white”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleyǵ- (“to shine”).

BLANKS.d: Plural of BLANK: Empty; not written or printed on.

BLAZAR.d: A very compact quasar, associated with a supermassive black hole at the center of an active galaxy.
BLAZAR.e: Blend of B + L + Lac + quasar. Coined by astronomer Edward Spiegel in 1978 from BL Lac object and quasar, punning blazing from its optical presentation compared to usual quasars. By surface analysis, blaze + -ar.

BLAZON.d: A verbal or written description of a coat of arms.
BLAZON.e: From Middle English blason, blasoun (“shield”), from Old French blason (“shield”).

BLEACH.d: A chemical, such as sodium hypochlorite or hydrogen peroxide, or a preparation of such a chemical, used for disinfecting or whitening.
BLEACH.e:
From Middle English blechen, from Old English blǣċan (“to bleach, whiten”), from Proto-West Germanic *blaikijan, from Proto-Germanic *blaikijaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel- (“to shine”).
Cognate with Dutch bleken (“to bleach”), German bleichen (“to bleach”), Danish blege, Sw...

BLEARY.d: Tired, having senses dulled by exhaustion.
BLEARY.e: From Middle English blery, equivalent to blear + -y. Compare Old English bleriġ (“bald”).

BLENCH.d: To shrink; start back; give way; flinch; turn aside or fly off.
BLENCH.e: From Middle English blench and blenchen, from Old English blenċan (“to deceive, cheat”), from Proto-Germanic *blankijaną (“to deceive”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleyǵ-. Cognate with Icelandic blekkja (“to deceive, cheat, impose upon”).

BLENDS.d: Plural of BLEND: To mix together; a mixture.

BLENNY.d: A true blenny, any of various marine fishes from the suborder Blennioidei or order Blenniiformes that are generally small and elongated which dwell on the sea floor, including scaled and scaleless forms and dramatically divergent appearance, in several families.
BLENNY.e: From Latin blennius, blendius, from Ancient Greek βλεννός (blennós, “mucus, slime”) (whence Modern Greek βλέννα (vlénna)), because of its slimy coating. From Proto-Indo-European *mel- (“soft”).

BLIGHT.d: A diseased condition suffered by a plant; specifically, a complete and rapid chlorosis, browning, then death of plant tissues such as floral organs, leaves, branches, or twigs, especially one caused by a fungus; a mildew, a rust, a smut.
BLIGHT.e:
The etymology of the noun is uncertain; suggested derivations include the following:

BLINDS.d: Plural of BLIND: Unable to see.

BLITHE.d: Casually careless or indifferent; showing a lack of concern; nonchalant.
BLITHE.e: From Middle English blithe (“glad, happy, joyful; causing joy, joyous; gentle, mild; gracious, merciful; bright, shining; beautiful, fair”) [and other forms], from Old English blīþe (“happy, gentle”), from Proto-West Germanic *blīþī, from Proto-Germanic *blīþiz (“friendly; gentle...

BLOBBY.d: Similar in shape to blobs; amorphous and rounded in appearance; partially irregular in appearance like bubbles.
BLOBBY.e: From Late Middle English blobby, equivalent to blob + -y.

BLOCKS.d: Plural of BLOCK: A solid piece of material; to obstruct.

BLOGGY.d: Having the characteristics of a blog; resembling a blog.

BLONDE.d: Alternative form of blond (“person with fair hair”). (Used especially of a woman. See the usage notes in the entry blond.)
BLONDE.e: From Middle French blonde f. See blond.

BLOODS.d: Plural of BLOOD: The red liquid flowing through the body.

BLOODY.e: From Middle English blody, blodi, from Old English blōdiġ, blōdeġ (“bloody”), from Proto-West Germanic *blōdag, from Proto-Germanic *blōþagaz (“bloody”), equivalent to blood + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian bläidich, blöidig, blouderch (“bloody”), West Frisian bloedich (“bloo...

BLOTCH.d: An uneven patch of color or discoloration.
BLOTCH.e: Uncertain. Perhaps a blend of blot + botch.

BLOUSE.d: A shirt, typically loose and reaching from the neck to the waist.
BLOUSE.e:
1828, from French blouse (“a workman's or peasant's smock”), see that for more.
More at blee, fold.

BLOUSY.d: Resembling or characteristic of a blouse; loose, flowing.

BLOWSY.d: Having a reddish, coarse complexion, especially with a pudgy face.

BLUESY.d: Characteristic of, or similar to, blues music.

BLUING.d: A substance used in laundry to whiten clothes.

BLUISH.d: Having a tint or hue similar to the colour blue.
BLUISH.e: From Middle English blewissh, blewisch (also Middle English bloysh), equivalent to blue + -ish.

BLURRY.d: Not clear, crisp, or focused; having fuzzy edges.

BOARDS.d: Plural of BOARD: A flat piece of wood; a group of directors.

BOATED.d: Past tense of BOAT: A craft used for transportation of goods, fishing, racing, recreational cruising, or military use on or in the water, propelled by oars or outboard motor or inboard motor or by wind.
BOATED.e: From Middle English bot, boot, boet, boyt (“boat”), from Old English bāt (“boat”), from Proto-West Germanic *bait, from Proto-Germanic *baitaz, *baitą (“boat, small ship”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“to break, split”) (whence also fissure via Latin). Cognate with Old Nors...

BOBBED.d: Past tense of BOB: To move gently and vertically, in either a single motion or repeatedly up and down, at or near the surface of a body of water, or similar medium.
BOBBED.e: From Middle English bobben (“to strike, beat, shake, jog”), of uncertain origin. Compare Scots bob (“to mark, dance with a bobbing motion”), Icelandic boppa (“to wave up and down”), Swedish bobba (“to bob”), Dutch dobberen ("bobbing").

BOBBER.d: Comparative form of BOB: To move gently and vertically, in either a single motion or repeatedly up and down, at or near the surface of a body of water, or similar medium.
BOBBER.e: From Middle English bobben (“to strike, beat, shake, jog”), of uncertain origin. Compare Scots bob (“to mark, dance with a bobbing motion”), Icelandic boppa (“to wave up and down”), Swedish bobba (“to bob”), Dutch dobberen ("bobbing").

BOBBIN.d: A spool or cylinder around which wire is coiled.
BOBBIN.e: Borrowed from French bobine, recorded in English since 1530.

BOBBLE.d: A furry ball attached on top of a hat.
BOBBLE.e:
* (noun): from bob + -le (diminutive suffix).
* (verb): from bob + -le (frequentative suffix).
Compare bauble.

BOBCAT.d: A North American wildcat (Lynx rufus), having tufted ears and a short tail.
BOBCAT.e: From bob (short hair; with reference to its tail) + cat.

BODEGA.d: A storehouse for maturing wine, a winery.
BODEGA.e: Borrowed from Spanish bodega, from Latin apotheca (“storehouse”), from Ancient Greek ἀποθήκη (apothḗkē, “storehouse”). Doublet of apotheke and boutique. In New York popularized by the Puerto Rican community.

BODICE.d: A corset-like sleeveless overgarment for women, sometimes provided with detachable sleeves.
BODICE.e: From bodies, plural of body (“upper part of a dress”).

BODIED.d: Past tense of BODY: Physical frame.
BODIED.e: From Middle English body, bodi, bodiȝ, from Old English bodiġ, bodeġ (“body, trunk, chest, torso, height, stature”), from Proto-West Germanic *bodag (“body, trunk”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰewdʰ- (“to be awake, observe”). Cognate with Old High German botah (“body, corpse, tru...

BODIER.d: Comparative form of BODY: Physical frame.
BODIER.e: From Middle English body, bodi, bodiȝ, from Old English bodiġ, bodeġ (“body, trunk, chest, torso, height, stature”), from Proto-West Germanic *bodag (“body, trunk”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰewdʰ- (“to be awake, observe”). Cognate with Old High German botah (“body, corpse, tru...

BODIES.e: From Middle English body, bodi, bodiȝ, from Old English bodiġ, bodeġ (“body, trunk, chest, torso, height, stature”), from Proto-West Germanic *bodag (“body, trunk”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰewdʰ- (“to be awake, observe”). Cognate with Old High German botah (“body, corpse, tru...

BODKIN.d: A small sharp pointed tool for making holes in cloth or leather.
BODKIN.e: From Middle English boydekin (“dagger”), apparently from *boyde, *boide (of unknown [Celtic?] origin) + -kin. Cognate with Scots botkin, boitkin, boikin (“bodkin”).

BOFFIN.d: An engineer or scientist, especially one engaged in technological or military research.
BOFFIN.e:
Origin unknown; a number of possible etymologies have been suggested, but no conclusive evidence exists.
One strong theory conjectures a connection from the "Mr. Boffins" of English novels, such as in Dickens' Our Mutual Friend.

BOGGED.d: Past tense of BOG: An area of decayed vegetation (particularly sphagnum moss) which forms a wet spongy ground too soft for walking.
BOGGED.e:
Inherited from Middle English bog (originally chiefly in Ireland and Scotland), from Irish and Scottish Gaelic bogach (“soft, boggy ground”), from Old Irish bog (“soft”), from Proto-Celtic *buggos (“soft, tender”) + Old Irish -ach, from Proto-Celtic *-ākos.
The frequent use to fo...

BOGGLE.d: (literally or figuratively) to stop or hesitate as if suddenly seeing a bogle.
BOGGLE.e: Variation or derivation of bogle, possibly cognate with bug.

BOILED.d: Past tense of BOIL: A localized accumulation of pus in the skin, resulting from infection.
BOILED.e:
From Middle English bile, büle (“boil, tumor”), from Old English bȳl, bȳle (“boil, swelling”), from Proto-Germanic *būlijō, *būlō (“boil”).
Akin to Dutch buil (“boil, swelling”), German Beule (“boil, hump”), Icelandic beyla (“swelling, hump”). The expected form is bile; the round...

BOKKEN.d: A wooden katana, used as a training sword.
BOKKEN.e: From Japanese 木剣 (ぼっけん, bokken, “wooden sword”), see below.

BOLDED.d: Past tense of BOLD: Courageous, daring.
BOLDED.e: From Middle English bold, bolde, bald, beald, from Old English bald, beald (“bold, brave, confident, strong, of good courage, presumptuous, impudent”), from Proto-West Germanic *balþ, from Proto-Germanic *balþaz (“strong, bold”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel-, *bʰlē- (“to bloat...

BOLERO.d: A lively Spanish dance in 3/4 time; also an unrelated slower-tempo dance of Cuban origin, in 2/4 time.

BOLETE.d: A type of fruiting body produced by certain fungus species in the order Boletales, especially those of genus Boletus, many of which are prized for their flavour; any species of said order that produces such a fruiting body.
BOLETE.e: Borrowed from Latin bōlētus (“edible mushroom”), from Ancient Greek βωλίτης (bōlítēs).

BOLTED.d: Past tense of BOLT: A (usually) metal fastener consisting of a cylindrical body that is threaded, with a larger head on one end. It can be inserted into an unthreaded hole up to the head, with a nut then threaded on the other end; a heavy machine screw.
BOLTED.e: From Middle English bolt, from Old English bolt, from Proto-West Germanic *bolt, from Proto-Germanic *bultaz, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeld- (“to knock, strike”). Compare Lithuanian beldu (“I knock”), baldas (“pole for striking”). Akin to Dutch and West Frisian bout, Ge...

BOLTER.d: A person or thing that bolts, or runs suddenly.

BONBON.d: A sweet, especially a small chocolate-covered candy.
BONBON.e: Borrowed from French bonbon, reduplication of bon (“good”), from Latin bonus.

BONDED.d: Past tense of BOND: A document constituting evidence of a long-term debt, by which the bond issuer (the borrower) is obliged to pay interest when due, and repay the principal at maturity, as specified on the face of the bond certificate. The rights of the holder are specified in the bond indenture, which contains the legal terms and conditions under which the bond was issued. Bonds are available in two forms: registered bonds, and bearer bonds.
BONDED.e: From Middle English bond, a variant of band, from Old English beand, bænd, bend (“bond, chain, fetter, band, ribbon, ornament, chaplet, crown”), from Proto-Germanic *bandaz, *bandiz (“band, fetter”). Cognate with Dutch band, German Band, Swedish band. Doublet of Bund. Related to ...

BONGED.d: Past tense of BONG: The clang of a large bell.

BONIER.d: Comparative form of BONY: Resembling, having the appearance or consistence of, or relating to bone; osseous.
BONIER.e: From Middle English bony, equivalent to bone + -y.

BONING.d: Present participle of BONE: A composite material consisting largely of calcium phosphate and collagen and making up the skeleton of most vertebrates.
BONING.e:
From Middle English bon, from Old English bān (“bone, tusk; the bone of a limb”), from Proto-Germanic *bainą (“bone”), from *bainaz (“straight”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyh₂- (“to hit, strike, beat”).
Cognate with Scots bane, been, bean, bein, bain (“bone”), North F...

BONITO.d: Any of various marine fish of the genus Sarda that are related to and resemble the tuna, but smaller.

BONKED.d: Past tense of BONK: To strike or collide with something.
BONKED.e: Of imitative origin. Compare English bang, bounce, bump.

BONNET.d: A type of hat, once worn by women or children, held in place by ribbons tied under the chin.
BONNET.e:
From Middle English bonet, from Middle French bonet (Modern French bonnet), from Old French bonet (“material from which hats are made”), from Frankish *bunni (“that which is bound”), from Proto-Germanic *bundiją (“bundle”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰendʰ- (“to tie”).
Compare al...

BONOBO.d: A great ape, Pan paniscus, from Africa south of the Congo river.
BONOBO.e: From Bolobo, a village on the Congo River where Europeans first made contact with the species. Bolobo is possibly imitative of the bubbling of the rapids at that section of the Congo.

BONSAI.d: A tree or plant that has been miniaturized by planting it in a small pot, restricting its roots, and by careful pruning.
BONSAI.e: From Japanese 盆栽 (bonsai), from Middle Chinese 盆 (MC bwon, “bowl”) + 栽 (MC tsoj|dzojH, “to plant”).

BOODLE.d: Money, especially when acquired or spent illegally or improperly; swag.
BOODLE.e: From Dutch boedel. Doublet of bottle (in the sense of "house").

BOOGIE.d: A piece of solid or semisolid mucus in or removed from the nostril cavity.

BOOING.d: Present participle of BOO: A loud exclamation intended to scare someone. Usually used when one has been hidden from the target, and then appears unexpectedly.
BOOING.e: From earlier (15c.) boh, coined to create a loud and startling sound. Compare Middle English bus! (“bang!”, interjection), Latin boō (“cry aloud, roar, shout”, verb), Ancient Greek βοάω (boáō, “shout”, verb).

BOOKED.d: simple past and past participle of book

BOOKIE.d: A bookmaker, being a person who, or business which, takes bets from the general public on sporting events and similar.

BOOMED.d: Past tense of BOOM: To make a loud, hollow, resonant sound.
BOOMED.e: Onomatopoeic, perhaps borrowed; compare German bummen, Dutch bommen (“to hum, buzz”). The sense "a period of economic growth" is generally taken to derive from the sense "a rapid expansion", although other origins have also been suggested.

BOOTED.d: Past tense of BOOT: A heavy shoe that covers part of the leg.
BOOTED.e: From Middle English boote, bote (“shoe”), from Old French bote (“a high, thick shoe”). Of obscure origin, but probably related to Old French bot (“club-foot”), bot (“fat, short, blunt”), from Old Frankish *butt, from Proto-Germanic *buttaz, *butaz (“cut off, short, numb, blunt”),...

BOOTEE.d: A soft, woolen shoe, usually knitted, for a baby or small pet.

BOPPED.d: Past tense of BOP: A very light smack, blow or punch.

BOPPER.d: Comparative form of BOP: A very light smack, blow or punch.

BORAGE.d: Borago officinalis, a Mediterranean plant with rough, cucumber-flavored leaves and stems, used in salads and cooked.
BORAGE.e: From Middle English borage, borrowed from Old French borage (compare French bourrache), from Medieval Latin borrago, either from Latin borra (“short wool, rough hair”) or Arabic أَبُو العَرَق (ʔabū l-ʕaraq, literally “father of sweat”).

BORANE.d: Any binary compound of boron and hydrogen.

BORATE.d: The oxyanion BO₃³⁻ or any of several more complex derivatives

BORDER.d: The line or frontier area separating political or geographical regions.
BORDER.e:
Inherited from Middle English bordure, from Old French bordeure, of Germanic origin, from Frankish *bord, equivalent to modern French bord (“a border”) + -er.
Akin to Middle High German borte (“border, trim”), German Borte (“ribbon, trimming”). Doublet of bordure. More at board.
...

BORING.d: The act or process of boring holes; such practice as an area of expertise in manufacturing.
BORING.e: From Middle English boryng (“making a hole”); equivalent to bore + -ing.

BORROW.d: To receive (something) from somebody temporarily, expecting to return it.
BORROW.e:
From Middle English borwen, borȝien, Old English borgian (“to borrow, lend, pledge surety for”), from Proto-West Germanic *borgōn, from Proto-Germanic *burgōną (“to pledge, take care of”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰergʰ- (“to take care”).
Cognate with Dutch borgen (“to borrow, ...

BORZOI.d: A dog of a particular breed, similar in shape to a greyhound but with longer silkier hair.
BORZOI.e: Borrowed from Russian борзо́й (borzój), from бо́рзый (bórzyj, “swift”), from Proto-Indo-European *mréǵʰus (whence English brief, brace and merry).

BOSHES.e: Borrowed from Ottoman Turkish بوش (boş, “empty, unoccupied”). Entered popular usage in English from the novels of James Justinian Morier.

BOSOMY.d: Full of sheltered hollows or recesses.

BOSSES.d: Plural of BOSS: A person who oversees and directs the work of others; a supervisor.
BOSSES.e: From Dutch baas, from Middle Dutch baes (“master of a household, friend”), from Old Dutch *baso (“uncle, kinsman”), from Proto-West Germanic *baswō, from Proto-Germanic *baswô (“uncle”), perhaps from Proto-Germanic *ba-, *bō- (“father, older male relative”), source also of the En...

BOTANY.d: A branch of biology concerned with the scientific study of plants.
BOTANY.e: First attested in 1696: Back-formation from botanic.

BOTFLY.d: One of several dipterous insects of the family Oestridae, the larvae of which are parasites on many animals, including humans.

BOTHER.d: To annoy, to disturb, to irritate; to be troublesome to, to make trouble for.
BOTHER.e: Borrowed from Scots bauther, bather (“to bother”). Origin unknown. Perhaps related to Scots pother (“to make a stir or commotion, bustle”), also of unknown origin. Compare English pother (“to poke, prod”), variant of potter (“to poke”). More at potter. Perhaps related to Irish bo...

BOTNET.d: A collection of compromised computers that is gradually built up and then unleashed as a DDOS attack or used to send very large quantities of spam.

BOTTLE.d: A container, typically made of glass or plastic and having a tapered neck, used primarily for holding liquids.
BOTTLE.e:
From Middle English botel (“bottle, flask, wineskin”), from Old French boteille, from Late Latin butticula, diminutive of buttis (“cask”). Doublet of botija.
Displaced native pinne and non-native Old English ampella. Broadly overtook Old English flasce.

BOTTOM.e:
PIE word
 *bʰudʰmḗn
From Middle English botme, botom, from Old English botm, bodan (“bottom, foundation; ground, abyss”), from Proto-West Germanic *butm, from Proto-Germanic *butmaz, *budmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰudʰmḗn (“bottom”).
Cognate with Dutch bodem, German Boden, I...

BOUNCE.d: To change the direction of motion after hitting an obstacle.
BOUNCE.e:
From Middle English bounsen, bunsen (“to beat, thump”), cognate with Scots bunce, bonce (“to bounce”). Of uncertain origin. Perhaps imitative, related to bump, or related to Middle English bonchen (“to pound, beat”) and Dutch bonken (“to bump”).
Compare Saterland Frisian bumzje (...

BOUNTY.d: Generosity; also (countable) an act of generosity.
BOUNTY.e: From Middle English bounte (“goodness, virtue; beauty; strength; chivalry, valour; excellence; kindness, mercy; good deed; generosity”) [and other forms], borrowed from Anglo-Norman bounté and Old French bonté, bontet, bunté (modern French bonté (“goodness, kindness”)), from Lati...

BOURNE.e: From Middle French borne, from Old French bodne, from Medieval Latin bodina, a word of unknown ultimate origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰudʰmḗn (“bottom, base”), see also Proto-Celtic *bundos.

BOURSE.e: Borrowed from French bourse, from Old French borse, from Latin bursa, from Ancient Greek βύρσα (búrsa). Doublet of purse, compare Danish børs, Swedish börs, German Börse. See also bursar.

BOVINE.d: Of, relating to, or characteristic of cattle.
BOVINE.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
Borrowed from Late Latin bovīnus (“relating to cattle”), from Latin bōs (“ox”). Cognate to beef.

BOWFIN.d: Any of the two extant elongated fish of the genus Amia, native to North America, previously thought to be the same species.

BOWING.d: present participle and gerund of bow (all senses)

BOWLEG.d: A leg that curves outward at the knee.

BOWSER.d: A fuel metering/delivery pump at a filling station.
BOWSER.e:
* (liquids): From Bowser (“a surname”),named after Sylvanus Bowser, US inventor of the first fuel pump; also a trade name of SF Bowser inc., the inventor's company.
* (Irish)

BOWYER.d: A person who makes or sells bows (for use with arrows).
BOWYER.e: From Middle English bowyere, bowȝere, variant forms of bowere (“bowyer”), equivalent to bow + -yer.

BOXCAR.d: An enclosed railway goods wagon, typically with a sliding door.

BOXFUL.d: as much as a box will hold

BOXIER.d: Comparative form of BOXY: Box-shaped, boxlike, or otherwise suggestive of boxes (with right angles or at least blunt profiles).

BOXING.d: present participle and gerund of box

BOXTOP.d: The upper portion of a product's box, used as a proof of purchase when claiming an associated offer.

BOYISH.d: Like a stereotypical boy in appearance or demeanor.

BRAIES.d: Plural of BRAY: Of an animal (now chiefly of animals related to the ass or donkey, and the camel): to make its cry.
BRAIES.e: The verb is derived from Middle English brayen, brai, bray, braye (“of a person or animal: to vocalize loudly; of the weather: to make a loud sound, howl, roar”), from Old French brai, braire (“of an animal: to bray; of a person: to cry or shout out”) (modern French braire (“of a...

BRAINS.d: Plural of BRAIN: The organ inside the head that controls the body.

BRAINY.e: From Middle English brayny; equivalent to brain + -y.

BRANCH.d: The woody part of a tree arising from the trunk and usually dividing.
BRANCH.e:
From Middle English branche, braunche, bronche, from Old French branche, branke, from Late Latin branca (“footprint”, later also “paw, claw”) (whence Middle High German pranke, German Pranke (“paw”)), of unknown origin.
Perhaps of Celtic origin, from a hypothetical Gaulish *vranc...

BRANDS.d: Plural of BRAND: A type of product; a mark of ownership.

BRANDY.d: An alcoholic liquor distilled from wine or fermented fruit juice.
BRANDY.e: Shortened form of brandywine, from Dutch brandewijn (“burnt wine”). Compare German Brantewein, Branntwein, Danish brændevin.

BRASSY.e: From brass + -y (suffix forming adjectives meaning “having the quality of”).

BRATTY.d: Characteristic of a brat; unruly and impolite.

BRAVED.d: Past tense of BRAVE: Ready to face danger; courageous.
BRAVED.e: From French brave, from Italian bravo.

BRAVES.d: Plural of BRAVE: Ready to face danger; courageous.
BRAVES.e: From French brave, from Italian bravo.

BRAWNY.d: Characterized by brawn; muscular, thewy; strong.
BRAWNY.e: From Middle English brawny; equivalent to brawn + -y.

BRAZEN.e:
From Middle English brasen, from Old English bræsen (“brazen, of brass”); equivalent to brass + -en (compare golden, wooden, etc.).
The word originally meant “of brass”; the figurative verb sense (as in brazen it out (“face impudently”)) dates from the 1550s (perhaps evoking the ...

BREACH.d: A gap or opening made by breaking or battering, as in a wall, fortification or levee / embankment; the space between the parts of a solid body rent by violence.
BREACH.e: From Middle English breche, from Old English bryċe (“fracture, breach”) and brǣċ (“breach, breaking, destruction”), from Proto-West Germanic *bruki, from Proto-Germanic *brukiz (“breach, fissure”) and *brēkō (“breaking”).

BREADS.d: Plural of BREAD: Food made from flour, water, and yeast.

BREAKS.d: Plural of BREAK: To separate into pieces; an interruption.

BREAST.d: Either of the two organs on the front of a female human's chest, which contain the mammary glands; also the analogous organs in males.
BREAST.e: From Middle English brest, from Old English brēost, from Proto-West Germanic *breust, from Proto-Germanic *breustą, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrews- (“to swell”). Compare West Frisian boarst, Danish bryst, Swedish bröst; cf. also Dutch borst, German Brust.

BREATH.d: The act or process of breathing.
BREATH.e: From Middle English breeth, breth, from Old English brǣþ (“odor, scent, stink, exhalation, vapor”), from Proto-West Germanic *brāþi (“vapour, waft, exhalation, breath”) (compare German Brodem (“haze, vapor; breath”), of a different but related formation).

BREECH.d: A garment whose purpose is to cover or clothe the buttocks.
BREECH.e: From Middle English breche, from Old English brēċ, from Proto-Germanic *brōkiz pl, from Proto-Germanic *brōks (“clothing for loins and thighs”). Cognate with Dutch broek, Alemannic German Bruech, Swedish brok. Doublet of vraka.

BREEZE.e:
From the earlier (nautical) term brise, brize (“breeze”), from Middle English brees (“wind”). Ultimate origin obscure.
Variously supposed to derive from a Germanic source like Saterland Frisian Briese (“breeze”), West Frisian brys (“a cool wind”), Dutch bries (“breeze”), early Du...

BREEZY.d: With a breeze blowing, with a lively wind, pleasantly windy.

BREVET.d: A military document entitling a commissioned officer to hold a higher rank temporarily, but without an increase in pay.
BREVET.e: Inherited from the Middle English brevet (“official letter”), from the Anglo-Norman diminutive of bref (“letter”), from the Latin brevis (“short”), whence brief.

BREWED.d: Past tense of BREW: To make tea or coffee by mixing tea leaves or coffee beans with hot water.
BREWED.e:
From Middle English brewen, from Old English brēowan, from Proto-West Germanic *breuwan, from Proto-Germanic *brewwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrewh₁-. Doublet of burn.
Cognate with
Dutch brouwen, German brauen, Swedish brygga, Norwegian Bokmål brygge; also Ancient Greek φρέα...

BRICKS.d: Plural of BRICK: A block of baked clay used in building.

BRIDAL.d: A wedding feast or festival; a wedding.
BRIDAL.e: From Middle English bridale, from Old English brȳdealo (“wedding ale; wedding feast”). The attributive usage was strengthened by association with bride + -al.

BRIDGE.d: A construction or natural feature that spans a divide.
BRIDGE.e:
From Middle English brigge, from Old English brycġ (“bridge”), from Proto-Germanic *brugjō, *brugjǭ (“bridge”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerw-, *bʰrēw- (“wooden flooring, decking, bridge”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots brig, brigg (“bridge”), Yola burge (“bridge”), North Frisian...

BRIDLE.d: The headgear with which a horse is directed and which carries a bit and reins.
BRIDLE.e: From Middle English bridel, from Old English brīdel, from Proto-West Germanic *brigdil, from Proto-Germanic *brigdilaz (“strap, rein”), equivalent to braid + -le.

BRIEFS.d: Plural of BRIEF: Of short duration; concise.

BRIGHT.d: Emitting much light; visually dazzling; luminous, lucent, radiant.
BRIGHT.e:
The adjective is from Middle English bright, from Old English beorht, from Proto-West Germanic *berht, from Proto-Germanic *berhtaz (“bright”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerHǵ- (“to shine, to gleam, whiten”).
The noun is derived from Middle English bright (“brightness...

BRINGS.d: Plural of BRING: To carry toward the speaker.

BROACH.d: A series of chisel points mounted on one piece of steel. For example, the toothed stone chisel shown here.
BROACH.e: From Middle English broche, from Old French broche, from Vulgar Latin *brocca, originally a feminine form of Latin broccus, perhaps ultimately of Gaulish origin (see Scottish Gaelic bròg). Doublet of brochure.

BROGUE.d: A strong dialectal accent, usually Irish or Scottish.
BROGUE.e: From Irish bróg (“boot, shoe”), from Old Irish bróc (“shoe, greave, legging, hose, breeches”), likely from Old Norse brók (“breeches”), from Proto-Germanic *brōks (“breeches”). The "accent" sense may instead be derived from Irish barróg (“a hold (on the tongue)”).

BROKEN.e: From Middle English broken, from Old English brocen, ġebrocen, from Proto-Germanic *brukanaz, past participle of Proto-Germanic *brekaną (“to break”). Cognate with Dutch gebroken (“broken”), German Low German broken (“broken”), German gebrochen (“broken”). Morphologically broke +...

BROKER.d: comparative form of broke: more broke

BRONCO.d: A horse of western North America that is wild or not fully broken.
BRONCO.e: Borrowed from Spanish bronco (“rough”), 19th c. which in Mexican usage also describes a horse that has not been broken and is still wild.

BRONZE.d: A naturally occurring or man-made alloy of copper, usually in combination with tin, but also with one or more other metals.
BRONZE.e: From French bronze (1511); from Italian bronzo (13th c.), of uncertain origin (q.v.). First use appears c. 1721 in the writings of Matthew Prior (for which, see citation below).

BROOCH.d: A piece of ornamental jewellery having a pin allowing it to be fixed to garments worn on the upper body.

BROODY.d: Of birds: sitting persistently and protectively on a nest, in order to hatch eggs.
BROODY.e: From Middle English *brody, *brodi, from Old English brōdiġ (“broody”), equivalent to brood + -y. Cognate with German brütig (“broody”).

BROWED.d: Past tense of BROW: The bony ridge over the eyes, upon which the eyebrows are located.
BROWED.e:
From Middle English browe, from Old English brū, from Proto-West Germanic *brāwu, from Proto-Germanic *brūwō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃bʰrúHs (“brow”).
Cognate with Scots broo (“brow”), Dutch brauw (“brow”), German Braue (“eyebrow”), Danish, Norwegian Nynorsk and Swedish bryn ...

BROWNS.d: Plural of BROWN: A colour produced by mixing red, yellow, and black.

BRUISE.d: To strike (a person), originally with something flat or heavy, but now specifically in such a way as to discolour the skin without breaking it; to contuse.
BRUISE.e:
From Middle English bruisen, brusen, brosen, brisen, bresen, from a merger two words, both ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrews- (“to break”):
* Old English brȳsan, brīesan (“to bruise; crush”), from Proto-Germanic *brausijaną, *brūsijaną (“to break; crumble; crack”). Prov...

BRUNCH.d: A meal eaten later in the day than breakfast and earlier than lunch, and often consisting of typical foods from both of those meals.
BRUNCH.e: Blend of breakfast + lunch. Attested from 1895 in British English and from 1930 in the United States.

BRUNET.d: Of a man's or boy's hair: brown or dark brown.
BRUNET.e: From French brunet. Compare also Middle English brunet, burnet (“brown”), from Old French brunet, which is the same word.

BRUTAL.d: Savagely violent, vicious, ruthless, or cruel, often in an unintelligent manner.
BRUTAL.e: From Medieval Latin brutalis (“savage, stupid”), from Latin brūtus (“dull, stupid”).

BRYONY.d: A perennial herb of the genus Bryonia, especially the common wild species Bryonia dioica.
BRYONY.e: From Middle English brionie, from Latin bryōnia (“bryony”), from Ancient Greek βρυωνία (bruōnía, “bryony”), from βρύω (brúō).

BUBBLE.d: A spherically contained volume of air or other gas, especially one made from soapy liquid.
BUBBLE.e: Partly imitative, also influenced by burble. Compare Middle Dutch bobbe (“bubble”) > Dutch bubbel (“bubble”), Low German bubbel (“bubble”), Danish boble (“bubble”), Swedish bubbla (“bubble”). The word was first used in its economic sense in association with the collapse of the So...

BUBOED.d: Past tense of BUBO: An inflamed swelling of a lymph node, especially in the armpit or groin, due to an infection such as bubonic plague, gonorrhea, tuberculosis, or syphilis.
BUBOED.e: Late Middle English, from Medieval Latin būbō, from Ancient Greek βουβών (boubṓn, “groin, swelling”).

BUCKED.d: Past tense of BUCK: A male deer, antelope, sheep, goat, rabbit, hare, and sometimes the male of other animals such as the hamster, ferret, salmonid, shad and kangaroo.
BUCKED.e:
From Middle English bukke, bucke, buc, from Old English buc, bucc, bucca (“he-goat, stag”), from Proto-West Germanic *bukk, *bukkō, from Proto-Germanic *bukkaz, *bukkô (“buck”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuǵ- (“ram”). Doublet of puck (“billy goat”).
Currency-related senses hail ...

BUCKET.d: A container made of rigid material, often with a handle, used to carry liquids or small items.
BUCKET.e: From Middle English buket, boket, partly from Old English bucc ("bucket, pitcher"; mod. dialectal buck), equivalent to bouk + -et; and partly from Anglo-Norman buket, buquet (“tub; pail”) (compare Norman boutchet, Norman bouquet), diminutive of Old French buc (“abdomen; object wi...

BUCKLE.d: A metal clasp with a hinged tongue or a spike through which a belt or strap is passed and penetrated by the tongue or spike, in order to fasten the ends of the belt together or to secure the strap to something else.
BUCKLE.e: The noun is derived from Middle English bokel (“spiked metal ring for fastening; ornamental clasp; boss of a shield; a shield, buckler; (figurative) means of defence”) [and other forms], from Old French boucle, bocle (“spiked metal ring for fastening; boss of a shield; a shield”)...

BUDDED.d: Past tense of BUD: A newly sprouted leaf or blossom that has not yet unfolded.
BUDDED.e: From Middle English budde (“bud, seed pod”), from Proto-Germanic *buddǭ (compare Dutch bot (“bud”), German Hagebutte (“hip, rosehip”), regional German Butzen (“seed pod”), Swedish dialect bodd (“head”)), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *bʰew-, *bu- (“to swell”).

BUDDER.d: Comparative form of BUD: A newly sprouted leaf or blossom that has not yet unfolded.
BUDDER.e: From Middle English budde (“bud, seed pod”), from Proto-Germanic *buddǭ (compare Dutch bot (“bud”), German Hagebutte (“hip, rosehip”), regional German Butzen (“seed pod”), Swedish dialect bodd (“head”)), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *bʰew-, *bu- (“to swell”).

BUDGET.d: The amount of money or resources earmarked for a particular institution, activity or timeframe.
BUDGET.e: Recorded since 1432 as Middle English bogett, bouget, bowgette (“leather pouch”), borrowed from Old French bougette, the diminutive of bouge (“leather bag, wallet”) (also the root of bulge), itself from Late Latin bulga (“leather bag, bellow”), which derives from Gaulish *bolgā (...

BUFFER.d: Someone or something that buffs (polishes and makes shiny).

BUFFET.d: A counter or sideboard from which food and drinks are served or may be bought.
BUFFET.e: Inherited from Middle English buffet (“stool”), from Middle French buffet (“side table”), from Old French buffet, of unknown origin. The modern pronunciation is remodelled after modern French buffet.

BUGFIX.d: A patch or change that fixes the unwanted behaviour caused by a bug.

BUGGED.d: Past tense of BUG: An insect of the order Hemiptera (the “true bugs”).
BUGGED.e:
First attested in this form around 1620 (referring to a “bedbug”), from earlier bugge (“beetle”), from Middle English bugge (“scarecrow, hobgoblin”) which is traced alternatively to:
* a Celtic root found in Scots bogill (“goblin, bugbear”) and obsolete Welsh bwg (“ghost, hobgobl...

BUGGER.e: From Middle English bougre (“heretic”), from Old French bougre, from Medieval Latin Bulgarus (“Bulgar”), from Old Church Slavonic блъгаринъ (blŭgarinŭ, “Bulgarian”), used in designation of heretics (especially the Bogomils, who arose around the 10th century AD in the First Bulgar...

BUILDS.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of build

BULBED.d: Past tense of BULB: The bulb-shaped underground portion of a plant such as a tulip, consisting of a shortened stem and many fleshy scale leaves, from which the rest of the plant may be regrown.
BULBED.e:
Etymology tree
Ancient Greek βολβός (bolbós)bor.
Latin bulbusder.
English bulb
Inherited from Middle English bulb, bolbe, from Latin bulbus (“bulb, onion”), from Ancient Greek βολβός (bolbós, “plant with round swelling on underground stem”).

BULBIL.d: A bulb-shaped bud in the place of a flower or in a leaf axil.
BULBIL.e: From Spanish bulbillo, from the diminutive form of Latin bulbus, from Ancient Greek βολβός (bolbós, “plant with round swelling on underground stem”).

BULBUL.d: Any of several passerine songbirds, of the family Pycnonotidae (currently, 27 genera recognized), native to Africa and Eurasia.
BULBUL.e: Borrowed from Classical Persian بلبل (bulbul) or from Arabic بُلْبُل (bulbul).

BULKED.d: Past tense of BULK: Size, specifically, volume.
BULKED.e: From Middle English bulk, bolke (“a heap, cargo, hold; heap; bulge”), borrowed from Old Norse búlki (“the freight or the cargo of a ship”), from Proto-Germanic *bulkô (“beam, pile, heap”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰelǵ- (“beam, pile, prop”). Compare Icelandic búlkast (“to be bu...

BULLET.d: A projectile, usually of metal, shot from a gun at high speed.
BULLET.e: From Middle English bullet (“an official tag or badge of registration or identification”), from Old French bullete, diminutive of boule (“ball”). Later influenced by Middle French boulette and French boulet.

BUMBLE.e: Onomatopoeia. Compare bungle, jumble, and fumble.

BUMMED.d: Past tense of BUM: The buttocks.
BUMMED.e: Attested since the 1300s, as Middle English bom (found in John Trevisa's 1387 Translation of the 'Polychronicon' of Ranulph Higden, "his bom is oute"), of uncertain origin. Sometimes suggested to be a shortening of botme, botom, bottum (“bottom”), but this is contradicted by the ...

BUMMER.d: Comparative form of BUM: The buttocks.
BUMMER.e: Attested since the 1300s, as Middle English bom (found in John Trevisa's 1387 Translation of the 'Polychronicon' of Ranulph Higden, "his bom is oute"), of uncertain origin. Sometimes suggested to be a shortening of botme, botom, bottum (“bottom”), but this is contradicted by the ...

BUMPED.d: Past tense of BUMP: A light blow or jolting collision.
BUMPED.e:
From Early Modern English bump (“a shock, blow from a collision”), probably of North Germanic origin; compare Danish bump (“a thump”), Danish bumpe (“to thump”), Old Danish bumpe (“to strike with a clenched fist”), all probably of imitative origin.
Apparently related to Middle En...

BUNCHY.e: From Middle English bunchy, bonchy, equivalent to bunch + -y.

BUNDLE.d: A group of objects held together by wrapping or tying.
BUNDLE.e: From Middle English bundel, from Middle Dutch bondel or Old English byndele, byndelle (“a binding; tying; fastening with bands”); both from Proto-Germanic *bundil-, derivative of *bundą (“bundle”). Compare also bindle, Dutch bundel, German Bündel.

BUNGED.d: Past tense of BUNG: A stopper, alternative to a cork, often made of rubber, used to prevent fluid passing through the neck of a bottle, vat, a hole in a vessel etc.
BUNGED.e: From Medieval Dutch bonge, bonne or bonghe (“stopper”), or perhaps from French bonde, which may itself be either of Germanic origin or from Proto-Celtic *bunda—either way probably from puncta (“hole”), the feminine singular form of Latin punctus, perfect passive participle of pun...

BUNGEE.d: An elastic fabric-bound strap with a hook at each end, used for securing luggage.
BUNGEE.e: Probably from slang language, maybe from bouncy + spongy.

BUNGLE.d: To incompetently perform (a task); to ruin (something) through incompetent action; to botch up, to bumble.
BUNGLE.e:
The origin of the verb is uncertain; it is either:
* onomatopoeic in origin (compare bumble (“to act in an inept, clumsy or inexpert manner; to make mistakes”), fumble (“to grope awkwardly in trying to find something; to blunder uncertainly”)); or
* from Old Norse; compare Old Sw...

BUNION.d: A bump or bulge on the first joint of the big toe caused by the swelling of a sac of fluid under the skin.
BUNION.e: From alteration of earlier bunny (“lump, swelling”), from Middle English bony, boni (“bunion, swelling”), perhaps Italian bubbone (augmented form of bugno (“beehive”)), or more likely from Lombard bugnon (“bunyon”), all three from Old French bugne, buigne, bune (“bump, knob, swel...

BUNKED.d: Past tense of BUNK: One of a series of berths or beds placed in tiers.
BUNKED.e:
Sense of sleeping berth possibly from Scottish English bunker (“seat, bench”), origin is uncertain but possibly Scandinavian.
Compare Old Swedish bunke (“boards used to protect the cargo of a ship”).
See also boarding, flooring and compare bunch.

BUNKER.d: A hardened shelter, often partly buried or fully underground, designed to protect the inhabitants from falling bombs or other attacks.
