BUNKER.e: The origin of the noun is uncertain; the earliest sense is sense 6.1 (“box or chest, the lid of which serves as a seat”), from Scots bunker (“bench; pew; window-seat; sand pit (especially in golf); coal receptacle; sleeping berth, bunk”), from Early Scots bunker, bunkur, bonker (...

BUNKUM.d: Senseless talk; nonsense; a piece of nonsense.
BUNKUM.e: From buncombe, from “speaking to (or for) Buncombe County, North Carolina”, a county in North Carolina named for Edward Buncombe. In 1820, Felix Walker, who represented the county in the U.S. House of Representatives, rose to address the question of admitting Missouri as a free o...

BUNTED.d: Past tense of BUNT: The middle part, cavity, or belly of a sail; the part of a furled sail which is at the center of the yard.
BUNTED.e: Unknown. Perhaps a nasalised variant of butt.

BUNYIP.d: A mythical Australian monster, said to inhabit swamps and lagoons.

BUOYED.d: Past tense of BUOY: A float moored in water to mark a location, warn of danger, indicate a navigational channel or for other purposes
BUOYED.e: From Middle English boy, boye, from Middle Dutch boeye (“float, buoy”), from Old French boue (“piece of wood or cork that floats above an anchor to indicate where it is anchored”) (modern French bouée), ultimately from Frankish *baukn (“beacon”). Doublet of beacon. Same root as E...

BURBLE.d: A bubbling, gurgling sound, as of a creek.
BURBLE.e: From Middle English burblen (“to bubble”), imitative.

BURBOT.d: A freshwater fish, taxonomic name Lota lota, which is similar to the ling and the cusk and spawns in the winter.
BURBOT.e: Borrowed from French barbote, from Latin barba (“a beard”). Displaced native eelpout.

BURDEN.e: From Middle English burden, birden, burthen, birthen, byrthen, from Old English byrden, byrþen, from Proto-West Germanic *burþini, from *burþī, from Proto-Germanic *burþį̄, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer- (“to carry, bear”).

BUREAU.d: An administrative unit of government; office.
BUREAU.e: Unadapted borrowing from French bureau, earlier "coarse cloth (as desk cover), baize", from Old French burel (“woolen cloth”), diminutive of *bure (compare Middle French bure (“coarse woolen cloth”), French bourre (“hair, fluff”)), from Late Latin burra (“wool, fluff, shaggy clot...

BURGEE.d: A flag, usually a broad tapering pennant, often with a swallowtail, flown by yachts to identify the owner's yacht club.

BURIAL.d: The act of burying; interment; placing remains into the earth.
BURIAL.e: From Middle English beriel, a re-interpretation of Old English byrġels as a plural, from byrġan (“to bury”) + -els, equivalent to bury + -al.

BURIED.d: Placed in a grave at a burial.

BURIER.e: From bury + -er, from Middle English birier, from Old English byrgere. Present form probably reformed from the verb based on West Midland dialect.

BURIES.d: Plural of BURY: To ritualistically inter in a grave or tomb.
BURIES.e:
Middle English burien, berien, from Old English byrġan, from Proto-West Germanic *burgijan, from Proto-Germanic *burgijaną (“to keep safe”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰergʰ- (“to defend, protect”).
Cognate with Icelandic byrgja (“to cover, shut; to hold in”); West Fri...

BURLAP.d: A very strong, coarse cloth, made from jute, flax, or hemp, and used to make sacks, etc.
BURLAP.e: Uncertain. Attested since about 1695 in the spelling bore-lap, borelapp. Likely from burel (“a coarse woollen cloth”) + lap (“flap of a garment”), where the first element is from Middle English burel, borel. Others feel that "its character and time of appearance makes a Dutch ori...

BURLED.d: Past tense of BURL: A tree growth in which the grain has grown in a deformed manner; a burr knot.
BURLED.e: From Middle English burle (“a knot or flaw in cloth”), from Old French bourle (“flocks or ends of threads which disfigure cloth”), diminutive of Old French bourre, from Medieval Latin burra (“flock of wool, coarse hair”).

BURLEY.d: A tobacco grown mainly in Kentucky, used in making cigarettes.
BURLEY.e: Unknown. Compare the personal name Burley.

BURNED.d: Past tense of BURN: A physical injury caused by heat, cold, electricity, radiation or caustic chemicals.
BURNED.e:
From Middle English bernen (collateral form of brennen), from Old English birnan (“to burn”), metathesis from Proto-West Germanic *brinnan, from Proto-Germanic *brinnaną (“to burn”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrenw-, present stem from *bʰrewh₁-. Doublet of brew.
Cognate with Cim...

BURPED.d: Past tense of BURP: A belch.
BURPED.e: Originally from American English, of imitative origin.

BURRED.d: Past tense of BUR: A rough, prickly husk around the seeds or fruit of some plants.
BURRED.e: From Middle English burre, of unknown origin but probably from North Germanic (Scandinavian) source or from Old English byrst (“bristle”). See also burr. Compare English bristle, Danish burre (“bur, burdock”), Norwegian borre, Swedish borre, and Old Norse burst (“bristle”).

BURRER.d: Comparative form of BUR: A rough, prickly husk around the seeds or fruit of some plants.
BURRER.e: From Middle English burre, of unknown origin but probably from North Germanic (Scandinavian) source or from Old English byrst (“bristle”). See also burr. Compare English bristle, Danish burre (“bur, burdock”), Norwegian borre, Swedish borre, and Old Norse burst (“bristle”).

BURROW.d: A tunnel or hole, often as dug by a small creature.
BURROW.e: From Middle English borowe, borewe, borwȝ, burȝe, burh, burye (“refuge for an animal, lair, burrow”), apparently a variant of Middle English burgh (“fortified dwelling, stronghold, refuge”) (see borough) and thus from Old English burh, from Proto-West Germanic *burg, from Proto-G...

BURSAR.d: The treasurer of a university, college or school.
BURSAR.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin bursārius, from bursa (“purse”) (English purse).

BUSBAR.d: An electrical conductor that carries a large current, especially one that is part of a power distribution system; typically a thick strip, or a tube, of copper or aluminium.

BUSHED.d: Past tense of BUSH: A woody plant distinguished from a tree by its multiple stems and lower height, being usually less than six metres tall; a horticultural rather than strictly botanical category.
BUSHED.e:
From Middle English bush, from Old English busċ, *bysċ (“copse, grove, scrub”, in placenames), from Proto-West Germanic *busk, from Proto-Germanic *buskaz (“bush, thicket”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to grow”). Doublet of bosque.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland F...

BUSHEL.d: A dry measure, containing four pecks, eight gallons, or thirty-two quarts; equivalent in volume to approximately 0.0364 cubic meters (imperial bushel) or 0.0352 cubic meters (U.S. bushel).
BUSHEL.e: From Middle English busshel, from Old French boissel, from boisse, a grain measure based on Gaulish *bostyā (“handful”), from Proto-Celtic *bostā (“palm, fist”) (compare Breton boz (“hollow of the hand”), Old Irish bas), from Proto-Indo-European *gwost-, *gwosdʰ- (“branch”).

BUSHES.d: Plural of BUSH: A woody plant distinguished from a tree by its multiple stems and lower height, being usually less than six metres tall; a horticultural rather than strictly botanical category.
BUSHES.e:
From Middle English bush, from Old English busċ, *bysċ (“copse, grove, scrub”, in placenames), from Proto-West Germanic *busk, from Proto-Germanic *buskaz (“bush, thicket”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to grow”). Doublet of bosque.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland F...

BUSIED.d: Past tense of BUSY: Crowded with business or activities; having a great deal going on.
BUSIED.e: From Middle English bisy, busie, from Old English bisiġ (“busy, occupied, diligent”), from Proto-West Germanic *bisīg (“diligent; zealous; busy”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian biesich (“active, diligent, hard-working, industrious”), Dutch bezig (“busy”), Low German besig (“busy...

BUSIER.d: Comparative form of BUSY: Crowded with business or activities; having a great deal going on.
BUSIER.e: From Middle English bisy, busie, from Old English bisiġ (“busy, occupied, diligent”), from Proto-West Germanic *bisīg (“diligent; zealous; busy”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian biesich (“active, diligent, hard-working, industrious”), Dutch bezig (“busy”), Low German besig (“busy...

BUSIES.d: Plural of BUSY: Crowded with business or activities; having a great deal going on.
BUSIES.e: From Middle English bisy, busie, from Old English bisiġ (“busy, occupied, diligent”), from Proto-West Germanic *bisīg (“diligent; zealous; busy”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian biesich (“active, diligent, hard-working, industrious”), Dutch bezig (“busy”), Low German besig (“busy...

BUSING.d: Present participle of BUS: A motor vehicle for transporting large numbers of people along roads.
BUSING.e: Clipping of omnibus. Superseded earlier 'bus, where the apostrophe indicated a clipping. The shift in spelling likely reflects the fact that modern speakers no longer perceive this term as a clipping. The electrical sense is derived from figurative application of the automotive s...

BUSKED.d: Past tense of BUSK: To solicit money by entertaining the public in the street or in public transport.
BUSKED.e: Apparently from French busquer or Spanish buscar.

BUSKIN.d: A soft boot reaching to calf or knee height.
BUSKIN.e: Apparently from Old French bousequin, variant of brousequin (compare modern French brodequin), probably from Middle Dutch broseken, of unknown origin.

BUSMAN.d: A person employed to drive a bus.

BUSSED.d: Past tense of BUS: A motor vehicle for transporting large numbers of people along roads.
BUSSED.e: Clipping of omnibus. Superseded earlier 'bus, where the apostrophe indicated a clipping. The shift in spelling likely reflects the fact that modern speakers no longer perceive this term as a clipping. The electrical sense is derived from figurative application of the automotive s...

BUSSER.d: Comparative form of BUS: A motor vehicle for transporting large numbers of people along roads.
BUSSER.e: Clipping of omnibus. Superseded earlier 'bus, where the apostrophe indicated a clipping. The shift in spelling likely reflects the fact that modern speakers no longer perceive this term as a clipping. The electrical sense is derived from figurative application of the automotive s...

BUSTED.d: Past tense of BUST: To break.
BUSTED.e: From a non-rhotic pronunciation of burst, which goes back to Middle English busten, a variant of bursten, bresten (“to burst”). Compare Low German basten, a variant of barsten (“to burst”).

BUSTLE.e: From Middle English bustlen, bustelen, bostlen, perhaps an alteration of *busklen (> Modern English buskle), a frequentative of Middle English busken (“to prepare; make ready”), from Old Norse búask (“to prepare oneself”); or alternatively from a frequentative form of Middle Engl...

BUSWAY.d: A right of way, roadway, or lane for the exclusive use of buses, possibly only during peak traffic hours.

BUTANE.d: A hydrocarbon (either of the two isomers of C₄H₁₀, n-butane and 2-methylpropane) found in gaseous petroleum fractions.
BUTANE.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
IUPAC nomenclature, from but- (“four carbon prefix”) + -ane (“alkane suffix”), the former is derived from the same stem as the foul-smelling carboxylic acid liberated in rancid butter, "butyric acid", hence cognate with butter.

BUTENE.d: Any of several forms of butylene.

BUTLER.d: A manservant having charge of wines and liquors.
BUTLER.e: From Middle English butler, butlere, boteler, botelere, from Old French buttiler, butiller, boteillier (“officer in charge of wine”), from Medieval Latin botellārius, equivalent to bottle + -er. Piecewise doublet of bottler.

BUTTED.d: Past tense of BUT: Apart from, except (for), excluding.
BUTTED.e: From Middle English but, buten, boute, bouten, from Old English būtan (“without, outside of, except, only”), from Proto-West Germanic *biūtan, *biūtini, equivalent to be- + out. Cognate with Scots but, bot (“outside, without, but”), Saterland Frisian buute (“without”), West Frisi...

BUTTER.d: A soft, fatty foodstuff made by churning the cream of milk (generally cow's milk).
BUTTER.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
From Middle English buter, butter, from Old English butere, from Proto-West Germanic *buterā, from Latin būtȳrum, from Ancient Greek βούτῡρον (boútūron, “cow cheese”), compound of βοῦς (boûs, “ox, cow”) and τῡρός (tūrós, “cheese”).

BUTTON.d: A knob or disc that is passed through a loop or (buttonhole), serving as a fastener.
BUTTON.e: From Middle English boton, botoun, from Old French boton (Modern French bouton), from Old French bouter, boter (“to push; thrust”), ultimately from a Germanic language. Doublet of Biden and beat. More at butt.

BUYERS.d: Plural of BUYER: A person who purchases something.

BUYING.d: Present participle of BUY: To obtain (something) in exchange for money or goods.
BUYING.e: From Middle English byen, from Old English bycġan (“to buy, pay for, acquire, redeem, ransom, procure, get done, sell”), from Proto-West Germanic *buggjan, from Proto-Germanic *bugjaną (“to buy”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *bʰūgʰ- (“to bend”), or from ...

BUYOUT.d: The acquisition of a controlling interest in a business or corporation by outright purchase or by purchase of a majority of issued shares of stock.

BUZZES.d: Plural of BUZZ: A continuous humming noise, as of bees; a confused murmur, as of general conversation in low tones.
BUZZES.e: From Middle English *bussen (suggested by Middle English bussyng (“buzzing”)), of onomatopoeic origin. Cognate with Scots bizz (“to buzz”). Compare Middle English bunning (“buzzing”), Middle English hossing (“buzzing”), Middle English bissen (“to hush”).

BYGONE.d: Having been or happened in the distant past.

BYLINE.d: A line at the head of a newspaper or magazine article carrying the writer's name.

BYNAME.d: A secondary name for a person or thing; a person's surname.
BYNAME.e: From by- + name. Cognate with Dutch bijnaam (“nickname”), German Beiname (“nickname, epithet”), Swedish binamn, Danish binavn and Norwegian Bokmål binavn.

BYPASS.d: A road that passes around something, such as a residential area or business district.
BYPASS.e: From Middle English *bypassen, *bipassen (suggested by past participle by-past, bipast), equivalent to by- + pass.

BYPATH.d: An unfrequented path; an indirect route; a byway.
BYPATH.e: Inherited from Middle English bypath; by surface analysis, by + path.

BYPLAY.d: Any action, carried out onstage during a performance, apart from the main action.

BYROAD.d: A road less frequented than a highway; a byway.

BYSSUS.d: The long fine silky filaments excreted by several mollusks (particularly Pinna nobilis) by which they attach themselves to the sea bed, and from which sea silk is manufactured.
BYSSUS.e: From New Latin byssus (“sea silk”), from Latin byssus (“fine cotton or cotton stuff, silk”), from Ancient Greek βύσσος (bússos, “a very fine yellowish flax and the linen woven from it”), from Hebrew בּוּץ (búts), Aramaic בּוּצָא (būṣā).

BYWORD.d: A proverb or proverbial expression, common saying; a frequently used word or phrase.
BYWORD.e: From Middle English byword, byworde (“proverb”), from Old English bīword, bīwyrd, bīwyrde (“proverb, household word", also "adverb”), from Proto-West Germanic *bīwurdī, equivalent to by- + word. Compare Latin proverbium, which byword may possibly be a translation of. Cognate with...

CABANA.d: A cabin or hut for relaxing.
CABANA.e: Borrowed from Spanish cabaña and Portuguese cabana, both from Late Latin capanna. Doublet of cabane and cabin.

CABBED.d: Past tense of CAB: A compartment at the front of a truck or train for the driver.

CABBER.d: Comparative form of CAB: A compartment at the front of a truck or train for the driver.

CABBIE.d: A cabdriver; someone who drives a taxi.

CABLED.d: Past tense of CABLE: A thick rope or wire.

CABLES.d: Plural of CABLE: A thick rope or wire.

CABMAN.d: The driver of a hackney cab.

CACHET.d: A seal, as of a letter.
CACHET.e: Borrowed from French cachet, first appearing in Scottish English, from 1630.

CACKLE.d: The cry of a hen or goose, especially when laying an egg.
CACKLE.e:
From Middle English caclen, cakelen, perhaps from Old English *caclian, *cacolian, from Proto-West Germanic *kakulōn, *kakilōn (“to cackle, gaggle, yelp, snarl”), perhaps of imitative origin.
Compare Dutch kakelen (“to cackle”), German Low German kakeln (“to cackle”), German kake...

CACTUS.d: Any member of the family Cactaceae, a family of flowering New World succulent plants suited to a hot, semi-desert climate.
CACTUS.e: From taxonomic name Cactus, a name given in 1752 by Linnaeus for a genus of cacti (now superseded by the genus name Mammillaria), from Latin cactus, from Ancient Greek κάκτος (káktos, “cardoon”), possibly of Pre-Greek origin.

CADDED.d: Past tense of CAD: Acronym of computer-aided design.

CADDIE.d: Synonym of cadet (“a gentleman (often a younger son from a noble family) who joined the military without a commission as a career”).
CADDIE.e: The noun is borrowed from Scots caddie (“military cadet; young man; ragamuffin; person engaged to run errands; person hired to assist a golfer”), from French cadet (“army cadet; younger sibling”), from capdet (“captain; chief”) (Gascony, archaic), from Late Latin capitettum, from...

CADENT.e: From the Latin cadens (“falling”), present active participle of cado (“I fall”).

CAECUM.d: A cavity open at one end (such as the blind end of a duct), especially a blind pouch connected to the large intestine between the ileum and the colon.
CAECUM.e: Borrowed from Latin caecum (“invisible, hidden”), clipping of intestīnum caecum (“blind gut”), translation of Ancient Greek τῠφλὸν ἔντερον (tŭphlòn énteron).

CAGING.d: Present participle of CAGE: An enclosure made of bars, normally to hold animals.
CAGING.e: From Middle English cage, from Old French cage, from Latin cavea. Doublet of cadge and cavea and related to jail.

CAHOOT.e: For the noun, see cahoots. The verb is derived from the noun.

CAIMAN.d: Any of the relatively small crocodilians of the genus Caiman, within the family Alligatoridae.
CAIMAN.e: From Spanish caimán or Portuguese caimão, from Kari'na acayouman.

CAIQUE.d: A small wooden trading vessel, brightly painted and rigged for sail, traditionally used for fishing and trawling.
CAIQUE.e: Borrowed from French caïque, from Italian caicco, from Ottoman Turkish قایق (kayık), from Proto-Turkic *kiayguk (“boat, oar”). Cognate with modern Turkish kayık.

CAJOLE.d: To persuade someone to do something which they are reluctant to do, especially by flattery or promises; to coax.
CAJOLE.e: Borrowed from French cajoler, probably a blend of Middle French cageoler (“chatter like a jay”) (from gajole, dialectal diminutive of geai (“jaybird”)) + Old French gaioler (“entice into a cage”), which is from Medieval Latin gabiola, from Late Latin caveola (whence English caveo...

CAKING.d: Present participle of CAKE: A rich, sweet dessert food, typically made of flour, sugar, and eggs and baked in an oven, and often covered in icing.
CAKING.e: From Middle English cake, from Old Norse kaka (“cake”) (compare Norwegian kake, Icelandic/Swedish kaka, Danish kage), from Proto-Germanic *kakǭ, of disputed origin. Likely a distant cognate with kaak. Perhaps related to cookie, kuchen, and quiche. Doublet of coca (pastry).

CALASH.d: Alternative form of calèche (“type of carriage with low wheels”).

CALCAR.d: A small oven or furnace, used for the calcination of sand and potash, and converting them into frit.

CALICO.d: A kind of rough cloth made from unbleached and not fully processed cotton, often printed with a bright pattern.
CALICO.e: From Calicut, from where the cloth was originally exported, from Malayalam കോഴിക്കോട് (kōḻikkōṭŭ, “Kozhikode”), from കോഴി (kōḻi, “palace”) + കോട് (kōṭŭ, “fortified palace”).

CALIPH.d: The holder of a monarchical title based on a claim to be a successor of Muhammad.
CALIPH.e: From Middle English calife, caliphe, from Old French caliphe, from Medieval Latin calipha, from Arabic خَلِيفَة (ḵalīfa, “caliph”) and خَلِيف (ḵalīf, “successor”).

CALLED.d: simple past and past participle of call

CALLEE.d: The person who is called by the caller (on the telephone).

CALLOP.d: an Australian freshwater fish, Macquaria ambigua; the golden perch or yellowbelly

CALLOW.d: Of a person: having no hair; bald, bare, hairless.
CALLOW.e:
From Middle English calwe (“(adjective) bald; (noun) bald person”), from Old English calu, caluw (“without hair, bald, callow”), from Proto-West Germanic *kalu, from Proto-Germanic *kalwaz (“bald; bare, naked”), and then either:
* from Proto-Indo-European *gol(H)-wo- (“bald; bare...

CALLUS.d: A hardened area of the skin (especially on the foot or hand) caused by repeated friction, wear or use.
CALLUS.e: Borrowed from Latin callum (“hard skin”). Displaced native Old English wearr.

CALMED.d: Past tense of CALM: Peaceful, quiet, especially free from anger and anxiety.
CALMED.e: From Middle English calm, calme, from Middle French calme, probably from Old Italian calma, of uncertain origin. Calma may derive from Late Latin cauma (“heat of the midday sun”), from Ancient Greek καῦμα (kaûma, “heat, especially of the sun”), from καίω (kaíō, “I burn”), or poss...

CALQUE.d: A word or phrase in a language formed by word-for-word or morpheme-by-morpheme translation of a word in another language.
CALQUE.e: From French calque (“calque”, literally “copy, tracing”), from calquer (“to copy, trace”) (whence also calk), itself borrowed from Italian calcare, from Latin calcāre (“to tread”). Doublet of calcate and calcation.

CALVES.d: Plural of CALF: A young cow or bull of any bovid, such as domestic cattle or buffalo.
CALVES.e:
From Middle English calf, from Anglian Old English cælf, calf (West Saxon ċealf), from Proto-Germanic *kalbaz, further etymology unknown.
Cognates

* Scots caff (“calf”)
* Scots calf (“calf”)
* Scots cauf (“calf”)
* Scots cawf (“calf”)
* North Frisian Kualev (“calf”)
* North Fris...

CALXES.d: Plural of CALX: The substance which remains after a metal or mineral has been thoroughly burnt, once seen as being the essential substance left after the expulsion of phlogiston, but now recognised as being the metallic oxide (or, in some cases, the metal in a state of sublimation).
CALXES.e: From Latin calx (“lime”). Doublet of cauk and chalk.

CAMBER.d: A slight convexity, arching or curvature of a surface of a road, beam, roof, ship's deck etc., so that liquids will flow off the sides.
CAMBER.e: From Old French cambre (“bent”), from Latin camurum, from camur (“arched”).

CAMERA.d: A device for taking still or moving pictures or photographs.
CAMERA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin camera (“chamber or bedchamber”), from Ancient Greek καμάρα (kamára, “anything with an arched cover, a covered carriage or boat, a vaulted chamber, a vault”), of Old Iranian origin, from Proto-Iranian *kamarā- (“something curved”), from *kamárati, fro...

CAMION.d: A truck or wagon, especially one used to transport ordnance.

CAMMED.d: Past tense of CAM: A turning or sliding piece which imparts motion to a rod, lever or block brought into sliding or rolling contact with it.
CAMMED.e:
PIE word
 *ǵómbʰos
Recorded since the 16th century, from Dutch kam (“cog of a wheel; originally, comb”) (cognate with English comb, and preserved in modern Dutch compounds such as kamrad, kamwiel (“cog wheel”)). Doublet of comb.

CAMPUS.d: The grounds or property of a school, college, university, business, church, or hospital, often understood to include buildings and other structures.
CAMPUS.e:
Borrowed from Latin campus (“field”). Doublet of camp and champ.
First used in its current sense in reference to Princeton University in the 1770s.

CANARD.d: A false or misleading report or story, especially if deliberately so.
CANARD.e:
Borrowed from French canard (“duck, hoax”).
etymology note
The primary English meaning of canard comes from the Medieval French expression “vendre un canard à moitié”, which literally means “to sell half a duck” or “to half-sell a duck”. This was perhaps the punch line to a joke....

CANARY.d: A small, usually yellow, finch (genus Serinus), a songbird native to the Canary Islands.
CANARY.e: From French canarie, from Spanish canario, from the Latin Canariae insulae (“Canary Islands”) (Spanish Islas Canarias); from the largest island Insula Canaria (“Dog Island" or "Canine Island”), named for its dogs, from canārius (“canine”), from canis (“dog”).

CANCAN.d: A high-kicking chorus line dance originating in France.

CANCEL.d: To cross out something with lines etc.
CANCEL.e: From Middle English cancellen, from Anglo-Norman canceler (“to cross out with lines”) (modern French chanceler (“to stagger, sway”)), from Old French canceler, from Latin cancellō (“to make resemble a lattice”), from cancellus (“a railing or lattice”), diminutive of cancer (“a la...

CANCER.d: A disease in which the cells of a tissue undergo uncontrolled (and often rapid) proliferation.
CANCER.e: Borrowed from Latin cancer (“crab”), a calque of Ancient Greek καρκίνος (karkínos, “crab; ulcer; cancer”) (possibly cognate), applied to cancerous tumors because the enlarged veins resembled the legs of a crab. Doublet of canker and chancre.

CANDLE.d: A light source consisting of a wick embedded in a solid, flammable substance such as wax, tallow, or paraffin.
CANDLE.e: From Middle English candel, from Old English candel (“candle”), borrowed from Latin candēla (“candle”), from Latin candeō (“be white, bright, shining”, verb); see candid. Doublet of candela and chandelle.

CANINE.d: Of, or pertaining to, a dog or dogs.
CANINE.e: From Latin canīnus (“of dogs, dog-like”), from canis (“dog”). Compare French canin.

CANING.d: present participle and gerund of cane

CANKER.d: A plant disease marked by gradual decay.
CANKER.e: From Middle English canker, cancre, from Old English cancer (“cancer; crab”), akin to Dutch kanker, Old High German chanchar. Ultimately from Latin cancer (“a cancer”). Doublet of cancer, a later borrowing from Latin, and chancre, which came through French.

CANNAE.d: A village in the Apulia region of south east Italy, known as the site of a battle in 216 B.C. in which the Carthaginians under Hannibal defeated the Romans

CANNED.d: Past tense of CAN: To know how to.
CANNED.e: From Middle English can, first and third person singular of connen, cunnen (“to be able, know how”), from Old English can(n), first and third person singular of cunnan (“to know how”), from Proto-West Germanic *kunnan, from Proto-Germanic *kunnaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃...

CANNER.d: Comparative form of CAN: To know how to.
CANNER.e: From Middle English can, first and third person singular of connen, cunnen (“to be able, know how”), from Old English can(n), first and third person singular of cunnan (“to know how”), from Proto-West Germanic *kunnan, from Proto-Germanic *kunnaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃...

CANNON.d: A complete assembly, consisting of an artillery tube and a breech mechanism, firing mechanism or base cap, which is a component of a gun, howitzer or mortar, which may include muzzle appendages.
CANNON.e: Attested from around 1400 as Middle English canon, canoun, from Old French canon, from Italian cannone, from Latin canna, from Ancient Greek κάννα (kánna, “reed”), from Akkadian 𒄀 (qanû, “reed”), from Sumerian 𒄀𒈾 (gi.na). Doublet of canyon. This spelling was not fixed until about...

CANOLA.e: Genericization of a trade name, of a rapeseed oil from Canada. Acronym of "Can"adian "o"il, "l"ow "a"cid.

CANOPY.d: A high cover providing shelter, such as a cloth supported above an object, particularly over a bed.
CANOPY.e: From Middle English canapy, canepie, canapee, canape, canope, from Old French conopé, Medieval Latin canapeum, canopeum, from Latin cōnōpēum (“mosquito net, canopy”), from Ancient Greek κωνωπεῖον (kōnōpeîon, “mosquito net”), from Ancient Greek κώνωψ (kṓnōps, “mosquito”), of uncer...

CANTED.d: simple past and past participle of cant

CANTER.d: A gait of a horse between a trot and a gallop, consisting of three beats and a "suspension" phase, where there are no feet on the ground. Also describing this gait on other four-legged animals.
CANTER.e: Short for Canterbury pace, from the supposed easy pace of medieval pilgrims to Canterbury.

CANTLE.d: A splinter, slice, or sliver broken off something.
CANTLE.e: From Middle English cantle, cantel, from Old Northern French cantel, Old French chantel (Modern French chanteau, Bourguignon chainteâ), from Medieval Latin cantellus, diminutive of Latin cantus (“corner”). Compare cant (Etymology 3).

CANTON.d: A division of a political unit.
CANTON.e: 1530s, from Middle French canton, from Old French canton (“corner”); heraldic sense from the 1570s, geographic sense from c. 1600.

CANTOR.d: singer, especially someone who takes a special role of singing or song leading at a ceremony
CANTOR.e: Borrowed from Latin cantor, agent noun from perfect passive participle cantus, from verb canere (“to sing”) + agent suffix -or. Doublet of chanter.

CANVAS.d: A type of coarse cloth, woven from hemp, useful for making sails and tents or as a surface for paintings.
CANVAS.e: From Middle English canevas, from Anglo-Norman, from Old Northern French canevas (compare Old French chanevas, chenevas) from a root derived from Latin cannabis, from Ancient Greek κάνναβις (kánnabis). Compare French canevas, resulting from a blend of the Old French and a Picard ...

CANYON.d: A valley, especially a long, narrow, steep valley, cut in rock by a river.
CANYON.e: Borrowed from Spanish cañón. Doublet of cannon.

CAPFUL.d: The amount that will fit into a cap.

CAPIAS.d: An arrest warrant; a writ commanding officers to take a specified person or persons into custody.
CAPIAS.e: Borrowed from Latin capiās (“you should seize, you are to seize”), from capiō (“to seize”).

CAPING.d: Present participle of CAPE: A piece or point of land, extending beyond the adjacent coast into a sea or lake; a promontory; a headland.
CAPING.e:
From Middle English cape, gappe, cap, from Old French cap (“cape, headland”), from Latin caput (“head”).
Doublet of capo, caput, chef, and chief, and distantly with head and Howth.
For sense development, compare English ness (“a promontory point, cape”) from a root related to nos...

CAPITA.e: From the Latin capita, plural of caput.

CAPLET.d: A smooth-coated tablet (pill, as in medicine) shaped like a capsule, used as a tamper-resistant alternative to a capsule, or an easy-to-swallow alternative to regular tablets.

CAPPED.d: Past tense of CAP: A close-fitting hat, either brimless or peaked.
CAPPED.e: Inherited from Middle English cappe, from Old English cæppe, from Proto-West Germanic *kappā (“covering, hood, mantle”), from Late Latin cappa, itself from Latin caput. Doublet of cape, chape, and cope.

CAPPER.d: Comparative form of CAP: A close-fitting hat, either brimless or peaked.
CAPPER.e: Inherited from Middle English cappe, from Old English cæppe, from Proto-West Germanic *kappā (“covering, hood, mantle”), from Late Latin cappa, itself from Latin caput. Doublet of cape, chape, and cope.

CAPSID.d: The outer protein shell of a virus.

CAPTOR.d: One who is holding a captive or captives.
CAPTOR.e: Borrowed from Late Latin captor, from Latin capiō. English usage began around 1688.

CARAFE.d: A bottle, usually glass and with a flared lip, used for serving water, wine, or other beverages.
CARAFE.e: First attested 1786, from French carafe, from Italian caraffa, probably from Arabic غُرْفَة (ḡurfa, “cup or dipper”), from غَرَفَ (ḡarafa, “to ladle”). Doublet of carboy.

CARBON.d: The chemical element (symbol C) with an atomic number of 6. It can be found in pure form for example as graphite, a black, shiny and very soft material, or diamond, a colourless, transparent, crystalline solid and the hardest known material.
CARBON.e: Borrowed from French carbone, coined by Antoine Lavoisier, from Latin carbō, carbōnem (“charcoal, coal”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kerh₃- (“to burn”). By surface analysis, carbo- + -on.

CARBOY.d: A large, rigid bottle, originally made of glass and mainly used for fermentation, and now commonly made of plastic and used to store liquids.
CARBOY.e: From Persian قرابه (qarrâbeh, qarrâbah). Doublet of carafe.

CARDED.d: Past tense of CARD: A playing card.
CARDED.e: From Middle English carde (“playing card”), from Old French carte, from Latin charta, from Ancient Greek χάρτης (khártēs, “paper, papyrus”). Doublet of chart.

CARDIO.d: Cardiovascular; pertaining to the health of the circulatory and respiratory systems.

CAREEN.d: To heave a ship down on one side so as to expose the other, in order to clean it of barnacles and weed, or to repair it below the water line.
CAREEN.e: First attested in the late 16th century, from French carène (“keel”), from Italian carena, from Latin carīna (“keel of a ship”). Doublet of carene and carina.

CAREER.d: One’s calling in life; one's working occupation or profession, especially when pursued seriously and/or over a long period of time.
CAREER.e: Mid 16th century, from French carrière (“road; racecourse”), from Italian carriera, from Old Occitan carreira, from Late Latin carrāria based on Latin carrus (“wheeled vehicle”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱr̥sós, from *ḱers- (“to run”); alternatively, from Middle Frenc...

CARESS.d: An act of endearment; any act or expression of affection; an embracing, or touching, with tenderness.
CARESS.e: From French caresse, from Italian carezza (“dear”), from Latin cārus (“dear”), from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂-, akin to Sanskrit काम (kāma, “love”). Doublet of karezza.

CARIES.d: The progressive destruction of bone or tooth by decay.

CARINA.d: A summer constellation of the southern sky, said to resemble the keel of a ship. It contains the star Canopus, the second brightest star in the night sky. Until 1763, it was part of a larger constellation, Argo Navis.
CARINA.e: Named by the French astronomer Nicolas Louis de Lacaille in 1763. From Latin carīna (“the keel of a ship”)

CARING.e: From care + -ing. The adjective follows from the verb.

CARKED.d: Past tense of CARK: To be filled with worry, solicitude, or troubles.
CARKED.e:
From Middle English carken (“to be anxious, worry”, intransitive), from Old English *carcian ("to be sorrowful, worry"; found in becarcian (“to worry about, care for”)), a frequentative form of Old English carian (“to care”), equivalent to care + -k.
The Middle English carken, al...

CARMAN.d: A person who transported goods, usually with a horse and cart.

CARMEN.d: A female given name from Spanish in the nineteenth century.
CARMEN.e: From Spanish Carmen, cognate with English Carmel. Made famous outside Spain by the opera Carmen (1875) by Georges Bizet. The male name is from Italian Carmine.

CARMOT.d: A mythical element of which the philosopher's stone was believed to be composed.

CARNAL.d: Relating to the physical and especially sexual appetites or activities.
CARNAL.e: From Middle English, from Latin carnālis (“fleshly, of the flesh”), from carō (“flesh”).

CARNET.d: A ticket book, a collection of tickets in the form of a booklet often sold at a discount to single tickets.
CARNET.e: From French carnet (“notebook”), from Middle French quernet (“group of four sheets”).

CARPAL.d: Any of the eight bones of the wrist (carpus).

CARPEL.d: A constituent part of a flower pistil: the female reproductive organs in a flower. A carpel is composed of an ovary, a style, and a stigma, although some flowers have carpels without a distinct style. In origin, carpels are leaves (megasporophylls) that have evolved to enclose the ovules. A pistil may be composed of a single carpel or of several carpels fused together.
CARPEL.e: 1835, borrowed from French carpelle, from New Latin carpellum, a diminutive of Ancient Greek κᾰρπός (kărpós, “fruit”), from Proto-Indo-European *kerp- (“to pluck, harvest”).

CARPET.d: A fabric used as a complete floor covering.
CARPET.e: From late Middle English carpette, from Old French carpite, from Medieval Latin carpita or Italian carpita, introduced in the 13th century by the Florentines from the Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia, from Middle Armenian կարպետ (karpet, “carpet, rug”), earlier կապերտ (kapert).

CARPUS.d: The group of bones that make up the wrist.
CARPUS.e: From New Latin carpus, from Ancient Greek καρπός (karpós, “wrist”).

CARREL.d: Alternative spelling of carol (“a small closet or enclosure built against the inner side of a window of a monastery's cloister, to sit in for study”).
CARREL.e: A variant of carol (“small closet or enclosure”), from Middle English carole (“round dance with singing; group of people dancing and singing in a circle; circular thing; braid, chain (?); stall for study or writing; writing table; etc.”) (possibly referring to the fact that the i...

CARROT.d: A vegetable with a nutritious, juicy, sweet root that is often orange in colour, Daucus carota, family Apiaceae, especially the subspecies sativus.
CARROT.e: From Middle English karette and Middle French carotte, both from Latin carōta, from Ancient Greek καρωτόν (karōtón). Doublet of carotte and related to caraway. Displaced native Middle English more, from Old English more, moru (“edible root, parsnip, carrot”), related to German Mö...

CARRYS.d: Plural of CARRY: To transport from one place to another.

CARTEL.d: A group of businesses or nations that collude to limit competition within an industry or market.
CARTEL.e: In the business sense, borrowed from German Kartell, first used by Eugen Richter in 1871 in the Reichstag. In the political sense, which was the vehicle for this metaphor, the English sense, like the German sense, was borrowed from French cartel in the sixteenth century, from Ita...

CARTON.d: An inexpensive, disposable box-like container fashioned from either paper, paper with wax-covering (wax paper), or other lightweight material.
CARTON.e: Borrowed from French carton, from Italian cartone. Doublet of cartoon.

CARVEL.d: Synonym of caravel (“a light, usually lateen-rigged sailing ship”).
CARVEL.e: From Middle English carvel, carvelle, carvile, kervel (“small ship; caravel”), from Old French caruelle, carvelle, kirvelle, see further at caravel. The English word is cognate with Middle Dutch karveel.

CASABA.d: A cultivar of the muskmelon (Cucumis melo), with bright yellow, wrinkled skin.
CASABA.e: From Turkish Kasaba, a town in Turkey, now Turgutlu.

CASBAH.d: The fortress in a city in North Africa or the Middle East.

CASEIN.d: A protein present in both milk and in the seeds of leguminous plants
CASEIN.e: From French caséine, formed from Latin cāseus (“cheese”) + -ine.

CASHED.d: Past tense of CASH: Money in the form of notes or bills and coins, as opposed to checks, credit or electronic transactions.
CASHED.e: From late Middle French caisse (“money-box”), itself borrowed from Occitan caissa, from Latin capsa (“box”), ultimately from capiō (“take, seize”), from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p- (“grasp”). Doublet of case, chase, and chasse. Compare Spanish caja (“box”).

CASHES.d: Plural of CASH: Money in the form of notes or bills and coins, as opposed to checks, credit or electronic transactions.
CASHES.e: From late Middle French caisse (“money-box”), itself borrowed from Occitan caissa, from Latin capsa (“box”), ultimately from capiō (“take, seize”), from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p- (“grasp”). Doublet of case, chase, and chasse. Compare Spanish caja (“box”).

CASHEW.d: A tree, Anacardium occidentale, native to northeastern Brazil, now widely grown in tropical climates for its cashew nuts and cashew apples.
CASHEW.e: Reanalysis of French acajou as a + cajou, from Old Tupi akaîu. Doublet of acajou.

CASINO.d: A public building or room for gambling.
CASINO.e: From Italian casino, diminutive form of casa (“house”), from Latin casa (“cottage, hut”).

CASKED.d: Past tense of CASK: A large barrel for the storage of liquid, especially of alcoholic drinks. (See a diagram of cask sizes.)
CASKED.e: From Middle French casque. Doublet of casco and casque.

CASKET.d: A little box, e.g. for jewellery.
CASKET.e: Probably from Norman cassette. Possibly reformed by analogy with cask, thus analyzable as cask + -et. Doublet of cassette.

CASQUE.e: Borrowed from French casque. Doublet of casco and cask.

CASSIA.d: The spice made from the bark of members of the genus Cinnamomum other than true cinnamon (C. verum), when they are distinguished from cinnamon.
CASSIA.e: From Latin cassia (“cinnamon”), from Ancient Greek κασσία, κασία, κάσια (kassía, kasía, kásia), from Hebrew קְצִיעָה (qəṣīʿā), from Aramaic קְצִיעֲתָא (qəṣīʿătā), from קְצַע (qṣaʿ, “to cut off”). Compare Kezia.

CASTER.e: From cast + -er; the wheel sense comes from obsolete cast (“to turn”).

CASTLE.d: A large residential building or compound that is fortified and contains many defences; in previous ages often inhabited by a nobleman or king. Also, a house or mansion with some of the architectural features of medieval castles.
CASTLE.e:
From Middle English castle, castel, from late Old English castel, castell (“a town, village”), borrowed from Late Latin castellum (“small camp, fort”), diminutive of Latin castrum (“camp, fort, citadel, stronghold”). Doublet of cashel, castell, castellum, and château.
Parallel bo...

CASTOR.d: A hat made from the fur of the beaver.
CASTOR.e: From Middle French castor, from Old French castor (“beaver”), from Latin castor (“beaver”), from Ancient Greek κάστωρ (kástōr), from Doric Greek κάστον (káston, “wood”).

CASUAL.e: From Middle French casuel, from Late Latin cāsuālis (“happening by chance”), from Latin cāsus (“event”) (English case), from cadere (“to fall”) (whence English cadence).

CATGUT.d: A cord of great toughness made from the intestines of animals, especially of sheep, used for strings of musical instruments, racquets, sutures etc.
CATGUT.e: Possibly an abbreviation of the word cattlegut. Alternatively, it may derive by folk etymology from kitgut or kitstring — the word kit, meaning fiddle, having at some point been confused with the word kit for a young cat.

CATION.d: A positively charged ion: one that would be attracted to the cathode in electrolysis.
CATION.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek κᾰτῐόν (kătĭón), neuter present participle of κᾰ́τειμῐ (kắteimĭ, “to go down, come down”), from κᾰτᾰ- (kătă-, “downwards, down, cata-”) + εἶμῐ (eîmĭ, “to go, come”). Coined by English polymath William Whewell in 1834 for Michael Faraday, who i...

CATKIN.d: A type of inflorescence, consisting of an axis with many unisexual apetalous flowers along its sides, as in the willow and poplar.
CATKIN.e: From Middle Dutch katteken (“catkin”, literally “little cat”). So named due to the resemblance of lengthier kinds to a kitten's tail, or, perhaps more probably, the fine fur found on some catkins (compare the pictures). Cognate with German Kätzchen, modern Dutch katje. By surface...

CATNAP.d: A brief, light sleep, usually during the daytime.

CATNIP.d: Any of the about 250 species of flowering plant of the genus Nepeta, family Lamiaceae, certain of which are said to have medicinal qualities.
CATNIP.e: Compound of cat + nep, nip (“catnip”), from Middle English nep, from Old English nepte, from Proto-West Germanic *nepetā, from Latin nepeta (“catnip”). Compare earlier catmint (“catnip”), from Middle English catt mynte, which very likely existed in Old English (as *cattes minte) ...

CATTED.d: Past tense of CAT: Terms relating to animals.
CATTED.e: From Middle English cat, catte, from Old English catt (“male cat”), catte (“female cat”), from Proto-West Germanic *kattu, from Proto-Germanic *kattuz, generally thought to be from Late Latin cattus (“domestic cat”) (c. 350, Palladius), from Latin catta (c. 75 A.D., Martial), fro...

CATTER.d: Comparative form of CAT: Terms relating to animals.
CATTER.e: From Middle English cat, catte, from Old English catt (“male cat”), catte (“female cat”), from Proto-West Germanic *kattu, from Proto-Germanic *kattuz, generally thought to be from Late Latin cattus (“domestic cat”) (c. 350, Palladius), from Latin catta (c. 75 A.D., Martial), fro...

CATTLE.d: Domesticated animal of the species Bos taurus (cows, bulls, steers, oxen etc), and other hoofed mammals of the genus Bos.
CATTLE.e: From Middle English catel, from Anglo-Norman catel (“personal property”), from Old Northern French (compare French cheptel, Old French chetel, chatel, also English chattel) from Medieval Latin capitāle, from Latin capitālis (“of the head”) (whence also capital, from caput (“head”...

CAUCUS.d: A usually preliminary meeting of party members to nominate candidates for public office or delegates to be sent to a nominating convention, or to confer regarding policy.
CAUCUS.e: Unknown. Often claimed to be from an Algonquian language; transcribed words such as cawaassough and caucauasu meaning "counselor, elder, adviser" appear in early texts. A popular folk etymology attested in Great Leaders and National Issues of 1896 stated: "In the early part of th...

CAUDAL.d: Pertaining to the tail or posterior or hind part of a body.
CAUDAL.e: Borrowed from Latin caudālis (“having a tail”).

CAUGHT.d: Of the method of being out in which the striker hits the ball and a fielder catches it.

CAUSED.d: Past tense of CAUSE: A reason; to make happen.

CAVEAT.e: Learned borrowing from Latin caveat (“may he/she/it beware”), third-person singular present active subjunctive of caveō (“I beware of”). Doublet of show, both ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewh₁- (“to heed, look, feel, take note of”).

CAVERN.e: From Middle English caverne, borrowing from Old French caverne, from Latin caverna (“hollow, cavity, cave”), from cavus (“hollow, excavated, concave”).

CAVIAR.d: Roe of the sturgeon or of certain other large fish, considered a delicacy.
CAVIAR.e: Borrowed from Middle French caviar, from Venetan caviaro (earlier found as Italian caviale), probably by way of Ottoman Turkish خاویار (havyar), from Classical Persian خَاوْیَار (xāwyār). Doublet of ajvar.

CAVING.d: The recreational sport of exploring caves.

CAVITY.d: A hole or hollow depression in a solid object.
CAVITY.e: From Middle French cavité or Late Latin cavitās, from cav(i) (“hollow, excavated, concave”) + -tās (“-ity”, nominal suffix). First attested in the Mid-16th c.

CAVORT.e: Originated in the United States in 1793, as cauvaut, applying to horses, probably from the colloquial intensifying prefix ca-/ka- + vault (“jump, leap”); later generalized. Early sources connect it to cavault, a term for a certain demeanor of horses. Alternatively, a variation of...

CAWING.d: Present participle of CAW: The harsh cry of a crow.

CEDING.d: Present participle of CEDE: To give up; yield to another.
CEDING.e: Borrowed from Middle French ceder, from Old French ceder, from Latin cēdō (“to yield”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱyesdʰ- (“to drive away; to go away”). Cognate with Tocharian B kätk- (“to cross, pass”).

CELERY.d: A European herb (Apium graveolens) of the carrot family.
CELERY.e: From French céleri, from Lombard sellero, from Latin selīnum, from Ancient Greek σέλῑνον (sélīnon). Displaced English march (“celery, smallage”) and smallage (“wild celery”).

CELLAR.d: An enclosed underground space, often under a building, used for storage or shelter.
CELLAR.e: From Middle English celer, seler, from Anglo-Norman celer, Old French celier (modern cellier), from Late Latin cellārium, from Latin cella. Doublet of cellarium.

CELLED.d: Past tense of CELL: A single-room dwelling for a hermit.
CELLED.e: From Middle English celle, selle, from Old English cell (attested in inflected forms), from Latin cella (“chamber, small room, compartment”), later reinforced by Old French cel, sele, Old French cele. Ultimately from Proto-Italic *kelnā, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱelneh₂, from Pr...

CEMENT.d: A powdered substance produced by firing (calcining) calcium carbonate (limestone) and clay that develops strong cohesive properties when mixed with water. The main ingredient of concrete.
CEMENT.e: From Middle English syment, cyment, from Old French ciment, from Latin caementum (“quarry stone; stone chips for making mortar”), from caedō (“I cut, hew”). Doublet of cementum.

CENOTE.d: A deep natural well or sinkhole, especially in Mexico and Central America, formed by the collapse of surface limestone that exposes groundwater underneath, and sometimes used by the ancient Mayans for sacrificial offerings.
CENOTE.e: From Spanish cenote, from Yucatec Maya tsʼonoʼot (“hole with water”).

CENSOR.d: One of the two magistrates who originally administered the census of citizens, and by Classical times (between the 8th century B.C.E. and the 6th century C.E.) was a high judge of public behaviour and morality.
CENSOR.e: The noun is borrowed from Latin cēnsor (“magistrate; critic”), from cēnseō (“to give an opinion, judge; to assess, reckon; to decree, determine”) + -sor (variant of -tor (suffix forming masculine agent nouns)). Cēnseō is derived from Proto-Italic *kensēō, ultimately from Proto-In...

CENSUS.d: An official count or enumeration of members of a population (not necessarily human), usually residents or citizens in a particular region, often done at regular intervals.
CENSUS.e: Borrowed from Latin cēnsus, from cēnseō. See censor.

CENTRE.d: Australia, British, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand, and South Africa standard spelling of center.
CENTRE.e: From Middle English center, centre, from Middle French centre, from Latin centrum, from Ancient Greek κέντρον (kéntron), from κεντεῖν (kenteîn, “to prick, goad”). Doublet of centrum.

CEREAL.d: A type of grass (such as wheat, rice or oats) cultivated for its edible grains.
CEREAL.e: Borrowed from French céréale (“having to do with cereal”), from Latin Cerealis (“of or relating to Ceres”), from Ceres (“Roman goddess of agriculture”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱer- (“grow”), from which also Latin sincerus (English sincere) and Latin crēscō (“grow”) (English cr...

CERISE.d: A deep, bright red colour tinted with pink.
CERISE.e: Borrowed from French cerise (mid 19th century), itself from Vulgar Latin ceresia, from Latin cerasium. Doublet of cherry and kirsch.

CERIUM.d: A chemical element (symbol Ce) with an atomic number of 58, a very soft, ductile, silvery-white metal that tarnishes when exposed to air.

CERMET.d: A composite material composed of ceramic and metal materials, used in such applications as industrial saws and turbine blades.

CERVIX.e: Borrowed from Latin cervīx (“neck”), see below.

CESSED.d: Past tense of CESS: An assessed tax, duty, or levy; billeting.
CESSED.e:
For the first meaning below, the writings of Edmund Spenser, published 1633, point to a borrowing from Irish cís (“tax, tribute, cess, rent”), likely from Latin census.
Other senses: Uncertain. Occurs in print at least as early as 1831, when Samuel Lover used the expression as on...

CESSES.d: Plural of CESS: An assessed tax, duty, or levy; billeting.
CESSES.e:
For the first meaning below, the writings of Edmund Spenser, published 1633, point to a borrowing from Irish cís (“tax, tribute, cess, rent”), likely from Latin census.
Other senses: Uncertain. Occurs in print at least as early as 1831, when Samuel Lover used the expression as on...

CHADOR.d: A loose robe made from a single cloth, worn as a combination head covering, veil and shawl by chiefly Muslim women (and occasionally by those of other faiths) in Iran and South Asia.
CHADOR.e:
From Hindi चादर (cādar) / Urdu چادر, from Classical Persian چادر (čādar, čādur), from Sanskrit छत्त्र (chattra). Doublet of chatra and chatta.
Spelling possibly influenced by modern Iranian Persian چادر (čâdor) or another language.

CHAETA.d: A chitinous bristle of an annelid worm.
CHAETA.e: From Ancient Greek χαίτη (khaítē, “crest, mane, flowing hair, foliage”).

CHAINS.d: Plural of CHAIN: A series of connected links.
CHAINS.e: From Old French chaine, from Latin catēna.

CHAIRS.d: Plural of CHAIR: A seat with a back.
CHAIRS.e: From Old French chaiere, from Latin cathedra.

CHAISE.d: An open, horse-drawn carriage for one or two people, usually with one horse and two wheels.
CHAISE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French chaise. Doublet of cathedra and chair.

CHAKRA.d: Any of (at least) seven centres of spiritual energy in or near the body, according to Ayurveda philosophy.
CHAKRA.e: From Hindi चक्र (cakra) and directly from Sanskrit चक्र (cakra, “wheel, disc, cycle”). As a synonym for hackery, either a correction or hypercorrection of that term based on one of its proposed etymologies. Doublet of chakram, charkha, chukker, cycle, cyclus, and wheel.

CHALET.d: An alpine style of wooden building with a sloping roof and overhanging eaves.
CHALET.e: Borrowed from French chalet, from Franco-Provençal çhalè (“herdsman's hut in the mountains”).

CHANCE.e: From Middle English chance, cheance, chaunce, cheaunce, a borrowing from Old French cheance (“accident, chance, luck”), from Vulgar Latin *cadentia (“falling”), from Latin cadere (“to fall, to die, to happen, occur”). Doublet of cadence and cadenza.

CHANGE.e: From Middle English changen, chaungen, from Old French changier, from Late Latin cambiāre, from Latin cambīre (“to exchange, barter”), derived from the noun cambium (“change”) (whence was loaned the English doublet cambium), from Gaulish cambion, earlier *kambyom (“change”), rela...

CHAPEL.d: A place of worship, smaller than or subordinate to a church.
CHAPEL.e:
From Middle English chapele, chapel, from Old French chapele, from Late Latin cappella (“little cloak; chapel”), diminutive of cappa (“cloak, cape”). Doublet of capelle.
(printing office): Said to be because printing was first carried on in England in a chapel near Westminster Ab...

CHARAS.d: Cannabis resin, used as an intoxicant in India.

CHARGE.d: The amount of money levied for a service.
CHARGE.e: From Middle English chargen, from Old French chargier, from Late Latin carricō (“to load”), from Latin carrus (“a car, wagon”); see car. Doublet of cargo.

CHARVA.d: Unruly youth; disobedient child or teenager.
CHARVA.e: Perhaps from nineteenth-century Romani chavo (“child or youth”). Compare charver, chav.

CHASTE.d: Synonym of pure and virtuous, particularly
CHASTE.e: From Middle English chaste, from Old French chaste (“morally pure”), from Latin castus (“pure”).

CHATTY.d: Of a person, chatting a lot or fond of chatting.

CHAVVY.d: Of or pertaining to a chav or something that a chav might do or use.

CHEAPO.e: From cheap + -o (“person with characteristic”, colloquialising suffix).

CHEAPS.d: Plural of CHEAP: Low in price; of poor quality.

CHECKS.d: Plural of CHECK: To examine; a pattern of squares.

CHEEKY.d: Impudent; impertinent; impertinently bold, often in a way that is regarded as endearing or amusing.
CHEEKY.e:
From cheek + -y.
Compary typologically barefaced, bald-faced; Italian sfacciato (< Latin ex- + faciēs); French effronté, Italian sfrontato (< Latin ex- + frons), Polish czelny (< czoło).

CHEERY.d: In a good mood, happy, cheerful.
CHEERY.e: From Middle English cheri, equivalent to cheer + -y.

CHEESE.d: A dairy product made from curdled or cultured milk.
CHEESE.e: From Middle English chese, from Anglian Old English ċēse, from Proto-West Germanic *kāsī, borrowed from Latin cāseus. Doublet of queso.

CHEESY.e:
From Middle English chesy, equivalent to cheese + -y. Doublet of caseic.
Compare German käsig (“cheesy”).

CHEQUE.d: A written order directing a bank to pay money to a person or entity.
CHEQUE.e: A variant of check, probably influenced exchequer. First attested in the 1790s.

CHERRY.d: A small fruit, usually red, black or yellow, with a smooth hard seed and a short hard stem.
CHERRY.e: From Middle English chery, cherie, chirie, from Anglo-Norman cherise (mistaken as a plural) and Old English ċiris, ċirse (“cherry”), both ultimately from Vulgar Latin ceresia, derived from Late Latin ceresium, cerasium, from Ancient Greek κεράσιον (kerásion, “cherry fruit”), from...

CHERUB.d: A winged creature attending God and guarding his throne described as a being with four faces (man, lion, ox, and eagle), human hands, calf hooves, four wings, and many eyes. A description can be found in Ezekiel chapter 1 and Ezekiel chapter 10; similar to a lamassu (winged bull with a human torso) in the pre-exilic texts of the Hebrew Bible, more humanoid in later texts.
CHERUB.e: From Middle English cherub, cherube, cherubin, cherubine, cherubym, cherubyn, cherybin, gerubin, jerubin (“angel of the second highest order; depiction of such an angel”), from Old English cerubin, cerubim, ceruphin, cherubin, from Latin cherūbīn, cherūbīm, from Ancient Greek χερ...

CHESTS.d: Plural of CHEST: The front of the body; a storage box.
CHESTS.e: From Old English cest, from Latin cista.

CHEVET.e: French [Term?], head of the bed, diminutive from chef (“head”).

CHEWED.d: Past tense of CHEW: To crush with the teeth by repeated closing and opening of the jaws; done to food to soften it and break it down by the action of saliva before it is swallowed.
CHEWED.e: From Middle English chewen, from Old English ċēowan, from Proto-West Germanic *keuwan, from Proto-Germanic *kewwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵyewh₁-. Cognate with West Frisian kôgje, Low German käwwen, Dutch kauwen, German kauen; also Latin gingīva (“gums”), Tocharian B śuwaṃ (...

CHICHI.d: Affectedly trendy; chic and stylish in a pretentious way.

CHICLE.d: The milky latex of the sapodilla tree, used after coagulation as the principal ingredient of chewing gum.
CHICLE.e: Borrowed from Spanish chicle, from a Nahuan language; compare Classical Nahuatl tzictli.

CHIEFS.d: Plural of CHIEF: A leader; most important.
CHIEFS.e: From Old French chief, from Latin caput (head).

CHILLY.e: From chill + -y. Cognate with Swedish kylig (“chilly”), Norwegian kjølig (“chilly”).

CHINAS.d: Plural of CHINA: A country in East Asia; fine ceramic ware.
CHINAS.e: From Persian Chīn, from Sanskrit Cīna.

CHINTZ.d: A painted or stained calico fabric, originally produced in India, and known for its brightly colored designs.

CHIRPY.d: In a good mood; happy and energetic.

CHISEL.d: A cutting tool used to remove parts of stone, wood or metal by pushing or pounding the back when the sharp edge is against the material. It consists of a slim, oblong block of metal with a sharp wedge or bevel formed on one end and sometimes a handle at the other end; there are hand tool versions (the original type) and versions as bits for power tools.
CHISEL.e: From Middle English chisel, chesel, from Old Northern French chisel, cisel, from cisoir (with a change in suffix), from Late Latin cīsōrium (“cutting tool”), from Latin caedō (“cut”). Doublet of scissors.

CHITAL.d: a large spotted deer, of genus Axis, native to India and Sri Lanka
CHITAL.e: From Hindi चीतल (cītal), from Sanskrit चित्रल (citrala, “variegated, spotted”) from Sanskrit चित्र (citra, “spotted, bright; spot, mark”).

CHITIN.d: A complex polysaccharide, a polymer of N-acetylglucosamine, found in the exoskeletons of arthropods and in the cell walls of fungi; thought to be responsible for some forms of asthma in humans.
CHITIN.e: From French chitine, from Latin chitōn (“mollusk”), from Ancient Greek χιτών (khitṓn). See also chiton.

CHIVVY.d: To coerce or hurry along, as by persistent request.
CHIVVY.e: From chivy, chevy (“to chase; to race, scamper”), from chivy, chevy (“a chase, hunt, pursuit”), probably from the title of The Ballad of Chevy Chase, first published in The Complaynt of Scotland (1549); the ballad is about a hunt taking place on a chase (“large country estate whe...

CHOICE.d: An option; a decision; an opportunity to choose or select something.
CHOICE.e: From Middle English chois, from Old French chois (“choice”), from choisir (“to choose, perceive”), possibly via assumed Vulgar Latin *causīre (“to choose”), from Gothic 𐌺𐌰𐌿𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽 (kausjan, “to make a choice, taste, test, choose”), from Proto-Germanic *kauzijaną, from *keusaną (“to ...

CHOLER.e: From Middle English coler (“yellow bile”), from Old French colere (“bile, anger”), from Latin cholera (“bilious disease”), from Ancient Greek χολή (kholḗ, “bile”). Doublet of cholera.

CHOOSE.d: To pick; to make the choice of; to select.
CHOOSE.e: From Middle English cheosen, chesen, from Old English ċēosan (“to choose, seek out, select, elect, decide, test, accept, settle for, approve”), from Proto-West Germanic *keusan, from Proto-Germanic *keusaną (“to taste, choose”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵéwseti, from *ǵews- (“to...

CHOOSY.d: Taking care when choosing that what is chosen best suits one's tastes, desires or requirements.

CHORAL.d: Of, relating to, written for, or performed by a choir or a chorus.
CHORAL.e: From Late Latin choralis, from Latin chorus.

CHOREA.d: An Ancient Greek circular dance accompanied by a chorus.

CHORUS.d: A group of singers and dancers in a theatrical performance or religious festival who commented on the main performance in speech or song.
CHORUS.e: The noun is borrowed from Medieval Latin chorus (“church choir”), Latin chorus (“group of dancers and singers; dance”), from Ancient Greek χορός (khorós, “group of dancers and singers, choir, chorus; dance accompanied by song; round dance”); further etymology uncertain, perhaps f...

CHOUGH.d: Either of two species of bird of the genus Pyrrhocorax in the crow family Corvidae that breed mainly in high mountains and on coastal sea cliffs of Eurasia.
CHOUGH.e: From Middle English choughe, choȝe, coo, cheo, from Old English ċēo (“a bird of the genus Corvus, a jay, crow, jackdaw, chough”) and ċeahhe (“a daw”), both from Proto-West Germanic *kahu (“jackdaw, crow”), from imitative Proto-Indo-European *gewH- (“to crow, caw, shout”). Cognate...

CHOWED.d: Past tense of CHOW: Food, especially snacks.
CHOWED.e: Shortened from chow-chow, from Chinese Pidgin English chow-chow. Compare Macanese chau-cháu. See also English chow fun, chow mein, etc.

CHRISM.d: A mixture of oil and balm, consecrated for use as an anointing fluid in certain Christian ceremonies, especially confirmation.
CHRISM.e: From Middle English crisme, from Late Old English crisma, from Medieval Latin crisma, from Ecclesiastical Latin chrisma, from Ancient Greek χρῖσμα (khrîsma, “anointing”, “unction”), from χρίω (khríō, “anoint”).

CHROMA.d: The colorfulness relative to the brightness of a similarly illuminated area

CHROME.d: Chromium, when used to plate other metals.

CHUBBY.d: Of a person: slightly overweight, somewhat fat, and hence plump, rounded, and soft.
CHUBBY.e: Recorded since 1611, from chub (“short, thick fish species used as bait"; used metaphorically since 1558 for "lazy person”), an assibilated form of cub (“a lump, heap, mass”) and cob, from Middle English *cubbe (found only in derivative cubbel (“a block to which an animal is teth...

CHURCH.d: A Christian house of worship; a building where Christian religious services take place.
CHURCH.e: From Middle English chirche, from Old English ċiriċe (“church”), from Proto-West Germanic *kirikā, an early borrowing of Ancient Greek κυριακόν (kuriakón), neuter form of κυριακός (kuriakós, “belonging to the lord”), from κύριος (kúrios, “ruler, lord”), from Proto-Indo-European *...

CICADA.d: Any of several insects in the superfamily Cicadoidea, with small eyes wide apart on the head and transparent well-veined wings.
CICADA.e: Borrowed from Latin cicāda, ultimately onomatopoeic. Doublet of cicala.

CICELY.d: A female given name from Latin, a variant of Cecily and Cecilia used since the Middle Ages.

CILIUM.d: A short microscopic hairlike organelle projecting from a eukaryotic cell (such as a unicellular organism or one cell of a multicelled organism) which serve either for propulsion by causing currents in the surrounding fluid or as sensors.

CINDER.d: Partially or mostly burnt material that results from incomplete combustion of coal or wood etc.; it often rides the rising smoke column into the air, and it can pose a fire hazard when it lands, in dry conditions.
CINDER.e: From Middle English cyndyr, syndir, synder, sinder, from Old English sinder (“cinder, dross, slag, scoria, dross of iron, impurity of metal”), from Proto-West Germanic *sindr, from Proto-Germanic *sindrą, *sindraz (“dross, cinder, slag”), from Proto-Indo-European *sendʰro- (“coag...

CINEMA.d: A movie theatre, a movie house.
CINEMA.e: Borrowed from French cinéma, clipping of cinématographe (term coined by the Lumière brothers in the 1890s), from Ancient Greek κίνημα (kínēma, “movement”) + γράφω (gráphō, “write, record”). Compare German Kino (“cinema”), ultimately from the same Greek source.

CIPHER.e: 14th century. From Middle English cifre, from Old French cyfre, cyffre (French chiffre), ultimately from Arabic صِفْر (ṣifr, “zero, empty”), from صَفَرَ (ṣafara, “to be empty”). Doublet of chiffre and zero. Sense 8 (a fault in an organ valve) may be a different word.

CIRCLE.d: A two-dimensional geometric figure, a line, consisting of the set of all those points in a plane that are equally distant from a given point (center).
CIRCLE.e: From Middle English circle, cercle, from Old French cercle and Latin circulus, diminutive of Latin circus (“circle, circus”), from Ancient Greek κίρκος (kírkos, “circle, ring”), related to Old English hring (“ring”). Compare also Old English ċircul (“circle, zodiac”), which came ...

CIRCUS.d: A traveling company of performers that may include acrobats, clowns, trained animals, and other novelty acts, that gives shows usually in a circular tent.
CIRCUS.e: From Middle English circus, circo, from Latin circus (“ring, circle”), from Ancient Greek κρίκος (kríkos), κίρκος (kírkos, “ring”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to bend, turn”). Doublet of cirque. Cognate with Old English hring (whence English ring) and Old English hringse...

CIRQUE.e: Borrowed from French cirque (“circular arena; cirque”), from Latin circus (“circle, ring”), from Ancient Greek κίρκος (kírkos, “circle, ring; racecourse, circus”), possibly ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to bend; to turn”). Doublet of circus.

CISTUS.d: A rockrose; a plant of the genus Cistus.

CITIED.d: Past tense of CITY: A large settlement, bigger than a town; sometimes with a specific legal definition, depending on the place.
CITIED.e: Inherited from Middle English cite, derived from Old French cite, derived from Late Latin cīvitātem (“city”), in Classical Latin "citizenry", derived from cīvis (“fellow-citizen”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱey- (“lie down; settle”). Cognate with Old English hīwan pl (...

CITIES.d: Plural of CITY: A large settlement, bigger than a town; sometimes with a specific legal definition, depending on the place.
CITIES.e: Inherited from Middle English cite, derived from Old French cite, derived from Late Latin cīvitātem (“city”), in Classical Latin "citizenry", derived from cīvis (“fellow-citizen”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱey- (“lie down; settle”). Cognate with Old English hīwan pl (...

CITIFY.d: To become more like or more in the character of a city.

CITING.d: Present participle of CITE: To quote; to repeat, as a passage from a book, or the words of another.
CITING.e: From Old French citer, from Latin citare (“to cause to move, excite, summon”), frequentative of ciēre (“to rouse, excite, call”). Sense 4 is the original one.

CITOLE.d: An archaic musical instrument whose exact form is uncertain, generally shown with four strings
CITOLE.e: Probably a French diminutive form of Latin cithara, and not from Latin cista (“a box”).

CITRON.e: Borrowed from French citron (“lemon, lime”), Latin citrus (“citron tree, thuja”), probably via Etruscan derived from Ancient Greek κέδρος (kédros, “cedar”) (see there for further etymology).

CITRUS.d: Any of several shrubs or trees of the genus Citrus in the family Rutaceae.
CITRUS.e: From Latin citrus (“citron tree, thuja”), probably via Etruscan from Ancient Greek κέδρος (kédros); compare Middle English citurtre, cytyr tre. Thus a possible doublet of cedar.

CLAIMS.d: Plural of CLAIM: To assert; a demand for something.
CLAIMS.e: From Old French clamer, from Latin clāmāre (to cry out).

CLAMMY.d: Cold and damp, usually referring to hands or palms.
CLAMMY.e: From Middle English clam (“viscous, sticky; slimy”) + -y, from Old English clǣman (“to smear, bedaub”). Compare German klamm (“clammy”) and klemmen (“to be stuck, stick”). See also clam.

CLAQUE.d: A group of people hired to attend a performance and to either applaud or boo.
CLAQUE.e: Borrowed from French claque (“group of people hired to applaud or boo, claque”, literally “a slap; a clap”).

CLARET.d: A dry red wine produced in the Bordeaux region of France, or a similar wine made elsewhere.
CLARET.e: From Middle English claret, from Middle French claret, from Medieval Latin clārātum vīnum, from clārus. Compare tent (“Spanish red wine”), also from color. Doublet of clairet.

CLASSY.e: From class + -y. Piecewise doublet of classic.

CLAUSE.d: A group of words that contains a subject and a verb; it may be part of a sentence or may constitute the whole sentence, depending on the syntax in each instance.
CLAUSE.e: From Middle English clause, claus, borrowed from Old French clause, from Medieval Latin clausa (Latin diminutive clausula (“close, end; a clause, close of a period”)), from Latin clausus, past participle of claudere (“to shut, close”). See close, its doublet.

CLAVER.d: Frivolous or nonsensical talk; prattle; chatter.

CLAWED.d: Past tense of CLAW: A curved, pointed, horny projection on each digit of the foot of a mammal, reptile, or bird.
CLAWED.e: From Middle English clawe, from Old English clawu, from Proto-Germanic *klawō. Compare West Frisian klau, Dutch klauw, German Klaue, Danish klo, Norwegian klo, and Swedish klo.

CLEARS.d: Plural of CLEAR: Transparent; obvious; to remove.
CLEARS.e: From Old French cler, from Latin clārus.

CLEAVE.d: To split or sever something with, or as if with, a sharp instrument.
CLEAVE.e:
From Middle English cleven, from the Old English strong verb clēofan (“to split, to separate”), from Proto-West Germanic *kleuban, from Proto-Germanic *kleubaną, from Proto-Indo-European *glewbʰ- (“to cut, to slice”).
Doublet of clive. Cognate with Dutch klieven, dialectal German...

CLENCH.e: From Middle English clenchen, from Old English clenċan (“to clinch; hold fast”), a variant of Old English clenġan (“to adhere; remain”), from Proto-Germanic *klangijaną, causative of *klinganą (“to stick; adhere”). Related to cling.

CLERGY.d: Body of persons, such as priests, who are trained and ordained for religious service.
CLERGY.e: From Middle English clergie (attested in the 13th century), from Old French clergie (“learned men”), from Late Latin clēricātus, from Latin clēricus (“one ordained for religious services”), from Ancient Greek κληρικός (klērikós, “of the clergy”). Equivalent to cleric + -ate.

CLERIC.e: Borrowed from Late Latin clēricus, from Ancient Greek κληρικός (klērikós), from κλῆρος (klêros, “a casting lots, drawing lots”). Many officers at Athens obtained their offices by lot, as opposed to election (Liddell and Scott). Doublet of clerk.

CLEVER.d: Nimble with hands or body; dexterous; skillful; adept.

CLEVIS.d: A U-shaped coupling having holes at each end, through which a bolt is run; used especially to fit attachments to a tractor or other vehicle as it allows a degree of rotation about the bolt.
CLEVIS.e: First attested in the 1590s. Ultimately related to cleave. Exact origin unknown; probably derived from the verb cleave. If so, the word ultimately may stem from Scandinavian: compare Old Norse kljúfa (“to split”), Old Norse klofi (“a forked stick”).

CLEWED.d: Past tense of CLEW: A roughly spherical mass or body.
CLEWED.e: From Middle English clewe, from Old English cleowen, cliewen, cliwen (“sphere, ball, skein; ball of thread or yarn; mass, group”), from Proto-Germanic *kliuwiną, *klewô (“ball, bale”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to conglomerate, gather into a mass; clump, ball, bale”). Aki...

CLIENT.d: A customer, a buyer or receiver of goods or services.
CLIENT.e: From Middle English client, from Anglo-Norman clyent, Old French client, from Latin cliēns, akin to clinare (“to lean”).

CLIMAX.d: A rhetorical device in which a series is arranged in ascending order.
CLIMAX.e: From Latin clīmax, from Ancient Greek κλῖμαξ (klîmax, “ladder, staircase, [rhetorical] climax”), from κλίνω (klínō, “I lean, slant”).

CLIMBS.d: Plural of CLIMB: To go upward.

CLINCH.d: To bend and hammer the point of (a nail) so it cannot be removed.

CLINIC.d: A medical facility, such as a hospital, especially one for the treatment and diagnosis of outpatients.
CLINIC.e: Borrowed from French clinique, from Late Latin clīnicus (“a bed-ridden person, one baptized on a sick-bed, a physician”), from Ancient Greek κλῑνικός (klīnikós, “pertaining to a bed”), from κλῑ́νη (klī́nē, “bed”), from κλῑ́νω (klī́nō, “to lean, incline”).

CLIQUE.d: A small, exclusive group of individuals, usually according to lifestyle or social status; a cabal.
CLIQUE.e: Borrowed from French clique, ultimately of imitative origin. Influenced by "claque", though this may have happened in French rather than in English.

CLITIC.d: A morpheme that functions like a word, but never appears as an independent word, instead being always attached to a following or preceding word (or, in some cases, within a surrounding word).

CLIVIA.d: Any plant of the genus Clivia, native to southern Africa.

CLOACA.e: Borrowed from Latin cloāca (“sewer”), related to cluō (“cleanse; purge”), but the derivation is uncertain.

CLOCHE.d: A glass covering, originally bell-shaped, for garden plants to prevent frost damage and promote early growth.
CLOCHE.e: Borrowed from French cloche (“bell”), from Medieval Latin clocca (“bell”). Doublet of cloak and clock.

CLOCKS.d: Plural of CLOCK: A device for measuring time.

CLONAL.d: Relating to, or created by asexual reproduction (cloning)

CLOSER.d: comparative form of close: more close

CLOSET.d: A small room within a house used to store clothing, food, or other household supplies.
CLOSET.e: From Middle English closet, from Old French closet, from clos (“private space”) + -et (diminutive suffix), from Latin clausum. Equivalent to close + -et, but generally applied in French solely to small open-air enclosures.

CLOTHE.d: To adorn or cover with clothing; to dress; to supply clothes or clothing.
CLOTHE.e: From Middle English clothen, from Old English *clāþian (“to clothe”), from Proto-Germanic *klaiþōną (“to clothe”), from Proto-Indo-European *gley- (“to adhere to, stick”). Cognate with Dutch kleden, German kleiden, Swedish kläda, after apocope klä. See also cloth, clad.

CLOUDS.d: Plural of CLOUD: A mass of water vapor in the sky.

CLOUDY.d: Covered with or characterised by clouds.
CLOUDY.e: From Middle English cloudy (“cloudy, overcast, gloomy, dark", also "hilly, rocky”), from Old English clūdiġ (“stony, rocky”), equivalent to cloud + -y.

CLOYED.d: Past tense of CLOY: To fill up or choke up; to stop up.
CLOYED.e: From an aphetic form of Middle English acloyen, from Old French enclouer, encloer, from Vulgar Latin *inclāvāre, from Late Latin clāvāre, from Latin clāvus.

CLUING.d: Present participle of CLUE: A strand of yarn etc. as used to guide one through a labyrinth; something which points the way, a guide.
CLUING.e: Variant of clew (“a ball of thread or yarn”), from Middle English clewe, from Old English clīewen (“ball”), from Proto-West Germanic *kliuwīn, from Proto-Germanic *kliuwīną, *klewô (“ball, bale”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to amass, conglomerate; clump, ball, bale”). Sens...

CLUMPY.d: Forming or tending to form clumps.

CLUMSY.d: Awkward, lacking coordination, not graceful, not dextrous.
CLUMSY.e: Possibly from an alteration of clumsed (“benumbed”) or from clumse (“a stupid fellow; lout”) + -y. More at clumse.

CLUTCH.d: To seize, as though with claws.
CLUTCH.e: From Middle English clucchen, clicchen, cluchen, clechen, cleken, from Old English clyċċan (“to clutch, clench”), from Proto-West Germanic *klukkjan, from Proto-Germanic *klukjaną, from Proto-Germanic *klu- (“to ball up, conglomerate, amass”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to...

COACHS.d: Plural of COACH: A trainer; a vehicle.

COALED.d: Past tense of COAL: A black or brownish black rock formed from prehistoric plant remains, composed largely of carbon and burned as a fuel.
COALED.e:
From Middle English cole, from Old English col, from Proto-West Germanic *kol, from Proto-Germanic *kulą, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵwelH- (“to burn, shine”).
Cognate with West Frisian koal (“coal”), Cimbrian kholl (“coal”), Dutch kool (“coal; carbon”), German Kohle (“coal”), Lux...

COARSE.d: With a rough texture; not smooth.
COARSE.e: Adjectival use of course that diverged in spelling in the 18th century. The sense developed from '(following) the usual course' (cf. of course) to 'ordinary, common' to 'lacking refinement', with 'not fine, granular' arising from its application to cloth. Compare the development ...

COASTS.d: Plural of COAST: Land beside the sea.
COASTS.e: From Old French coste, from Latin costa (rib, side).

COATED.d: simple past and past participle of coat

COATER.d: A machine that coats material with a fluid.

COAXED.d: Past tense of COAX: To fondle, kid, pet, tease.
COAXED.e: Originally (1586) in the slang phrase to make a coax of, from earlier noun coax, cox, cokes "fool, simpleton", itself of obscure origin, perhaps related to cock (“male bird, pert boy”). The modern spelling is from 1706.

COAXES.d: Plural of COAX: To fondle, kid, pet, tease.
COAXES.e: Originally (1586) in the slang phrase to make a coax of, from earlier noun coax, cox, cokes "fool, simpleton", itself of obscure origin, perhaps related to cock (“male bird, pert boy”). The modern spelling is from 1706.

COBALT.d: A chemical element (symbol Co) with an atomic number of 27: a hard, lustrous, silver-gray metal.
COBALT.e: From German Kobalt, formerly also Kobald, ‑olt, ‑old, ‑elt, ‑el, apparently the same word as Kobold (“goblin”), from Middle High German, which became also a Harz Mountains silver miners’ term for rock laced with arsenic and sulfur, so called because it degraded the ore and made t...

COBBED.d: Past tense of COB: A corncob.
COBBED.e: Of uncertain origin. The word has many disparate senses, which are likely of diverse origin. The specifics of these origins have long been debated, as has the question of which senses arise from which origins. At least the swan sense originated in Middle English cobbe (“male swan...

COBBER.d: Comparative form of COB: A corncob.
COBBER.e: Of uncertain origin. The word has many disparate senses, which are likely of diverse origin. The specifics of these origins have long been debated, as has the question of which senses arise from which origins. At least the swan sense originated in Middle English cobbe (“male swan...

COBBLE.e: From Middle English cobill, kobill (used in various combinations with ston, stan (“stone”), note, nutt (“nut”), etc.), probably a diminutive of Middle English *cob, *cobb, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *kubb- (“lump; round object”). Equivalent to cob + -le.

COBWEB.d: A spiderweb, or the remains of one, especially an asymmetrical one that is woven with an irregular pattern of threads.
COBWEB.e: From Middle English copweb, coppeweb. Compare Middle Dutch kopwebbe, German Low German Kobbenwebbe (Westphalian). By surface analysis, cop (“spider”, obsolete) + web.

COCCUS.e: From New Latin, from Latin coccum, from Ancient Greek κόκκος (kókkos, “grain, seed”).

COCCYX.d: The final (bottom-most) fused vertebrae at the base of the spine, the tailbone.
