COCCYX.e: From Latin coccyx, from Ancient Greek κόκκυξ (kókkux, “cuckoo”), referring to the curved shape of a cuckoo's beak when viewed from the side.

COCHOA.d: Any member of the genus Cochoa of medium-sized frugivorous, insectivorous and molluscivorous birds.

COCKED.d: Past tense of COCK: A male bird, especially:
COCKED.e:
From Middle English cok, from Old English coc, cocc (“cock, male bird”), from Proto-West Germanic *kokk, from Proto-Germanic *kukkaz (“cock”), probably of onomatopoeic origin.
Cognate with Middle Dutch cocke (“cock, male bird”) and Old Norse kokkr ("cock"; whence Danish kok (“coc...

COCKLE.d: Any of various edible European bivalve mollusks, of the family Cardiidae, having heart-shaped shells.
COCKLE.e: From Middle English cokel, cokkel, kokkel, cocle, of uncertain origin. Perhaps a diminutive of Middle English cokke, cok (“cockle”), from Old English cocc (found in sǣcocc (“cockle”)) + -le; or perhaps from Old French coquille, from Vulgar Latin *cocchilia, from conchylia, from A...

COCOON.d: The silky case spun by the larvae of some insects in which they metamorphose, protecting the pupa within.
COCOON.e: From French cocon, diminutive of coque (“shell”).

CODDED.d: Past tense of COD: An Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua).
CODDED.e:
From Middle English cod, codde, of uncertain origin:
* Oldest English form cotfich as a surname in the 13th century; for more see cot (“chamber, cottage”).
* A bag or pouch, related to its bloated shape; see Etymology 2 below.
* From Latin gadus, from Ancient Greek γάδος (gádos, ...

CODDER.d: Comparative form of COD: An Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua).
CODDER.e:
From Middle English cod, codde, of uncertain origin:
* Oldest English form cotfich as a surname in the 13th century; for more see cot (“chamber, cottage”).
* A bag or pouch, related to its bloated shape; see Etymology 2 below.
* From Latin gadus, from Ancient Greek γάδος (gádos, ...

CODDLE.d: To treat gently or with great care.
CODDLE.e: Probably from caudle. Compare British dialect caddle (“to coax, spoil, fondle”) and cade.

CODGER.d: An amusingly eccentric or grumpy and usually elderly man.
CODGER.e: Possibly derived from cadger (“hawker”). Or abbreviation of coffin dodger, but this is likely to be a folk etymology.

CODIFY.d: To reduce to a code, to arrange into a code.

CODING.d: The process of encoding or decoding.

COELOM.d: A fluid-filled cavity within the body of an animal. The digestive system is suspended within the cavity, which is lined by a tissue called the peritoneum.
COELOM.e: From international scientific vocabulary, from New Latin, from Ancient Greek κοίλωμα (koílōma, “hollow, cavity”). Cognate with coeliac.

COERCE.d: To restrain by force, especially by law or authority; to repress; to curb.
COERCE.e: From Latin coërceō (“to surround, encompass, restrain, control, curb”), from co- (“together”) + arceō (“to inclose, confine, keep off”).

COEVAL.d: Of the same age or era; contemporary.
COEVAL.e: From Late Latin coaevus, from Latin con- (“equal”) + aevum (“age”).

COFFEE.d: A beverage made by infusing the beans of the coffee plant in hot water.
COFFEE.e: Borrowed from Dutch koffie, from Italian caffè, from Ottoman Turkish قهوه (kahve), from Arabic قَهْوَة (qahwa). Doublet of café and caffè and cognate with the words for "coffee" in other major European languages, most of which are derived from the Turkish and Italian words.

COFFER.d: A strong chest or box used for keeping money or valuables safe.
COFFER.e: From Middle English cofre, coffre, from Old French cofre, coffre, from Latin cophinus (“basket”), from Ancient Greek κόφινος (kóphinos, “basket”). Doublet of coffin. Cognate with German Koffer (“a suitcase”).

COFFIN.d: A closed box in which the body of a dead person is placed for burial.
COFFIN.e: From Middle English coffyn, from Old Northern French cofin (“sarcophagus", earlier "basket, coffer”), from Latin cophinus (“basket”), a loanword from Ancient Greek κόφινος (kóphinos, “a basket”). Doublet of coffer.

COGENT.d: Reasonable and convincing; based on evidence.
COGENT.e: From French cogent, from Latin cōgēns, present active participle of cōgō (“drive together, compel”), from cō + agō (“drive”).

COGGED.d: Past tense of COG: A tooth on a gear.
COGGED.e:
Inherited from Middle English cogge, from Old Norse *kogge, *koggr (see Old Swedish kogge, kogger), from Proto-Germanic *kuggō (“cog, swelling”), from Proto-Indo-European *gugā (“hump, ball”), from *gēw- (“to bend, arch”). Compare Lithuanian gugà (“pommel, hump, hill”).
Cognates ...

COGGER.d: Comparative form of COG: A tooth on a gear.
COGGER.e:
Inherited from Middle English cogge, from Old Norse *kogge, *koggr (see Old Swedish kogge, kogger), from Proto-Germanic *kuggō (“cog, swelling”), from Proto-Indo-European *gugā (“hump, ball”), from *gēw- (“to bend, arch”). Compare Lithuanian gugà (“pommel, hump, hill”).
Cognates ...

COGNAC.d: A brandy distilled from white wine in the region around Cognac in France.
COGNAC.e: Borrowed from French cognac, from Cognac, a city in France, from Medieval Latin Comniacum, from the name Cominius + Gallo-Roman suffix -acum, from Proto-Celtic *-ākom.

COHERE.d: To stick together physically, by adhesion.
COHERE.e: From the Latin cohaereō (“cohere, cling (closely) together, harmonise, be consistent (with), be in agreement with”).

COHORT.d: A group of people supporting the same thing or person.
COHORT.e: From Latin cohors (stem cohort-); borrowed into Old English as coorta, but reintroduced into Middle English as cōhort and chōors via Old French cohorte. Doublet of court.

COHOSH.d: A perennial American herb (Caulophyllum thalictroides), the rough rootstock of which is used in medicine.
COHOSH.e: From an Algonquian word meaning "rough", probably Eastern Abenaki / Penobscot *kkwὰhas. Compare Massachusett kushki (“(it is) rough”). Compare English cocash.

COIFED.d: Past tense of COIF: A hairdo.
COIFED.e: From Middle English coif, coife, coyf, coyfe, coyffe, from Old French coife, coiffe, from Late Latin cofia, from Proto-West Germanic *kuffju, related to Old High German kupphia, kupha, kupfe (“mug, hood, cap”), from Proto-Germanic *kuppijǭ (“cap, hat, bonnet, headpiece”), Proto-G...

COILED.d: Past tense of COIL: Something wound in the form of a helix or spiral.
COILED.e: From Middle English coilen, from Old French coillir, cuillir (“to gather, pluck, pick, cull”) (modern French cueillir), from Latin colligō (“to gather together”), past participle collectus, from com- (“together”) + legō (“to gather”); compare legend. Doublet of cull.

COINED.d: Past tense of COIN: A piece of currency, usually metallic and in the shape of a disc, but sometimes polygonal, or with a hole in the middle.
COINED.e: From Middle English coyn, from Old French coigne (“wedge, cornerstone, die for stamping”), from Latin cuneus (“wedge”). Doublet of coign and cuneus. See also quoin (“cornerstone”). Displaced Middle English mynt, from Old English mynet (whence modern English mint), which was deriv...

COITAL.d: Of or relating to coitus (sexual intercourse).

COITUS.d: Sexual intercourse, especially involving penile–vaginal penetration.

COKING.d: Present participle of COKE: Solid residue from roasting coal in a coke oven; used principally as a fuel and in the production of steel and formerly as a domestic fuel.
COKING.e: The origin is not certain. The OED says it is first attested in 1669. The MED has an earlier attestation in the related sense of "charcoal" in 1430: Middle English coke. This may be the same word as colk (“core”) (perhaps from the notion that coke is the core of the material left...

COLEUS.d: Any of certain plants in the mint family, many used as ornamentals for their colorful, variegated leaves, sometime included in genus Plectranthus (spurflowers), sometimes in their own genus Coleus,
COLEUS.e: From the genus name translingual Coleus, from Latin coleus, from Ancient Greek κολεός (koleós, “sheath”) in reference to the manner in which the stamens are united.

COLLAR.e: From Middle English coler, borrowed from Old French coler (Modern French collier), from Late Latin collāre, from Latin collāris, from collum (“neck”). Cognate with Gothic 𐌷𐌰𐌻𐍃 (hals, “neck”), Old English heals (“neck”). Compare Spanish cuello (“neck”). More at halse. Doublet of c...

COLLET.d: A band, flange, ferrule, or collar, designed to grip and hold a tool or a workpiece under proper control, and usually to release it under control thereafter; such a collet usually is made of a hard, springy material, especially a metal.
COLLET.e: From Middle French collet. Doublet of collar.

COLLIE.d: Any of various breeds of dog originating in Scotland and England as sheepdogs
COLLIE.e: Perhaps originally from coal, with reference to its colour; compare colly and collier. More at Wikipedia at collie § Name.

COLONY.d: An area under the political control of another country and typically occupied by settlers (colonists) from it, or by their descendants.
COLONY.e: From Middle English colane, colonye, from Latin colōnia (“colony”), from colōnus (“farmer; colonist”), from colō (“till, cultivate, worship”), from earlier *quelō, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷel- (“to move; to turn (around)”). Doublet of Cologne, Colonia, and Köln.

COLOUR.d: Commonwealth and Ireland standard spelling of color.

COLUMN.d: A solid upright structure designed usually to support a larger structure above it, such as a roof or horizontal beam, but sometimes for decoration.
COLUMN.e: From Middle English columne, columpne, columpe, borrowed from Old French columne, from Latin columna (“a column, pillar, post”), originally a collateral form of columen, contraction culmen (“a pillar, top, crown, summit”). Akin to Latin collis (“a hill”), celsus (“high”), probabl...

COMBAT.d: A battle, a fight (often one in which weapons are used).
COMBAT.e: 16th century, borrowed from Middle French combat, deverbal from Old French combatre, from Vulgar Latin *combattere, from Latin com- (“with”) + battuere (“to beat, strike”).

COMEDY.d: a choric song of celebration or revel, especially in Ancient Greece
COMEDY.e: From Middle English comedie, from Middle French comedie, from Latin cōmoedia, from Ancient Greek κωμῳδία (kōmōidía), from κῶμος (kômos, “revel, carousing”) + either ᾠδή (ōidḗ, “song”) or ἀοιδός (aoidós, “singer, bard”), both from ἀείδω (aeídō, “to sing”). Doublet of commedia.

COMELY.e: The adjective is derived from Middle English comly, comli, cumly, cumlich (“of a person: beautiful, handsome, etc.; of noble birth, bearing, or character; of behaviour: appropriate, becoming; of an event: convenient; favourable; of a thing: beautiful, wonderful; fitting, proper”)...

COMFIT.d: A confection consisting of a nut, seed or fruit coated with sugar.
COMFIT.e: From Old French confit (“preserved fruit”), from Latin cōnfectum. Doublet of confect, confetto, confit, and konfyt. Compare confit.

COMING.d: Present participle of COME: To move nearer to the point of perspective.
COMING.e:
From Middle English comen, cumen, from Old English cuman, from Proto-West Germanic *kweman, from Proto-Germanic *kwemaną (“to come”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷémt (“to step”), from *gʷem- (“to step”).
Cognates
Cognate from Proto-Germanic with Scots cum (“to come”), Saterland F...

COMITY.d: Courtesy and considerate behaviour towards others; social harmony.
COMITY.e: From Late Middle English comite (“association”), from Latin cōmitās.

COMMIE.d: A communist; a person with communist sympathies; a supposed communist infiltrator.

COMMIT.d: To give in trust; to put into charge or keeping; to entrust; to consign; used with to or formerly unto.
COMMIT.e: Inherited from Middle English committen, itself borrowed from Latin committō (“to bring together, join, compare, commit (a wrong), incur, give in charge, etc.”), from com- (“together”) + mittō (“to send”). See mission.

COMMON.d: Mutual; shared by more than one.
COMMON.e: From Middle English comun, from Anglo-Norman comun, from Old French comun (rare in the Gallo-Romance languages, but reinforced as a Carolingian calque of Proto-West Germanic *gamainī (“common”) in Old French), from Latin commūnis (“common, public, general”), from Proto-Indo-Europ...

COMPED.d: Past tense of COMP: Clipping of complimentary.

COMPEL.e: From Middle English compellen, borrowed from Middle French compellir, from Latin compellere, itself from com- (“together”) + pellere (“to drive”). Displaced native Old English nīedan.

COMPLY.d: To yield assent; to accord; to acquiesce, agree, consent; to adapt oneself, to conform.
COMPLY.e: From Italian complire, Catalan complir (“to complete, fulfil; to carry out”), Spanish cumplir (“to complete, fulfil”), (alternatively from Old French compli), from Latin complēre, from compleō (“to finish, complete; to fulfil”), from com- (prefix indicating completeness of an act...

CONCHA.e: Borrowed from Late Latin concha (“a mussel shell”). Doublet of conch.

CONCUR.d: To agree (in action or opinion); to have a common opinion; to coincide; to correspond.
CONCUR.e: Borrowed from Latin concurro (“to run together, agree”).

CONDOM.d: A flexible sleeve made of latex or other impermeable material such as polyurethane or sheepskin, worn over an erect penis during sexual intercourse as a contraceptive or as a way to prevent the spread of STIs during PIV, anal, or oral.
CONDOM.e: Unknown. Many speculations exist. Possibly derived from Italian guantone, from guanto (“a glove”).

CONDOR.d: Either of two New World vultures, Vultur gryphus of the Andes or Gymnogyps californianus, a nearly extinct vulture of the mountains of California.
CONDOR.e: From Spanish cóndor, from Classical Quechua kuntur. The change /t/ to /d/ was characteristic of the "coastal" variety of the language.

CONFAB.d: Clipping of confabulation (“a casual chat or talk”).
CONFAB.e: Clipping of confabulation, from Middle English confabulacion (“conversation”), from Latin confābulātiōnem, from cōnfābulārī + -tiōnem (suffix forming nouns relating to actions or their results); see further at etymology 2.

CONFER.d: To grant as a possession; to bestow.
CONFER.e: From Early Modern English conferre, from Middle French conférer, from Old French conferer, from Latin cōnferō. Compare Dutch confereren, German konferieren, Danish konferere, Swedish konferera. Doublet of collate. See also infer, relate and refer, delate and defer, as well as pre...

CONFIT.d: Any of various kinds of food that have been immersed in a substance for both flavor and preservation.
CONFIT.e: Unadapted borrowing from French confit, past participle of confire (“to preserve”), from Latin cōnficiō (perfect passive participle cōnfectus). Doublet of comfit, confect, confetto, and konfyt. Compare comfit.

CONGER.d: Any of several scaleless marine eels, of the genus Conger, found in coastal waters
CONGER.e: From Middle English congre, from Old French congre, from Latin conger, from Ancient Greek γόγγρος (góngros), from Proto-Indo-European *geng-, *gong- (“a lump, rounded object”).

CONIES.d: Plural of CONY: A rabbit, especially the European rabbit, Oryctolagus cuniculus (formerly known as Lepus cuniculus).
CONIES.e: From Middle English cony, back formation from conies (plural), from Anglo-Norman conis, the plural of connil (“rabbit”), from Latin cunīculus, of unknown origin. Cognate to Dutch konijn, German Kaninchen, Spanish conejo, and Portuguese coelho. The original pronunciation was /ˈkʌn...

CONING.d: Present participle of CONE: A surface of revolution formed by rotating a segment of a line around another line that intersects the first line.
CONING.e: From Middle English cone (“corner, angle”) and conoun (“cone”), from Medieval Latin cōnus, cōnon (“cone, wedge, peak”), from Ancient Greek κῶνος (kônos, “cone, spinning top, pine cone”). Reinforced by Middle French cone, from the same Graeco-Latin source.

CONIUM.d: Any of the species in the genus Conium of poisonous perennial herbaceous flowering plants.

CONKED.d: Past tense of CONK: The shelf- or bracket-shaped fruiting body of a bracket fungus (also called a shelf fungus), i.e. a mushroom growing off a tree trunk.
CONKED.e: Variant or figurative use of conch. Attested since the nineteenth century.

CONNED.d: Past tense of CON: To study or examine carefully, especially in order to gain knowledge of; to learn, or learn by heart.
CONNED.e:
Etymology tree
Middle English connen
English con
Inherited from Middle English connen, inherited from Old English cunnan (“to know, know how”), inherited from Proto-West Germanic *kunnan (“recognize, know how”), inherited from Proto-Germanic *kunnaną (“to know, know how”), inheri...

CONSUL.d: Either of the two heads of government and state of the Roman Republic or the equivalent nominal post under the Roman and Byzantine Empires.
CONSUL.e: From Middle English consul, from Old English consul, from Latin cōnsul.

CONTRA.d: Against; contrary or opposed to; in opposition or contrast to.

CONVEX.d: Curved or bowed outward like the outside of a bowl, circle, or sphere.
CONVEX.e: Borrowed from Middle French convexe, from Latin convexus (“arched”).

CONVEY.d: To move (something) from one place to another.
CONVEY.e: From Middle English conveien, from Old French conveier (French convoyer), from Vulgar Latin *convio, from Classical Latin via (“way”). Compare convoy.

CONVOY.d: One or more merchant ships sailing in company to the same general destination under the protection of naval vessels.
CONVOY.e: From Middle English, from Old French convoier, another form of conveier, from Vulgar Latin *convio (compare Medieval Latin convio (“to accompany on the way”)), from Latin con- (“together”) + via (“way”).

COOING.d: Present participle of COO: The murmuring sound made by a dove or pigeon.

COOKED.e: From the past tense of the verb cook.

COOKER.e: From cook + -er (agent noun suffix) or + -er (patient suffix) (apple; one who is cooked).

COOKIE.d: A small, flat, baked good which is either crisp or soft but firm.
COOKIE.e:
Borrowed from Dutch koekie, dialectal diminutive of koek (“cake”), from Proto-Germanic *kōkô (compare German Low German Kookje (“biscuit, cookie, cracker”), Low German Kook (“cake”), German Kuchen (“cake”)). More at cake. Not related to English cook.
The computing senses derive f...

COOLED.d: Past tense of COOL: Of a mildly low temperature.
COOLED.e:
From Middle English cool, from Old English cōl (“cool, cold, tranquil, calm”), from Proto-West Germanic *kōl(ī), from Proto-Germanic *kōlaz, *kōluz (“cool”), from Proto-Indo-European *gel- (“cold”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian köil (“cool”), West Frisian koel (“cool”), Dutch k...

COOLIE.d: An unskilled Asian worker, usually of Chinese or Indian descent; a labourer; a porter. Coolies were frequently transported to other countries in the 19th and early 20th centuries as indentured labourers.
COOLIE.e: From Hindustani क़ुली / قلی (qulī, “hired laborer”), possibly from Ottoman Turkish قول (kul, “servant”). Another theory says that it is named after Gujarati કોળી (koḷī), a Gujarati tribe or caste. Other forms occur in Bengali কুলি (kuli) and Tamil கூலி (kūli, “daily hire”). Possi...

COOLTH.d: The state of being cool, temperature-wise; coolness.
COOLTH.e: From cool + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Compare Old Dutch kuolitha (“coolness”).

COOPED.d: Past tense of COOP: A basket, pen or enclosure for birds or small animals.
COOPED.e: From Middle English cǒupe, cupe, from Old English cȳpe (“basket, cask”) or possibly from Middle Dutch cûpe (compare modern Dutch kuip, Saterland Frisian kupe, Middle Low German kûpe), from Old Saxon *kûpa, côpa (“cask”) (compare Middle Low German kôpe, Old High German chôfa, chuo...

COOPER.d: An English surname originating as an occupation of cooper.

COOTIE.e: Probably from Malay kutu (“flea, louse”) (and/or Tagalog/Maori). First attested in English in 1917 as British army slang during World War I.

COPIED.d: Past tense of COPY: The result of copying; an identical or nearly identical duplicate of an original.
COPIED.e: From Middle English copy, copie, from Old French copie (“abundance, plenty; transcript, copy”), from Medieval Latin copia (“reproduction, transcript”), from Latin cōpia (“plenty, abundance”), from *coopia, from co- (“together”) + ops (“wealth, riches”). More at opulent.

COPIER.d: Comparative form of COPY: The result of copying; an identical or nearly identical duplicate of an original.
COPIER.e: From Middle English copy, copie, from Old French copie (“abundance, plenty; transcript, copy”), from Medieval Latin copia (“reproduction, transcript”), from Latin cōpia (“plenty, abundance”), from *coopia, from co- (“together”) + ops (“wealth, riches”). More at opulent.

COPIES.d: Plural of COPY: The result of copying; an identical or nearly identical duplicate of an original.
COPIES.e: From Middle English copy, copie, from Old French copie (“abundance, plenty; transcript, copy”), from Medieval Latin copia (“reproduction, transcript”), from Latin cōpia (“plenty, abundance”), from *coopia, from co- (“together”) + ops (“wealth, riches”). More at opulent.

COPING.d: The top layer of a brick wall, especially one that slopes in order to throw off water.
COPING.e: From cope (sense 2), used in the sense "dress in a cope," "to cover."

COPITA.d: A sherry glass with a tapering bowl.

COPPED.d: Past tense of COP: to capture or arrest someone
COPPED.e: Uncertain. Perhaps from Middle English *coppen, *copen, from Old English copian (“to plunder; pillage; steal”); or possibly from Middle French caper (“to capture”), from Latin capiō (“to seize, grasp”); or possibly from Dutch kapen (“to seize, hijack”), from Old Frisian kāpia (“t...

COPPER.d: A reddish-brown metal, symbol Cu, and atomic number 29.
COPPER.e: Inherited from Middle English coper, from Old English coper, copor (“copper”), from Late Latin cuprum (“copper”), contraction of Latin aes Cyprium (literally “Cyprian brass”), from Ancient Greek Κύπρος (Kúpros, “Cyprus”). Doublet of kobo. Cognate with Dutch koper (“copper”), Germ...

COPSES.d: Plural of COPS: plural of cop

COPTER.e: Clipping of helicopter; see also -copter § Etymology.

COPULA.d: A word, usually a verb, used to link the subject of a sentence with a predicate (usually a subject complement or an adverbial), that unites or associates the subject with the predicate.
COPULA.e: Borrowed from Latin copula (“connection, linking of words”), from co- (“together”) + apere (“fasten”). Doublet of couple.

CORBEL.d: A structural member jutting out of a wall to carry a superincumbent weight.
CORBEL.e: From Middle English corbel, from Old French corbel, from Late Latin corbellus, corvellus, diminutive of Latin corvus (“raven”).

CORDED.d: Past tense of CORD: A long, thin, flexible length of twisted yarns (strands) of fibre (a rope, for example).
CORDED.e: From Middle English corde, from Old French corde, from Latin chorda, from Ancient Greek χορδή (khordḗ, “string of gut, the string of a lyre”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰerH- (“bowels, intestines”)). Doublet of chord and cuerda. More at yarn and hernia.

CORDER.d: One who prepares wood as cordwood.

CORDON.d: A ribbon normally worn diagonally across the chest as a decoration or insignia of rank etc.
CORDON.e: From Middle English cordon, from Middle French cordon, from Old French cordon, diminutive of corde. More at cord.

CORING.d: present participle and gerund of core

CORNEA.d: The transparent layer making up the outermost front part of the eye, covering the iris, pupil, and anterior chamber.
CORNEA.e: From Latin cornea tela (“horny tissue”), from cornu (“horn”).

CORNED.d: Past tense of CORN: Any cereal plant (or its grain) that is the main crop or staple of a country or region.
CORNED.e:
Inherited from Middle English corn, from Old English corn, from Proto-West Germanic *korn, from Proto-Germanic *kurną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵr̥h₂nóm (“grain; worn-down”), from *ǵerh₂- (“grow old, mature”).
Cognate with Dutch koren, German Low German Koorn, German Korn, Danis...

CORNER.d: The point where two converging lines meet; an angle, either external or internal.
CORNER.e: From Middle English corner, from Anglo-Norman cornere (compare Old French cornier, corniere (“corner”)), from Old French corne (“corner, angle”, literally “a horn, projecting point”), from Vulgar Latin *corna (“horn”), from Latin cornua, plural of cornū (“projecting point, end, h...

CORNET.d: A musical instrument of the brass family, slightly smaller than a trumpet, usually in the musical key of B-flat.
CORNET.e: From Middle English cornet, from Old French cornet, a diminutive of a popular reflex of Latin cornū (“horn”).

CORONA.d: A large, round, pendent chandelier, with spikes around its upper rim to hold candles or lamps, usually hung from the roof of a church.
CORONA.e: The noun is borrowed from Latin corōna (“crown; garland, wreath”), from Ancient Greek κορώνη (korṓnē, “type of crown; curved object (door handle, tip of a bow, stern of a ship, etc.)”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to turn, bend”). The English word is a doublet of crown, k...

CORPSE.d: A dead body, especially that of a human as opposed to an animal.
CORPSE.e:
From Middle English, from earlier corse, from Old French cors, from Latin corpus (“body”).
Displaced native English likam and English lich. The ⟨p⟩ was inserted due to the original Latin spelling. Doublet of corps and corpus, and distantly of riff. The verb sense derives from the...

CORPUS.d: A collection of written or spoken texts.
CORPUS.e: Borrowed from Latin corpus (“body”). Doublet of corpse, corps, and riff.

CORRAL.d: An enclosure for livestock, especially a circular one.
CORRAL.e: From Spanish corral. Doublet of kraal.

CORRIE.d: A bowl-shaped geographical feature formed by glaciation.

CORSET.d: A woman's foundation garment, reinforced with stays, that supports the waistline, hips and bust.
CORSET.e: From Middle English corset, from Old French corset. Equivalent to corse + -et.

CORTEX.d: The outer layer of an internal organ or body structure, such as the kidney or the brain.

CORVES.d: Plural of CORF: A large basket, especially as used for coal.
CORVES.e: From Middle English corf, borrowed from Middle Low German korf or Middle Dutch korf, ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *korb.

CORYMB.d: A cluster of flowers with a flat or convex top.
CORYMB.e: From the French corymbe, from the Latin corymbus, from the Ancient Greek κόρυμβος (kórumbos). Doublet of corymbus.

COSHED.d: Past tense of COSH: A weapon made of leather-covered metal similar to a blackjack.

COSHES.d: Plural of COSH: A weapon made of leather-covered metal similar to a blackjack.

COSIER.d: Comparative form of COSY: Affording comfort and warmth; snug; social and comfortable.
COSIER.e: From Scots cosie, from Old Scots colsie, but ultimate derivation is unknown. Possibly of North Germanic origin, such as Norwegian kose seg (“to have a cozy time”), from Old Norse kose sig, from koselig, koslig, perhaps ultimately from Old High German kōsa; see modern German kosen...

COSIES.d: Plural of COSY: Affording comfort and warmth; snug; social and comfortable.
COSIES.e: From Scots cosie, from Old Scots colsie, but ultimate derivation is unknown. Possibly of North Germanic origin, such as Norwegian kose seg (“to have a cozy time”), from Old Norse kose sig, from koselig, koslig, perhaps ultimately from Old High German kōsa; see modern German kosen...

COSIGN.d: To sign a document jointly with another person, sometimes as an endorsement.

COSINE.d: In a right triangle, the ratio of the length of the side adjacent to an acute angle to the length of the hypotenuse. Symbol: cos
COSINE.e: From co- + sine, short for complementi sinus in Latin, meaning “sine of the complement”. Doublet of cosinus.

COSMIC.d: Of or from or pertaining to the cosmos or universe.

COSMOS.d: The universe regarded as a system with harmony and order.
COSMOS.e:
From Middle English cossmos (“the universe; the world”), borrowed from Ancient Greek κόσμος (kósmos, “order; universe; the earth, the world; decoration, ornament”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱens- (“to announce, proclaim; to put in order”).
The plural form cosmoi is a ...

COSSET.d: To treat like a pet; to overly indulge.
COSSET.e: Perhaps from Middle English cotsete, from Old English cotsǣta (“cottager”), from cot (“cottage”) (Modern English cot (“cottage”) (archaic)) + -sǣta (“-sitter”); compare coscet. Compare German Hauslamm (literally “house lamb”), Italian casiccio.

COSTED.d: Past tense of COST: To incur a charge of; to require payment of a (specified) price.
COSTED.e: From Middle English costen, from Old French coster, couster (“to cost”), from Medieval Latin cōstō, from Latin cōnstō (“stand together”).

COSTLY.e: From Middle English costly, costely, costeley, equivalent to cost + -ly.

COTING.d: Present participle of COTE: A cottage or hut.
COTING.e: From Middle English cote, from the Old English cote, the feminine form of cot (“small house”); doublet of cot (in the sense of “cottage”) and more distantly related to cottage. Cognate to Dutch kot.

COTTAR.d: Alternative form of cotter (“peasant inhabiting a cottage”).

COTTED.d: Past tense of COT: A simple bed, especially one for portable or temporary purposes.
COTTED.e: Borrowed from Hindi खाट (khāṭ), from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀔𑀝𑁆𑀝𑀸 (khaṭṭā), from Sanskrit खट्वा (khaṭvā, “bedstead”).

COTTER.d: Comparative form of COT: A simple bed, especially one for portable or temporary purposes.
COTTER.e: Borrowed from Hindi खाट (khāṭ), from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀔𑀝𑁆𑀝𑀸 (khaṭṭā), from Sanskrit खट्वा (khaṭvā, “bedstead”).

COTTON.e: From Middle English cotoun, from Anglo-Norman cotun, Old French coton, from (Genoese) Old Italian cotone, from Arabic قُطُن (quṭun).

COUGAR.d: A wild feline, of species Puma concolor, native to the Americas.
COUGAR.e: From French couguar, from Portuguese cuguardo, a deformation of Brazilian Portuguese suçuarana (earlier çuçuarana), perhaps from Old Tupi sûasuarana (“deerlike animal”), from suasú (“deer”); compare sɨwasuarána (“cervine”)) or perhaps from Guaraní guaçuara).

COULIS.d: A thick sauce made with pureed vegetable or fruit and often used as a garnish.

COUNTY.d: The land ruled by a count or a countess.
COUNTY.e: From Middle English countee, counte, conte, from Anglo-Norman counté, Old French conté (French comté), from Latin comitātus (“jurisdiction of a count”), from comes (“count, earl”). Cognate with Spanish condado (“county”) and Italian contea (“county”). Doublet of comitatus, borrow...

COUPLE.d: Two of the same kind connected or considered together.
COUPLE.e: From Middle English couple, from Old French couple, from Latin cōpula. Doublet of copula.

COUPON.d: A section of a ticket, showing the holder to be entitled to some specified accommodation or service, as to a passage over a designated line of travel, a particular seat in a theater, a discount, etc.
COUPON.e: From French coupon, from couper (“to cut”).

COURSE.e: From Middle English cours, from Old French cours, from Latin cursus (“course of a race”), from currō (“run”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱers- (“to run”). Doublet of cursus and cour.

COURTS.d: Plural of COURT: A place for legal proceedings; a royal residence.
COURTS.e: From Old French cort, from Latin cohors.

COUSIN.d: Chiefly with a qualifying word: Any relation (especially a distant one) who is not a direct ancestor or descendant but part of a person's extended family; a kinsman or kinswoman.
COUSIN.e: The noun is derived from Middle English cosin, cosine, cosyn (“blood relative, kinsman or kinswoman; any relative; nephew or niece; first cousin; grandson or granddaughter; descendant; godchild or godparent, or a relative of a godchild or godparent; (figurative) closely related o...

COVARY.d: To vary together with another variable, particularly in a way that may be predictive

COVERT.e: From Middle English covert, from Old French covert, past participle of covrir (“to cover”) (corresponding to Latin coopertus); cognate to cover. Not closely related to overt, despite what the most common pronunciation would suggest.

COVING.d: Present participle of COVE: A hollow in a rock; a cave or cavern.
COVING.e: From Middle English cove, from Old English cofa (“chamber; den”), from Proto-West Germanic *kobō, from Proto-Germanic *kubô. Cognate with Dutch koof (“cove”), German Low German Koov (“small room”), German Koben (“nook, shed”), Icelandic kofi (“hut, shack”). This word has probably...

COWARD.e:
From Middle English coward, from Old French coart, cuard ( > French couard), from coue (“tail”), coe + -ard (pejorative agent noun suffix); coue, coe is in turn from Latin cauda.
The reference seems to be to an animal "turning tail", or having its tail between its legs, especiall...

COWBOY.d: A man who tends free-range cattle, especially in the American West.
COWBOY.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
From cow + boy. More on Wikipedia.

COWING.d: Present participle of COW: An adult female of the species Bos taurus, especially one that has calved.
COWING.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *gʷṓws
Proto-Germanic *kōz
Proto-West Germanic *kō
Old English cū
Middle English cow
English cow
Inherited from Middle English cow, cou, from Old English cū (“cow”), from Proto-West Germanic *kō, from Proto-Germanic *kōz (“cow”), from Proto-Indo...

COWPOX.d: A pustular, eruptive skin disease of cattle caused by a virus of species Orthopoxvirus cowpox, with lesions occurring principally on the udder and teats. Human infection may occur from touching cows, and gives immunity to smallpox.

COWRIE.d: A small gastropod (Monetaria moneta, syn. Cypraea moneta) common in the Indian Ocean; its shell.
COWRIE.e: Mid-17th century, borrowed from Hindi कौड़ी (kauṛī).

COXING.d: Present participle of COX: A coxswain of a boat, especially of a racing crew.

COYING.d: Present participle of COY: Bashful, shy, retiring.
COYING.e: From Middle English coy, from Old French coi, earlier quei (“quiet, still”), from Latin qu(i)ētus (“resting, at rest”). Doublet of quit, quiet, quite, and quietus.

COYOTE.d: Canis latrans, a species of canine native to North America.
COYOTE.e: Borrowed from Spanish coyote, from a Nahuan language, from Proto-Nahuan *koyootl. Compare Chinook ki-o-tī.

COZZIE.d: A swimming costume (especially a female swimming costume).

CRABBY.d: Relating to or resembling crabs; crablike.

CRACKS.d: Plural of CRACK: A narrow break; to break without separating.

CRADLE.d: A bed or cot for a baby, oscillating on rockers or swinging on pivots.
CRADLE.e: From Middle English cradel, credel, from Old English cradol, from Proto-West Germanic *kradul, from Proto-Germanic *kradulaz, from Proto-Germanic *kradô (“(wicker) basket”). Related to cart.

CRAFTS.d: Plural of CRAFT: A skill; a vehicle; to make by hand.

CRAFTY.e: From Middle English crafty, crefty, craftiȝ, from Old English cræftiġ (“ingenious; skilful; crafty; cunning; virtuous; powerful”), from Proto-West Germanic *kraftag, *kraftīg, *kraftug, from Proto-Germanic *kraftugaz (“powerful”), equivalent to craft + -y. Cognate with Saterland ...

CRAGGY.d: Characterized by rugged, sharp, or coarse features.

CRANKY.d: Not in good working condition; defective, faulty.
CRANKY.e: From crank + -y. Compare Middle Low German krankich (“sickly, unwell”).

CRANNY.d: A small, narrow opening, fissure, crevice, or chink, as in a wall, or other substance.
CRANNY.e: From Middle English crany, crani (“cranny”), apparently a diminutive of *cran (+ -y), from Old French cran, cren (“notch, fissure”), a derivative of crener (“to notch, split”), from Medieval Latin crenō (“split”, verb), from Vulgar Latin *crinō (“split, break”, verb), of obscure ...

CRAPPY.d: Of very poor quality; unpleasant; distasteful.

CRATER.d: A hemispherical pit created by the impact of a meteorite or other object.
CRATER.e: First coined 1613, from Latin crātēr (“basin”), from Ancient Greek κρᾱτήρ (krātḗr, “mixing-bowl, wassail-bowl”).

CRATON.d: A part of the Earth’s crust that has survived the splitting and merging of continents.
CRATON.e: From Ancient Greek κράτος (krátos, “strength, might”). Shortened from original cratogen which was analogical to orogen.

CRAVAT.d: A wide fabric band worn as a necktie by men having long ends hanging in front.
CRAVAT.e: From French cravate, an appellative use of Cravate (“Croat”), from Dutch Krawaat, from German Krawatte, from Serbo-Croatian Hr̀vāt/Хр̀ва̄т (“Croat”). The cravat is regarded as originating from a linen scarf worn by Croatian mercenaries which was adopted into French fashion in the...

CRAVEN.d: Unwilling to fight; lacking even the rudiments of courage; extremely cowardly.
CRAVEN.e: From Middle English cravant, either borrowed from Old French cravanté (“defeated”), past participle of cravanter (ultimately from Latin crepare), or a modification of creaunt (“defeated”) after craven (“to crave”).

CRAYON.d: A stick of colored chalk or wax used for drawing.
CRAYON.e: Borrowed from French crayon (“pencil”), from craie (“chalk”) + -on (“(diminutive)”), from Latin creta (“chalk, clay”), from crētus.

CREAMS.d: Plural of CREAM: The fatty part of milk; a pale yellow colour.

CREAMY.e: From Middle English cremy, equivalent to cream + -y. Piecewise doublet of cremey.

CREASE.d: A line or mark made by folding or doubling any pliable substance; hence, a similar mark, however produced.
CREASE.e: From earlier English creast, from Middle English crest (“ridge, crest”). More at crest.

CREATE.d: To bring into existence; (sometimes in particular:)
CREATE.e: From Middle English createn, from Latin creātus, the perfect passive participle of creō, see -ate (verb-forming suffix). In this sense, mostly displaced Old English wyrċan (whence Modern English work) and ġesċieppan (whence Modern English shape).

CREDIT.d: To believe; to put credence in.
CREDIT.e: Borrowed from Middle French crédit (“belief, trust”), from Latin crēditum (“a loan, credit”), neuter of crēditus, past participle of crēdere (“to believe”). The verb is from the noun. Doublet of shraddha, creed.

CREOLE.d: A language formed from two or more languages which has developed from a pidgin to become a first language.
CREOLE.e: See Creole. Attested in English to refer to language from the 18th century.

CRETIN.d: A person who fails to develop mentally and physically due to a congenital hypothyroidism.
CRETIN.e: From French crétin (“cretin, idiot”), likely from crestin, an Alpine dialectal form of chrétien, from Latin christiānus in the lost sense of “anyone in Christendom”, often with a sense of “poor fellow”. Doublet of Christian.

CREWEL.d: Worsted yarn, slackly twisted, used for embroidery.
CREWEL.e: Of unknown origin; earlier forms include crule, crewle, and croole.

CRIMES.d: Plural of CRIME: An illegal act.

CRINGE.d: To cower, flinch, recoil, shrink, or tense, as in disgust, embarrassment, or fear.
CRINGE.e: The verb is derived from Middle English crengen (“to bend in a haughty manner; to condescend”) [and other forms], from Old English *crenċan, *crenċġan, *crenġan (“to cause to fall or turn”), the causative of crinċġan (“to yield; to cringe; to fall; to die, perish”), from Proto-Ge...

CRISIS.d: A crucial or decisive point or situation; a turning point.
CRISIS.e: From Latin crisis, from Ancient Greek κρίσις (krísis, “a separating, power of distinguishing, decision, choice, election, judgment, dispute”), from κρίνω (krínō, “pick out, choose, decide, judge”).

CRISPY.d: Having a crisp texture; brittle yet tender.
CRISPY.e: From Middle English crispy; equivalent to crisp + -y.

CRITIC.d: A person who appraises the works of others.
CRITIC.e: Borrowed from Middle French critique, from Latin criticus, from Ancient Greek κριτικός (kritikós, “of or for judging, able to discern”), from κρίνω (krínō, “I judge”).

CROCUS.d: A perennial flowering plant (of the genus Crocus in the Iridaceae family). Saffron is obtained from the stamens of Crocus sativus.
CROCUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin crocus, from Ancient Greek κρόκος (krókos, “crocus”), from an ancient Semitic language.

CROTCH.d: The ventral area (very bottom) of the human body between where the legs fork from the torso, in the area of the genitals and anus.
CROTCH.e:
Of disputed origin; two possibilities seem likely:
* From Middle English croche, variant of crucche (“crutch”); compare crook.
* From Middle English croche, variant of crouche (“cross, crozier”).

CROTON.d: Any of various plants, of the genus Croton, that yield croton oil.
CROTON.e: From New Latin crotōn, from Ancient Greek κροτών (krotṓn, “tick”), from the size and shape of the seed.

CROUCH.d: To bend down; to stoop low; to stand close to the ground with legs bent, like an animal when waiting for prey, or someone in fear.
CROUCH.e: From Middle English crouchen (“to bend, crouch”), variant of croken (“to bend, crook”), from crok (“crook, hook”), from Old Norse krókr (“hook”), from Proto-Germanic *krōkaz (“hook”), from Proto-Indo-European *gerg- (“wicker, bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *ger- (“to turn, wind...

CROUPY.d: Of, pertaining to, suggestive of, or caused by croup.

CROWDS.d: Plural of CROWD: A large group of people.

CROWED.d: Past tense of CROW: A bird, usually black, of the genus Corvus, having a strong conical beak, with projecting bristles; it has a harsh, croaking call.
CROWED.e: From Middle English crowe, from Old English crāwe, from Proto-West Germanic *krāā, from Proto-Germanic *krēǭ (compare West Frisian krie, Dutch kraai, German Krähe), from *krēaną (“to crow”). See below.

CROWNS.d: Plural of CROWN: A royal headdress; the top of the head.
CROWNS.e: From Anglo-Norman coroune, from Latin corōna.

CRUDDY.e: From Middle English cruddi, equivalent to crud + -y.

CRUISE.d: A sea or lake voyage, especially one taken for pleasure.
CRUISE.e: Borrowed from Dutch kruisen (“cross, sail around”), from kruis (“cross”), from Middle Dutch cruce, from Latin crux.

CRUNCH.d: To crush something, especially food, with a noisy crackling sound.
CRUNCH.e: From earlier craunch, cranch, of imitative origin.

CRUSES.d: Plural of CRUS: The shin (tibia and fibula)

CRUSTY.d: Having a crust, especially a thick one.
CRUSTY.e: From Middle English, equivalent to crust + -y.

CRUTCH.d: A device to assist in motion as a cane, especially one that provides support under the arm to reduce weight on a leg.
CRUTCH.e:
From Middle English crucche, from Old English cryċċ (“crutch, staff”), from Proto-West Germanic *krukkju, from Proto-Germanic *krukjō (“crutch, staff”), from Proto-Indo-European *grewg- (“wrinkle, bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *ger- (“to turn, bend”).
Cognate with Scots curche...

CRUXES.d: Plural of CRUX: The basic, central, or essential point or feature.
CRUXES.e: From Latin crux (“cross, wooden frame for execution”), possibly from the Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to turn, to bend”). Doublet of cross and crouch (“cross”).

CRYING.d: Present participle of CRY: To shed tears; to weep. Especially in anger or sadness
CRYING.e: The verb is from Middle English crien (13th century), from Old French crier, from Vulgar Latin *crītāre, generally thought to derive from Classical Latin quirītāre (Proto-West Germanic *krītan has also been suggested as a source). The noun corresponds to Middle English cry, crie,...

CRYPTO.e: All senses trace back to clippings of words derived from the prefix crypto-, developed at various times in the 20th and 21st centuries. During the 2010s and 2020s, the "cryptocurrency" sense has become the dominant sense. The "cryptography" sense predates that one; thus, a comput...

CUBANE.d: One of the Platonic hydrocarbons, C₈H₈, having the carbon atoms placed at the vertices of a cube.

CUBING.d: Present participle of CUBE: A regular polyhedron having six identical square faces.
CUBING.e: From Old French cube, from Latin cubus, from Ancient Greek κύβος (kúbos).

CUBISM.d: An artistic movement in the early 20th Century characterized by the depiction of natural forms as geometric structures of planes.
CUBISM.e: From French cubisme. One story is that, in 1908, as a new canvas by Braque was being carried past, someone said, “Encore des cubes! assez de cubisme!”. The quotations below ascribe the coinage to Matisse. Sometimes attributed to French art critic Louis Vauxcelles who popularized ...

CUBOID.d: Of the shape of a cube.

CUCKOO.d: Any of various birds, of the family Cuculidae within the order Cuculiformes, famous for laying its eggs in the nests of other species; but especially a common cuckoo (Cuculus canorus), that has a characteristic two-note call.
CUCKOO.e:
From Middle English cokkou, kokkow, cukkuk, gokkouȝ, probably from Old French cocu, coquu, cucu (whence French coucou); ultimately onomatopoeic of the song of the male Common Cuckoo (Cuculus canorus), perhaps via Latin cucūlus (“cuckoo”).
Compare dialectal English gowkoo (“cuckoo...

CUDDLE.d: An intimate physical embrace, typically while lying (or sitting): a snuggle, an instance of lying together snugly, as one might with a partner (more intimate than a hug, and typically of longer duration).
CUDDLE.e: Origin uncertain, but probably from a frequentative form of Middle English *cudden, cuththen, keththen (“to embrace”), a variant of cuthen, kuthen, kithen (“to be familiar with, make known”), from Middle English cuth, couth (“known, familiar”), equivalent to couth + -le. Cognate ...

CUDDLY.d: Suitable for cuddling; designed to be cuddled.

CUDGEL.d: A short heavy club with a rounded head used as a weapon.
CUDGEL.e: From Middle English kuggel, from Old English cyċġel (“a large stick, cudgel”), from Proto-West Germanic *kuggil, from Proto-Germanic *kuggilaz (“knobbed instrument”), derivative of Proto-Germanic *kuggǭ (“cog, swelling”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewgʰ- (“swelling, bow”), from P...

CUEING.d: Present participle of CUE: The name of the Latin-script letter Q/q.
CUEING.e: From Middle English cu (used for half a farthing, from q as an abbreviation for Latin quadrāns (“quarter of an as”)), from Latin cū, kū. Compare French ku.

CUESTA.d: A hill or ridge with a gentle slope on one side, and a steep slope on the other.
CUESTA.e: Borrowed from Spanish cuesta (“slope”). Doublet of coast.

CUFFED.d: Past tense of CUFF: Glove; mitten
CUFFED.e: From Middle English cuffe, coffe (“glove, mitten”), of obscure origin. Perhaps from Old English cuffie (“hood, cap”), from Medieval Latin cofia, cofea, cuffa, cuphia (“helmet, headdress, hood, cap”), from Frankish *kuf(f)ja (“headdress”), from Proto-West Germanic *kuffju, from Pr...

CUISSE.d: Defensive armour (especially of plate) for the thigh.
CUISSE.e: From French cuisse (“thigh”); compare French cuissard, Old French cuissot (“armour for the thigh, cuish”). Doublet of coxa.

CULLET.d: Scrap glass which is melted down for reuse.

CULMED.d: Past tense of CULM: Waste coal, used as a poor quality fuel.
CULMED.e: From Middle English culme, colme (“fragments of coal”), of uncertain origin. Probably from Old English *colm, related to Old English col (“coal”). Alternatively, perhaps from Welsh cwlm (“knot or tie”), applied to this species of coal, which is much found in balls or knots in som...

CULTUS.d: Established or accepted religious rites or customs of worship; state of religious development.
CULTUS.e: From Latin cultus (“cultivation, culture”). See cult.

CUMBER.d: To slow down; to hinder; to burden; to encumber.
CUMBER.e: From Middle English combren, aphetic form of acombren or encombren, borrowed from Old French encombrer, ultimately either from Latin cumulus or Proto-Celtic *kombereti (“to bring together”), from *kom- + *bereti (“to bear”). Cognate with German kümmern (“to take care of”).

CUMMER.d: Comparative form of CUM: Used in indicating a thing or person which has two or more roles, functions, or natures, or which has changed from one to another.

CUPFUL.d: The amount necessary to fill a cup.
CUPFUL.e: From Middle English copful, copfull, cupfulle, cuppefulle, equivalent to cup + -ful. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Kopful (“cupful”), West Frisian kopfol (“cupful”).

CUPOLA.d: A dome-shaped ornamental structure located on top of a larger roof or dome.
CUPOLA.e: Borrowed from Italian cupola, from Latin cūpula (“little tub”); from Latin cūpa, cuppa (“cup”); named for its resemblance to a cup turned over.

CUPPED.d: Past tense of CUP: A concave vessel for drinking, usually made of opaque material (as opposed to a glass) and with a handle.
CUPPED.e:
Inherited from Middle English cuppe, coppe, from the merger of Old English cuppe (“cup”) and Old English copp (“cup, vessel”).
Old English cuppe is a borrowing from Late Latin cuppa, itself of obscure origin, but probably from earlier Latin cūpa (“tub, cask”), from Proto-Indo-Eur...

CUPPER.d: Comparative form of CUP: A concave vessel for drinking, usually made of opaque material (as opposed to a glass) and with a handle.
CUPPER.e:
Inherited from Middle English cuppe, coppe, from the merger of Old English cuppe (“cup”) and Old English copp (“cup, vessel”).
Old English cuppe is a borrowing from Late Latin cuppa, itself of obscure origin, but probably from earlier Latin cūpa (“tub, cask”), from Proto-Indo-Eur...

CUPULE.d: Any small structure shaped like a cup, such as at the base of an acorn, or the sucker on the feet of some flies.

CURACY.d: The office or position of a curate.

CURARE.d: A plant, Strychnos toxifera, formerly used in arrow poisons in South America due to its D-tubocurarine content.
CURARE.e: From a Cariban language; compare Kari'na urari, Trió urari, wïrari, Akawaio urari, Pemon urari, Macushi urari, referring to various vines of genus Strychnos.

CURATE.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin cūrātus (“one who has been curated, a curate”), a substantivation of the perfect passive participle of cūrō. Doublet of curato and curé. Equivalent to cure + -ate (noun-forming suffix).

CURBED.d: Past tense of CURB: A concrete margin along the edge of a road; a kerb (UK, Australia, New Zealand).
CURBED.e: From Middle French courbe (“curve, curved object”), from Latin curvus (“bent, crooked, curved”). Doublet of curve.

CURDED.d: Past tense of CURD: The part of milk that coagulates when it sours or is treated with enzymes; used to make cottage cheese, dahi, etc.
CURDED.e: From Middle English curd, a metathetic variant of crud, crudde (“coagulated substance”). Doublet of crud.

CURDLE.d: To form curds so that it no longer flows smoothly; to cause to form such curds. (usually said of milk)
CURDLE.e: Metathesis of earlier dialectal cruddle, crudle, equivalent to curd + -le (frequentative suffix).

CURFEW.d: Any regulation requiring people to be off the streets and in their homes by a certain time.
CURFEW.e: From Middle English curfu, from Old French cuevre-fu (French couvre-feu), from the imperative of covrir (“to cover”) + fu (“fire”). Compare kerchief.

CURING.d: Present participle of CURE: A method, device or medication that restores good health.
CURING.e: From Middle English cure, borrowed from Old French cure (“care, cure, healing, cure of souls”), from Latin cura (“care, medical attendance, cure”). Displaced native Old English hǣlu, but survived as heal.

CURIUM.d: A highly fissile transuranic chemical element (symbol Cm) with an atomic number of 96.
CURIUM.e: From Curie + -ium; named after Pierre and Marie Curie.

CURLED.d: Past tense of CURL: A curving piece or lock of hair; a ringlet.
CURLED.e: From metathesis of Middle English crulle (“curled, curly”), of uncertain origin but probably from an unrecorded Old English word or from Middle Dutch crul, crulle (“curl”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *kruzlǭ (“bent or crooked object, curl”), connected to *krūsą (“curl”), of u...

CURLEW.d: Any of several migratory wading birds in the genus Numenius, remarkable for their long, slender, downcurved bills.
CURLEW.e: From Middle English curlew, from Old French courlieu (see French courlis), claimed to be imitative of the bird's cry but apparently assimilated with dialectal *corliu (“runner, messenger”), a variant of coureur (the bird is adept at running).

CURRED.d: Past tense of CUR: A contemptible or inferior dog.
CURRED.e: From Middle English curre (“watchdog, small hunting dog, mongrel, mutt”), perhaps of Middle Low German or North Germanic origin. Compare Middle Dutch corre (“domestic dog, yard dog, watch-dog”), dialectal Dutch korre (“dog, yard dog”), dialectal Swedish kurre (“a dog”). Compare a...

CURSED.d: Under some divine harm, malady, or other curse.
CURSED.e: From Middle English cursed, cursd, curst, corsed, curset, cursyd, equivalent to curse + -ed.

CURSES.d: Plural of CURS: plural of cur

CURSOR.d: A part of any of several scientific or measuring instruments that moves back and forth to indicate a position.
CURSOR.e: Borrowed from Latin cursor (“runner”), from currō (“run”) + -or (agentive suffix). Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European.

CURTED.d: Past tense of CURT: Brief or terse, especially to the point of being rude.
CURTED.e: From the Latin curtus (“shortened”). Cognate with Dutch kort, German kurz, Galician curto, French court, Italian corto, Portuguese curto, and Spanish corto. Doublet of short.

CURVET.d: Of a horse or, by extension, another animal: to leap about, to frolic.
CURVET.e: From Italian corvetta, diminutive of corva, an early form of curva (“curve”), from Latin curva, feminine of curvus (“bent, curved”).

CUSCUS.d: Any arboreal marsupial of genera Ailurops, Phalanger, Spilocuscus, and Strigocuscus, all in the family Phalangeridae, native to Australia.
CUSCUS.e: From New Latin Cuscus, former genus name, ultimately (probably via French and Dutch koeskoes) from a local word for the marsupials in a language of the Moluccas.

CUSHAT.d: A pigeon, wood pigeon or ring dove.
CUSHAT.e: From Middle English cowshott, cowschote, quyshte, from Old English cūsċeote (literally “cow shoot”), although it is difficult to understand why such a name would be given to these birds. Doublet of quist.

CUSPED.d: Past tense of CUSP: A sharp point or pointed end.
CUSPED.e: From Latin cuspis (“a point, spear, pointed end”); first used in astrology. Doublet of cuspid and cuspis.

CUSPID.d: A tooth with a single cusp; a canine tooth.
CUSPID.e: From Latin cuspid-, stem of cuspis (“point, apex”). Doublet of cusp and cuspis.

CUSSED.d: simple past and past participle of cuss

CUSSES.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of cuss

CUSTOM.d: Frequent repetition of the same behavior; way of behavior common to many; ordinary manner; habitual practice; method of doing, living or behaving.
CUSTOM.e:
PIE word
 *ḱóm
 PIE word
 *swé
From Middle English custume, borrowed from Anglo-Norman custume, inherited from Latin consuētūdinem, a noun derived from cōnsuēscō, from con- (“with”) + suēscō (“become used or accustomed to”). Doublet of costume and consuetude.
The adjectival form ...

CUTESY.d: Overly, affectedly or unnecessarily cute; too cute to be taken seriously.

CUTLER.d: One whose business is making or dealing in cutlery.
CUTLER.e: From Middle English coteler (“knife-maker”), from Anglo-Norman cuteler, from Old French coutelier (“knife-maker”).

CUTLET.d: A thin slice of meat, usually fried.
CUTLET.e: From French côtelette (recorded in English since 1706), from Middle French costelette (“little rib”), from coste + -elette, from Old French coste (“rib, side”), from Latin costa. Influenced by English cut, as if from cut + -let. Doublet of kotlet and kotleta.

CUTTED.d: Past tense of CUT: To incise, to cut into the surface of something.
CUTTED.e: From Middle English cutten, kitten, kytten, ketten (“to cut”) (compare Scots kut, kit (“to cut”)), of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse *kytja, *kutta, from Proto-Germanic *kutjaną, *kuttaną (“to cut”), of uncertain origin, perhaps related to Proto-Germanic *kwetwą (“meat, fl...

CUTTER.d: Comparative form of CUT: To incise, to cut into the surface of something.
CUTTER.e: From Middle English cutten, kitten, kytten, ketten (“to cut”) (compare Scots kut, kit (“to cut”)), of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse *kytja, *kutta, from Proto-Germanic *kutjaną, *kuttaną (“to cut”), of uncertain origin, perhaps related to Proto-Germanic *kwetwą (“meat, fl...

CUTTLE.e: From Middle English cutil, codel, codul, from Old English cudele (“cuttlefish”), a diminutive from Proto-Germanic *kudilǭ, from Proto-Germanic *kuddô + -ilǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *gewt- (“pouch, sack”), from *gew- (“to bend, bow, arch, vault, curve”). Equivalent to cod + -le ...

CYBORG.d: A being which is part machine and part organic.
CYBORG.e: Blend of cybernetic + organism. Coined by Austrian neuroscientist Manfred Clynes in 1960.

CYBRID.d: An artificial hybrid cell produced by introducing nuclear material from one organism into a cell (of the same or different species) from which the nucleus has been removed

CYCLIN.d: Any of a group of proteins whose presence in a cell varies through its cycle, and that regulates this cycle by forming a complex with kinase

CYGNET.e: From Middle English cignet, signet, from Anglo-Norman cignet, diminutive of Old French cigne (“swan”), from Latin cygnus, cycnus (“swan”), from Ancient Greek κύκνος (kúknos, “swan”).

CYMBAL.d: A concave plate of metal, usually brass or bronze, that produces a sharp, ringing sound when struck: played either in pairs, by striking them together, or singly by striking with a drumstick or the like.
CYMBAL.e: From Middle English cymbal, from Old English cimbal, cimbala and Old French cimbale, both from Latin cymbalum (“cymbal”), from Ancient Greek κύμβαλον (kúmbalon), from κύμβη (kúmbē, “bowl”). See also chime.

CYMOSE.d: having a cyme, a usually flat-topped flower cluster in which the main and branch stems each end in a flower that opens before those below it or to its side.
CYMOSE.e: From the Latin cȳmōsus, from cȳma, whence the English cyma.

CYSTED.d: Past tense of CYST: A pouch or sac without opening, usually membranous and containing morbid matter, which develops in one of the natural cavities or in the substance of an organ.
CYSTED.e: From Late Latin cystis, from Ancient Greek κύστις (kústis, “anatomical sac”).

DABBED.d: Past tense of DAB: To press lightly in a repetitive motion with a soft object without rubbing.
DABBED.e: From Middle English dabben (“to strike”), probably of North Germanic origin, related to Old Icelandic dabba (“to tap, slap”), perhaps ultimately imitative. Compare also with Middle Dutch dabben (“to pinch, knead, fumble, dabble”) (Dutch dabben (“(of a horse) to stamp with the for...

DABBER.d: Comparative form of DAB: To press lightly in a repetitive motion with a soft object without rubbing.
DABBER.e: From Middle English dabben (“to strike”), probably of North Germanic origin, related to Old Icelandic dabba (“to tap, slap”), perhaps ultimately imitative. Compare also with Middle Dutch dabben (“to pinch, knead, fumble, dabble”) (Dutch dabben (“(of a horse) to stamp with the for...

DABBLE.d: To make slightly wet or soiled by spattering or sprinkling a liquid (such as water, mud, or paint) on it; to bedabble.
DABBLE.e: From earlier dable, equivalent to dab + -le (frequentative suffix), possibly from Middle Dutch dabbelen (“to pinch; knead; to fumble; to dabble”); cognate with Icelandic dafla (“to dabble”).

DACITE.d: An igneous, volcanic rock with a high iron content.
DACITE.e: From German Dazit, from Latin Dācia (“greater Romania”). First used in 1863 by Austrian geologists Franz von Hauer and Guido Stache, in a description of the geology of Transylvania.

DACOIT.d: A bandit or armed robber, especially in former parts of British India.
DACOIT.e: Borrowed from Hindustani ڈکیت / डकैत (ḍakait), from ڈاکا (ḍākā) / डाका (ḍākā, “gang-robbery”).

DACTYL.d: A metrical foot of three syllables (— ⏑ ⏑), one long followed by two short, or one accented followed by two unaccented.
DACTYL.e: Learned borrowing from Latin dactylus, from Ancient Greek δάκτυλος (dáktulos, “finger”), three bones of the finger corresponding to three syllables. Doublet of dactylus and date.

DADDER.d: Comparative form of DAD: A father, a male parent.
DADDER.e:
From Early Modern English dadd, dadde (circa 1500), undoubtedly older, from unrecorded Middle English *dadde, of uncertain ultimate origin. Compare West Frisian deite (“dad, daddy”).
* Perhaps of Celtic origin, compare Welsh and Breton tad (from Proto-Brythonic *tad), Old Irish d...

DADOED.d: Past tense of DADO: The section of a pedestal above the base.
DADOED.e: From Italian dado, first attested in 1664.

DAEMON.e: A borrowing of Latin daemōn (“tutelary deity”), from Ancient Greek δαίμων (daímōn, “dispenser, tutelary deity”).

DAFFED.d: Past tense of DAFF: A fool; an idiot; a blockhead.
DAFFED.e: From Middle English daf, daffe (“fool, idiot”), from Old Norse daufr (“deaf, stupid”), from Proto-Germanic *daubaz (“deaf, stunned”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, whirl, smoke, be obscure”). Doublet of deaf, dof, and dowf. Cognate with Swedish döv (“deaf”), Danis...

DAGGER.d: A stabbing weapon, similar to a sword but with a short, double-edged blade.
DAGGER.e: From Middle English daggere, daggare, dagard, probably adapted from Old French dague (1229), related to Occitan, Italian, Spanish daga, Dutch dagge, German Degen, Middle Low German dagge (“knife's point”), Old Norse daggarðr, Danish daggert, Faroese daggari, Welsh dager, dagr, Br...

DAHLIA.d: Any plant of the genus Dahlia, tuberous perennial flowering plants native to Mexico.
DAHLIA.e: Named 1791 after Anders Dahl, by Spanish botanist Antonio José Cavanilles.

DAINTY.e: From Middle English deynte (as noun), from Old French deintié, from Latin dignitātem. Doublet of dignity.

DAISED.d: Past tense of DAIS: A raised platform in a room for a high table, a seat of honour, a throne, or other dignified occupancy, such as ancestral statues; a similar platform supporting a lectern, pulpit, etc., which may be used to speak from.
DAISED.e: From Middle English deis, from Anglo-Norman deis, from Old French deis, dois (modern French dais), from Latin discum, accusative singular of discus (“discus, disc, quoit; dish”) (Late Latin discum (“table”)), from Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “discus, disc; tray”), from δικεῖν (...

DAISES.d: Plural of DAIS: A raised platform in a room for a high table, a seat of honour, a throne, or other dignified occupancy, such as ancestral statues; a similar platform supporting a lectern, pulpit, etc., which may be used to speak from.
DAISES.e: From Middle English deis, from Anglo-Norman deis, from Old French deis, dois (modern French dais), from Latin discum, accusative singular of discus (“discus, disc, quoit; dish”) (Late Latin discum (“table”)), from Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “discus, disc; tray”), from δικεῖν (...

DAMAGE.d: Injury or harm; the condition or measure of something not being intact.
DAMAGE.e: From Middle English damage, from Old French damage, from Vulgar Latin *damnāticum from Classical Latin damnum. Compare modern French dommage. Largely displaced native Middle English scath (whence unscathed).

DAMASK.d: An ornate silk fabric originating from Damascus.
DAMASK.e: From Middle English damaske, from Medieval Latin damascus, named after the city Damascus, where the fabric was originally made.

DAMMED.d: Past tense of DAM: A structure placed across a flowing body of water to stop the flow or part of the flow, generally for purposes such as retaining or diverting some of the water or retarding the release of accumulated water to avoid abrupt flooding.
DAMMED.e: From Middle English dam, from Old English *damm, from Proto-West Germanic *damm, from Proto-Germanic *dammaz.

DAMMER.d: Comparative form of DAM: A structure placed across a flowing body of water to stop the flow or part of the flow, generally for purposes such as retaining or diverting some of the water or retarding the release of accumulated water to avoid abrupt flooding.
DAMMER.e: From Middle English dam, from Old English *damm, from Proto-West Germanic *damm, from Proto-Germanic *dammaz.

DAMMIT.d: Expressing anger, irritation, contempt, or disappointment.

DAMNED.d: Past tense of DAMN: To condemn.
DAMNED.e: From Middle English dampnen, from Old French damner, from Latin damnāre (“to condemn, inflict loss upon”), from damnum (“loss”).

DAMPED.d: Past tense of DAMP: In a state between dry and wet; moderately wet; moist.
DAMPED.e: From Middle English dampen (“to stifle; suffocate”). Akin to Low German damp, Dutch damp, and German Dampf (“vapor, steam, fog”), Icelandic dampi, Swedish damm (“dust”), and to German dampf imperative of dimpfen (“to smoke”). Also Middle English dampen (“to extinguish, choke, suf...

DAMPEN.d: To make damp or moist; to make moderately wet.

DAMSEL.e: From Middle English dameisele, from Old French damoisele, from Vulgar Latin *domnicella, a diminutive from Classical Latin domina (“mistress, lady”), from dominus, from *demh₂-. Doublet of demoiselle, doncella, and donzella.

DAMSON.d: A subspecies of plum tree, Prunus domestica subsp. insititia, native to Eurasia.
DAMSON.e: From Middle English damascene, damasyn, damacene, from Latin prūnum damascēnum (“Damascene plum, plum of Damascus”). Doublet of damascene.

DANCED.d: Past tense of DANCE: To move rhythmically to music.

DANCES.d: Plural of DANCE: To move rhythmically to music.

DANDER.d: Dandruff—scaly white dead skin flakes from the human scalp.

DANDLE.d: To move up and down on one's knee or in one's arms, in affectionate play, usually said of a child.
DANDLE.e: Compare Scots dandill (“to dander; go about idly; move uncertainly; trifle”), English dialectal dander (“to wander about; talk incoherently; rave”), Middle Dutch dantinnen (“to trifle”) (from French dandiner (“to swing; waddle”)), German dändeln, tändeln (“to trifle, dandle”), Mi...

DANGER.e: From Middle English daunger (“power, dominion, peril”), from Anglo-Norman dangier, from Old French dangier, alteration of Old French dongier (due to association with Latin damnum (“damage”)) from Vulgar Latin *dominārium (“authority, power”) from Latin dominus (“lord, master”). D...

DANGLE.d: To hang loosely with the ability to swing.
DANGLE.e: Uncertain, but likely of North Germanic origin, akin to Danish dingle, dangle, Swedish dangla (“to swing about”), Norwegian dangla, perhaps via North Frisian dangeln; all possibly related to Old Norse dengja (“to hit”).

DANNER.d: Comparative form of DAN: A title of honour or respect similar to "master" or "Sir", used of historical and legendary figures of the past.
DANNER.e: From Middle English dan, daun, dam (“lord”), from Anglo-Norman daun, daunz and Old French dan, dam, from Latin dominus. Doublet of don.

DAPHNE.d: A dryad pursued by Apollo, who was turned into a laurel tree by the river god Peneus.

DAPPED.d: Past tense of DAP: A plimsoll.
DAPPED.e: Onomatopoeic, from the sound made when a person runs while wearing daps.

DAPPER.e: From Middle English daper (“pretty, neat”), from Middle Dutch dapper (“stalwart, nimble”), Old Dutch *dapar, from Proto-Germanic *dapraz (“stout; solid; heavy; bold”) (compare German tapfer "bold", Norwegian daper "saddened, dreary"), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeb- ‘thick, heavy...

DAPPLE.d: A mottled marking, usually in clusters.
DAPPLE.e:
Uncertain. The adjective is first attested circa 1550 though the first element is already attested in dapple-grey as early as 1386, in Middle English, and later as dappled circa 1400; the OED suggests either:
* a back-formation from dapple-grey, itself a variant of apple-grey, co...

DARING.d: present participle and gerund of dare

DARKED.d: Past tense of DARK: Having an absolute or (more often) relative lack of light.
DARKED.e: From Middle English derk, from Old English deorc, from Proto-West Germanic *derk (“dark”), of uncertain origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerg- (“dim, dull”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰer- (“dull, dirty”).

DARKEN.d: To make dark or darker by reducing light.
DARKEN.e:
From Middle English derkenen, dirkenen, from Old English *deorcnian, *diercnian (“to darken”), from Proto-West Germanic *dirkinōn (“to darken”), equivalent to dark + -en.
Cognate with Scots derken, durken (“to darken”), Old High German tarchanjan, terchinen (“to darken”), Middle ...

DARKLY.d: With insufficient light for easy discernment or comprehension.
DARKLY.e: From Middle English derkly, derkely, derkliche, derkeliche; equivalent to dark + -ly. Compare Old English deorclīċe, a parallel formation.

DARNEL.d: Any of genus Lolium of grasses, especially as a weed in wheat fields.
DARNEL.e:
From Middle English darnel, dernel, from Old Northern French darnelle ( > dialectal French dernelle, darnette), of Germanic origin, possibly Proto-West Germanic *darjan (“to harm, injure”).
Related to Walloon darne, derne (“stunned, dazed, drunk”), Middle Dutch verdarnt, verdaern...

DARTED.d: Past tense of DART: A pointed missile weapon, intended to be thrown by the hand; for example, a short lance or javelin.
DARTED.e:
From Middle English dart, from Old French dart, dard (“dart”), from Medieval Latin dardus, from Frankish *darōþu (“dart, spear”), from Proto-Germanic *darōþuz (“dart, spear”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerh₃- (“to leap, spring”).
Compare Old High German tart (“javelin, dart”), O...

DASHED.d: Past tense of DASH: Any of the following symbols: ‒ (figure dash), – (en dash), — (em dash), or ― (horizontal bar).
DASHED.e: From Middle English daschen, dassen, from Danish daske (“to slap, strike”), related to Swedish daska (“to smack, slap, spank”), of obscure origin. Compare German tatschen (“to grope, paw”), Old English dwǣsċan (“to quell, put out, destroy, extinguish”). See also dush.

DASHES.d: Plural of DASH: Any of the following symbols: ‒ (figure dash), – (en dash), — (em dash), or ― (horizontal bar).
DASHES.e: From Middle English daschen, dassen, from Danish daske (“to slap, strike”), related to Swedish daska (“to smack, slap, spank”), of obscure origin. Compare German tatschen (“to grope, paw”), Old English dwǣsċan (“to quell, put out, destroy, extinguish”). See also dush.

DASSIE.d: A small, herbivorous mammal in the order Hyracoidea, the rock hyrax.
DASSIE.e: Borrowed from Afrikaans dassie, from Dutch das (“badger”).

DATARY.d: an officer in the Roman Catholic Church who dispensed benefices

DATING.d: Present participle of DATE: The fruit of the date palm, Phoenix dactylifera, somewhat in the shape of an olive, containing a soft, sweet pulp and enclosing a hard kernel.
DATING.e: From Middle English date, from Old French date, datil, datille, from Latin dactylus (likely via Old Provençal datil), from Ancient Greek δάκτυλος (dáktulos, “finger”) (from the resemblance of the date to a human finger), probably a folk-etymological alteration of a word from a Se...

DATIVE.d: Denoting the case of a noun which expresses the remoter or indirect object, generally indicated in English by to or for with the objective.
DATIVE.e: From Latin datīvus (“appropriate for giving”), itself from datus (the past participle of dō (“I give”)) + -īvus (“-ive”).

DATURA.d: A plant of the genus Datura, known for its trumpet-shaped flowers and poisonous properties.

DAWDLE.d: Chiefly followed by away: to spend (time) without haste or purpose.
DAWDLE.e:
The verb is possibly:
* a variant of daddle (“(Britain, dialectal) to walk or work slowly, dawdle, saunter, trifle”) or doddle (“(Britain, dialectal) to walk feebly or slowly, dawdle, idle, saunter, stroll”), possibly influenced by daw (“(Britain, dialectal) lazy, good-for-nothin...

DAWNED.d: Past tense of DAWN: To begin to brighten with daylight.
DAWNED.e: From Middle English dawnen, either a back-formation from dawnynge or a modification of dawen (“to dawn”) after it. The noun is from the verb.

DAYBED.d: A couch that can be used as a sofa by day and a bed by night.

DAYING.d: Present participle of DAY: The time when the Sun is above the horizon and it lights the sky.
DAYING.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *dʰegʷʰ-?
Proto-Germanic *dagaz
Proto-West Germanic *dag
Old English dæġ
Middle English day
English day
Inherited from Middle English day, from Old English dæġ, from Proto-West Germanic *dag, from Proto-Germanic *dagaz.
Latin diēs, Russian день ...

DAZING.d: Present participle of DAZE: The state of being dazed
DAZING.e:
From Middle English, back-formation from dazed.
Compare Old Norse dasask (“to become weary”), with reflexive suffix -sk, Swedish dasa (“lie idly”), and Icelandic dasask (“to make weary with cold”). Also compare Proto-Germanic *dusāną, to slumber.
Alternatively from Middle Dutch d...

DAZZLE.d: To confuse or overpower the sight of (someone or something, such as a sensor) by means of excessive brightness.

DEACON.d: A designated minister of charity in the early Church (see Acts 6:1-6).
DEACON.e: Inherited from Middle English deken, dekne, from Old English diacon, from Ecclesiastical Latin diāconus, from Ancient Greek διᾱ́κονος (diā́konos, “servant, minister”).

DEADEN.d: To render less lively; to diminish; to muffle.
DEADEN.e: From dead + -en. Compare Dutch doden (“to kill”), West Frisian deadzje (“to kill”).

DEADLY.e: From Middle English dedly, dedlych, dedlich, from Old English dēadlīċ (adjective), from Proto-West Germanic *dauþalīk, from Proto-Germanic *dauþalīkaz (“deadly”, literally “deathly”). By surface analysis, dead + -ly. Cognate with Saterland Frisian dodelk (“deadly”), West Frisian ...

DEAFEN.d: To make deaf, either temporarily or permanently.
DEAFEN.e: From deaf + -en (verbal suffix), compare Middle English deven, deaven (“to make deaf”), Old English ādēafian (“to deafen”), Dutch verdoven (“to stupefy, deafen”), German betäuben (“to stun, stupefy, deafen”).

DEANED.d: Past tense of DEAN: A senior official in a college or university, who may be in charge of a division or faculty (for example, the dean of science) or have some other advisory or disciplinary function (for example, the dean of students).
DEANED.e: From Middle English den, deen (“dean”), from Anglo-Norman deen and continental Old French deien (modern French doyen), from Latin decānus. Doublet of doyen.

DEARIE.d: A person who is dear; sweetie.

DEARTH.d: A period or condition when food is rare and hence expensive; famine.
DEARTH.e: First attested at least as early as the late 1300s, and appearing in Tyndale’s Pentateuch (1530) as well as the Coverdale Bible (1535). From Middle English derth, derthe, derþe, probably from Old English *dīerþ, *dīerþu, from Proto-West Germanic *diuriþu, from Proto-Germanic *diu...

DEATHS.d: Plural of DEATH: The end of life.

DEAVES.d: Plural of DEAF: Unable (or partially able) to hear.
DEAVES.e: From Middle English def, deef, from Old English dēaf, from Proto-West Germanic *daub, from Proto-Germanic *daubaz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, smoke, darken, obscure”). Cognate with Ancient Greek τυφλός (tuphlós, “blind”). See also dumb. Doublet of daff, dof, an...

DEBARK.d: To unload goods from an aircraft or ship.
DEBARK.e: From French débarquer, from de- (Old French des-) + barque (“bark, small ship”).

DEBASE.d: To lower in character, quality, or value; to degrade.
DEBASE.e: From de- + base, from Old French bas, from Latin bassus. Cognate with Spanish debajo (“under, beneath, below”). Compare abase.

DEBATE.d: To participate in a debate; to dispute, argue, especially in a public arena.
DEBATE.e: From Middle English debaten, from Old French debatre (“to fight, contend, debate, also literally to beat down”), from Romanic desbattere, from Latin dis- (“apart, in different directions”) + battuō (“to beat, to fence”).

DEBEAK.d: To remove part of the beak of a chicken or other bird to prevent pecking in chicken farms.

DEBRIS.d: Rubble, wreckage, scattered remains of something destroyed.
DEBRIS.e: Borrowed from French débris, itself from dé- (“de-”) + bris (“broken, crumbled”), or from Middle French debriser (“to break apart”), from Old French debrisier, itself from de- + brisier (“to break apart, shatter, bust”), from Frankish *bristijan, *bristan, *brestan (“to break vio...

DEBTED.d: Past tense of DEBT: An action, state of mind, or object one has an obligation to perform for another, adopt toward another, or give to another.
DEBTED.e: From Middle English dette, dett, borrowed from Old French dete (French dette), from Medieval Latin dēbita, from Latin dēbitum (“what is owed, a debt, a duty”), neuter of dēbitus, perfect passive participle of dēbeō (“I owe”), contraction of *dehibeō (“I have from”), from de (“fro...

DEBTOR.d: A person or firm that owes money; one in debt; one who owes a debt.
DEBTOR.e: From Middle English dettour, from Old French detour, from Latin debitor, equivalent to debt + -or. Doublet of debitor. Displaced native Old English *sċola.

DECADE.d: A group, set, or series of ten , particularly
DECADE.e: From Middle English decade, from Old French decade, from Late Latin decādem (“(set of) ten”), from Ancient Greek δεκάς (dekás), from δέκα (déka, “ten”). In reference to a span of ten years, originally a clipping of the phrase decade of years. By surface analysis, deca- + -ade. Do...

DECAMP.d: To break up camp and move on.

DECEIT.d: An act or practice intended to deceive; a trick.
DECEIT.e: From Middle English deceyte, from Old French deceite, deçoite, from decevoir (“to deceive”), from Latin dēcipere (“to cheat, mislead”).

DECENT.e: Borrowed from Middle French décent, or its source, Latin decēns, present participle of decet (“it is fitting or suitable”), from Proto-Indo-European *deḱ- (“to take, accept, to receive, greet, be suitable”) (compare Ancient Greek δοκέω (dokéō, “I appear, seem, think”), δέχομαι (d...

DECIDE.d: To resolve (a contest, problem, dispute, etc.); to choose, determine, or settle.
DECIDE.e: From Middle English deciden, from Old French decider, from Latin dēcīdere, infinitive of dēcīdō (“cut off, decide”), from dē (“down from”) + caedō (“cut”).

DECILE.d: Any of the values in a series that divides the distribution of individuals in that series into ten groups of equal frequency.

DECKLE.d: A frame or edge which limits the pulp and, consequently, the size of the resulting paper.
DECKLE.e: From German Deckel, diminutive of Decke (“covering”).

DECLAW.d: To surgically remove the claws of (an animal); to perform onychectomy on.

DECOCT.e: From Latin decoquō (“I boil down”), from de- + coquō (“I cook”).

DECODE.d: To convert from an encrypted form to plain text.

DECREE.e: From Middle English decre, decree, from Old French decré (French décret), from Latin dēcrētum.

DEDUCE.d: To reach (a conclusion) by applying rules of logic or other forms of reasoning to given premises or known facts.
DEDUCE.e: From Late Middle English deducen (“to demonstrate, prove, show; to argue, infer; to bring, lead; to turn (something) to a use; to deduct”), borrowed from Latin dēdūcere, the present active infinitive of dēdūcō (“to lead or bring out or away; to accompany, conduct, escort; (figura...

DEDUCT.d: To take one thing from another; remove from; make smaller or less by some amount.
DEDUCT.e: Borrowed from Latin deductus, perfect passive participle of verb deducere (“lead from”).

DEEDED.d: Past tense of DEED: An action or act; something that is done.
DEEDED.e:
From Middle English dede, from Old English dēd, dǣd (“deed, act”), from Proto-West Germanic *dādi, from Proto-Germanic *dēdiz (“deed”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰéh₁tis (“deed, action”). Analyzable through Proto-Germanic as do + -th. Doublet of thesis.
The real estate sense der...

DEEJAY.e: Pronunciation spelling of the abbreviation DJ.

DEEMED.d: Past tense of DEEM: To judge, to pass judgment on; to doom, to sentence.
DEEMED.e: From Middle English dēmen (“to judge; to criticize, condemn; to impose a penalty on, sentence; to direct, order; to believe, think, deem”), from Old English dēman (“to decide, decree, deem”), from Proto-West Germanic *dōmijan, from Proto-Germanic *dōmijaną (“to judge, think”), fr...
