DEFACE.d: To damage or vandalize something, especially a surface, in a visible or conspicuous manner.
DEFACE.e: From Middle English defacen, from Old French defacier, desfacier (“to mutilate, destroy, disfigure”), from des- (“away from”) (see dis-) + Late Latin facia.

DEFAME.d: To disgrace; to bring into disrepute.
DEFAME.e: From Middle English defamen, from Anglo-Norman defamer (verb), defame (noun), and its source, Latin diffāmō, from fāma (“fame; rumour; reputation”).

DEFEAT.d: To overcome in battle or contest.
DEFEAT.e: From Middle English defeten, from Middle English defet (“disfigured”, past participle) and defet (“defect”, noun), see Etymology 2 below.

DEFECT.e: Borrowed from Latin defectus (“a failure, lack”), from deficere (“to fail, lack, literally 'undo'”), from past participle defectus, from de- (“of, from”) + facere (“to do”).

DEFEND.d: To ward off attacks against; to fight to protect; to guard.
DEFEND.e: From Middle English defenden, from Old French defendre, deffendre (Modern French défendre), from Latin dēfendō (“to ward off”), from Proto-Italic *fendō, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰen-. Displaced native Old English bewerian.

DEFIED.d: Past tense of DEFY: To challenge (someone) or brave (a hazard or opposition).
DEFIED.e: From Old French desfier, from Vulgar Latin *disfidare (“renounce one's faith”), from Latin dis- (“away”) + fidus (“faithful”). Meaning shifted in the 14th century from "be disloyal" to "challenge". Contrast confide, fidelity, faith.

DEFIER.d: Comparative form of DEFY: To challenge (someone) or brave (a hazard or opposition).
DEFIER.e: From Old French desfier, from Vulgar Latin *disfidare (“renounce one's faith”), from Latin dis- (“away”) + fidus (“faithful”). Meaning shifted in the 14th century from "be disloyal" to "challenge". Contrast confide, fidelity, faith.

DEFIES.d: Plural of DEFY: To challenge (someone) or brave (a hazard or opposition).
DEFIES.e: From Old French desfier, from Vulgar Latin *disfidare (“renounce one's faith”), from Latin dis- (“away”) + fidus (“faithful”). Meaning shifted in the 14th century from "be disloyal" to "challenge". Contrast confide, fidelity, faith.

DEFILE.d: To make (someone or something) physically dirty or unclean; to befoul, to soil.
DEFILE.e: From Late Middle English defilen (“to make dirty, befoul; rape; abuse; destroy; injure; oppress”) [and other forms], a variant of defoulen (“to make dirty, defile, pollute; have sexual intercourse with; rape; etc.”) (compare also defoilen). Defoulen is a blend of Middle English f...

DEFINE.d: To determine with precision; to mark out with distinctness; to ascertain or exhibit clearly.
DEFINE.e: From Middle English definen, from Old French definer, variant of definir, from Latin dēfīniō (“limit, settle, define”), from dē + fīniō (“set a limit, bound, end”).

DEFORM.d: Having an unusual and unattractive shape; deformed, misshapen; hence, hideous, ugly.
DEFORM.e:
PIE word
 *de
From Middle English deforme (“out of shape, deformed”) [and other forms], from Middle French deforme (modern French difforme (“misshapen, deformed”)), or directly from its etymon Latin dēfōrmis (“departing physically from the correct shape, deformed, malformed, miss...

DEGGED.d: Past tense of DEG: Abbreviation of degree.

DEGGER.d: Comparative form of DEG: Abbreviation of degree.

DEGREE.d: A stage of proficiency or qualification in a course of study, now especially an award bestowed by a university/college, as a certification of academic achievement. (In the United States, can include secondary schools.)
DEGREE.e: From Middle English degre, borrowed from Old French degré (French: degré), itself from Latin gradus, with the prefix de-.

DEHUSK.d: To remove the husk from (a coconut or cereal grain).

DEJECT.e: From Old French dejeter, from Latin deicere (“to throw down”).

DEKING.d: Present participle of DEKE: A feint, fake, or other move made by the player with the puck to deceive a goaltender or defenceman.
DEKING.e: Canadian English, a contraction of decoy.

DELATE.e: From Latin delātus, perfect passive participle of deferō, see -ate (verb-forming suffix). Doublet of defer (Etymology 2). See also infer, collate and confer, relate and refer, as well as prelate and prefer among others.

DELETE.d: To remove, get rid of or erase, especially written or printed material, or data on a computer or other device.
DELETE.e: From Latin dēlētus, past participle of dēlēre (“destroy, blot out, efface”), from dēlēvī, originally perf. tense of dēlinere (“to daub, erase by smudging”), from dē- (“from, away”) + linere (“to smear, wipe”). Original sense first appears c. 1495. In common use for ordering the a...

DELICT.d: A wrongful act, analogous to a tort in common law.
DELICT.e: Borrowed from Latin dēlīctum (“fault”), neuter of dēlīctus, past participle of delinquo (“to fail; to be lacking”), from dē- + linquō (“to leave, quit, forsake, depart from”).

DELINK.d: To unlink, or remove a link from.

DELUDE.d: To deceive into believing something which is false; to lead into error; to dupe.
DELUDE.e: From Middle English deluden, borrowed from Latin dēlūdō (“mock, deceive”), from de + lūdō (“to make sport of, to mock”). See ludicrous.

DELUGE.e: From Middle English deluge, from Old French deluge, alteration of earlier deluvie, from Latin dīluvium, from dīluō (“wash away”). Doublet of diluvium.

DEMAND.d: The desire to purchase goods and services.
DEMAND.e: From late Middle English demaunden, from Old French demander, from Latin dēmandō, dēmandāre.

DEMEAN.d: To debase; to lower; to degrade.
DEMEAN.e: (1595) From de- + mean (“lowly, base, common”), from Middle English mene, aphetic variation of imene (“mean, base, common”), from Old English ġemǣne (“mean, common”). Compare English bemean.

DEMENT.e: Borrowed from Middle French dément, from Latin demens.

DEMINE.d: To remove explosive mines (landmines or naval mines) from.

DEMISE.d: The conveyance or transfer of an estate, either in fee for life or for years, most commonly the latter.
DEMISE.e: From Middle English demyse, dimise, dimisse, dymyse, from Middle French démise, the feminine singular past participle of démettre (“to put down, relinquish”); from Latin dēmissa, feminine singular of perfect passive participle of dēmittō. The "death" and "end" senses derive by wa...

DEMIST.d: To remove the layer of fine liquid particles from the surface of (a window or mirror).

DEMOTE.d: To lower the rank or status of.
DEMOTE.e: From de- (“down”) + promote (“advance in rank/status (ending abstracted)”).

DEMURE.e:
Inherited from Middle English demure, demwre, an abbreviation of Anglo-Norman de mure port (“with a mature demeanor”) (compare Old French meur from Latin mātūrus):
*si il seyt coy e de mure port (Amur curteiz) (“he sits quietly and with a mature appearance”)
* Documents illustrat...

DENARY.e: From Middle English denarie, from the Latin dēnārius, used elliptically for dēnārius nummus (“denary coin, coin containing ten asses”). Piecewise doublet of etymology 2 below. Doublet of dinar, denar, and denier.

DENGUE.d: An acute febrile disease of the (sub)tropics caused by the Dengue virus, a flavivirus, transmitted by Aedes mosquitoes, and characterized by high fever, rash, headache, and severe muscle and joint pain.
DENGUE.e: From West Indian Spanish dengue in 1828, from the Kiswahili term dinga (in full kidingapopo or kidinga pepo, "a kind of sudden cramp-like seizure caused by an evil spirit", dinga itself meaning sudden cramp-like seizure). The borrowed term changed to dengue in Spanish due to this...

DENIED.d: Past tense of DENY: To disallow or reject.
DENIED.e: From Middle English denyen, from Old French denoier (“to deny, to repudiate”) (French dénier), from Latin denegare (“to deny, to refuse”), from de- (“away”) and negare (“to refuse”), the latter ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *né (“no, not”). Doublet of denegate.

DENIER.d: Comparative form of DENY: To disallow or reject.
DENIER.e: From Middle English denyen, from Old French denoier (“to deny, to repudiate”) (French dénier), from Latin denegare (“to deny, to refuse”), from de- (“away”) and negare (“to refuse”), the latter ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *né (“no, not”). Doublet of denegate.

DENIES.d: Plural of DENY: To disallow or reject.
DENIES.e: From Middle English denyen, from Old French denoier (“to deny, to repudiate”) (French dénier), from Latin denegare (“to deny, to refuse”), from de- (“away”) and negare (“to refuse”), the latter ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *né (“no, not”). Doublet of denegate.

DENNED.d: Past tense of DEN: A small cavern or hollow place in the side of a hill, or among rocks; especially, a cave used by a wild animal for shelter or concealment.
DENNED.e: From Middle English den, from Old English denn (“den, lair (of a beast), cave; a swine-pasture, a woodland pasture for swine”), from Proto-West Germanic *dani (“threshing-floor, barn-floor”). Cognate with Scots den (“den, lair”), Middle Dutch denne (“burrow, den, cave, attic”), D...

DENSER.d: comparative form of dense: more dense

DENTAL.e: Borrowed from Middle French dental or Late Latin dentālis, from dēns (“a tooth”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix).

DENTED.d: Past tense of DENT: A shallow deformation in the surface of an object, produced by an impact.
DENTED.e: From Middle English dent, dente, dint (“a blow; strike; dent”), from Old English dynt (“blow, strike, the mark or noise of a blow”), from Proto-Germanic *duntiz (“a blow”). Akin to Old Norse dyntr (“dint”). Doublet of dint.

DENTIL.d: Any one of a series of small rectangular blocks projecting like teeth from a molding or beneath a cornice.
DENTIL.e: From French dentille, ultimately from Latin dente, ablative singular of dēns.

DENUDE.d: To divest of all covering; to make bare or naked; to strip.
DENUDE.e: From Middle French dénuder, from Latin dēnūdāre, from dē- + nūdus (“bare”).

DEPART.e: From Old French departir, from Late Latin departiō (“to divide”), from dē- (“away from”) + partiō (“part, divide”).

DEPEND.d: To be contingent or conditioned; to have something as a necessary condition
DEPEND.e: From Middle English dependen, from Old French dependre and Latin dependeō, from Latin dē- + pendeō (“to hang”). In this sense, displaced native Old English hangian (“to hang or depend”).

DEPICT.d: To render a representation of something, using words, sounds, images, or other means.
DEPICT.e: From Middle English depicten, from Latin dēpictus, from dēpingō.

DEPLOY.d: To prepare and arrange (originally military unit or units, i.e., to array troops) for use.
DEPLOY.e: Borrowed from French déployer (“to unroll, unfold”), from Old French desploiier, itself from des- + ploiier, or possibly from Late Latin displicāre (“to unfold, display”), from Latin dis- (“apart”) + plicare (“to fold”). Compare Middle English desployen, dysployen (“to unfold, di...

DEPORT.e: Borrowed from French déporter. With the meaning of "behave", from Old French deporter (“behave”), from Latin deportō, from de- + portō.

DEPTHS.d: Plural of DEPTH: The distance from top to bottom.

DEPUTE.d: To assign (someone or something) to or for something.
DEPUTE.e: From French députer, from Latin deputo.

DEPUTY.d: One appointed as the substitute of others, and empowered to act for them, in their name or their behalf; a substitute in office.
DEPUTY.e: From French député, from Late Latin deputatus (“appointed”).

DERAIL.d: Synonym of derailer: A device placed on railway tracks in order to cause a train to derail.
DERAIL.e: From French dérailler (“to go off the rails”). Analyzable as de- + rail.

DERIDE.d: To laugh at or mock (someone or something) harshly; to ridicule, to scorn.
DERIDE.e:
PIE word
 *de
Learned borrowing from Latin dērīdēre, the present active infinitive of dērīdeō (“to laugh at, make fun of, mock, deride”), from dē- (prefix denoting putting down or subjecting to indignity) + rīdeō (“to laugh; to laugh at, mock, ridicule”) (further etymology uncert...

DERIVE.d: To obtain or receive (something) from something else.
DERIVE.e: From Middle English deriven, from Old French deriver, from Latin dērīvō (“to lead, turn, or draw off (a liquid), draw off, derive”), from dē (“away”) + rīvus (“a stream”); see rival. Unrelated to arrive.

DERMIS.d: The tissue of the skin underlying the epidermis.
DERMIS.e: From New Latin dermis, from Ancient Greek δέρμα (dérma, “skin, hide”), from δέρω (dérō, “to skin, to flay”).

DESCRY.d: To announce a discovery: to disclose; to reveal.
DESCRY.e: From Middle English descrien, descriven in the 14th century already had the dual sense of "to proclaim, announce, make known" and "to see, discern, discover". On the one hand, the Middle English word is a loan Old French descrier (“to proclaim, announce, cry”), from des- + crier ...

DESEED.d: To remove seed or seeds from.

DESERT.d: A barren area of land or desolate terrain, especially one with little water or vegetation; a wasteland.
DESERT.e: From Middle English desert (“wilderness”), from Old French desert, from Latin dēsertum, past participle of dēserō (“to abandon”). Generally displaced native Old English wēsten.

DESIGN.d: A specification of an object or process, referring to requirements to be satisfied and thus conditions to be met for them to solve a problem.
DESIGN.e: From Middle English designen, from Old French designer, from Latin designō (“I mark out, point out, describe, design, contrive”), from de- (or dis-) + signō (“I mark”), from signum (“mark”). Doublet of designate.

DESIRE.d: To want; to wish for earnestly.
DESIRE.e: From Middle English desir, desire (noun) and desiren (verb), from Old French desirer, desirrer, from Latin dēsīderō (“to long for, desire, feel the want of, miss, regret”), apparently from de- + sidus (in the phrase de sidere, "from the stars") in connection with astrological hop...

DESIST.d: To cease to proceed or act; to stop (often with from).

DESMAN.d: Either of two species, Desmana moschata or Galemys pyrenaicus, of aquatic or semiaquatic insectivore of the mole family, Talpidae, found in Europe.
DESMAN.e: From French desman, German Desman, from Swedish desmanråtta (“muskrat”), from desman (“musk”, older also desma, desme), from Middle Low German dēsem, from Old Saxon desamo, alteration of *besamo (cf. Old High German bisamo), from Late Latin bisamum (“musk”), from Hebrew בושם (bāś...

DESORB.d: To remove (or be removed) from a surface onto which it was adsorbed or through which it was absorbed

DESPOT.d: A ruler with absolute power; a tyrant.
DESPOT.e: From Middle French despote, from Old French despote, from Medieval Latin despota, from Ancient Greek δεσπότης (despótēs, “lord, master, owner”). Cognate with Sanskrit दम्पति (dámpati).

DETACH.d: To take apart from; to take off.
DETACH.e: From Old French destachier, from the same root as attach; compare French détacher and Portuguese and Spanish destacar.

DETAIN.d: To keep someone from proceeding by holding them back or making claims on their attention.
DETAIN.e: From Old French detenir. Cognate with Italian detenere, Portuguese deter, Romanian deține, and Spanish detener.

DETECT.d: To discover or find by careful search, examination, or probing.
DETECT.e: From Latin detectus, perfect passive participle of detegere (“to uncover or disclose”), from de- + tegere (“to cover”); see tegument, tile, thatch.

DETENT.d: That which locks or unlocks a movement; a catch (stopping mechanism), pawl, or dog; especially, in clockwork, the catch which locks and unlocks the wheelwork in striking.
DETENT.e: From French détente, from Latin tendō (“to stretch”).

DETEST.d: To dislike (someone or something) intensely; to loathe.
DETEST.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Middle French detester (French détester), from Latin dētestor (“to imprecate evil while calling the gods to witness", "denounce", "hate intensely”), from dē- + testor (“to testify, bear witness”), from testis (“a witness”); see test, testify. Doublet of det...

DEVEIN.d: To remove the vein-like colon from (shrimp).

DEVICE.d: Any piece of equipment made for a particular purpose, especially a mechanical or electrical one.
DEVICE.e: From Middle English devis, devise, devyce, devys, devyse, from Old French devis and devise, from Latin dīvīsus, past participle of dīvidō (“to divide”). Doublet of devise (noun).

DEVISE.d: To use one’s intellect to plan or design (something).
DEVISE.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English devisen, devysen, from Old French deviser, from Vulgar Latin devisō, from Latin dīvisō, frequentative of dīvidō.

DEVKIT.d: A set of development tools that allow the creation of software for a particular platform or framework.

DEVOIR.d: Duty, business; something that one must do.
DEVOIR.e: From Middle English devoir, borrowed from Middle French devoir, from Old French deveir, from Latin dēbēre (“to owe; ought, must”).

DEVOTE.d: to give one's time, focus one's efforts, commit oneself, etc. entirely for, on, or to a certain matter; to consecrate.
DEVOTE.e: From Latin dēvōtus, past participle of Latin dēvoveō (“dedicate by a vow, sacrifice oneself, promise solemnly”). Doublet of devow; see also devout. Displaced native Middle English ēstful, from Old English ēstful.

DEVOUR.d: To eat quickly, greedily, hungrily, or ravenously.
DEVOUR.e: Inherited from Middle English devouren, from Old French devorer (Modern French dévorer), from Latin dēvorō, from vorō.

DEVOUT.d: Devoted to religion or to religious feelings and duties; pious; extremely religious; godly.
DEVOUT.e: From Middle English devout, devot, from Old French devot (French dévot), from Latin dēvōtus, perfect passive participle of dēvōveō. Doublet of devote.

DEWIER.d: Comparative form of DEWY: Covered by dew.
DEWIER.e: From Middle English dewy, deuhy, from Old English dēawiġ, from Proto-West Germanic *dauwag, *dauwīg, equivalent to dew + -y.

DEWING.d: Present participle of DEW: Any moisture from the atmosphere condensed by cool bodies upon their surfaces.
DEWING.e:
From Middle English dew, from Old English dēaw (“dew”), from Proto-West Germanic *dauw, from Proto-Germanic *dawwaz, *dawwą (“dew, moisture”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“smoke, haze”).
Cognate with German Tau, Dutch dauw and Afrikaans dou. Doublet of dag.

DEWLAP.d: The pendulous skin under the neck of an ox, or a similar feature on any other animal.
DEWLAP.e: From Middle English dewlappe. The first element may be dew (and if not, seems to have been altered by folk etymology to resemble it); the second element is lap (“loose fabric”), Old English læppa (“a loose hanging piece”); compare jellop and jowlop (from jowl + lap), and dewclaw....

DEXTER.d: Right; on the right-hand side. (In heraldry, specifically the bearer's right, which is the viewer's left.)

DHAMMA.e: Transliteration of Pali dhamma. Doublet of dharma and firm.

DHARMA.d: The natural order of the universe; natural law, cosmic order.
DHARMA.e: Learned borrowing from Sanskrit धर्म (dhárma, “that which upholds or supports”). The definitions pertaining to Buddhism are influenced by dhamma, a loan word from Pali. Doublet of dhamma and firm.

DIADEM.d: An ornamental headband worn as a badge of royalty.
DIADEM.e: From Middle English diademe, dyademe, from Old French diademe, from Latin diadēma, from Ancient Greek διάδημα (diádēma, “band, especially worn around a tiara”), from διαδέω (diadéō, “bind around”).

DIALED.d: Past tense of DIAL: A graduated, circular scale over which a needle moves to show a measurement (such as speed).
DIALED.e: The original meaning was 'sundial' and/or 'clock dial'; from Middle English diall, from Middle French dyal, from Latin diālis (“daily, concerning the day”), because of its use in telling the time of day, from Latin diēs (“day”). Compare Spanish dial and día (“day”).

DIAPIR.d: An intrusion of a ductile rock into an overburden.
DIAPIR.e: From Ancient Greek διαπειραίνω (diapeiraínō, “to pierce through”).

DIATOM.d: Any of a group of minute unicellular algae having a siliceous covering of great delicacy, now categorized as class Diatomophyceae or division Bacillariophyta.
DIATOM.e: From (deprecated) genus name Diatoma, from Ancient Greek διάτομος (diátomos, “cut through, cut in half”).

DIBBER.d: A tool with a handle on one end and a point on the other, used in the garden to poke holes in preparation for planting seeds, bulbs, etc.

DIBBLE.d: A pointed implement used to make holes in the ground in which to set out plants or to plant seeds.
DIBBLE.e: Possibly dib (“to dab lightly”) + -le (frequentative suffix indicating repetition or continuousness); however, the word dibble is attested earlier than dib.

DICING.d: present participle and gerund of dice

DICTUM.d: An authoritative statement; a dogmatic saying; a maxim, an apothegm.
DICTUM.e: From Latin dictum (“proverb, maxim”), from dictus (“having been said”), perfect passive participle of dico (“I say”). Compare Spanish dicho (“saying”). Doublet of dict.

DIDDER.d: Comparative form of DID: simple past of do

DIDDLE.d: In percussion, two consecutive notes played by the same hand (either RR or LL), similar to the drag, except that by convention diddles are played the same speed as the context in which they are placed.
DIDDLE.e: From dialectal duddle (“to trick”) (16th century), and diddle, duddle (“to totter”) (17th century), perhaps dissimilated from dialectal didder, dither (“to shake, tremble”), from Middle English dideren (“to shake, quiver, tremble”) and Middle English bididren (“to seduce, deceive...

DIDDLY.d: A small amount of no worth.

DIEING.d: Present participle of DIE: To stop living; to become dead; to undergo death.
DIEING.e: From Middle English deyen, from Old English *dīeġan and Old Norse deyja, both from Proto-Germanic *dawjaną (“to die”). Displaced native Old English sweltan, whence Modern English swelt, and Old English steorfan, whence modern starve.

DIESEL.d: A fuel derived from petroleum (or other oils) but heavier than gasoline/petrol. Used to power diesel engines which burn this fuel using the heat produced when air is compressed.
DIESEL.e: From German Diesel, named after inventor Rudolf Diesel, who developed a heavy-duty engine in Germany (1892–1897) and perfected it throughout his life.

DIETED.d: Past tense of DIET: The food and beverage a person or animal consumes.
DIETED.e: From Middle English diet, dyet, diete, from Old French diete, from Medieval Latin dieta (“regimen, regulation; assembly”), from Latin diaeta, from Ancient Greek δίαιτα (díaita).

DIFFER.d: Not to have the same traits or characteristics; to be unalike or distinct.
DIFFER.e: From Middle English differren, from Old French differer, from Latin differō (“carry apart, put off, defer; differ”), from dis- (“apart”) + ferō (“carry, bear”). Compare Ancient Greek διαφέρω (diaphérō). Doublet of defer and dilate, see also infer, confer and collate, refer and re...

DIGEST.d: To distribute or arrange methodically; to work over and classify; to reduce to portions for ready use or application.
DIGEST.e: From Middle English digesten, from Latin dīgestus, past participle of dīgerō (“carry apart”), from dī- (for dis- (“apart”)) + gerō (“I carry”), influenced by Middle French digestion. Partly displaced native Old English meltan (intransitive) and mieltan (transitive), both “to melt...

DIGGED.d: Past tense of DIG: To move hard-packed earth out of the way, especially downward to make a hole with a shovel. Or to drill, or the like, through rocks, roads, or the like. More generally, to make any similar hole by moving material out of the way.
DIGGED.e: From Middle English diggen (“to dig”, 13th c.), an alteration of dīken, from Old English dīcian (“to dig a ditch, mound up earth”), from Proto-West Germanic *dīkōn, which see for cognates. This verb is denominal from Proto-Germanic *dīkaz (“pool, puddle; dyke, ditch”), from Proto...

DIGGER.d: Comparative form of DIG: To move hard-packed earth out of the way, especially downward to make a hole with a shovel. Or to drill, or the like, through rocks, roads, or the like. More generally, to make any similar hole by moving material out of the way.
DIGGER.e: From Middle English diggen (“to dig”, 13th c.), an alteration of dīken, from Old English dīcian (“to dig a ditch, mound up earth”), from Proto-West Germanic *dīkōn, which see for cognates. This verb is denominal from Proto-Germanic *dīkaz (“pool, puddle; dyke, ditch”), from Proto...

DIKING.d: Present participle of DIKE: Alternative spelling of dyke: ditch; embankment; waterway; etc.

DIKKOP.d: A bird of the family Burhinidae.
DIKKOP.e: From Afrikaans dikkop, from dik (“thick”) + kop (“head”).

DIKTAT.d: A harsh penalty or settlement imposed upon a defeated party by the victor.
DIKTAT.e: Borrowed from German Diktat, from Latin dictātum (“that which has been dictated”), from the perfect passive participle of dictō (“dictate”). Doublet of dictate.

DILATE.e: First attested in 1393, in Middle English; inherited from Middle English dilaten, from Old French dilater, from Latin dīlātō (“to spread out”), from dī- + lātus (“wide”) + -ō (verb-forming suffix). Doublet of dilatate.

DILUTE.d: To make thinner by adding solvent to a solution, especially by adding water.
DILUTE.e: From Latin dīlūtus, from dīluere (“to wash away, dissolve, cause to melt, dilute”), from dī-, dis- (“away, apart”) + luere (“to wash”). See lave, and compare deluge.

DIMITY.d: A light strong fabric with woven stripes or squares.
DIMITY.e: From earlier dimite, from Middle English demit, demyt, from Medieval Latin dimitum, from Byzantine Greek δίμιτον (dímiton), from Ancient Greek δίμιτος (dímitos, “of double thread”).

DIMMED.d: Past tense of DIM: Not bright or colorful.
DIMMED.e: From Middle English dim, dym, from Old English dim, dimm (“dim, dark, gloomy; wretched, grievous, sad, unhappy”), from Proto-West Germanic *dimm, from Proto-Germanic *dimmaz (“dark”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰem- (“to whisk, smoke; obscure”). Compare Faroese dimmur (“dark”), I...

DIMMER.d: Comparative form of DIM: Not bright or colorful.
DIMMER.e: From Middle English dim, dym, from Old English dim, dimm (“dim, dark, gloomy; wretched, grievous, sad, unhappy”), from Proto-West Germanic *dimm, from Proto-Germanic *dimmaz (“dark”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰem- (“to whisk, smoke; obscure”). Compare Faroese dimmur (“dark”), I...

DIMPLE.d: A small depression or indentation in a surface.
DIMPLE.e: From Middle English dimpel, dimpil, dympull, from Old English *dympel, from Proto-West Germanic *dumpil, from Proto-Germanic *dumpilaz (“sink-hole, dimple”), from Proto-Germanic *dumpaz (“hole, hollow, pit”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewb- (“deep, hollow”), equivalent to dialec...

DIMWIT.d: A person who is deficient in intelligence.

DINGHY.d: A small open boat, propelled by oars or paddles, carried as a tender, lifeboat, or pleasure craft on a ship.
DINGHY.e: From Bengali ডিঙি (ḍiṅi), perhaps from Sanskrit द्रोण (droṇa, “wooden trough”).

DINGLE.d: A small, narrow or enclosed, usually wooded valley.
DINGLE.e: From Middle English dingle (“a deep hollow; dell”), from Old English *dyngel, a diminutive of Old English dung (“dungeon; pit”), equivalent to dung + -le (diminutive suffix). Compare Saterland Frisian Dongel (“hollow tooth, cavity”), English dimble (“a dingle, glen, retired place...

DINING.d: Present participle of DINE: To eat; to eat dinner or supper.
DINING.e: From Middle English dynen, from Old French disner (“to dine, eat the main meal of the day”), from Vulgar Latin *disiūnāre (“to eat breakfast”), from *disieiūnāre (“to break the fast”), from Late Latin, from dis- + iēiūnō (“to fast”), from Latin ieiūnus.

DINNED.d: Past tense of DIN: The German Institute for Standardization.

DINNER.d: Comparative form of DIN: The German Institute for Standardization.

DINTED.d: Past tense of DINT: A blow, stroke, especially dealt in a fight.
DINTED.e: From Middle English dint, dent, dünt, from Old English dynt (“dint, blow, strike, stroke, bruise, stripe; the mark left by a blow; the sound or noise made by a blow, thud”), from Proto-Germanic *duntiz (“a blow”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰen- (“to strike, hit”). Cognate with S...

DIOECY.d: The condition of being dioecious, namely having separate sexes, especially of plants.
DIOECY.e: From Ancient Greek δι- (di-, “twice”) + οἰκία (oikía, “house, family, tribe”).

DIOXIN.d: The unsaturated six-membered heterocycle having four carbon atoms, two oxygen atoms, and two double bonds (molecular formula C₄H₄O₂); 1,2-dioxin and 1,4-dioxin.
DIOXIN.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From di- (prefix meaning ‘double; two’) + ox(ygen) + -in (suffix indicating a neutral chemical compound), a reference to the fact that the compound has two oxygen atoms.

DIPOLE.d: Any object (such as a magnet, polar molecule or antenna) that is oppositely charged at two points (or poles).

DIPPED.d: Past tense of DIP: A lower section of a road or geological feature.
DIPPED.e: From Middle English dippen, from Old English dyppan, from Proto-West Germanic *duppjan, from Proto-Germanic *dupjaną; see *daupijaną (“to dip”). Related to deep.

DIPPER.d: Comparative form of DIP: A lower section of a road or geological feature.
DIPPER.e: From Middle English dippen, from Old English dyppan, from Proto-West Germanic *duppjan, from Proto-Germanic *dupjaną; see *daupijaną (“to dip”). Related to deep.

DIRECT.e:
Borrowed from Latin dīrectus, perfect passive participle of dīrigō (“straighten, direct”), from dis- (“asunder, in pieces, apart, in two”) + regō (“make straight, rule”). Compare dress. Doublet of derecho.
For the meaning development compare with Russian напра́вить (naprávitʹ, “t...

DIRKED.d: Past tense of DIRK: A long Scottish dagger with a straight blade.
DIRKED.e:
Etymology unknown, apparently from Scots dirk.
First attested in 1602 as dork, in the later 17th century as durk. The spelling dirk is due to Johnson's Dictionary of 1755.
Early quotations as well as Johnson 1755 suggest that the word is of Scottish Gaelic origin, but no such Gae...

DIRNDL.d: A traditional Alpine woman's dress having a tight bodice and full skirt.
DIRNDL.e: Borrowed from German Dirndl, a diminutive of Dirne (“girl”) (Austria, Bavaria), from Middle High German dierne (“girl; servant”), from Old High German diorna, thiorna (“girl; servant”), from Proto-West Germanic *þewernā (“maiden, young girl; female servant, handmaid”), ultimately...

DISARM.d: To deprive of weapons; to deprive of the means of attack or defense; to render defenseless.
DISARM.e: From Middle English desarmen (“to divest of arms”), from Anglo-Norman desarmer.

DISBAR.d: To expel from the bar, or the legal profession; to deprive (an attorney, barrister, or counselor) of his or her status and privileges as such.

DISBUD.d: To remove buds from a plant in order to promote growth and health in the remaining buds.

DISCED.d: Past tense of DISC: A thin, flat, circular plate or similar object.
DISCED.e: From French disque, from Latin discus, from Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “disk, quoit, platter”). Doublet of dais, desk, discus, dish, disk, and diskos.

DISCUS.d: A round plate-like object that is thrown for sport.
DISCUS.e: 1656. From Latin discus, from Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “disk, quoit, platter”). Doublet of dais, desk, disc, dish, disk, and diskos.

DISHED.d: Past tense of DISH: A vessel such as a plate for holding or serving food, often flat with a depressed region in the middle.
DISHED.e: From Middle English dissh, disch, from Old English disċ (“plate; bowl; dish”), from Proto-West Germanic *disk (“table; dish”) (whence also Proto-Slavic *dъska, whence Bulgarian дъска́ (dǎská), Polish deska, Russian доска́ (doská)), Russian чан (čan)) from Latin discus. Doublet of...

DISHES.d: Plural of DISH: A vessel such as a plate for holding or serving food, often flat with a depressed region in the middle.
DISHES.e: From Middle English dissh, disch, from Old English disċ (“plate; bowl; dish”), from Proto-West Germanic *disk (“table; dish”) (whence also Proto-Slavic *dъska, whence Bulgarian дъска́ (dǎská), Polish deska, Russian доска́ (doská)), Russian чан (čan)) from Latin discus. Doublet of...

DISKED.d: Past tense of DISK: A thin, flat, circular plate or similar object.
DISKED.e: From Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “a circular plate suited for hurling”), from δικέω (dikéō, “to hurl, to launch”). Doublet of dais, desk, disc, discus, dish, and diskos.

DISMAL.e: From Middle English dismal, dismale, from Anglo-Norman dismal, from Old French (li) dis mals (“(the) bad days”), from Medieval Latin diēs malī (“bad days”).

DISMAY.d: To cause to feel apprehension; great sadness, or fear; to deprive of energy.
DISMAY.e: From Middle English dismayen, from Anglo-Norman *desmaiier, alteration of Old French esmaier (“to frighten”), probably from Vulgar Latin *exmagare (“to deprive (someone) of strength, to disable”), from ex- + *magare (“to enable, empower”), from Proto-Germanic *maginą, *maganą (“m...

DISPEL.d: To drive away or cause to vanish by scattering.
DISPEL.e: From Middle English dispelen, from Latin dispellere (“to disperse; to dispel”).

DISTAL.d: Remote from the point of attachment or origin.

DISTIL.d: To exude (a liquid) in small drops; also, to give off (a vapour) which condenses in small drops.
DISTIL.e:
PIE word
 *de
From Late Middle English distillen (“to fall, flow, or shed in drops, drop, trickle; to shed drops; to fill (the eyes) with tears; (alchemy, medicine) to subject (something) to distillation; to obtain (something) using distillation; to distil; to condense or vaporiz...

DISTRO.d: A set of software components, often open source, that have been packaged into a larger product or component for distribution to end-users.

DISUSE.d: The state of not being used; neglect.
DISUSE.e: From Old French desuser, equivalent to dis- + use.

DITHER.e:
Variant of didder, from Middle English dideren (“to tremble”). Compare Middle English bididren, bididdren (“to seduce, deceive”), from Old English bedidrian, bedyderian (“to deceive, trick”).
Alternatively, perhaps with expressive voicing from *titeren, from Proto-Germanic *titrō...

DIVERT.d: To turn aside from a course.
DIVERT.e: From Middle English diverten, Old French divertir (“to turn or go different ways, part, separate, divert”), from Latin di- (“apart”) + vertere (“to turn”); see verse.

DIVEST.d: To strip, deprive, or dispossess (someone) of something (such as a right, passion, privilege, or prejudice).
DIVEST.e: Alteration of devest, from Middle French devester (“strip of possessions”), from Old French desvestir, from des- (“dis-”) + vestir (“to clothe”).

DIVIDE.d: To split or separate (something) into two or more parts.
DIVIDE.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English dividen, from Latin dīvidere (“to divide”). Displaced native Old English tōdǣlan.

DIVINE.d: Of or pertaining to a god.
DIVINE.e: From Old French divin, from Latin dīvīnus (“of a god”), from divus (“god”). Displaced native Old English godcund.

DIVING.d: Present participle of DIVE: To swim under water.
DIVING.e: From Middle English diven, duven, from the merger of Old English dȳfan (“to dip, immerse”, transitive weak verb) (from Proto-Germanic *dūbijaną) and dūfan (“to duck, dive, sink, penetrate”, intransitive strong verb) (past participle ġedofen). Cognate with Icelandic dýfa (“to dip,...

DOBBIN.e: From Dobbin, a common name given to workhorses.

DOCILE.d: Ready to accept instruction or direction; obedient; subservient.
DOCILE.e:
From Middle English docyle, from Middle French docile, from Latin docilis, from docēre (“teach”).
Compare Spanish dócil ("docile").

DOCKED.d: Past tense of DOCK: Any of the genus Rumex of coarse weedy plants with small green flowers related to buckwheat, especially bitter dock (Rumex obtusifolius), and used as potherbs and in folk medicine, especially in curing nettle rash.
DOCKED.e: From Middle English dokke, from Old English docce, from Proto-West Germanic *dokkā, from Proto-Germanic *dukkǭ (compare Old Danish dokke (“water-dock”), West Flemish dokke, dokkebladeren (“coltsfoot, butterbur”)), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰew- (“dark”) (compare Latvian duga (“s...

DOCKET.e: Uncertain; perhaps a diminutive of dock.

DOCTOR.d: A physician; a member of the medical profession; one who is trained and licensed to heal the sick or injured. The final examination and qualification may award a doctor degree in which case the post-nominal letters are DO, DPM, MD, DMD, or DDS in the US, or MBBS or BDS in the UK.
DOCTOR.e: From Middle English doctor, doctour (“an expert, authority on a subject”), from Anglo-Norman doctour, from Latin doctor (“teacher”), from doceō (“to teach”). Displaced native Middle English lerare (“doctor, teacher”) (from Middle English leren (“to teach, instruct”) from Old Engl...

DODDER.d: To shake or tremble as one moves, especially as of old age or childhood; to totter.
DODDER.e: From Middle English daderen (“to quake, tremble”). Compare Norwegian dudra (“to tremble”).

DODDLE.d: A job, task, or other activity that is easy to complete or simple.
DODDLE.e: Uncertain. Possibly from dialectal English doddle (“to toddle; sway; nod drowsily”).

DODGEM.d: A bumper car in an amusement park.

DOFFED.d: Past tense of DOFF: To remove or take off (something worn on the body such as armour or clothing, or something carried).
DOFFED.e:
PIE word
 *h₂epó
The verb is derived from Late Middle English doffen (“to take off (clothing); to remove (headwear) as a sign of respect; to remove (grease) by skimming”), a contraction of Middle English do off, don off, from Old English dōn of, from dōn (“to do; to put; to take ...

DOGATE.d: The office or dignity of a doge.
DOGATE.e: See doge and compare French dogat, Italian dogato.

DOGDOM.d: The state or essence of being a dog.

DOGGED.d: simple past and past participle of dog

DOGGER.d: Comparative form of DOG: Initialism of digital on-screen graphic.

DOGIES.d: Plural of DOGY: Alternative spelling of dogie.

DOGLEG.d: Something (such as a canyon or road) with a sharp bend or turn in it.
DOGLEG.e: The noun is derived from dog + leg, referring to the shape of the hind leg of a dog. The verb is derived from the noun.

DOGNAP.d: To abduct or steal a dog, especially in order to sell it.

DOITED.d: Past tense of DOIT: A small Dutch coin, equivalent to one-eighth of a stiver.
DOITED.e: Borrowed from Middle Low German doyt, cognate with Middle Dutch duit. Doublet of thwaite.

DOLINE.d: A depression (basin, hollow) in karstic terrain/limestone.
DOLINE.e: From a Slavic (most likely Russian or Slovene) word dolina ("valley"), perhaps via German Doline.

DOLING.d: Present participle of DOLE: To distribute in small amounts; to share out small portions of a meager resource.
DOLING.e: From Middle English dol, from Old English dāl (“portion, share, division, allotment”), from Proto-Germanic *dailą (“part, deal”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰayl- (“part, watershed”). Cognate with Old Church Slavonic дѣлити (děliti, “divide”). More at deal.

DOLLAR.d: Official designation for currency in some parts of the world, including Canada, the United States, Australia, New Zealand, Singapore, Hong Kong, and elsewhere. Its symbol is $.
DOLLAR.e: Attested since the mid-16th century, from early Dutch daler, daalder, from German Taler, Thaler (“dollar”), earlier Joachimsthaler, literally “of Joachimstal”, the town where the original dollars were minted. The name means “(Saint) Joachim's valley”, from Joachim + Tal. Possibly...

DOLLOP.d: A considerable lump, scoop, or quantity of something, especially soft food.
DOLLOP.e: From earlier East Anglian dialectal dallop (“patch, tuft (of grass, etc.)”), of unknown origin. Compare dialectal Norwegian dolp (“lump”).

DOLMAN.d: A long, loose garment with narrow sleeves and an opening in the front, generally worn by Turks.
DOLMAN.e: Apparently from French doliman, dolman (sense 2), ultimately from Ottoman Turkish طولامان, دولامان (dolaman, “robe”), from طولامق (dolamak, “to wrap around”). Compare German Doliman, Dollman; Hungarian dolmány.

DOLMEN.d: A prehistoric megalithic tomb consisting of a capstone supported by two or more upright stones, most having originally been covered with earth or smaller stones to form a barrow.
DOLMEN.e: Borrowed from French dolmen. Perhaps incorrectly fabricated from Breton taol maen (taol (“table”) + maen (“stone”)) (the correct compound would be *taolvaen, not **daolmaen). See also menhir.

DOLOUR.e: From Middle English dolour (“physical pain, agony, suffering; painful disease; anguish, grief, misery, sorrow; grieving for sins, contrition; hardship, misery, trouble; cause of grief or suffering, affliction”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman dolour, Old French dolour, dolor...

DOMAIN.d: A geographic area owned or controlled by a single person or organization.
DOMAIN.e: From Middle English demayne, demain (“rule”), from Old French demeine, demaine, demeigne, domaine (“power”), (French domaine), from Latin dominium (“property, right of ownership”), from dominus (“master, proprietor, owner”). See dame, and compare demain, danger, dungeon. Doublet ...

DOMING.d: Present participle of DOME: A structural element resembling the hollow upper half of a sphere.
DOMING.e: Borrowed from Middle French dome, domme (modern French dôme), from Italian duomo, from Latin domus (ecclesiae) (literally “house (of the church)”), a calque of Ancient Greek οἶκος τῆς ἐκκλησίας (oîkos tês ekklēsías). Doublet of domus and duomo.

DOMINO.d: A tile divided into two squares, each having 0 to 6 (or sometimes more) dots or pips (as in dice), used in the game of dominoes.
DOMINO.e: 1801, borrowed from French domino (1771), originally the term for a hooded garment, itself from Medieval Latin domino, oblique case of dominus (“lord, master”); compare Medieval Latin dominicale (“a kind of veil”).

DONATE.d: To make a donation; to give away something of value to support or contribute towards a cause or for the benefit of another.
DONATE.e: Circa 1845, back-formation from donation on the basis of -ate (verb-forming suffix), chiefly found in American English. Ultimately from Latin dōnāre (“to give”).

DONGLE.d: Any small device that plugs into an electronic device, typically a computer, and alters its functionality. Common examples include wireless modems, digital media players, software copy protect devices, and adapters.
DONGLE.e: Unknown. Likely a descendant of dangle, reflecting that electronic accessories such as computer peripherals often are plugged in via a flexible cable (although wirelessness is also often relevant). Claims that the word comes from a man named "Don Gall" were made up by an advertis...

DONKEY.d: A domestic animal, Equus asinus asinus, similar to a horse.
DONKEY.e: The origin is uncertain. Originally a slang term from the late eighteenth century. Perhaps from Middle English *donekie (“a miniature dun horse”), a double diminutive of Middle English don, dun, dunne (a name for a dun horse), equivalent to modern English dun (“brownish grey colo...

DONNED.d: Past tense of DON: A university professor, particularly one at Oxford or Cambridge.
DONNED.e: From Latin dominus (“lord, head of household”), akin to Italian don, Sicilian don, Spanish don; from domus (“house”). Doublet of dom, domine, dominie, and dominus.

DOODLE.d: A fool, a simpleton, a mindless person.
DOODLE.e:
Originally dialectal, from Low German dudeldopp (“simpleton”). Influenced by dawdle. Compare also German dudeln (“to play (the bagpipe)”).
The word doodle first appeared in the early 17th century to mean a fool or simpleton. German variants of the etymon include Dudeltopf, Dudent...

DOOFER.d: An object whose name the speaker or writer cannot remember or does not know.
DOOFER.e: Respelling of “do for”, as in “it will do for that job”.

DOOMED.d: Past tense of DOOM: Destiny, especially terrible.
DOOMED.e:
From Middle English doom, dom, from Old English dōm (“judgement”), from Proto-West Germanic *dōm, from Proto-Germanic *dōmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰóh₁mos.
Cognates
Compare Dutch doem (“condemnation, doom; judgement”), Danish, Norwegian Bokmål, Norwegian Nynorsk, and Swedis...

DOORED.d: Past tense of DOOR: A portal of entry into a building, room, or vehicle, typically consisting of a rigid plane movable on a hinge. It may have a handle to help open and close, a latch to hold it closed, and a lock that ensures it cannot be opened without a key.
DOORED.e:
From Middle English dore, dor, from Old English duru (“door”), dor (“gate”), from Proto-West Germanic *dur, from Proto-Germanic *durz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰwṓr, from *dʰwer- (“doorway, door, gate”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots door (“door”), Saterland Frisian Doore (“door”...

DOPANT.d: A substance added in small amounts to a pure material, such as semiconductor, to alter its original electrical or optical properties; a doping agent.

DOPIER.d: Comparative form of DOPY: Alternative spelling of dopey.

DOPING.d: Present participle of DOPE: Any viscous liquid or paste, such as a lubricant, used in preparing a surface.
DOPING.e:
From Dutch doop (“thick dipping sauce”), from Dutch dopen (“to dip”), from Middle Dutch dopen, from Old Dutch *dōpen, from Frankish *daupijan, from Proto-Germanic *daupijaną.
“Doop” in the sense “narcotic drug” ultimately refers to viscous opium juice, the drug of choice of the a...

DORADO.d: A small constellation of the southern sky, said to resemble a goldfish or swordfish. It lies between the constellations Pictor and Reticulum, and is notable for containing most of the Large Magellanic Cloud.
DORADO.e: Named by Dutch explorers Pieter Dirkszoon Keyser and Frederick de Houtman between 1595 and 1597. From Italian dorato (“gilded, golden”), ultimately from Latin deaurātus, the past participle of deaurō (“to gild”).

DORIES.d: Plural of DORY: A small flat-bottomed boat with pointed or somewhat pointed ends, used for fishing both offshore and on rivers.
DORIES.e: Attested in American English from 1709 C.E.; possibly derived from an indigenous language of the West Indies or Central America, perhaps Miskito.

DORSAL.d: With respect to, or concerning the side in which the backbone is located, or the analogous side of an invertebrate.
DORSAL.e: From Late Middle English dorsal/dorsale, borrowing from Medieval Latin dorsālis (“of or relating to the back”), from dorsum (“the back”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix); equivalent to dorsum + -al.

DORSUM.d: The back or dorsal region on the surface of an animal.
DORSUM.e: Learned borrowing from Latin dorsum (“the back”).

DOSAGE.d: The administration of a medication etc, in a measured amount; dosing.

DOSING.d: Present participle of DOSE: A measured portion of medicine taken at any one time.
DOSING.e: Borrowed from Middle French dose, from Late Latin dosis, from Ancient Greek δόσις (dósis, “a portion prescribed”, literally “a giving”), used by Galen and other Greek physicians to mean an amount of medicine, from δίδωμι (dídōmi, “to give”). Doublet of doos.

DOSSAL.d: Alternative form of dorsal (“a hanging or canopy”).

DOSSED.d: Past tense of DOS: Initialism of date of service.

DOSSER.d: Someone who dosses, someone known for avoiding work.

DOTAGE.d: Decline in judgment and other cognitive functions, associated with aging; senility.
DOTAGE.e: From Middle English dotage, from doten (“to dote”) + -age; equivalent to dote + -age.

DOTARD.d: An old person with impaired intellect; a senile person; one in their dotage.
DOTARD.e: From Middle English dotard; equivalent to dote + -ard.

DOTING.d: Present participle of DOTE: To be weakly or foolishly fond of somebody.
DOTING.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English doten, from Middle Low German doten (“to be foolish”) or Middle Dutch doten (“to be silly”). Doublet of doit (Scottish English).
The noun in the sense of "imbecile" is derived from Middle English dote (“simpleton”), itself from doten (see a...

DOTTED.d: Past tense of DOT: A small, round spot.
DOTTED.e: From Middle English *dot, dotte, from Old English dott (“a dot, point”), from Proto-West Germanic *dott, from Proto-Germanic *duttaz (“wisp”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Dot, Dotte (“a clump”), Dutch dot (“lump, knot, clod”), Low German Dutte (“a plug”), dialectal Swedish dot...

DOTTER.d: Comparative form of DOT: A small, round spot.
DOTTER.e: From Middle English *dot, dotte, from Old English dott (“a dot, point”), from Proto-West Germanic *dott, from Proto-Germanic *duttaz (“wisp”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Dot, Dotte (“a clump”), Dutch dot (“lump, knot, clod”), Low German Dutte (“a plug”), dialectal Swedish dot...

DOUBLE.d: Made up of two matching or complementary elements.
DOUBLE.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English double, from Old French doble, double, from Latin duplus (“twofold”). Doublet of doppio and duple.

DOUBTS.d: Plural of DOUBT: Uncertainty; to question.
DOUBTS.e: From Old French douter, from Latin dubitāre.

DOUCHE.d: A jet or current of water or vapour directed upon some part of the body to benefit it medicinally; in particular, such a jet directed at the vagina for irrigation.
DOUCHE.e: Borrowed from French douche (“shower”), from Italian doccia (“shower”).

DOUGHY.d: Having the characteristics of dough especially in appearance or consistency: as

DOWNED.d: Past tense of DOWN: From a higher position to a lower one; downwards.
DOWNED.e: From Middle English doun, doune, from Old English dūne (“down”), aphetic form of adūne (“down, downward”), from earlier ofdūne (“down”, literally “off the hill”), from of (“of, off of”) + dūn (“hill, mount, dune, down”). More at Etymology 2 below. For the development from directi...

DOXIES.d: Plural of DOXY: A sweetheart; a prostitute or a mistress.
DOXIES.e: Perhaps from Middle Dutch *doketje, diminutive of Middle Dutch docke (“a doll”), from Proto-Germanic *dokko (“something round”), related to *dukkǭ (“muscle, strength”). Cognate with Low German dokke (“doll”), Saterland Frisian dok, dokke (“a doll”), Swedish docka (“doll, puppet”)...

DOZIER.d: Comparative form of DOZY: Quite sleepy or tired.

DOZING.d: Present participle of DOZE: To sleep lightly or briefly; to nap, snooze.
DOZING.e:
From Middle English *dosen, from Old Norse dúsa (“to doze, rest, remain quiet”), from Proto-Germanic *dusāną (“to be dizzy”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰews- (“to fly, whirl”), from *dʰew- (“to fly, shake, reek, steam, smolder”).
Cognate with Old Frisian dusia (“to be dizzy”), G...

DRACHM.d: A small unit of weight, variously:
DRACHM.e: Borrowed into late Middle English from Old French dragme (modern French drachme), from Late Latin dragma. Doublet of dirham.

DRAFTS.d: Plural of DRAFT: A preliminary version; a current of air.

DRAGGY.d: Moving or developing very slowly; tending to drag on; dull.

DRAGON.d: A legendary serpentine or reptilian creature.
DRAGON.e: From Middle English dragoun, borrowed from Old French dragon, from Latin dracō(n), from Ancient Greek δράκων (drákōn, “a serpent of huge size, a python, a dragon”), probably from δέρκομαι (dérkomai, “I see clearly”). Mostly displaced Old English draca (whence modern drake)—from t...

DRAMAS.d: Plural of DRAMA: A play; exciting events.

DRAWEE.d: The party directed to pay the amount of a draft or cheque.

DRAYED.d: Past tense of DRAY: Any of various forms of low horse-drawn cart or wagon, often without sides or with removable sides, and used especially for heavy loads.
DRAYED.e: From Middle English draye, dreye, from Old English dræġe (“dragnet”), from Proto-Germanic *dragǭ. Cognate with Middle Low German drāge (“stretcher; dray”), Middle High German trage (“a litter”). Related to Old English dragan (“to pull; draw”). More at draw.

DREAMS.d: Plural of DREAM: Images during sleep; an aspiration.

DREAMY.d: As in a dream; resembling a dream.

DREARY.e: From Middle English drery, from Old English drēoriġ (“sad”), from Proto-Germanic *dreuzagaz (“bloody”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰrews- (“to break, break off, crumble”), equivalent to drear + -y. Cognate with Dutch treurig (“sad, gloomy”), Low German trurig (“sad”), German trau...

DREDGE.d: Any instrument used to gather or take by dragging; as:
DREDGE.e: From Scots dreg-boat, dreg-bot (from Old English *dreċġ); or alternatively from Middle Dutch dregghe (“drag-net”), probably ultimately from the same root as drag.

DRENCH.d: A dose or draught of liquid medicine (especially one causing sleepiness) taken by a person; specifically, a (large) dose, or one forced or poured down the throat.
DRENCH.e: From Middle English drench, drenche (“beverage, drink; cup of drink, specifically a poisoned drink; medicinal potion, specifically an emetic (?)”) [and other forms], from Old English drenċ (“drink; draft, potion; dose (of medicine, poison, etc.)”), from Proto-West Germanic *drank...

DRIEST.d: Superlative form of DRY: Free from or lacking moisture.
DRIEST.e: Adjective and noun from Middle English drye, dryge, drüȝe, from Old English drȳġe (“dry; parched, withered”), from Proto-West Germanic *drūgī, *draugī, from Proto-Germanic *drūgiz, *draugiz (“dry, hard”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard”), from *dʰe...

DRINKS.d: Plural of DRINK: To swallow liquid; a beverage.

DRIVEL.e: From Middle English dravel, dribil, a deverbal from drevelen, drivelen (Etymology 2).

DRIVES.d: Plural of DRIVE: To operate a vehicle; a journey by car.

DROGUE.d: A floating object attached to the end of a harpoon line to slow a whale down and prevent it from diving.
DROGUE.e: Uncertain; probably related to drag in some way.

DRONGO.d: Any bird of the genus Dicrurus.

DROOPY.e: Inherited from Middle English drupi, from drup (“sad”), from Old Norse drúpr (“drooping sadness”); related to Middle English drupen, droupen (“to sag, droop”), also from Old Norse. By surface analysis, droop + -y.

DROPSY.e: From Middle English dropesie, idropesie, from Old French idropsie, ydropisie, from Latin hydrōps, from Ancient Greek ὕδρωψ (húdrōps), from ὕδωρ (húdōr, “water”). Doublet of hydropsy and hydrops.

DROWSE.d: To make (someone or something) heavy with drowsiness or sleepiness.
DROWSE.e:
The verb is either:
* a back-formation from drowsy, which is attested earlier; or
* possibly from Middle English *drousen (no known attestations), from Old English drūsan, drūsian (“to droop, sink; to become feeble, inactive, low, or slow, drowse”), from Proto-Germanic *drūsijaną...

DROWSY.d: Inclined to drowse; heavy with sleepiness
DROWSY.e: From drowse + -y, despite the fact that drowsy (1520) is recorded before drowse (1570). Compare Old English drūsian (“to droop, drowse, become languid”).

DRUDGE.d: A person who works in a low servile job.
DRUDGE.e: From Middle English druggen, perhaps from Old English *dryċġan, from Proto-West Germanic *druggjan, from Proto-Germanic *drugjaną, a denominative built to a lost noun *drugjaz (preserved in Old English Dryċġhelm), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰrewgʰ-; compare Old English drēogan (“...

DRYING.d: Present participle of DRY: Free from or lacking moisture.
DRYING.e: Adjective and noun from Middle English drye, dryge, drüȝe, from Old English drȳġe (“dry; parched, withered”), from Proto-West Germanic *drūgī, *draugī, from Proto-Germanic *drūgiz, *draugiz (“dry, hard”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard”), from *dʰe...

DUBBED.d: Past tense of DUB: To confer knighthood; the conclusion of the ceremony was marked by a tap on the shoulder with a sword, the accolade.
DUBBED.e: From Middle English dubben, from Old English dubbian (“to knight by striking with a sword, dub”) from Old French adober (“to equip with arms; adorn”) (also 11th century, Modern French adouber), both from Proto-West Germanic *dubbōn, from Proto-Germanic *dub- (“to hit, strike”), f...

DUBBER.d: One who dubs, or gives a name.

DUBBIN.d: A mixture of tallow and oil used to soften leather, and make it waterproof.

DUCKED.d: Past tense of DUCK: To quickly lower (the head or body), often in order to prevent it from being struck by something.
DUCKED.e:
From Middle English ducken, duken, douken (“to duck, plunge under water, submerge”), from Old English *dūcan (“to dip, dive, duck”), from Proto-West Germanic *dūkan, from Proto-Germanic *dūkaną (“to dip, dive, bend down, stoop, duck”).
Cognates
Related to Scots dulk (“to duck”), ...

DUCTED.d: Past tense of DUCT: A pipe, tube or canal which carries gas or liquid from one place to another.
DUCTED.e: Borrowed from Latin ductus (“leading, conducting”, noun), from dūcō (“to lead, conduct, draw”) + -tus (action noun suffix). Doublet of ductus and douit. Also via Medieval Latin ductus (“a conveyance of water; a channel”), which itself has the first mentioned etymology.

DUDDER.d: Comparative form of DUD: A device or machine that is useless because it does not work properly or has failed to work, such as a bomb, or explosive projectile.
DUDDER.e: From Middle English dudde (“cloak, mantle, kind of cloth; ragged clothing or cloth”), from Old English *dudda (attested only as personal name Dudda, part of modern English Dudley), akin to Old Norse dúði (“swaddling clothes”), Low German dudel. Possibly borrowed from the Old Nors...

DUDEEN.d: A short-stemmed Irish pipe made out of clay.

DUELED.d: Past tense of DUEL: Arranged, regular combat between two private persons, often over a matter of honor.
DUELED.e:
From Medieval Latin duellum (“fight between two men, duel”), itself from Old Latin duellum (“war, fight”), which survived in Classical Latin as a rare byform of bellum and was later reinterpreted as “duel” by unetymological association with duo (“two”).
May have entered English t...

DUENDE.d: A small, mischievous humanoid creature in Iberian (Spanish/Portuguese), Latin American, and Philippine folklore/mythology; an imp.
DUENDE.e: Borrowed from Spanish duende and (especially in reference to Portuguese or Brazilian folklore) Portuguese duende. Doublet of duwende.

DUENNA.d: a chaperon of a young lady, usually an older woman.
DUENNA.e: From Old Spanish duenna or dueña, from Vulgar Latin donna, from Latin domina (“Lady”). Doublet of dame.

DUFFED.e: Representing a northern England and Scots pronunciation of dough.

DUFFEL.d: A kind of coarse woolen cloth, having a thick nap or frieze.
DUFFEL.e: From Dutch duffel, named after Duffel, a town in Belgium, itself ultimately from Latin Dubrolocus, the first particle from Gaulish dubrum.

DUFFLE.e: Alteration of duffel, influenced by suffix -le.

DUGONG.d: A plant-eating aquatic marine mammal, of the species Dugong dugon, found in tropical regions.

DUGOUT.d: A canoe made from a hollowed-out log.
DUGOUT.e: From the verb phrase dug out.

DUIKER.d: Any of several species of small southern African antelopes of the Cephalophinae subfamily.
DUIKER.e: Borrowed from Afrikaans duiker (literally “diver”), from Dutch duiker, from Middle Dutch dukere. Piecewise doublet of ducker.

DULCET.d: Sweet, especially when describing voice or tones; melodious.
DULCET.e: From Middle English doucet, from Old French doucet, from dulz, dulce (“sweet, pleasant”) + diminutive -et, from Latin dulcis (“sweet, pleasant”). Cognate with Spanish dulce, French doux, Italian dolce, Portuguese doce, and Romanian dulce. Doublet of dolcetto and doucet.

DULLED.d: Past tense of DULL: Lacking the ability to cut easily; not sharp.
DULLED.e: From Middle English dull, dul (also dyll, dill, dwal), from Old English dol (“dull, foolish, erring, heretical; foolish, silly; presumptuous”), from Proto-West Germanic *dol, from Proto-Germanic *dulaz, from earlier *dwulaz, a variant of *dwalaz (“stunned, mad, foolish, misled”),...

DUMBED.d: Past tense of DUMB: Unable to speak; lacking power of speech.
DUMBED.e: From Middle English dumb (“silent, speechless, mute, ineffectual”), from Old English dumb (“silent, speechless, mute, unable to speak”), from Proto-West Germanic *dumb, from Proto-Germanic *dumbaz (“dull, dumb”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, smoke, darken, obscur...

DUMDUM.d: A soft-nosed bullet that expands on impact to cause a gaping wound.
DUMDUM.e: From Dum Dum, a city in India where the type of bullet was developed, from Hindi दम दम (dam dam) (Bengali দমদম (domodom)), from Hindi दमदमा (damadmā, “tenaille, a raised mound or battery”).

DUMPED.d: Past tense of DUMP: A place where waste or garbage is left; a ground or place for dumping ashes, refuse, etc.; a disposal site.
DUMPED.e: From Middle English dumpen, dompen, probably from Old Norse dumpa (“to thump”) (whence Danish dumpe (“to fall suddenly”)), of uncertain origin, possibly imitative of falling, similar to thump.

DUNGED.d: Past tense of DUNG: Manure; animal excrement.
DUNGED.e: From Middle English dung, dunge, donge, from Old English dung (“dung; excrement; manure”), from Proto-West Germanic *dungu, from Proto-Germanic *dungō (“dung”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰengʰ- (“to cover”).

DUNKED.d: Past tense of DUNK: To submerge briefly in a liquid.
DUNKED.e:
From Pennsylvania German dunke, from Middle High German dunken, from Old High German dunkōn (“to dip, submerge, dunk”), from Proto-West Germanic *þunkōn (“to make wet”), possibly from Proto-Germanic *þunkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *teng- (“to moisten, wet”).
Cognate with Germa...

DUNLIN.d: A small wading bird, Calidris alpina, found along the coast and having a distinctive black belly patch in its breeding plumage. A type of stint.

DUNNED.d: Past tense of DUN: A brownish grey colour.
DUNNED.e: From Middle English dun, donn, dunne, from Old English dunn (“dun, dingy brown, bark-colored, brownish black”), from Proto-West Germanic *duʀn, from Proto-Germanic *duznaz, *dusnaz (“brown, yellow”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust”). Cognate with Old Sax...

DUNNER.d: Comparative form of DUN: A brownish grey colour.
DUNNER.e: From Middle English dun, donn, dunne, from Old English dunn (“dun, dingy brown, bark-colored, brownish black”), from Proto-West Germanic *duʀn, from Proto-Germanic *duznaz, *dusnaz (“brown, yellow”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust”). Cognate with Old Sax...

DUPERY.d: The act or practice of duping; the condition of being deceived.

DUPING.d: Present participle of DUPE: A person who has been deceived.
DUPING.e: From French duper, from Middle French duppe, alteration of huppe (“hoopoe”), from Latin, onomatopoeic.

DUPION.d: A double cocoon, made by two silkworms.
DUPION.e: From French doupion, Italian doppione, from doppio (“double”), Latin duplus. See double, and compare doubloon.

DUPLEX.d: Double; made up of two parts.
DUPLEX.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
Borrowed from Latin duplex (“double, two-fold”), from duo (“two”) + plico (“fold together”); compare the roots of διπλόος (diplóos, “double”); compare also πλέκω (plékō, “twist, braid”). By surface analysis, duo- + -plex.

DURBAR.d: A ceremonial gathering held by a ruler in India.
DURBAR.e: From Hindustani دربار / दरबार (darbār), from Classical Persian دربار (darbār, “royal court”).

DURESS.e: Borrowed into Middle English from Old French duresse, from Latin duritia (“hardness”), from durus (“hard”).

DURIAN.d: Any of several trees, genus Durio, of Southeast Asia.
DURIAN.e: From Malay durian, ultimately from Proto-Austronesian *duʀi (“thorn”). Doublet of iwi, from Māori.

DUSKED.d: Past tense of DUSK: Tending to darkness or blackness; moderately dark or black; dusky.
DUSKED.e: From Middle English dosk, dusk(e) (“dusky”, adj.), from Old English dox (“dark, swarthy”), from Proto-Germanic *duskaz (“dark, smoky”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰwes-, related to *dʰewh₂- (“smoke, mist, haze”). Cognate to Latin fuscus (“dark, dusky”), Sanskrit धूसर (dhūsara, “d...

DUSTED.d: Past tense of DUST: Fine particles.
DUSTED.e: From Middle English dust, doust, from Old English dūst (“dust, dried earth reduced to powder; other dry material reduced to powder”), from the fusion of Proto-Germanic *dustą (“dust”) and *dunstą (“mist, dust, evaporation”), both from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, rais...

DUTIED.d: Past tense of DUTY: That which one is morally or legally obligated to do.
DUTIED.e: From Middle English duete, from Middle English dewe + Middle English -te. Equivalent to due + -ty.

DUTIES.d: Plural of DUTY: That which one is morally or legally obligated to do.
DUTIES.e: From Middle English duete, from Middle English dewe + Middle English -te. Equivalent to due + -ty.

DYBBUK.d: A malicious possessing spirit, believed to be the dislocated soul of a dead person.
DYBBUK.e: From Yiddish דיבוק (dibek), from Hebrew דבק (dovek, “cling”).

DYEING.d: Present participle of DYE: A colourant, especially one that has an affinity to the substrate to which it is applied.
DYEING.e:
From Middle English deye, from Old English dēah, dēag (“color, hue, dye”), from Proto-West Germanic *daugu (“colour, shade”), from *daugan (“to conceal, be dark”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust, camouflage”).
Cognates
Cognate with Old High German tougan...

DYKING.d: Present participle of DYKE: A long, narrow hollow dug from the ground to serve as a boundary marker.
DYKING.e:
A variant of dike, from Northern Middle English dik and dike (“ditch”), from Old Norse díki (“ditch”). Influenced by Middle Dutch dijc (“ditch; dam”) and Middle Low German dīk (“dam”). See also
ditch.

DYNAMO.d: An electricity generator; a dynamo-electric machine.
DYNAMO.e: A shortening of dynamo-electric machine. The element dynamo- is ultimately from Ancient Greek δύναμις (dúnamis, “power”).

DYNAST.d: A ruler or governor, especially a hereditary ruler or someone who founded or is part of a dynasty.
DYNAST.e: From Late Latin dynastēs, from Ancient Greek δυνάστης (dunástēs, “lord, ruler”), from δύναμαι (dúnamai, “to be powerful”).

DYNODE.d: Any of a series of electrodes within a photomultiplier tube.

EAGLET.d: The immature young of an eagle; an eagle chick.

EANING.d: present participle and gerund of ean

EARBUD.d: A small earphone designed to be placed in the ear canal for use with portable sound systems.

EARFUL.d: an angry reprimand, castigation or telling off

EARING.d: Present participle of EAR: The organ of hearing, consisting of the pinna or auricle, auditory canal, eardrum, malleus, incus, stapes and cochlea.
EARING.e: From Middle English ere, eare, from Old English ēare (“ear”), from Proto-West Germanic *auʀā, from the voiced Verner alternant of Proto-Germanic *ausô (“ear”) (compare Scots ear, West Frisian ear, Dutch oor, German Ohr, Swedish öra, Danish øre), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ṓws (c...

EARNED.d: Past tense of EARN: To gain (success, reward, recognition) through applied effort or work.
EARNED.e: From Middle English ernen, from Old English earnian, from Proto-West Germanic *aʀanōn, from Proto-Germanic *azanōną. This verb is denominal from the noun *azaniz (“harvest”).

EARTHS.d: Plural of EARTH: The planet we live on; soil.

EARTHY.e: From Middle English erthy, equivalent to earth + -y. Compare German erdig (“earthy”), Swedish jordig (“earthy”).

EARWAX.d: A waxy substance secreted by the ear.
EARWAX.e: From Middle English erewax, from ere + wax. Equivalent to ear + wax.

EARWIG.d: Any of various insects of the order Dermaptera that have elongated bodies, large membranous wings folded underneath short leathery forewings and a pair of large pincers protruding from the rear of the abdomen.
EARWIG.e: From Middle English erwigge, from Old English ēarwicga, from ēare (“ear”) + wicga (“insect”), so named from the appearance of the hindwings, which are unique in their resemblance to human ears when unfolded.

EASIER.d: Comparative form of EASY: Comfortable; at ease.
EASIER.e: From Middle English esy, eesy, partly from Middle English ese (“ease”) + -y, equivalent to ease + -y, and partly from Anglo-Norman eisé from Old French aisié (“eased, at ease, at leisure”), past participle of aisier (“to put at ease”), from aise (“empty space, elbow room, opportu...

EASIES.d: Plural of EASY: Comfortable; at ease.
EASIES.e: From Middle English esy, eesy, partly from Middle English ese (“ease”) + -y, equivalent to ease + -y, and partly from Anglo-Norman eisé from Old French aisié (“eased, at ease, at leisure”), past participle of aisier (“to put at ease”), from aise (“empty space, elbow room, opportu...

EASING.d: present participle and gerund of ease

EASTED.d: Past tense of EAST: The direction of the earth's rotation, specifically 90°.
EASTED.e:
From Middle English est, from Old English ēast, from Proto-West Germanic *austr, from Proto-Germanic *austrą, from Proto-Germanic *austraz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éwsteros (“east”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots aist (“east”), North Frisian uast, ååst, ööst (“east”), Saterland...

EATERY.d: A restaurant or café; a place to purchase and eat food.

EATING.d: present participle and gerund of eat

EBBING.d: Present participle of EBB: The receding movement of the tide.
EBBING.e:
From Middle English ebbe, from Old English ebba (“ebb, tide”), from Proto-West Germanic *abbjā, from Proto-Germanic *abjô, *abjǭ, from Proto-Germanic *ab (“off, away”), from Proto-Indo-European *apó.
See also West Frisian ebbe, Dutch eb, German Ebbe, Danish ebbe, Old Norse efja (...

ECHIUM.d: Any member of the genus Echium of flowering plants.

ECHOED.d: Past tense of ECHO: A reflected sound that is heard again by its initial observer.
ECHOED.e: From Middle English eccho, ecco, ekko, from Medieval Latin ēccō, from Latin ēchō, from Ancient Greek ἠχώ (ēkhṓ), from ἠχή (ēkhḗ, “sound”). Possibly from the same Proto-Indo-European root as sough.

ECLOSE.d: To give rise to, or to undergo, eclosion.

ECZEMA.d: A non-contagious acute or chronic inflammation of the skin, characterized by redness, itching, and the outbreak of oozing vesicular lesions which become encrusted and scaly.
ECZEMA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin eczema, from Ancient Greek ἔκζεμᾰ (ékzemă, “cutaneous eruption”), from ἐκζέω (ekzéō, “to boil out, break out”) + -μᾰ (-mă, nominal suffix).

EDDIED.d: Past tense of EDDY: A current of air or water running back, or in an opposite direction to the main current.
EDDIED.e: From Middle English eddy, from Old English edēa, from ed- (“turning, back, reverse”) + ēa (“water”), equivalent to ed- + ea. Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁é, and, consequently, cognate with Latin et. Related also to Danish ide (“eddy”), Swedish eda (“eddy”), Norwegian id...

EDDIES.d: Plural of EDDY: A current of air or water running back, or in an opposite direction to the main current.
EDDIES.e: From Middle English eddy, from Old English edēa, from ed- (“turning, back, reverse”) + ēa (“water”), equivalent to ed- + ea. Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁é, and, consequently, cognate with Latin et. Related also to Danish ide (“eddy”), Swedish eda (“eddy”), Norwegian id...

EDGIER.d: Comparative form of EDGY: Nervous, apprehensive.
EDGIER.e: From edge + -y. Compare German eckig (“angular, edgy”).

EDGING.d: present participle and gerund of edge

EDIBLE.d: Capable of being eaten without harm; suitable for consumption; innocuous to humans.
EDIBLE.e: From Late Latin edibilis, from Latin edō (“eat”).

EDITED.d: simple past and past participle of edit

EDITOR.d: A person who edits or makes changes to documents.
EDITOR.e: From Medieval Latin ēditor, from Late Latin ēditor, from ēditus, perfect passive participle of ēdō (“give out, put forth, publish”).

EELING.d: Present participle of EEL: Any freshwater fish of the order Anguilliformes, which are elongated and resemble snakes.
EELING.e:
From Middle English el, from Old English ǣl (“eel”), from Proto-West Germanic *āl, from Proto-Germanic *ēlaz (“eel”), which is of unknown origin.
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian iel (“eel”), Dutch aal (“eel”), German Low German Aal, Ool (“eel”), German Aal (“eel”), Swedish, Da...

EERIER.d: Comparative form of EERY: Alternative spelling of eerie.

EFFACE.d: To erase (as anything impressed or inscribed upon a surface); to render illegible or indiscernible.
EFFACE.e: From Middle French effacer (“erase”), from Old French esfacier (“remove the face”).

EFFECT.d: The result or outcome of a cause.
EFFECT.e:
Of the noun: from Middle English effect, from Old French effect (modern French effet), from Latin effectus (“an effect, tendency, purpose”), from efficiō (“accomplish, complete, effect”); see effect as a verb. Displaced Old English fremming, fremednes from fremman.
Of the verb: f...

EFFETE.e: From Latin effētus (“exhausted”, literally “that has given birth”), 1620s.

EFFIGY.d: A dummy or other crude representation of a person, group or object that is hated.
EFFIGY.e: From French effigie, from Latin effigiēs (“likeness, effigy”), from effingō (“represent, portray”).

EFFLUX.e: From Latin effluxus, from effluō (“flow out or away”), from ex (“out of, from”) + fluō (“flow”). See also effluxion.

EFFORT.d: The work involved in performing an activity; exertion.
EFFORT.e:
From Middle French effort, from Old French esfort, deverbal of esforcier (“to force, exert”), from Vulgar Latin *exfortiō, from Latin ex + fortis (“strong”).
Compare typologically Bulgarian усилие (usilie), Czech úsilí, Polish wysiłek, Russian уси́лие (usílije) (< Proto-Slavic *s...

EFFUSE.e: Borrowed from Middle French effuser, from Latin effusus, past participle of effundere (“to pour out”).

EGGCUP.d: A small dish used to support a boiled egg while it is eaten.
EGGCUP.e: From egg + cup. Compare Swedish äggkopp.

EGGNOG.d: A beverage based on milk, eggs, sugar, and nutmeg; often made alcoholic with rum, brandy, or whisky; popular at Christmas.
EGGNOG.e:
American English c. 1775 (although drinks like it are attested far earlier, e.g. posset, of which a monastic Christmas recipe used eggs), from egg + nog.
The second element is uncertain and long-debated; prominent claims include Norfolk dialect nog (“strong ale”), or a clipping o...

EGISES.d: Plural of EGIS: Alternative spelling of aegis.

EGOISM.d: The tendency to think selfishly with exclusive self-interest in mind.
EGOISM.e: From French égoïsme, from New Latin egoismus, from Latin ego. By surface analysis, ego + -ism.

EGOIST.e: From French égoïste, from Latin ego + -iste. By surface analysis, ego + -ist.

EGRESS.e: From Latin ēgressus, from ex- + gressus.

EIGHTY.d: The cardinal number occurring after seventy-nine and before eighty-one, represented in Roman numerals as LXXX and in Arabic numerals as 80.
EIGHTY.e: Inherited from Middle English eiȝti, eyȝty, eiȝtety, aghty, from Old English hundeahtatiġ, from Proto-Germanic *ahtōutēhundą (“eighty”), equivalent to eight + -ty. Cognate with Scots hechty, auchty (“eighty”), Saterland Frisian tachentich (“eighty”), West Frisian tachtich (“eight...

EJECTA.d: Material which has been ejected, especially from a volcano or an impact crater.

ELAPID.d: Any of many species of snakes of the family Elapidae, including the cobras, mambas, and coral snakes

ELAPSE.e: From Middle French elapser, from Latin elapsus.

ELATED.d: Extremely happy and excited; delighted; pleased, euphoric.

ELDING.d: Present participle of ELD: One's age, age in years, period of life.
ELDING.e: From Middle English elde, from Old English ieldu, eldo, ieldo (“age, period of time; period; time of life, years; mature or old age, eld; an age of the world, era, epoch”), from Proto-West Germanic *aldī, from Proto-Germanic *alþį̄ (“eld, age”), from *aldaz (“grown up, mature, ol...

ELEVEN.d: The cardinal number occurring after ten and before twelve. Represented as 11 in Arabic digits.
ELEVEN.e: From Middle English elleven, enleven, eleven, from Old English endleofan; from Proto-Germanic *ainalif (“one left”) (i.e., one left over after having already counted to ten), a compound of *ainaz and *-lif, from Proto-Indo-European *leyp- (“leave, remain”). Compare West Frisian a...

ELFISH.d: Characteristic of an elf; elfin, elven.

ELICIT.d: To evoke, educe (emotions, feelings, responses, etc.); to generate, obtain, or provoke as a response or answer.
ELICIT.e: Borrowed from Latin elicitus from eliciō (“draw forth”).

ELITES.d: Plural of ELITE: A select group of superior people.
ELITES.e: From French élite, from élire (to elect).

ELIXIR.d: A liquid which converts lead to gold.
ELIXIR.e: From Medieval Latin elixir (“philosopher's stone”), from Arabic اَلْإِكْسِير (al-ʔiksīr, “philosopher's stone”), from Ancient Greek ξηρίον (xēríon, “powder for drying wounds”), from ξηρός (xērós, “dry”).

ELODEA.d: Any of several underwater freshwater perennials, of the genus Elodea, that have grasslike leaves; ditchmoss or pondweed.

ELUATE.d: A liquid solution that results from elution.
ELUATE.e: From Latin ēluō + -ate (noun-forming suffix, of participial origin). On the other hand, elute has been borrowed directly from the perfect passive participle of ēluō, ēlūtus.

ELVISH.d: Of or having to do with elves; elven.
ELVISH.e: From Middle English elvyssh, from Old English ielfisċ. Equivalent to elf + -ish.

EMBALM.d: To treat a corpse with preservatives in order to prevent decomposition.
EMBALM.e: From Middle English enbawmen, from Middle French embaumer, from Old French embasmer. See balm.

EMBANK.d: to put up a bank so as to confine or to defend

EMBARK.d: To go aboard a craft or vessel for transportation.
EMBARK.e: Borrowed from Middle French embarquer, from em- + barque (“small ship”). Compare with Portuguese embarcar, Spanish abarcar.

EMBLEM.d: A representative symbol, such as a trademark, a badge or logo.
EMBLEM.e: From Old French embleme, from Latin emblema (“raised ornaments on vessels, tessellated work, mosaic”), from Ancient Greek ἔμβλημα (émblēma, “an insertion”), from ἐμβάλλειν (embállein, “to put in, to lay on”). Doublet of emblema.

EMBODY.d: To represent in a physical or concrete form; to incarnate or personify.

EMBOSS.d: To cause (something) to stick out or swell; to extrude; also, to cause (someone or something) to be covered in swellings.
EMBOSS.e:
PIE word
 *h₁én
The verb is derived from Late Middle English embossen, embosen, embocen (“to be bloated; to bulge; to cause to bulge; to ornament in relief, emboss”) [and other forms], from Old French embocer (modern French embosser), from em- (a variant of en- (prefix meaning ‘i...

EMBRYO.d: In the reproductive cycle, the stage after the fertilization of the egg that precedes the development into a fetus.
EMBRYO.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin embryō, from Ancient Greek ἔμβρυον (émbruon, “fetus”), from ἐν (en, “in-”) + βρύω (brúō, “I grow, swell”). Possibly related to Hebrew עֻבָּר (“fetus, embryo”) (ʊbar).

EMERGE.e: First attested in the late 16th century. Borrowed from Middle French emerger, from Latin ēmergō (“to rise up or out”), from ē- (a variant of ex- (“out, forth”)) + mergō (“to dip, to sink”)

EMESIS.d: The act or process of vomiting.
EMESIS.e: From Ancient Greek ἔμεσις (émesis), from ἐμέω (eméō, “vomit”). Compare ἔμετος (émetos, “vomit”, noun). Synchronically held to end in the suffix -esis.

EMETIC.e: From French émétique, from Vulgar Latin *emeticus, from Ancient Greek ἐμετικός (emetikós), from ἔμετος (émetos, “vomit”); by surface analysis, em(esis) + -etic.

EMPATH.d: One who has the ability to sense emotions; someone who is empathic or practises empathy.

EMPIRE.d: A political state, often a monarchy, that has achieved a much greater current size than its initial size by conquering surrounding territories, cities or nations.
EMPIRE.e: From Middle English empire, from Old French empire, empere, from Latin imperium, inperium (“command, control, dominion, sovereignty, a dominion, empire”), from imperare, inperare (“to command, order”), from in (“in, on”) + parare (“to make ready, order”). Doublet of empery and im...

EMPLOY.e: From late Middle English emploien, imploien, emplien (“to apply to a specific purpose”), from Anglo-Norman emploier, Old French emploiier (“to entangle, fabricate, to make use of”), ultimately from Latin implicāre (“to infold, entangle, involve, engage”), from in- (“in”) + plicār...
