ENABLE.d: To make somebody able (to do, or to be, something); to give sufficient ability or power to do or to be; to give strength or ability to.
ENABLE.e: From Middle English enablen, equivalent to en- + able.

ENAMEL.d: An opaque, glassy coating baked onto metal or ceramic objects.
ENAMEL.e: From Middle English enamel, from Anglo-Norman enamailler, from en- (“in-”) + amailler (“to enamel”), variant of Old French esmailler (“to enamel”), from esmal (“enamel”), from Early Medieval Latin smaltum, from Frankish *smalt, from Proto-Germanic *smeltaną (“to melt, smelt”).

ENCAGE.d: To lock inside a cage; to imprison.

ENCAMP.d: To establish a camp or temporary shelter.

ENCASE.d: To enclose, as in a case.

ENCASH.d: To convert a financial instrument or funding source into cash.
ENCASH.e: Probably a back-formation from encashment, equal to en- + cash.

ENCORE.d: A brief extra performance, done after the main performance is complete.
ENCORE.e: Borrowed from French encore (“more, again”), and once used in this sense.

ENDEAR.d: To make (something) more precious or valuable.

ENDIAN.d: Preceded by a qualifying word: of a computer: storing multibyte numbers with the most significant byte at a particular memory address; for example, at the smallest address (big-endian) or the largest address (little-endian).
ENDIAN.e: From end + -ian (suffix meaning ‘one from, belonging to, like, or relating to’ forming nouns, and meaning ‘from, like, or related to’ forming adjectives), originally in the noun Big-Endian coined by the Anglo-Irish author Jonathan Swift (1667–1745) in his novel Gulliver’s Travels...

ENDIVE.d: A leafy salad vegetable, Cichorium endivia, which is often confused with common chicory (Cichorium intybus).
ENDIVE.e: From Middle French endive, from Medieval Latin endivia or Italian indivia or endivia, from Late Latin intibus.

ENDURE.d: To continue or carry on, despite obstacles or hardships; to persist.
ENDURE.e: From Middle English enduren, from Old French endurer, from Latin indūrō (“to make hard”). Displaced Old English drēogan, which survives dialectally as dree. Doublet of dure.

ENDURO.d: A motorcycle sport run on predominantly off-road courses, with many obstacles and challenges.

ENERGY.d: The impetus behind all motion and all activity.
ENERGY.e: From Middle French énergie, from Late Latin energia, from Ancient Greek ἐνέργεια (enérgeia, “activity”), from ἐνεργός (energós, “active”), from ἐν (en, “in”) + ἔργον (érgon, “work”). The sense in physics was coined by English polymath Thomas Young in 1802 in his lectures on Natur...

ENFOLD.d: To envelop and wrap up something.
ENFOLD.e: Alteration of earlier infold, from Middle English infolden, equivalent to en- + fold.

ENGAGE.e: From Middle English engagen, from Old French engagier (“to pledge, engage”), from Frankish *anwadjōn (“to pledge”), from Proto-Germanic *an-, *andi- + Proto-Germanic *wadjōną (“to pledge, secure”), from Proto-Germanic *wadją (“pledge, guarantee”), from Proto-Indo-European *wedʰ- ...

ENGINE.d: A large construction used in warfare, such as a battering ram, catapult etc.
ENGINE.e: From Middle English engyn, from Anglo-Norman engine, Old French engin (“skill, cleverness, war machine”), from Latin ingenium (“innate or natural quality, nature, genius, a genius, an invention, (in Late Latin) a war-engine, battering-ram”), related to ingignō (“to instil by birt...

ENGRAM.d: A postulated physical or biochemical change in neural tissue that represents a memory.
ENGRAM.e: Borrowed from German Engramm which was coined by German evolutionary biologist Richard Semon in 1904. First attested in English in 1921 (see quotation below). Ultimately from Ancient Greek ἐν (en, “in”) + γράμμα (grámma, “writing, picture”).

ENIGMA.d: Something or someone puzzling, mysterious or inexplicable.
ENIGMA.e: From Latin aenigma (“riddle”), being derived itself from the Ancient Greek verbal noun αἴνιγμα (aínigma, “dark saying, speaking in riddles”).

ENJOIN.d: To lay upon, as an order or command; to give an injunction to; to direct with authority; to order; to charge.
ENJOIN.e: From Middle English enjoinen, from Old French enjoindre (“to join with”), from Latin iniungo (“to attach”), a compound of in- (“into” “upon”) and iungo.

ENJOYS.d: Plural of ENJOY: To take pleasure in.

ENLACE.d: To bind or encircle with lace, or as with lace

ENLIST.d: To enter on a list; to enroll; to register.

ENMESH.d: To mesh; to tangle or interweave in such a manner as not to be easily separated, particularly in a mesh- or net-like manner.

ENMITY.d: The quality of being an enemy; hostile or unfriendly disposition.
ENMITY.e: From Middle English enemyte, from Old French enemisté, ennemistié, from Late Latin, Vulgar Latin *inimīcitās, *inimīcitātem, from Latin inimīcus (“enemy”); cognates: French inimitié, Portuguese inimizade, Spanish enemistad. Equivalent to enemy + -ity.

ENNEAD.e: From Ancient Greek ἐννεάς (enneás), ἐννεάδος (enneádos, “body of nine”) + -ad (suffix designating a unit); analysable as ennea- + -ad. The Greek words ἐννεάς and ἐννεάδος are derived from ἐννέᾰ (ennéă, “nine”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁néwn̥ (“nine”)) + -ᾰ́ς (-ắs, s...

ENOSIS.d: Any political movement aiming to incorporate Greek-populated areas currently outside Greece into Greece.

ENRAGE.e: From Old French enrager, enragier, from rage. Equivalent to en- + rage.

ENRICH.e: From Middle English enrichen, from Anglo-Norman enrichir and Old French enrichier. By surface analysis, en- + rich.

ENROBE.d: To invest or adorn with a robe or vestment; to attire.

ENSIGN.d: A badge of office, rank, or power.
ENSIGN.e: From Middle English ensigne, from Old French enseigne, from Latin īnsignia, nominative plural of īnsigne, meaning marked, distinguished. Doublet of insignia.

ENSOUL.d: To give a soul or place in the soul.

ENSURE.d: To make sure or certain of something (usually some future event or condition).
ENSURE.e: From Middle English ensuren, from Anglo-Norman enseurer, from Old French seur (“sure”). Doublet of insure.

ENTAIL.e: From Middle English entaillen, from Old French entaillier, entailler (“to notch”, literally “to cut in”); from prefix en- + tailler (“to cut”), from Late Latin taliare, from Latin talea. Compare late Latin feudum talliatum (“a fee entailed, i.e., curtailed or limited”).

ENTERS.d: Plural of ENTER: To come or go into.
ENTERS.e: From Old French entrer, from Latin intrāre.

ENTICE.d: To lure; to attract by arousing desire or hope.
ENTICE.e: From Middle English enticen, from Old French enticier (“to stir up or excite”), from a Vulgar Latin *intitiāre (“I set on fire”), from in- + titiō (“firebrand (tool)”), from Proto-Italic *tītjō (“heating”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *teih₁- (“to become hot, melt or to end...

ENTIRE.e: From Middle English entere, enter, borrowed from Anglo-Norman entier, from Latin integrum, accusative of integer (“whole”), from Proto-Italic *əntagros (“untouched”). Doublet of entier and integer.

ENTITY.d: That which has a distinct existence as an individual unit, often used for organizations which have no physical form.
ENTITY.e: From the Medieval Latin entitās, from ēns (“being”) (stem: ent-) + -tās (compare essentia), see there for more information.

ENTOMB.e: From Old French entomber (“deposit in a tomb”). Equivalent to en- + tomb.

ENTRAP.d: To catch in a trap or snare.
ENTRAP.e: From Middle French entrapper, entraper, from Old French entraper, antraper (“catch in a trap”), equivalent to en- + trap. Compare Middle English bitrappen, from Old English betræppan (“to catch in a trap, entrap”), from the same West Germanic source (see Modern English betrap).

ENVIED.d: Past tense of ENVY: Resentful desire of something possessed by another or others (but not limited to material possessions).
ENVIED.e: From Middle English envie, from Old French envie, from Latin invidia (“envy”), from invidere (“to look at with malice”), from in- (“on, upon”) + videre (“to look, see”). Doublet of envie. Cognate to Proto-Slavic *zavistь (“envy”).

ENVIER.d: Comparative form of ENVY: Resentful desire of something possessed by another or others (but not limited to material possessions).
ENVIER.e: From Middle English envie, from Old French envie, from Latin invidia (“envy”), from invidere (“to look at with malice”), from in- (“on, upon”) + videre (“to look, see”). Doublet of envie. Cognate to Proto-Slavic *zavistь (“envy”).

ENVIES.d: Plural of ENVY: Resentful desire of something possessed by another or others (but not limited to material possessions).
ENVIES.e: From Middle English envie, from Old French envie, from Latin invidia (“envy”), from invidere (“to look at with malice”), from in- (“on, upon”) + videre (“to look, see”). Doublet of envie. Cognate to Proto-Slavic *zavistь (“envy”).

ENWRAP.d: To wrap around, surround; to envelop.
ENWRAP.e: From Middle English enwrappen, inwrappen (“to wrap in”), equivalent to en- + wrap. Compare also Middle English inwlappen (See lap, “to enwrap”). More at en-, wrap. Cognate via Old French with envelop, envelope. Doublet of envelop.

ENZYME.d: A biomolecule that catalyses a biological chemical reaction: either a globular protein with this function or an RNA molecule with this function.
ENZYME.e: From German Enzym, coined 1878 by the German physiologist Wilhelm Kühne from Ancient Greek ἐν (en, “in”) + ζύμη (zúmē, “leaven”).

EOLITH.d: Crudely chopped flints, believed to be naturally produced by geological processes such as glaciation.

EPARCH.d: The governor or prefect of a province.
EPARCH.e: From Ancient Greek ἔπαρχος (éparkhos), from ἐπί (epí, “over”) + ἀρχός (arkhós, “ruler”).

EPHEBE.d: An 18- to 20-year-old man in ancient Greece undergoing military training.
EPHEBE.e: Via Latin ephēbus, from Ancient Greek ἔφηβος (éphēbos, “adolescent”), from ἐπί (epí, “early”) + ἥβη (hḗbē, “manhood”), late 19th c.

EPIMER.d: Any diastereoisomer that has the opposite configuration at only one of the stereogenic centres.

EPONYM.d: A person who gave or supposedly gave their name to a people, place, institution, etc.
EPONYM.e: From Latin eponymus, from Ancient Greek ἐπώνῠμος (epṓnŭmos), from ἐπί (epí, “upon, epi-”) + ὄνυμα (ónuma, “name”) + -ος (-os, suffix forming adjectives and nouns). Equivalent to epi- + -nym.

EQUALS.d: Plural of EQUAL: The same in quantity or value.

EQUATE.d: To consider equal or equivalent (to or with).
EQUATE.e: From Middle English equaten, from Latin aequātus, perfect passive participle of aequō, see -ate (verb-forming suffix).

EQUINE.d: Of or relating to a horse or horses.
EQUINE.e: Learned borrowing from Latin equīnus (“of or pertaining to horses”).

EQUITY.d: Fairness, impartiality, or justice as determined in light of "natural law" or "natural right".
EQUITY.e: From Middle English equitee, equytee, from Old French equité, from Latin aequitās (“uniformity; impartiality; fairness”).

ERASES.d: Plural of ERAS: plural of era

ERBIUM.d: A chemical element (symbol Er) with atomic number 68: a silvery-white metal, in nature always found in combination with other elements.
ERBIUM.e: Borrowed from New Latin erbium; itself from Swedish Ytterby (the name of the town where the element was first discovered) + -ium, coined by Swedish chemist and mineralogist Carl Gustaf Mosander in 1843. Doublet of terbium, ytterbium, and yttrium.

ERMINE.d: A weasel found in northern latitudes (Mustela erminea in Eurasia, Alaska, and the Arctic, Mustela haidarum in Haida Gwaii, Mustela richardsonii in the rest of North America); its dark brown fur turns white in winter, apart from the black tip of the tail.
ERMINE.e:
From Middle English ermine, ermin, ermyn, from Old French ermin, ermine, hermine.
There are two main theories for the origin of Old French ermine. Germanic origin is suggested via Old Dutch *harmino (“stoat skin”), from *harmo (“stoat, weasel”) (compare Dutch hermelijn and dialec...

EROTIC.d: Relating to or tending to arouse sexual desire or excitement.
EROTIC.e: From French érotique, from Ancient Greek ἐρωτικός (erōtikós, “related to love”), from ἔρως (érōs, “sexual love”).

ERRAND.d: A journey undertaken to accomplish some task.
ERRAND.e: From Middle English erande, erende, from Old English ǣrende, from Proto-West Germanic *ārundī (“message, errand”).

ERRANT.d: Straying from the proper course or standard, or outside established limits.
ERRANT.e:
From Middle English erraunt [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman erraunt, from Old French errant, the present participle of errer (“to walk (to); to wander (to); (figuratively) to travel, voyage”), and then:
* from Vulgar Latin iterāre (compare Late Latin itinerāre, itinerāri (“t...

ERRATA.e: Borrowed from Latin errāta (“mistaken things, mistakes”), neuter plural of errātus (“mistaken”).

ERRING.d: present participle and gerund of err

ERRORS.e: From Latin error, from errāre (to wander).

ERSATZ.d: inauthentic or inadequate substitute or imitation
ERSATZ.e: Borrowed from German Ersatz (“replacement”); and from the German ersetzen (“to replace”, verb).

ERYNGO.d: The root of sea holly, Eryngium maritimum, formerly candied and taken as confectionery and held to have aphrodisiac properties.
ERYNGO.e: Ultimately from Latin ēryngion, from Ancient Greek ἠρύγγιον (ērúngion), from ἤρυγγος (ḗrungos).

ESCAPE.d: To get free; to free oneself.
ESCAPE.e: From Middle English escapen, from Anglo-Norman and Old Northern French escaper ( = Old French eschaper, modern French échapper), from Vulgar Latin *excappāre (“to escape a garment, get out of one's clothing”, literally “to free oneself from one's cape”), from Latin ex- (“out”) + ...

ESCARP.e: From French escarpe, from Proto-Germanic *skarpaz. Doublet of scarp.

ESCHEW.d: To avoid; to shun, to shy away from.
ESCHEW.e:
From Middle English eschewen, from Anglo-Norman eschiver, (third-person present eschiu), from Frankish *skiuhijan (“to dread, shun, avoid”); thus a doublet of skew.
For the pronunciation with /ʃ/, compare the development of marshal from Middle English marschal (/marsˈt͡ʃaːl/) or ...

ESCORT.d: A group of people or vehicles, generally armed, who go with a person or people of importance to safeguard them on a journey or mission.
ESCORT.e: Borrowed from French escorte, itself borrowed from Italian scorta.

ESCROW.d: A contractual arrangement whereby money or assets are held in trust by an independent agent by the agreement of the parties, which can only be released to the relevant party once certain contractual conditions have been fulfilled.
ESCROW.e: Learned borrowing from Law French escrowe, from Old French escroe (“register, note; bit of parchment; piece”), from Frankish *skrōda (“piece”), from Proto-Germanic *skraudō, derivative of Proto-Germanic *skraudaną (“to shred”). Doublet of scrow and shred and partially scroll.

ESCUDO.d: The state currency formerly used in Portugal, divided into 100 centavos. The symbol is $ which is positioned between the escudos & centavos, 2$50.
ESCUDO.e: From Portuguese escudo (“shield”). Doublet of scutum, scute, écu, and scudo.

ESPIAL.d: An act of noticing or observing.
ESPIAL.e: From Middle English espiaille, from Old French espier (“to watch”).

ESPIED.d: Past tense of ESPY: To find out or observe (someone or something, especially if not easy to see) by spying or looking; to catch sight of; to see; to spot.
ESPIED.e: From Middle English aspien, espien (“to make covert observations of (a person or place) with hostile intent, to spy on; to seek to discover by spying; to act as a spy; to catch sight of, see; to look over, observe; to wait in ambush, to ambush; to plot against; to look for, seek ...

ESPIER.d: Comparative form of ESPY: To find out or observe (someone or something, especially if not easy to see) by spying or looking; to catch sight of; to see; to spot.
ESPIER.e: From Middle English aspien, espien (“to make covert observations of (a person or place) with hostile intent, to spy on; to seek to discover by spying; to act as a spy; to catch sight of, see; to look over, observe; to wait in ambush, to ambush; to plot against; to look for, seek ...

ESPIES.d: Plural of ESPY: To find out or observe (someone or something, especially if not easy to see) by spying or looking; to catch sight of; to see; to spot.
ESPIES.e: From Middle English aspien, espien (“to make covert observations of (a person or place) with hostile intent, to spy on; to seek to discover by spying; to act as a spy; to catch sight of, see; to look over, observe; to wait in ambush, to ambush; to plot against; to look for, seek ...

ESPRIT.e: Borrowed from French esprit (“spirit”). Doublet of spirit, spiritus, spirytus, sprite, and spright, possibly also spree.

ESTATE.d: The collective property and liabilities of someone, especially a deceased person.
ESTATE.e: From Middle English estat, from Anglo-Norman estat and Old French estat (French: état), from Latin status. Doublet of state and status.

ESTEEM.d: Assessment, estimation, or regard; especially; favourable estimation or regard.
ESTEEM.e:
First at end of 16th century; borrowed from Middle French estimer, borrowed from Latin aestimō.
See estimate and aim, an older word, partly a doublet.

ETALON.d: An optical device containing parallel mirrors, used as a narrow band filter, often in laser design.

ETCHED.d: Past tense of ETCH: To cut into a surface with an acid or other corrosive substance in order to make a pattern. Best known as a technique for creating printing plates, but also used for decoration on metal, and, in modern industry, to make circuit boards.
ETCHED.e: From Dutch etsen (“to etch”), from German ätzen (“to etch”), from Old High German azzon (“to cause to bite or feed”), from Proto-Germanic *atjaną, causative of *etaną (“to eat”) (whence also English eat).

ETCHES.d: Plural of ETCH: To cut into a surface with an acid or other corrosive substance in order to make a pattern. Best known as a technique for creating printing plates, but also used for decoration on metal, and, in modern industry, to make circuit boards.
ETCHES.e: From Dutch etsen (“to etch”), from German ätzen (“to etch”), from Old High German azzon (“to cause to bite or feed”), from Proto-Germanic *atjaną, causative of *etaną (“to eat”) (whence also English eat).

ETHANE.d: An aliphatic hydrocarbon, C₂H₆, gaseous at normal temperatures and pressures, being a constituent of natural gas.

ETHENE.d: The organic chemical compound ethylene. The simplest alkene, a colorless gaseous (at room temperature and pressure) hydrocarbon with the chemical formula C₂H₄

ETHNIC.d: Of or relating to a group of people having common racial, ancestral, national, religious or cultural origins.
ETHNIC.e: From Middle English ethnik, from Latin ethnicus ("pagan", "heathen"), from Ancient Greek ἐθνικός (ethnikós, “of or for a nation, heathen”), from ἔθνος (éthnos, “a company", later "a people or nation, heathens”).

ETHOXY.d: The univalent radical CH₃CH₂O- derived from ethanol

ETYMON.d: The original or earlier form of an inherited or borrowed word, affix, or morpheme either from an earlier period in a language's development, from an ancestral language, or from a foreign language.
ETYMON.e: From Ancient Greek ἔτυμον (étumon, “the true sense of a word according to its origin”), from ἔτυμος (étumos, “true, real, actual”).

EUCHRE.d: A trump card game played by four players in two partnerships with a reduced deck of 24 cards.
EUCHRE.e: Possibly from German Juckerspiel, name of an eighteenth-century Alsatian card game, itself apparently a compound of Jucker (“joker?”, may be dialectal) + Spiel (“game”). Likely a doublet of joker.

EULOGY.d: An oration to honor a deceased person, usually at a funeral.
EULOGY.e: From Middle English wloge (“commendation of the virtues of a deceased person”), from Latin eulogium, apparently from a confusion between ēlogium (whence English elogium, elogy) and eulogia (from Ancient Greek εὐλογία (eulogía, “praise”), whence English eulogia); equivalent to eu-...

EUNUCH.e: From Middle English eunuk, from Middle French eunuque, from Latin eunūchus, from Ancient Greek εὐνοῦχος (eunoûkhos), from εὐνή (eunḗ, “bed”) + ἔχω (ékhō, “I have, keep”). Originally probably used to refer to a bed chamber attendant.

EUREKA.d: An exclamation indicating a sudden discovery.
EUREKA.e: From Ancient Greek εὕρηκα (heúrēka, “I have found”), perfect active indicative first person singular of εὑρίσκω (heurískō, “to find”). Archimedes supposedly exclaimed this when he figured out how to determine the density of an object. First use appears c. 1603 in a text by Philem...

EVENTS.d: Plural of EVENT: Something that happens; an occasion.
EVENTS.e: From Latin ēventus, from ēvenīre (to happen).

EVINCE.d: To show or demonstrate clearly; to manifest.
EVINCE.e: From Middle French évincer, from Latin ēvincō (“conquer entirely, prevail over; prove exhaustively”), from ē- (short form of ex- (intensive prefix)) + vincō (“conquer”). Doublet of evict.

EVOLVE.d: To move (something) in regular procession through a system.
EVOLVE.e: Borrowed from Latin ēvolvō (“unroll, unfold”), from ē- (“out of”) (short form of ex) + volvō (“roll”).

EVZONE.d: A member of the Greek presidential guard.
EVZONE.e: From Greek εύζωνος (évzonos), from Ancient Greek εὔζωνος (eúzōnos, “girt for battle”), from εὖ (eû, “well”) + ζώνη (zṓnē, “girdle”).

EXABIT.d: One quintillion (10¹⁸, or 1,000,000,000,000,000,000) bits or 1,000 petabits.

EXACTS.e: From Latin exactus, from exigere (to demand).

EXARCH.d: In the Byzantine Empire, a governor of a distant province.

EXCEED.e: From Middle English exceden, from Old French exceder, from Latin excēdō (“to go beyond”), from ex- (“out, forth”) with cēdō (“to go”); see cede and compare accede etc. Partly displaced native Old English ofersteppan, whence Modern English overstep.

EXCEPT.d: To exclude; to specify as being an exception.
EXCEPT.e: Borrowed from Middle French excepter, from Latin exceptus.

EXCESS.d: The state of surpassing or going beyond a limit; the state of being beyond sufficiency, necessity, or duty; more than what is usual or proper.
EXCESS.e: From Middle English exces (“excess, ecstasy”), from Old French exces, from Latin excessus (“a going out, loss of self-possession”), from excedere, excessum (“to go out, go beyond”). See exceed.

EXCISE.d: A tax charged on goods produced within the country (as opposed to customs duties, charged on goods from outside the country).
EXCISE.e: From Middle Dutch excijs, altered under the influence of Latin excisus (“cut out, removed”), from earlier accijs (“tax”), from Old French acceis (“tax, assessment”) (whence modern French accise), from Vulgar Latin *accensum, ultimately from Latin ad + census (“tax, census”).

EXCITE.d: To stir the emotions of; to cause to feel excitement.
EXCITE.e: From Middle English exciten, from Old French exciter, from Latin excitō (“to call out, call forth, arouse, wake up, stimulate”), frequentative of excieō (“to call out, arouse, excite”), from ex (“out”) + cieō (“to call, summon”). See cite and compare to accite, concite, incite.

EXCUSE.d: To forgive; to pardon; to overlook.
EXCUSE.e: From Middle English excusen (verb) and excuse (noun), borrowed from Old French escuser (verb) and excuse (noun), from Latin excūsō, excūsāre (“to excuse, allege in excuse, literally, free from a charge”), from ex (“out”) + causa (“a charge”); see cause, accuse and recuse. Displac...

EXEMPT.d: Free from a duty, obligation, rule, law, etc.
EXEMPT.e: From Middle French exempt, from Latin exemptus, past participle of eximō.

EXEQUY.e: A back-formation from exequies, from Middle English exequies, from Old French exequies, from Latin exsequiās, accusative of exsequiae (“a funeral, seeing-off procession”).

EXEUNT.d: A stage direction for more than one actor to leave the stage.
EXEUNT.e: Borrowed from Latin exeunt (“they leave”), the third-person plural present active indicative of exeō (“leave”).

EXHALE.d: To expel air from the lungs through the nose or mouth by action of the diaphragm, to breathe out.
EXHALE.e: From Middle French exhaler, from Latin exhalare, from ex (“out”) + halare (“to breathe”).

EXHORT.e: From Middle English exorten, from Old French exhorter, from Latin exhortārī (“to encourage”), from ex- (“out of, from”) + hortārī (“to incite, spur”).

EXHUME.d: To dig out of the ground; to take out of a place of burial; to disinter.
EXHUME.e: From Medieval Latin exhumō, from Latin ex- + humō (“to bury”).

EXISTS.d: Plural of EXIST: To have being; to live.

EXODUS.d: The departure of the Hebrew slaves from Egypt under the leadership of Moses.
EXODUS.e: From Latin Exodus, from Ancient Greek ἔξοδος (éxodos), from ἐξ (ex, “out of”) + ὁδός (hodós, “way”).

EXOPOD.d: The outer ramus of a biramous limb of a crustacean.

EXOTIC.d: Foreign, especially in an exciting way.
EXOTIC.e: Borrowed from Middle French exotique, from Latin exōticus, from Ancient Greek ἐξωτικός (exōtikós, “foreign”, literally “from the outside”), from ἐξω- (exō-, “outside”), from ἐξ (ex, “out of”).

EXPAND.d: To change (something) from a smaller form or size to a larger one; to spread out or lay open.
EXPAND.e: Recorded in Middle English since 1422 (as expanden, expaunden), from Anglo-Norman espaundre, from Latin expandere (“to spread out”), itself from ex- (“out, outwards”) + pandō (“to spread”). Doublet of spawn.

EXPECT.d: To predict or believe that something will happen
EXPECT.e: From Latin expectāre, infinitive form of exspectō (“look out for, await, expect”), from ex (“out”) + spectō (“look at”), frequentative of speciō (“see”).

EXPEND.e: Borrowed from Latin expendō (“I weigh; I pay out”). Doublet of spend.

EXPERT.e: Inherited from Middle English [Term?], derived from Old French [Term?] (“experienced”), derived from Latin expertus, perfect active participle of experior (“to try”).

EXPIRE.e: From Middle English expire, from Middle French expirer, from Latin expīrō, exspīrō, from ex- (“out”) + spīrō (“breathe, be alive”).

EXPORT.d: Of or relating to exportation or exports.

EXPOSE.d: To reveal, uncover, make visible, bring to light, introduce (to).
EXPOSE.e: Borrowed from Middle French exposer (“to lay open, set forth”), from Latin expōnō (“set forth”), with contamination from poser (“to lay, place”). Doublet of expone and expound (via Old French espondre (“to set forth, explain”)), from the same Latin term.

EXSERT.d: To thrust out; to cause to protrude.
EXSERT.e: From Latin exsertus, past participle of exserō (“to stretch out or forth”). See exert.

EXTEND.e: From Middle English extenden, from Anglo-Norman extendre, estendre, from Latin extendō (“I stretch out”).

EXTENT.d: A range of values or locations.
EXTENT.e: From Middle English extente, from Anglo-Norman extente and Old French estente (“valuation of land, stretch of land”), from estendre, extendre (“extend”) (or from Latin extentus), from Latin extendere (See extend.)

EXTORT.d: To take or seize from an unwilling person by physical force, menace, duress, torture, or any undue or illegal exercise of power or ingenuity.
EXTORT.e: Borrowed from Latin extortus, past participle of extorquere (“to twist or wrench out, to extort”); from ex (“out”) + -tort, from torqueō (“twist, turn”).

EXTRAS.d: Plural of EXTRA: Additional; more than usual.

EXUVIA.e: Back-formation from the plurale tantum exuviae (“the skin of an animal sloughed off”), from exuō (“to take off”). See also exuvium.

EYEFUL.d: A full or complete view; a good look.

EYEING.d: Present participle of EYE: An organ through which animals see (“perceive surroundings via light”).
EYEING.e:
From Middle English eye, yë, eyghe, from Old English ēage (“eye”), from Proto-West Germanic *augā, from Proto-Germanic *augô (“eye”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃okʷ-, *h₃ekʷ- (“eye; to see”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots ee, eh (“eye”), North Frisian Oog, uug (“eye”), Saterland F...

EYELET.d: An object that consists of a rim and small hole or perforation to receive a cord or fastener, as in garments, sails, etc. An eyelet may reinforce a hole.
EYELET.e: From Middle English oylet, from Old French oillet, equivalent to Old French oil (“eye”) + -et (diminutive suffix). Spelling as eye + -let is due to folk etymology.

EYELID.d: A thin skin membrane that covers and moves over an eye.
EYELID.e: From Middle English eyelidd, eye-led, eiȝelid, eghe-lydd, yȝe-lydd, ehlid, yhelidd, from an unrecorded Old English *ēaghlid (“eyelid”), from Proto-West Germanic *augahlid (“eyelid”), equivalent to eye + lid. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Oogenlid (“eyelid”), West Frisian eachlid...

FABRIC.e: Borrowed from French fabrique, from Latin fabrica (“a workshop, art, trade, product of art, structure, fabric”), from faber (“artisan, workman”). Doublet of fabrica, borrowed from Latin, and forge, borrowed from Old French.

FACADE.d: The face of a building, especially the front view or elevation.
FACADE.e: Borrowed from French façade, from Italian facciata, a derivation of faccia (“front”), from Latin faciēs (“face”); compare face.

FACIAL.e: Early 17th century, borrowed from Medieval Latin faciālis (“face-to-face, direct, open”), from faciēs (“form, configuration, figure; face, visage, countenance”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix).

FACILE.e: Borrowed from Middle French facile, from Latin facilis (“easy to do, easy, doable”), from Latin facere (“to do, make”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁- (“to do, put”) Compare Spanish fácil (“easy”). First use appears c. 1484 in a translation by William Caxton.

FACING.d: Positioned so as to face (in a particular direction)

FACTOR.d: A doer, maker; a person who does things for another person or organization.
FACTOR.e: From Middle French facteur, from Latin factor (“a doer, maker, performer”), from factus (“done or made”), perfect passive participle of faciō (“do, make”).

FACULA.d: A bright spot or patch between sunspots.

FADING.d: present participle and gerund of fade.

FAERIE.e: A deliberately archaic spelling of fairy (attested since the 1300s in spellings like fairye, fayre), based on Old French faerie, used in 1590 by Edmund Spenser in The Faerie Queene.

FAGGED.d: Past tense of FAG: In textile inspections, a rough or coarse defect in the woven fabric.
FAGGED.e: Probably from fag end (“remnant”), from Middle English fagge (“flap”).

FAGGER.d: Comparative form of FAG: In textile inspections, a rough or coarse defect in the woven fabric.
FAGGER.e: Probably from fag end (“remnant”), from Middle English fagge (“flap”).

FAGGOT.d: A bundle of sticks or brushwood intended to be used for fuel tied together for carrying. (Some sources specify that a faggot is tied with two bands or withes, whereas a bavin is tied with just one.)
FAGGOT.e: From Middle English fagot, from Old French fagot (“bundle of sticks”), of uncertain origin. Unlikely from Old Occitan fagot or Italian fagotto, as these appear later than the Old French term. Compare also Italian fangotto and Spanish fajo (“bundle, wad”). Perhaps from a diminutiv...

FAILED.d: Past tense of FAIL: To be unsuccessful.
FAILED.e:
Inherited from Middle English failen, borrowed from Old French falir, from Vulgar Latin *fallire, alteration of Latin fallere (“to deceive, disappoint”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰāl- (“to lie, deceive”) or Proto-Indo-European *sgʷʰh₂el- (“to stumble”).
Compare Alemannic German...

FAILLE.d: A fabric woven from silk, cotton, or rayon with slight ribs.

FAITHS.d: Plural of FAITH: Complete trust; religious belief.
FAITHS.e: From Old French feid, from Latin fidēs.

FAJITA.d: A Tex-Mex dish of strips of spicy marinated meat and/or vegetables in a soft flour tortilla, often served with salad or a savoury filling.
FAJITA.e: From American Spanish fajita, diminutive of faja (“strip, band”).

FAKING.d: Present participle of FAKE: Not real; false, fraudulent.
FAKING.e: The origin is not known with certainty, although first attested in 1775 C.E. in British criminals' slang. It is probably from feak, feague (“to give a better appearance through artificial means, spruce up, embellish”), itself from German Low German fegen, from Middle Low German v...

FALCON.d: Any bird of the genus Falco, all of which are birds of prey.
FALCON.e:
From Middle English faucoun, falcon, faulcon, from Old French falcun, from Late Latin falcō (“falcon”), of Germanic origin, probably via Frankish *falkō (“falcon, hawk”), from Proto-Germanic *falkô (“falcon”), from Proto-Indo-European *pol̑- (“pale”), from *pel- (“fallow”).
Cogna...

FALLOW.d: Ground ploughed and harrowed but left unseeded for one year.
FALLOW.e:
[Alt: A photograph of a ploughed field.]
From Middle English falwe, from Old English fealh, fealg (“fallow land”), from Proto-West Germanic *falgu (compare Saterland Frisian Falge, West Frisian falig, felling, Dutch valg, German Felge), from Proto-Indo-European *polḱéh₂ (“arable ...

FALTER.e: From Middle English falteren (“to stagger; be unsteady, tremble, quiver; to stammer; be entangled, get caught”), further origin unknown. Probably from a North Germanic source such as Old Norse faltrask (“to hesitate, be puzzled, be encumbered”). May also be a frequentative of fol...

FAMILY.d: A group of people who are closely related to one another (by blood, marriage or adoption); kin; in particular, a set of parents and their children; an immediate family.
FAMILY.e: From Late Middle English famylye, from Latin familia (“a household”). Displaced native Old English hīred. Doublet of familia.

FAMINE.d: Extreme shortage of food in a region.
FAMINE.e: Borrowed from Middle French famine, itself from the root of Latin fames. Cognate with Spanish hambruna (“famine”).

FAMING.d: Present participle of FAME: Something said or reported; gossip, rumour.
FAMING.e: From Middle English fame, from Old French fame (“celebrity, renown”), itself borrowed from Latin fāma (“talk, rumor, report, reputation”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰéh₂-meh₂, from *bʰeh₂- (“to speak, say, tell”). Cognate with Ancient Greek φήμη (phḗmē, “talk”). Related also to ...

FAMISH.d: To starve (to death); to kill or destroy with hunger.
FAMISH.e: From Middle English famisshe, from famen (“starve”), from Old French afamer, ultimately from Latin famēs (“hunger”). Compare affamish, famine. Cognate with Spanish hambre (“hunger”).

FAMOUS.e: From Middle English famous, from Anglo-Norman famous, from Latin fāmōsus, equivalent to fame + -ous. Displaced native Old English hlīsful.

FANBOY.d: A male fan who is obsessive about a particular subject (especially, something or someone in popular entertainment media).

FANDOM.d: The fans of a sport, activity, work, person etc., taken as a group.

FANGED.d: Past tense of FANG: A long, pointed canine tooth used for biting and tearing flesh.
FANGED.e: From an abbreviation of fangtooth, from Middle English *fangtooth, *fengtooth, from Old English fengtōþ (“canine tooth”, literally “snag-tooth, catch-tooth”). Cognate with German Fangzahn (“fang”, literally “catch-tooth”) and Dutch vangtand.

FANNED.d: Past tense of FAN: A hand-held device consisting of concertinaed material, or slats of material, gathered together at one end, that may be opened out into the shape of a sector of a circle and waved back and forth in order to move air towards oneself and cool oneself.
FANNED.e:
Inherited from Middle English fan, inherited from Old English fann (“a winnowing, fan”), derived from Latin vannus (“fan for winnowing grain”), derived from Proto-Indo-European *h₂weh₁- (“to blow”).
Cognates
*Latin ventus (“wind”)
*Dutch wan (“winnowing basket”)
*German Wanne (“w...

FANOUT.d: The degree to which something fans out, or splits into separate sections.
FANOUT.e: From fan + out, from the phrasal verb.

FARDEL.d: A fourth part: a quarter of anything.
FARDEL.e: A clipped form of Middle English ferthendel (literally “fourth part”), equivalent to fourth + deal. Cognate with Dutch vierendeel (“a fourth part, quarter”), German Viertel (“a quarter, fourth”), Danish fjerdedel (“a quarter”), Swedish fjärdedel (“a fourth, quarter”).

FARINA.d: A fine flour or meal made from cereal grains or from the starch or fecula of vegetables, extracted by various processes, and used in cookery.
FARINA.e: Borrowed from Latin farīna (“flour, meal”), from far (“kind of grain”).

FARING.d: Present participle of FARE: A going; journey; travel; voyage; course; passage.
FARING.e: From Middle English fare, from a merger of Old English fær (“journey, road”) and faru (“journey, companions, baggage”), from Proto-Germanic *farą and *farō (“journey, fare”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“a going, passage”).

FARMED.d: Past tense of FARM: A place where agricultural and similar activities take place, especially the growing of crops or the raising of livestock.
FARMED.e: Inherited from Middle English ferme, farme (“rent, revenue, produce, factor, stewardship, meal, feast”), influenced by Anglo-Norman ferme (“rent, lease, farm”), from Medieval Latin ferma, firma. There is debate as to whether Medieval Latin acquires this term from Old English feor...

FAROFA.d: A toasted manioc flour used in Brazilian cookery, typically as an accompaniment to a main meal.
FAROFA.e: From Portuguese farofa, perhaps from Kimbundu falofa or from Latin far (“a type of hulled wheat”) + offa (“chunk; dumpling”).

FARROW.e:
From Middle English *farow, *fargh (found only in the plural faren), from Old English fearh (“piglet”), from Proto-West Germanic *farh, from Proto-Germanic *farhaz, from Proto-Indo-European *pórḱos, from *perḱ- (“to dig”).
See also Old High German farah, Middle Irish orc (“piglet...

FARTED.d: Past tense of FART: To emit digestive gases from the anus; to flatulate.
FARTED.e:
From Middle English ferten, farten, from Old English *feortan, from Proto-West Germanic *fertan, from Proto-Germanic *fertaną, from Proto-Indo-European *perd-.
The noun is from Middle English fert, fart, from the verb.

FASCIA.d: A wide band of material covering the ends of roof rafters, sometimes supporting a gutter in steep-slope roofing, but typically it is a border or trim in low-slope roofing.
FASCIA.e: Borrowed from Latin fascia (“a band, bandage, swathe”). Related to fascēs (“bundle of rods containing an axe with the blade projecting”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰask- (“bundle, band”). Cognate with fajita, fess, and fascism.

FASHED.d: Past tense of FASH: To worry; to bother, annoy.
FASHED.e: From early modern French fascher (now fâcher), from Latin fastus (“disdain”).

FASHES.d: Plural of FASH: To worry; to bother, annoy.
FASHES.e: From early modern French fascher (now fâcher), from Latin fastus (“disdain”).

FASTED.d: Past tense of FAST: Firmly or securely fixed in place; stable.
FASTED.e:
From Middle English fast, fest, from Old English fæst (“firm, secure”), from Proto-West Germanic *fast, from Proto-Germanic *fastuz; see it for cognates and further etymology.
The development of “rapid” from an original sense of “secure” apparently happened first in the adverb an...

FASTEN.d: To attach or connect in a secure manner.
FASTEN.e: From Middle English fastenen, from Old English fæstnian, from Proto-West Germanic *fastinōn (“to secure, fasten”). Equivalent to fast + -en.

FATHER.d: A male parent, especially of a human; a male who parents a child (which he has sired, adopted, fostered, taken as his own, etc.).
FATHER.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *peh₂-?
Proto-Indo-European *-tḗr
Proto-Indo-European *ph₂tḗr
Proto-Germanic *fadēr
Proto-West Germanic *fader
Old English fæder
Middle English fader
English father
Inherited from Middle English fader, from Old English fæder, from Proto-West Ger...

FATHOM.d: A man's armspan, generally reckoned to be six feet (about 1.8 metres). Later used to measure the depth of water, but now generally replaced by the metre outside American usage.
FATHOM.e: From Middle English fathome, fadom, fadme (“unit of length of about six feet; depth of six feet for nautical soundings; (loosely) cubit; ell”) [and other forms], from Old English fæþm, fæþme (“encircling or outstretched arms, bosom, embrace; envelopment; control, grasp, power; fa...

FATING.d: Present participle of FATE: The presumed cause, force, principle, or divine will that predetermines events.
FATING.e: From Middle English fate, from Latin fāta (“prediction”), plural of fātum, from fātus (“spoken”), from for (“to speak”). In this sense, displaced native Old English wyrd, whence Modern English weird.

FATTED.d: Past tense of FAT: Carrying more fat than usual on one's body; plump; not lean or thin.
FATTED.e: From Middle English fat, from Old English fǣtt (“fatted, fat”), from Proto-West Germanic *faitid (“fatted”), originally the past participle of the verb *faitijan (“to make fat”), from *fait (“fat”).

FATTEN.d: To cause (a person or animal) to be fat or fatter.

FATTER.d: Comparative form of FAT: Carrying more fat than usual on one's body; plump; not lean or thin.
FATTER.e: From Middle English fat, from Old English fǣtt (“fatted, fat”), from Proto-West Germanic *faitid (“fatted”), originally the past participle of the verb *faitijan (“to make fat”), from *fait (“fat”).

FAULTS.d: Plural of FAULT: A defect; responsibility for a mistake.
FAULTS.e: From Old French faute, from Latin fallere (to deceive).

FAULTY.d: Having or displaying faults; not perfect; not adequate or acceptable.

FAVELA.d: A slum or shantytown, especially in Brazil.
FAVELA.e: Unadapted borrowing from Brazilian Portuguese favela.

FAWNED.d: Past tense of FAWN: A young deer.
FAWNED.e: From Middle English fawne, fowne, foun, from Old French faon, foon, feon, from Vulgar Latin *fētōnem, from Latin fētus (“offspring, young”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁(y)- (“to suckle, nurse”). Displaced native Old English hindċealf (literally “deer calf”). Doublet of fetus.

FAXING.d: Present participle of FAX: The hair of the head.
FAXING.e: From Middle English fax, from Old English feax (“hair, head of hair”), from Proto-West Germanic *fahs, from Proto-Germanic *fahsą (“hair, mane”), from Proto-Indo-European *poḱsom (“hair”, literally “that which is combed, shorn, or plucked”), from Proto-Indo-European *peḱ- (“to co...

FAYING.d: Present participle of FAY: To fit.
FAYING.e: Inherited from Middle English feyen, feien, from Old English fēġan (“to join, unite”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōgijan, from Proto-Germanic *fōgijaną (“to join”), from *fōgō (“joint, slot”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ḱ- (“to fasten, place”). Akin to Saterland Frisian fougje...

FAZING.d: Present participle of FAZE: To frighten or cause hesitation; to daunt, put off (usually used in the negative); to disconcert, to perturb.
FAZING.e: From English dialectal (Kentish) feeze, feese (“to alarm, discomfit, frighten”), from Middle English fēsen (“to chase, drive away; put to flight; discomfit, frighten, terrify”), from Old English fēsan, fȳsan (“to send forth; to hasten, impel, stimulate; to banish, drive away, put...

FEALTY.d: Fidelity to one's lord or master; the feudal obligation by which the tenant or vassal was bound to be faithful to his lord.
FEALTY.e: From Middle English feaute, feute, from Anglo-Norman fëauté, fëuté, from Latin fidēlitās (“faithfulness”; “homage, fealty” in Medieval Latin), from fidēlis (“faithful”) + -tās (noun suffix); the modern form (for expected *feauty /ˈfjuːti/) is due to learned influence. Equivalent ...

FEARED.d: Past tense of FEAR: A strong, unpleasant emotion or feeling caused by actual or perceived danger or threat.
FEARED.e: From Middle English feer, fere, fer, from Old English fǣr, ġefǣr (“calamity, sudden danger, peril, sudden attack, terrible sight”), from Proto-Germanic *fērō, *fērą (“danger”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“to go through, carry forth, try”). Cognate with Dutch gevaar (“danger,...

FEASTS.d: Plural of FEAST: A large meal; a celebration.
FEASTS.e: From Old French feste, from Latin festa.

FECUND.d: Highly fertile; able to produce offspring.
FECUND.e: From Middle French fécond, from Latin fēcundus (“fertile”), which is related to fētus and fēmina (“woman”).

FEDORA.d: A felt hat with a fairly low, creased crown with a brim that can be turned up or down.
FEDORA.e: From a 19th-century play by Victorien Sardou titled Fédora. The heroine, Fédora Romazov, wore a center-creased, soft brimmed hat. The name comes from the Russian Федо́ра (Fedóra), feminine form of Фёдор (Fjódor), from Ancient Greek Θεόδωρος (Theódōros, “gift of god”), derived fro...

FEEBLE.e: From Middle English feble, from Anglo-Norman feble (“weak, feeble”) (compare French faible), from Latin flēbilis (“tearful, mournful, lamentable”) by dissimilation, from fleō (“I weep, cry”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleh₁-. Doublet of foible.

FEEDED.d: Past tense of FEED: To give (someone or something) food to eat.
FEEDED.e: From Middle English feden, from Old English fēdan (“to feed”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōdijan, from Proto-Germanic *fōdijaną (“to feed”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to guard, graze, feed”). Cognate with West Frisian fiede (“to nourish, feed”), Dutch voeden (“to feed”), ...

FEEING.d: Present participle of FEE: An amount charged for a privilege.
FEEING.e: From Middle English fee, fe, feh, feoh, from Old English feoh (“cattle, property, wealth, money, payment, tribute, fee”) with contamination from Old French fieu, fief (from Medieval Latin fevum, a variant of feudum (see feud), from Frankish *fehu (“cattle, livestock”); whence fie...

FEIJOA.d: A South American evergreen shrub, Acca sellowiana (syn. Feijoa sellowiana).
FEIJOA.e: From the New Latin former genus name Feijoa, which was named after Portuguese botanist João da Silva Feijó by the German botanist Otto Karl Berg.

FEISTY.e: 1896, American, feist (“small, aggressive dog”) + -y; the term feist (now rare) itself originally meant “stink”, and earlier “fart”, from Middle English, from Old English, from Proto-Germanic, presumably from Proto-Indo-European – see feist for details.

FELINE.e: Borrowed from Latin fēlīnus, from fēlēs (“wildcat, marten”).

FELLAH.d: A peasant, farmer or agricultural laborer in the Middle East and North Africa.
FELLAH.e: From Arabic فَلَّاح (fallāḥ, “peasant”), from Classical Syriac ܦܠܚܐ (“worker; peasant”). Attested since 1743.

FELLED.d: Past tense of FELL: To make something fall; especially to chop down a tree.
FELLED.e: From Middle English fellen, from Old English fellan, fiellan (“to cause to fall, strike down, fell, cut down, throw down, defeat, destroy, kill, tumble, cause to stumble”), from Proto-West Germanic *fallijan, from Proto-Germanic *fallijaną (“to fell, to cause to fall”), causative...

FELLOW.e: From Middle English felowe, Early Middle English felage (“companion, good friend”) from Old English fēolaga, from Old Norse félagi, derived from félag (“joint venture; partnership”, literally “a laying together of property”), from fé (“livestock, property; money”) (ultimately fro...

FELONY.d: A serious criminal offense, which, under United States federal law, is punishable by a term of imprisonment of not less than one year or by the death penalty in the most serious offenses.
FELONY.e: From Middle English felony, felonie, from Old French felonie (“evil, immoral deed”), from felon (“evildoer”). Ultimately of Proto-Germanic origin. More at felon. By surface analysis, felon + -y.

FELSIC.d: Enriched in minerals predominantly composed of the lighter elements such as silicon, oxygen, aluminium, sodium, and potassium.

FELTED.d: Past tense of FELT: A cloth or stuff made of matted fibres of wool, or wool and fur, fulled or wrought into a compact substance by rolling and pressure, with lees or size, without spinning or weaving.
FELTED.e: From Middle English felt, from Old English felt, from Proto-West Germanic *felt (compare Dutch vilt, German Filz, Danish filt, French feutre), from Proto-Indo-European *pilto, *pilso 'felt' (compare Latin pilleus (“felt”, adjective), Old Church Slavonic плъсть (plŭstĭ), Albanian ...

FEMALE.d: Belonging to the sex which typically produces eggs (ova), or to the gender which is typically associated with it.
FEMALE.e: From Middle English female, an alteration of Middle English femele, from Old French femele, femelle (“female”), from Medieval Latin fēmella (“a female”), from Latin fēmella (“a girl, a young female, a young woman”), diminutive of fēmina (“a woman”). The English spelling and pronu...

FENDED.d: Past tense of FEND: To take care of oneself; to take responsibility for one's own well-being.
FENDED.e: From Middle English fenden (“defend, fight, prevent”), shortening of defenden (“defend”), from Old French deffendre (Modern French défendre), from Latin dēfendō (“to ward off”), from dē- + *fendō (“hit, thrust”), from Proto-Italic *fendō, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰen- (“strike...

FENNEC.d: A small fox of the species Vulpes zerda, found in the Sahara (excluding the coast) and having distinctive oversized ears.
FENNEC.e: Borrowed from French fennec, from Arabic فَنَك (fanak).

FENNEL.d: A plant, Foeniculum vulgare, of the parsley family, which has a sweet, anise-like flavor.
FENNEL.e: From the Middle English fenel, from the late Old English finuðl, finule (weak feminine forms); fenol, finul (masculine forms), from Proto-West Germanic *fenukl, from the Vulgar Latin *fēnuclum, fēnoclum, from Late Latin fēnuculum, from the Classical Latin faeniculum, a diminutive...

FENNER.d: Comparative form of FEN: A type of wetland fed by ground water and runoff, containing peat below the waterline, characteristically alkaline.
FENNER.e:
From Middle English fen, fenne, from Old English fenn (“fen; marsh; mud; dirt”), Proto-West Germanic *fani, from Proto-Germanic *fanją, from Proto-Indo-European *pen- (“bog, mire”).
See also West Frisian fean, Dutch veen, German Fenn, Norwegian fen; also Middle Irish en (“water”)...

FERNED.d: Past tense of FERN: Any of a group of some twenty thousand species of vascular plants classified in the division Pteridophyta that lack seeds and reproduce by shedding spores to initiate an alternation of generations.
FERNED.e:
From Middle English fern, from Old English fearn, from Proto-West Germanic *farn, from Proto-Indo-European *pornóm (“feather, wing; fern, leaf”), from *p(t)erH- (“fern”).
Cognate with Scots fairn (“fern”), West Frisian fear (“fern”), Dutch varen (“fern”), German Farn, Farm (“fern...

FERRER.d: Comparative form of FER: Pronunciation spelling of for.

FERRET.d: An often domesticated mammal (Mustela putorius furo) rather like a weasel, descended from the polecat and often trained to hunt burrowing animals.
FERRET.e: From Middle English furet, ferret, from Old French furet, from Vulgar Latin *furittum (“weasel, ferret”), diminutive of Latin fūr (“thief”).

FERULA.e: Borrowed from Latin ferula (“giant fennel”), whose stalks were once used in punishing schoolboys. Doublet of ferule.

FERULE.d: A ruler-shaped instrument, generally used to slap naughty children on the hand.
FERULE.e: From Middle French ferule (modern French férule), from Latin ferula (“giant fennel”). Doublet of ferula.

FERVID.e: Borrowed from Latin fervidus, from ferveō.

FESCUE.d: A straw, wire, stick, etc., used chiefly to point out letters to children when learning to read.
FESCUE.e: From Old French festu (modern fétu), from Proto-Romance festu, from Latin festūca (“stalk, stem, straw”).

FESSES.d: Plural of FESS: To confess; to admit.

FESTAL.d: festive, relating to a festival or feast
FESTAL.e: From Middle French festal, from Latin festum (“feast”).

FESTER.e: Inherited from Middle English festre, festur, borrowed from Old French festre (cognate with Italian fistola, Occitan fistola, Spanish fístula), from Latin fistula. The verb is derived from the noun, while the “condition of something that festers” noun sense is derived from the ve...

FETING.d: Present participle of FETE: A festival open to the public, the proceeds from which are often given to charity.
FETING.e:
* The noun derives from French fête. Doublet of feast, fiesta, and fest.
* The verb derives from French fêter.

FETISH.d: Something which is believed to possess, contain, or cause spiritual or magical powers; an amulet or a talisman.
FETISH.e: Borrowed from French fétiche, from Portuguese feitiço, from Latin factīcius (“artificial”). Doublet of factitious.

FETTER.d: A chain or similar object used to bind a person or animal – often by its legs (usually in plural).
FETTER.e: From Middle English feter, from Old English feter, Proto-West Germanic *fetur, from Proto-Germanic *feturaz (“fetter”), from Proto-Indo-European *ped- (“foot, step”). Cognate with Dutch veter (“lace”). Related to foot.

FETTLE.d: A state of physical condition; kilter or trim.
FETTLE.e:
From Late Middle English fetlen (“(verb) to bestow; to fix, prepare, put in place; to prepare (oneself) for battle, gird up; to shape; to be about to, or to ready (oneself) to stay; (adjective) shaped (well or poorly)”) [and other forms], which possibly:
* from Old English fetel ...

FEUDED.d: Past tense of FEUD: A state of long-standing mutual hostility.
FEUDED.e:
Inherited from Northern Middle English fede, feide, from Old French faide, feide, fede, from Proto-West Germanic *faihiþu (“hatred, enmity”) (corresponding to foe + -th), from Proto-Indo-European *peyḱ- (“hostile”).
Cognate to Old English fǣhþ, fǣhþu, fǣhþo (“hostility, enmity, v...

FEZZED.d: Past tense of FEZ: A felt hat in the shape of a truncated cone, having a flat top with a tassel attached.
FEZZED.e: From Ottoman Turkish فس (fes) (modern Turkish fes), named after Fez, Morocco, (capital of the Kingdom of Morocco until 1927), where the dye to color the hat was extracted from crimson berries.

FIACRE.d: A small horse-drawn carriage for hire; a hackney carriage.
FIACRE.e: Borrowed from French fiacre. From Hôtel de Saint Fiacre, a tavern in Paris operating a horse-carriage service from the 1640s, itself named after the Irish Saint Fiacre (c. 600–670 CE), perhaps from Irish fiach (“raven”).

FIASCO.e: Borrowed from Italian fiasco (“bottle, flask”), from Late Latin flasca, flascō (“bottle, container”), from Frankish *flaskā (“bottle, flask”) from Proto-Germanic *flaskǭ (“bottle”); see flask. “Failure” sense comes through French faire fiasco from Italian theatrical slang far fia...

FIBBED.d: Past tense of FIB: A lie, especially one that is more or less inconsequential.
FIBBED.e: Unknown. Probably from fable; compare fibble-fable (“nonsense”).

FIBBER.d: Comparative form of FIB: A lie, especially one that is more or less inconsequential.
FIBBER.e: Unknown. Probably from fable; compare fibble-fable (“nonsense”).

FIBRIL.e: Borrowed from Latin fibrilla, diminutive of Latin fibra. Doublet of fibrilla. Compare fibre.

FIBRIN.d: A white, albuminous, fibrous substance, formed in the coagulation of the blood.
FIBRIN.e: From fibre + -in (used to form chemical names of proteins, etc).

FIBULA.d: An ancient kind of brooch used to hold clothing together, similar in function to the modern safety pin.
FIBULA.e: Borrowed from Latin fībula (“buckle, clasp, pin”). The bone is so named because the shape it makes with the tibia resembles a clasp, the fibula being the pin.

FICKLE.d: Quick to change one’s opinion or allegiance; insincere; not loyal or reliable.
FICKLE.e: From Middle English fikil, fikel, from Old English ficol (“fickle, cunning, tricky, deceitful”), equivalent to fike + -le. More at fike.

FIDDLE.d: A violin, a small unfretted stringed instrument with four strings tuned (lowest to highest) G-D-A-E, usually held against the chin, shoulder, chest or on the upper thigh and played with a bow (see also usage notes below).
FIDDLE.e: From Middle English fithele, from Old English *fiþele, from Proto-West Germanic *fiþulā, from Proto-Germanic *fiþulǭ (“fiddle”), of uncertain etymology. Some contest that the Germanic terms are borrowed variations of Late Latin vitula (see viola); others contest that the word has...

FIDGET.d: To wiggle or twitch; to move the body, especially the fingers, around nervously or idly.
FIDGET.e: From fidge (“to fidget”) + *-et (frequentative ending), possibly from Middle English *-ten, from Old English -ettan.

FIELDS.d: Plural of FIELD: An area of open land; a subject of study.

FIERCE.d: Exceedingly violent, severe, ferocious, cruel or savage.
FIERCE.e: From Middle English fers, fiers, borrowed from Old French fers (“wild", "ferocious”), nominative of fer, from Latin ferus (“wild", "untamed”).

FIESTA.e: Borrowed from Spanish fiesta, from Late Latin festa, from the plural of festum (“feast”). Doublet of feast, fest, and fete.

FIFING.d: Present participle of FIFE: A small shrill pipe, resembling the piccolo flute, used chiefly to accompany the drum in military music
FIFING.e: From German Pfeife (“whistle, smoking pipe”). Doublet of pipe.

FIFTHS.d: Plural of FIFTH: The ordinal number 5th.

FIGGED.d: Past tense of FIG: The fruit of the fig tree, pear-shaped and containing many small seeds.
FIGGED.e: From Middle English fige, fygge (also fyke, from Old English fīc, see fike), borrowed from Anglo-Norman figue, borrowed from Old French figue, from Old Occitan figa, from Vulgar Latin *fīca (“fig”), from Latin fīcus (“fig tree”), from a pre-Indo European language, perhaps Phoenic...

FIGHTS.d: Plural of FIGHT: A violent struggle; to engage in combat.

FIGURA.d: Any of the non-signifying constituents of signifiers.
FIGURA.e: From Latin figūra. Coined by Louis Hjelmslev.

FIGURE.d: A drawing or diagram conveying information.
FIGURE.e: From Middle English figure, borrowed from Old French figure, from Latin figūra (“form, shape, form of a word, a figure of speech, Late Latin a sketch, drawing”), from fingō (“to form, shape, mold, fashion”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeyǵʰ- (“to mold, shape, form, knead”). Cogna...

FILIAL.d: Pertaining to or befitting a son or daughter.
FILIAL.e: From Middle English filial, from Latin fīliālis, from filius (“son”) / filia (“daughter”) + -al.

FILING.d: Any particle that has been removed by a file or similar implement; a shaving.

FILLET.d: A headband; a ribbon or other band used to tie the hair up, or keep a headdress in place, or for decoration.
FILLET.e: From Middle English filet, vylette, felet, filette, flette, from Old French filet, diminutive of fil (“thread”), from Latin fīlum (“thread”).

FILLIP.d: The action of holding the tip of a finger against the thumb and then releasing it with a snap; a flick.
FILLIP.e: From Middle English filippen, philippe (“to flick or snap a finger from against the thumb”); further origin uncertain, but probably imitative. See flip. It is not clear whether the verb is derived from the noun, or vice versa.

FILMED.d: Past tense of FILM: A thin layer of some substance; a pellicle; a membranous covering, causing opacity.
FILMED.e: From Middle English filme, from Old English filmen (“film, membrane, thin skin, foreskin”), from Proto-West Germanic *filmīn-, from Proto-Germanic *filmīn- (“thin skin, membrane”) (compare Proto-Germanic *felma- (“skin, hide”)), from Proto-Indo-European *pél-mo- (“membrane”), fro...

FILTER.d: A device which separates a suspended, dissolved, or particulate matter from a fluid, solution, or other substance; any device that separates one substance from another.
FILTER.e: From Middle English filtre, from Medieval Latin filtrum (compare also Old French feutre (“felt; filter”)), from Frankish *filtir, from Proto-West Germanic *felt. See felt. Doublet of phin.

FILTHY.e: From Middle English filthy, filthi, equivalent to filth + -y.

FINALE.d: The grand end of something, especially of a show or piece of music.
FINALE.e: From Italian finale (“ending”), from Late Latin fīnālis, from Latin fīnis (“end; boundary, limit”). Doublet of final.

FINALS.d: Plural of FINAL: Last; coming at the end.

FINGER.d: A slender jointed extremity of the human hand, (often) exclusive of the thumb.
FINGER.e:
PIE word
 *pénkʷe
From Middle English fynger, finger, from Old English finger (“finger”), from Proto-West Germanic *fingr, from Proto-Germanic *fingraz (“finger”), from Proto-Indo-European *penkʷrós, from *pénkʷe (“five”). Compare West Frisian finger, Low German/German Finger, Du...

FINIAL.d: Especially in Gothic architecture: an ornament, often in the form of a bunch or knot of foliage, on the peak of the gable of a roof, a pediment, a pinnacle, etc.
FINIAL.e: From Late Middle English finial (“(adjective) final; (noun) ornament at the upper extremity of a pinnacle, spire, etc.”) [and other forms], a variant of final (“pertaining to the close or end of something, last, final”), from Old French final (“last, final; definitive”) (modern F...

FINING.d: present participle and gerund of fine

FINISH.d: An end; the end of anything.
FINISH.e: From Middle English finishen, finisshen, finischen, from Old French finiss-, stem of some of the conjugated forms of finir, from Latin fīnīre, from fīnis (“end, limit, border, boundary”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeygʷ- (“to stick, set up”) or from Proto-Indo-European ...

FINITE.d: Having an end or limit; (of a quantity) constrained by bounds; (of a set) whose number of elements is a natural number.
FINITE.e:
The adjective is derived from Middle English fynyte, finit, from Latin fīnītus, perfect passive participle of fīniō (“to finish; to terminate”), from fīnis (“boundary”). The word displaced Old English ġeendodlīċ.
The noun is derived from the adjective.

FINNED.d: Past tense of FIN: One of the appendages of a fish, used to propel itself and to manoeuvre/maneuver.
FINNED.e: From Middle English fin, from Old English finn, from Proto-Germanic *finnō, *finǭ (“dorsal fin”) (compare Dutch vin, German Finne, Swedish finne, fena), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)pīn- (“backbone, dorsal fin”) (compare Old Irish ind (“end, point”), Latin pinna (“feather, wing, ...

FINNER.d: Comparative form of FIN: One of the appendages of a fish, used to propel itself and to manoeuvre/maneuver.
FINNER.e: From Middle English fin, from Old English finn, from Proto-Germanic *finnō, *finǭ (“dorsal fin”) (compare Dutch vin, German Finne, Swedish finne, fena), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)pīn- (“backbone, dorsal fin”) (compare Old Irish ind (“end, point”), Latin pinna (“feather, wing, ...

FIPPLE.d: The mouthpiece of a ducted flute, or the plug forming the floor of the windway.
FIPPLE.e: Perhaps related to Icelandic flipi (“the lip of a horse”).

FIRING.d: The process of applying heat or fire, especially to clay, etc., to produce pottery.

FIRKIN.d: A varying measure of capacity, usually being a quarter of a barrel; specifically, a measure equal to nine imperial gallons.
FIRKIN.e: From Middle Dutch *vierdekijn, diminutive of vierde (“fourth”), from vier (“four”); equivalent to fourth + -kin.

FIRMAN.d: A royal decree issued by a sovereign in certain historical Islamic states, especially by the Sultan of Turkey.
FIRMAN.e: From Ottoman Turkish فرمان (ferman), from Persian فرمان (farmân, “command, order, decree”).

FIRMED.d: Past tense of FIRM: A business partnership; the name under which it trades.
FIRMED.e: From Italian firma (“signature”), from firmare (“to sign”), from Latin firmāre (“to make firm, to confirm (by signature)”), from firmus (“firm, stable”). The contemporary sense developed in the 18th century simultaneously with German Firma (“business, name of business”). There ar...

FIRSTS.d: Plural of FIRST: Before all others.

FISCAL.d: Related to the treasury of a country, company, region or city, particularly to government spending and revenue.
FISCAL.e: From Middle French fiscal, from Latin fiscus (“treasury”) – see fiscus and fisc.

FISHED.d: Past tense of FISH: A typically cold-blooded vertebrate animal that lives in water, moving with the help of fins and breathing with gills.
FISHED.e:
From Middle English fisch, from Old English fisċ (“fish”), from Proto-West Germanic *fisk, from Proto-Germanic *fiskaz (“fish”), from Proto-Indo-European *peysk- (“fish”).
Cognates
Cognate with Yola wish (“fish”), North Frisian fasch, fask, Fesk (“fish”), Saterland Frisian Fisk (...

FISHER.d: A person who catches fish, especially for a living or for sport; a person engaging in the pastime of fishing.
FISHER.e: From Middle English fischer, fischare, from Old English fisċere (“fisher”), from Proto-Germanic *fiskārijaz (“fisher”), equivalent to fish + -er. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Fisker (“fisher”), West Frisian fisker (“fisher”), Dutch visser (“fisher”), German Low German Fisker, F...

FISHES.d: Plural of FISH: A typically cold-blooded vertebrate animal that lives in water, moving with the help of fins and breathing with gills.
FISHES.e:
From Middle English fisch, from Old English fisċ (“fish”), from Proto-West Germanic *fisk, from Proto-Germanic *fiskaz (“fish”), from Proto-Indo-European *peysk- (“fish”).
Cognates
Cognate with Yola wish (“fish”), North Frisian fasch, fask, Fesk (“fish”), Saterland Frisian Fisk (...

FISTED.d: Past tense of FIST: A hand with the fingers clenched or curled inward.
FISTED.e:
From Middle English fist, from Old English fȳst (“fist”), from Proto-West Germanic *fūsti, of uncertain origin.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola fest, hist (“fist”), Saterland Frisian Fäste, Fääste (“fist”), Central Franconian Fuus (“fist”), Cimbrian bòista, vòista (“fist”), Dutch vuis...

FITFUL.e: From fit (“convulsion, seizure; sudden burst of activity”) + -ful (suffix forming adjectives from nouns, with the sense of being full of, tending to, or thoroughly possessing the quality expressed by the noun).

FITTED.d: Past tense of FIT: Suitable; proper
FITTED.e: Possibly from Middle English fit (“an adversary of equal power”), of uncertain further origin. The original sense appears to have been "to marshal or deploy troops", which shifted to "to suit (troops to a certain location" > "suitable", and may be further related to Icelandic fit...

FITTER.d: Comparative form of FIT: Suitable; proper
FITTER.e: Possibly from Middle English fit (“an adversary of equal power”), of uncertain further origin. The original sense appears to have been "to marshal or deploy troops", which shifted to "to suit (troops to a certain location" > "suitable", and may be further related to Icelandic fit...

FIXATE.d: To make something fixed and stable; to fix.
FIXATE.e: From fix + -ate (verb-forming suffix) or Latin fixus (“fixed, solid”) + -ate.

FIXING.d: The act of subverting (fixing) a vote.

FIXITY.d: The state or condition of being fixed.

FIZGIG.d: A flirtatious, coquettish girl, inclined to gad or gallivant about; a gig, a giglot, a jillflirt.
FIZGIG.e: From Middle English gig (“a frivolous woman”); the first element of the word may be from fise (“an instance of flatulence”), from fist (“an act of breaking wind”).

FIZZES.d: Plural of FIZZ: An emission of a rapid stream of bubbles.

FIZZLE.e:
Attested in English since 1525-35. From earlier fysel (“to fart”). Related to fīsa (“to fart”). Compare with Swedish fisa (“to fart (silently)”). See also feist.
It could also come from old Norse: "fise" simply means "blow," like in "blow in the wind." A weather-exposed community...

FLABBY.d: Yielding to the touch, and easily moved or shaken; hanging loose by its own weight; lacking firmness; flaccid.
FLABBY.e: From a variant of flappy, from flap (“to hang loose”). Compare English dialectal flapsy (“flabby”), Middle Dutch flabbe (“a slap in the face; a fan-blade; a hair ribbon; a wagging tongue”), Middle Low German flabbe (“a gaping mouth; a chatterbox”), Danish flab (“the jaw; cheeks; ...

FLACON.d: A small stoppered glass bottle, often used for keeping perfume.
FLACON.e: Borrowed from French flacon. Doublet of fiasco, flagon, and flask.

FLAGON.d: A large vessel resembling a jug, usually with a handle, lid, and spout, for serving drinks such as cider or wine at a table; specifically (Christianity), such a vessel used to hold the wine for the ritual of Holy Communion.
FLAGON.e: From Middle English flagon, flakon [and other forms], from Middle French flacon, Old French flacon, flascon (“flask”) (modern French flacon (“vial”)), from Medieval Latin flascōnem, the accusative singular of Late Latin flascō (“bottle; glass or earthenware vessel for wine; porta...

FLAMEN.d: A priest devoted to the service of a particular god, from whom he received a distinguishing epithet. The most honored were those of Jupiter, Mars, and Quirinus, called respectively Flamen Dialis, Flamen Martialis, and Flamen Quirinalis.

FLANGE.d: An external or internal rib or rim, used either to add strength or to hold something in place.
FLANGE.e: From dialectal English flange (“to project”), flanch (“a projection”), from Middle French flanche, from Old French flanche (“flank, side”), from Frankish *hlanka, from Proto-Germanic *hlankō (“bend, curve; side, flank”). See flank. As a term for a group of baboons, it was popular...

FLASHY.d: Showy; visually impressive, attention-getting, or appealing.

FLATED.d: Past tense of FLAT: Having no variations in height.
FLATED.e: From Middle English flat, a borrowing from Old Norse flatr (compare Norwegian and Swedish flat, Danish flad), from Proto-Germanic *flataz, from Proto-Indo-European *pleth₂- (“flat”); akin to Saterland Frisian flot (“smooth”), German Flöz (“a geological layer”), Ancient Greek πλατ...

FLATUS.d: Gas generated in the digestive tract.
FLATUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin flātus (“blowing, wind, fart”). First attested in the 1660s–1670s.

FLAUNT.d: To wave or flutter smartly in the wind.
FLAUNT.e:
Of North Germanic origin. Perhaps related to Norwegian flanta (“to show off, wander about”), Icelandic flana (“to rush about, act rashly or heedlessly”) and then also to French flâner (“to wander around, loiter”).
Alternatively, it could be related to Swedish flankt (“loosely, fl...

FLAWED.d: Past tense of FLAW: A flake, fragment, or shiver.
FLAWED.e:
From Middle English flawe, flay (“a flake of fire or snow, spark, splinter”), probably from Old Norse flaga (“a flag or slab of stone, flake”), from Proto-Germanic *flagō (“a layer of soil”), from Proto-Indo-European *plok- (“broad, flat”).
Cognate with Icelandic flaga (“flake”),...

FLAXES.d: Plural of FLAX: A plant of the genus Linum, especially Linum usitatissimum, which has a single, slender stalk, about a foot and a half high, with blue flowers. Also known as linseed, especially when referring to the seeds.
FLAXES.e: From Middle English flax, from Old English fleax, from Proto-Germanic *flahsą, from Proto-Indo-European *pleḱ- (“to plait”). Cognate with Old Frisian flax, Dutch vlas, Old High German flahs (German Flachs); the Northern Germanic (and most likely the Gothic too) stem is different.

FLAYED.d: Past tense of FLAY: To cause to fly; put to flight; drive off (by frightening).
FLAYED.e: From Middle English flayen, flaien, fleien, from Old English *flīeġan ("to cause to fly, put to flight, frighten"; found only in compounds: āflīeġan), from Proto-Germanic *flaugijaną (“to let fly, cause to fly”), causative of Proto-Germanic *fleuganą (“to fly”).

FLEDGE.d: To care for a young bird until it is capable of flight.
FLEDGE.e: From Middle English flegge, fligge, flygge, from Old English *flyċġe (“able to fly, fledged”) (attested in *unflyċġe, unfligge (“unfledged”)), from Proto-West Germanic *flugi, from Proto-Germanic *flugjaz (“able to fly, fledged”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to run, flow, ...

FLEECE.d: Hair or wool of a sheep or similar animal
FLEECE.e: From Middle English flees, flese, flus, fleos, from Old English flēos, flīes, flȳs, from Proto-West Germanic *fleus.

FLEING.d: Present participle of FLEE: To run away; to escape.
FLEING.e:
From Middle English flen, from Old English flēon, from Proto-Germanic *fleuhaną, from Proto-Indo-European *plewk-, *plew- (“to fly, flow, run”).
Cognate with Dutch vlieden, German fliehen, Icelandic flýja, Swedish fly, Gothic 𐌸𐌻𐌹𐌿𐌷𐌰𐌽 (þliuhan). Within English, related to fly and ...

FLENSE.d: To strip the blubber or skin from, as from a whale, seal, etc.

FLESHY.d: Of, related to, or resembling flesh.
FLESHY.e: From Middle English fleisshy, fleischy, fleschi, equivalent to flesh + -y. Piecewise doublet of fleischig.

FLEWED.d: Past tense of FLEW: simple past of fly
FLEWED.e: From Middle English flew, flow, from Old English flēag, flug-, from Proto-Germanic *flaug, *flug-, past tense forms of Proto-Germanic *fleuganą (“to fly”). Compare Saterland Frisian flooch (“flew”), West Frisian fleach (“flew”), Dutch vloog (“flew”), German flog (“flew”), Danish ...

FLEXED.d: Past tense of FLEX: Flexibility, pliancy.
FLEXED.e: From Latin flexus, past participle of flecto (“to bend”).

FLEXES.e: From Latin flexus, past participle of flecto (“to bend”).

FLEXOR.d: A muscle whose contraction acts to bend a joint or limb.
FLEXOR.e: From New Latin flexor, agent noun of flectō (“I bend”).

FLIEST.d: Superlative form of FLY: Any insect of the order Diptera; characterized by having two wings (except for some wingless species), also called true flies.
FLIEST.e: From Middle English flye, flie, from Old English flȳġe, flēoge (“a fly”), from Proto-Germanic *fleugǭ (“a fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”). Cognate with Scots flee, Saterland Frisian Fljooge, Dutch vlieg, German Low German Fleeg, German Fliege, Danish flue, Norw...

FLIGHT.e: From Middle English flight, from Old English flyht (“flight”), from Proto-West Germanic *fluhti (“flight”), derived from *fleuganą (“to fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”), enlargement of *plew- (“flow”). Analyzable as fly + -t (variant of -th).

FLIMSY.d: Likely to bend or break under pressure; easily damaged; frail, unsubstantial.
FLIMSY.e: The origin of the adjective is uncertain; it is possibly from flim(-flam) (“(noun) false information presented as true, misinformation, nonsense; poor attempt at deception, confidence trick, pretence; (adjective) frivolous, nonsensical; deceptive; fictitious”) or a metathesis of ...

FLINCH.e: From Middle French flenchir (“to bend”), of Germanic origin. Compare Middle High German lenken (“to bend”). Attested in English since the 16th century.

FLINTY.d: Resembling or containing flint; hard like flint.

FLITCH.d: The flank or side of an animal, now almost exclusively a pig when cured and salted; a side of bacon.
FLITCH.e: From Middle English flicche, from Old English fliċċe (“side of an animal, flitch”), from Proto-Germanic *flikkiją (“side, flitch”), from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₁ḱ- (“to tear, peel off”). Cognate with Low German flikke, French flèche, Icelandic flikki (“flitch”), Middle Low Germ...

FLOORS.d: Plural of FLOOR: The lower surface of a room.

FLOPPY.d: Limp, not hard, firm, or rigid; flexible.

FLORAL.d: Of, pertaining to, or connected with flowers.
FLORAL.e: From French floral, from Latin flōrālis, from flōs (“flower”).

FLORET.d: A small flower, especially one of a cluster in a composite flower.
FLORET.e: From Old French florete, diminutive of flor (“flower”). Doublet of fleuret and floweret.

FLORID.d: Having a rosy or pale red colour; ruddy.
FLORID.e: From French floride (“flourishing”), from Latin floridus (“flowery, blooming”). Doublet of Florida.

FLORIN.d: Any of several gold coins once produced in Florence, Italy; model for the other currencies.
FLORIN.e: From Middle English florin, floren, from Old French florin, from Italian fiorino (“little flower”). Doublet of fiorino and forint.

FLOURY.e: From Middle English floury, equivalent to flour + -y. Piecewise doublet of flowery.

FLOWER.d: A colorful, conspicuous structure associated with angiosperms, frequently scented and attracting various insects, and which may or may not be used for sexual reproduction.
FLOWER.e:
From Middle English flour, from Anglo-Norman flur, from Latin flōrem, accusative of flōs, from Proto-Italic *flōs, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleh₃- (“to thrive, bloom”). Doublet of fleur, flor, flour, bloom, and blossom.
Partly displaced native Old English blostma (which is cogn...

FLUENT.e: From Latin fluens (“flowing”), present active participle of fluō (“I flow”).

FLUIDS.d: Plural of FLUID: A substance that flows; able to flow.
FLUIDS.e: From Latin fluidus, from fluere (to flow).

FLUING.d: Present participle of FLUE: A pipe or duct that carries gaseous combustion products away from the point of combustion (such as a furnace).
FLUING.e: From Middle English flue, flewe (“mouthpiece of a hunting horn”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps a back-formation from Middle English *flews (mistaken as a plural), from Old English flēwsa (“a flow, flowing, flux”). Alternatively, perhaps an alteration of Middle English floute, fle...

FLUNKY.d: A person who always agrees with their superior or employer.

FLURRY.d: A light, brief snowfall; a shower of snow.
FLURRY.e: Perhaps an American English blend of flutter and hurry. Alternatively, perhaps from an obsolete term flurr (“scatter”).

FLUXED.d: Past tense of FLUX: The act of flowing; a continuous moving on or passing by, as of a flowing stream.
FLUXED.e: From Old French flux, from Latin fluxus (“flow”).

FLUXES.d: Plural of FLUX: The act of flowing; a continuous moving on or passing by, as of a flowing stream.
FLUXES.e: From Old French flux, from Latin fluxus (“flow”).

FLYING.d: Present participle of FLY: Any insect of the order Diptera; characterized by having two wings (except for some wingless species), also called true flies.
FLYING.e: From Middle English flye, flie, from Old English flȳġe, flēoge (“a fly”), from Proto-Germanic *fleugǭ (“a fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”). Cognate with Scots flee, Saterland Frisian Fljooge, Dutch vlieg, German Low German Fleeg, German Fliege, Danish flue, Norw...

FLYMAN.d: Someone who drives the type of coach called a fly.

FLYWAY.d: A migratory route used by birds between breeding areas.

FOALED.d: Past tense of FOAL: A young horse or other equine, especially just after birth or less than a year old.
FOALED.e: From Middle English fole, from Old English fola, from Proto-West Germanic *folō, from Proto-Germanic *fulô, from pre-Germanic *pl̥Hon-, from Proto-Indo-European *pōlH- (“animal young”) (cognate with Saterland Frisian Foole, West Frisian fôle, foalle, Dutch veulen, German Low Germ...

FOAMED.d: Past tense of FOAM: A substance composed of a large collection of bubbles or their solidified remains, especially
FOAMED.e: From Middle English fom, foom, from Old English fām, from Proto-West Germanic *faim, from Proto-Germanic *faimaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)poHy-m-os, from *(s)poH(y)- (“foam”). Cognate with German Feim (“foam”), Latin spūma (“foam”), Latin pūmex (“pumice”), Sanskrit फेन (phén...

FOBBED.d: Past tense of FOB: A little pocket near the waistline of a pair of trousers or in a waistcoat or vest to hold money or valuables, especially a pocket watch.
FOBBED.e:
From Low German Fobke (“pocket”) or High Prussian Fuppe (“pocket”), probably related to Swedish ficka (“pocket”), Old Danish fikke, Alemannic German figge, Middle Dutch vicke, all from Proto-Germanic *fikkja, of uncertain ultimate origin:
* possibly from Proto-Indo-European *pewǵ...

FODDER.d: Food for animals; that which is fed to cattle, horses, and sheep, such as hay, cornstalks, vegetables, etc.
FODDER.e:
From Middle English fodder, foder, from Old English fōdor (“feed; fodder”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōdr, from Proto-Germanic *fōdrą, from *fōdô (“food”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to guard, graze, feed”).
Compare Saterland Frisian Fodder, West Frisian foer, Dutch voer ...

FOEMAN.d: An enemy; a foe in battle; an armed or unarmed adversary; a demon.
FOEMAN.e: From Middle English foman (“an enemy, devil, demon”), from Old English fāhman (“enemy”), equivalent to foe + man.

FOGGED.d: Past tense of FOG: A thick cloud that forms near the ground; the obscurity of such a cloud.
FOGGED.e: Origin uncertain; but probably of North Germanic origin. Probably either a back-formation from foggy (“covered with tall grass; thick, marshy”), from the earlier-attested fog (“tall grass”) (see below), or from or related to Danish fog (“spray, shower, drift, storm”), related to ...
