FOGGER.d: Comparative form of FOG: A thick cloud that forms near the ground; the obscurity of such a cloud.
FOGGER.e: Origin uncertain; but probably of North Germanic origin. Probably either a back-formation from foggy (“covered with tall grass; thick, marshy”), from the earlier-attested fog (“tall grass”) (see below), or from or related to Danish fog (“spray, shower, drift, storm”), related to ...

FOGIES.d: Plural of FOGY: Alternative spelling of fogey.

FOIBLE.d: A quirk, idiosyncrasy, frailty, or mannerism; an unusual habit that is slightly strange or silly.
FOIBLE.e: 1640–50, from Early Modern French foible (“feeble”) (contemporary French faible). Doublet of feeble.

FOILED.d: Past tense of FOIL: An acronym for the algorithm for multiplying two binomials.
FOILED.e: Acronym of first outer inner last or similar.

FOLATE.d: A salt or ester of folic acid, especially one present in the vitamin B complex.

FOLDED.d: Past tense of FOLD: To bend (any thin material, such as paper) over so that it comes in contact with itself.
FOLDED.e:
The verb is from Middle English folden, from Old English fealdan, from Proto-West Germanic *falþan, from Proto-Germanic *falþaną (“to fold”), from Proto-Indo-European *pel- (“to fold”).
The noun is from Middle English folde, falde, itself derived from the verb.

FOLKIE.d: A folk singer, or an enthusiast of folk music.

FOLLER.d: Comparative form of FOL: Initialism of first-order logic.

FOLLOW.d: To go after; to pursue; to move behind in the same path or direction, especially with the intent of catching.
FOLLOW.e: From Middle English folwen, folȝen, folgen, from Old English folgian (“to follow, pursue”), from Proto-West Germanic *folgēn, from Proto-Germanic *fulgāną (“to follow”).

FOMENT.d: To incite or cause troublesome acts; to encourage; to instigate.
FOMENT.e: From Middle English fomenten, a borrowing from Old French fomenter, from Late Latin fōmentāre, from Latin fōmentum (“lotion”), from fovēre (“heat, cherish”).

FOMITE.d: An inanimate object capable of carrying infectious agents (such as bacteria, viruses or prions), and thus passively enabling their transmission between hosts; common examples include towels, dishcloths, kitchenware/flatware, and laundry.
FOMITE.e: A back-formation from fomites, plural of fomes, a borrowing of medical Latin fōmes (“tinder, kindling”), used figuratively to evoke the analogy of a spreading infection to a spreading fire.

FONDED.d: Past tense of FOND: Having a liking or affection (for).
FONDED.e: From Middle English fond, fonned, past participle of fonnen (“to be foolish, be simple, dote”), equivalent to fon + -ed. More at fon.

FONDUE.d: A dish made of melted cheese, or chocolate etc., or of a boiling liquid into which food can be dipped.
FONDUE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French fondue (“melted”), from fondre (“to melt”).

FONTED.d: Past tense of FONT: A receptacle in a church for holy water, especially one used in baptism.
FONTED.e: From Old English font, an early borrowing from Latin fōns, fontis (“fountain”).

FOODIE.d: A person with a special interest in or knowledge of food, a gourmet.
FOODIE.e: From food + -ie. Popularized by Ann Barr and Paul Levy in The Official Foodie Handbook (1984). Levy credits New York food critic Gael Greene with the coinage. The word was used by Greene in a 1980 article in New York magazine, see quotations.

FOOLED.d: Past tense of FOOL: A person with poor judgment or little intelligence.
FOOLED.e: From Middle English fole (“fool”), from Old French fol (cf. modern French fou (“mad”)) from Latin follis. Doublet of fals and follis. Displaced native Old English dwæs.

FOOTED.d: Past tense of FOOT: A biological structure found in many animals that is used for locomotion and that is frequently a separate organ at the terminal part of the leg.
FOOTED.e:
From Middle English fot, fote, foot, from Old English fōt, from Proto-West Germanic *fōt, from Proto-Germanic *fōts, from Proto-Indo-European *pṓds. Doublet of pes, pie (“Spanish unit of length”), and pous.
Cognates
*Scots fit (“foot”)
*Yola voote (“foot”)
*North Frisian fut, föt...

FOOTLE.e: Probably variant of footer (“to screw around”), from obsolete fouter (“an act of sexual intercourse”), from French foutre (“to have sexual intercourse”), from Latin futuere.

FOOZLE.d: To do something clumsily or awkwardly; to bungle.

FOPPED.d: Past tense of FOP: A vain man; a dandy.
FOPPED.e: From Middle English foppe, fobbe (“fop, fool”). Akin to German foppen (“to jeer”).

FORAGE.d: Fodder for animals, especially cattle and horses.
FORAGE.e:
From Middle English forage, from Old French fourage, forage, a derivative of fuerre (“fodder, straw”), from Frankish *fōdar (“fodder, sheath”), from Proto-Germanic *fōdrą (“fodder, feed, sheath”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to protect, to feed”).
Cognate with Ol...

FORBID.e: From Middle English forbeden, from Old English forbēodan (“to forbid, prohibit, restrain, refuse, repeal, annul”), from Proto-Germanic *furibeudaną, from *furi + *beudaną. Equivalent to for- (“from, away”) + bid (“to offer, proclaim”). Cognate with Dutch verbieden (“to forbid”), ...

FORCED.d: Past tense of FORCE: Strength; to compel.
FORCED.e: From Old French force, from Latin fortis (strong).

FORCES.d: Plural of FORCE: Strength; to compel.
FORCES.e: From Old French force, from Latin fortis (strong).

FORDED.d: Past tense of FORD: A location where a stream is shallow and the bottom has good footing, making it possible to cross from one side to the other with no bridge, by walking, riding, or driving through the water; a crossing.
FORDED.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *per-
Proto-Indo-European *-tus
Proto-Indo-European *pértus
Proto-Germanic *furduz
Proto-West Germanic *furdu
Old English ford
English ford
Inherited from Middle English fōrd, from Old English ford, from Proto-West Germanic *furdu, from Proto-Ge...

FOREGO.e: From Middle English forgan, from Old English foregān, equivalent to fore- + go.

FOREST.d: A dense uncultivated tract of trees and undergrowth, larger than woods.
FOREST.e: Inherited from Middle English forest, from Old French forest, from Early Medieval Latin forestis, likely from Frankish or Proto-West Germanic *furhisti (“forest, fir-grove, wooded land”), equivalent to fir + hurst. Related to Old English fyrhþe (“forested land”), Old High German ...

FORGER.d: A person who creates forgeries, falsifies documents with intent to defraud, e.g. to create a false will or illicit copies of currency; counterfeiter.
FORGER.e: From Middle English forger, forgere, from Old French forgiere; equivalent to forge + -er.

FORGET.e:
From Middle English forgeten, forgiten, foryeten, forȝiten, from Old English forġietan (“to forget”) [influenced by Old Norse geta ("to get, to guess")], from Proto-West Germanic *fragetan (“to give up, forget”). Equivalent to for- + get.
Cognate with :
* Scots forget, forȝet (“t...

FORINT.d: The basic unit of currency of Hungary; formerly subdivided into 100 fillér.
FORINT.e: From Hungarian forint, from Italian fiorino (“florin, former currency of Tuscany”). Doublet of florin.

FORKED.d: Past tense of FORK: Any of several types of pronged (tined) tools (physical tools), as follows:
FORKED.e: From Middle English forke (“digging fork”), from Old English force, forca (“forked instrument used to torture”), from Proto-West Germanic *furkō (“fork”), from Latin furca (“pitchfork, forked stake; gallows, beam, stake, support post, yoke”), of uncertain origin. The Middle Engli...

FORMAL.e: From Middle English formel, borrowed from Old French formel, from Latin fōrmālis, from fōrma (“form”); equivalent to form + -al.

FORMAT.d: The layout of a publication or document.
FORMAT.e: Via French format and German Format, from New Latin liber fōrmātus (“book fashioned”), from fōrmō (“I shape, fashion”).

FORMED.d: simple past and past participle of form

FORMER.e: Inherited from Middle English former, comparative of forme (“first”), from Old English forma (“first”), descended from Proto-Germanic *frumô. Parallel to prior (via Latin), as comparative form from same Proto-Indo-European root. Related to first and fore (thence before), from Pro...

FORNIX.d: An archlike or vaulted structure or fold:
FORNIX.e: Borrowing from Latin fornix (“an arch, vault”).

FORTIS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin fortis (“strong”). Doublet of fort and forte.

FORUMS.d: Plural of FORUM: A place for public discussion.

FOSSIL.d: The mineralized remains of an animal or plant.
FOSSIL.e: From French fossile, from Latin fossilis (“something which has been dug up”), from fodio (“I dig up”).

FOSTER.d: Providing parental care to children not related to oneself.
FOSTER.e:
From Middle English foster, from Old English fōstor (“food, sustenance”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōstr, from Proto-Germanic *fōstrą (“nourishment, food”).
Cognate with Middle Dutch voester (“nursemaid”), Middle Low German vôster (“food”), Old Norse fóstr (“nurturing, education...

FOUGHT.d: simple past and past participle of fight

FOULED.d: Past tense of FOUL: Covered with, or containing unclean matter; dirty.
FOULED.e:
Inherited from Middle English foul, from Old English fūl (“foul, dirty, unclean, impure, vile, corrupt, rotten, stinking, guilty”), from Proto-West Germanic *fūl, from Proto-Germanic *fūlaz (“foul, rotten”), from Proto-Indo-European *puH- (“to rot”).
Cognate with Dutch vuil (“fou...

FOUNDS.d: Plural of FOUND: Past tense of find; to establish.
FOUNDS.e: From Old English findan / Old French fonder.

FOURTH.d: The ordinal form of the number four.
FOURTH.e:
Inherited from Middle English fourthe, an alteration (due to four) of ferthe, from Old English fēorþa, fēowerþa, from Proto-West Germanic *feurþō, from Proto-Germanic *fedurþô, equivalent to four + -th (ordinal suffix).
Cognates
Compare West Frisian fjirde, Saterland Frisian fjäd...

FOWLED.d: Past tense of FOWL: A bird hunted or kept for food, grouped into landfowl (order Galliformes), also called gamefowl, and waterfowl (order Anseriformes: ducks, geese, swans, etc.), which together form the clade Galloanserae.
FOWLED.e: From Middle English foul, foghel, fowel, fowele, from Old English fugol (“bird”), from Proto-West Germanic *fugl, from Proto-Germanic *fuglaz, dissimilated variant of *fluglaz (compare Old English flugol ‘fleeing’, Mercian fluglas heofun ‘birds of the air’), from *fleuganą (“to f...

FOXIER.d: Comparative form of FOXY: The recreational drug 5-methoxy-dimethyltryptamine (5-MeO-DMT).

FOXING.d: present participle and gerund of fox

FRACAS.d: A noisy disorderly quarrel, fight, brawl, disturbance or scrap.
FRACAS.e: From French fracas, derived from fracasser, from Italian fracassare, from fra- + cassare, equivalent to Latin infra + quassare.

FRAISE.d: To put in danger, in terror, or at risk.
FRAISE.e: From Middle English fraisen, from Old English frāsian (“to ask, try, tempt”), from Proto-Germanic *fraisōną (“to attempt, try”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“to attempt, try; risk, peril”). Cognate with West Frisian freezje (“to fear”), Dutch vrezen (“to fear, dread, be afrai...

FRAMED.d: Past tense of FRAME: A border or structure; to construct.

FRAMES.d: Plural of FRAME: A border or structure; to construct.

FRANKS.d: Plural of FRANK: Open and honest.

FRATER.e:
PIE word
 *bʰréh₂tēr
Learned borrowing from Latin frāter (“brother”). Doublet of bhai, brother, bru, friar, pal, and vai.

FRAYED.d: Past tense of FRAY: To rub or wear away (something); to cause (something made of strands twisted or woven together, such as cloth or rope) to unravel through friction; also, to irritate (something) through chafing or rubbing; to chafe.
FRAYED.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English fraien (“to beat so as to cause bruising, to bruise; to crush; to rub; to wear, wear off”), borrowed from Old French fraier, freier, freiier (modern French frayer (“to clear, open up (a path, etc.); (figuratively) to find one’s way thr...

FREEZE.d: Especially of a liquid, to become solid due to low temperature.
FREEZE.e:
From Middle English fresen, from Old English frēosan (“to freeze”), from Proto-West Germanic *freusan, from Proto-Germanic *freusaną (“to frost, freeze”), from Proto-Indo-European *prews- (“to frost, freeze”).
Cognate with Scots frese (“to freeze”), North Frisian friis, friise, f...

FRENZY.d: A state of wild activity or panic.
FRENZY.e: From Middle English frensy, frenesie, from Old French frenesie, from Latin phrenesis, from Ancient Greek *φρένησις (*phrénēsis), a later equivalent of φρενῖτις (phrenîtis, “inflammation of the brain”): see frantic and frenetic. Doublet of phrenesis.

FRESCO.d: A cool, refreshing state of the air; coolness, duskiness, shade.
FRESCO.e: From Italian fresco, from Vulgar Latin *friscum, from Proto-Germanic *friskaz. Doublet of fresh and frisk.

FRIARY.d: A house or convent where friars (members of certain religious communities) live.
FRIARY.e: From friar (“brother”) in a religious order, from Latin frater (“brother”), from Latin.

FRIDGE.e:
The noun is a clipping of refrigerator, perhaps influenced by the Frigidaire brand of refrigerators, or frigerator (“(dated) refrigerator”). The spelling is likely influenced by analogy with bridge, ridge, etc. The verb is derived from the noun.
The fandom slang verb sense allude...

FRIEND.d: A person, typically someone other than a family member, spouse or lover, whose company one enjoys and towards whom one feels affection.
FRIEND.e:
From Middle English frend, freend, from Old English frēond (“friend”, literally “loving [one], lover”), from Proto-West Germanic *friund, from Proto-Germanic *frijōndz (“lover, friend”), from Proto-Indo-European *preyH- (“to love”), roughly equivalent to free + -nd.
Cognates
Cogn...

FRIEZE.d: A kind of coarse woollen cloth or stuff with a shaggy or tufted (friezed) nap on one side.
FRIEZE.e: Late Middle English, from French and Middle French frise, probably from Medieval Latin Frisia (“Frisian (wool)”) due to import via Northern ships. Or, from French friser (“to curl”)..

FRIGHT.d: A state of terror excited by the sudden appearance of danger; sudden and violent fear, usually of short duration; a sudden alarm.
FRIGHT.e:
From Middle English fright, furht, from Old English fryhtu, fyrhto (“fright, fear, dread, trembling, horrible sight”), from Proto-Germanic *furhtį̄ (“fear”), from Proto-Indo-European *pr̥k- (“to fear”).
Cognate with Scots fricht (“fright”), Old Frisian fruchte (“fright”), Low Ger...

FRIGID.e: Borrowed from Latin frīgidus (“cold”), from frīgeō (“I am cold”), from frīgus (“cold, coldness”), from Proto-Indo-European *sríHgos.

FRINGE.e: From Middle English frenge, from Old French frenge, from Vulgar Latin *frimbia, a metathesis of Latin fimbriae (“fibers, threads, fringe”, plural), of uncertain origin. Compare German Franse and Danish frynse. Displaced native Middle English fnæd (“fringe”), Middle English byrd (...

FRIZZY.d: Formed of a mass of small, tight, wiry curls; unruly or extending in all directions.

FROLIC.d: Merry, joyous, full of mirth; later especially, frolicsome, sportive, full of playful mischief.
FROLIC.e:
From Dutch vrolijk (“cheerful”), from Middle Dutch vrolijc, from Old Dutch frōlīk, from Proto-Germanic *frawalīkaz. Compare German fröhlich (“blitheful, gaily, happy, merry”).
The first element, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *frawaz, is cognate with Middle English frow (“hasty”)...

FRONTS.d: Plural of FRONT: The forward part or surface.
FRONTS.e: From Old French front, from Latin frōns.

FROSTY.e:
From Middle English frosty, forsty, from Old English forstiġ, fyrstiġ (“frosty”), from Proto-West Germanic *frostag, *frustīg, By surface analysis, frost + -y.
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian froastich (“frosty”), Dutch vorstig (“frosty”), German Low German fröstig (“frosty”),...

FROTHY.d: Foamy or churned to the point of becoming infused with bubbles.

FROWST.d: Stuffiness; stifling warmth in a room.

FROZEN.d: Having undergone the process of freezing; in ice form.
FROZEN.e: From Middle English frozen, frosen, ifrozen, variant of froren, ifroren ("frozen"; > see frorn), past participle of Middle English fresen, freosen (“to freeze”). By surface analysis, freeze + -n.

FRUGAL.d: Of something which is consumed (such as money, goods, etc.): Careful or wise in expenditure; avoiding waste.
FRUGAL.e: From Middle French, from Latin frugalis (“virtuous, thrifty”). Displaced native Old English spærhende (literally “spare-handed”).

FRUITS.d: Plural of FRUIT: The seed-bearing part of a plant.
FRUITS.e: From Old French fruit, from Latin frūctus.

FRUMPY.e: Either from frump or from Middle English frumple + -y.

FRYING.d: Present participle of FRY: A method of cooking food.
FRYING.e: From Middle English fryen, borrowed from Old French frire, from Latin frīgō (“to roast, fry”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer-. Cognate with Ancient Greek φρύγω (phrúgō, “I roast, bake”), Sanskrit भृज्जति (bhṛjjati, “to roast, grill, fry”), भृग् (bhṛg, “the crackling of fire”). R...

FUCKED.d: Past tense of FUCK: To have sexual intercourse; to copulate.
FUCKED.e: From Middle English *fukken, probably of Germanic origin: either from Old English *fuccian or Old Norse *fukka, both from Proto-Germanic *fukkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *pewǵ- (“to strike, punch, stab”). Compare windfucker and its debated etymology.

FUCOSE.d: The aldohexose (3S,4R,5R,6S)-6-methyloxane-2,3,4,5-tetrol present in several glycans and mucopolysaccharides

FUDDLE.e: Compare Dutch vod (“soft”), German dialect fuddeln (“to swindle”).

FUELED.d: Past tense of FUEL: Substance consumed to provide energy through combustion, or through chemical or nuclear reaction.
FUELED.e: From Middle English fewell, from Old French fouaille, feuaille (“firewood, kindling”), from feu (“fire”), from Late Latin focus (“fire”), from Latin focus (“hearth”). Cognate with Spanish fuego (“fire”), and Portuguese fogo (“fire”). Doublet of focus.

FUGGED.d: Past tense of FUG: A heavy, musty, stuffy or unpleasant atmosphere, usually in a poorly-ventilated area.
FUGGED.e: Unknown. Compare British slang fogo (“stench”) and English fog, or possibly a blend of funk + fog.

FULLED.d: Past tense of FULL: Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
FULLED.e:
From Middle English ful, from Old English full (“full”), from Proto-West Germanic *full, from Proto-Germanic *fullaz (“full”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós (“full”).
Germanic cognates include West Frisian fol, Low German vull, Dutch vol, German voll, Danish fuld, and Norweg...

FULLER.d: comparative form of full: more full

FULMAR.d: Either of two species of pelagic seabird in the genus Fulmarus, Fulmarus glacialis and F. glacialoides, which breed on cliffs.
FULMAR.e: From Old Norse fúll (“foul”) + már (“gull”) (cognate to English mew), evidently in reference to the foul-smelling vomit it ejects to deter predators.

FUMAGE.e: From Old French fumage, fumaige, from Latin fumus (“smoke”).

FUMBLE.e:
From late Middle English, from Low German fummeln, fommeln, fammeln (German fummeln), or Dutch fommelen.
Or, perhaps from a Scandinavian/North Germanic source; compare related Old Norse fálma, Icelandic fálma, Danish fumle, especially Swedish fumla, famla, with variants: fumbla (...

FUMIER.d: Comparative form of FUMY: Producing or filled with fumes.

FUMING.d: Present participle of FUME: A gas or vapour/vapor that is strong-smelling or dangerous to inhale.
FUMING.e: From Middle English fume, from Old French fum (“smoke, steam, vapour”), from Latin fūmus (“vapour, smoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰuh₂mós (“smoke”), from *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust”). Doublet of thymus and thymos. More at dun, dusk, dust.

FUNDED.d: simple past and past participle of fund

FUNDUS.d: The large, hollow part of an organ farthest from an opening; especially:
FUNDUS.e:
PIE word
 *bʰudʰmḗn
From Latin fundus (“bottom”). Doublet of fond and fund.

FUNGUS.d: Any member of the kingdom Fungi; a eukaryotic organism typically having chitin cell walls but no chlorophyll or plastids. Fungi may be unicellular or multicellular.

FUNKED.d: Past tense of FUNK: Foul or unpleasant smell, especially body odor.
FUNKED.e: 1620, from French dialectal (Norman) funquer, funquier (“to smoke, reek”), from Old Northern French fungier (“to smoke”), from Vulgar Latin fūmicāre, alteration of Latin fūmigāre (“to smoke, fumigate”). Related to French dialect funkière (“smoke”). More at fumigate.

FUNKIA.d: Any of the plants of the genus Funkia (now Hosta).
FUNKIA.e: From the genus name, translingual Funkia, from German Funck, after botanist H. C. Funck.

FUNNED.d: Past tense of FUN: Amusement, enjoyment or pleasure.
FUNNED.e: From Middle English fonne, fon (“foolish, simple, silly”) or fonnen (“make a fool of”), from Middle English fonne (“a fool, dupe”), probably of North Germanic origin, related to Swedish fånig (“foolish”), Swedish fåne (“a fool”), from Old Norse fáni (“vain person, swaggerer”), bu...

FUNNEL.d: A utensil in the shape of an inverted hollow cone terminating in a narrow pipe, for channeling liquids or granular material; typically used when transferring said substances from any container into ones with a significantly smaller opening.
FUNNEL.e:
From Middle English funell, fonel, probably through Old French *founel (compare Middle French fonel, Old Occitan fonilh, enfounilh), from Latin fundibulum, infundibulum (“funnel”), from infundere (“to pour in”);
in (“in”) + fundere (“to pour”); compare Breton founilh (“funnel”), ...

FURIED.d: Past tense of FURY: Extreme anger.
FURIED.e: From Middle English furie, from Old French furie, from Latin furia (“rage”).

FURIES.e: From Middle English furie, from Old French furie, from Latin furia (“rage”).

FURLED.d: Past tense of FURL: To lower, roll up and secure (something, such as a sail or flag)
FURLED.e: Perhaps from Old French ferlier, modern French ferler.

FURORE.e: Borrowed from Italian furore, from Latin furor. Doublet of furor.

FURPHY.d: A rumour, or an erroneous or improbable story.
FURPHY.e:
From Furphy (“a surname”).
The firm of Furphy and Sons (still in business today) manufactured and supplied water carts to the Australian Imperial Force in Egypt during World War I. Soldiers stood around these and talked, exchanging rumours and news. The manufacturer's name, which...

FURRED.d: Past tense of FUR: The hairy coat of various mammal species, especially when fine, soft and thick.
FURRED.e: From Middle English furre, forre, from Anglo-Norman forre, fuerre (“a case; sheath”), from Frankish *fōdar, from Proto-West Germanic *fōdr, from Proto-Germanic *fōdrą (“sheath”) (compare Old English fōdor (“sheaf”), Dutch voering (“lining”), German Futter (“lining”), Gothic 𐍆𐍉𐌳𐍂 ...

FURROW.d: A trench cut in the soil, as when plowed in order to plant a crop.
FURROW.e: From Middle English furgh, forow, from Old English furh, from Proto-West Germanic *furh, from Proto-Germanic *furhs (compare Saterland Frisian Fuurge, Dutch voor, German Furche, Swedish fåra, Norwegian Bokmål fure), from Proto-Indo-European *perḱ- (“to dig”). Compare Welsh rhych ...

FUSING.d: present participle and gerund of fuse

FUSION.d: The act of merging separate things, or the result thereof.
FUSION.e: First appears c. 1555, in a translation by Richard Eden. From Middle French fusion, from Latin fūsiōnem (the accusative of fūsiō), from fusus, past participle of fundō (“I pour, I melt”) (see also found). Doublet of foison.

FUSSED.d: Past tense of FUSS: Excessive activity, worry, bother, or talk about something.
FUSSED.e: Of unknown origin. Perhaps from Danish fjas (“nonsense”), from Middle Low German (compare German faseln (“to maunder, talk nonsense”)). Compare also fouse (“to hasten, rush, tumble, disarrange”).

FUSSES.d: Plural of FUSS: Excessive activity, worry, bother, or talk about something.
FUSSES.e: Of unknown origin. Perhaps from Danish fjas (“nonsense”), from Middle Low German (compare German faseln (“to maunder, talk nonsense”)). Compare also fouse (“to hasten, rush, tumble, disarrange”).

FUSTIC.d: A tropical American tree (Maclura tinctoria), whose wood produces a yellow dye.
FUSTIC.e: From Middle English fustik, from Middle French fustec, variant of fustet.

FUTILE.d: Incapable of producing results, useless; doomed not to be successful; not worth attempting.
FUTILE.e: From Middle French futile, from Latin fūtilis.

FUTSAL.d: A form of soccer played indoors, with five players per team.
FUTSAL.e: From Portuguese futsal, a blend of futebol de salão (literally “hall football”).

FUTURE.d: The time ahead; those moments yet to be experienced.
FUTURE.e: From Middle English future, futur, from Old French futur, from Latin futūrus, irregular future active participle of sum (“I am”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to become, be”). Cognate with Old English bēo (“I become, I will be, I am”). More at be. Displaced native Old Englis...

FUZZED.d: Past tense of FUZZ: A frizzy mass of hair or fibre.
FUZZED.e: Uncertain. Some dictionaries suggest a Germanic source; compare Low German fussig (“loose; spongy”), Dutch voos (“unsound; rotten”). Others, such as Webster's New College Dictionary, suggest a back-formation from fuzzy. The Oxford English Dictionary suggests, “Perhaps imitative o...

FUZZES.d: Plural of FUZZ: A frizzy mass of hair or fibre.
FUZZES.e: Uncertain. Some dictionaries suggest a Germanic source; compare Low German fussig (“loose; spongy”), Dutch voos (“unsound; rotten”). Others, such as Webster's New College Dictionary, suggest a back-formation from fuzzy. The Oxford English Dictionary suggests, “Perhaps imitative o...

FYLFOT.d: A swastika, especially one with the arms bent in an anticlockwise direction.
FYLFOT.e: Uncertain, but likely from Middle English fillen (“to fill”) (from Old English fyllan) + fot (“foot”) (from Old English fōt), in reference to its use as a design to be placed at the bottom of stained-glass windows.

GABBED.d: Past tense of GAB: Idle chatter.
GABBED.e: Inherited from Middle English gab, gabbe, from Old Norse gabb (“jest, mockery”) (whence also Old French gab, gap (“mockery, derision, scorn”)). Cognate with Icelandic gabb (“hoax”).

GABBER.d: Comparative form of GAB: Idle chatter.
GABBER.e: Inherited from Middle English gab, gabbe, from Old Norse gabb (“jest, mockery”) (whence also Old French gab, gap (“mockery, derision, scorn”)). Cognate with Icelandic gabb (“hoax”).

GABBLE.d: To talk fast, idly, foolishly, or without meaning.
GABBLE.e: From gab + -le. Cognate with Saterland Frisian gabbelje (“to mock”), Dutch gabbelen (“to chatter, babble”), German Low German gabbeln (“to mock”).

GABBRO.d: Originally, a kind of serpentine; now generally a coarsely crystalline, igneous rock consisting of lamellar pyroxene and labradorite.

GABIES.d: Plural of GABY: A female given name from French.

GABION.d: A cylindrical basket or cage of wicker which was filled with earth or stones and used in fortifications and other engineering work (a precursor to the sandbag).
GABION.e: Borrowed from Italian gabbione, augmentative of gabbia (“cage”), itself from Latin cavea (whence also English jail, English cajole), from Latin cavus (whence also English cage, English cave).

GABLET.d: A small gable, or gable-shaped canopy, formed over a tabernacle, niche, etc.

GADDED.d: Past tense of GAD: An exclamation roughly equivalent to by God, goodness gracious, for goodness' sake.

GADDER.d: Comparative form of GAD: An exclamation roughly equivalent to by God, goodness gracious, for goodness' sake.

GADFLY.d: Any dipterous (“two-winged”) insect or fly of the family Oestridae (commonly known as a botfly) or Tabanidae (horsefly), noted for irritating animals by buzzing about them, and biting them to suck their blood; a gadbee.
GADFLY.e: From gad (“(obsolete) sharp point, spike; (dialectal) sharp-pointed rod for driving cattle, horses, etc., goad”) + fly, in the sense of a fly which irritates cattle, etc., by biting them, similar to the prodding of a goad. Gad is derived from Middle English gad, gadde (“metal spi...

GADGET.d: A thing whose name cannot be remembered; thingamajig, doohickey.
GADGET.e: Unknown. First used in print by Robert Brown in 1886 (see quote in definition section). Might come from French gâchette or gagée, or from the French family name Gaget, an industrialist who produced promotional gadgets in collaboration with the project to build the statue of Liber...

GADOID.d: Of or pertaining to cod or to the Gadidae family of related fish.
GADOID.e: From modern Latin gadus, from Ancient Greek γάδος (gádos, “cod”). See -oid.

GAGGED.d: Past tense of GAG: A device to restrain speech, such as a rag in the mouth secured with tape or a rubber ball threaded onto a cord or strap.
GAGGED.e: The noun is from Early Modern English gagge; the verb is from Middle English gaggen. Possibly imitative or perhaps related to or influenced by Old Norse gag-háls ("with head thrown backwards"; > Norwegian dialectal gaga (“bent backwards”)). The intransitive sense "to retch" is fr...

GAGGER.d: Comparative form of GAG: A device to restrain speech, such as a rag in the mouth secured with tape or a rubber ball threaded onto a cord or strap.
GAGGER.e: The noun is from Early Modern English gagge; the verb is from Middle English gaggen. Possibly imitative or perhaps related to or influenced by Old Norse gag-háls ("with head thrown backwards"; > Norwegian dialectal gaga (“bent backwards”)). The intransitive sense "to retch" is fr...

GAGGLE.d: A group of geese when they are on the ground or on the water.
GAGGLE.e: From Middle English gagelen (“to cackle; cackle like a goose”). Compare Dutch gaggelen (“to cackle”), Icelandic gagl (“small goose; gosling”), Norwegian Nynorsk gagl (“wild goose”).

GAGING.d: Present participle of GAGE: To bind (someone) by pledge or security; to engage.
GAGING.e: From Middle English gage, from later Old French or early Middle French gager (verb), (also guagier in Old French) gage (noun), ultimately from Frankish *waddi, from Proto-Germanic *wadją (whence English wed). Doublet of wage, from the same origin through the Old Northern French v...

GAIETY.d: The state of being happy or merry.
GAIETY.e: Borrowed from Middle French gaieté, from gai. By surface analysis, gay + -ety.

GAIJIN.e: From Japanese 外人 (gaijin, “foreigner”), from Middle Chinese 外人 (ngwajᴴ nyin). Compare Mandarin 外人 (wàirén), from Old Chinese 外人 (*ŋʷaːds njin, “foreigner, outsider” < “non-relative”), from 外 (wài, “outside, outer”) + 人 (rén, “person”).

GAITED.d: Past tense of GAIT: Manner of walking or stepping; bearing or carriage while moving on legs.
GAITED.e: From Middle English gate (“way”), from Old Norse gata (“road”), from Proto-Germanic *gatwǭ. Doublet of gate.

GALAGO.d: Any of several species of small, nocturnal and arboreal African primates, of the family Galagidae, with a catlike head and very large, translucent eyes.
GALAGO.e: Scientific Latin / translingual Galago (as a genus name), probably from Wolof golo (“monkey”).

GALAXY.d: The Milky Way; the apparent band of concentrated stars which appears in the night sky over earth.
GALAXY.e: From Middle English galaxye, galaxie, from Old French galaxie, from Latin galaxias, from Ancient Greek γαλαξίας (galaxías, “Milky Way”), shortening of γαλαξίας κύκλος (galaxías kúklos, “milky circle”), from γάλα (gála, “milk”).

GALENA.d: A mineral, lead sulphide (PbS), mined as an ore for lead.
GALENA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin galēna (“dross from smelting lead”).

GALLED.d: Past tense of GAL: Abbreviation of gallon.

GALLER.d: Comparative form of GAL: Abbreviation of gallon.

GALLEY.d: A long, slender ship propelled primarily by oars, whether having masts and sails or not; usually a rowed warship used in the Mediterranean from the 16th century until the modern era.
GALLEY.e: From Middle English galeie, from Old French galee, from Latin galea, from Byzantine Greek γάλεα (gálea) of unknown origin, probably from Ancient Greek γαλέη (galéē), a kind of a small fish, from γαλεός (galeós, “dog-fish or small shark”).

GALLON.d: A unit of volume, equivalent to eight pints
GALLON.e: From Middle English gallon, galoun, galun, from Old Northern French galun, galon (“liquid measure”) (compare Old French jalon), from Late Latin galum, galus (“measure of wine”), from Vulgar Latin *galla (“vessel”), possibly from Gaulish *galla, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European...

GALLOP.d: The fastest gait of a horse, a two-beat stride during which all four legs are off the ground simultaneously.
GALLOP.e: From Middle English galopen (“to gallop”), from Old French galoper (compare modern French galoper), from Frankish *wala hlaupan (“to run well”), from *wala (“well”) + *hlaupan (“to run”), from Proto-Germanic *hlaupaną (“to run, leap, spring”), from Proto-Indo-European *klaup-, *k...

GALOOT.e: From Quranic Arabic جالُوت (jālūt, pronounced galūt in Egyptian Arabic), proper name equivalent to English Goliath, giant warrior of the ancient Philistine ethnicity; cf. connotations of derogatory uses of English Philistine. Doublet of goliath.

GALOSH.d: An overshoe or boot worn in wet weather:
GALOSH.e:
From Middle English galoche, from Old French galoche (“shoe with a wooden sole”), but further history is uncertain.
further theories
* From Vulgar Latin *galopium or Late Latin calopedia (“a wooden shoe; a shoe with a wooden sole”), from Ancient Greek κᾱλοπόδιον (kālopódion), dim...

GAMBIT.d: An opening in chess in which a minor piece or a pawn is sacrificed to gain an advantage.
GAMBIT.e: From Italian gambetto (“act of tripping; gambit”), from Italian gamba (“leg”), from Late Latin gamba.

GAMBLE.e: From earlier gamel, from Middle English *gamlen, *gamelen, variant of Middle English gamenen, from Old English gæmnian, gamnian, gamenian (“to joke; play”), related to Old English gamen (“joy; mirth; pleasure; entertainment; pastime; sport; game”), equivalent to game + -le. Compa...

GAMBOL.d: To move about playfully; to frolic.
GAMBOL.e: From earlier gambolde, from Middle French gambade (modern gambade).

GAMEST.d: superlative form of game: most game

GAMETE.d: A reproductive cell (sperm in males or eggs in females), having only half of a complete set of chromosomes.
GAMETE.e: From Ancient Greek γαμετή (gametḗ, “wife”), γαμέτης (gamétēs, “husband”), ultimately from γάμος (gámos, “marriage”).

GAMGEE.e: From Gamgee Tissue, a surgical dressing containing cotton wool, invented by Dr. Joseph Sampson Gamgee in Birmingham, England, in 1880.

GAMIER.d: Comparative form of GAMY: Alternative spelling of gamey.

GAMIFY.d: To convert into the form of a game.

GAMINE.d: A (usually female) street urchin; a homeless girl.

GAMING.d: present participle and gerund of game

GAMMON.d: A cut of quick-cured pork leg.
GAMMON.e: From Middle English *gammon, gambon, from Old French gambon (compare modern French jambon (“ham”)), from gambe (“leg”), from Late Latin gamba, from Ancient Greek καμπή (kampḗ). Doublet of jambon and jamon.

GANDER.e:
From Middle English gandre, from Old English gandra, ganra (“gander”), from Proto-West Germanic *ganʀō, from Proto-Germanic *ganzô (“gander”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰh₂éns (“goose”). The meaning "a look" is derived from the image of craning one's neck like a goose.
Cognates
...

GANNET.d: Any of three species of large seabird in the genus Morus, of the family Sulidae. They have black and white bodies and long pointed wings, and hunt for fish by plunge diving and pursuing their prey underwater.
GANNET.e:
From Middle English ganet, gante, from Old English ganot, from Proto-West Germanic *ganat, *ganatō, from Proto-Germanic *ganatuz, *ganutô (“gander”), ultimately related to Proto-Germanic *ganzô.
Cognates
Cognate with Dutch gent, Middle Low German gante, German Ganter, Ganser, all...

GANOID.d: Having a smooth, shining surface, as if polished or enameled: specifically applied to those scales or plates of fishes which are generally of an angular form and composed of a bony or hard horny tissue overlaid with enamel.

GANTRY.d: A framework of steel bars resting on side supports to bridge over or around something.
GANTRY.e: From earlier gauntree, possibly from dialectal gaun (“gallon”) + tree, perhaps as a reinterpretation of Middle English *gaunter, from Old Northern French gantier, from Late Latin cantarium, from Latin canterius (“trellis, sort of frame”).

GAOLED.d: Past tense of GAOL: Dated spelling of jail.
GAOLED.e: From Middle English gayole, gaiol, gaylle, gaille, gayle, gaile, via Old French gaiole, gayolle, gaole, from Medieval Latin gabiola, for Late Latin caveola, a diminutive of Latin cavea (“cavity, coop, cage”). See also cage.

GAPING.d: Present participle of GAPE: To open the mouth wide, especially involuntarily, as in a yawn, anger, or surprise.
GAPING.e: From Middle English gapen, from Old Norse gapa (“to gape”) (compare Swedish gapa, Danish gabe), from Proto-Germanic *gapōną (descendants Middle English geapen, Dutch gapen, German gaffen), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰеh₂b-. Cognates include Russian зяпа (zjapa).

GAPPED.d: Past tense of GAP: An opening in anything made by breaking or parting.
GAPPED.e: From Middle English gap, gappe, from Old Norse gap (“an empty space, gap, chasm”), from gapa (“to gape, scream”), from Proto-Germanic *gapōną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₂- (“to open wide, gape”). Related to Danish gab (“an expanse, space, gap”), Old English ġeap (“open space,...

GAPPER.d: Comparative form of GAP: An opening in anything made by breaking or parting.
GAPPER.e: From Middle English gap, gappe, from Old Norse gap (“an empty space, gap, chasm”), from gapa (“to gape, scream”), from Proto-Germanic *gapōną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₂- (“to open wide, gape”). Related to Danish gab (“an expanse, space, gap”), Old English ġeap (“open space,...

GARAGE.d: A building (or section of a building) used to store a car or cars, tools and other miscellaneous items.
GARAGE.e: Borrowed from French garage (“keeping under cover, protection, shelter”), derivative of French garer (“to keep under cover, dock, shunt, guard, keep”), from Middle French garer, garrer, guerrer; partly from Old French garir, warir (from Old Frankish *warjan); and partly from Old ...

GARBED.d: Past tense of GARB: Fashion, style of dressing oneself up.
GARBED.e: From Middle French garbe ("graceful outline, silhouette"; > Modern French galbe), from Italian garbo (“grace, elegance”), from Germanic (compare Old High German garwi, garawi (“dress, equipment, preparation”), Middle High German gerwe (“outfitting, jewelry, clothing, robe, regali...

GARBLE.d: To pick out such parts (of a text) as may serve a purpose not intended by the original author; to mutilate; to pervert.
GARBLE.e: From Middle English garbelen, from Anglo-Norman garbeler (“to sift”), from Medieval Latin garbellare (or a similar Italian word), from Arabic غَرْبَلَ (ḡarbala, “to sift”).

GARDEN.d: An outdoor area containing one or more types of plants, usually plants grown for food or ornamental purposes.
GARDEN.e: From Middle English gardyn, garden, from Anglo-Norman gardin, from Frankish *gardin-, oblique stem of *gardō (“enclosure, yard”), from Proto-Germanic *gardô (“enclosure, garden, house”), whence also inherited English yard. (compare Old French jart alongside jardin, Medieval Latin...

GARGET.d: An inflammation on a cow's or sheep's udder; synonym of mastitis.
GARGET.e: From Middle English garget, gargate (“throat”), from Old French gargate. Compare gorge.

GARGLE.d: To clean one's mouth by holding water or some other liquid in the back of the mouth and blowing air out from the lungs.
GARGLE.e: From French gargouiller (“to gargle”), from Old French gargouille, gargole (“gutter, throat”). Compare gargoyle and Spanish garganta. Displaced non-native Middle English gargargisen (“to gargle”) from Latin, and native Old English swillan (“to gargle”) (ancestor of English swill)...

GARISH.d: Overly ostentatious; so colorful as to be in bad taste.
GARISH.e: Unknown, possibly from obsolete Middle English gawren (“to stare”) which is of uncertain origin, probably from Old Norse gá (“to watch, heed”) or gaurr (“rough fellow”) (Proto-Indo-European *gʰow-rós, from *gʰew- (“to be angry”)). Compare with English gaw.

GARLIC.d: A plant, Allium sativum, related to the onion, having a pungent bulb much used in cooking.
GARLIC.e: Inherited from Middle English garlek, garlik, from Old English gārlēac (“garlic”, literally “spear-leek”), from gār ("spear"; in reference to its sharp, tapering leaves) + lēac (“leek”). Cognate with Scots garlic (“garlic”), Faroese geirleykur (“garlic”), Icelandic geirlaukur (“g...

GARNER.d: A granary; a store of grain.
GARNER.e: From Middle English gerner, from Old French gernier, guernier, variant of grenier, from Latin grānārium (“granary”). Doublet of granary.

GARNET.d: A hard transparent mineral that is often used as gemstones and abrasives.
GARNET.e: From Middle English gernet, granate, from Old French grenate, from grenat (“pomegranate red”). Doublet of grenade.

GARRET.d: An attic or semi-finished room just beneath the roof of a house.
GARRET.e: From Middle English garett, garite, from Old French garite, guerite (“watchtower”), from garir, guarir (“to defend, protect”) (compare English garrison), ultimately of Germanic origin (see English garage). Doublet of guerite.

GARTER.d: A band worn around the leg to hold up a sock or stocking.
GARTER.e: From Middle English garter, from Old Northern French gartier, from Old French garet (compare Old French jartier, from jaret), from Gaulish *garrā, from Proto-Celtic *garros (“calf, shank”) (compare Cornish gar, Cornish gar,Middle Welsh garr, Old Irish gairr). Cognate with French ...

GASBAG.d: A bag or bladder to hold a reservoir of gas, as in a hot-air balloon.

GASHED.d: Past tense of GASH: A deep cut.
GASHED.e: Alteration of older garsh, from Middle English garsen, from Old French garser, jarsier (Modern French gercer), from Vulgar Latin *charaxāre, from Ancient Greek χαρακτήρ (kharaktḗr, “engraver”).

GASHES.d: Plural of GASH: A deep cut.
GASHES.e: Alteration of older garsh, from Middle English garsen, from Old French garser, jarsier (Modern French gercer), from Vulgar Latin *charaxāre, from Ancient Greek χαρακτήρ (kharaktḗr, “engraver”).

GASIFY.d: To convert into gas, or an aeriform fluid, as by the application of heat, or by chemical processes.

GASKET.d: A length of rope or canvas band used for reefing a sail, or holding a stowed sail in place.
GASKET.e: Perhaps from Middle French garcette (“gasket”), from Old French garce (“young woman”), feminization of garçon.

GASMAN.d: A worker for a company that supplies gas (in the sense of the gaseous fuel), especially one who visits premises to read the meter, test appliances etc.

GASPED.d: Past tense of GASP: To draw in the breath suddenly, as if from a shock.
GASPED.e: From Middle English gaspen, gayspen (“to gape, outbreathe”), related to and likely derived from Old Norse geispa (“to yawn”) or its descendant Danish gispe, which may be related to gapa (“to gape”).

GASSED.d: Past tense of GAS: Matter in an intermediate state between liquid and plasma that can be contained only if it is fully surrounded by a solid (or in a bubble of liquid, or held together by gravitational pull); it can condense into a liquid, or can (rarely) become a solid directly by deposition.
GASSED.e: Borrowed from Dutch gas, coined by chemist Jan Baptist van Helmont in Ortus Medicinae. Derived from Ancient Greek χάος (kháos, “chasm, void, empty space”); perhaps also inspired by geest (“breath, vapour, spirit”). Doublet of chaos. First attested in 1648.

GASSER.d: One who gasses, or poisons with gas.

GATEAU.e: Borrowed from French gâteau. Doublet of wastel.

GATHER.e: From Middle English gaderen, from Old English gaderian (“to gather, assemble”), from Proto-West Germanic *gadurōn (“to bring together, unite, gather”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰedʰ- (“to unite, assemble, keep”).

GATING.d: Present participle of GATE: A doorlike structure outside a house.
GATING.e:
From Middle English gate, gat, ȝate, ȝeat, from Old English ġeat (“gate”), from Proto-West Germanic *gat, from Proto-Germanic *gatą (“hole, opening”).
See also Old Norse gat, Swedish and Dutch gat, Low German Gaat, Gööt.

GAUCHE.d: Awkward or lacking in social graces; bumbling; apt to make gaffes.
GAUCHE.e: Borrowed from French gauche (“left, awkward”), from gauchir (“to veer, turn”), from Old French gaucher (“to trample, walk clumsily”), from Frankish *walkan (“to full, trample”), from Proto-Germanic *walkaną (“to full, roll up”). Akin to Old High German walchan (“to knead”), Old E...

GAUCHO.d: A cowboy of the South American pampas.
GAUCHO.e: Borrowed from Spanish gaucho, of uncertain origin.

GAUGER.e: From Middle English gauger, gager, equivalent to gauge + -er. Compare Old French gaugeur, jaugëor.

GAVIAL.e: From Hindi घड़ियाल (ghaṛiyāl). Doublet of gharial.

GAWKED.d: Past tense of GAWK: A cuckoo; (sometimes by extension) any gawky bird.
GAWKED.e:
From a variant of gowk, from Middle English gowke, goke, from Old Norse gaukr (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Germanic *gaukaz (“cuckoo”). Cognate with Danish gøg, Swedish gök, German Gauch, Old English ġēac.
Compare also French gauche, and English gawky and gallock.

GAYDOM.d: The collective gay experience, community, and culture.

GAZEBO.d: A belvedere, either a type of summer-house or a roofed, detached porch-like structure, usually in a yard, park or lawn.
GAZEBO.e: Possibly from gaze + Latin conjugation ending -ēbō (as in vidēbō); or possibly from Arabic قَصَبَة (qaṣaba) (whence also casbah), refashioned after gaze.

GAZING.d: Present participle of GAZE: To stare intently or earnestly.
GAZING.e: From Middle English gasen; akin to Swedish dialectal gasa and Gothic 𐌿𐍃𐌲𐌰𐌹𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽 (usgaisjan, “to terrify”).

GEARED.d: Past tense of GEAR: Equipment or paraphernalia, especially that used for an athletic endeavor.
GEARED.e: From Middle English gere, a borrowing from Old Norse gervi, from Proto-Germanic *garwijaną (“to prepare”). See also adjective yare, yar from the same root via Old English.

GEEING.d: Present participle of GEE: A general exclamation of surprise or frustration.
GEEING.e: A shortening of Jesus, perhaps as in the oath by Jesus.

GEISHA.d: A Japanese female entertainer skilled in various arts such as tea ceremony, dancing, singing and calligraphy.
GEISHA.e: Borrowed from Japanese 芸者(げいしゃ) (geisha, “artisan”), from Middle Chinese 藝 (MC ngjiejH, “art, craft”) + 者 (MC tsyaeX, “-er”).

GELATI.e: Borrowed from Italian gelati, the plural form of gelato, from Latin gelātus, derived from gelū (“frost, chill”), ultimately from the Proto-Indo-European *gel- (“cold”).

GELATO.d: An Italian variant of ice cream made from milk and sugar, combined with other flavourings. The ingredients are supercooled while stirring to break up ice crystals as they form.
GELATO.e: Borrowed from Italian gelato (“ice cream”), from Latin gelātus, derived from gelū (“frost, chill”), ultimately from the Proto-Indo-European *gel- (“cold”).

GELCAP.d: a pill where the medicine is held inside gelatin capsules

GELDED.e: From Middle English geld and reinforced by Medieval Latin geldum, both from Old English geld, ġield (“payment, tribute”), from Proto-West Germanic *geld, from Proto-Germanic *geldą (“reward, gift, money”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰeldʰ- (“to pay”). Probably reinforced by gelt ...

GELLED.d: Past tense of GEL: A semi-solid to almost solid colloid of a solid and a liquid, such as jelly, cheese or opal.
GELLED.e: Coined by Thomas Graham in the mid 19th century as a clipping of gelatin, from French gélatine, from Italian gelatina, diminutive form of gelata (“iced”), from Latin gelata, past participle of gelo (“to freeze”), from gelu (“frost”), from Proto-Indo-European *gel- (“cold”). For t...

GEMMED.d: Past tense of GEM: A precious stone, usually of substantial monetary value or prized for its beauty or shine.
GEMMED.e: Inherited from Middle English gemme, gimme, yimme, ȝimme, from Old English ġimm, from Proto-West Germanic *gimmu (“gem”) and Old French gemme (“gem”), both from Latin gemma (“a swelling bud; jewel, gem”). Doublet of gemma and Gemma.

GEMMER.d: Comparative form of GEM: A precious stone, usually of substantial monetary value or prized for its beauty or shine.
GEMMER.e: Inherited from Middle English gemme, gimme, yimme, ȝimme, from Old English ġimm, from Proto-West Germanic *gimmu (“gem”) and Old French gemme (“gem”), both from Latin gemma (“a swelling bud; jewel, gem”). Doublet of gemma and Gemma.

GENDER.e: From Middle English gendre, borrowed from Old French gendre, borrowed from Latin genere (“type, kind”). Doublet of genre and genus. The verb developed after the noun.

GENIAL.e: From Middle French génial, from Latin geniālis (“of or pertaining to marriage; festive, genial”), from genius (“guardian spirit”) + -ālis.

GENIUS.d: Someone possessing extraordinary intelligence or skill; especially somebody who has demonstrated this by a creative or original work in science, music, art, etc.
GENIUS.e: From Latin genius (“inborn nature; a tutelary deity of a person or place; wit, brilliance”), from gignō (“to beget, produce”), Old Latin genō, from the Proto-Indo-European root *ǵenh₁-. Doublet of genio. See also genus.

GENOME.d: The complete genetic information (either DNA or, in some viruses, RNA) of an organism.
GENOME.e: From earlier genom, from German Genom, coined by German botanist Hans Winkler in 1920 as a blend of Gen (“gene”) + Chromosom (“chromosome”). By surface analysis, gen(e) + -ome, or a blend of gen(e) + (chromos)ome. Spelling altered to reflect the surface analysis.

GENTLE.d: Tender and amiable; of a considerate or kindly disposition.
GENTLE.e: From Middle English gentil (“courteous, noble”), from Old French gentil (“high-born, noble”), from Latin gentilis (“of the same family or clan”), from gens (“[Roman] clan”). Doublet of gentile, genteel, and jaunty.

GENTOO.d: A non-Muslim inhabitant of India, a Hindu; specifically, in Southern India, an ethnic-Telugu.
GENTOO.e: Of Anglo-Indian origin (17th century), apparently a borrowing from Portuguese gentio (“heathen”) (compare gentile (“pagan”)).

GENTRY.e: From Old French genterie (“noble people collectively; nobility of character or manners”), from gent (“well-born”) + -erie.

GEOTAG.d: To augment (a photograph or other item) with metadata indicating a geographic location.

GERBIL.d: A member of one of several species of small, jumping, mouselike rodents of the subfamily Gerbillinae, native to Africa, India, and Southern Europe.
GERBIL.e: From French gerbille, from Latin gerbo, from Arabic جَرْبُوع (jarbūʕ) or يَرْبُوع (yarbūʕ, “jerboa”). Doublet of jerboa.

GERUND.d: A verbal form that functions as a verbal noun. (In English, a gerund has the same spelling as a present participle, but functions differently; however, this distinction may be ambiguous or unclear and so is no longer made in some modern texts such as A Comprehensive Grammar of the English Language and The Cambridge Grammar of the English Language)
GERUND.e: From Latin gerundium, from gerendus (“which is to be carried out”), future passive participle (gerundive) of gerō (“carry, bear”).

GETTER.d: One who, or that which, gets.

GEWGAW.d: A showy trifle, a toy; a showy trinket, ornament or decoration.
GEWGAW.e: From earlier gugaw, gygaw, from Middle English givegove (“gewgaw, trifle”), a reduplication of Middle English give, geove (“gift”), from Old English giefu, geofu, geafu (“gift”), from Proto-Germanic *gebō (“gift”). Compare Icelandic gyligjöf (“showy gifts, gewgaw”). More at give.

GEYSER.d: A boiling natural spring which throws forth jets of water, mud, etc., at frequent intervals, driven upwards by the expansive power of steam.
GEYSER.e: From the name of a particular Icelandic geyser which is mentioned as early as the 1760s in The Annual Register, as “Geyser, a wonderful spring in the valley of Haukadal”. From Geysir (“Gusher”), the Icelandic name of the hot spring in Iceland (see Wikipedia), from the verb geysa ...

GHAZAL.d: A poetic form mostly used for love poetry in Middle Eastern, South, and Central Asian poetry.
GHAZAL.e: From Persian غزل (ġazal), from Arabic غَزَلَ (ḡazala, “to display love to the loved one via speech, to exchange talk of love with the loved one”).

GHETTO.d: An (often walled) area of a city in which Jews are concentrated by force and law. (Used particularly of areas in medieval Italy and in Nazi-controlled Europe.)
GHETTO.e: Borrowed from the name of the Venetian Ghetto, whose etymology and original source language is uncertain. Compare Italian ghetto.

GIAOUR.d: A non-Muslim, especially a Christian, an infidel; especially as used by Turkish people with particular reference to Christians such as Greeks, Armenians, Bulgarians, Serbs and Assyrians.
GIAOUR.e: Borrowed from French giaour, from Ottoman Turkish كاور (gâvur), from Classical Persian گَاوُر (gāwur), a variant of گَبْر (gabr, “infidel”); see there for more. Doublet of Gheber and Gueber.

GIBBED.d: Past tense of GIB: A castrated male cat or ferret.
GIBBED.e: Unknown (14th century). Perhaps abbreviated from Gilbert, the name of the cat in the medieval fables of Reynard the Fox, Romaunt of the Rose, and so on.

GIBBER.e: Uncertain; usually regarded as a back-formation from gibberish (see gibberish for more).

GIBBET.d: An upright post with a crosspiece used for execution and subsequent public display.
GIBBET.e: From Middle English gibet, from Old French gibet (French gibet), either from Frankish *gibb (“forked stick”) or from Latin gibbus (“hunchbacked”).

GIBBON.d: A small ape of the family Hylobatidae with long limbs, which they use to travel through rainforests by swinging from branch to branch.
GIBBON.e: Reborrowing from French gibbon, folk etymology (compare English Gibbon) ultimately from a Northern Aslian language (compare Batek kəboɲ).

GIBING.d: Present participle of GIBE: Alternative spelling of gybe.

GIBLET.d: The edible viscera of a bird.

GIFTED.d: Endowed with special, in particular intellectual, abilities.

GIGGED.d: Past tense of GIG: Originally (music), a performing engagement by a musician or musical group; (by extension, film, television, theater) a job or role for a performer.
GIGGED.e: The etymology of the noun is unknown, but compare Old French gigue (“a fiddle”). The verb is derived from the noun.

GIGGER.d: Comparative form of GIG: Originally (music), a performing engagement by a musician or musical group; (by extension, film, television, theater) a job or role for a performer.
GIGGER.e: The etymology of the noun is unknown, but compare Old French gigue (“a fiddle”). The verb is derived from the noun.

GIGGLE.d: To laugh gently in a playful, nervous, or affected manner.
GIGGLE.e:
Early 16th century, probably of imitative origin.
Or, perhaps a frequentative based on dialectal English gig (“to creak”), from Middle English gigen (“to make a creaking sound”) + -le; or perhaps of Dutch or Low German origin: compare Saterland Frisian güüchelje (“to giggle”), We...

GIGOLO.d: A man who has a sexual relationship with a woman from whom he receives payment; a prostitute.
GIGOLO.e: First attested in English in 1922. From French gigolo (“young lover kept by an older woman”), first attested in that sense in 1904 (attested since 1850 in the sense “Amant de cœur, compagnon d'une gigolette", and since 1894 in the sense “elegant young man whose means of livelihoo...

GILDED.d: Past tense of GILD: To cover with a thin layer of gold; to cover with gold leaf.
GILDED.e: From Middle English gilden, gulden, from Old English gyldan (“to gild, to cover with a thin layer of gold”), from Proto-West Germanic *gulþijan, from Proto-Germanic *gulþijaną, from Proto-Germanic *gulþą (“gold”).

GILGAI.d: A small concavity or depression between ridges, where rainwater gathers.

GILLIE.d: A male attendant of a Scottish Highland chief.
GILLIE.e: From Scottish Gaelic gille (“helper”), from Middle Irish gilla (“youth, young man; boy, male child; messenger, page, servant”), possibly borrowed from Old Norse gildr (“brawny, stout; of full worth”). Compare Irish giolla (“boy”).

GIMBAL.d: A device for suspending something, such as a ship's compass, so that it will remain level when its support is tipped.
GIMBAL.e: Alteration of gemel, from Old French gemel, jumel (“twin”) (French jumeau), from Latin gemellus.

GIMBLE.e: Compared by the EDD to dialectal Swedish gimla (“to move the lips in an unseemly manner, to make a wry face, to move the lips awry”). Compare also North Frisian gēmeli (“to move the lips before laughing”). Nall compares Old English ginian; the hard g in this form needs explanatio...

GIMLET.d: A small screw-tipped tool for boring holes.
GIMLET.e:
From Middle English gimlet etc., from Old French guinbelet, guimbelet, guibelet, probably a diminutive of the Anglo-Norman wimble, a variation of guimble (“drill”), from the Middle Low German wiemel; continued in New French as gibelet.
Cocktail either named after the tool, in ref...

GIMPED.d: Past tense of GIMP: A narrow ornamental fabric or braid of silk, wool, or cotton, often stiffened with metallic wire or coarse cord running through it, used as trimming for dresses, curtains, furniture, etc. Also guimpe.
GIMPED.e:
Attested since about 1660, perhaps from Dutch gimp or French guimpe, and likely from Old French guimpre, a variant of guipure, a kind of trimming.
The regional sense of "gumption" is attested since about 1905, and may have developed due to the reinforced nature of gimp cord, or p...

GINGER.d: The pungent aromatic rhizome of a tropical Asian herb, Zingiber officinale, used as a spice and as a stimulant and acarminative.
GINGER.e:
Etymology tree
Old Tamil 𑀇𑀜𑁆𑀘𑀺 (iñci)
Proto-Dravidian *wēr
Old Tamil 𑀯𑁂𑀭𑁆 (vēr)
Old Tamil 𑀇𑀜𑁆𑀘𑀺𑀯𑁂𑀭𑁆 (iñcivēr)bor.
Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀲𑀺𑀁𑀕𑀺𑀯𑁂𑀭 (siṃgivera)der.
Ancient Greek ζιγγίβερις (zingíberis)bor.
Late Latin zingiberi
Late Latin gingiberbor.
Proto-West Germanic *gingiberō
Old E...

GINKGO.d: Ginkgo biloba, a tree native to China with small, fan-shaped leaves and edible seeds.
GINKGO.e: From Japanese 銀杏 (ginkyō), from Chinese 銀杏／银杏 (yínxìng, “silver apricot”). Ginkgo is the name that is printed in Amoenitatum exoticarum politico-physico-medicarum Fasciculi V … (1712) authored by Engelbert Kaempfer, the first Westerner to see the species. In his way of transcript...

GINNED.d: Past tense of GIN: A colourless non-aged alcoholic liquor made by distilling fermented grains such as barley, corn, oats or rye with juniper berries; the base for many cocktails.
GINNED.e: Abbreviation of geneva, alteration of Dutch genever (“juniper”) from Old French genevre (modern French genièvre), from Vulgar Latin ziniperus, from Latin iūniperus (“juniper”). Hence gin rummy (first attested 1941).

GINNER.d: Comparative form of GIN: A colourless non-aged alcoholic liquor made by distilling fermented grains such as barley, corn, oats or rye with juniper berries; the base for many cocktails.
GINNER.e: Abbreviation of geneva, alteration of Dutch genever (“juniper”) from Old French genevre (modern French genièvre), from Vulgar Latin ziniperus, from Latin iūniperus (“juniper”). Hence gin rummy (first attested 1941).

GIRDED.d: Past tense of GIRD: To bind with a flexible rope or cord.
GIRDED.e: From Middle English girden, gerden, gürden, from Old English gyrdan (“to put a belt around, to put a girdle around”), from Proto-Germanic *gurdijaną (“to gird”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰerdʰ-. Cognate with West Frisian gurdzje, girdzje, Dutch gorden, German gürten, Swedish gj...

GIRDLE.d: That which girds, encircles, or encloses; a circumference.
GIRDLE.e:
From Middle English girdel, gerdel, gurdel, from Old English gyrdel, from Proto-West Germanic *gurdil, from Proto-Germanic *gurdilaz (“girdle, belt”), equivalent to gird + -le.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Gäddel (“belt”), West Frisian gurdle, gurle, gurl (“belt”), Dut...

GIRLIE.d: A magazine targeting an adult male audience and containing nude or seminude photographs of women.

GIRTED.d: Past tense of GIRT: A horizontal structural member of post and beam architecture, typically attached to bridge two or more vertical members such as corner posts.

GITTER.d: Comparative form of GIT: A silly, incompetent, stupid, or annoying person (usually a man).
GITTER.e: From Middle English get (“[illegitimate] offspring”). A southern variant of Scots get (“illegitimate child, brat”), related to beget.

GIVING.d: present participle and gerund of give

GLAIVE.d: A light lance with a long, sharp-pointed head.
GLAIVE.e: From Middle English gleyve (“lance, glaive”), from Old French glaive (“lance; sword”), from Late Latin glavus. The further etymology is uncertain; one possibility is that glavus reflects Latin gladius (“sword”) crossed with clāva (“club”); another is that it derives from a re-cro...

GLANCE.d: To turn (one's eyes or look) at something, often briefly.
GLANCE.e:
The verb is derived from Late Middle English glenchen (“of a blow: to strike obliquely, glance; of a person: to turn quickly aside, dodge”) [and other forms], a blend of:
* Old French glacier, glachier, glaichier (“to slide; to slip”) (whence also Middle English glacen (“of a blo...

GLASSY.d: Of or like glass, especially in being smooth and somewhat reflective.
GLASSY.e: From Middle English glasy, equivalent to glass + -y. Compare Saterland Frisian glääsich (“glassy”), Dutch glazig (“glassy”), German Low German glasig (“glassy”), German glasig (“glassy”).

GLIOMA.d: A tumour that arises from glial cells in the brain or spinal cord

GLITCH.e:
Probably from Yiddish גליטש (glitsh), from German glitschig (“slippy”), from glitschen (“to slide, glide, slip”) + -ig (“-y”). Related to gleiten (“glide”). Cognate with French glisser (“to slip, slide, skid”).
Popularized in the 1960s, by the US space program. Attested in 1962 b...

GLOBAL.d: Concerning all parts of the world.

GLOBED.d: Past tense of GLOBE: A spherical object; the Earth.

GLOBES.d: Plural of GLOBE: A spherical object; the Earth.

GLOOMY.d: Not very illuminated; dim because of darkness, especially when appearing depressing or frightening.
GLOOMY.e: From gloom + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian glumig (“dark, gloomy”).

GLOSSY.d: Having a smooth, silklike, reflective (shiny) surface.

GLOWED.d: Past tense of GLOW: To emit light as if heated.
GLOWED.e:
From Middle English glowen, from Old English glōwan, from Proto-West Germanic *glōan, from Proto-Germanic *glōaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰleh₁-.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian gloie, glöie, gluuje, West Frisian gloeie, Dutch gloeien, German glühen, Danish and Norwegian glo, ...

GLOWER.d: To look or stare with anger.
GLOWER.e: From an alteration (possibly Scots) of glore, from Middle English glōren, glouren (“to gleam; to glare, glower”); or from glow (“to stare”) (obsolete), and ultimately from a Scandinavian (North Germanic) language. Cognate with Low German gloren (“to flicker; to glimmer”), Dutch g...

GLUCAN.d: Any polysaccharide that is a polymer of glucose

GLUING.d: Present participle of GLUE: A hard gelatin made by boiling bones and hides, used in solution as an adhesive; or any sticky adhesive substance.
GLUING.e:
From Middle English glew, glue, from Old French glu (“glue, birdlime”), from Late Latin glūs (stem glūt-), from Latin glūten. Related to clay.
Partially displaced native Old English līm (“glue”) and ġelīman (“to glue”) (whence modern lime).

GLUNCH.d: To look sullen or glum; to frown
GLUNCH.e: Borrowed from Scots glunch, of uncertain origin, possibly an alteration of glum or glump.

GLUTEN.d: Fibrin (formerly considered as one of the "animal humours").
GLUTEN.e: From Middle French gluten, borrowed from Latin glūten (“glue”).

GLYCAN.d: Any polysaccharide or oligosaccharide, especially one that is part of a glycoprotein or glycolipid.

GNARLY.d: Having or characterized by gnarls; gnarled.
GNARLY.e: From gnarl (“knot in wood”) + -y. The slang senses were particularly popularized by US surf culture in the 1970s.

GNAWED.d: Past tense of GNAW: To bite something persistently, especially something tough.
GNAWED.e:
From Middle English gnawen, gnaȝen, from Old English gnagan, from Proto-West Germanic *gnagan, from Proto-Germanic *gnaganą (“to gnaw”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *gʰnēgʰ- (“to gnaw, scratch”).
Cognate with Dutch knagen, German nagen, Danish gnave (“to gnaw”), Norwegian B...

GNEISS.d: A common and widely-distributed metamorphic rock having bands or veins, but not schistose.
GNEISS.e: From German Gneis, from Middle High German gneist (“spark”), from Old High German gneisto (“spark”). More at gnast.

GNOMIC.d: Of, or relating to gnomes (sententious sayings).
GNOMIC.e: From French gnomique, ultimately from Ancient Greek γνωμικός (gnōmikós), from γνώμη (gnṓmē, “thought, judgement”), akin to γιγνώσκω (gignṓskō, “know”). By surface analysis, gnome + -ic.

GNOMON.d: An object such as a pillar or a rod that is used to tell time by the shadow it casts when the sun shines on it, especially the pointer on a sundial.
GNOMON.e: Borrowed from French gnomon, or directly from its etymon Latin gnōmōn, or directly from its etymon Ancient Greek γνώμων (gnṓmōn, “discerner, interpreter; carpenter’s square; gnomon of a sundial; (geometry) gnomon”), from γιγνώσκω (gignṓskō, “to be aware of; to perceive; to know”)...

GNOSIS.d: An immanent form of knowledge or transcendent insight, such as sought by the Gnostics.

GOADED.d: Past tense of GOAD: A long, pointed stick used to prod animals.
GOADED.e: From Middle English gode, from Old English gād (“goad”), from Proto-Germanic *gaidō (compare Old Norse gedda (“pike (fish)”), Lombardic gaida (“spear”)), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰey- (compare Old Irish gath (“spear”), Sanskrit हिन्वति (hinvati), हिनोति (hinoti, “to urge on, th...

GOALED.d: Past tense of GOAL: A result that one is attempting to achieve.
GOALED.e: From Middle English gol (“boundary, limit”), from Old English *gāl (“obstacle, barrier, marker”), suggested by its derivatives Old English gǣlan (“to hinder, delay, impede, keep in suspense, linger, hesitate, dupe”), and hyġegǣls (“hesitating, slow, sluggish”), hyġegǣlsa (“slow o...

GOANNA.d: Any of various monitor lizards native to Australia.
GOANNA.e: A respelling in Australia of guana, from iguana. Rhyming slang sense rhyming on colloquial pronunciation 'pianner'.

GOATEE.d: A beard trimmed to grow only at the center of the chin.
GOATEE.e: From goat + -ee (diminutive suffix), referring to the tuft of hair on the chin of many domestic goats.

GOBBED.d: Past tense of GOB: A lump of soft or sticky material.
GOBBED.e: From Middle English gobbe (also Middle English gobet), from Old French gobet, gobe (“lump, mouthful”), from Transalpine Gaulish *gobbo- (“neb, muzzle”).

GOBBER.d: Comparative form of GOB: A lump of soft or sticky material.
GOBBER.e: From Middle English gobbe (also Middle English gobet), from Old French gobet, gobe (“lump, mouthful”), from Transalpine Gaulish *gobbo- (“neb, muzzle”).

GOBBET.d: A quantity of liquid, often in a sticky blotch.
GOBBET.e: From Middle English gobet, from Middle French gobet (“mouthful, piece”), diminutive of gobe. See gober.

GOBBLE.d: To eat hastily or greedily; to scoff or scarf (often used with up)
GOBBLE.e: From Middle English gobben (“to drink or swallow greedily”), of uncertain origin + -le (frequentative suffix). Middle English gobben is perhaps an alteration of Middle English globben (“to gulp down”), related to English gulpen (“to gulp”). However, compare also French gober.

GOBIES.d: Plural of GOBY: Any of various small fish from the large family Gobiidae, in which the pelvic fins are fused to form a disc-shaped sucker.
GOBIES.e: From Latin gobius (“gudgeon”), from Ancient Greek κωβιός (kōbiós), a type of small fish, of unknown ultimate origin. See also gudgeon.

GOBLET.d: A drinking vessel with a foot and stem.
GOBLET.e: From Middle English goblet (= Middle Low German gobelet, kobelet (“goblet”)), from Old French gobellet, diminutive of gobel, from or related to the verb gober (“to ingest”).

GOBLIN.d: A malevolent and grotesque diminutive humanoid, often associated with orcs or trolls.
GOBLIN.e: From Middle English gobelyn, from Old Northern French gobelin (compare Norman goubelin, Walloon gobelin), possibly a blend of Old Dutch *kobeholdo (“goblin”) (compare Dutch kabouter, German Kobold) and Late Latin cobalus (“mountain sprite”), from Ancient Greek κόβαλος (kóbalos, “...

GODDED.d: Past tense of GOD: A deity or supreme being; a supernatural, typically immortal, being with superior powers, to which personhood is attributed.
GODDED.e:
Inherited from Middle English god, from Old English god, originally neuter, then changed to masculine to reflect the change in religion to Christianity, from Proto-West Germanic *god n, from Proto-Germanic *gudą; see there for further origin.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots God (“God...

GODOWN.e: Borrowed from Malay gudang, from Tamil கிடங்கு (kiṭaṅku, “store room”) or Telugu గిడ్డంగి (giḍḍaṅgi, “store room, warehouse”).

GODSON.d: A male child whose baptism is sponsored by a godparent.
GODSON.e: From Middle English godsone, gossone, from Old English godsunu (“godson”), equivalent to god- + son. Cognate with Danish gudsøn (“godson”), Swedish gudson (“godson”), Icelandic guðsonur (“godson”).

GODWIT.d: Any of four species of long-billed migratory wading birds in the genus Limosa, of the family Scolopacidae.
GODWIT.e: Origin unknown. A surface analysis would suggest Old English *gōdwiht as the term's ultimate origin, corresponding to good + wight (“creature”), but the term is attested only since late Middle English. The Oxford English Dictionary considers the term to probably have originally b...

GOFFER.e: Borrowed from French gaufrer (“to stamp with a patterned tool”), from gaufre (“honeycomb”).

GOGGLE.d: To stare (at something) with wide eyes.
GOGGLE.e: From 14th century Middle English gogelen (“to roll (eyes), to look sideways”). Earlier source is unknown. The noun is attested from the 17th century. Compare Irish gog (“a nod, a slight motion”).

GOITRE.d: An enlargement of the front and sides of the neck caused by inflammation of the thyroid gland.
GOITRE.e: Borrowed from French, either from Old French goitron (“throat, neck, goitre”), itself from Vulgar Latin *gutturiō, *gutturiōnem (“throat, goitre-like protrusions”), from Latin guttur, or a back-formation from French goitreux (“goitered”).

GOLDEN.d: Made of, or relating to, gold.
GOLDEN.e: From Middle English golden, a restored form (due to the noun gold) of earlier Middle English gulden, gylden, gilden ("golden"; > English gilden), from Old English gylden (“golden”), from Proto-West Germanic *gulþīn, from Proto-Germanic *gulþīnaz (“golden, made of gold”), equivale...

GOLFED.d: Past tense of GOLF: A ball game played by individuals competing against one another in which the object is to hit a ball into each of a series of (usually 18 or nine) holes in the minimum number of strokes.
GOLFED.e: The word is first known in English from the 17th century as a borrowing from Middle Scots golf, gouff. Although the etymology is uncertain, the most likely origin is that it comes from the Middle Dutch colve, colf (“club”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *kulbaz (“club”), related...

GONGED.d: Past tense of GONG: A percussion instrument consisting of a metal disk that emits a loud resonant sound when struck with a soft hammer.

GOODLY.d: Good; pleasing in appearance; attractive; comely; graceful; pleasant; desirable.
GOODLY.e: From Middle English goodly, goodlich, gōdlich, from Old English gōdlīċ (“good, goodly”), from Proto-West Germanic *gōdalīk, from Proto-Germanic *gōdalīkaz (“good, goodly”); equivalent to good + -ly. Cognate with Dutch goedelijk, goelijk (“harmless, benign”), German gütlich (“frie...

GOOFED.d: Past tense of GOOF: A mistake or error.
GOOFED.e:
Perhaps from dialectal English goff (“foolish clown”), from earlier goffe, in which case further etymology is uncertain.
Perhaps from Middle English goffen (“to speak in a frivolous manner”), possibly from Old English gaf, ġegaf (“base; wanton; lewd”, adjective), ġegaf (“buffoone...

GOOGLE.d: To bowl (a cricket ball) so that it performs a googly (“a ball by a leg-break bowler that spins from off to leg (to a right-handed batsman), unlike a normal leg-break delivery”).
GOOGLE.e: Back-formation from googly + -le (frequentative suffix (indicating continuousness or repetition) forming verbs).

GOOGLY.d: A ball, bowled by a leg-break bowler, that spins from off to leg (to a right-handed batsman), unlike a normal leg-break delivery.
GOOGLY.e: Unknown; perhaps derived from googie (“an egg, in reference to the unusual direction of bounce”). Though the delivery was perfected and made famous by English cricketer Bernard Bosanquet, circa 1900, the term is recorded earlier in Australian English (1896).

GOOGOL.d: The number 10¹⁰⁰, or ten to the power of a hundred. Equivalent to ten duotrigintillion (short scale), or ten sexdecilliard (long scale).
GOOGOL.e: Coined by nine-year-old by Milton Sirotta in 1920, nephew of American mathematician Edward Kasner, who had asked Milton to think of a name for the 100th power of ten. The word was first published in the book Mathematics and the Imagination (1940).

GOPHER.d: A small burrowing rodent native to North and Central America, especially in the family Geomyidae (pocket gophers).
GOPHER.e: Perhaps an adaptation of Cajun French gaufre (literally “honeycomb, waffle”), based on the analogy of holes in the ground to the indentations in a honeycomb or a waffle (doublet of waffle). Alternatively, from Muskogean.

GORGET.d: A piece of armour protecting the throat and/or the upper part of the chest.
GORGET.e: From Middle English gorget, from Old French gorgete, from gorge (“throat”).

GORGON.d: A vicious female monster from Greek mythology with sharp fangs and hair of living, venomous snakes. One of the three sisters: Medusa, Stheno and Euryale
GORGON.e: From Middle English gorgon, from Latin Gorgō, from Ancient Greek Γοργώ (Gorgṓ), from γοργός (gorgós, “terrible”). Possibly from the same root as the Sanskrit word "garğ" (गर्जन), which is defined as a guttural sound, similar to the growling of a beast, thus possibly originating a...

GORIER.d: Comparative form of GORY: Covered with blood; very bloody.
GORIER.e: From gore + -y. Compare Middle English gorry (“muddy”), and güre, gire, girre (“gory, clotted”), from Old English gyr, gyru (“filthy, muddy”), from gor (“dirt, dung”); Old Frisian gere, iere (“muddy water”). More at gore.

GORING.d: Present participle of GORE: Blood, especially that from a wound when thickened due to exposure to the air.
GORING.e:
From Middle English gore, gor, gorre (“mud, muck”), from Old English gor (“manure, dung, filth, muck, dirt”), from Proto-West Germanic *gor, from Proto-Germanic *gurą (“half-digested stomach contents; faeces; manure”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰer- (“hot; warm”).
Cognate to Ol...

GOSPEL.d: The first section of the Christian New Testament scripture, comprising the books of Matthew, Mark, Luke and John, concerned with the birth, ministry, passion, and resurrection of Jesus.
GOSPEL.e: From Middle English gospel, gospell, godspel, godspell, goddspell, from Old English godspell (“gospel”), corresponding to God + spell (“talk, tale, story”), literally “the message of God”, believed to be an alteration of earlier *gōdspell (literally “good news”), used to translat...

GOSSIP.d: Someone who likes to talk about other people's private or personal business.
GOSSIP.e: From Middle English godsybbe, godsib (“a close friend or relation, a confidant; a godparent”), from Old English godsibb (“godparent, sponsor”), equivalent to god + sib. Doublet of godsib. For sense evolution to "gossip, discussing others' personal affairs," compare French comméra...

GOUJON.e: Borrowed from French goujon (“gudgeon (fish)”). Doublet of gudgeon.

GOVERN.d: To make and administer the public policy and affairs of; to exercise sovereign authority in.
GOVERN.e: From Middle English governen, governe, from Anglo-Norman and Old French governer, guverner, from Latin gubernō, from Ancient Greek κυβερνάω (kubernáō, “I steer, drive, govern”).

GOWKED.d: Past tense of GOWK: A cuckoo.
GOWKED.e: From Middle English goke, gowke, from Old Norse gaukr (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Germanic *gaukaz (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰegʰuǵʰ- (“cuckoo”).

GOWNED.d: Past tense of GOWN: A loose, flowing upper garment.
GOWNED.e: From Middle English gowne, from Anglo-Norman goune, gune (“fur-trimmed coat, pelisse”), from Old French goune, from Late Latin gunna (“leather garment, a fur”). Cognate with Manx gooyn, Irish gúna.

GRABEN.d: An elongated block of the Earth's crust, bounded by faults, that has dropped relative to the surrounding area.
GRABEN.e: Borrowed from German Graben (“ditch”), from the verb graben (“to dig”).

GRACED.d: Past tense of GRACE: Elegance; divine favor.
GRACED.e: From Old French grace, from Latin grātia.

GRACES.d: Plural of GRACE: Elegance; divine favor.
GRACES.e: From Old French grace, from Latin grātia.

GRADED.d: Past tense of GRADE: A level of quality; a school year.

GRADES.d: Plural of GRADE: A level of quality; a school year.

GRADIN.d: Any of a series of terraced steps or seats, as in an arena or an altar.

GRADUS.d: A handbook used as an aid in a difficult art or practice, specifically, a dictionary of Greek or Latin prosody used as a guide in writing of poetry in Greek or Latin.
GRADUS.e: From Gradus ad Parnassum (Latin, literally, a step to Parnassus), a 17th-century prosody dictionary long used in British schools. Doublet of grade.

GRAINS.d: Plural of GRAIN: Seeds of cereal plants; a small amount.
GRAINS.e: From Old French grain, from Latin grānum.

GRAINY.e: From Middle English greyny, equivalent to grain + -y.

GRANDS.d: Plural of GRAND: Large and impressive.
GRANDS.e: From Old French grant, from Latin grandis.

GRANGE.e: From Middle English graunge, borrowed from Old French grange (“granary; barn; small farm”), from Vulgar Latin *grānica, from Latin grānum (“grain”).

GRANTS.d: Plural of GRANT: To give; to agree to.

GRAPPA.d: An Italian grape-based spirit of between 80 and 100 proof, made from the distillation of pomace.
GRAPPA.e: Borrowed from Italian grappa. Doublet of grape.

GRASSY.e: From Middle English grasy, from Old English *græsiġ, *gærsiġ, from Proto-West Germanic *grasagrōnī, from Proto-Germanic *grasagrōniz, equivalent to grass + -y. Compare Saterland Frisian gäärsich (“grassy”), Dutch grazig (“grassy”), German grasig (“grassy”), Icelandic grösugur (“g...

GRATIN.d: The top crust of a dish, consisting of breadcrumbs or grated cheese heated under a grill; the dish itself.

GRAVED.d: Past tense of GRAVE: A place of burial; serious.
GRAVED.e: From Old English græf / Old French grave.

GRAVEL.d: Small fragments of rock, used for laying on the beds of roads and railways, and as ballast.
GRAVEL.e: From Middle English gravel, grauel, from Old French gravele, diminutive of grave (“gravel, seashore”), from Medieval Latin grava, ultimately from Proto-Celtic *grāwā (“gravel, pebbles”) (compare Breton groa, Cornish grow, Welsh gro), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰroh₁weh₂, from *gʰ...

GRAVID.e: From Latin gravidus (“laden, pregnant”), from gravis (“heavy”).

GRAYED.d: Past tense of GRAY: Of a colour between black and white, having neutral hue and intermediate brightness.
GRAYED.e:
From Middle English gray, from Old English grǣġ, grǣw (“grey”), from Proto-West Germanic *grāu, from Proto-Germanic *grēwaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰreh₁- (“to green, to grow”).
Cognate with West Frisian grau (“grey”), Dutch grauw (“grey”), German Low German grau, gr...

GREASE.d: Animal fat in a melted or soft state.
