GREASE.e: From Middle English grece, from Anglo-Norman grece, from Vulgar Latin *grassia, noun derived from Latin crassus (“fat, thick”).

GREASY.d: Having a slippery surface; having a surface covered with grease.
GREASY.e: From Middle English gresi, gressy, equivalent to grease + -y.

GREATS.d: Plural of GREAT: Very large; excellent.

GREAVE.d: A bush; a tree; a grove.
GREAVE.e:
From Middle English greve, from Old English grǣfe, grǣfa (“bush, bramble, grove, thicket, copse, brush-wood (for burning), fuel”), probably related to Proto-Germanic *grōbō (“ditch, hole”).
Cognate with Scots greve, greave (“grove”). Compare also Proto-Germanic *grainiz (“twig”),...

GREEDY.d: Having greed; consumed by selfish desires.
GREEDY.e:
From Middle English gredy, from Anglian Old English grēdiġ (“greedy, hungry, eager”) (cognate West Saxon form grǣdiġ), from Proto-Germanic *grēdagaz (“hungry”), from Proto-Germanic *grēdaz, *grēduz, *grēdô (“hunger”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰer-. Equivalent to greed + -y.
Cog...

GREENS.d: Plural of GREEN: The colour of grass.

GREIGE.d: Of clothing, textiles, etc.: neither bleached nor dyed, nor otherwise fully processed; unfinished.
GREIGE.e: The adjective is borrowed from French grège and Middle French grège (“of silk: raw, unfinished; of the colour of such silk, greyish-beige”, adjective), from Italian greggio (“raw, unrefined; unbleached”); further etymology uncertain, possibly from Vulgar Latin *gregius (as in lan...

GREYED.d: Past tense of GREY: Commonwealth standard spelling of gray.
GREYED.e: From Middle English grey, from Old English grǣġ, from Proto-Germanic *grēwaz (compare Dutch grauw, German grau, Old Norse grár), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰreh₁- (“to green, to grow”) (compare Latin rāvus (“grey”), Old Church Slavonic зьрѭ (zĭrjǫ, “to see, to glance”), Russian з...

GRIEVE.d: To cause sorrow or distress to.
GRIEVE.e:
From Middle English greven, from Old French grever (“to burden”), from Latin gravō, gravāre, from adjective gravis (“grave”).
For the meaning development compare Russian тяготи́ть (tjagotítʹ, “to be a burden (on), to oppress”), Russian тужи́ть (tužítʹ, “to experience grief”), rel...

GRILLE.d: Alternative form of grill (only in the senses of "grating over opening", "grating on the front of a vehicle", and "window divider")

GRILSE.d: A young salmon after its first return from the sea.
GRILSE.e: From Middle English grills, grilles, of unknown origin. Cognate with Scots grils, grissill, girls (“young salmon”). Compare English grawl, Scots grawl, graulse (“young salmon, grilse”).

GRINGO.d: A white person from an English-speaking country, particularly the United States.
GRINGO.e: Borrowed from Spanish gringo, from griego (“Greek”), used for anyone who spoke an unintelligible language. Doublet of Greek.

GRIPPE.e: Borrowed from French grippe, from gripper (“to seize, snatch”), from Frankish *grīpan, from Proto-Germanic *grīpaną, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰreyb- (“to grab, to grasp”). Borrowed from French into many languages of the world. More at gripe.

GRIPPY.d: Having a tight grip, or tending to grip well.

GRISLY.e: From Middle English grisely, grysly, grissliȝ, griselich, grislich, from Old English grisliċ (“grisly, horrible; dreadful, horrid”), from grīsan (“to shudder with horror; to tremble, to be terrified; to make tremble, to terrify; to agrise, grise”) (unattested but implied in āgrīs...

GRISON.d: A small, carnivorous South American mammal, of the genus Galictis, somewhat resembling a weasel.
GRISON.e: From Old French gris (“gray”) + -on (diminutive suffix). Doublet of Grisons.

GRITTY.d: Containing sand or grit; consisting of grit; caused by grit; full of hard particles.

GROCER.d: A person who retails groceries (foodstuffs and household items) from a grocery.
GROCER.e: From Old French grossier (“wholesaler”) Compare gross.

GROGGY.d: Slowed or weakened, as by drink, sleepiness, etc.

GROOVE.d: A long, narrow channel or depression; e.g., such a slot cut into a hard material to provide a location for an engineering component, a tire groove, or a geological channel or depression.
GROOVE.e: From Middle English grov, grove, groof, grofe (“cave; pit; mining shaft”), probably from Old Norse gróf (“pit”) or from Middle Dutch groeve (“furrow, ditch”), both from Proto-West Germanic *grōbu, from Proto-Germanic *grōbō (“groove, furrow”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰrebʰ- (“...

GROOVY.d: Of, pertaining to, or having grooves.

GROTTO.e:
From Italian grotta, from Vulgar Latin grupta, from Classical Latin crypta. Doublet of crypt.
The Philippine sense is from the holy cave in Lourdes, France.

GROTTY.e: Clipping of grotesque + -y. Piecewise doublet of grody, the American equivalent. Compare Middle English groti, grooti (“slimy, muddy”), from Old English grotiġ (“earthy, dirty”) (modern dialectal English groaty, Scots grotty), which is equivalent to groat + -y. Compare also Scott...

GROUCH.d: A complaint, a grumble, a fit of ill-humor.
GROUCH.e: From Middle English grouchen, variant of grucchen (“to complain, mumble, murmur”). See grutch.

GROUND.d: The surface of the Earth, as opposed to the sky or water or underground.
GROUND.e: From Middle English ground, from Old English grund, from Proto-West Germanic *grundu, from Proto-Germanic *grunduz. Cognate with West Frisian grûn, Dutch grond and German Grund.

GROUPS.d: Plural of GROUP: A number of people or things together.
GROUPS.e: From French groupe, from Italian gruppo.

GROUSE.d: Any of various game birds of the subfamily Tetraoninae which inhabit temperate and subarctic regions of the Northern Hemisphere; specifically, the red grouse (Lagopus lagopus scotica) native to heather moorland on the British Isles.
GROUSE.e:
Attested in the 1530s, as grows ("moorhen"), a plural used collectively.
The origin of the noun is unknown; the following derivations have been suggested:
* From Old French grue (“crane”) (modern French grue) or Medieval Latin gruta (“crane”), both from Latin grūs (“crane”).
* Bo...

GROVEL.d: To be prone on the ground.
GROVEL.e: From Middle English *grovelen, from Old Norse grufla, grœfla (“to grovel”), from Proto-Germanic *grubilōną (“to dig, delve into”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰrebʰ‑ (“to dig, scrape, scrabble, scratch”); akin to Old Norse á grufu (“on one's belly”) ( > Old Norse grúfa (“to lie fa...

GROWED.d: Past tense of GROW: To become larger, to increase in magnitude.
GROWED.e:
From Middle English growen, from Old English grōwan (“to grow, increase, flourish, germinate”), from Proto-West Germanic *grōan, from Proto-Germanic *grōaną (“to grow, grow green”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰreh₁- (“to grow, become green”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots grow, gre...

GROWTH.d: An increase in size, number, value, or strength.
GROWTH.e: From grow + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Compare Old Frisian grēd ("meadow, pasture"; > North Frisian greyde (“growth, pasture”)), Middle High German gruote, gruot (“greens, fresh growth, shoot”), Old Norse gróðr ("growth, crop"; > Faroese grøði, Danish grøde (“fruits”), Swedis...

GROYNE.d: An often wooden structure that projects from a coastline to prevent erosion, longshore drift etc.; a breakwater.
GROYNE.e: From Middle English groyn (“snout”), from Old French groign, from Late Latin grunium, grunia, from Latin grunnire (“grunt like a pig”).

GRUDGE.d: Deep-seated and/or long-term animosity or ill will about something or someone, especially due to perceived mistreatment.
GRUDGE.e:
A variant of grutch (mid 15th-century, younger than begrudge), from Middle English grucchen (“to murmur, complain, feel envy, begrudge”), from Old French grouchier, groucier (“to murmur, grumble”), of Germanic origin, probably ultimately imitative.
Akin to Middle High German grog...

GRUNGE.d: Dirt or filth, especially when difficult to clean.

GRUNGY.e: Probably a blend of grunt + dingy, influenced by grimy.

GUAIAC.d: A paper treated with alpha-guaiaconic acid, used in tests to detect blood in the faeces.

GUARDS.d: Plural of GUARD: A person who protects; to watch over.

GUDDLE.d: To catch (fish) with the hands, especially by groping at the bank of a stream or under stones.
GUDDLE.e: From Scots guddle, imitative of the splashing of water, and modelled after words like muddle and puddle, perhaps influenced by Scots gutter (“to spatter with mud”).

GUENON.d: A member of the genus Cercopithecus of Old World monkeys, of sub-Saharan Africa, principally forests.

GUESTS.d: Plural of GUEST: A person invited to visit.

GUFFAW.e: Early 18th century, originally Scots, probably onomatopoeic.

GUGGLE.d: To make a sound as of liquid being poured from a small-necked container

GUIDED.d: Past tense of GUIDE: A person who shows the way; to direct.

GUIDER.e: From Middle English gider, gyder, equivalent to guide + -er. Compare Old French guidëor.

GUIDES.d: Plural of GUIDE: A person who shows the way; to direct.

GUIDON.d: A small pennant or banner carried by infantry soldiers to direct troop movement.
GUIDON.e: From French guidon, from Italian guidone. Equivalent of guide + on.

GUILTY.e: From Middle English gilty, gulty, from Old English gyltiġ (“offending, guilty”); equivalent to guilt + -y.

GUINEA.d: The coastal region of West Africa between Morocco and the Congo, particularly the north shore of the Gulf of Guinea.
GUINEA.e: From Portuguese Guiné + -ia, which is of uncertain origin.

GUISER.d: A person in disguise, as for a parade or festival.

GUITAR.d: A stringed musical instrument, of European origin, usually with a fretted fingerboard and six strings, played with the fingers or a plectrum (guitar pick).
GUITAR.e: From Spanish guitarra, from Arabic قِيثَارَة (qīṯāra), from Ancient Greek κῐθᾰ́ρᾱ (kĭthắrā). Doublet of cithara, cither, and zither.

GULDEN.d: An old currency of the Netherlands (and its former overseas territory the Netherlands Antilles or the Dutch East Indies).
GULDEN.e: From Middle English, from Middle Dutch gulden (florijn) (“golden (florin)”).

GULFED.d: Past tense of GULF: A hollow place in the earth; an abyss; a deep chasm or basin.
GULFED.e: From Middle English gulf, goulf, golf, from Old French golf, from Italian golfo, from Late Latin colfos, from Ancient Greek κόλπος (kólpos, “bosom, gulf”), of obscure origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kʷelp- (“to curve, arch”).

GULLET.e: From Middle English golet, borrowed from Old French goulet, from Latin gula, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷel- (“throat”).

GULOSE.d: A sugar C₆H₁₂O₆ stereoisomeric with glucose and obtainable by synthesis from xylose.

GULPED.d: Past tense of GULP: The usual amount swallowed.
GULPED.e:
From Middle English gulpen, probably from West Flemish or Middle Dutch gulpen, golpen, of uncertain origin. Perhaps of imitative origin, or related to Dutch galpen (“to roar, squeal”), English galp, gaup (“to gape”).
Related to German Low German gulpen (“to gush out, belch, gulp”...

GUMMED.d: Past tense of GUM: The flesh around the teeth.
GUMMED.e:
From Middle English gome, from Old English gōma (“palate”), from Proto-West Germanic *gōmō, from Proto-Germanic *gōmô, *gaumô (“palate”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰh₂u-mo-, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₂w- (“to gape, yawn”).
See also German Gaumen, Old Norse gómr, Icelandic gó...

GUMMER.d: Comparative form of GUM: The flesh around the teeth.
GUMMER.e:
From Middle English gome, from Old English gōma (“palate”), from Proto-West Germanic *gōmō, from Proto-Germanic *gōmô, *gaumô (“palate”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰh₂u-mo-, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₂w- (“to gape, yawn”).
See also German Gaumen, Old Norse gómr, Icelandic gó...

GUNITE.d: A form of shotcrete in which a dry cementitious mixture is blown through a hose to the nozzle, with water injected only at the point of application.
GUNITE.e: From gun + -ite, originally a trademark from 1909.

GUNMAN.d: A criminal armed with a gun, especially a professional killer.

GUNNED.d: Past tense of GUN: A device for shooting projectiles or ditto (a shooter), functioning through stored energy: a firearm, cannon, harpoon gun/spear gun, raygun, etc, not a bow and arrow, or slingshot.
GUNNED.e: From Middle English gunne, gonne, possibly from Gunnhild, a female given name formerly used as a nickname for engines of war. The name is composed of the Norse elements gunnr and hildr, both meaning "battle".

GUNNEL.e: From Middle English gonnewalle, itself from gonne (“gun”) + wale, as it used to support the ship's guns; equivalent to gun + wale.

GUNNER.d: Comparative form of GUN: A device for shooting projectiles or ditto (a shooter), functioning through stored energy: a firearm, cannon, harpoon gun/spear gun, raygun, etc, not a bow and arrow, or slingshot.
GUNNER.e: From Middle English gunne, gonne, possibly from Gunnhild, a female given name formerly used as a nickname for engines of war. The name is composed of the Norse elements gunnr and hildr, both meaning "battle".

GUNTER.d: A male given name from the Germanic languages used in medieval England.
GUNTER.e: From German Gunther, from Proto-West Germanic *Gunþihari, from Proto-Germanic *Gunþiharjaz.

GUNYAH.d: A traditional Aboriginal dwelling made of bark and sticks.
GUNYAH.e: Borrowed from Dharug gunya (“shelter”), first recorded 1803.

GURGLE.d: To flow with a bubbling sound.
GURGLE.e: Back formation from Middle English gurguling (“a rumbling in the belly”). Akin to Middle Dutch gorgelen (“to gurgle”), Middle Low German gorgelen (“to gurgle”), German gurgeln (“to gargle”), and perhaps to Latin gurguliō (“throat”).

GUSHED.d: Past tense of GUSH: A sudden rapid outflow.
GUSHED.e:
From Middle English guschen, gusshen, gosshien, perhaps from Middle Dutch guysen (“to flow out with a gurgling sound, gush”) or Old Norse gusa (“to gush”), ultimately imitative.
Compare Old Norse geysa (“to gush”), German gießen (“to pour”), Old English ġēotan ("to pour"; > Engli...

GUSHES.d: Plural of GUSH: A sudden rapid outflow.
GUSHES.e:
From Middle English guschen, gusshen, gosshien, perhaps from Middle Dutch guysen (“to flow out with a gurgling sound, gush”) or Old Norse gusa (“to gush”), ultimately imitative.
Compare Old Norse geysa (“to gush”), German gießen (“to pour”), Old English ġēotan ("to pour"; > Engli...

GUSSET.d: A small piece of cloth inserted in a garment, for the purpose of strengthening some part or giving it a tapering enlargement cf. godet.
GUSSET.e: From Middle English gusset, gysset, from Old French gosset, gousset (“the hollow of the armpit”), diminutive of gose, gosse (“bean pod, hull, husk”).

GUSTED.d: Past tense of GUST: A strong, abrupt rush of wind.
GUSTED.e: Apparently from an unrecorded Middle English *gust, from Old Norse gustr (“a gust, blast”), from Proto-Germanic *gustiz, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰew-. Cognate with Icelandic gustur (“gust of wind”). Related also to Old Norse gusa (“to gush forth”), Old High German gussa (“floo...

GUTTED.d: Past tense of GUT: The alimentary canal, especially the intestine.
GUTTED.e:
From Middle English gut, gutte, gotte, from Old English gutt (usually in plural guttas (“guts, entrails”)), from Proto-Germanic *gut-, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰewd- (“to pour”). Related to English gote (“drain”), Old English ġēotan (“to pour”). More at gote, yote.
The verb is ...

GUTTER.d: A prepared channel in a surface, especially at the side of a road adjacent to a curb, intended for the drainage of water.
GUTTER.e: From Middle English gutter, guttur, goter, from Anglo-Norman guttere, from Old French goutiere (French gouttière), ultimately from Latin gutta (“drop”).

GUYING.d: Present participle of GUY: An effigy of a man burned on a bonfire on the anniversary of the Gunpowder Plot (5th November).
GUYING.e: Coined by semantic widening from the name of Guy Fawkes (1570–1606), an English Catholic executed for his role in the Gunpowder Plot, from Old French Gui, a form of Proto-Germanic *Wido, a short form of names beginning with the element witu "wood" from Proto-Germanic *widuz, such...

GUZZLE.d: To drink or eat quickly, voraciously, or to excess; to gulp down; to swallow greedily, continually, or with gusto.
GUZZLE.e: Attested since 1576. Possibly imitative of the sound of drinking greedily, or from Old French gouziller, gosillier (“to pass through the throat”), from gosier (“throat”), and akin to Italian gozzo (“throat; a bird's crop”).

GYBING.d: Present participle of GYBE: To shift a fore-and-aft sail from one side of a sailing vessel to the other, while sailing before the wind.
GYBING.e:
Probably from Dutch gijben (obsolete), gijpen; cognate with Danish gibbe, German gieben, giepen, Swedish gipa, gippa.
The noun is derived from the verb; compare Dutch gijb (obsolete), gijp (“act of gybing; a boom”).

GYPPED.d: Past tense of GYP: A cheat or swindle; a rip-off.
GYPPED.e:
Perhaps from the term gypsy (“Roma”), due to a stereotype of the Roma as swindlers. Compare jew (“defraud”), from Jew, and welsh (“swindle by defaulting on a debt”), from Welsh.
Could also be derived from dupe, with the same pattern (yod coalescence) as idiot becomes eejit in Sco...

GYPPER.d: Comparative form of GYP: A cheat or swindle; a rip-off.
GYPPER.e:
Perhaps from the term gypsy (“Roma”), due to a stereotype of the Roma as swindlers. Compare jew (“defraud”), from Jew, and welsh (“swindle by defaulting on a debt”), from Welsh.
Could also be derived from dupe, with the same pattern (yod coalescence) as idiot becomes eejit in Sco...

GYPSUM.d: A mineral consisting of hydrated calcium sulphate. When calcinated, it forms plaster of Paris.
GYPSUM.e: From Latin gypsum, from Ancient Greek γύψος (gúpsos). Doublet of gesso.

GYRATE.d: To revolve round a central point; to move spirally about an axis, as a tornado.
GYRATE.e: Back-formation from gyration, on the basis of -ate (verb-forming suffix), from gyre (“to spin around; to gyrate, to whirl; (rare) to make (something) spin or whirl around; to spin, to whirl”) + -ation (suffix indicating actions or processes), further from Late Middle English gire...

GYRING.d: Present participle of GYRE: A swirling vortex.
GYRING.e: Borrowed from Latin gȳrus (“circle; circular motion”), from Ancient Greek γῦρος (gûros, “circle; ring”), from Proto-Indo-European *gew- (“to bend; to curve”). The English word is a doublet of gyro and gyrus.

GYTTJA.d: A mud formed from the partial decay of peat.

HABOOB.d: A violent duststorm or sandstorm in the deserts of Arabia, North Africa, India, or North America.
HABOOB.e:
[Alt: A large dust cloud over the city]
Borrowed from Arabic هَبُوب (habūb, “strong wind, gale; haboob”), from the root ه ب ب (h b b)
(“relating to wind blowing”).

HACKED.d: Past tense of HACK: To chop or cut down in a rough manner.
HACKED.e:
From Middle English hacken, hakken, from Old English *haccian (“to hack”), from Proto-West Germanic *hakkōn, from Proto-Germanic *hakkōną (“to chop; hoe; hew”), from Proto-Indo-European *keg-, *keng- (“to be sharp; peg; hook; handle”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian häkje (“to ha...

HACKLE.d: An instrument with steel pins used to comb out flax or hemp.
HACKLE.e: From Middle English hakle (compare the compound meshakele), from Old English hæcla, hacele, from Proto-Germanic *hakulǭ, equivalent to hack + -le. Cognate with Dutch hekel, German Hechel.

HADDER.d: Comparative form of HAD: simple past and past participle of have
HADDER.e: From Middle English hadde (preterite), yhad (past participle), from Old English hæfde (first and third person singular preterite), ġehæfd (past participle), from Proto-Germanic *habdaz, past and past participle stem of *habjaną (“to have”), equivalent to have + -ed. Cognate with ...

HADING.d: Present participle of HADE: State; order, estate, rank, degree, or quality.
HADING.e: From Middle English hade, had, hod, hed, from Old English hād (“person, individual, character, individuality, degree, rank, order, office, holy office, condition, state, nature, character, form, manner, sex, race, family, tribe, choir”), from Proto-West Germanic *haidu, from Prot...

HADRON.d: A composite particle that comprises two or more quarks held together by the strong force and (consequently) can interact with other particles via said force; a meson or a baryon.
HADRON.e: From Ancient Greek ἁδρός (hadrós, “thick”) + -on. Coined by Russian physicist Lev Okun in 1962 in a plenary talk at the International Conference on High Energy Physics.

HAFTED.d: Past tense of HAFT: The handle of a tool or weapon.
HAFTED.e: From Middle English haft, from Old English hæft, from Proto-West Germanic *haftī, from Proto-Germanic *haftiją.

HAGGED.d: Past tense of HAG: A witch, sorceress, or enchantress; a female wizard.
HAGGED.e: From Middle English hagge, hegge (“demon, old woman”), shortening of Old English hægtesse, hægtes (“harpy, witch”), from Proto-West Germanic *hagatussjā. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Häkse (“witch”), Dutch heks, German Hexe (“witch”). Doublet of hex.

HAGGER.d: Comparative form of HAG: A witch, sorceress, or enchantress; a female wizard.
HAGGER.e: From Middle English hagge, hegge (“demon, old woman”), shortening of Old English hægtesse, hægtes (“harpy, witch”), from Proto-West Germanic *hagatussjā. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Häkse (“witch”), Dutch heks, German Hexe (“witch”). Doublet of hex.

HAGGIS.d: A traditional Scottish dish made from minced sheep offal with oatmeal and spices, etc., originally boiled in the stomach of a sheep but now often in an artificial casing, and usually served with neeps and tatties (mashed swede and potatoes) and accompanied with whisky.
HAGGIS.e: From Late Middle English hagis (“haggis”), from hag, haggen (“to chop, cut, hack; to cut into”) (from Old Norse hǫggva (“to hew”)), or from hakken (“to chop, hack; to dice, mince”) (from Old English hēawan (“to chop, hew; to dice, mince”)), both ultimately from Proto-Indo-Europea...

HAGGLE.d: To argue for a better deal, especially over prices with a seller.
HAGGLE.e: 1570s, "to cut unevenly" (implied in haggler), frequentative of Middle English haggen (“to chop”), variant of hacken (“to hack”), equivalent to hack + -le. Sense of "argue about price" first recorded c.1600, probably from notion of chopping away.

HAILED.d: Past tense of HAIL: Balls or pieces of ice falling as precipitation, often in connection with a thunderstorm.
HAILED.e: From Middle English hayle, haile, hail, hawel, haghil, haȝel, from Old English hæġl, hæġel, hagol (“hail”), from Proto-West Germanic *hagl, from Proto-Germanic *haglaz, of uncertain origin. Either from Proto-Indo-European *kagʰlos (“pebble”); or alternatively from *ḱoḱló-, a redu...

HALIDE.d: Any salt of any halogen acid (such as hydrochloric acid, hydrofluoric acid, or hydroiodic acid).

HALING.d: Present participle of HALE: Sound, entire, healthy; robust, not impaired.
HALING.e: From Northern Middle English hal, hale, variants of hole (“healthy; safe; whole”) (whence whole), from Old English hāl, from Proto-West Germanic *hail, from Proto-Germanic *hailaz (“whole; entire; healthy”). See whole for more.

HALITE.d: Native salt; sodium chloride NaCl as a mineral; rock salt.

HALLOO.d: Used to greet someone, or to catch their attention.
HALLOO.e: From Middle English hallow (“pursue, urge on”), from Old French haloer, which is imitative.

HALLOW.d: A saint; a holy person; an apostle.
HALLOW.e: Inherited from Middle English halwe (“a saint, holy thing, shrine”), from Old English hālga (“a holy one, saint”), from Proto-Germanic *hailagô (“holy one”), from *hailagaz (“holy”), from Proto-Germanic *hailaz (“whole, safe, hale”), from Proto-Indo-European *kéh₂ilos (“safe, unh...

HALLUX.e: From Late Latin hallux, from Latin allus, hallus.

HALOED.d: Past tense of HALO: A circular band of coloured light, visible around the sun or moon etc., caused by reflection and refraction of light by ice crystals in the atmosphere.
HALOED.e: From Latin halōs, from Ancient Greek ἅλως (hálōs, “threshing floor; disk; disk of the sun or moon; ring of light around the sun or moon”), of unknown origin. The threshing floor's circular threshold or oxen walking on it in a circle gave rise to the other meanings. Used in Englis...

HALTER.d: A bitless headpiece of rope or straps, placed on the head of animals such as cattle or horses to lead or tie them.
HALTER.e:
From Middle English halter, helter, helfter, from Old English hælfter, hælftre (“halter”), from Proto-West Germanic *halftrijā (“harness”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kelH- (“to cut”), equivalent to half- + -ter.
Cognate with Scots helter (“halter”), Dutch halfter, halster (“ha...

HALVES.d: Plural of HALF: One of two usually roughly equal parts into which anything may be divided, or considered as divided.
HALVES.e:
From Middle English half, halfe from Old English healf (“half”); as a noun, 'half', 'side', 'part', from Proto-West Germanic *halb, from Proto-Germanic *halbaz.
Cognates
Cognate with Old Saxon, Old Frisian, and Old Dutch half, West Frisian heal, Dutch half, German halb, Swedish, ...

HAMATE.e: From Latin hamus (“hook”) + -ate (adjective forming suffix); the noun is a back-formation from hamate bone, see -ate (noun-forming suffix).

HAMLET.d: A small village or a group of houses.
HAMLET.e: From Middle English hamlet, hamelet, a borrowing from Old French hamelet, diminutive of Old French hamel, in turn diminutive of Old French ham, of Germanic origin, from Frankish *haim, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *haimaz (whence English home). Equivalent to Middle English ham ...

HAMMED.d: Past tense of HAM: The region back of the knee joint; the popliteal space; the hock.
HAMMED.e:
Inherited from Middle English hamme, from Old English hamm (“inner or hind part of the knee, ham”), from Proto-West Germanic *hammu, from Proto-Germanic *hamō, *hammō, *hanmō, from Proto-Indo-European *kónh₂m (“leg”).
Cognate with Dutch ham (“ham”), dialectal German Hamme (“hind ...

HAMMER.d: A tool with a heavy head and a handle used for pounding.
HAMMER.e: From Middle English hamer, from Old English hamor, from Proto-West Germanic *hamar, from Proto-Germanic *hamaraz (“tool with a stone head”) (compare West Frisian hammer, Low German Hamer, Dutch hamer, German Hammer, Danish hammer, Swedish hammare). This is traditionally ascribed ...

HAMPER.d: A large basket, usually with a cover, used for the packing and carrying of articles or small animals.
HAMPER.e: From Middle English hamper, contracted from hanaper, hanypere, from Anglo-Norman hanaper, Old French hanapier, hanepier (“case for holding a large goblet or cup”), from hanap (“goblet, drinking cup”), from Frankish *hnapp (“cup, bowl, basin”), from Proto-Germanic *hnappaz (“cup, ...

HANDED.d: Having a certain kind or number of hands.

HANDLE.d: The part of an object which is (designed to be) held in the hand when used or moved.
HANDLE.e: From Middle English handel, handle, from Old English handle (“a handle”), from *handulā. See verb below. Cognate with Danish handel (“a handle”).

HANGAR.d: A large garage-like structure where aircraft are kept.
HANGAR.e: Borrowed from French hangar (“shed, hangar”), from Middle French hanghart (“enclosure near a house”), from Old French hangart, *hamgart, from Old Frankish *haimgard (“fence around a group of houses”), from *haim (“home, village, hamlet”) + *gard (“yard”). Cognate with Old High Ge...

HANGRY.d: Hungry and angry, especially when the anger is induced by the hunger.

HANKED.d: Past tense of HANK: A diminutive of the male given name Henry.

HANKER.e: With a secondary frequentative suffix -er, ultimately pointing to Proto-Germanic *hankōną, an iterative to *hanhaną (“to hang”). Related to Dutch hunkeren (“to crave”), which continues the zero-grade iterative.

HAPPED.d: Past tense of HAP: A person's lot (good or bad), luck, fortune, fate.
HAPPED.e: From Middle English hap, happe (“chance, hap, luck, fortune”), potentially cognate with or from Old English ġehæp (“fit, convenient”) and/or Old Norse happ (“hap, chance, good luck”), from Proto-Germanic *hampą (“convenience, happiness”), from Proto-Indo-European *kob- (“good for...

HAPPEN.e: From Middle English happenen, hapnen, augmented from Middle English happen (“to come to pass, happen”), perhaps from Old English hæppan (“to move accidentally, slip”) and/or from Old Norse *happa, *heppa, from Proto-Germanic *hampijaną (“to fit in, be fitting”). Equivalent to hap...

HAPPER.d: Comparative form of HAP: A person's lot (good or bad), luck, fortune, fate.
HAPPER.e: From Middle English hap, happe (“chance, hap, luck, fortune”), potentially cognate with or from Old English ġehæp (“fit, convenient”) and/or Old Norse happ (“hap, chance, good luck”), from Proto-Germanic *hampą (“convenience, happiness”), from Proto-Indo-European *kob- (“good for...

HAPTIC.d: Of or relating to the sense of touch.
HAPTIC.e: From Ancient Greek ἁπτικός (haptikós, “able to come in contact with”), from ἅπτω (háptō, “to touch”) + -ικός (-ikós, suffix forming adjectives from nouns).

HARASS.d: To annoy (someone) frequently or systematically; to pester.
HARASS.e: The verb is derived from Middle French, Old French harasser (“to exhaust, tire out, wear out; to harry, torment, vex”) (modern French harasser (“to exhaust, tire out, wear out”)), possibly from Old French harer (“to set a dog on”), from Frankish *hara (“here, hither”) (a command ...

HARDEN.e: From Middle English hardenen, equivalent to hard + -en. Cognate with Danish hærdne (“to harden; cure”), Swedish hårdna (“to harden”), Norwegian herdne (“to harden”), Icelandic harðna (“to harden”).

HARING.d: Present participle of HARE: Any of several plant-eating mammals of the genus Lepus, similar to a rabbit, but larger and with longer ears.
HARING.e:
From Middle English hare, from Old English hara (“hare”), from Proto-West Germanic *hasō ~ *haʀ-, from Proto-Germanic *hasô, from *haswaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱh₂s-én-.
Cognates
See also West Frisian hazze, Dutch haas, German Hase, Norwegian and Swedish hare, Icela...

HARKED.d: Past tense of HARK: To listen attentively.
HARKED.e: From Middle English herken, herkien, from Old English *hercian, *heorcian, *hiercian, from Proto-West Germanic *hauʀikōn, *hauʀukōn, derived ultimately from Proto-Germanic *hauzijaną (“to hear”) + formative/intensive -k (see also the related hīeran, whence English hear). Equivale...

HARKEN.d: Alternative spelling of hearken: to hear, to listen, to have regard.

HARLOT.e: From Middle English harlot, from Old French harlot, herlot, arlot (“vagabond; tramp”), of obscure origin. Likely to be ultimately of Germanic origin, either from a derivation of *harjaz (“army; camp; warrior; military leader”) or from a diminutive of *karilaz (“man; fellow”). Com...

HARMED.d: Past tense of HARM: Physical injury; hurt; damage.
HARMED.e: From Middle English harm, herm, from Old English hearm, from Proto-West Germanic *harm, from Proto-Germanic *harmaz (“harm; shame; pain”). Cognate with Dutch harm (“harm”), German Harm (“harm”), Danish harme (“indignation, resentment”), Icelandic harmur (“sorrow, grief”), Swedish...

HARPED.d: Past tense of HARP: A musical instrument consisting of a body and a curved neck, strung with strings of varying length that are stroked or plucked with the fingers and are vertical to the soundboard when viewed from the end of the body
HARPED.e: From Middle English harpe, from Old English hearpe (“harp”), from Proto-West Germanic *harpā, from Proto-Germanic *harpǭ (“harp”). Cognate with Scots hairp (“harp”), West Frisian harpe, harp (“harp”), Low German Harp (“harp”), Dutch harp (“harp”), German Harfe (“harp”), Danish ha...

HARROW.d: A device consisting of a heavy framework having several disks or teeth in a row, which is dragged across ploughed land to smooth or break up the soil, to remove weeds or cover seeds; a harrow plow.
HARROW.e: From Middle English harwe, harow, from Old English *hearwa (perhaps ultimately cognate with harvest), or from Old Norse harfr/herfi; compare Danish harve (“harrow”), Dutch hark (“rake”). Akin to Latin carpere. According to the OED, the verb senses are partly derived from the noun...

HARTAL.d: the closure of shops and offices, typically as a strike.
HARTAL.e: Borrowed, via Hindi हड़ताल (haṛtāl), from Gujarati હડતાળ (haḍtāḷ), હડતાલ (haḍtāl), literally “locking of shops”.

HASHED.d: Past tense of HASH: Food, especially meat and potatoes, chopped and mixed together.
HASHED.e: From French hacher (“to chop”), from Middle French hacher, from Old French hacher, from Old French hache (“axe”), from Frankish *happjā (“axe”). Compare also Old English ġehæċċa (“sausage meat”, literally “that which is hacked or chopped up”).

HASHES.d: Plural of HASH: Food, especially meat and potatoes, chopped and mixed together.
HASHES.e: From French hacher (“to chop”), from Middle French hacher, from Old French hacher, from Old French hache (“axe”), from Frankish *happjā (“axe”). Compare also Old English ġehæċċa (“sausage meat”, literally “that which is hacked or chopped up”).

HASLET.d: The internal organs of an animal, especially the heart and liver of a pig.
HASLET.e: Inherited from Middle English hastelet, from Anglo-Norman hastilet (“roast meat”), diminutive of haste (“spear, spit, roast meat”), from Latin hasta (“spear”).

HASPED.d: Past tense of HASP: A clasp, especially a metal strap fastened by a padlock or a pin; also, a hook for fastening a door.
HASPED.e:
From Middle English haspe, hespe, from Old English hæsp, hæpse (“hasp; clasp; fastening”), from Proto-West Germanic *haspijā, from Proto-Germanic *haspijǭ, *hapsijǭ (“hasp”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kamb- (“to bend; crook”).
Cognate with Middle Dutch haspe, Middle Low German...

HASSLE.d: Trouble, bother, unwanted annoyances or problems.
HASSLE.e: Unknown. Probably from US Southern dialectal hassle (“to pant, breathe noisily”), possibly from haste + -le (frequentative suffix).

HASTEN.d: To move or act in a quick fashion.

HATBOX.d: A piece of luggage for a hat; a case or box for a hat.

HATFUL.d: The amount that will fit into a hat.

HATING.d: Present participle of HATE: An object of hatred.
HATING.e: From Middle English hate (noun), probably from Old English hatian (“to hate”, verb) and/or Old Norse hatr (“hate”, noun). Merged with Middle English hete, hæte, heate (“hate”), from Old English hete, from Proto-Germanic *hataz (“hatred, hate”), from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂d- (“...

HATRED.d: A strong aversion; an intense dislike.
HATRED.e: From Middle English haterede, hatrede (“hatred”), from hate (“hate”) + -rede (“suffix denoting state or condition”), equivalent to hate + -red; compare sibred, Scots luferent. Related to Icelandic hatri (“hatred”).

HATTED.d: Past tense of HAT: A covering for the head, often in the approximate form of a cone, dome or cylinder closed at its top end, and sometimes having a brim and other decoration.
HATTED.e:
From Middle English hat, from Old English hætt, from Proto-Germanic *hattuz (“hat”), perhaps from a late PIE root Proto-Indo-European *kedʰ- (“to guard, cover, care for, protect”) or wanderwort.
Cognate with North Frisian hat (“hat”), Danish hat (“hat”), Swedish hatt (“hat”), Ice...

HATTER.d: Comparative form of HAT: A covering for the head, often in the approximate form of a cone, dome or cylinder closed at its top end, and sometimes having a brim and other decoration.
HATTER.e:
From Middle English hat, from Old English hætt, from Proto-Germanic *hattuz (“hat”), perhaps from a late PIE root Proto-Indo-European *kedʰ- (“to guard, cover, care for, protect”) or wanderwort.
Cognate with North Frisian hat (“hat”), Danish hat (“hat”), Swedish hatt (“hat”), Ice...

HAULED.d: Past tense of HAUL: To transport by drawing or pulling, as with horses or oxen, or a motor vehicle.
HAULED.e: From Middle English hālen, hailen, haulen, halien (“to drag, pull; to draw up”), from Old French haler (“to haul, pull”), from Frankish *halōn (“to drag, fetch, haul”) or Middle Dutch halen (“to drag, fetch, haul”), possibly merging with Old English *halian (“to haul, drag”); all...

HAULER.d: A person or thing that hauls another person or thing.
HAULER.e: From Middle English halere, equivalent to haul + -er. Doublet of haulier.

HAUNCH.d: The area encompassing the upper thigh, hip and buttocks on one side of a human, primate, or quadruped animal, especially one that can sit on its hindquarters.
HAUNCH.e: From Middle English haunche, hanche, from Old French hanche, hance, anche (compare French hanche, Italian anca), from a Germanic source, probably Frankish *ankijā, from Proto-Germanic *ankijǭ (“joint; ankle”), from Proto-Indo-European *ang- (“joint; lith”). Cognate with Old High ...

HAVING.d: Present participle of HAVE: To possess, own.
HAVING.e: From Middle English haven, from Old English habban (“to have”), from Proto-West Germanic *habbjan, from Proto-Germanic *habjaną (“to have”), durative of *habjaną (“to lift, take up”), from Proto-Indo-European *kh₂pyéti, present tense of *keh₂p- (“to take, seize, catch”). Related ...

HAWING.d: Present participle of HAW: An imitation of laughter, often used to express scorn or disbelief. Often doubled or tripled (haw haw or haw haw haw).
HAWING.e: From Middle English ha (interjection). Compare Old Norse há (interjection), Middle Low German ha, hā (interjection), Old High German aha, hei (interjection).

HAWKED.d: Past tense of HAWK: A diurnal predatory bird of the family Accipitridae, smaller than an eagle.
HAWKED.e:
From Middle English hauk, hauke, hawke, havek, from Old English hafoc (“hawk”), from Proto-West Germanic *habuk, from Proto-Germanic *habukaz, controversially derived from Proto-Indo-European *kopuǵos, perhaps ultimately derived from *keh₂p- (“seize”).
See also West Frisian hauk,...

HAYBOX.d: A chest insulated with a layer of hay or another insulant that utilizes the heat of the food being cooked to complete the cooking process.

HAYING.d: Present participle of HAY: Grass cut and dried for use as animal fodder.
HAYING.e:
From Middle English hey, from Old English hīeġ, from Proto-West Germanic *hawi, from Proto-Germanic *hawją, from *hawwaną (“to hew, cut down”).
Cognate with West Frisian hea (“hay”), Alemannic German Heuw (“hay”), Cimbrian höobe (“hay”), Dutch hooi (“hay”), German Heu (“hay”), Lu...

HAYMOW.d: A pile of hay stored in a barn.
HAYMOW.e: From Middle English hay mowe; equivalent to hay + mow.

HAZARD.d: The chance of suffering harm; danger, peril, risk of loss.
HAZARD.e: From Middle English hasard, from Old French hasart (“a game of dice”) (noun), hasarder (verb), from Arabic اَلزَّهْر (az-zahr, “the dice”). Compare Spanish azar, Portuguese azar.

HAZIER.d: Comparative form of HAZY: Thick or obscured with haze.
HAZIER.e: From earlier hawsey (1625), a nautical term of uncertain origin. Possibly from Middle English *hasi, *haswy, from Old English haswiġ (“grey; ashen; dusky”), from Old English hasu (“dusky; grey; ashen”), from Proto-Germanic *haswaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱeh₂s- (“brig...

HAZING.d: Present participle of HAZE: Very fine solid particles (smoke, dust) or liquid droplets (moisture) suspended in the air, slightly limiting visibility. (Compare fog, mist.)
HAZING.e:
* The earliest instances are of the latter part of the 17th century.
* Possibly back-formation from hazy.
* Compare Old Norse höss (“grey”), akin to Old English hasu (“gray”).

HEADED.d: Past tense of HEAD: The part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth, and main sense organs.
HEADED.e: From Middle English hed, from Old English hēafd-, hēafod (“head; top; chief”), from Proto-West Germanic *haubud, from Proto-Germanic *haubudą (“head”), from Proto-Indo-European *káput.

HEALED.d: Past tense of HEAL: To make better from a disease, wound, etc.; to revive or cure.
HEALED.e: From Middle English helen, from Old English hǣlan (“to heal, cure, save, greet, salute”), from Proto-West Germanic *hailijan, from Proto-Germanic *hailijaną (“to heal, make whole, save”), from Proto-Indo-European *koyl- (“safe, unharmed”). Derived from the adjective at hand in wh...

HEALTH.d: The state of being free from physical or psychological disease, illness, or malfunction; wellness.
HEALTH.e: Inherited from Middle English helthe, from Old English hǣlþ, from Proto-West Germanic *hailiþu, from Proto-Germanic *hailiþō, from Proto-Germanic *hailaz (“whole, hale”). Cognate with Old High German heilida. Analyzable as whole, hale, or heal + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Mor...

HEAPED.d: Past tense of HEAP: A crowd; a throng; a multitude or great number of people.
HEAPED.e: From Middle English hepe, from Old English hēap, from Proto-West Germanic *haup, from Proto-Germanic *haupaz (compare Dutch hoop, German Low German Hupen, German Haufen), from Proto-Indo-European *koupos (“hill”) (compare Lithuanian kaũpas, Albanian qipi (“stack”), Avestan 𐬐𐬂𐬟𐬀 (...

HEARER.e: From Middle English heerar, herere, hyerere, equivalent to hear + -er.

HEARSE.d: A framework of wood or metal placed over the coffin or tomb of a deceased person, and covered with a pall; also, a temporary canopy bearing wax lights and set up in a church, under which the coffin was placed during the funeral ceremonies.
HEARSE.e: From Middle English herse, hers, herce, from Old French herce, from Medieval Latin hercia, from Latin herpicem, hirpex; ultimately from Oscan 𐌇𐌉𐌓𐌐𐌖𐌔 (hirpus, “wolf”), a reference to the teeth, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰers- (“stiff, rigid, bristled”). The Oscan term ...

HEARTH.d: The place in a home where a fire is or was traditionally kept for home heating and for cooking, usually constituted by at least a hearthstone and often enclosed to varying degrees by any combination of reredos, fireplace, oven, smoke hood, or chimney.
HEARTH.e: From Middle English herth, herthe, from Old English heorþ, from Proto-West Germanic *herþ, from Proto-Germanic *herþaz, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kerh₃- (“heat; fire”). Cognate with West Frisian hurd, Dutch haard, German Herd, Swedish härd.

HEARTS.d: Plural of HEART: The organ that pumps blood; emotions.

HEARTY.d: Warm and cordial towards another person.

HEATED.d: simple past and past participle of heat

HEAVEN.e:
From a wide variety of Middle English forms including hevene, heven, hevin, and hewin (“heaven, sky”), from Old English heofon, heofone (“heaven, sky”), from Proto-West Germanic *hebn (“heaven, sky”), of uncertain origin.
Cognate with Scots heiven, hewin (“heaven, sky”), Middle D...

HECKLE.d: To question harshly in an attempt to find or reveal weaknesses.
HECKLE.e: Transferred usage of Middle English hekelen (“to comb flax or hemp with a heckle”), from hekele (“a comb for flax or hemp”), from Middle Dutch hekelen (“to prickle, irritate”), from Proto-West Germanic *hakilōn, from Proto-Germanic *hakilōną, related to *hakô (“hook”). Related to...

HECTIC.d: Very busy with activity and confusion.
HECTIC.e: From Middle English etik, ethik, from Old French etique, from Medieval Latin *hecticus, from Ancient Greek ἑκτικός (hektikós, “habitual, hectic, consumptive”), from ἕξις (héxis, “a state or habit of body or of mind, condition”), from ἔχειν (ékhein, “to have, hold, be in a certain...

HECTOR.d: Sometimes in the form Hector: a blustering, noisy, turbulent fellow; a braggart, bully.
HECTOR.e: From Hector (“in Greek and Roman mythology, a character in Homer’s Iliad who is the greatest warrior of Troy”), from Late Middle English Hector (“warrior with the qualities of Hector”), from Latin Hectōr or Ancient Greek Ἕκτωρ (Héktōr), from ἕκτωρ (héktōr, “holding fast”), from ἔ...

HEDDLE.d: A component in a loom, being one of a number of similar components, through the eye of each of which a distinct strand of the warp is threaded.
HEDDLE.e: From Middle English helde, from Old English hefeld, from the root of Proto-Germanic *habjaną (“to have, heave”), from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p-. Cognate with Old Saxon hevild, Middle Low German hevelte, Icelandic hafald.

HEEDED.d: Past tense of HEED: Careful attention.
HEEDED.e: From Middle English heden, from Old English hēdan (“to heed, take care, observe, attend, guard, take charge, take possession, receive”), from Proto-West Germanic *hōdijan (“to heed, guard”), from Proto-Indo-European *kadʰ- (“to heed, protect”). Cognate with West Frisian hoedje (“...

HEELED.d: Past tense of HEEL: The rear part of the foot, where it joins the leg.
HEELED.e:
From Middle English hele, from Old English hēla, from Proto-West Germanic *hą̄hilō, from Proto-Germanic *hanhilaz, diminutive of Proto-Germanic *hanhaz (“heel, hock”), equivalent to hock + -le. More at hock.
Compare North Frisian haiel, West Frisian hyl, Dutch hiel, German Low Ge...

HEFTED.d: Past tense of HEFT: The feel of the weight of something; heaviness.
HEFTED.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English heft (“heaviness; something heavy, a weight”), from heven (“to lift, raise; to make an effort to lift or raise, heave”) + -th (suffix denoting a condition, quality, state of being, etc., forming nouns), by analogy with the development ...

HEGIRA.d: A journey taken to escape from danger; an exodus.
HEGIRA.e: From Arabic هِجْرَة (hijra, “exodus; emigration”). Doublet of hijra.

HEIFER.d: A young female cow, (particularly) one over one year old but which has not calved.
HEIFER.e: Inherited from Middle English heyfre, hayfre, heyfer, from Old English hēahfore, hēahfru, of disputed origin; see the Old English entry for more discussion.

HEIGHT.d: The distance from the base to the top of something.
HEIGHT.e:
From Middle English heighte, heiȝþe, from Old English hēahþu, hēhþo, hīehþu (“height”), Proto-West Germanic *hauhiþu, from Proto-Germanic *hauhiþō (compare *hauhaz). Equivalent to high + -t (abstract nominal suffix).
Cognates
See also Saterland Frisian Höchte, Hööchte (“height”),...

HEILED.d: Past tense of HEIL: To greet with a Sieg Heil.
HEILED.e: Borrowed from German Heil. Doublet of whole, hail, and hale.

HEIRED.d: Past tense of HEIR: Someone who inherits, or is designated to inherit, the property of another.
HEIRED.e: From Middle English heir, from Anglo-Norman eir, heir, from Latin hērēs.

HELIUM.d: The second-lightest chemical element (symbol He), with an atomic number of 2 and atomic weight of 4.002602, a colorless, odorless and inert noble gas.
HELIUM.e: From New Latin helium, from Ancient Greek ἥλιος (hḗlios, “sun”) (because its presence was first theorised in the Sun's atmosphere) with the suffix + -ium. Probably coined by Norman Lockyer. This suffix is unusual, because it is usually used only for metallic elements. It is likel...

HELMED.d: Past tense of HELM: The tiller (or, in a large ship, the wheel) which is used to control the rudder of a marine vessel; also, the entire steering apparatus of a vessel.
HELMED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English helm, helme (“tiller of a ship”), from Old English helma (“helm, tiller”), from Proto-Germanic *helmô (“handle; helm, tiller”), either from Proto-Indo-European *ḱel- (“to cover”) or from the same source as haulm and helm (“bentgrass, straw”...

HELMET.d: A hard, protective head covering, typically part of armour.
HELMET.e: From Middle English helmet, helmett, a borrowing from Old French helmet, heaumet, a diminutive of helme (Modern French heaume), equivalent to helm + -et. The Old French is itself of Germanic origin (whence Old English helm). Used in English since the 15th century, it has largely ...

HELPED.d: Past tense of HELP: Action given to provide assistance; aid.
HELPED.e:
From Middle English help, from Old English help (“help, aid, assistance, relief”), from Proto-Germanic *helpō (“help”), *hilpiz, *hulpiz, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱelb-, *ḱelp- (“to help”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Hälpe (“help”), West Frisian help (“help”), Cimbrian hölfe...

HELTER.d: Alternative spelling of halter (rope, cord, or similar thing that fastens around the neck).

HEMMED.d: Past tense of HEM: Used to fill in the gap of a pause with a vocalized sound.
HEMMED.e: A sound uttered in imitation of clearing the throat (onomatopoeia)

HEMMER.d: Comparative form of HEM: Used to fill in the gap of a pause with a vocalized sound.
HEMMER.e: A sound uttered in imitation of clearing the throat (onomatopoeia)

HENTAI.d: A work of anime or manga (or any similar medium) that contains heavily sexual or pornographic art.
HENTAI.e: Pseudo-Japonism, derived from 変態(へんたい) (hentai, “pervert”), short for 変態性欲者(へんたいせいよくしゃ) (hentai seiyoku-sha, literally “person with abnormal sexual desires”).

HEPCAT.d: A jazz performer, especially one from the 1940s and 1950s.
HEPCAT.e: From hep + cat, from hep (“sophisticated, aware”). Compare cat (“jazz enthusiast”). Attested in the sense of “sophisticated person” from the 1920s.

HEPTAD.d: Synonym of septet: a group of seven things.

HERALD.d: A messenger, especially one bringing important news.
HERALD.e: From Latin heraldus, from Middle English herald, herauld, heraud, from Anglo-Norman heraud, from Old French heraut, hiraut (modern French héraut), from Frankish *heriwald, from Proto-Germanic *harjawaldaz, a compound consisting of Proto-Indo-European *ker- (“army”) + *h₂welh₁- (“...

HERDED.d: Past tense of HERD: A number of domestic animals assembled together under the watch or ownership of a keeper.
HERDED.e: From Middle English herde, heerde, heorde, from Old English hierd, heord (“herd, flock; keeping, care, custody”), from Proto-West Germanic *herdu, from Proto-Germanic *herdō (“herd”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱerdʰ- (“file, row, herd”). Cognate with German Herde, Danish hjord, S...

HERESY.d: A doctrine held by a member of a religion at variance or conflict with established religious beliefs.
HERESY.e: From Middle English heresie, from Old French heresie (modern hérésie), from Latin haeresis, from Ancient Greek αἵρεσις (haíresis, “choice, system of principles”), from αἱρέομαι (hairéomai, “to take for oneself, to choose”), the middle voice of αἱρέω (hairéō, “to take”), possibly ...

HERIOT.e:
From Old English hereġeatwa (“military equipment, army gear”).
Per Etymonline: "An Anglo-Saxon service of weapons, loaned by the lord to his retainer and repayable to him upon the retainer's death; sense transferred by 13c. to a feudal due upon the death of a tenant, payable to h...

HERMIT.d: A religious recluse; someone who lives alone for religious reasons; an eremite.
HERMIT.e: From Middle English hermite, heremite, eremite, from Old French eremite, from Ecclesiastical Latin, Late Latin eremita, from Ancient Greek ἐρημίτης (erēmítēs, “person of the desert”) from ἐρημία (erēmía, “desert, solitude”), from ἔρημος (érēmos) or ἐρῆμος (erêmos, “uninhabited”) ...

HERNIA.d: A disorder in which a part of the body protrudes abnormally through a tear or opening in an adjacent part, especially of the abdomen.
HERNIA.e: Borrowed from Latin hernia (“protruded viscus”). See also yarn and cord.

HEROIC.d: Of or relating to a hero or heroine; supremely noble.
HEROIC.e: Partly from Middle French heroïque and partly from Latin hērōicus. By surface analysis, hero + -ic.

HEROIN.d: A powerful and addictive drug derived from opium producing intense euphoria, classed as an illegal narcotic in most of the world.
HEROIN.e: Since the 1890s, from German Heroin, originally a trademark, from Ancient Greek ἥρως (hḗrōs, “hero”) and the suffix -in (“-ine”). Said to have been called thus to evoke quick and sweeping effect as a painkiller and cough suppressant (its original uses). Alternatively explained as...

HERPES.d: A viral infection, caused by Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, marked by painful, watery blisters in the skin or in the mucous membranes or on the genitals.
HERPES.e: From Latin herpēs, from Ancient Greek ἕρπης (hérpēs, “herpes”, literally “a creeping”), from ἕρπειν (hérpein, “to creep”).

HETERO.d: Heterosexual: of, pertaining to, or being a heterosexual person.

HETMAN.e: From Polish hetman, probably from Middle High German houbetman, heuptman (“commander”), from Old High German houbitman, from Proto-West Germanic *haubidamann. Compare modern German Hauptmann (“captain”), Haupt, Mann. The Polish e in hetman attests to a borrowing from an East Cent...

HEXANE.d: Any of five isomeric aliphatic hydrocarbons, C₆H₁₄. They are colorless, volatile liquids.

HEXING.d: Present participle of HEX: To cast a spell on (specifically an evil spell), to bewitch.
HEXING.e: First attested about 1830, from Pennsylvania German hexe (“to practice witchcraft”), from German hexen (compare Hexe (“witch”)). The noun appeared later, in the 1850s. Cognate to Norwegian Bokmål heks (“witch”) and Dutch heks (“witch”), Dutch beheksen (“to bewitch”), Old English ...

HEXOSE.d: A sugar or saccharide containing six carbon atoms.

HEYDAY.d: A period of success, popularity, or power; prime.
HEYDAY.e: Late 16th century, from earlier heyda (1520s), as exclamation – compare hey, hei. Sense “period of success, vigor” is a respelling as heyday based on unrelated day (as “period of time”) – compare day in the sun.

HIATUS.d: A gap in a series, making it incomplete.
HIATUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin hiātus (“opening”) (mid-16th century), from hiō (“stand open, yawn”).

HICCUP.d: A spasm of the diaphragm, or the resulting sound.
HICCUP.e:
From earlier hickop, alteration of earlier hicket, hyckock, from hic (onomatopoeic) + -ock (diminutive suffix).
Akin to Scots hick, hix (“hiccup”), West Frisian hik (“hiccup”), Dutch hik (“hiccup”), Middle Low German hükup, huckup, hueckup (modern Low German hick (“hiccup”)), Ger...

HIDING.d: present participle and gerund of hide

HIEING.d: Present participle of HIE: To hasten; to go quickly, to hurry.
HIEING.e:
From Middle English hien, hyen, highen, heiȝen, hiȝen, from Old English hīgian (“to hie, hasten, strive”), from Proto-West Germanic *hīgōn, from Proto-Germanic *hīgōną (“to breathe, snort”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱēygʰ- (“swift, fierce, violent”).
Cognate with Dutch hijgen (“...

HIJACK.d: To forcibly seize control of some vehicle in order to rob it or to reach a destination (especially an airplane, truck or a boat).
HIJACK.e: Possibly from a blend of highway + jacker (“one who holds up”) (1915).

HIKING.d: Present participle of HIKE: A long walk, usually for pleasure or exercise.
HIKING.e: From English dialectal hyke (“to walk vigorously”), probably a Northern form of hitch, from Middle English hytchen, hichen, icchen (“to move, jerk, stir”). Cognate with Scots hyke (“to move with a jerk”), dialectal German hicken (“to hobble, walk with a limp”), Danish hinke (“to ...

HILLED.d: Past tense of HILL: An elevated landmass smaller than a mountain.
HILLED.e:
From Middle English hil, from Old English hyll (“hill”), from Proto-Germanic *hulliz (“hill”), from Proto-Indo-European *kl̥Hnís (“top, hill, rock”) (compare also Proto-Germanic *halluz (“stone, rock”)).
Cognate with Middle Dutch hille, hulle (“hill”), Low German hull (“hill”), O...

HILTED.d: Past tense of HILT: The handle of a sword, consisting of grip, guard, and pommel, designed to facilitate use of the blade and afford protection to the hand.
HILTED.e: From Middle English hilt, hilte, from Old English hilt, hilte, from Proto-Germanic *heltą, *heltǭ, *heltō, *hiltijō, (compare Old Norse hjalt, Old High German helza, Old Saxon helta), from Proto-Indo-European *kel- (“to strike, cut”) (see holt).

HINDER.d: To make difficult to accomplish; to act as an obstacle; to frustrate.
HINDER.e: From Middle English hindren, from Old English hindrian, from Proto-Germanic *hindrōną, *hinderōną (“to hinder”), from Proto-Germanic *hinder (“back”) (adverb). Cognate with Dutch hinderen and German hindern, Latin contra (“back, against”).

HINNIE.d: Alternative form of hinny (“term of endearment”).

HINTED.d: Past tense of HINT: A clue.
HINTED.e: From Middle English hinten, hynten, variant of henten (“to lay hold of, catch”), from Old English hentan (“to seize, grasp”), from Proto-West Germanic *hantijan, from Proto-Germanic *hantijaną. Doublet of hent. Related also to hunt.

HIPPED.d: Past tense of HIP: The outward-projecting parts of the pelvis and top of the femur and the overlying tissue.
HIPPED.e: From Middle English hipe, hupe, from Old English hype, from Proto-Germanic *hupiz (compare Dutch heup, Low German Huop, German Hüfte), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱewb- (compare Welsh cysgu (“to sleep”), Latin cubāre (“to lie”), Ancient Greek κύβος (kúbos, “hollow in the hips”), Al...

HIPPER.d: Comparative form of HIP: The outward-projecting parts of the pelvis and top of the femur and the overlying tissue.
HIPPER.e: From Middle English hipe, hupe, from Old English hype, from Proto-Germanic *hupiz (compare Dutch heup, Low German Huop, German Hüfte), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱewb- (compare Welsh cysgu (“to sleep”), Latin cubāre (“to lie”), Ancient Greek κύβος (kúbos, “hollow in the hips”), Al...

HIPPIE.d: A teenager who imitated the beatniks.
HIPPIE.e: From 1953, a usually disparaging variant of hipster. See also etymology of hippie.

HIRING.d: present participle and gerund of hire

HISSED.d: Past tense of HIS: Belonging to him.
HISSED.e: From Middle English his, from Old English his (“his; its”), from Proto-Germanic *hes (“of this”), genitive of Proto-Germanic *hiz (“this, this one”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱe-, *ḱey- (“this”). Cognate with Danish, Swedish, Norwegian, Icelandic hans (“his”). More at he; see al...

HISSER.d: Comparative form of HIS: Belonging to him.
HISSER.e: From Middle English his, from Old English his (“his; its”), from Proto-Germanic *hes (“of this”), genitive of Proto-Germanic *hiz (“this, this one”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱe-, *ḱey- (“this”). Cognate with Danish, Swedish, Norwegian, Icelandic hans (“his”). More at he; see al...

HISSES.d: Plural of HISS: A sibilant sound, such as that made by a snake or escaping steam; an unvoiced fricative.
HISSES.e: From Middle English hissen, probably of onomatopoeic origin. Compare Middle Dutch hissen, hisschen (“to chase away, shoo”), Middle Low German hissen (“to chase, hound, incite”).

HISTED.d: Past tense of HIST: History (in journal titles such as "J Hist Neurosci" - "Journal of the History of Neuroscience").

HITMAN.d: A male contract killer, especially one paid by a mafia.

HITTER.d: Comparative form of HIT: To strike.
HITTER.e: From Middle English hitten (“to hit, strike, make contact with”), from Old English hittan (“to meet with, come upon, fall in with”), from Old Norse hitta (“to strike, meet”), from Proto-Germanic *hittijaną (“to come upon, find”), from Proto-Indo-European *kh₂eyd- (“to fall; fall ...

HIVING.d: Present participle of HIVE: A structure, whether artificial or natural, for housing a swarm of honeybees.
HIVING.e:
From Middle English hyve, from Old English hȳf, from Proto-West Germanic *hūfi, from Proto-Indo-European *kuHp- (“water vessel”), from *kew- (“to bend, curve”).
See also Dutch huif (“beehive”), Danish dialect huv (“ship’s hull”); also Latin cūpa (“tub, vat”), Ancient Greek κύπη (...

HOARED.d: Past tense of HOAR: A white or greyish-white colour.
HOARED.e: From Middle English hor, hore, from Old English hār (“hoar, hoary, grey, old”), from Proto-West Germanic *hair, from Proto-Germanic *hairaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ḱeh₃- (“grey, dark”). Cognate with German hehr (“noble, sublime”), Herr (“sir, gentleman”), Scottish ...

HOARSE.d: Having a dry, harsh tone to the voice, as a result of a sore throat, age, emotion, etc.
HOARSE.e: From Middle English hors, hos, from Old English hās, *hārs, from Proto-Germanic *haisaz, *haisraz, akin to Old Norse háss (West Norse) and heiss (East Norse) (whence Icelandic hás, Norwegian Nynorsk hås, Norwegian Bokmål hes and Swedish hes).

HOAXED.d: Past tense of HOAX: To deceive (someone) by making them believe something that has been maliciously or mischievously fabricated.
HOAXED.e:
Reportedly a form of hocus. Possibly from hocus-pocus or Latin iocus (“joke”).
Compare hokey.

HOAXES.d: Plural of HOAX: To deceive (someone) by making them believe something that has been maliciously or mischievously fabricated.
HOAXES.e:
Reportedly a form of hocus. Possibly from hocus-pocus or Latin iocus (“joke”).
Compare hokey.

HOBBED.d: Past tense of HOB: A kind of cutting tool, used to cut the teeth of a gear.
HOBBED.e: Related to hub, but the ultimate origin of both words is obscure.

HOBBER.d: Comparative form of HOB: A kind of cutting tool, used to cut the teeth of a gear.
HOBBER.e: Related to hub, but the ultimate origin of both words is obscure.

HOBBIT.d: A member of a fictional race of small humanoids with shaggy hair and hairy feet.
HOBBIT.e: Coined in its current sense by J. R. R. Tolkien in the 1930s, featured in the novels The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings. Jocularly etymologized by him as from a hypothetical Old English *holbytla (literally “hole-builder”), from hol (“hole”) + bytlan (“to build”) + -a (“-er”). ...

HOBBLE.d: One of the short straps tied between the legs of unfenced horses, allowing them to wander short distances but preventing them from running off.
HOBBLE.e: From Middle English hobblen, hobelen, akin to Middle Dutch hoblen, hobbelen (Modern Dutch hobbelen).

HOBNOB.d: A toast made while touching glasses together.
HOBNOB.e: From hob and nob, hob or nob (“a phrase spoken when making a toast, possibly meaning ‘give and take’; to take turns toasting or buying rounds of drinks”) (archaic), from dialectal hab nab (“to have or have not, in the sense of an invitation to have a drink”), from Old English hab...

HOCKED.d: Past tense of HOCK: A Rhenish wine, of a light yellow color, either sparkling or still, from the Hochheim region; often applied to all Rhenish wines.

HOCKEY.d: Any of a family of sports in which hockey sticks are used to move a ball or puck into a goal.
HOCKEY.e: 16th century, of unknown origin. Possibly related to hook due to the curvature of the stick, or from French hoquet.

HODDEN.e: From a dialectal form of holden, archaic past participle of hold.

HODDER.d: Comparative form of HOD: To bob up and down on horseback, as an inexperienced rider may do; to jog.
HODDER.e: Borrowed from Scots hod (“to jog along on horseback”), probably related to hotch (“(verb) to move up and down jerkily, bob; to jog along on horseback; to hop like a frog; to fidget; to shrug; to heave with laughter; to cause to move jerkily; to shift in a sitting position to make...

HOEING.d: Present participle of HOE: Any of various tools for scraping, scratching, digging, or stirring soil or other materials.
HOEING.e: From Middle English howe, from Anglo-Norman houe, from Frankish *hauwā, derivative of Frankish *hauwan (“to hew”), from Proto-Germanic *hawwaną. More at hew.

HOGGED.d: Past tense of HOG: Any animal belonging to the Suidae family of mammals, especially the pig, the warthog, and the boar.
HOGGED.e:
From Middle English hog, from Old English hogg, hocg (“hog”), possibly from Old Norse hǫggva (“to strike, chop, cut”), from Proto-Germanic *hawwaną (“to hew, forge”), from Proto-Indo-European *kewh₂- (“to beat, hew, forge”).
Cognate with Old High German houwan, Old Saxon hauwan, ...

HOGGER.d: Comparative form of HOG: Any animal belonging to the Suidae family of mammals, especially the pig, the warthog, and the boar.
HOGGER.e:
From Middle English hog, from Old English hogg, hocg (“hog”), possibly from Old Norse hǫggva (“to strike, chop, cut”), from Proto-Germanic *hawwaną (“to hew, forge”), from Proto-Indo-European *kewh₂- (“to beat, hew, forge”).
Cognate with Old High German houwan, Old Saxon hauwan, ...

HOGGET.d: A young colt or sheep of either gender from about 9 to 18 months of age (until it cuts 2 teeth).
HOGGET.e: From Middle English hogget, from Anglo-Norman hoget and an Anglo-Latin hogettus.

HOGNUT.d: A pignut or hickory tree (Carya glabra of family Juglandaceae).

HOLIER.d: Comparative form of HOLY: Dedicated to a religious purpose or a god.
HOLIER.e: Inherited from Middle English holi, hali, from Old English hāliġ, hāleġ (“holy, consecrated, sacred, venerated, godly, saintly, ecclesiastical, pacific, tame”), from Proto-West Germanic *hailag, from Proto-Germanic *hailagaz (“holy, bringing health”), from Proto-Germanic *hailaz ...

HOLIES.d: Plural of HOLY: Dedicated to a religious purpose or a god.
HOLIES.e: Inherited from Middle English holi, hali, from Old English hāliġ, hāleġ (“holy, consecrated, sacred, venerated, godly, saintly, ecclesiastical, pacific, tame”), from Proto-West Germanic *hailag, from Proto-Germanic *hailagaz (“holy, bringing health”), from Proto-Germanic *hailaz ...

HOLING.d: Present participle of HOLE: A hollow place or cavity; an excavation; a pit; a dent; a depression; a fissure.
HOLING.e: Inherited from Middle English hole, hol, from Old English hol (“orifice, hollow place, cavity”), from Proto-West Germanic *hol, from Proto-Germanic *hulą (“hollow space, cavity”), noun derivative of Proto-Germanic *hulaz (“hollow”), which is of uncertain ultimate origin. Related ...

HOLISM.d: A theory or belief that the whole is greater than the sum of the parts.
HOLISM.e: From hol- (“whole, entire, total”) + -ism. Coined in 1926 by Jan Smuts.

HOLIST.d: That concentrates on forming an overview of the topic.

HOLLER.e: American variant of holla, hallo or hollo.

HOLLOW.e: From Middle English holow, holowe, holwe, holwȝ, holgh, from Old English holh (“a hollow”), from Proto-West Germanic *holh, from Proto-Germanic *hulhwą, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ḱólḱwos. Cognate with Old High German huliwa and hulwa, Middle High German hülwe. Related to ...

HOMAGE.d: A demonstration of respect, as towards a person after his or her retirement or death.
HOMAGE.e: From Middle English homage, from Old French homage, hommage, from Medieval Latin homināticum (“homage, the service of a vassal or 'man'”), from Latin homō (“a man, in Medieval Latin a vassal”) + -āticum (noun-forming suffix). The American pronunciations in /-ɑːʒ/ and with silent ...

HOMBRE.d: A man, a chap, a guy; especially a Hispanic or Spanish man.
HOMBRE.e: Borrowed from Spanish hombre (“man; human being”), from Old Spanish omne, from Latin hominem, accusative of homō (“a human being, a person”), from Old Latin hemō, from Proto-Italic *hemō (“man”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰmṓ (“earthling”), from *dʰéǵʰōm (“earth”). Doublet of go...

HOMELY.d: Characteristic of, belonging to, or befitting a home; domestic, cosy.
HOMELY.e: From Middle English homly, hoomly, hamely (“domestic, familiar, plain, unattractive”), from Old English *hāmlīċ (“of the home, domestic”), from Proto-West Germanic *haimalīk (“of or characteristic of home”), equivalent to home + -ly. Cognate with Scots hamely (“familiar, personal...

HOMILY.d: A sermon, especially concerning a practical matter.
HOMILY.e: From Middle English omelī, omelīe, omelye, from Old French omelie and directly from Late Latin homīlia (“homily”), from Ancient Greek ὁμιλία (homilía, “homily; instruction”), from ὅμῑλος (hómīlos, “crowd, throng”) + -ῐ́ᾱ (-ĭ́ā, suffix forming abstract feminine nouns). ὅμῑλος is d...

HOMING.d: Present participle of HOME: A dwelling.
HOMING.e:
From Middle English hōm, from Old English hām, from Proto-West Germanic *haim, from Proto-Germanic *haimaz (“home, village”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱóymos (“village, home”), from the root *tḱey-. Doublet of heyem.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots hame (“home”), Yola haime, hime, h...

HONEST.d: Scrupulous with regard to telling the truth; not given to swindling, lying, or fraud; upright.
HONEST.e: From Middle English honest, honeste (“honourable, appropriate, excellent”), from Old French honeste, from Latin honestus, from honor. For the verb, see Latin honestāre (“to clothe or adorn with honour”), and compare French honester. Displaced native Old English sōþfæst (literally...

HONING.d: Present participle of HONE: A sharpening stone composed of extra-fine grit used for removing the burr or curl from the blade of a razor or some other edge tool.
HONING.e: From Middle English hon (“whetstone”), from Old English hān, from Proto-Germanic *hainō (compare Dutch heen, Norwegian hein), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱeh₃i- (“to sharpen”) (compare Ancient Greek κῶνος (kônos, “cone”), Persian سان (sân, “whetstone”)).

HONKED.d: Past tense of HONK: To use a car horn.

HONOUR.d: British, Canadian, Commonwealth, and Ireland standard spelling of honor.

HOODIE.d: A sweatshirt with an integral hood and, sometimes, a large kangaroo pocket at the front.
HOODIE.e: From hood + -ie (diminutive suffix). In sense “person wearing a hoodie”, influenced by sense -ie (“person associated with suffixed noun, often derogatory”); compare townie.

HOODOO.d: A set of spiritual practices and traditions created and concealed from slave-owners by enslaved Africans in North America, based on traditional African beliefs.

HOOFED.d: Past tense of HOOF: The tip of a toe of an ungulate such as a horse, ox or deer, strengthened by a thick keratin covering.
HOOFED.e: From Middle English hoof, hof, from Old English hōf, from Proto-Germanic *hōfaz (compare West Frisian hoef, Dutch hoef, German Huf, Danish hov, Norwegian hov, Swedish hov), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱoph₂ós (compare Sanskrit शफ (śaphá, “hoof, claw”), Avestan 𐬯𐬀𐬟𐬀 (safa, “hoof”), ...

HOOKAH.d: A pipe with a long flexible tube that draws the smoke through water, traditionally used for smoking tobacco, which is often flavored.
HOOKAH.e: Borrowed from Hindustani حقہ / हुक़्क़ा (huqqā) and, in turn, derived from Arabic حُقَّة (ḥuqqa, “pot, jar”), from حُقّ (ḥuqq, “cavity, hollow”).

HOOKED.d: Past tense of HOOK: A rod bent into a curved shape, typically with one end free and the other end secured to a rope or other attachment.
HOOKED.e:
From Middle English hoke, from Old English hōc, from Proto-West Germanic *hōk, from Proto-Germanic *hōkaz, variant of *hakô (“hook”), probably ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *kog-, *keg-, *keng- (“peg, hook, claw”).
Cognates
Compare West Frisian heak, Dutch haak (“hook”)) (c...

HOOPED.d: Past tense of HOOP: A circular band of metal used to bind a barrel.
HOOPED.e: From Middle English hoop, hoope, from Old English hōp (“mound, raised land; in combination, circular object”), from Proto-Germanic *hōpą (“bend, bow, arch”) (compare Saterland Frisian Houp (“hoop”), Dutch hoep (“hoop”), Old Norse hóp (“bay, inlet”)), from Proto-Indo-European *kāb...

HOOPLA.d: A bustling to-do, excited speech or noise.
HOOPLA.e: Earlier houp-la, hoop la, first attested in c. 1877, probably from French houp-là, oup-là (“upsadaisy, upsy-daisy”), a cry to various animals close to humans like horses and dogs, of likely onomatopoeic origin (but see là). Compare interjections like whoop, ahoy, hoo.

HOOPOE.d: Any Old World bird of genus Upupa, especially Upupa epops (Eurasian hoopoe), known for its distinctive plumage, fanlike crest, and slender bill.
HOOPOE.e: Alteration of obsolete hoopoop, from earlier hoop, from Middle French and Old French huppe, from Latin upupa, ultimately onomatopoeic; Compare Ancient Greek ἔποψ (épops), Persian پوپو (popo).

HOORAY.d: Used to express approval, joy or victory.
HOORAY.e:
Unknown, first attested in the late 17th c. Possible etymologies:
* Alteration of huzzah. This is however questionable.
* From hurra in German, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian, húrra in Icelandic, hoera in Dutch.

HOOTCH.d: Alternative spelling of hooch (“type of drink”).

HOOTED.d: Past tense of HOOT: A derisive cry or shout.
HOOTED.e: From Middle English houten, huten, hoten, of North Germanic origin, from or related to Old Swedish huta (“to cast out in contempt”), related to Middle High German hiuzen, hūzen (“to call to pursuit”), Swedish hut! (“begone!”, interjection), Dutch hui (“ho, hallo”), Danish huj (“h...

HOOVER.d: An American surname from German (shared by several famous people including J. Edgar Hoover and Herbert Hoover).
HOOVER.e: The surname is an anglicization of German Huber or Low German Hufer, originally designating a landowner or a prosperous small-scale farmer. The common noun and verb are taken from the brand name of one of the first vacuum cleaners (see hoover).

HOOVES.d: Plural of HOOF: The tip of a toe of an ungulate such as a horse, ox or deer, strengthened by a thick keratin covering.
HOOVES.e: From Middle English hoof, hof, from Old English hōf, from Proto-Germanic *hōfaz (compare West Frisian hoef, Dutch hoef, German Huf, Danish hov, Norwegian hov, Swedish hov), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱoph₂ós (compare Sanskrit शफ (śaphá, “hoof, claw”), Avestan 𐬯𐬀𐬟𐬀 (safa, “hoof”), ...

HOPING.d: Present participle of HOPE: To want (something) to happen, with a sense of expectation that it might [with that (+ clause); or (informal) with clause; or with so or (negative) not].
HOPING.e:
From Middle English hopen, from Old English hopian (“hope”), from Proto-West Germanic *hopōn, further etymology unclear.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland Frisian, West Frisian hoopje (“to hope”), Cimbrian hòffan (“to hope”), Dutch hopen (“to hope”), German, Luxembourgish hoffen (“...

HOPPED.d: Past tense of HOP: A short jump.
HOPPED.e:
From Middle English hoppen, from Old English hoppian (“to hop, spring, leap, dance”), from Proto-West Germanic *huppōn, from Proto-Germanic *huppōną (“to hop”), from Proto-Indo-European *kewb- (“to bend, bow”).
Cognate with Dutch hoppen (“to hop”), German hopfen, hoppen (“to hop”...

HOPPER.d: Comparative form of HOP: A short jump.
HOPPER.e:
From Middle English hoppen, from Old English hoppian (“to hop, spring, leap, dance”), from Proto-West Germanic *huppōn, from Proto-Germanic *huppōną (“to hop”), from Proto-Indo-European *kewb- (“to bend, bow”).
Cognate with Dutch hoppen (“to hop”), German hopfen, hoppen (“to hop”...

HOPPLE.d: A fetter for horses or cattle when turned out to graze.

HORARY.d: Pertaining to an hour or hours.
HORARY.e: From Medieval Latin hōrārius, from Latin hōra (“hour”).

HORNED.e:
From Middle English horned, hornyd, from Old English hyrned, ġehyrned (“having horns; horned”),
from Proto-Germanic *hurnidaz (“horned”), past participle of Proto-Germanic *hurnijaną (“to horn; provide or fit with horns”); equivalent to horn (“noun”) + -ed. Cognate with Dutch geh...

HORNET.d: A large wasp, of the genus Vespa, having a brown-and-yellow-striped body and the ability to inflict a serious sting.
HORNET.e: From Middle English hernet, from Old English hyrnetu, hyrnete, from Proto-West Germanic *hurnutu, from Proto-Germanic *hurznutō (compare German Hornisse), alteration of Proto-Germanic *hursulǭ (compare Dutch horzel), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱr̥h₂sro- (“hornet”, literally “the o...

HORRID.e: Borrowed from Latin horridus (“rough, bristly, savage, shaggy, rude”), from horrere (“to bristle”). See horrent, horror, ordure.

HORROR.d: An intense distressing emotion of fear or repugnance.
HORROR.e: From Middle English horer, horrour, from Old French horror, from Latin horror (“a bristling, a shaking, trembling as with cold or fear, terror”), from horrere (“to bristle, shake, be terrified”). Displaced native Old English ōga.

HORSED.d: Past tense of HORSE: A large four-legged animal used for riding.

HOSIER.d: One who deals in hose or stocking, or in goods knit or woven like hose.
HOSIER.e: From Middle English hosyer; equivalent to hose + -ier.

HOSING.d: Present participle of HOSE: A flexible tube conveying water or other fluid.
HOSING.e:
From Middle English hose (“leggings, hose”), from Old English hose, hosa (“hose, leggings”), from Proto-West Germanic *hosā, from Proto-Germanic *husǭ (“coverings, leggings, trousers”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewH- (“to cover”).
Cognate with West Frisian hoas (“hose”), Dutc...

HOSTED.d: Past tense of HOST: One which receives or entertains a guest, socially, commercially, or officially.
HOSTED.e: From Middle English hoste, from Old French oste (French: hôte), from Latin hospitem, accusative of hospes (“a host, also a sojourner, visitor, guest; hence, a foreigner, a stranger”), from *hostipotis, an old compound of hostis and the root of potis, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰó...

HOSTEL.d: A commercial overnight lodging place, with dormitory accommodation and shared facilities, especially a youth hostel.
HOSTEL.e: From Middle English hostel, from Old French hostel, ostel, from Late Latin hospitale (“hospice”), from Classical Latin hospitalis (“hospitable”) itself from hospes (“host”) + -alis (“-al”). Doublet of hotel and hospital. Obsolete from the 16th to 18th centuries, until it was revi...

HOTBED.d: A low bed of earth covered with glass, and heated with rotting manure, used for the germination of seeds and the growth of tender plants, like a miniature hothouse.

HOTBOX.d: A container maintained at elevated temperatures in order to heat or cook its contents.

HOTELS.d: Plural of HOTEL: An establishment providing lodging.

HOTTED.d: Past tense of HOT: Relating to heat and conditions which produce it.
HOTTED.e: From Middle English hot, hat, from Old English hāt (“hot”), from Proto-West Germanic *hait, from Proto-Germanic *haitaz (“hot”), from Proto-Indo-European *keHy- (“hot; to heat”). Cognate with Scots hate, hait (“hot”), North Frisian hiet (“hot”), Saterland Frisian heet (“hot”), We...

HOTTER.d: Comparative form of HOT: Relating to heat and conditions which produce it.
HOTTER.e: From Middle English hot, hat, from Old English hāt (“hot”), from Proto-West Germanic *hait, from Proto-Germanic *haitaz (“hot”), from Proto-Indo-European *keHy- (“hot; to heat”). Cognate with Scots hate, hait (“hot”), North Frisian hiet (“hot”), Saterland Frisian heet (“hot”), We...

HOTTIE.e: From hot + -ie. Sense “stolen vehicle” perhaps from hot-wired.

HOUSED.d: Enclosed, provided or covered with a house.

HOUSIE.d: A gambling game similar to bingo.

HOWDAH.d: A seat, usually with a canopy, carried on the back of an elephant or camel.
HOWDAH.e: From Hindi हौदा (haudā), from Arabic هَوْدَج (hawdaj, “litter carried by a camel”) (1774).

HOWLED.d: Past tense of HOWL: The protracted, mournful cry of a dog, wolf or other canid; also of other animals.
HOWLED.e:
From Middle English howlen, houlen, from Old English *hūlian, from Proto-West Germanic *hūilōn, from Proto-Germanic *hūwilōną, *hiuwilōną (“to howl”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *kū-, *kew- (“to howl, scream”). Likely of imitative origin.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian huul...

HOYDEN.d: A rude, uncultured or rowdy girl or woman.
HOYDEN.e: Probably from Middle Dutch heyden (“heathen, gypsy”), heidin (Modern Dutch heiden).

HUBBED.d: Past tense of HUB: The central part, usually cylindrical, of a wheel; the nave.
HUBBED.e: From earlier hubbe, which has the same immediate origin as hob. Hub was originally a dialectal word; its ultimate origin is unknown. Compare German Hubbel (“bump on a surface”), from Proto-West Germanic *hubil (“bump, hill”) (which contains a diminutive suffix *-il); compare Engl...

HUBBER.d: Comparative form of HUB: The central part, usually cylindrical, of a wheel; the nave.
HUBBER.e: From earlier hubbe, which has the same immediate origin as hob. Hub was originally a dialectal word; its ultimate origin is unknown. Compare German Hubbel (“bump on a surface”), from Proto-West Germanic *hubil (“bump, hill”) (which contains a diminutive suffix *-il); compare Engl...

HUBBUB.d: A confused uproar, commotion, tumult or racket.
HUBBUB.e: Mid 16th c. Perhaps from Irish; compare Irish ababú!, abú! (battle-cry), Scottish Gaelic ub! ub! (expressing contempt, etc.), ubh ubh! (expressing disgust).

HUBCAP.d: A decorative and protective disk that covers the hub of a motor car wheel.

HUBRIS.d: Excessive pride, presumption, or arrogance (originally toward the gods).
HUBRIS.e: From Ancient Greek ὕβρις (húbris, “insolence, sexual outrage”).

HUCHEN.d: Hucho hucho, a species of freshwater fish in the salmon family (Salmonidae) of order Salmoniformes.
