HUDDLE.e: From Middle English *hudelen, alteration (due to hudels, hidels (“hiding place”), see hiddle) of *huderen, hoderen (“to cover; press together; huddle”), a frequentative form of Middle English huden, hiden (“to hide”), equivalent to hide + -le and/or hide + -er. Compare Low German...

HUFFED.d: Past tense of HUFF: A heavy breath; a grunt or sigh.
HUFFED.e: Probably an altered spelling of earlier *hough, represented by Scots hech (“to breathe hard, pant”). Compare also German hauchen (“to breathe”).

HUGGED.d: Past tense of HUG: A close embrace, especially when charged with an emotion such as affection, joy, relief, lust, anger, aggression, compassion, and the like, as opposed to being characterized by formality, equivocation or ambivalence (a half-embrace or "little hug").
HUGGED.e: From earlier hugge (“to embrace, clasp with the arms”) (1560), probably representing a conflation of huck (“to crouch, huddle down”) and Old Norse hugga (“to comfort, console”), from hugr (“mind, heart, thought”), from Proto-Germanic *hugiz (“mind, thought, sense”), cognate with ...

HUGGER.d: Comparative form of HUG: A close embrace, especially when charged with an emotion such as affection, joy, relief, lust, anger, aggression, compassion, and the like, as opposed to being characterized by formality, equivocation or ambivalence (a half-embrace or "little hug").
HUGGER.e: From earlier hugge (“to embrace, clasp with the arms”) (1560), probably representing a conflation of huck (“to crouch, huddle down”) and Old Norse hugga (“to comfort, console”), from hugr (“mind, heart, thought”), from Proto-Germanic *hugiz (“mind, thought, sense”), cognate with ...

HULKED.d: Past tense of HULK: A large ship used for transportation; (more generally) a large ship that is difficult to manoeuvre.
HULKED.e:
From Middle English hulk, hulke, holke (“hut; shed for hogs; type of ship; husk, pod, shell; large, clumsy person; a giant”) (probably reinforced by
Middle Dutch hulk, huelc, and Middle Low German hulk, holk, hollek (“freighter, cargo ship, barge”)), from Old English hulc (“light...

HULLED.d: Past tense of HULL: The outer covering of a fruit or seed.
HULLED.e:
From Middle English hul, hulle, holle (“seed covering, hull of a ship”), from Old English hulu (“seed covering”), from Proto-Germanic *hul-, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ḱel- (“to cover, hide”); or possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kal- (“hard”).
Compare Dutch hul (“hood”),...

HUMANE.d: Having or showing concern for the pain or suffering of another; compassionate.
HUMANE.e: From Middle English humain, humayne, from Old French humain, umain, from Latin hūmānus, from Latin homō (“man”). Cognate with Old English guma (“man”), whence the groom in English bridegroom.

HUMANS.d: Plural of HUMAN: Relating to people; a person.

HUMBLE.d: Not pretentious or magnificent; unpretending; unassuming.
HUMBLE.e: From Middle English humble, from Old French humble, umble, humle, from Latin humilis (“low, slight, hence mean, humble”) (compare Greek χαμηλός (khamēlós, “on the ground, low, trifling”)), from humus (“the earth, ground”), humi (“on the ground”). See homage, and compare chameleon...

HUMBUG.e: Origin unknown; the Oxford English Dictionary (OED) states that “the facts as to its origin appear to have been lost, even before the word became common enough to excite attention”. It has been suggested that the word possibly derives from hummer (“(slang) An obvious lie”), or fr...

HUMITE.d: An orthorhombic-dipyramidal mineral containing fluorine, hydrogen, iron, magnesium, oxygen, and silicon.

HUMMED.d: Past tense of HUM: A hummed tune, i.e. created orally with lips closed.
HUMMED.e: From Middle English hummen (“to hum, buzz, drone, make a murmuring sound to cover embarrassment”); akin to Dutch hommelen (“to bumble, buzz”), dialectal Dutch hommen (“to buzz, hum”), Middle High German hummen (“to hum”), probably ultimately of imitative origin.

HUMMER.d: Comparative form of HUM: A hummed tune, i.e. created orally with lips closed.
HUMMER.e: From Middle English hummen (“to hum, buzz, drone, make a murmuring sound to cover embarrassment”); akin to Dutch hommelen (“to bumble, buzz”), dialectal Dutch hommen (“to buzz, hum”), Middle High German hummen (“to hum”), probably ultimately of imitative origin.

HUMMUS.d: A Levantine Arab dip made of chickpea paste with various additions, such as olive oil, fresh garlic, lemon juice, and tahini, often eaten with pitta bread, or as a meze.

HUMOUR.d: The quality of being amusing, comical, funny.
HUMOUR.e: From Middle English humour, from Old French humor, humour, from Latin hūmor, correctly ūmor (“liquid”), from hūmeō, correctly ūmeō (“to be moist”). The h in these words, which was silent in late Classical Latin, is folk etymological, due to the erroneous association with the word...

HUMPED.d: Past tense of HUMP: A mound of earth.
HUMPED.e: Probably borrowed from Dutch homp (“hump, lump”) or Middle Low German hump (“heap, hill, stump”), from Old Saxon *hump (“hill, heap, thick piece”), from Proto-Germanic *humpaz (“hip, height”), from Proto-Indo-European *kumb- (“curved”). Compare Proto-Germanic *huppōną (“to hop”),...

HUNGER.d: A need or compelling desire for food.
HUNGER.e:
From Middle English hunger, from Old English hungor (“hunger, desire; famine”), from Proto-West Germanic *hungr, from Proto-Germanic *hungruz, *hunhruz (“hunger”), from Proto-Indo-European *kenk- (“to burn, smart, desire, hunger, thirst”).
Cognate with West Frisian honger, hûnger...

HUNGRY.d: Affected by hunger; having the physical need for food.
HUNGRY.e: From Middle English hungry, from Old English hungriġ, from Proto-West Germanic *hungrug, from Proto-Germanic *hungrugaz (“hungry”); equivalent to hunger + -y. Cognate with West Frisian hongerich (“hungry”), Dutch hongerig (“hungry”), German hungrig (“hungry”), Swedish hungrig (“h...

HUNKER.d: To crouch or squat close to the ground or lie down
HUNKER.e: Originally Scottish. Origin uncertain, but probably of Germanic origin, perhaps *hunk- a nasalised variant of *huk- (compare Scots hoonk, hounk, variants of huk, hok (“to squat, crouch”); Scots hocker (“to crouch down, hunker”)), all of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse huka ...

HUNTED.d: Past tense of HUNT: To find or search for an animal in the wild with the intention of killing the animal for its meat or for sport.
HUNTED.e: From Middle English hunten, from Old English huntian (“to hunt”), from Proto-West Germanic *huntōn (“to hunt, capture”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *ḱent- (“to catch, seize”). Related to Old High German hunda (“booty”), Gothic 𐌷𐌿𐌽𐌸𐍃 (hunþs, “body of captives”), Old English...

HURDLE.d: An artificial barrier, variously constructed, over which athletes or horses jump in a race.
HURDLE.e:
]
From Middle English hurdel, hirdel, herdel, hyrdel, from Old English hyrdel (“frame of intertwined twigs used as a temporary barrier”), diminutive of *hyrd, from Proto-Germanic *hurdiz, from Pre-Germanic *kr̥h₂tis, from Proto-Indo-European *kreh₂-. Cognate with Dutch horde, Ger...

HURLED.d: Past tense of HURL: To throw (something) with force.
HURLED.e: Inherited from Middle English hurlen, of onomatopoeic origin; compare hurry, hurtle.

HURLEY.d: A stick used in the game of hurling.

HURRAH.e: Unknown. Possibly adopted from German hurra, itself of uncertain origin, or possibly an alteration of huzzah.

HURTED.d: Past tense of HURT: To cause (a person or animal) physical pain and/or injury.
HURTED.e: From Middle English hurten, hirten, hertan (“to injure, scathe, knock together”), from Old Northern French hurter ("to ram into, strike, collide with"; > Modern French heurter), perhaps from Frankish *hūrt (“a battering ram”), cognate with Welsh hwrdd (“ram”) and Cornish hordh (“...

HURTLE.d: To propel or throw (something) hard or violently; to fling, to hurl.
HURTLE.e: The verb is derived from Middle English hurtelen, hurtlen (“to cast, hurl, throw; to charge at; to clash in combat, fight; to collide; to injure; to knock down; to propel, push, thrust; to rush; to stumble”) [and other forms], from hurten (“to injure, wound, hurt (physically or f...

HUSHED.d: Past tense of HUSH: To become quiet.
HUSHED.e: From Middle English huschen (“to hush”) (as past participle husht (“silent; hushed”) and interjection husht (“quiet!”)). Cognate with Low German huschen, hüssen (“to hush; lull”), German huschen (“to shoo; scurry”), Danish hysse (“to hush”), and maybe Albanian hesht.

HUSHES.d: Plural of HUSH: To become quiet.
HUSHES.e: From Middle English huschen (“to hush”) (as past participle husht (“silent; hushed”) and interjection husht (“quiet!”)). Cognate with Low German huschen, hüssen (“to hush; lull”), German huschen (“to shoo; scurry”), Danish hysse (“to hush”), and maybe Albanian hesht.

HUSKED.d: Past tense of HUSK: The dry, leafy or stringy exterior of certain vegetables or fruits, which must be removed before eating the meat inside.
HUSKED.e: From Middle English huske, husk (“husk”). Perhaps from Old English *husuc, *hosuc (“little covering, sheath”), diminutive of hosu (“pod, shell, husk”), from Proto-West Germanic *hosā, from Proto-Germanic *husǭ (“covering, shell, leggings”), from Proto-Indo-European *kawəs- / kawe...

HUSSAR.d: A member of the national cavalry of Hungary, Croatia and Poland.
HUSSAR.e: Borrowed from French hussard, from Hungarian huszár (“cavalryman”), from Serbo-Croatian gusar (“corsair”), from Byzantine Greek χωσάριος, χονσάριος (khōsários, khonsários) or from Italian corsaro (“corsair”), from Medieval Latin cursārius (“pirate”), from Latin cursus (“running”)...

HUSTLE.d: To push someone roughly; to crowd; to jostle.
HUSTLE.e: From Dutch husselen or by metathesis from Dutch hutselen (“to shake up”), a frequentative of hutsen (“to stir, to move something (back and forth)”).

HUTTED.d: Past tense of HUT: A small, simple one-storey dwelling or shelter, often with just one room, and generally built of readily available local materials.
HUTTED.e: From Middle English *hutte, hotte, from both Old English hōd and Old English hȳdan (“to hide”) and influenced by Anglo-Norman hute or hutte, from Middle French hutte, from Old French hute (“hut”), hute (“cottage”), from Old High German hutta (“hut, cottage”), from Proto-Germanic ...

HYBRID.d: Offspring resulting from cross-breeding different entities, e.g. two different species or two purebred parent strains.
HYBRID.e: From Latin hybrida, a variant of hibrida (“a mongrel; specifically, offspring of a tame sow and a wild boar”). Attested since 1601, but rare before c. 1850.

HYMNAL.d: A collection of hymns; a hymn book.
HYMNAL.e: From Middle English hymnale, from Medieval Latin hymnāle, noun use of neuter of hymnālis.

HYMNED.d: Past tense of HYMN: A song of praise or worship, especially a religious one.
HYMNED.e: From Middle English ymne, from Old English ymen (reinforced by Old French ymne), from Latin hymnus, borrowed from Ancient Greek ὕμνος (húmnos).

HYPHEN.d: The symbol "‐", typically used to join two or more words to form a compound term, or to indicate that a word has been split at the end of a line.
HYPHEN.e: From Late Latin, from Ancient Greek ὑφέν (huphén, “together”), contracted from ὑφ’ ἕν (huph’ hén, “under one”), from ὑπό (hupó, “under”) + ἕν (hén, “one”), neuter of εἷς (heîs, “one”).

HYPING.d: Present participle of HYPE: Promotion or propaganda, especially exaggerated claims.

HYPOED.d: Past tense of HYPO: Melancholy; a fit of hypochondria; a morbid depression.
HYPOED.e: Clipping of various terms beginning with hypo-, from Ancient Greek ὑπό (hupó, “under”).

HYPOID.d: Describing gear wheels whose axes are offset from each other.

HYSSOP.d: Any of several aromatic bushy herbs, of the genus Hyssopus, native to Southern Europe and once used medicinally.
HYSSOP.e: Via Latin hȳsōpum, from Ancient Greek ὕσσωπος (hússōpos), of Semitic origin.

IAMBIC.d: Consisting of iambs (metrical feet with an unstressed-stressed pattern) or characterized by their predominance.
IAMBIC.e: From Middle French iambique, from Late Latin ïambicus, from Ancient Greek ἰαμβικός (iambikós), from ἴαμβος (íambos) + -ικός (-ikós).

IAMBUS.e: Borrowed from Latin ïambus (“a certain poetic meter”), from Ancient Greek ἴαμβος (íambos).

IBEXES.d: Plural of IBEX: A type of wild mountain goat of the genus Capra, such as the species Capra ibex.
IBEXES.e: From Latin ībex (“chamois”), possibly from Iberian or Aquitanian; akin to Old Spanish bezerro (“bull”) (modern becerro (“yearling”)).

IBISES.d: Plural of IBIS: Any of various long-legged wading birds in the family Threskiornithidae, having long downcurved bills used to probe the mud for prey such as crustaceans.
IBISES.e: Mentioned in the Wycliffe Bible as ybyn or ibin, as ibys from 16th century and ibis shortly after. From Latin ībis, from Ancient Greek ἶβις (îbis), from Egyptian h-b-G26 (hbj) (compare Coptic ϩⲓⲃⲱⲓ (hibōi) or ϩⲓⲡ (hip)).

ICEBOX.d: A box or compartment containing ice, typically used to keep provisions cool.

ICICLE.d: A drooping, tapering shape of ice.
ICICLE.e: From Middle English isykle, isikel, from Old English *īsġicel, from Proto-West Germanic *īsajikil, *īsajekul, equivalent to ice + ickle. It was assimilated to nouns in -icle, from Latin -iculus—the expected spelling would have -ickle. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Iesjuukel (“ic...

ICIEST.d: Superlative form of ICY: Pertaining to, resembling, or abounding in ice; cold; frosty.
ICIEST.e: From ice + -y; cf. Old English īsiġ.

ICKIER.d: Comparative form of ICKY: Unpleasantly sticky; yucky; disgusting.
ICKIER.e: 1935, American English; from icky-boo (circa 1920): sickly, nauseated; baby talk corruption of sick; from a sentimental term for jazz music.

IDEAED.d: Past tense of IDEA: An abstract archetype of a given thing, compared to which real-life examples are seen as imperfect approximations; pure essence, as opposed to actual examples.
IDEAED.e: Borrowed from Latin idea (“a (Platonic) idea; archetype”), from Ancient Greek ἰδέα (idéa, “notion, pattern”), from εἴδω (eídō, “I see”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *weyd- (“to know; see”). Cognate with French idée. Doublet of idée. Related to idol, idolum, and eidolon.

IDEATE.d: To apprehend in thought so as to fix and hold in the mind; to memorize.

IDIOCY.d: The state or condition of being an idiot; the quality of having an intelligence level far below average; mental retardation; intellectual disability.
IDIOCY.e: From French idiotie, from Old French idiot. Displaced earlier idiotacy, idiotry. Equivalent to idiot + -cy.

IDLING.d: Present participle of IDLE: Empty, vacant.
IDLING.e: From Middle English idel, ydel, from Old English īdel, from Proto-West Germanic *īdal, from Proto-Germanic *īdalaz. Cognate with Dutch ijdel (“vain, meaningless”), ijl (“rareified, skinny”), iel (“thin, slender”); German Low German iedel (“vain, idle”); German eitel (“vain, conce...

IFFIER.d: Comparative form of IFFY: Of dubious authenticity, legitimacy or legality.

IGNITE.d: to set fire to (something), to light (something)
IGNITE.e: From Latin ignītus, past participle of igniō, ignire (“to set on fire, ignite”), from Latin ignis (“fire”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁n̥gʷnis, and thus related to Sanskrit अग्नि (agní), Lithuanian ugnis, and Russian ого́нь (ogónʹ).

IGNORE.d: To deliberately not listen or pay attention to.
IGNORE.e: From French ignorer, from Latin ignōrō (“to have no knowledge of, mistake, take no notice of, ignore”), from ignārus (“not knowing”), from in + gnārus (“knowing”), from gnōscō, nōscō; see know.

IGUANA.d: A green iguana (Iguana iguana), a large tropical American lizard often kept as a pet.
IGUANA.e: Borrowed from Spanish iguana, from Taíno *iwana.

ILEXES.d: Plural of ILEX: Holm oak (Quercus ilex).

ILLUDE.d: To give a false impression to.

ILLUME.d: To throw or spread light upon; to make light or bright.

IMAGED.d: Past tense of IMAGE: A visual representation; an impression.
IMAGED.e: From Old French image, from Latin imāgō.

IMAGES.d: Plural of IMAGE: A visual representation; an impression.
IMAGES.e: From Old French image, from Latin imāgō.

IMBIBE.d: To drink (used frequently of alcoholic beverages).
IMBIBE.e: From Middle English imbiben, from Latin imbibō, from im- + bibō (“to drink”) (whence also beverage), from Proto-Italic *pibō, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₃-, whence also potable, potion.

IMBRUE.d: To stain [with in or with ‘blood, slaughter, etc.’].
IMBRUE.e: From Middle English embrewen, from Old French *embrever (whence Middle French embreuver), metathetic variant of embevrer (“to imbibe, steep, penetrate, soak”) (with same stem variation found in French abreuver and beuverie), from Vulgar Latin imbiberāre.

IMMUNE.e: From Middle English, from Middle French immun, from Latin immūnis (“exempt from public service”), from in- (“not”) + mūnus (“service”).

IMMURE.d: To cloister, confine, imprison or hole up: to lock someone up or seclude oneself behind walls.
IMMURE.e: From Middle English enmuren and Middle French emmurer, both from Old French enmurer, from Latin immūrō, from in- + mūrus (“wall”). Modern spelling is modelled after the Latin.

IMPACT.d: The striking of one body against another; collision.
IMPACT.e: Attested since the 17th century, from Latin impāctus.

IMPAIR.d: To weaken; to affect negatively; to have a diminishing effect on.
IMPAIR.e: From Middle English impairen, empeiren, from Old French empeirier, from Early Medieval Latin impeiōrāre, from in- + Late Latin peiōrāre (“worsen”), from peiōrem (“worse”), comparative of malus (“bad”).

IMPALA.d: An African antelope, Aepyceros melampus, noted for its leaping ability; the male has ridged, curved horns.

IMPALE.d: To pierce (something) with any long, pointed object.
IMPALE.e: From Middle French, from Medieval Latin impālāre, from Latin palus, whence also pale.

IMPARK.d: To enclose or confine in, or as if in, a park.

IMPART.d: To give or bestow (e.g. a quality or property).
IMPART.e: From Middle English imparten, borrowed from Middle French impartir, empartir, from Late Latin impartiō, impertiō, from im- (“in”) + Latin partiō (“divide”).

IMPEDE.d: To get in the way of; to hinder.
IMPEDE.e: Borrowed from Latin impediō (“to shackle”), from pēs (“foot”) (compare pedestrian). First attested use as a verb was in William Shakespeare's Macbeth, see quotations.

IMPEND.d: To hang or be suspended over (something); to overhang.
IMPEND.e: Borrowed from Latin impendere (“to hang over, to weigh out”), 1590s.

IMPING.d: The act or process of grafting or mending.

IMPISH.d: Mischievous; of or befitting an imp.

IMPORT.d: Something brought in from an exterior source, especially for sale or trade.
IMPORT.e: From Middle English importen, from Old French emporter, importer, from Latin importō (“bring in from abroad, import”, verb), from in (“in, at, on; into”) + portō (“I carry, bear; convey”).

IMPOSE.d: To physically lay or place (something) on another thing; to deposit, to put, to set.
IMPOSE.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English imposen (“to place, set; to impose (a duty, etc.)”), borrowed from Middle French imposer, and Old French emposer, enposer (“to impose (a duty, tax, etc.)”) (modern French imposer), from im-, em- (variants of en- (prefix meaning ‘in, in...

IMPOST.d: A tax, tariff or duty that is imposed, especially on merchandise.
IMPOST.e: Borrowed from Middle French impost, itself borrowed or adapted from Latin impōsitus, past participle of impōnō (“I impose”).

IMPUGN.e: Borrowed from Middle French impugner, from Latin impugnō, from im- + pugnō (“fight”), from pugnus (“fist”), as in English pugilism (“fighting with fists, boxing”).

IMPURE.e: From Middle French impur, from Latin impūrus.

IMPUTE.d: To attribute or ascribe (responsibility or fault) to a cause or source.
IMPUTE.e: Borrowed from Middle French imputer, from Latin imputō (“to bring into the reckoning, charge, impute”).

INARCH.d: To graft by uniting, as a scion, to a stock, without separating either from its root before the union is complete.

INCALL.d: A visit by a client to a provider of some service, such as a massage therapist or a prostitute.

INCANT.e: First attested in 1546; borrowed from Latin incantō. Doublet of enchant and incantate.

INCEPT.e:
* Originally borrowed from Latin inceptus, past participle of incipio. The term is marked "obsolete" in the first edition of the OED (1905); newer usage is a back-formation from inception.
* (put an idea into someone's mind): Inspired by the film Inception (2010).

INCEST.d: Sexual relations between close relatives, especially immediate family members and sometimes first cousins, usually considered taboo.
INCEST.e: From Latin incestus. Displaced native Old English mǣġhǣmed (literally “relative-sex”). Doublet of inchaste.

INCHED.d: Past tense of INCH: An English unit of length equal to 1/12 of a foot or 2.54 cm, conceived as roughly the width of a thumb.
INCHED.e: From Middle English ynche, enche, from Old English ynċe, borrowed from Latin uncia (“Roman inch, various similar units”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *óynos (“one”). Cognate with Middle Dutch enke (“thumb, thumb's width, inch”). Doublet of ounce, uncia, onça, onza, oka, o...

INCHES.d: Plural of INCH: An English unit of length equal to 1/12 of a foot or 2.54 cm, conceived as roughly the width of a thumb.
INCHES.e: From Middle English ynche, enche, from Old English ynċe, borrowed from Latin uncia (“Roman inch, various similar units”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *óynos (“one”). Cognate with Middle Dutch enke (“thumb, thumb's width, inch”). Doublet of ounce, uncia, onça, onza, oka, o...

INCISE.d: To cut in or into with a sharp instrument; to carve; to engrave.

INCITE.d: To stir up or excite; to rouse or goad into action.
INCITE.e: From Middle French inciter, from Latin incitō (“to set in motion, hasten, urge, incite”), from in (“in, on”) + citō (“to set in motion, urge”), frequentative of cieō (“to rouse, excite, call”).

INCOME.d: Money one earns by working or by capitalising on the work of others.
INCOME.e: From Middle English income, perhaps continuing (in altered form) Old English incyme (“an in-coming, entrance”), equivalent to in- + come. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Íenkúumen (“income”), West Frisian ynkommen (“income”), Dutch inkomen, inkomst (“income, earnings, gainings”), ...

INCUSE.d: Hammered or pressed in (usually on a coin).
INCUSE.e: From Latin incūsus, past participle of incūdō, from in- + cūdō.

INDABA.d: A tribal conference held by Nguni leaders.
INDABA.e: Borrowed from Zulu índaba (“affair, issue, matter; piece of news; story”), from ín- (class 9 noun prefix) + -daɓa (stem meaning ‘affair, matter’).

INDENT.d: A cut or notch in the margin of anything, or a recess like a notch.
INDENT.e: Partly from Middle English indenten (“to dent in”), equivalent to in- + dent (see dent); partly from Middle English indenten, endenten, from Old French endenter (“to provide with teeth”), from en- (“in-, en-”) + dent (“tooth”), from Latin dēns.

INDICT.e:
From Middle English enditen, endyten (“to accuse”), from Old French enditer (“to dictate, indite”), from Late Latin indictāre, frequentative of Latin indicere (“to proclaim”), from in- + dicere (“to say”), or from in- + dictāre (“to say often, to dictate”). Doublet of indite.
The...

INDIGO.e: 16th century (as indico, modern spelling from the 17th century), Spanish índigo, Portuguese endego (modern índigo), or Dutch (via Portuguese) indigo, all from Latin indicum (“indigo”), from Ancient Greek ἰνδικόν (indikón, “Indian dye”), from Ἰνδία (Indía). Doublet of Indic.

INDITE.d: To physically make (letters and words) on a writing surface; to inscribe.
INDITE.e: Originally a variant of indict; from Middle English enditen, endyten, from Old French enditer, from Late Latin indictāre, from in- + dictare (“to declare”). Doublet of indict.

INDIUM.d: A chemical element (symbol In) with an atomic number of 49: a soft silvery-white metal.
INDIUM.e: Coined as a New Latin term from German Indigo (“indigo”), based on the color of its spectral lines.

INDOLE.d: An organic compound, C₈H₇N, found in coal tar, and produced in the gut by the bacterial decomposition of tryptophan; it is an aromatic bicyclic heterocycle having a benzene ring fused with a pyrrole ring; indole and its derivatives occur widely in nature and have many industrial applications.

INDUCE.d: To lead by persuasion or influence; incite or prevail upon.
INDUCE.e: From Middle English enducen, borrowed from Latin indūcere (“lead in, bring in, introduce”), from in + dūcō (“lead, conduct”). Compare also abduce, adduce, conduce, deduce, produce, reduce etc. Doublet of endue.

INDULT.d: A permission or privilege granted by the church authority that excepts an individual from what is otherwise a norm of church law, such as a release from monastic vows.

INDUNA.d: A South African tribal councillor or headman (under the king); someone in authority, a boss.

INFALL.d: The act or process of falling in.

INFAMY.e: From late Middle English infamie, from Old French infamie, from Latin īnfāmia (“infamy”), from īnfāmis (“infamous”), from in- (“not”) + fāma (“fame, renown”). Displaced native Old English unhlīsa (literally “bad fame”).

INFANT.d: A very young human being, from birth to somewhere between six months and two years of age after birth, needing almost constant care and attention.
INFANT.e: Inherited from Middle English infaunt, borrowed from Latin īnfantem, accusative masculine singular of īnfāns, nominal use of the adjective meaning 'not able to speak', from īn- (“not”) + fāns, present participle of for (“to speak”). The verb is from Anglo-Norman enfanter, from th...

INFECT.d: To bring (the body or part of it) into contact with a substance that causes illness (a pathogen), so that the pathogen begins to act on the body; (of a pathogen) to come into contact with (a body or body part) and begin to act on it.
INFECT.e: From Middle French infect, from Latin infectus, perfect passive participle of inficiō (“dye, taint”).

INFEST.d: To inhabit a place in unpleasantly large numbers; to plague, harass.
INFEST.e: From Middle English infesten, from Old French infester (“to infest”), from Latin īnfestō (“assail, molest”, verb), from īnfestus (“hostile”).

INFILL.d: To fill in a space, hole or gap.

INFIRM.d: Weak or ill, not in good health.
INFIRM.e:
* The noun is from Middle English infirme, from Latin infirmus (“weak, feeble”).
* The verb is from Latin īnfirmāre.

INFLOW.d: The act or process of flowing in or into.
INFLOW.e: From Middle English inflowen, equivalent to in- + flow.

INFLUX.d: A flow inward or into something; a coming in.
INFLUX.e: From Latin īnflūxus (“inflow; influence”), from īnfluō (“flow or run into”).

INFORM.d: To instruct, train (usually in matters of knowledge).
INFORM.e: From Middle English informen, enformen, borrowed from Old French enformer, informer (“to train, instruct, inform”), from Latin īnfōrmō (“to shape, form, train, instruct, educate”), from in- (“into”) + fōrma (“form, shape”), equivalent to in- + form.

INFULA.d: A fillet of white wool, worn on the head by ancient Roman priests.

INFUSE.d: To cause to become an element of something; to insert or fill.
INFUSE.e: From Middle English infusen, from Latin infusus, from infundo.

INGEST.d: To take (a substance, e.g., food) into the body of an organism, especially through the mouth and into the gastrointestinal tract.

INHALE.d: To draw air into the lungs, through the nose or mouth by action of the diaphragm.
INHALE.e: From Latin inhalare (“to breathe on (breathe in)”), from in (“in, into, on”) + halare (“to breathe”).

INHERE.d: To be inherent; to be an essential or intrinsic part of; to be fixed or permanently incorporated with something.
INHERE.e: From Latin inhaerēre (“stick in, stick to, inhere to”), from in (“in”) + haereō (“stick”); see hesitate. Compare adhere, cohere.

INHOLD.e: From in- + hold. Compare Old English onhealdan (“to hold, keep, maintain”). More at in, hold.

INJECT.d: To push or pump (something, especially fluids) into a cavity or passage.
INJECT.e: From Latin iniectus, injectus, participle of iniciō, injiciō (“I throw in”), from in- + iaciō (“I throw”).

INJURE.d: To wound or cause physical harm to a living creature.
INJURE.e: A back-formation from injury, from Anglo-Norman injurie, from Latin iniūria (“injustice; wrong; offense”), from in- (“not”) + iūs, iūris (“right, law”).

INKIER.d: Comparative form of INKY: Of the colour of ink, especially black ink; dark.

INKIES.d: Plural of INKY: Of the colour of ink, especially black ink; dark.

INKING.d: Present participle of INK: A pigment (or dye)-based fluid used for writing, printing etc.
INKING.e: From Middle English ynke, from Old French enque, from Latin encaustum (“purple ink used by Roman emperors to sign documents”), from Ancient Greek ἔγκαυστον (énkauston, “burned-in”), from ἐν (en, “in”) + καίω (kaíō, “burn”). In this sense, displaced native Old English blæc (“ink”,...

INKJET.d: A device, particularly one used in the printing of documents, which propels tiny droplets of ink to the paper.

INLAND.d: Within the land; relatively remote from the ocean or from open water; interior.
INLAND.e: From Middle English inland, inlond, from Old English inland, equivalent to in- + land. Compare West Frisian ynlân (“inland”), German Inland (“inland”), Danish indland (“inland”), Swedish inland (“inland”), Norwegian innland (“inland”). Compare also Dutch binnenland.

INLIER.d: An area of older rocks surrounded by younger rocks, typically formed by erosion of part of the younger rock.

INMATE.d: A person confined to an institution such as a prison (as a convict) or hospital (as a patient).

INNATE.d: Inborn; existing or having existed since birth.
INNATE.e: The adjective is first attested in the 1420's, the verb in 1602; from Middle English innat(e) (“innate, inborn”), borrowed from Latin innātus (“inborn, innate”) (see -ate (adjective-forming suffix)), perfect active participle of innāscor (“to be born in, grow up in”), from in- (“...

INNERS.d: Plural of INNER: Located inside; private.

INPUTS.d: Plural of INPUT: What is put in; data entered.

INROAD.d: An advance into enemy territory, an attempted invasion; an encroachment, an incursion.
INROAD.e:
The noun is derived from in + road (“(obsolete) act of riding on horseback; hostile ride against a particular area, raid”).
The verb is derived from the noun.

INSERT.d: To put in between or into.
INSERT.e: From Latin insertus, past participle of inserō, from in- + serō (“join, bind together, connect, entwine, interweave”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ser- (“to bind, put together, to line up”). Compare exsert.

INSIDE.e:
From Middle English ynneside; equivalent to in- + side.
Compare German Innenseite (“inside”), Danish inderside (“inside”), Swedish insida (“inside”), Dutch binnenzijde (“inside”), German Low German Binnensied, Binnersied (“inside”), Saterland Frisian Binnersiede (“inside”).

INSIST.d: To hold up a claim emphatically.
INSIST.e: Partly from Middle French insister, from Latin īnsistere; and partly from a back-formation from insistence.

INSOLE.d: The inside sole of a shoe or other footwear.

INSOUL.d: To set a soul in; reflexively, to fix one's strongest affections on.

INSTAR.d: Any one of the several stages of postembryonic development which an arthropod undergoes, between molts, before it reaches sexual maturity.
INSTAR.e: From Latin instar (“form, likeness”), which is of obscure origin.

INSTEP.d: The arched part of the top of the foot between the toes and the ankle.

INSTIL.d: Australia, Ireland, and UK standard spelling of instill.

INSULA.d: A block of buildings in a Roman town.
INSULA.e: From Latin insula (“island”). Doublet of isle.

INSULT.d: To be insensitive, insolent, or rude to (somebody); to affront or demean (someone).
INSULT.e: The verb is derived from Middle French insulter (modern French insulter (“to insult”)) or its etymon Latin īnsultō (“to spring, leap or jump at or upon; to abuse, insult, revile, taunt”), the frequentative form of īnsiliō (“to bound; to leap in or upon”), from in- (prefix meaning...

INSURE.d: To provide for compensation if some specified risk occurs. Often agreed by policy (contract) to offer financial compensation in case of an accident, theft or other undesirable event.
INSURE.e: First attested in c. 1440, as a variant of Middle English ensuren (from Anglo-Norman enseurer, itself from en- + seür (“sure”), probably influenced by Old French asseürer (“to assure”)); took on its particular sense of "make safe against loss by payment of premiums" in 1635, repl...

INTACT.d: Left complete or whole; not touched, defiled, sullied, or otherwise damaged.
INTACT.e: From Middle French intact, from Latin intact(us).

INTAKE.d: The place where water, air or other fluid is taken into a pipe or conduit; opposed to outlet.
INTAKE.e: From English dialectal (Northern England/Scotland), deverbal of take in, equivalent to in- + take. More at in-, take.

INTEND.d: To fix the mind upon (something, or something to be accomplished); be intent upon
INTEND.e:
From Middle English intenden, entenden (“direct (one’s) attention towards”), borrowed from Old French entendre, from Latin intendō, intendere. See also intensive. Doublet of entendre.
Largely displaced native Old English myntan (“to mean, intend; to think, suppose”), whence diale...

INTENT.e: Existing since Middle English entente, from Old French entent or entente, ultimately from Latin intentus. Modified later in spelling to align more closely with the Latin word. Compare intention.

INTERN.d: A person who is interned, forcibly or voluntarily.
INTERN.e: From French interner, from interne (“inner, internal”), from Latin internus (“within, internal”), compare Etymology 2.

INTONE.d: To give tone or variety of tone to; to vocalize.
INTONE.e: From Middle English entune, entone, from Old French entoner, from Medieval Latin intonō, from in- (inchoative prefix) + tonus (“pitch, tone”) + -ō (verb-forming suffix); doublet of intonate. Cognate with French entonner, Italian intonare.

INTRON.d: A portion of a split gene that is included in pre-RNA transcripts but is removed during RNA processing and rapidly degraded.

INTUIT.d: To know intuitively or by immediate perception.
INTUIT.e: A back-formation from intuition and intuitive; compare Latin intuitus (“observed; considered”), perfect participle of intueor (“to look at, upon or towards; to observe, regard; to consider, contemplate”), from in- (“in, inside”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁én (“in”)) ...

INULIN.d: A polysaccharide found in the roots and tubers of certain plants, especially the Compositae; it is mostly a polymer of fructose.

INVENT.d: To design a new process or mechanism.
INVENT.e:
From Middle English inventen, borrowed from Old French inventer, from Latin inventus, perfect passive participle of inveniō (“come upon, meet with, find, discover”), from in (“in, on”) + veniō (“come”); see venture. Compare advent, covent, event, prevent, etc.
Displaced native Ol...

INVERT.d: To turn (something) upside down or inside out; to place in a contrary order or direction.

INVEST.d: To spend money, time, or energy on something, especially for some benefit or purpose; used with in.
INVEST.e: Borrowed from Middle French investir or Medieval Latin investire, from Latin investio (“to clothe, cover”), from in- (“in, on”) + vestio (“to clothe, dress”), from vestis (“clothing”); see vest. The sense “to spend money etc.” probably via Italian investire, of the same root.

INVITE.d: To ask for the presence or participation of someone or something.
INVITE.e: From Middle French inviter, from Latin invītō. Displaced native Old English laþian.

INVOKE.d: To call upon (a person, a god) for help, assistance or guidance.
INVOKE.e: From Middle English *invoken, envoken, borrowed from Old French envoquer, from Latin invocāre (“to call upon”), itself from in- + vocare (“to call”). Doublet of invocate.

INWARD.d: Situated on the inside; that is within, inner; belonging to the inside.
INWARD.e: From Middle English inward, from Old English inweard, corresponding to in + -ward.

IODATE.d: The anion IO₃⁻; any salt of iodic acid.

IODIDE.d: A binary compound of iodine and another element or radical.

IODINE.d: A chemical element (symbol: I) with an atomic number of 53; one of the halogens.
IODINE.e: From French iode + -ine, from Ancient Greek ἰοειδής (ioeidḗs, “violet”). Coined by British chemist Humphry Davy in 1814.

IODISE.d: Non-Oxford British English standard spelling of iodize.

IONISE.d: Non-Oxford British English standard spelling of ionize.

IPECAC.d: The dried rhizome and roots of either of two tropical American plants (Cephaelis acuminata and Cephaelis ipecacuanha) of the madder family used especially as a source of emetine.
IPECAC.e: Contraction of ipecacuanha, from Portuguese ipecacuanha, from Old Tupi ypekakûãîa, from ypeka (“duck”) + akûãîa (“penis”).

IRENIC.d: Promoting or fitted to promote peace or peacemaking, especially over disputes; conciliatory, non-confrontational, peaceful.
IRENIC.e: From Ancient Greek εἰρηνικός (eirēnikós, “characterized by peace, peaceful”) + English -ic (suffix forming adjectives with the sense ‘of or pertaining to’). Εἰρηνικός (Eirēnikós) is derived from εἰρήνη (eirḗnē, “peace”) (possibly from εἴρω (eírō, “to fasten together”) (ultimately...

IRISED.d: Past tense of IRIS: A plant of the genus Iris, common in the northern hemisphere, and generally having attractive blooms (See Iris (plant) on Wikipedia.Wikipedia).
IRISED.e: From Middle English iris, from Latin īris, from Ancient Greek ἶρις (îris, “rainbow”). Presuming an earlier form *ϝῖρις (*wîris), possibly from a derivative of Proto-Indo-European *w(e)ih₁-ro- (“a twist, thread, cord, wire”), from *weh₁y- (“to turn, twist, weave, plait”). If so, i...

IRISES.d: Plural of IRIS: A plant of the genus Iris, common in the northern hemisphere, and generally having attractive blooms (See Iris (plant) on Wikipedia.Wikipedia).
IRISES.e: From Middle English iris, from Latin īris, from Ancient Greek ἶρις (îris, “rainbow”). Presuming an earlier form *ϝῖρις (*wîris), possibly from a derivative of Proto-Indo-European *w(e)ih₁-ro- (“a twist, thread, cord, wire”), from *weh₁y- (“to turn, twist, weave, plait”). If so, i...

IRKING.d: Present participle of IRK: to irritate; annoy; bother
IRKING.e: Inherited from Middle English irken (“to tire, grow weary”), from Old Norse yrkja (“to work”), from Proto-Germanic *wurkijaną (“to work”), from Proto-Indo-European *werǵ- (“to work”). Cognate with Icelandic yrkja (“to compose”), Swedish yrka (“to urge, argue”), Old English wyrċan...

IRRUPT.e: From Latin irruptus, past participle of irrumpō.

ISATIN.d: The indole derivative 1H-indole-2,3-dione, used in the synthesis of dyes.

ISLAND.d: A contiguous area of land, smaller than a continent, totally surrounded by water.
ISLAND.e: From earlier iland, from Middle English iland, yland, ylond, from Old English īeġland, from Proto-West Germanic *auwjuland, from Proto-Germanic *awjōlandą (from Proto-Germanic *awjō (“island, waterland, meadow”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ekʷeh₂) + *landą (“land”), equivalent t...

ISLING.d: Present participle of ISLE: An island, usually very small. Compare with islet.
ISLING.e: From Middle English ile, yle (with s added, similar to English island), borrowed from Old French ille, idle, isle, from Latin insula. Not related to island. Doublet of insula.

ISOBAR.d: A line drawn on a map or chart connecting places of equal or constant pressure.
ISOBAR.e: From Ancient Greek ἴσος (ísos, “equal”) + βάρος (báros, “weight”), equivalent to iso- + bar-.

ISOHEL.d: A line on a map connecting places that receive equal solar radiation, or equal daily hours of sunshine.

ISOMER.d: Any of two or more compounds with the same molecular formula but with different structure.

ISOPOD.d: Any of very many crustaceans, of the order Isopoda, that have a flattened body and no carapace.
ISOPOD.e: From the taxonomic name Isopoda; by surface analysis, iso- + -pod.

ISSUED.d: Past tense of ISSUE: A topic; a problem; to distribute.
ISSUED.e: From Old French issue, from Latin exīre (to go out).

ISSUES.d: Plural of ISSUE: A topic; a problem; to distribute.
ISSUES.e: From Old French issue, from Latin exīre (to go out).

ITALIC.d: Designed to resemble a handwriting style developed in Italy in the 16th century.
ITALIC.e: Named after the nation of Italy, as it was first used by an Italian printer, Aldo Manuzio, around 1500. Literally Italy + -ic.

ITCHED.d: Past tense of ITCH: A sensation felt on an area of the skin that causes a person or animal to want to scratch said area.
ITCHED.e: From Middle English icche, ȝicche, from Old English ġiċċe (“an itch”), from Proto-Germanic *jukjǭ (“an itch”), of unknown origin. Cognate with Scots yeuk (“an itch, itchiness”), Dutch jeuk (“an itch”), German jucken.

ITCHES.d: Plural of ITCH: A sensation felt on an area of the skin that causes a person or animal to want to scratch said area.
ITCHES.e: From Middle English icche, ȝicche, from Old English ġiċċe (“an itch”), from Proto-Germanic *jukjǭ (“an itch”), of unknown origin. Cognate with Scots yeuk (“an itch, itchiness”), Dutch jeuk (“an itch”), German jucken.

ITEMED.d: Past tense of ITEM: A distinct physical object.
ITEMED.e: From Middle English item, from Latin item (“also; in the same manner”). The present English meaning derives from a usage in lists, where the first entry would begin in primis (“firstly”) or imprimis, and the other entries with item (“also, moreover”). Later, the members of lists ...

JABBED.d: Past tense of JAB: A quick stab or blow; a poking or thrusting motion.
JABBED.e: Originally a Scottish (unclear if Scots or Scottish English) form of English job (“peck, poke, thrust”), from Middle English jobben.

JABBER.d: To talk rapidly, indistinctly, or unintelligibly; to utter gibberish or nonsense.
JABBER.e: From Middle English jaberen, javeren, chaveren (“to chatter, babble”), dissimilated forms of jablen, chavelen (“to jabber”), from Middle English chavel ("jaw"; > modern English jowl). Equivalent to jowl + -er (iterative suffix).

JABIRU.d: A species of bird Jabiru mycteria in the monotypic genus Jabiru, of the stork family Ciconiidae, endemic to the Americas.
JABIRU.e: From a Tupian term such as Old Tupi îabyru, said to mean either "swollen neck" or "one that spits".

JACANA.d: Any of a group of wading birds in the family Jacanidae, usually having long toes and claws, and found throughout the world.
JACANA.e: Borrowed from Brazilian Portuguese jaçanã, from a term jasaná in an undetermined Tupian language, perhaps Guaraní jasana.

JACKAL.d: Any of certain wild canids of the genera Lupulella and Canis, native to the tropical Old World and smaller than a wolf.
JACKAL.e: From French chacal, chacale, checale, schakal, ciacale, from Turkish çakal, from Persian شغال (šaġâl), borrowed from Sanskrit शृगाल (śṛgāla, “jackal”).

JACKED.d: Past tense of JACK: A coarse medieval coat of defence, especially one made of leather.
JACKED.e: Inherited from Middle English jakke, from Anglo-Norman jacke, Middle French jaque, jacque, from jacques (“peasant”), from the proper name Jacques. Compare jacquerie.

JACKET.d: A piece of clothing worn on the upper body outside a shirt or blouse, often waist length to thigh length.
JACKET.e: From Middle French jacquet, diminutive of Old French jaque.

JADING.d: Present participle of JADE: A semiprecious stone, either nephrite or jadeite, generally green or white in color, often used for carving figurines.
JADING.e: Borrowed from French le jade, rebracketing of earlier l'éjade (“jade”), from Spanish piedra de ijada (“flank stone”), via Vulgar Latin *iliata from Latin ilia (“flank”). (Jade was thought to cure pains in the side.)

JAGGED.d: Unevenly cut; having the texture of something so cut.

JAGGER.d: Comparative form of JAG: A sharp projection.
JAGGER.e:
The noun is from late Middle English jagge, from Old English giagga, giacga. The ultimate origin could be sound-symbolic of sudden movement, compare with jam and rag.
The verb is from jaggen, from Old English giacgian.

JAGUAR.d: A carnivorous spotted large cat native to South and Central America, Panthera onca.
JAGUAR.e: From Portuguese jaguar, from Old Tupi îagûara.

JAILED.d: Past tense of JAIL: A place or institution for the confinement of persons held against their will in lawful custody or detention, especially (in US usage) a place where people are held for minor offenses or with reference to some future judicial proceeding.
JAILED.e: From Middle English gayole, gaylle, gaille, gayle, gaile, from Old French gaiole, gayolle, gaole, from Medieval Latin gabiola, from Late Latin caveola (“small cage, cell”), a diminutive of Latin cavea (“cavity, coop, cage”). Doublet of caveola and related to cage. More at cajole....

JALOPY.d: An old, dilapidated or unpretentious automobile.
JALOPY.e: Unknown. Perhaps from Jalapa, Mexico (now Xalapa), to whose scrapyards used cars were often sent from New Orleans starting in the 1920s. First recorded written use in 1924.

JAMMED.d: Past tense of JAM: A sweet mixture of fruit boiled with sugar and allowed to congeal. Often spread on bread or toast or used in jam tarts
JAMMED.e: First attested in the early 18th c. as a verb meaning “to press, be pressed, be wedged in”. Compare dialectal jammock (“to press, squeeze, crush into a soft mass, chew food"; also "a soft, pulpy substance”). Perhaps from Middle English chammen, champen ("to bite upon something, g...

JAMMER.d: A player of the massively multiplayer online game Animal Jam (now either the app so named, formerly Animal Jam – Play Wild!, or the desktop game renamed Animal Jam Classic).

JANGLE.d: To cause (something) to make a rattling metallic sound.
JANGLE.e: From Middle English janglen (“to talk excessively, chatter; to talk idly, gossip; to nag; to complain, grumble; to argue, debate; to discuss, talk; to talk indistinctly, jabber; to make a noise or outcry; of a bird: to chatter, twitter”) [and other forms], from Old French jangler...

JANSKY.d: A non-SI unit (symbol Jy) measuring electromagnetic flux density equal to 10⁻²⁶ watts per square meter per hertz.
JANSKY.e: Named after radio astronomer Karl Guthe Jansky.

JAPING.d: Present participle of JAPE: A joke or quip.
JAPING.e:
From Middle English japen (“to deceive, play tricks on; act foolishly, joke; have sex with”), of uncertain origin, but perhaps combining Old French japer (“to bark, howl, scream; chatter, gossip”) with gaber (“to mock, deride”).
See also gab, Old Occitan japar, jaupar (“to bark, ...

JARFUL.d: As much as a jar will hold

JARGON.d: A technical terminology unique to a particular subject.
JARGON.e: From Middle English jargoun, jargon, from Old French jargon, a variant of gargon, gargun (“chatter; talk; language”).

JARRAH.d: A eucalypt tree of species Eucalyptus marginata, occurring in the southwest of Western Australia.

JARRED.d: Past tense of JAR: An earthenware container, either with two or no handles, for holding oil, water, wine, etc., or used for burial.
JARRED.e: Inherited from Middle English jarre (“jar”), from Medieval Latin jarra, or from Middle French jarre (“liquid measure”) (from Old French jare; modern French jarre (“earthenware jar”)), or from Spanish jarra, jarro (“jug, pitcher; mug, stein”), all from Arabic جَرَّة (jarra, “earth...

JASPER.d: Any bright-coloured kind of chalcedony apart from cornelian.
JASPER.e: From Middle English jasper, jaspre, from Old French jaspre, a variant of jaspe (modern French jaspe), from Latin iaspis, from Ancient Greek ἴασπις (íaspis).

JAUNTY.e: Formerly spelt janty, from French gentil. See gentle, and compare genty. Doublet of genteel, gentile, and gentle.

JAWING.d: Present participle of JAW: One of the bones, usually bearing teeth, which form the framework of the mouth.
JAWING.e:
From Middle English jawe/jowe (“jaw; sides of the lower face”, 14th century), the further origin of which is disputed. Either:
* From Anglo-Norman jowe, from Old French joe (“cheek; jaw”), from Vulgar Latin *ga(v)ota (“cheek”), of uncertain further origin.
** It has been objected...

JAZZED.d: Past tense of JAZZ: A musical art form rooted in West African cultural and musical expression and in the African American blues tradition, with diverse influences over time, commonly characterized by blue notes, syncopation, swing, call and response, polyrhythms and improvisation.
JAZZED.e: Unknown. First attested around 1912 in a discussion of baseball; attested in reference to music around 1915. Numerous references suggest that the term may be connected to jasm and jism.

JAZZES.d: Plural of JAZZ: A musical art form rooted in West African cultural and musical expression and in the African American blues tradition, with diverse influences over time, commonly characterized by blue notes, syncopation, swing, call and response, polyrhythms and improvisation.
JAZZES.e: Unknown. First attested around 1912 in a discussion of baseball; attested in reference to music around 1915. Numerous references suggest that the term may be connected to jasm and jism.

JEERED.d: Past tense of JEER: A mocking remark or reflection.
JEERED.e: From earlier gyr, probably from Dutch gieren (“to roar with laughter, laugh loudly”) (related to German gieren (“to gape, snap”)); or from Dutch gekscheren (“to jeer”, literally “to shear the fool”), from gek (“a fool”) (see geck) + scheren (“to shear”) (see shear (verb)). The OE...

JELLED.d: Past tense of JELL: a jelly or gel
JELLED.e: A back-formation from jelly; reinforced by gel. Compare obsolete geal.

JENNET.d: A female ass or donkey; a jenny.
JENNET.e: From Late Middle English genet, from Old French genet, from Old Catalan genet or Old Spanish ginete (“small fast horse; light horseman”), from Andalusian Arabic زَنَاتِي (zanātī), the Zenati or Zenata Berbers, known as excellent horse breeders. Doublet of Zenati.

JERBOA.d: Any of a number of species comprising the family Dipodidae, native to the deserts of Asia and northern Africa, being a small, jumping rodent with a long tufted tail, very small forefeet and very long hind legs.
JERBOA.e: From Arabic جَرْبُوع (jarbūʕ) or يَرْبُوع (yarbūʕ). Doublet of gerbil.

JERKED.d: Past tense of JERK: A sudden, often uncontrolled movement, especially of the human body.
JERKED.e: Probably from Middle English yerk (“sudden motion”) and Middle English yerkid (“tightly pulled”), from Old English ġearc (“ready, active, quick”) and Old English ġearcian (“to prepare, make ready, procure, furnish, supply”). Cognate with Scots yerk (“to jerk”). Related also to En...

JERKIN.d: A type of men's garment popular in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries: a close-fitting collarless jacket, with or without sleeves.
JERKIN.e: First recorded in early 1500s. Possibly related to Dutch jurk (“dress”), itself of unknown origin and not attested before the 17th century. Derivation from Old French jo(u)rne (“day”) has been suggested.

JERSEY.d: A garment knitted from wool, worn over the upper body.
JERSEY.e: From a typical fisherman's sweater used on the island of Jersey.

JESSES.d: Plural of JESS: A diminutive of the male given name Jesse.
JESSES.e: Clipping of Jesse, Jessica, or Jessamy.

JESTED.d: Past tense of JEST: An act performed for amusement; a joke.
JESTED.e: From Middle English geste (“idle tale”), from Old French geste (“acts, exploits”), from Latin gesta (“acts, deeds”). Doublet of gest.

JETSAM.d: Items thrown overboard from a ship or boat in distress in order to lighten its load.
JETSAM.e: From Middle English jetteson, from Anglo-Norman getteson. Doublet of jettison.

JETTED.d: Past tense of JET: A collimated stream, spurt or flow of liquid or gas from a pressurized container, an engine, etc.
JETTED.e: Borrowed from French jet (“spurt”, literally “a throw”), from Old French get, giet, from Vulgar Latin *iectus, jectus, from Latin iactus (“a throwing, a throw”), from iacere (“to throw”). See abject, ejaculate, gist, jess, jut. Cognate with Spanish echar.

JETTER.d: Comparative form of JET: A collimated stream, spurt or flow of liquid or gas from a pressurized container, an engine, etc.
JETTER.e: Borrowed from French jet (“spurt”, literally “a throw”), from Old French get, giet, from Vulgar Latin *iectus, jectus, from Latin iactus (“a throwing, a throw”), from iacere (“to throw”). See abject, ejaculate, gist, jess, jut. Cognate with Spanish echar.

JIBBED.d: Past tense of JIB: A triangular staysail set forward of the foremast. In a sloop (see image) the basic jib reaches back roughly to the level of the mast.
JIBBED.e: Attested since the 1660s, of uncertain origin. Perhaps related to jib (“shift or swing around”) (see below).

JIBBER.d: Comparative form of JIB: A triangular staysail set forward of the foremast. In a sloop (see image) the basic jib reaches back roughly to the level of the mast.
JIBBER.e: Attested since the 1660s, of uncertain origin. Perhaps related to jib (“shift or swing around”) (see below).

JIBING.d: Present participle of JIBE: A facetious or insulting remark; a jeer, a taunt.
JIBING.e:
Uncertain; possibly from Old French giber (“to engage in horseplay; to play roughly in sport”). Compare English jib (“usually of a horse: to stop and refuse to go forward”), Old Norse geipa (“to talk nonsense”).
The noun is derived from the verb.

JIGGED.d: Past tense of JIG: A light, brisk musical movement; a gigue.
JIGGED.e: Unknown. Derivation from Middle English gyge (“fiddle”), from Old French gigue (“a fiddle”) has been proposed, but the connection and sense development are obscure. The sense “a type of dance” of modern French gigue is borrowed from English.

JIGGER.d: A double-ended vessel, generally of stainless steel or other metal, one end of which typically measures 1½ fluid ounces (approx. 44 ml), the other typically 1 fluid ounce (approx. 30 ml).
JIGGER.e: From jig + -er (agent suffix). Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary suggests a possible link to Old High German gīga (“fiddle”).

JIGSAW.d: A power saw with fine teeth and a narrow blade which can cut curves in wood or metal.

JILTED.d: Past tense of JILT: A woman who readily casts aside her lover.
JILTED.e: Contraction of jillet (“a giddy girl, a jill-flirt”).

JINGLE.d: The sound of metal or glass clattering against itself.
JINGLE.e: The verb, which is older than the noun, is from Middle English gyngle. Onomatopoeic; compare jangle.

JINGLY.d: that jingles, having a jingling sound.

JINKED.d: Past tense of JINK: A quick evasive turn.
JINKED.e: Origin uncertain. The Oxford English Dictionary suggests onomatopoeia for motion. Attested since the 18th century. Compare unnasalised dialectal jick (“to avoid with a sudden jerk of the body, elude”).

JINXED.d: Past tense of JINX: A hex; an evil spell.
JINXED.e: From jynx in the transferred sense “a charm or spell”.

JINXES.d: Plural of JINX: A hex; an evil spell.
JINXES.e: From jynx in the transferred sense “a charm or spell”.

JITTER.e: Possibly alteration of chitter (“to tremble, shiver”), from Middle English chittern (“to twitter, chatter”). Ultimately onomatopoeic; compare didder and teeter as well as German zittern.

JIVING.d: Present participle of JIVE: To deceive; to be deceptive.
JIVING.e: Unknown. Slang attested in African-American and rural American culture. Frequently used to imply lying, verbal deception or trickery. Has a possible historical antecedent in gyve (“shackle”). Alternatively, of African origin, compare Wolof jev, jeu (“to talk about someone absent,...

JOBBED.d: Past tense of JOB: A task.
JOBBED.e: From the phrase jobbe of work (“piece of work”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from a variant of Middle English gobbe (“mass, lump”); or perhaps related to Middle English jobben (“to jab, thrust, peck”), or Middle English choppe (“piece, bargain”). More at gob, jab, chop.

JOBBER.d: Comparative form of JOB: A task.
JOBBER.e: From the phrase jobbe of work (“piece of work”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from a variant of Middle English gobbe (“mass, lump”); or perhaps related to Middle English jobben (“to jab, thrust, peck”), or Middle English choppe (“piece, bargain”). More at gob, jab, chop.

JOCKEY.e: The word is by origin a diminutive of jock, the Northern English or Scots colloquial equivalent of the first name John, which is also used generically for "boy" or "fellow" (compare Jack, Dick), at least since 1529. A familiar instance of the use of the word as a name is in "Jock...

JOCOSE.e: From Latin iocōsus (“humorous”), from iocus (“jest, joke”).

JOCUND.d: Jovial; exuberant; lighthearted; merry and in high spirits; exhibiting happiness.
JOCUND.e: From Old French jocond, from Latin iūcundus (“pleasant, agreeable”). Doublet of jucund.

JOGGED.d: Past tense of JOG: An energetic trot, slower than a run, often used as a form of exercise.
JOGGED.e:
Of uncertain origin. Originally with the meaning of "to shake up and down." Possibly from Middle English joggen, a variant of jaggen (“to pierce, prod, stir up, arouse”); see jag (“sharp projection”).
Or, perhaps an early alteration of English shog (“to jolt, shake; depart, go”),...

JOGGER.d: Comparative form of JOG: An energetic trot, slower than a run, often used as a form of exercise.
JOGGER.e:
Of uncertain origin. Originally with the meaning of "to shake up and down." Possibly from Middle English joggen, a variant of jaggen (“to pierce, prod, stir up, arouse”); see jag (“sharp projection”).
Or, perhaps an early alteration of English shog (“to jolt, shake; depart, go”),...

JOGGLE.d: To shake slightly; to push suddenly but slightly, so as to cause to shake or totter; to jostle; to jog.

JOHNNY.d: A diminutive of the male given name John.
JOHNNY.e: From John + -y. In the sense of an Englishman, compare John Bull.

JOINED.d: Past tense of JOIN: To connect or combine into one; to put together.
JOINED.e: From Middle English joinen, joynen, joignen, from Old French joindre, juindre, jungre, from Latin iungō (“join, yoke”, verb), from Proto-Indo-European *yewg- (“to join, unite”). Cognate with Old English iucian, iugian, ġeocian, ġyċċan (“to join; yoke”). More at yoke.

JOJOBA.d: Any of species Simmondsia chinensis of shrubs native to the southwestern United States and to Mexico, the only plant known to store liquid wax in its seed.
JOJOBA.e: Borrowed from Spanish jojoba, from O'odham hohowai.

JOKIER.d: Comparative form of JOKY: in the nature of a joke; jocular

JOKING.d: Present participle of JOKE: An amusing story.
JOKING.e: From Latin iocus (“joke, jest, pastime”), from Proto-Italic *jokos (“word, (playful?) saying”), from Proto-Indo-European *yokos (“word, utterance”), from ultimate root Proto-Indo-European *yek- (“to speak, utter”) (of which distant cognates include Proto-Celtic *yextis (“language...

JOLTED.d: Past tense of JOLT: To push or shake abruptly and roughly.
JOLTED.e: Perhaps from joll (“to knock, strike”) + -t (frequentative suffix).

JOSHED.d: Past tense of JOSH: A diminutive of the male given name Joshua.

JOSHES.d: Plural of JOSH: A diminutive of the male given name Joshua.

JOSSES.d: Plural of JOSS: A Chinese household divinity; a Chinese idol.
JOSSES.e: From Chinese Pidgin English joss, from Macau Pidgin Portuguese, from Portuguese deus (“god”), from Latin deus (“god”), from Proto-Indo-European *deywós (“god/that which belongs to heaven”).

JOSTLE.d: To bump into or brush against while in motion; to push aside.
JOSTLE.e: Originally justle (“to have sex with”), formed from Middle English jousten, from the Old French joster (“to joust”), from Latin iuxtā (“next to”), from iungō (“join, connect”), equivalent to joust + -le.

JOTTED.d: Past tense of JOT: The smallest letter or stroke of any writing; an iota.
JOTTED.e: The noun is borrowed from Latin iōta (“the letter iota of the Ancient Greek alphabet”), from Ancient Greek ἰῶτα (iôta, “ninth letter of the Ancient Greek alphabet; (figurative) very small part of writing, jot”), from Phoenician 𐤉 (y‬, “tenth letter of the Phoenician abjad, yodh”)...

JOTTER.d: Comparative form of JOT: The smallest letter or stroke of any writing; an iota.
JOTTER.e: The noun is borrowed from Latin iōta (“the letter iota of the Ancient Greek alphabet”), from Ancient Greek ἰῶτα (iôta, “ninth letter of the Ancient Greek alphabet; (figurative) very small part of writing, jot”), from Phoenician 𐤉 (y‬, “tenth letter of the Phoenician abjad, yodh”)...

JOUNCE.d: To jolt; to shake, especially by rough riding or by driving over obstructions.
JOUNCE.e: Unknown, possibly a portmanteau / blend of jolt + bounce.

JOVIAL.e: First attested in 1590; borrowed from Middle French jovial (“under the influence of Jupiter; of Jove; jovial, jolly”), from Italian gioviale (“(now obsolete) born under the influence of the planet Jupiter”) (attested in Dante, Paradiso, canto XVIII, early 14th century), from Late...

JOWLED.d: Past tense of JOWL: The jaw, jawbone; especially one of the lateral parts of the mandible.
JOWLED.e: From Middle English jawle, chawl, chavel (“jaw, jawbone”), from Old English ċeafl (“jaw, cheek”), from Proto-West Germanic *kafl (“jaw, cheek”). The modern form (for expected chavel, chawl; still found dialectally) is influenced by jaw, which it is a partial doublet of.

JOYING.d: Present participle of JOY: A feeling of extreme happiness or cheerfulness, especially related to the acquisition or expectation of something good.
JOYING.e: The noun is from Middle English joye, borrowed from Old French joie, from Late Latin gaudia, neuter plural (mistaken as feminine singular) of Latin gaudium (“joy”), from gaudēre (“to be glad, rejoice”). Doublet of jo and gaudy (“Oxford college reunion”). Displaced native Old Engl...

JOYOUS.e: From Middle English joyous, joious, from Old French joieus, from joie + -eus.

JOYPAD.d: A type of game controller held in the hands, where the digits (especially thumbs) are used to provide input.
JOYPAD.e: From joy + pad, modelled on earlier joystick.

JUBBLY.e: Unknown. Originally Australian. Attested since the 1990s. Compare jugs.

JUDGED.d: Past tense of JUDGE: A person who presides over a court; to form an opinion.
JUDGED.e: From Old French juge, from Latin iūdex.

JUDGES.d: Plural of JUDGE: A person who presides over a court; to form an opinion.
JUDGES.e: From Old French juge, from Latin iūdex.

JUDOKA.d: A practitioner of the Japanese martial art of judo.
JUDOKA.e: From Japanese 柔(じゅう)道(どう)家(か) (jūdōka).

JUGATE.e: Borrowed from Latin iugātus (“yoked together in pairs”), perfect passive participle of iugō (“to yoke”), see -ate (adjective-forming suffix) and -ate (noun-forming suffix).

JUGFUL.d: As much as a jug will hold.

JUGGED.d: Past tense of JUG: A serving vessel or container, typically circular in cross-section and typically higher than it is wide, with a relatively small mouth or spout, an ear handle and often a stopper or top.
JUGGED.e: From Middle English jugge, of uncertain origin. Possibly a variant of Middle English jubbe, jobbe, iubbe, geobbe, itself of unknown origin; or perhaps continuing (in altered form) Old English ċēac (“pitcher; jug”). Compare also jug (“a low woman, maidservant”), from Jug, familiar...

JUGGER.d: Comparative form of JUG: A serving vessel or container, typically circular in cross-section and typically higher than it is wide, with a relatively small mouth or spout, an ear handle and often a stopper or top.
JUGGER.e: From Middle English jugge, of uncertain origin. Possibly a variant of Middle English jubbe, jobbe, iubbe, geobbe, itself of unknown origin; or perhaps continuing (in altered form) Old English ċēac (“pitcher; jug”). Compare also jug (“a low woman, maidservant”), from Jug, familiar...

JUGGLE.d: To manipulate objects, such as balls, clubs, beanbags, rings, etc. in an artful or artistic manner. Juggling may also include assorted other circus skills such as the diabolo, devil sticks, hat, and cigar box manipulation as well.
JUGGLE.e: From Middle English jogelen, partly a back-formation of Middle English jogeler (“juggler”), and partly a borrowing from Old French jogler, jongler (“to have fun with someone”), a conflation of Latin joculāri (“to jest; joke”) and Old French jangler (“to regale; entertain; have fu...

JUICED.d: Past tense of JUICE: Liquid from fruit or vegetables.
JUICED.e: From Old French jus, from Latin iūs (broth).

JUICES.d: Plural of JUICE: Liquid from fruit or vegetables.
JUICES.e: From Old French jus, from Latin iūs (broth).

JUJUBE.d: The sweet and edible drupes (fruits) of several Mediterranean and African species of small trees.
JUJUBE.e: From Middle English jujube, from Medieval Latin jujuba or Old French jujube, perhaps via Old Occitan from Classical Latin zīzyphum, zīzyphus, from Ancient Greek ζίζυφον (zízuphon)․ First attested in the 14th century.

JUMBLE.e: From Middle English jumbelen, alteration of jumbren, jombren, a variant of jumpren, frequentative of jumpen (“to jump”), equal to jump + -le. More at jumber, jump, jumper.

JUMPED.d: Past tense of JUMP: To propel oneself rapidly upward, downward and/or in any horizontal direction such that momentum causes the body to become airborne.
JUMPED.e: From Middle English jumpen (“to walk quickly, run, jump”), probably of Middle Low German or North Germanic origin, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *gumpōną ~ *gumbōną (“to hop, skip, bounce”), an iterative verb. The OED suggests an imitative origin. Related to jumble. In the sense...

JUNGLE.d: A large, undeveloped, humid forest, especially in a tropical region, that is home to many wild plants and animals; a tropical rainforest.
JUNGLE.e: Borrowed from Hindustani جَن٘گَل (jaṅgal) / जंगल (jaṅgal), from Sanskrit जङ्गल (jaṅgala, “arid, sterile, desert”). First appears c. 1776 in a translation by Nathaniel Halhed.

JUNIOR.d: Low in rank; having a subordinate role, job, or situation.
JUNIOR.e: Borrowed from Latin junior, a contraction of iuvenior (“younger”) which is the comparative of iuvenis (“young”); see juvenile.

JUNKED.d: Past tense of JUNK: Miscellaneous items of little value, especially discarded or unwanted items.
JUNKED.e: From earlier meaning "old refuse from boats and ships", from Middle English junk, jounke, jonk, joynk (“an old cable or rope”, nautical term), sometimes cut into bits and used as caulking; of uncertain origin; perhaps related to join, joint, juncture. Often compared to Middle Eng...

JUNKET.e:
From Middle English jonket (“basket made of rushes”), from Medieval Latin iuncta, possibly from Latin iuncus (“rush, reed”) and therefore a possible doublet of jonquil.
Meaning shifted to “feast or banquet” by 1520s, probably via the notion of a picnic basket. This in turn led to...

JUNKIE.d: A narcotics addict, especially a heroin user.

JUSTED.d: Past tense of JUST: Factually right, correct; factual.
JUSTED.e: From Middle English juste, from Old French juste, from Latin iūstus (“just, lawful, rightful, true, due, proper, moderate”), from Proto-Italic *jowestos, related to Latin iūs (“law, right”); ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂yew-. Compare Scots juist (“just”), Saterland Fris...

JUSTLY.d: In a just or fair manner; rightfully.

JUTTED.d: Past tense of JUT: To stick out.
JUTTED.e: From Middle English jutten (“to project, jut out”), an alteration of jetten (“to strut, be showy”). More at English jet.

KABOOM.d: The sound of an explosion, typically seen in comic strips or heard in a light-hearted conversation.

KABUKI.d: A form of Japanese theatre in which elaborately costumed male performers use stylized movements, dances, and songs in order to enact tragedies and comedies.

KAFFIR.e: Ultimately from Arabic كَفَّار (kaffār, “infidel”) or كَافِر (kāfir, “unbeliever”), both from كَفَرَ (kafara, “to cover, to hide”); in some (especially early) uses, via Spanish cafre, Dutch kaffer or other European languages. Doublet of kafir.

KAFTAN.d: A long tunic worn in the Eastern Mediterranean.
KAFTAN.e: Via Russian кафта́н (kaftán), from Ottoman Turkish قفتان (kaftan), from Classical Persian خَفْتَان (xaftān), which occurs already in the Shahnameh.

KAKAPO.d: A large flightless parrot, Strigops habroptilus, with greenish plumage, that is nocturnal and native to New Zealand.

KALMIA.d: Any plant in the taxonomic genus Kalmia.
KALMIA.e: Borrowed from translingual Kalmia, from Swedish Kalm + translingual -ia, equivalent to Kalm + -ia.

KALONG.d: A fruit bat, especially the black-eared flying fox (Pteropus melanotus).

KANAKA.e: 1840. From Hawaiian kanaka (“person”), ultimately from Proto-Polynesian *taŋata.

KANUKA.d: Kunzea ericoides, the white tea tree of Australia and New Zealand, which can grow at high altitudes and in close proximity to geothermal features such as fumaroles.

KAOLIN.d: A fine clay, rich in kaolinite, used in ceramics, papermaking, etc.
KAOLIN.e: From French kaolin, François Xavier d'Entrecolles's irregular romanization of the Mandarin pronunciation of Chinese 高嶺土 /高岭土 (gāolǐngtǔ, “Gaoling earth”), from 高嶺 /高岭 (Gāolǐng, “High Ridge”), a village in Fuliang County, Jingdezhen Prefecture, Jiangxi Province, that became Jingde...

KARAKA.d: An evergreen tree, Corynocarpus laevigatus, bearing fruits with a kernel that can be eaten after extensive roasting and washing.

KARATE.d: An Okinawan martial art involving primarily punching and kicking, but additionally, advanced throws, arm bars, grappling and all means of fighting.
KARATE.e: Borrowed from Japanese 空(から)手(て) (karate), from 唐(から)手(て) (karate), an orthographic borrowing from Okinawan 唐手(とーでぃー) (tōdī, “Chinese hand”).

KAROSS.d: A treated animal-skin cloak or blanket with the hair still left on.
KAROSS.e: From Afrikaans karos, from Khoekhoe karo.s (“dried skin”).

KATANA.d: A type of Japanese longsword, having a single edge and slight curvature, historically used by samurai and ninja.
KATANA.e: Borrowed from Japanese 刀(かたな) (katana).

KAYOED.d: Past tense of KAYO: A knockout.
KAYOED.e: Respelling of the initial letters KO.

KECKED.d: Past tense of KECK: To heave or retch as if to vomit.

KEEKED.d: Past tense of KEEK: To peek; peep.
KEEKED.e:
From Middle English kyken, kiken, keken (“to look, peep”), probably from Middle Dutch kiken, kieken or Middle Low German kîken (“to look, peep”), from Old Saxon *kīkan (“to look”), from Proto-West Germanic *kīkan, from Proto-Germanic *kīkaną (“to look”).
Cognate with Dutch kijken...

KEELED.d: Past tense of KEEL: A large beam along the underside of a ship’s hull from bow to stern.
KEELED.e: From Middle English kele, from Old Norse kjǫlr, itself from Proto-Germanic *keluz, of uncertain origin. Displaced Old English ċēol from a related root. Distantly related to kile.

KEENED.d: Past tense of KEEN: Often with a prepositional phrase, or with to and an infinitive: showing a quick and ardent responsiveness or willingness; eager, enthusiastic, interested.
KEENED.e:
From Middle English kene (“bold, brave, sharp”), from Old English cēne (“keen, fierce, bold, brave, warlike, powerful; learned, clever, wise”), from Proto-Germanic *kōniz (“knowledgeable, skilful, experienced, clever, capable”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃- (“to know”).
Cogna...

KELPED.d: Past tense of KELP: Any of several large brown algae seaweeds (order Laminariales).
KELPED.e: From Middle English culp, culpe, of uncertain origin; possibly from Old English *colba, *colfa, from Proto-West Germanic *kolbō (“bulb, cob”), from Proto-Germanic *kulbaz (“round object, club”). Compare Middle High German kolbe (“clublike plant”), Old Norse kolfr (“bulb of a plan...

KELPIE.d: A malevolent shapeshifting spirit, most often in the form of a horse, believed to haunt the rivers and lochs of Scotland.
KELPIE.e: The dog breed derives from the name shared by the first two breeding bitches (dam and pup), which name derives from the mythological spirit.

KELVIN.d: In the International System of Units, the base unit of thermodynamic temperature; ¹⁄_(273.16) of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.
KELVIN.e: Named after Irish-born Scottish physicist William Thomson, Lord Kelvin.

KENNED.d: Past tense of KEN: To give birth, conceive, beget, be born; to develop (as a fetus); to nourish, sustain (as life).
KENNED.e: From Middle English kennen (“to give birth, conceive, generate, beget; to develop (as a fetus), hatch out (of eggs); to sustain, nourish, nurture”), from Old English cennan (“to give birth, conceive, generate, beget”), from Proto-West Germanic *kannjan, from Proto-Germanic *kanja...

KENNEL.d: A house or shelter for a dog.
KENNEL.e:
PIE word
 *ḱwṓ
From Middle English kenel, kenell, borrowed from Anglo-Norman *kenil, northern variant of Old French chenil, from Vulgar Latin *canīle, from Latin canis.

KENNER.d: Comparative form of KEN: To give birth, conceive, beget, be born; to develop (as a fetus); to nourish, sustain (as life).
KENNER.e: From Middle English kennen (“to give birth, conceive, generate, beget; to develop (as a fetus), hatch out (of eggs); to sustain, nourish, nurture”), from Old English cennan (“to give birth, conceive, generate, beget”), from Proto-West Germanic *kannjan, from Proto-Germanic *kanja...

KERBED.d: Past tense of KERB: Alternative spelling of curb.
KERBED.e: From curb (“raised border or frame”) [from mid-17th c.]. Doublet of curve.

KERFED.d: Past tense of KERF: The act of cutting or carving something; a stroke or slice.
KERFED.e: From Middle English kerf, kirf, kyrf, from Old English cyrf (“an act of cutting, a cutting off; a cutting instrument”), from Proto-West Germanic *kurbi, from Proto-Germanic *kurbiz (“a cut; notch; clipping”), from Proto-Indo-European *gerbʰ- (“to scratch”). Cognate with Saterland...

KERMES.d: Any of several insects of the genus Kermes.
KERMES.e:
PIE word
 *kʷŕ̥mis
First attested ca. 1600, from French kermès, from Medieval Latin cremesinus (compare Italian chermes, Spanish carmes), from Arabic قِرْمِز (qirmiz) (whence also Portuguese quermes, alquermes), from a Persian word meaning “worm-colored” (compare modern Persian ق...

KERNEL.d: The core, center, or essence of an object or system.
KERNEL.e: From Middle English kernel, kirnel, kürnel, from Old English cyrnel, from Proto-West Germanic *kurnil, diminutive of Proto-Germanic *kurną (“seed, grain, corn”), equivalent to corn + -le. Cognate with Yiddish קערנדל (kerndl), Middle Dutch kernel, cornel, Middle High German kornel...

KERSEY.d: A type of rough woollen cloth.
KERSEY.e: Inherited from Middle English kersey, perhaps from the village of Kersey in Suffolk, England, UK, in the region where the cloth was made.

KETONE.d: A homologous series of organic molecules whose functional group is an oxygen atom joined to a carbon atom—by a double bond—in a carbon-hydrogen based molecule.
KETONE.e: From German Keton, from Aketon (“acetone”), from French acétone (“acetone”). See acetone.

KETTLE.d: A vessel for boiling a liquid or cooking food, usually metal and equipped with a lid.
KETTLE.e: From Middle English ketel, also chetel, from Old English ċietel (“kettle, cauldron”) and in Middle English possibly influenced by Old Norse ketill and both from Proto-Germanic *katilaz (“kettle, bucket, vessel”), of uncertain origin and formation. Usually regarded as a borrowing ...

KEWPIE.e: Diminutive of Cupid; originally a brand name.

KEYING.d: Present participle of KEY: An object designed to open and close a lock.
KEYING.e: From Middle English keye, kaye, keiȝe, from Old English cǣġ (“key, solution, experiment”) (whence also Scots key and kay (“key”)), of uncertain origin. The only sure cognates are Saterland Frisian Koai (“key”), West Frisian kaai (“key”), and North Frisian kai, koie (“key”). Possi...

KEYPAD.d: A small board with keys primarily used for tactile input into a machine.

KEYPAL.d: The email equivalent of a penpal; someone with whom to exchange email for the simple joy of communicating.
KEYPAL.e: From key + pal, in reference to the computer keyboard.

KEYWAY.d: A slot into which a precision attachment (a key) is fitted.

KIBBLE.e: Unknown; verb sense c. 1790, Shropshire dialect, perhaps variant of chip or derived from Etymology 2 below.

KIBOSH.d: Chiefly in put on the kibosh or put the kibosh on: something which checks or restrains.
KIBOSH.e:
The origin of the noun is uncertain; the following etymologies have been suggested:
* According to Gerald Leonard Cohen, Stephen Goranson, and Matthew Little, at present the most likely derivation is as a non-rhotic variant of kurbash (“heavy whip, lash”), from Arabic كُرْبَاج (k...

KICKED.d: Past tense of KICK: To strike or hit with the foot or other extremity of the leg.
KICKED.e: From Middle English kyken (“to strike out with the foot”), from Old Norse kikna (“to sink at the knees”) and keikja (“to bend backwards”) (compare Old Norse keikr (“bent backwards, the belly jutting forward”)), from Proto-Germanic *kaikaz (“bent backwards”), of uncertain origin. ...

KIDDED.d: Past tense of KID: A child, adolescent, or (loosely) a young adult.
KIDDED.e: From Middle English kide, from Old Norse kið (“young goat”), from Proto-Germanic *kidją, *kittīną (“goatling, kid”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *gʰaydn-, *ǵʰaydn- (“goat”) or Proto-Indo-European *gidʰ- (“kid, goatling, little goat”). Compare Swedish and Danish kid, German K...

KIDDER.d: Comparative form of KID: A child, adolescent, or (loosely) a young adult.
KIDDER.e: From Middle English kide, from Old Norse kið (“young goat”), from Proto-Germanic *kidją, *kittīną (“goatling, kid”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *gʰaydn-, *ǵʰaydn- (“goat”) or Proto-Indo-European *gidʰ- (“kid, goatling, little goat”). Compare Swedish and Danish kid, German K...

KIDDLE.d: A kind of fishweir resembling a wattle or fence.
KIDDLE.e: From Middle English kidel, kedel, kydel, from Anglo-Norman quidel, quideau (“a wicker framework used to trap fish”), from Old Breton kidel (“a net at the mouth of a stream”).

KIDNAP.d: To seize or detain a person unlawfully and move or conceal them; sometimes for ransom.
KIDNAP.e: From kid + nap (“to nab; to grab”).

KIDNEY.d: An organ in the body that filters the blood, producing urine.
KIDNEY.e: From Middle English kedney, kydeney, from earlier kidnēre, kidenēre (“kidney”), of obscure origin and formation. Probably a compound consisting of Middle English *kid, *quid (“belly, womb”), from Old English cwiþ, cwiþa (“belly, womb, stomach”) + Middle English nēre (“kidney”), f...

KIDULT.d: An adult who participates in youth culture and activities traditionally intended for children.

KILNED.d: Past tense of KILN: An oven or furnace or a heated chamber, for the purpose of hardening, burning, calcining or drying anything; for example, firing ceramics, curing or preserving tobacco, or drying grain.
KILNED.e:
From Middle English kilne, from Old English cyln, cylen, cylin (“large oven, kiln”), from Latin culīna (“kitchen, kitchen stove”).
Middle English -ln(e) usually becomes modern -ll as in mill. The pronunciation /kɪln/ may be based on dialects in which this simplification did not t...

KILTED.d: Past tense of KILT: To gather up (skirts) around the body.
KILTED.e: From Middle English kilten (“to tuck up, gird”), apparently from North Germanic, ultimately from Old Norse kelta, kjalta (“skirt; lap”). Perhaps from Proto-Germanic *kelt-, *kelþǭ, *kilþį̄ (“womb”), from Proto-Indo-European *gelt- (“round body; child”). Cognate with Danish kilte ...

KILTIE.d: A shoe having a fringed tongue or fringed extra piece that lies over the tongue.

KIMONO.d: A traditional Japanese T-shaped, wrapped-front garment with square sleeves and a rectangular body, now generally worn only on formal occasions.
KIMONO.e: Borrowed from Japanese 着物(きもの) (kimono, “clothing”), which is from 着 (“wearing”) + 物(もの) (mono, “thing”).
