KINASE.d: Any of a group of enzymes that transfer phosphate groups from high-energy donor molecules, such as ATP, to specific target molecules (substrates), in a process termed phosphorylation.
KINASE.e: From Ancient Greek κινεῖν (kineîn, “to move”) + -ase, a suffix forming enzyme names.

KINDLE.d: To start (a fire) or light (a torch, a match, coals, etc.).
KINDLE.e: From Middle English kyndelen, from Old Norse kynda (“to inflame”), from Proto-Germanic *kundijaną.

KINDLY.d: Having a kind personality; kind, warmhearted, sympathetic.
KINDLY.e: From Middle English kyndely, kyndeliche, from Old English cyndelīċ (“natural, kindly”); equivalent to kind + -ly.

KINGED.d: Past tense of KING: A male monarch; a man who heads a monarchy; in an absolute monarchy, the supreme ruler of his nation.
KINGED.e:
From Middle English king, kyng, from Old English cyng, cyning (“king”), from Proto-West Germanic *kuning, from Proto-Germanic *kuningaz, *kunungaz (“king”), equivalent to kin + -ing. Doublet of cyning and knez.
Cognate with Scots keeng (“king”), North Frisian köning (“king”), Wes...

KINGLY.d: Of or belonging to a king or kings; exercised by a king.
KINGLY.e: From Middle English kyngly, from Old English *cyninglīċ (“kingly, royal”), equivalent to king + -ly. Cognate with Dutch koninklijk (“kingly, royal”), German königlich (“kingly”), Swedish kunglig (“kingly”). Compare also Old English cynelīċ (“kingly, royal, public”).

KINKED.d: Past tense of KINK: To laugh loudly.
KINKED.e: From Middle English kinken, kynken, from Old English *cincian (attested in cincung), from Proto-West Germanic *kinkōn, from Proto-Germanic *kinkōną (“to laugh”), from Proto-Indo-European *gang- (“to mock, jeer, deride”), related to Old English canc (“jeering, scorn, derision”). C...

KIPPAH.d: The cloth skullcap or yarmulke traditionally worn by male Jews.

KIPPED.d: Past tense of KIP: The untanned hide of a young or small beast, such as a calf, lamb, or young goat.
KIPPED.e: 1325–75, Middle English kipp, from Middle Dutch kip, from Middle Low German kip (“pack, bundle of hides”).

KIPPER.d: A split, salted and smoked herring or salmon.
KIPPER.e: From Old English cypera (“male salmon”), perhaps related to Old English coper (“reddish-brown metal”) (see copper), on resemblance of color. Another theory connects it to kip (“sharp, hooked lower jaw of the male salmon in breeding season”), from Middle English kippen (“to seize,...

KIRSCH.d: A clear brandy made from black cherries: kirschwasser.
KIRSCH.e: Borrowed from French kirsch, from German Kirschwasser (“cherry water”). Doublet of cerise and cherry.

KIRTLE.e: From Middle English kirtel, from Old English cyrtel, cognate with Old Norse kyrtill (“tunic”) (whence Icelandic kyrtill, Danish kjortel (“gown, tunic”), Swedish kjortel (“petticoat, skirt”)), from Old Norse *kurtil-, supposedly a diminutive of *kurt-, from Latin curtus (“short, s...

KISMET.d: Fate; a predetermined or unavoidable destiny.
KISMET.e: From Ottoman Turkish قسمت (kısmet, “fate, destiny”) (Turkish kısmet), from Arabic قِسْمَة (qisma, “division, lot, destiny”).

KISSED.d: Past tense of KISS: To touch with the lips or press the lips against, usually to show love or affection or passion, or as part of a greeting.
KISSED.e:
From Middle English kissen, kussen, from Old English cyssan (“to kiss”), from Proto-West Germanic *kussijan, from Proto-Germanic *kussijaną (“to kiss”).
Cognates include Saterland Frisian küsje, Dutch kussen, German Low German küssen, German küssen, Danish kysse, Swedish kyssa, N...

KISSES.d: Plural of KISS: To touch with the lips or press the lips against, usually to show love or affection or passion, or as part of a greeting.
KISSES.e:
From Middle English kissen, kussen, from Old English cyssan (“to kiss”), from Proto-West Germanic *kussijan, from Proto-Germanic *kussijaną (“to kiss”).
Cognates include Saterland Frisian küsje, Dutch kussen, German Low German küssen, German küssen, Danish kysse, Swedish kyssa, N...

KITING.d: Present participle of KITE: A bird of prey of the family Accipitridae.
KITING.e: The noun is from Middle English kyte, kīte, kete (“a kite endemic to Europe, especially the red kite (Milvus milvus)”), from Old English cȳta (“kite; bittern”), from Proto-West Germanic *kūtijō, diminutive of Proto-Germanic *kūts (“bird of prey”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewH-d...

KITSCH.d: Art, decorative objects, and other forms of representation of questionable artistic or aesthetic value; a representation that is excessively sentimental, overdone, or vulgar.
KITSCH.e: From German Kitsch, from dialectal kitschen (“to coat, to smear”); the word and concept were popularized in the 1930s by several critics who contrasted it with avant garde art.

KITTED.d: Past tense of KIT: A circular wooden vessel, made of hooped staves.
KITTED.e: From Middle English kyt, kytt, kytte, from Middle Dutch kitte (“a wooden vessel made of hooped staves”). Related to Dutch kit (“tankard”) (see below). The further etymology is unknown. Perhaps from Proto-Germanic *kitjō-, *kut-, which would be related to the root of Dutch kot (“r...

KITTEN.d: A young cat, especially before sexual maturity (reached at about seven months).
KITTEN.e: From Middle English kitoun, kytton, kyton, keton (“kitten”), of obscure origin. Seemingly from, and usually explained as being from, unattested Anglo-Norman *kitoun, *ketun (compare Old French chitoun, cheton, chaton (“kitten”), diminutive of cat, chat (“cat”)); whence Modern Fre...

KITTER.d: Comparative form of KIT: A circular wooden vessel, made of hooped staves.
KITTER.e: From Middle English kyt, kytt, kytte, from Middle Dutch kitte (“a wooden vessel made of hooped staves”). Related to Dutch kit (“tankard”) (see below). The further etymology is unknown. Perhaps from Proto-Germanic *kitjō-, *kut-, which would be related to the root of Dutch kot (“r...

KITTLE.e:
From Middle English kitelen, from Old English citelian (“to tickle”), from Proto-West Germanic *kitilōn, from Proto-Germanic *kitilōną, frequentative form of Proto-Germanic *kitōną (“to tickle”), from Proto-Indo-European *geid- (“to stick, jab, tickle”).
Cognate with Dutch kittel...

KLAXON.d: A loud electric alarm or horn, especially as used in automobiles in the early 20th century.
KLAXON.e: From the trademark Klaxon, based on Ancient Greek κλάζω (klázō, “make a sharp sound; scream”) (from Proto-Indo-European *glag- (“to make a noise, clap, twitter”), from *gal- (“to roop, scream, shout”)). The word was coined by Franklyn Hallett Lovell Jr., the founder of the Lovell...

KLEPHT.d: An anti-Ottoman insurgent living in the mountains when Greece was a part of the Ottoman Empire.

KLUDGE.d: An improvised device, typically crudely constructed to test the validity of a principle before implementing a finished design.
KLUDGE.e:
Perhaps from British military slang, possibly based on Scots word kludge or kludgie (“common toilet”), or perhaps from German klug (“clever”). Alternatively, possibly related to Polish klucz (“key, clue, main point”) and Russian ключ (ključ, “key, clue”).
Alternatively, perhaps f...

KNAWEL.d: A low, spreading weed of the genus Scleranthus, especially
KNAWEL.e: From German Knauel, Kneuel (“ball of thread, coil”) (see Knäuel). Doublet of clew.

KNIFED.d: Past tense of KNIFE: A cutting instrument with a blade.
KNIFED.e: From Old English cnīf, from Old Norse knífr.

KNIFES.d: Plural of KNIFE: A cutting instrument with a blade.
KNIFES.e: From Old English cnīf, from Old Norse knífr.

KNIGHT.d: A young servant or follower; a trained military attendant in service of a lord.
KNIGHT.e: From Middle English knight, knyght, kniht, from Old English cniht (“boy; servant, knight”), from Proto-West Germanic *kneht.

KNIVES.d: Plural of KNIFE: A cutting instrument with a blade.
KNIVES.e: From Old English cnīf, from Old Norse knífr.

KNOTTY.d: Of string or something stringlike: full of, or tied up, in knots.
KNOTTY.e: From Middle English knotti, knotty (“having a knot in it; full of knots; tied together (?); resembling a knot, knotlike; having knobs or protuberances; bulging, convex; of a tree, branch, etc.: full of knots, gnarled; of a plant cutting to be grafted or planted: full of buds or e...

KOBOLD.d: An ambivalent, sometimes vindictive, spirit that is capable of materialising as an object or human, often a child; a sprite.
KOBOLD.e: Borrowed from German Kobold. Doublet of cobalt.

KORUNA.d: The currency of the former Czechoslovakia, divided into 100 hellers.
KORUNA.e: From Czech and Slovak koruna; cognate with krone and German Krone. Doublet of corona, crown, korona, krona, króna, and krone.

KOSHER.d: Fit for use or consumption, in accordance with Jewish law (especially relating to food).
KOSHER.e: Borrowed from Yiddish כּשר (kosher), from Hebrew כָּשֵׁר (kashér).

KOWHAI.d: Any of several small woody legume trees in the genus Sophora native to New Zealand that have yellow flowers. The national flower of New Zealand.

KOWTOW.d: To kneel and bow low enough to touch one’s forehead to the ground.
KOWTOW.e: From either Cantonese 叩頭 /叩头 (kau³ tau⁴) or Mandarin 叩頭 /叩头 (kòutóu). Literally, “knock head”.

KWANZA.d: The currency of Angola, symbol Kz, divided into a hundred cêntimos.
KWANZA.e: Named after the Kwanza (Cuanza) River in Angola.

LAAGER.d: A defensive encampment encircled by wagons, especially by South African Boers.
LAAGER.e: From South African Dutch lager (“camp”) (modern Afrikaans laer), from German Lager, from Middle High German leger, from Old High German legar, from Proto-Germanic *legrą. Doublet of lager and lair.

LABBER.d: Comparative form of LAB: A laboratory.

LABIAL.d: Of or pertaining to the lips or labia.
LABIAL.e: Borrowing from Medieval Latin labiālis (“of or pertaining to the lips”), from labium (“a lip”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix); equivalent to labium + -al.

LABIUM.d: A liplike structure; especially one of the vulva's two pairs of folds of skin on either side.
LABIUM.e: Learned borrowing from Latin labium (“a lip”). Doublet of lip.

LABORS.d: Plural of LABOR: Work; physical effort.

LABOUR.d: Effort expended on a particular task; toil, work.
LABOUR.e: From Middle English labor, labour, labur, from Old French labor (modern labeur) and its etymon, Latin labor.

LABRET.d: A body piercing consisting of an adornment attached to the lip.
LABRET.e: From Latin labrum (“lip”) + -et; modelled on anklet, bracelet, etc. Sometimes incorrectly assumed to be of French origin.

LABRUM.d: The uppermost of the mouthparts (trophi) of a typical insect, such as a cockroach. Typically resembles an upper lip and forms part of the roof of the mouth in such insects.

LACHES.e: From Anglo-Norman laches, from Old French lachesse (“laxness”), from laschier, from Vulgar Latin laxico, frequentative of Latin laxo (“relax, moderate, weaken”).

LACIER.d: Comparative form of LACY: Made of lace or decorated with it.

LACING.d: present participle and gerund of lace

LACKED.d: Past tense of LACK: A deficiency or need (of something desirable or necessary); an absence, want, dearth.
LACKED.e: From Middle English lack, lakke, lak, from Old English *læc (“deficiency, lack, want”), from Proto-West Germanic *lak, from Proto-Germanic *laką, *lakaz (“slackness”), from Proto-Germanic *lakaz (“limp, slack, loose, low”), related to *lak(k)ōną (“to blame, reproach”), from Proto...

LACKEY.d: A footman, a liveried male servant.
LACKEY.e: Borrowed from Middle French laquais, which is probably (via Old Occitan lacai?) from Spanish lacayo, itself perhaps from Italian lacchè and Greek λακές (lakés), from Turkish ulak. Another possibility is through French, from Catalan alacay, from Arabic الْقَائِد (al-qāʔid). See Fr...

LACTAM.d: Any of a class of cyclic amides that are the nitrogen analogs of lactones, formed by heating amino acids; the tautomeric enol forms are known as lactims.

LACUNA.d: A small opening; a small pit or depression, especially in bone.
LACUNA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin lacūna (“a ditch, pit; a hollow, cavity; a gap, defect”). Doublet of lacune and lagoon.

LADDER.d: A frame, usually portable, of wood, metal, or rope, used for ascent and descent, consisting of two side pieces to which are fastened rungs (cross strips or rounds acting as steps).
LADDER.e:
Inherited from Middle English ladder, laddre; from Old English hlǣder, from Proto-West Germanic *hlaidriju, from Proto-Germanic *hlaidrijō, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱlóydʰrom, from *ḱley- (“to lean”).
Compare Scots ledder, North Frisian ladder, Saterland Frisian Laadere, West Fr...

LADIES.d: Plural of LADY: The mistress of a household.
LADIES.e: From Middle English lady, laddy, lafdi, lavedi, from Old English hlǣfdīġe (“mistress of a household, wife of a lord, lady”, literally “bread-kneader”), from hlāf (“bread, loaf”) + dīġe (“kneader”), related to Old English dǣġe (“maker of dough”) (whence dey (“dairymaid”)). Compare...

LADIFY.d: To make a lady of; to make ladylike.

LADING.e: Gerund of lade (verb). Cognate with Dutch lading (“cargo, charge”), German Ladung (“cargo, charge”), Polish ładunek (“cargo, charge”), Swedish laddning (“charge”). Doublet of loading.

LAGENA.d: The upper part of the cochlear duct.
LAGENA.e: From Latin lagēna (“flagon; large flask”), from Ancient Greek λάγηνος (lágēnos, “flask, pitcher”). alternative form of λᾰ́γῡνος (lắgūnos)

LAGOON.d: A shallow body of water separated from deeper sea by a bar.
LAGOON.e: Borrowed from French lagune, from Italian laguna, from Latin lacuna. Related to Old English lagu via Proto-Indo-European. Doublet of lacuna and lacune.

LAIRED.d: Past tense of LAIR: A place inhabited by a wild animal, often a cave or a hole in the ground.
LAIRED.e: From Middle English leir, leire, lair, lare, from Old English leġer (“couch, bed”), from Proto-Germanic *legrą, from Proto-Indo-European *legʰ-.

LAKING.d: Present participle of LAKE: A large, landlocked stretch of water or similar liquid.
LAKING.e:
Arose from a conflation of
* Middle English lake (“small stream of running water, pool, lake”), from Old English lacu (“stream, pool, pond, lake”), from Proto-West Germanic *laku, from Proto-Germanic *lakō (“stream, pool, body of water", originally "a place where water collects”)...

LAMBDA.d: The eleventh letter of the Classical and Modern Greek alphabet, the twelfth of the Old Greek alphabet.
LAMBDA.e: From Ancient Greek λάμβδα (lámbda). Doublet of lamed.

LAMBED.d: Past tense of LAMB: A young sheep.
LAMBED.e:
From Middle English lamb, from Old English lamb, from Proto-West Germanic *lamb, from Proto-Germanic *lambaz, probably from Proto-Indo-European *h₁l̥h₁onbʰos, enlargement of *h₁elh₁én, ultimately from *h₁el-.
See also Dutch lam, German Lamm, Bavarian Lamperl, Danish lam, Swedish ...

LAMENT.d: An expression of grief, suffering, sadness or regret.
LAMENT.e: From French lamenter, from Latin lāmentor (“I wail, weep”), from lāmenta (“wailings, laments, moanings”); with formative -mentum, from the root *la-, probably ultimately imitative. Also see latrare.

LAMINA.d: A thin layer, plate, or scale of material.
LAMINA.e: Borrowed from Latin lāmina (“a thin piece of metal, wood, marble; a plate, leaf, layer”). Doublet of lame.

LAMING.d: Present participle of LAME: Unable to walk properly because of a problem with one's feet or legs.
LAMING.e: From Middle English lame, from Old English lama (“lame”), from Proto-West Germanic *lam, from Proto-Germanic *lamaz (“lame”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃lemH- (“to tire; to break”).

LAMMED.d: Past tense of LAM: To beat or thrash.
LAMMED.e: From Middle English lamen, lemen, from Old English lemian and Old Norse lemja; both from Proto-Germanic *lamjaną.

LAMMER.d: Comparative form of LAM: To beat or thrash.
LAMMER.e: From Middle English lamen, lemen, from Old English lemian and Old Norse lemja; both from Proto-Germanic *lamjaną.

LAMPED.d: Past tense of LAMP: A device that generates heat, light or other radiation. Especially an electric light bulb.
LAMPED.e: From Middle English laumpe, lampe, from Old French lampe (“lamp, light”), from Latin lampas (“torch, lamp, light”), from Ancient Greek λαμπάς (lampás, “torch, lamp, beacon, light, meteor”), from Proto-Indo-European *leh₂p- (“to shine”). Cognate with Lithuanian lópė (“light”), Wel...

LANCET.d: A sharp, pointed, two-edged surgical instrument used in venesection and for opening abscesses etc.
LANCET.e: From Middle English launcet, from Old French lancete, a diminutive of lance. By surface analysis, lance + -et.

LANDAU.d: A type of lightweight, four-wheeled carriage in which the front and back passenger seats face each other.
LANDAU.e: Named after the German city of Landau, where such carriages were first made. Compare German Landauer.

LANDER.d: One who lands, or who lands something.

LANGUR.d: Any of the Old World monkeys of the genera Simias, Trachypithecus (lutungs), Presbytis (surilis), and Semnopithecus (gray langurs).
LANGUR.e: Borrowed from Hindustani لنگور / लंगूर (laṅgūr, “monkey”), from Sanskrit लाङ्गूल (lāṅgūla, “tail”) (compare लाङ्गूलिन् (lāṅgūlin, “tailed; monkey”)).

LANNER.e: From Middle French lanier (“cowardly”), possibly from Latin lānārius.

LANUGO.d: Soft down or fine hair, specifically that covering the human foetus or a tumorous area.

LAPFUL.d: As much as somebody's lap can hold.

LAPPED.d: Past tense of LAP: The loose part of a coat; the lower part of a garment that plays loosely; a skirt; an apron.
LAPPED.e: From Middle English lappe, from Old English læppa (“skirt or flap of a garment”), from Proto-Germanic *lappô (“cloth; rag”), of uncertain origin, possibly Proto-Indo-European *leb- (“to hang loosely”). Cognate with Dutch lap (“cloth; rag”), German Lappen (“cloth; lobe; flap”), Ic...

LAPPER.d: One who laps liquid, who takes liquid in with the tongue.

LAPPET.d: A small decorative fold or flap, especially of lace or muslin, in a garment or headdress.

LAPSES.d: Plural of LAPS: plural of lap

LAPTOP.e: From lap (“upper legs of a seated person”) + top, modeled after desktop.

LARDED.d: Past tense of LARD: Fat from the abdomen of a pig, especially as prepared for use in cooking or pharmacy.
LARDED.e: From Middle English lard, from Old French lard (“bacon”), from Latin lārdum, lāridum (“bacon fat”).

LARDON.d: Meat strips used for larding, especially salted pork.
LARDON.e: From Middle English lardon, lardun, from Old French lardon.

LARGES.d: Plural of LARGE: Of great size.
LARGES.e: From Old French large, from Latin largus.

LARKED.d: Past tense of LARK: Any of various small, singing passerine birds of the family Alaudidae.
LARKED.e: From Middle English larke, laverke, from Old English lāwerce, lǣwerce, lāuricæ, from Proto-West Germanic *laiwarikā, from Proto-Germanic *laiwarikǭ, *laiwazikǭ (compare dialectal West Frisian larts, Dutch leeuwerik, German Lerche), from *laiwaz (borrowed into Finnish leivo, Eston...

LARRUP.e:
Uncertain.
Many dictionaries suggest a connection with Dutch larpen (“to thresh with flails”).

LARYNX.d: A hollow muscular organ of the neck of mammals situated just below where the tract of the pharynx splits into the trachea and the oesophagus. It is involved in breath control and protection of the trachea, and, as it houses the vocal cords, sound production.
LARYNX.e: Borrowed from New Latin larynx, from Ancient Greek λᾰ́ρῠγξ (lắrŭnx, “larynx; windpipe; gullet, throat”).

LASHED.d: Past tense of LASH: The thong or braided cord of a whip, with which the blow is given.
LASHED.e:
From Middle English lashe, lasshe, lasche (“a stroke; the flexible end of a whip”), from Proto-Germanic *laskô (“flap of fabric, strap”).
Cognate with Dutch lasch, las (“a piece; seal; joint; notch; seam”), German Low German Laske, Lask (“a flap; dag; strap”), German Lasche (“a f...

LASHES.d: Plural of LASH: The thong or braided cord of a whip, with which the blow is given.
LASHES.e:
From Middle English lashe, lasshe, lasche (“a stroke; the flexible end of a whip”), from Proto-Germanic *laskô (“flap of fabric, strap”).
Cognate with Dutch lasch, las (“a piece; seal; joint; notch; seam”), German Low German Laske, Lask (“a flap; dag; strap”), German Lasche (“a f...

LASING.d: Present participle of LASE: To use a laser beam on, as for cutting.
LASING.e: Back-formation from laser, as if removing -er. Compare mase.

LASQUE.d: A diamond having a flat shape.

LASSES.d: Plural of LASS: A girl; also (by extension), a young woman.
LASSES.e:
From Middle English las, lasce, lasse (“female infant or child; young woman”), probably from Proto-Norse *laskwa (“unmarried”, adjective).
Cognates
Scots lass, lassie

LASSIE.d: A young girl, a lass, especially one seen as a sweetheart.

LASTED.d: Past tense of LAST: Final, ultimate, coming after all others of its kind.
LASTED.e: From Middle English laste, latst, syncopated variant of latest.

LATEEN.d: A triangular fore-and-aft sail set on a boom in such way that the tack is attached to the hull of the vessel and the free end of the boom lifts the sail.

LATENT.d: Existing or present but concealed or inactive.
LATENT.e: From Middle English latent, latente, from Old French latent, from Latin latēns, present participle of lateō (“lie hidden”).

LATEST.d: superlative form of late: most late
LATEST.e: From Middle English lateste, from Old English latost, latest, lætest, superlative of læt, whence English late.

LATHER.d: The foam made by rapidly stirring soap and water.
LATHER.e: From Middle English lather, from Old English lēaþor (“a kind of nitre used for soap, soda”), from Proto-West Germanic *lauþr, from Proto-Germanic *lauþrą (“that which is used for washing, soap”), from Proto-Indo-European *lówh₃trom (“that which is used for washing”), from *lewh₃-...

LATRIA.d: The highest form of worship, named adoration, properly given to the triune God alone.
LATRIA.e: From Late Latin, from Ancient Greek λατρεία (latreía, “service,” “worship”), from λατρευειν (latreuein, “wait on,” “serve with prayer”).

LATTEN.d: An alloy of copper and tin, similar to bronze, with a sufficient portion of tin to make it a pewter-like color with yellowish tinge (rather than the brownish-gold color of bronze of higher copper content), once used in thin sheets and for domestic utensils and light-duty tools.
LATTEN.e: From Middle English laten, latun, latoun, from Old French laton, laiton, from Arabic لَاطُون (lāṭūn, “copper, copper alloy”), itself from Proto-Common Turkic *altun (“gold”). See Turkish altın, Old Turkic 𐰞𐱃𐰆𐰣 (altun, “gold”), Karakhanid اَلْتُونْ (altūn, “gold”).

LATTER.d: Relating to or being the second of two items.
LATTER.e: From Old English lætra, comparative form of læt (“late”). Doublet of later; also, cognate with last, whose doublet is latest.

LAUGHS.d: Plural of LAUGH: To express amusement audibly.

LAUNCH.d: To throw (a projectile such as a lance, dart or ball); to hurl; to propel with force.
LAUNCH.e: From Middle English launchen (“to throw as a lance”), Old French lanchier, another form (Old Northern French/Norman variant, compare Jèrriais lanchi) of lancier, French lancer, from lance.

LAUREL.d: An evergreen shrub of species Laurus nobilis, having aromatic leaves of a lanceolate shape, with clusters of small, yellowish white flowers in their axils.
LAUREL.e: Inherited from Middle English laurer, laurel, from Anglo-Norman lorer, from Old French lorier, from Vulgar Latin *laurārius, from Latin laurus (“laurel”). Doublet of loureiro.

LAVABO.d: A ritual involving the washing of one's hands at a church's offertory before handling the Eucharist.
LAVABO.e: From the Christian ritual, which was traditionally accompanied in Catholicism by a recitation of Psalm 25:6 (Psalm 26:6, in the Hebrew and in most modern translations) which in Latin begins with the word lavābō (“I will wash”). The sense of "room with a toilet" developed under th...

LAVING.d: Present participle of LAVE: To bathe or wash (someone or something).
LAVING.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English laven (“to bathe, wash; to bail or draw water, drain, exhaust; to dampen, wet; to pour; of water, etc.: to flow, stream”), and then partly:
* from Old French laver (“to be washed; to wash”) (modern French laver (“to wash (oneself)”)), from ...

LAVISH.d: Expending or bestowing profusely; profuse; prodigal.
LAVISH.e: From Middle English laves, lavas, lavage (“extravagant, wasteful, prodigal”), from lavas (“excessive abundance”), from Old French lavasse, lavache (“torrent of rain”); possibly later conflated in some senses by Middle English laven (“to pour out”), equivalent to lave + -ish. Comp...

LAWFUL.d: Conforming to, or recognised by the laws of society.
LAWFUL.e: From Middle English laweful, equivalent to law + -ful, conflated with Middle English leful, leeful, leveful (“according to law, lawful, pertaining to law”). See also leveful.

LAWING.d: Present participle of LAW: The body of binding rules and regulations, customs, and standards established in a community by its legislative and judicial authorities.
LAWING.e: From Middle English lawe, laȝe, from Old English lagu (“law”), borrowed from Old Norse lǫg (“law”, literally “things laid down or firmly established”), originally the plural of lag (“layer, stratum, a laying in order, measure, stroke”), from Proto-Germanic *lagą (“that which is l...

LAWMAN.d: A lawspeaker: a declarer of the law.
LAWMAN.e: From Middle English laweman, laȝaman (as a man's name, Laȝamon, Layamon), from Old English lahmann, borrowed from Old Norse lǫgmaðr. In present use as a law-enforcement officer, law + -man.

LAWNED.d: Past tense of LAWN: Ground (generally in front of or around a house) covered with grass kept closely mown.
LAWNED.e: Early Modern English laune (“turf, grassy area”), alteration of laund (“glade”), from Middle English launde, from Old French lande (“heath, moor”), of Germanic or Gaulish origin, from Proto-Germanic *landą (“land”) or Proto-Celtic *landā, both from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“l...

LAWYER.d: A professional person with a graduate law degree that qualifies for legal work (such as Juris Doctor)
LAWYER.e: From Middle English lawiere, lawier, lawer, equivalent to law + -yer.

LAXITY.d: The state of being lax; looseness, lack of tension.
LAXITY.e: Borrowed from Middle French laxité, itself borrowed from Latin laxitas, laxitatem, from laxus. By surface analysis, lax + -ity.

LAYERS.d: Plural of LAYER: A sheet or thickness of material.

LAYING.d: present participle and gerund of lay

LAYMAN.d: Layperson, someone who is not an ordained cleric or member of the clergy.
LAYMAN.e: From Middle English layman, lay man, equivalent to lay (“non-clergy”) + man. Cognate with Old Frisian lēkmann, lēkmonn (“layman”), obsolete Dutch leekeman (“layman”), Old High German leihman (“layman”), Danish lægmand (“layman”), Swedish lekman (“layman”), Norwegian lekmann (“lay...

LAYOUT.d: A structured arrangement of items within certain limits.

LAZIED.d: Past tense of LAZY: Unwilling to do work or make an effort; disinclined to exertion.
LAZIED.e:
Attested since 1540, origin uncertain. Probably from Low German and Middle Low German lasich (“slack, feeble, lazy”), from las, from Old Saxon lask, from Proto-Germanic *lasiwaz, *laskaz (“feeble, weak”), from Proto-Indo-European *las- (“weak”).
Akin to Dutch leuzig (“lazy”), Old...

LAZIER.d: Comparative form of LAZY: Unwilling to do work or make an effort; disinclined to exertion.
LAZIER.e:
Attested since 1540, origin uncertain. Probably from Low German and Middle Low German lasich (“slack, feeble, lazy”), from las, from Old Saxon lask, from Proto-Germanic *lasiwaz, *laskaz (“feeble, weak”), from Proto-Indo-European *las- (“weak”).
Akin to Dutch leuzig (“lazy”), Old...

LAZIES.d: Plural of LAZY: Unwilling to do work or make an effort; disinclined to exertion.
LAZIES.e:
Attested since 1540, origin uncertain. Probably from Low German and Middle Low German lasich (“slack, feeble, lazy”), from las, from Old Saxon lask, from Proto-Germanic *lasiwaz, *laskaz (“feeble, weak”), from Proto-Indo-European *las- (“weak”).
Akin to Dutch leuzig (“lazy”), Old...

LAZING.d: Present participle of LAZE: To be lazy, waste time.

LEADED.d: Past tense of LEAD: A heavy, pliable, inelastic metal element, having a bright, bluish color, but easily tarnished; both malleable and ductile, though with little tenacity. It is easily fusible, forms alloys with other metals, and is an ingredient of solder and type metal. Atomic number 82, symbol Pb (from Latin plumbum).
LEADED.e:
From Middle English led, leed, from Old English lēad (“lead”), from Proto-West Germanic *laud (“lead”), possibly borrowed from Proto-Celtic *ɸloudom, from Proto-Indo-European *plewd- (“to flow”).
Cognate with Scots leid, lede (“lead”), North Frisian lud, luad (“lead”), West Frisi...

LEADEN.e: From Middle English leden, leaden, from Old English lēaden (“leaden, of lead”). Cognate with West Frisian leaden (“leaden”), Dutch loden (“leaden”). By surface analysis, lead + -en.

LEADER.d: Any person who leads or directs.
LEADER.e: From Middle English leder, ledere, from Old English lǣdere (“leader”), from Proto-West Germanic *laidijārī (“leader”), equivalent to lead + -er. Cognate with Scots ledar, leidar (“leader”), West Frisian lieder (“leader”), Dutch leider (“leader”), German Leiter (“leader, conductor...

LEAFED.d: Past tense of LEAF: The usually green and flat organ that represents the most prominent feature of most vegetative plants.
LEAFED.e:
From Middle English leef, from Old English lēaf, from Proto-West Germanic *laub, from Proto-Germanic *laubą (“leaf”), from Proto-Indo-European *lowbʰ-o-m, from *lewbʰ- (“leaf, rind”)
See also West Frisian leaf, Low German Loov, Dutch loof, German Laub, Danish løv, Swedish löv, No...

LEAGUE.d: A group or association of cooperating members.
LEAGUE.e: From Middle English liege, ligg, lige (“a pact between governments, an agreement, alliance”), from Middle French ligue, from Italian lega, from the verb legare, from Latin ligō (“I tie”).

LEAKED.d: Past tense of LEAK: A crack, crevice, fissure, or hole which admits water or other fluid, or lets it escape.
LEAKED.e:
From Middle English leken (“to let water in or out”), from Old English *lecan (“to leak”), Middle Dutch leken (“to leak, drip”) or Old Norse leka (“to leak, drip”); all from Proto-Germanic *lekaną (“to leak, drain”), from Proto-Indo-European *leg-, *leǵ- (“to leak”).
Cognate with...

LEANED.d: Past tense of LEAN: To incline, deviate, or bend, from a vertical position; to be in a position thus inclining or deviating.
LEANED.e:
From Middle English lenen (“to lean”), from Old English hleonian, hlinian (“to lean, recline, lie down, rest”), from Proto-West Germanic *hlinēn, from Proto-Germanic *hlināną (“to lean, incline”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱley-.
Cognate via Proto-Germanic with Middle Dutch leune...

LEAPED.d: Past tense of LEAP: To jump.
LEAPED.e:
From Middle English lepen, from Old English hlēapan, from Proto-West Germanic *hlaupan, from Proto-Germanic *hlaupaną. Doublet of lope, lowp, elope, gallop, galop, interlope, and loop.
Cognate with North Frisian laap, luup, luupe (“to jog, run, walk”), Saterland Frisian lope, loo...

LEARNS.d: Plural of LEARN: To gain knowledge or skill.

LEASES.d: Plural of LEAS: plural of lea

LEASTS.d: Plural of LEAST: Smallest in amount or degree.

LEAVED.d: Past tense of LEAVE: To go away from; to allow to remain.

LEAVEN.d: Any agent used to make dough rise or to have a similar effect on baked goods.
LEAVEN.e: From Middle English levayn, borrowed from Old French levain, from Vulgar Latin *levāmen, a noun based on Latin levō (“raise”).

LEAVES.d: Plural of LEAF: The usually green and flat organ that represents the most prominent feature of most vegetative plants.
LEAVES.e:
From Middle English leef, from Old English lēaf, from Proto-West Germanic *laub, from Proto-Germanic *laubą (“leaf”), from Proto-Indo-European *lowbʰ-o-m, from *lewbʰ- (“leaf, rind”)
See also West Frisian leaf, Low German Loov, Dutch loof, German Laub, Danish løv, Swedish löv, No...

LECHER.d: A lecherous person: someone given to excessive sexual activity or debauchery.
LECHER.e: From Middle English lechour, from Old French lecheor (“glutton, sensualist, libertine”) , from Old French lecher, lechier, lekier, lescher (“to lick, live in gluttony or sensuality”), from Old Frankish *likkōn (“to lick”), from Proto-Germanic *likkōną (“to lick”), from Proto-Indo...

LECTIN.d: Any of a class of proteins that bind specific carbohydrates.
LECTIN.e: From Latin lēctus (“chosen”) + -in. Coined by W.C. Boyd in 1954.

LECTOR.d: A lay person who reads aloud certain religious texts in a church service.
LECTOR.e: From Middle English lector, lectoure, lectour, from Late Latin lēctor, from legō (“I read”). “Voice-over” sense probably adapted from Polish lektor.

LEERED.d: Past tense of LEER: To look sideways or obliquely; now especially with sexual desire or malicious intent.
LEERED.e: Exact development uncertain, but apparently from a verb *leer (“to make a face, look sideways”), from leer (“cheek, face, profile”).

LEEWAY.d: The drift of a ship or aeroplane in a leeward direction.
LEEWAY.e: From lee (“side away from the wind”) + way.

LEGACY.d: Money or property bequeathed to someone in a will.
LEGACY.e: From Middle English legacie, from Old French legacie and Medieval Latin lēgātia, from Latin lēgātum.

LEGATE.d: A deputy representing the pope, specifically a papal ambassador sent on special ecclesiastical missions.
LEGATE.e: Inherited from Old English legat(e), from Old French legat, from Latin lēgātus, substantivized from the perfect passive participle of lēgō (“to bequeath, send as envoy”).

LEGATO.e: Borrowed from Italian legato, past participle of legare (“to tie up, tie together, to bind”), learned borrowing from Latin ligō (“tie, bind”). Doublet of ligate.

LEGEND.d: The life story of a saint (such stories are often embellished, but any kind is called a legend).
LEGEND.e: From Middle English legende, from Old French legende, from Medieval Latin legenda (“a legend, story, especially the lives of the saints”), from Latin legenda (“things which ought to be read”), from lego (“I read”).

LEGGED.d: Past tense of LEG: A limb or appendage that an animal uses for support or locomotion on land.
LEGGED.e:
From Middle English leg, legge, from Old Norse leggr (“leg, calf, bone of the arm or leg, hollow tube, stalk”), from Proto-Germanic *lagjaz, *lagwijaz (“leg, thigh”) (see it for more).
Cognate with Scots leg (“leg”), Icelandic leggur (“leg, limb”), Norwegian Bokmål legg (“leg”), ...

LEGGER.d: Comparative form of LEG: A limb or appendage that an animal uses for support or locomotion on land.
LEGGER.e:
From Middle English leg, legge, from Old Norse leggr (“leg, calf, bone of the arm or leg, hollow tube, stalk”), from Proto-Germanic *lagjaz, *lagwijaz (“leg, thigh”) (see it for more).
Cognate with Scots leg (“leg”), Icelandic leggur (“leg, limb”), Norwegian Bokmål legg (“leg”), ...

LEGION.d: Numerous; vast; very great in number.
LEGION.e:
Attested (in Middle English, as legioun) around 1200, from Old French legion, from Latin legiō, legionem, from legō (“to gather, collect”); akin to legend, lecture. Doublet of León, which was borrowed from Spanish.
Generalized sense of “a large number” is due to an allusive phras...

LEGIST.e: From Middle French légiste, from Medieval Latin lēgista, from Latin lex (“law”). Compare legal.

LEGUME.d: The fruit or seed of leguminous plants (as peas or beans) used for food.
LEGUME.e: Borrowed from French légume, from Latin legūmen (“bean”). Doublet of legumen.

LENDED.d: Past tense of LEND: To allow to be used by someone temporarily, on condition that it or its equivalent will be returned.
LENDED.e: From earlier len (with excrescent -d, as in sound, round, etc.), from Middle English lenen, lænen, from Old English lǣnan (“to lend; give, grant, lease”), from Proto-West Germanic *laihnijan, from Proto-Germanic *laihnijaną (“to loan”), from Proto-Germanic *laihną (“loan”), from ...

LENGTH.d: The distance measured along the longest dimension of an object.
LENGTH.e: From Middle English lengthe, from Old English lengþ, lengþu, from Proto-West Germanic *langiþu, from Proto-Germanic *langiþō, equivalent to long + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Cognate with Scots lenth, lainth (“length”), Saterland Frisian Loangte (“length”), West Frisian lingte...

LENITE.d: To cause (a consonant) to undergo lenition.

LENITY.e: From Middle French lénité, from Latin lēnitās.

LENSES.d: Plural of LENS: An object, usually made of glass, that focuses or defocuses the light that passes through it.
LENSES.e: Borrowed from Latin lēns (“lentil”), with Medieval Latin later taking on the sense of “lens”, a semantic loan from Arabic عَدْسَة (ʕadsa, “lentil; optic lens”).

LENTIL.d: Any of several plants of the genus Lens, especially Lens culinaris, from southwest Asia, that have edible, lens-shaped seeds within flattened pods.
LENTIL.e: From Middle English lentile, from Old French lentille from Latin lenticula, diminutive of lēns, from a pre-Indo-European substrate source shared by German Linse, Ancient Greek λάθυρος (láthuros) and Lithuanian lęšis. Doublet of lenticula.

LEPTIN.d: A protein hormone produced in adipose tissue; it plays a role in regulating appetite and metabolism.

LEPTON.d: A coin used since ancient times in Greece, serving in modern times as one hundredth of a phoenix, a drachma, and a euro (as the Greek form of the Eurocent).
LEPTON.e: From Ancient Greek λεπτόν (leptón), neuter form of λεπτός (leptós, “small”).

LESION.e: From Middle English lesioun, from Old French lesion, from Latin laesiō (“injury”), itself from laesus, perfect passive participle of laedō (“I injure, hurt”).

LESSEE.d: An individual or a corporation who has the right of use of something of value, gained through a lease agreement with the real owner of the property.
LESSEE.e: From Anglo-Norman lessié, past participle of lessier (“to permit, to let”).

LESSEN.d: To make less; to diminish; to reduce.
LESSEN.e: From Middle English lessenen, lasnen, equivalent to less + -en (verbal suffix).

LESSON.e: From Middle English lessoun, from Old French leçon, from Latin lēctiō, lēctiōnem (“a reading”), from legō (“I read, I gather”). Doublet of lection.

LESSOR.d: The owner of property that is leased; the landlord to a lease.
LESSOR.e: From Middle English lessour, from Anglo-Norman lessour.

LETHAL.d: Of, pertaining to, or causing death; deadly; mortal; fatal.
LETHAL.e: Learned borrowing from Latin lētālis (“deadly, mortal, fatal”), improperly written lēthālis, from lētum (“death”), improperly written as lēthum, from a supposed connection with Ancient Greek λήθη (lḗthē, “oblivion, forgetfulness”).

LETTED.d: Past tense of LET: To allow to, not to prevent (+ infinitive, but usually without to).
LETTED.e:
Derived from Middle English leten, læten, from Old English lǣtan (“to allow, let go, bequeath, leave, rent”), from Proto-West Germanic *lātan, from Proto-Germanic *lētaną (“to leave behind, allow”), from Proto-Indo-European *leh₁d- (“to be tired, leave”).
Cognates
Cognate with Sc...

LETTER.e: From Middle English letter, lettre, from Old French letre, from Latin littera (“letter of the alphabet"; in plural, "epistle”). Displaced Old English bōcstæf (literally “book staff”) in sense 1 and ǣrendġewrit (literally “message writing”) in sense 2.

LEVANT.d: A cultural region of West Asia, consisting of the countries bordering the eastern Mediterranean Sea, namely Syria, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine, Jordan and Cyprus (and sometimes, especially in a historical context, also including Turkey and Egypt, then part of the Ottoman Empire).
LEVANT.e: Borrowed from French levant (“rising, sun's point of rising”), form of lever (“to rise”), from Latin levō (“to rise”) (cf. also the present participle levāns), from levis (“light, not heavy”).

LEVELS.d: Plural of LEVEL: A horizontal plane; a degree.
LEVELS.e: From Old French livel, from Latin libella.

LEVIED.d: Past tense of LEVY: To impose (a tax or fine) to collect monies due, or to confiscate property.
LEVIED.e: From Anglo-Norman leve, from Old French levee, from lever (“to raise”).

LEVIER.d: Comparative form of LEVY: To impose (a tax or fine) to collect monies due, or to confiscate property.
LEVIER.e: From Anglo-Norman leve, from Old French levee, from lever (“to raise”).

LEVIES.d: Plural of LEVY: To impose (a tax or fine) to collect monies due, or to confiscate property.
LEVIES.e: From Anglo-Norman leve, from Old French levee, from lever (“to raise”).

LEVITY.d: A lightness of manner or speech, frivolity; flippancy; a lack of appropriate seriousness; an inclination to make a joke of serious matters.
LEVITY.e: Coined in 1564, from Latin levitās (“lightness, frivolity”), from levis (“lightness (in weight)”). Cognate to lever, and more distantly, light.

LEXEME.d: A lexical item corresponding to the set of all words (or of all multi-word expressions) that are semantically related through inflection of a particular shared basic form.
LEXEME.e: From Latin lexis, from Ancient Greek λέξις (léxis, “word”) + -eme, a suffix indicating a fundamental unit in some aspect of linguistic structure, on the model of phoneme.

LIAISE.e: Back-formation from liaison, itself from French liaison (“binding”).

LIBBED.e: Abbreviation for various words beginning in lib-.

LIBBER.d: One who supports liberation for some group.

LIBERO.d: A central defender to whom no forward is assigned for marking, forming the last line of defence and often initiating the offensive play.
LIBERO.e: From Italian libero (literally “free one”). So called because he has no direct opponent to mark and is therefore free to join in the offensive. The volleyball use is younger.

LIBIDO.e: Learned borrowing from Latin libīdō (“lust, desire”). Used originally in psychoanalytic contexts.

LICHEN.d: Any of many symbiotic organisms, being associations of algae and fungi, often found as white or yellow-to-blue–green patches on rocks, old walls, etc.
LICHEN.e: Borrowed from Latin līchēn, from Ancient Greek λειχήν (leikhḗn), from λείχω (leíkhō, “to lick”). Originally used of liverwort; the modern sense first recorded 1715.

LICKED.d: Past tense of LICK: To stroke with the tongue.
LICKED.e:
From Middle English likken, from Old English liccian, from Proto-West Germanic *likkōn, from Proto-Germanic *likkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyǵʰ- (“to lick”). Sense evolution towards violence unclear; not paralleled in any other Germanic language.
See also Saterland Frisian ...

LICTOR.d: An officer in Ancient Rome, attendant on a consul or magistrate, who bore the fasces and was responsible for punishing criminals.

LIDDED.d: Past tense of LID: The top or cover of a container.
LIDDED.e: Inherited from Middle English lid, lyd, from Old English hlid, from Proto-West Germanic *hlid, from Proto-Germanic *hlidą (compare Dutch lid, German Lid (“eyelid”), Swedish lid (“gate”)), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱlitós (“covered”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱley- (“to cover”).

LIDDER.d: Comparative form of LID: The top or cover of a container.
LIDDER.e: Inherited from Middle English lid, lyd, from Old English hlid, from Proto-West Germanic *hlid, from Proto-Germanic *hlidą (compare Dutch lid, German Lid (“eyelid”), Swedish lid (“gate”)), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱlitós (“covered”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱley- (“to cover”).

LIERNE.d: A cross-shaped rib of an ogival vault.

LIFTED.d: Past tense of LIFT: To raise or rise.
LIFTED.e: From Middle English liften, lyften, from Old Norse lypta (“to lift, air”, literally “to raise in the air”), from Proto-Germanic *luftijaną (“to raise in the air”), related to *luftuz (“roof, air”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *lewp- (“to peel, break off, damage”) or from a r...

LIGAND.d: A molecule or moiety (ion, functional group, or radical) that binds to another chemical entity to form a larger complex; as, especially:
LIGAND.e: Borrowed from Latin ligandus, gerundive of ligo (“bind”).

LIGASE.d: Any of a group of enzymes that catalyze the binding of two molecules; synthetase.

LIGATE.d: To bind with a ligature or bandage.
LIGATE.e: First attested in 1599; borrowed from Latin ligātus, perfect passive participle of ligō (“to bind”), see -ate (verb-forming suffix). Doublet of legato. Compare league.

LIGNIN.d: A complex non-carbohydrate aromatic polymer present in all wood.

LIKELY.d: Probable; having a greater-than-even chance of occurring.
LIKELY.e: From Middle English likely, likly, lykly, likliche, from Old English ġelīclīċ (“suitable”) and Old Norse líkligr (“likely”) (probably independent formations), equivalent to like + -ly (adjectival suffix).

LIKING.d: present participle and gerund of like
LIKING.e: From Middle English likinge, likinde, likende, likande, licande, from Old English līciende, līciġende, from Proto-Germanic *līkāndz, present participle of Proto-Germanic *līkāną, equivalent to like + -ing.

LILIED.d: Past tense of LILY: Any of several flowers in the genus Lilium of the family Liliaceae, which includes a great many ornamental species.
LILIED.e: From Middle English lilie, from Old English lilie, from Latin līlia, plural of līlium, from Ancient Greek λείριον (leírion). See there for more.

LILIES.d: Plural of LILY: Any of several flowers in the genus Lilium of the family Liliaceae, which includes a great many ornamental species.
LILIES.e: From Middle English lilie, from Old English lilie, from Latin līlia, plural of līlium, from Ancient Greek λείριον (leírion). See there for more.

LILTED.d: Past tense of LILT: To do something rhythmically, with animation and quickness, usually of music.

LIMBED.d: Past tense of LIMB: A major appendage of human or animal, used for locomotion (such as an arm, leg or wing).
LIMBED.e:
From Middle English lyme, lim, from Old English lim (“limb, branch”), from Proto-West Germanic *limu, from Proto-Germanic *limuz (“branch, limb”). Cognate with Old Norse limr (“limb”).
The spelling with the silent unetymological -b first arose in the late 1500s. Compare crumb.

LIMBER.e: Unknown; possibly related to limb or limp.

LIMIER.d: Comparative form of LIMY: containing or resembling lime

LIMING.d: Present participle of LIME: Any inorganic material containing calcium, usually calcium oxide (quicklime) or calcium hydroxide (slaked lime).
LIMING.e:
From Middle English lyme, lym, lime, from Old English līm, from Proto-West Germanic *līm, from Proto-Germanic *līmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂leyH- (“to smear”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Liem (“glue”), Dutch lijm, German Leim (“glue”), Danish lim (from Old Norse lím), L...

LIMNED.d: Past tense of LIMN: To draw or paint; to delineate.
LIMNED.e: From Middle English limnen, limyne, lymm, lymn, lymne (“to illuminate (a manuscript)”), a variant of luminen (“to illuminate (a manuscript)”), short form of enluminen (“to shed light on, illuminate; to enlighten; to make bright or clear; to give colour to; to illuminate (a manusc...

LIMPED.d: Past tense of LIMP: To walk lamely, as if favoring one leg.
LIMPED.e:
From Middle English limpen (“to fall short”), from Old English limpan, from Proto-West Germanic *limpan, from Proto-Germanic *limpaną (“to hang down”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)lemb-, *(s)lembʰ- (“to hang loosely, hang limply”).
Cognate with Low German lumpen (“to limp”), Mid...

LIMPET.d: Any of various gastropods with a conical shell shape patelliform and a strong, muscular foot that they use to create strong suction to cling onto rocks or other hard surfaces.
LIMPET.e: From Middle English lempet, from Old English lempedu (“lamprey”), borrowed from Medieval Latin lampreda, alteration of Late Latin lampetra (“lamprey”), whose further origin is unknown, though is traditionally thought to derive from lambō (“I lick, lap”) + petra (“stone, rock”). D...

LIMPID.e: From French limpide, from Latin limpidus.

LINDEN.e: From Middle English linden, from Old English linden (“linden”, adjective), from Proto-Germanic *lindīnaz, from Proto-Germanic *lindō (“linden tree”), equivalent to lind + -en. Cognate with Middle Low German linden (“linden”, adjective), German Low German Linnenboom (“linden-tree”...

LINEAL.d: Pertaining to lines; consisting of lines.
LINEAL.e: From Old French lineal, from Latin līneālis, from līnea (“a line”) + -ālis (adjective-forming suffix). By surface analysis, line + -al. Doublet of linear.

LINEAR.d: Having the form of a line; straight or roughly straight; following a direct course.
LINEAR.e: Borrowed from Latin līneāris, from līnea (“line”) + -āris (adjectival suffix), equivalent to line + -ar. Doublet of lineal.

LINGAM.d: The aniconic phallic representation traditionally worshipped as a symbol of or in connection with Shiva.
LINGAM.e: Learned borrowing from Sanskrit लिङ्गम् (liṅgam, nominative singular of लिङ्ग (liṅga, “sign, mark”)).

LINGER.d: To stay or remain in a place or situation, especially as if unwilling to depart or not easily able to do so.
LINGER.e: From Middle English lengeren, frequentative of lengen (“to stay, dwell, tarry”), from Old English lenġan (“to lengthen, delay, extend”), from Proto-West Germanic *langijan, from Proto-Germanic *langijaną (compare West Frisian lingje (“to linger”), Dutch lengen, German längen, Ice...

LINGUA.e: Unadapted borrowing from Latin lingua (“the tongue”). Doublet of langue and tongue.

LINHAY.d: A shed or other outbuilding, originally open-fronted with a hay loft.

LINIER.d: Comparative form of LINY: Alternative form of liney.

LINING.d: A covering for the inside surface of something.

LINKED.d: Past tense of LINK: A connection between places, people, events, things, or ideas.
LINKED.e: From Middle English linke, lenke, from a merger of Old English hlenċe, hlenċa (“ring; chainlink”) and Old Norse *hlenkr, hlekkr (“ring; chain”); both from Proto-Germanic *hlankiz (“ring; bond; fettle; fetter”). Used in English since the 14th century. Related to lank.

LINNET.d: A small passerine bird, the common linnet (Linaria cannabina, syn. Carduelis cannabina), in the finch family Fringillidae, native to Europe, western Asia, and north Africa.
LINNET.e: From Old French linette, from lin (“flax”), from the bird's fondness for the seeds of flax, the source of linen and Old English līnete, līnetwige (“linnet”) (> dialectal English lintwhite).

LINTEL.d: A horizontal structural beam spanning an opening, such as between the uprights of a door or a window, and which supports the wall above.
LINTEL.e: From Middle English lyntel, from Old French lintel, from Vulgar Latin *līntellus, for *līmitellus, diminutive noun from līmes. Equivalent to limit + -el.

LIPASE.d: Any of a group of enzymes that catalyse the hydrolysis of lipids.
LIPASE.e: Borrowed from French lipase. By surface analysis, lipid + -ase

LIPOMA.d: A nonmalignant tumor comprising fat cells.

LIPPED.d: Past tense of LIP: Either of the two fleshy protrusions around the opening of the mouth.
LIPPED.e:
From Middle English lippe, from Old English lippa, lippe (“lip”), from Proto-West Germanic *lippjō (“lip”), from Proto-Germanic *lepô, from Proto-Indo-European *leb- (“to hang loosely, droop, sag”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Lippe (“lip”), West Frisian lippe (“lip”), Dutch l...

LIPPER.d: Comparative form of LIP: Either of the two fleshy protrusions around the opening of the mouth.
LIPPER.e:
From Middle English lippe, from Old English lippa, lippe (“lip”), from Proto-West Germanic *lippjō (“lip”), from Proto-Germanic *lepô, from Proto-Indo-European *leb- (“to hang loosely, droop, sag”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Lippe (“lip”), West Frisian lippe (“lip”), Dutch l...

LIQUID.d: A substance that is flowing, and keeping no shape, such as water; a substance of which the molecules, while not tending to separate from one another like those of a gas, readily change their relative position, and which therefore retains no definite shape, except that determined by the containing receptacle; an inelastic fluid.
LIQUID.e: From Middle English liquide, from Old French liquide, from Latin liquidus (“fluid, liquid, moist”), from liqueō (“to be liquid, be fluid”). Doublet of liquidus. As a term for a consonant, it comes from Latin liquida (cōnsōnāns), a calque of Ancient Greek ὑγρὸν (σύμφωνον) (hugròn ...

LIQUOR.e: From Middle English licour, from Anglo-Norman licour, from Latin liquor (“fluidity, liquidness, a fluid, a liquid”), from liquere (“to be fluid or liquid”); see liquid. Doublet of liqueur.

LISPED.d: Past tense of LISP: The act or a habit of lisping.
LISPED.e: From Middle English lispen, lipsen, wlispen, from Old English *wlispian (attested in āwlyspian (“to lisp”)), from Old English wlisp, wlips (“stammering, lisping”, adjective), from Proto-Germanic *wlispaz (“lisping”), from Proto-Indo-European *wlis-, *wleys- (“rod”), from *wel- (“...

LISSOM.d: Flexible and graceful in movement; lithe.
LISSOM.e: From Middle English lithsum, equivalent to lithe + -some. Doublet of lithesome.

LISTED.d: Past tense of LIST: A strip of fabric, especially from the edge of a piece of cloth.
LISTED.e: From Middle English lī̆st, lī̆ste (“band, stripe; hem, selvage; border, edge, rim; list, specification; barriers enclosing area for jousting, etc.”), from Old English līste (“hem, edge, strip”), or Old French liste, listre (“border; band; strip of paper; list”), or Medieval Latin...

LISTEN.d: To use one's sense of hearing and auditory cognition in an intentional way; to make deliberate use of one's ears; to pay attention to or wait for a specific sound.
LISTEN.e: From Middle English listenen, listnen, alteration (due to Middle English listen (“to listen, give heed to”)) of Old English hlysnan (“to listen”), from Proto-Germanic *hlusnijaną, *hlusnōną (compare Middle High German lüsenen), from Proto-Germanic *hlusēną (compare Old High Germa...

LITANY.d: A ritual liturgical prayer in which a series of prayers recited by a leader are alternated with responses from the congregation.
LITANY.e: From Middle English, from Old French letanie, from Latin litania, from Ancient Greek λιτανεία (litaneía, “prayer”), from λιτή (litḗ, “prayer, entreaty”).

LITCHI.e: From Chinese 荔枝 (lìzhī). Doublet of lychee.

LITHIA.d: Lithium oxide, Li₂O, used in the manufacture of ceramics and glass.
LITHIA.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek λίθος (líthos, “a stone”), apparently because it is found only in minerals; discovered 1817 by Johan August Arfwedson.

LITMUS.d: A dyestuff extracted from certain lichens, that changes color when exposed to pH levels greater than or less than certain critical levels.
LITMUS.e: From Middle English litmose, lytmose, litemose, from Old Norse litmosi (“moss used for dyeing”), from lita (“to dye, stain”) + mosi (“moss”), the former from litr (“colour, dye, blee”), from Proto-Germanic *wlitiz, *wlituz (“appearance, blee”), from Proto-Indo-European *wel- (“to...

LITTER.d: Straw, grass, and similar loose material used as bedding for people or animals.
LITTER.e: From Middle English litere, lytere, &c., from Anglo-Norman litere, litiere, &c., from Old French litiere (“bedding; bed of loose straw; litter”), from Late Latin lectuāria (“bedding; blankets”), from Latin lectus (“bed; couch”) + -āria (“forming related nouns”), from Proto-Italic...

LITTLE.e:
From Middle English litel, from Old English lyttel, lȳtel, from Proto-West Germanic *lūtil, from Proto-Germanic *lūtilaz (“tending to stoop, crouched, little”), from Proto-Indo-European *lewd- (“to bend, bent, small”), equivalent to lout + -le.
Cognate with Dutch luttel, regional...

LIVELY.e: From Middle English lyvely, lifly, from Old English līflīċ (“living, lively, long-lived, necessary to life, vital”), from Proto-West Germanic *lībalīk (“living, lively”), equivalent to life + -ly. Cognate with Scots lively, lifely (“of or pertaining to life, vital, living, life-l...

LIVERY.d: Any distinctive identifying uniform worn by a group, such as the uniform worn by chauffeurs and male servants.
LIVERY.e: From Middle English livery, liveree, from Anglo-Norman liveree, from Old French livree. Compare modern French livrée.

LIVING.e: From Middle English livynge, libbyng, livinde, livand, livende, libbinde, libbende, from Old English lifiġende, lifiende, libbende, from Proto-West Germanic *libbjandī, from Proto-Germanic *libjandz (“living”), present participle of Proto-Germanic *libjaną (“to live”), equivalent...

LIZARD.d: Any reptile of the order Squamata that is not a snake or part of Mosasauria — typically characterised by a rounded torso, a short neck with an elevated head, four limbs and a long tail, although some species are legless.
LIZARD.e: From Middle English lesarde, lisarde, from Anglo-Norman lusard, from Old French lesard (compare French lézard), from Latin lacertus, which is of obscure origin. Displaced native Middle English aske, from Old English āþexe (> modern English ask, askard).

LOAMED.e: From Middle English lome, lame, lam, from Old English lām (“clay, mud, mire, earth”), from Proto-West Germanic *laim, from Proto-Germanic *laimaz, *laimô (“clay”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂leyH- (“to smear”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Leem (“loam”), West Frisian liem (“lo...

LOANED.e:

LOANEE.d: borrower; someone who is loaned something

LOATHE.d: To detest, hate, or revile (someone or something).
LOATHE.e: From Middle English lothe, from Old English lāþian, from Proto-West Germanic *laiþēn, from Proto-Germanic *laiþāną. Cognate with Old Norse leiðask ( > Danish ledes, Icelandic leiðast, all reflexive), German Leid.

LOBBED.d: Past tense of LOB: To throw or hit a ball into the air in a high arc.
LOBBED.e: First attested late 16th c. in the sense "allow or cause to dangle, hang," from sense 2.

LOBBER.d: Comparative form of LOB: To throw or hit a ball into the air in a high arc.
LOBBER.e: First attested late 16th c. in the sense "allow or cause to dangle, hang," from sense 2.

LOBING.d: Present participle of LOBE: Any projection or division, especially one of a somewhat rounded form.
LOBING.e: From Middle French lobe in early 16th century, from New Latin lobus (“a lobe”), from Ancient Greek λοβός (lobós, “the lobe of the ear or of the liver, the pod of a leguminous plant”).

LOCALE.e: From French local (adj), nominal use of the adjective.

LOCALS.d: Plural of LOCAL: Relating to a particular place.

LOCATE.d: To place; to set in a particular spot or position.
LOCATE.e: Borrowed from Latin locātus, perfect passive participle of locō (“to place”) (see -ate (verb-forming suffix)), from locus (“place”) + -ō (verb-forming suffix). Cognate with French louer; see also local and lieu.

LOCHAN.e: Borrowed from Scottish Gaelic lochan, diminutive of loch (“lake”).

LOCHIA.d: Normal post-partum vaginal discharge; blood, mucus, and placental tissue that are discharged from a female's vagina (similar to menstruation) for several weeks after she has given birth.
LOCHIA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin lochia, from Ancient Greek λοχεία (lokheía), neuter plural of λοχείος (lokheíos, “of childbirth”), from λόχος (lókhos, “childbirth”).

LOCKED.d: Past tense of LOCK: Something used for fastening, which can only be opened with a key or combination.
LOCKED.e:
From Middle English lok, from Old English loc, from Proto-West Germanic *lok, from Proto-Germanic *luką from Proto-Indo-European *lewg- (“to bend; turn”).
Cognate with Cimbrian loch, lòch (“hole”), Dutch lok (“hole”), German Loch (“hole”), German Low German Lock (“hole”), Luxembo...

LOCKET.d: A pendant that opens to reveal a space used for storing a photograph or other small item.
LOCKET.e: From French loquet, from a diminutive of Anglo-Norman loc, itself from Old English loc, whence lock.

LOCOED.d: Past tense of LOCO: A direction in written or printed music to be returning to the proper pitch after having played an octave higher or lower.

LOCUST.d: Any of the grasshoppers, often polyphenic and usually swarming, in the family Acrididae that are very destructive to crops and other vegetation, especially migratory locusts (Locusta migratoria).
LOCUST.e:
From Middle English locuste, locust, from Anglo-Norman locuste, Middle French locuste, and their source, Latin locusta (“locust, crustacean, lobster”). Doublet of langouste.
The tree sense, originally referring to the carob (compare locust bean), is based on the resemblance of th...

LOFTED.d: Past tense of LOFT: air, the air; the sky, the heavens.
LOFTED.e:
From Middle English lofte (“air, sky, upper region, loft”), from Old English loft, (doublet of native Old English lyft) of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse lopt (“upper chamber, attic, region of sky, air”), from Proto-Germanic *luftuz (“air, sky”).

LOGGED.e: From Middle English logge, logg (first recorded in Anglo-Latin as loggum), of uncertain origin, but probably from Old Norse lóg, lág (“felled tree, log”), derived from Old Norse liggja (“to lie”). If so, then cognate with Norwegian låg (“fallen tree”), Dutch loog (“wood, timber, ...

LOGGER.d: Comparative form of LOG: The trunk of a dead tree, cleared of branches.
LOGGER.e: From Middle English logge, logg (first recorded in Anglo-Latin as loggum), of uncertain origin, but probably from Old Norse lóg, lág (“felled tree, log”), derived from Old Norse liggja (“to lie”). If so, then cognate with Norwegian låg (“fallen tree”), Dutch loog (“wood, timber, ...

LOGGIA.d: A roofed, open gallery, usually on an upper level.
LOGGIA.e: Borrowed from Italian loggia, from Old French loge, from Medieval Latin laubĭa, from Frankish *laubijā. Doublet of lobby and lodge.

LOGICS.d: Plural of LOGIC: Reasoning; a system of principles.

LOGION.d: A traditional saying of a religious leader.

LOGJAM.d: An excess of logs being conveyed on a river, so that their motion halts.

LOGOFF.d: The process or an instance of logging off.

LOGOUT.d: The act or process of logging out.

LOINED.d: Past tense of LOIN: The part of the body (of humans and quadrupeds) at each side of the backbone, between the ribs and hips.
LOINED.e: From Middle English loyne, from Old French loigne, from Vulgar Latin *lumbea, from Latin lumbus, of uncertain origin, possibly from Oscan-Umbrian *londwo- or Proto-Germanic *lundwuz, both ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“kidney, waist”). Cognate with Modern English l...

LOITER.d: To stand about without any aim or purpose; to stand about idly.
LOITER.e: From Middle English loitren, from Middle Dutch loteren ("to shake, wag, wobble"; > modern Dutch leuteren (“to dawdle, ramble”)), ultimately connected with a frequentative form of Proto-Germanic *lūtaną (“to bend, stoop, cower, shrink from, decline”), see lout. Cognate with Dutch ...

LOLCAT.d: An image macro of, usually, a kitten or a cat with a humorous caption.

LOLLED.d: Past tense of LOLL: To act lazily or indolently while reclining; to lean; to lie at ease.
LOLLED.e: From Middle English lollen, lullen (“to lounge idly, hang loosely”), of uncertain origin; the Middle English Dictionary suggests a derivation from Middle Dutch lollen, lullen (“to doze; to mumble, talk nonsense”), though the words could merely be cognate. Compare modern Dutch lol...

LOLLOP.d: To walk or move with a bouncing or undulating motion and at an unhurried pace.

LOMENT.d: A type of modified legume that breaks apart at constrictions occurring between the segments of the seeds.

LONELY.d: Unhappy due to feeling isolated from contact with other people.
LONELY.e: From lone + -ly, or from an apheretic shortening of alonely. See lone.

LONGAN.d: An evergreen tree, Dimocarpus longan, of the Sapindaceae family, native to southern China.
LONGAN.e: Borrowed from Cantonese 龍眼 /龙眼 (lung⁴ ngaan⁵, literally “dragon’s eye”). Doublet of Longyan (“grape”).

LOOFAH.d: Any of several tropical vines of the genus Luffa, having almost cylindrical fruit with a spongy, fibrous interior; the dishcloth gourd.

LOOING.d: Present participle of LOO: A lavatory: a room used for urination and defecation.
LOOING.e: Uncertain, although usually derived in some way from Waterloo, the site of Wellington's 1815 victory over Napoleon, likely via a pun based on water closet. Other suggested derivations include corruptions of French l'eau (“water”), lieu (“place”), lieux d'aisances (“'places of con...

LOOKED.d: simple past and past participle of look

LOOKER.d: One that looks or is actively looking; a watcher; an observer.

LOOMED.d: Past tense of LOOM: A utensil; tool; a weapon; (usually in compound) an article in general.
LOOMED.e: From Middle English lome, from Old English *lōma, ġelōma (“tool, utensil, implement, article of furniture, household effect”) (also as andlōma, andġelōma, andlama (“utensil, instrument, implement, tool, vessel”), from Proto-West Germanic *lōmō, *lamō (“tool, utensil”), of uncerta...

LOOSED.d: Past tense of LOOSE: Not firmly fixed; not tight.

LOOTED.d: Past tense of LOOT: Synonym of booty, goods seized from an enemy by violence, particularly (historical) during the sacking of a town in war or (video games) after successful combat.
LOOTED.e: Borrowed from Hindi लूट (lūṭ, “booty”), either from Sanskrit लोप्त्र (loptra, “booty, stolen property”) or लुण्ट् (luṇṭ, “to rob, plunder”). The figurative meaning developed in American English in the 1920s, resulting in a generalized meaning by the 1950s.

LOPING.d: Present participle of LOPE: To travel an easy pace with long strides.
LOPING.e: From Middle English lopen, from Old Norse hlaupa (“to leap, jump”). See leap. Cognate with German laufen (“walk, run”), Danish løbe (“run”), Dutch lopen (“walk, run”), Norwegian løpe (“run”). Doublet of leap.

LOPPED.d: Past tense of LOP: To cut off as the top or extreme part of anything, especially to prune a small limb off a shrub or tree, or sometimes to behead someone.
LOPPED.e: From Middle English loppe (“bough”); the verb is a back-formation from the noun.

LOPPER.d: Comparative form of LOP: To cut off as the top or extreme part of anything, especially to prune a small limb off a shrub or tree, or sometimes to behead someone.
LOPPER.e: From Middle English loppe (“bough”); the verb is a back-formation from the noun.

LOQUAT.d: Any of species Eriobotrya japonica of trees (Japanese medlar, Chinese plum, Japanese plum).
LOQUAT.e: Borrowed from Cantonese 盧橘 /卢橘 (lou⁴ gwat¹).

LORDLY.d: Of or relating to a lord.
LORDLY.e:
From Middle English lordly, lordlich, from Old English hlāfordlīċ (“lordly; heroic; noble”), equivalent to lord + -ly.
The adverb is from Middle English lordly, lordely, lordliche.

LORIES.d: Plural of LORY: Any of various small, brightly coloured parrots native to Australasia. They are usually classified in the subfamily Loriinae.
LORIES.e: From Malay luri, name of kind of parrot, said to be a dialectal variant of Malay nuri. Doublet of lourie. Unrelated to Spanish loro.

LORING.d: Present participle of LORE: All the facts and traditions about a particular subject that have been accumulated over time through education or experience.
LORING.e: From Middle English lore, from Old English lār, from Proto-West Germanic *laiʀu, from Proto-Germanic *laizō, from *laizijaną (“to teach”). Cognate with Dutch leer, German Lehre, Swedish lära and Danish lære. See also learn.

LOSING.d: Present participle of LOSE: To cease to have (something) in one's possession or capability.
LOSING.e: From Middle English losen, from Old English losian, from Proto-West Germanic *losōn, from Proto-Germanic *lusōną, *luzōną, from Proto-Germanic *lusą. The modern pronunciation with /uː/ (instead of the /oʊ~əʊ/ that would be expected from Early Modern /ɔː/) is due to conflation wit...

LOSSES.d: Plural of LOSS: The result of no longer possessing an object, a function, or a characteristic due to external causes or misplacement.
LOSSES.e:
From Middle English los, from Old English los (“damage, destruction, loss”), from Proto-West Germanic *los, from Proto-Germanic *lusą (“dissolution, break-up, loss”), from Proto-Indo-European *lews- (“to cut, sunder, separate, loose, lose”).
Cognate with Icelandic los (“dissoluti...

LOTION.d: A low- to medium-viscosity topical preparation intended for application to unbroken skin.
LOTION.e: From Middle English locion, borrowed from Latin lōtiō, lōtiōnem (“a washing”), from lavō (“to wash”); see lave. Doublet of lavation.

LOTTED.d: Past tense of LOT: A large quantity or number; a great deal.
LOTTED.e:
From Middle English lot, from Old English hlot (“portion, choice, decision”), from Proto-West Germanic *hlut, from Proto-Germanic *hlutą.
Cognate with North Frisian lod, Saterland Frisian Lot, West Frisian lot, Dutch lot, French lot, German Low German Lott, Middle High German luz...

LOTTER.d: Comparative form of LOT: A large quantity or number; a great deal.
LOTTER.e:
From Middle English lot, from Old English hlot (“portion, choice, decision”), from Proto-West Germanic *hlut, from Proto-Germanic *hlutą.
Cognate with North Frisian lod, Saterland Frisian Lot, West Frisian lot, Dutch lot, French lot, German Low German Lott, Middle High German luz...

LOUCHE.d: Of questionable taste or morality; decadent.

LOUNGE.d: To relax; to spend time lazily; to stand, sit, or recline, in an indolent manner.
LOUNGE.e: Origin uncertain. Perhaps from French s'allonger (“to lie down”). Compare French longer (“to walk along”). Compare also German lungern (“to hang or lounge around, linger”).

LOURED.d: Past tense of LOUR: To frown; to look sullen.
LOURED.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English louren, lour, loure (“to frown or scowl; to be dark or overcast; to droop, fade, wither; to lurk, skulk”), probably from Old English *lūran, *lūrian, from Proto-Germanic *lūraną (“to lie in wait, lurk”).
The English word is cognate with Dan...

LOUTED.d: Past tense of LOUT: A troublemaker, often violent; a rude violent person; a yob.
LOUTED.e:
Of dialectal origin, likely derived from Middle English louten (“to bow, bend low, stoop over”), from Old English lūtan (“to bow, bend forward, stoop”), from Proto-West Germanic *lūtan, from Proto-Germanic *lūtaną (“to bow down, lout”).

LOUVRE.d: A famous art museum and former royal palace in Paris, France.
LOUVRE.e: Borrowed from French Louvre. More at Louvre Palace.

LOVELY.d: Delightful for beauty, harmony, or grace.
LOVELY.e: From Middle English lovely, luvelich, lufli, from Old English luflīċ, luflīc (“amiable, loving, lovable”), equivalent to love + -ly.

LOVING.d: Present participle of LOVE: A deep caring for the existence of another.
LOVING.e:
From Middle English love, luve, from Old English lufu, from Proto-West Germanic *lubu, from Proto-Germanic *lubō, from Proto-Indo-European *lewbʰ- (“love, care, desire”).
The close of a letter sense is presumably a truncation of With love or the like.

LOWERS.d: Plural of LOWER: Less high; to move down.

LUBBER.e: From Middle English, perhaps from Old French lobeor (“swindler”), or of Scandinavian origin, compare dialectal Swedish lubber. The grasshopper was likely so called after sense 1 (“a clumsy or lazy person”).

LUCENT.e: From Latin lūcentem, the present participle of lūcēre (“to shine”).

LUCKED.d: Past tense of LUCK: Something that happens to someone by chance, a chance occurrence.
LUCKED.e: From Middle English luk, lukke, related to Old Frisian luk (“luck”), West Frisian gelok (“luck”), Saterland Frisian Gluk (“luck”), Dutch geluk (“luck, happiness”), Low German luk (“luck”), German Glück (“luck, good fortune, happiness”), Danish lykke (“luck”), Swedish lycka (“luck...

LUGGED.e: From Middle English luggen, possibly from Scandinavian source, (compare Swedish lugga, Norwegian lugge); also in English dialectal as lig (“to lug”). Noun is via Scots lugge, probably from Old Norse (compare Norwegian and Swedish lugg). Probably related to slug (“lazy, slow-movin...

LUGGER.d: Comparative form of LUG: The act of hauling or dragging.

LUGING.d: Present participle of LUGE: A racing sled for one or two people that is ridden with the rider or riders lying on their back.
LUGING.e: The noun is borrowed from Swiss French or Franco-Provençal luge, from Medieval Latin scludia, from Late Latin sclodia, of Celtic origin, from Gaulish *stludio, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *sleydʰ- (“to slide, slip; to be slick or slippery”). If so, it is related to sled and...

LULLED.d: Past tense of LULL: A period of rest or soothing.
LULLED.e:
From Middle English lullen, lollen. Originally, perhaps expressive in origin from la-la-la or lu-lu-lu sounds made in calming a child. Compare Finnish laulaa (“to sing”) and Hiligaynon lala (“to sing a lullaby”).
Cognate with Scots lul, lule, loll (“to lull, put to sleep, howl, c...

LUMBAR.d: Related to the lower back or loin, specifically the five vertebrae between the rib cage and the pelvis.
LUMBAR.e: From Latin lumbāris, from lumbus (“loin”) + -āris. See loin.

LUMBER.d: Wood sawn into planks or otherwise prepared for sale or use, especially as a building material.
LUMBER.e: Exact origin unknown. The earliest recorded reference for the noun was to heavy, useless objects such as old, discarded furniture. Perhaps from the verb lumber in reference to meaning "awkward to move"; Online Etymological Dictionary thinks this may derive from the same root as l...

LUMMOX.d: A clumsy, stupid person; an awkward bungler.
LUMMOX.e: Unknown. First attested in 1825 in East Anglian slang. Perhaps from "dumb ox", influenced by lumbering; or from or cognate to dialectal verb lummock (“move about heavily or clumsily”), itself a word of uncertain origin.

LUMPED.d: Past tense of LUMP: Something that protrudes, sticks out, or sticks together; a cluster or blob; a mound or mass of no particular shape.
LUMPED.e: From Middle English lumpe, from a Germanic base akin to Proto-Germanic *limpaną (“to glide, go, hang loosely”). Compare Dutch lomp (“rag”), German Low German Lump (“rag”), German Lumpen (“rag”) and Lump (“ragamuffin”).

LUNACY.d: The state of being mad, insanity

LUNATE.e: First attested in 1777; borrowed from Latin lūnātus (“crescent-shaped”), from lūna (“moon”), see -ate (adjective-forming suffix).

LURING.d: Present participle of LURE: Something that tempts or attracts, especially one with a promise of reward or pleasure.
LURING.e: From Anglo-Norman lure, from Old French loirre (Modern French leurre), from Frankish *lōþr, from Proto-Germanic *lōþr-, perhaps ultimately related to *laþō (“invitation, calling”), or from Proto-Indo-European *leh₂- (“to hide”). Compare English allure, also from Old French. Proba...

LURKED.d: Past tense of LURK: To remain concealed in order to ambush.
LURKED.e:
From Middle English lurken, from Old Norse *lúrka, possibly from Proto-Germanic *lūrukōną (“to be lying in wait, lurk”), equivalent to lour + -k (frequentative suffix).
Cognate with Norwegian Nynorsk lurka (“to sneak away, go slowly”), dialectal Swedish lurka (“to dawdle, be slow...

LUSHED.e:
From Middle English lusch (“slack, relaxed, limp, loose”), from Old English *lysċ, lesċ (“slack; limp”), from Proto-West Germanic *laskw, from Proto-Germanic *laskwaz (“weak, false, feeble”), from Proto-Indo-European *lēy- (“to let; leave behind”).
