LUSHES.e:
From Middle English lusch (“slack, relaxed, limp, loose”), from Old English *lysċ, lesċ (“slack; limp”), from Proto-West Germanic *laskw, from Proto-Germanic *laskwaz (“weak, false, feeble”), from Proto-Indo-European *lēy- (“to let; leave behind”).
Akin to Old English lysu, lesu ...

LUSTED.d: Past tense of LUST: A feeling of strong desire, especially such a feeling driven by sexual arousal.
LUSTED.e:
From Middle English lust, from Old English lust (“lust, pleasure, longing”), from Proto-West Germanic *lustu, from Proto-Germanic *lustuz.
Akin to Old Saxon, Dutch lust, Old Frisian, Old High German, German Lust, Swedish lust, Danish lyst, Icelandic lyst, Old Norse losti, Gothic ...

LUSTRE.d: British standard spelling of luster (shine, etc.).
LUSTRE.e: From Middle French lustre. See luster (etymology 1).

LUTEIN.d: A yellow carotenoid pigment, widely distributed in both plants and animals.

LUTING.d: present participle and gerund of lute

LUXATE.e: From Latin luxātus (“dislocated”) perfect passive participle of lū̆xō (“to dislocate”), see -ate (verb-forming suffix) for more.

LUXURY.d: Very wealthy and comfortable surroundings; the state of being that they create.
LUXURY.e: From Middle English luxurie, from Old French luxurie, from Latin luxuria (“rankness, luxury”), from luxus (“extravagance, luxury”).

LYCEUM.d: A public hall designed for lectures, readings, or concerts.
LYCEUM.e: From Latin Lyceum, from Ancient Greek Λύκειον (Lúkeion) (the name of a gymnasium, or athletic training facility, near Athens where Aristotle established his school), from Λύκειος, from Proto-Greek *λύκη), "light." The meaning of the epithet "Lyceus" later became associated with A...

LYCHEE.d: The Chinese tropical fruit tree Litchi chinensis, of the soapberry family.
LYCHEE.e: From Cantonese 荔枝 (lai⁶ zi¹). Doublet of litchi.

LYNXES.d: Plural of LYNX: Any of several medium-sized wild cats of the genus Lynx.
LYNXES.e:
From Middle English lynx, linx, lenx, lynce, from Latin lynx, from Ancient Greek λύγξ (lúnx), from Proto-Hellenic *lúnks, from Proto-Indo-European *lewk- (“white; light; bright”), because of the cat's glowing eyes and ability to see in the dark.
Displaced English los; Middle Engl...

LYSINE.d: An amino acid, C₆H₁₄N₂O₂, in L- or D-forms.
LYSINE.e: From lysis + -ine, in reference to its tendency to participate in catalysis.

MACHAN.d: A kind of safety platform in a tree, used when hunting large animals or to escape a flood; found most commonly in Indian jungles.

MACING.d: Present participle of MACE: A heavy fighting club.
MACING.e: From Middle English mace, borrowed from Old French mace, mache, from Vulgar Latin *mattia, *mattea, matia, (compare Italian mazza, Spanish maza), probably from Proto-West Germanic *mattjō (“cutting tool, hoe”).

MACRON.d: A short, straight, horizontal diacritical mark (◌̄) placed over a letter, usually to indicate that the pronunciation of a vowel is long.
MACRON.e: From Ancient Greek μακρόν (makrón), neuter form of μακρός (makrós, “long”) (English macro-).

MACULA.d: An oval yellow spot near the center of the retina of the human eye, histologically defined as having two or more layers of ganglion cells, responsible for detailed central vision.
MACULA.e: From Middle English macula (“spot on the skin or in the eye”), borrowed from Latin macula (“spot, stain”). Doublet of macchia and macule.

MADAME.e: Borrowed from French madame, from Old French ma dame (“my lady”). Doublet of madam and Madonna.

MADCAP.d: A person who acts in a capricious, impulsive, or reckless manner.
MADCAP.e: The noun is derived from mad + cap (“(informal) head”). The adjective is from an attributive use of the noun.

MADDED.d: Past tense of MAD: Insane; crazy, mentally deranged.
MADDED.e: From Middle English mad, madde, madd, medd, from Old English ġemǣd, ġemǣded (“enraged”), past participle of ġemǣdan, *mǣdan (“to make insane or foolish”), from Proto-Germanic *maidijaną (“to change; damage; cripple; injure; make mad”), from Proto-Germanic *maidaz ("weak; crippled...

MADDER.d: Comparative form of MAD: Insane; crazy, mentally deranged.
MADDER.e: From Middle English mad, madde, madd, medd, from Old English ġemǣd, ġemǣded (“enraged”), past participle of ġemǣdan, *mǣdan (“to make insane or foolish”), from Proto-Germanic *maidijaną (“to change; damage; cripple; injure; make mad”), from Proto-Germanic *maidaz ("weak; crippled...

MADMAN.d: A man who is insane or mentally disturbed.

MADRAS.d: Former name of Chennai: the capital and largest city of Tamil Nadu, India.
MADRAS.e: The etymology is uncertain; it may derive from Madraspattinam. See Wikipedia for several possible etymologies.

MAENAD.d: A female follower of Dionysus (“the god of wine”), associated with intense revelling.
MAENAD.e: From Late Middle English *menadyen (attested in the plural form menadyens) + English -ad (suffix forming names of nymphs). *Menadyen is derived from Latin maenad-, a stem of maenās (“follower of Bacchus, bacchant”), from Ancient Greek μαινάς (mainás, “frantic; raving”), from μαίν...

MAGGED.d: Past tense of MAG: Clipping of magazine.

MAGGOT.d: A soft, legless larva of a fly or other dipterous insect, that often eats decomposing organic matter.
MAGGOT.e: From Middle English magot, magat, maked, probably a metathetic alteration of maddock, maðek (“worm", "maggot”), originally a diminutive form of a base represented by Old English maþa (Scots mathe), from Proto-West Germanic *maþō, from Proto-Germanic *maþô, from the Proto-Indo-Eur...

MAGICS.d: Plural of MAGIC: The power of apparently influencing events by supernatural means.
MAGICS.e: From Old French magique, from Latin magicus.

MAGNET.d: A piece of material that attracts some metals by magnetism.
MAGNET.e: From Middle English magnete, via Old French magnete, Latin magnēs, magnētem (“lodestone”), from Ancient Greek μαγνῆτις [λίθος] (magnêtis [líthos], “Magnesian [stone]”), either after the Lydian city Magnesia ad Sipylum (modern-day Manisa, Turkey), or after the Greek region of Μαγν...

MAGNON.d: A quantum of a spin wave.

MAGNUM.d: A bottle containing 1.5 liters of fluid, double the volume of a standard wine bottle.
MAGNUM.e:
From Latin magnum, neuter of magnus (“great”).
* (bottle): Ellipsis of magnum bonum.
* (handgun): Name registered 1935 by Smith & Wesson Inc., of Springfield, Massachusetts.

MAGPIE.d: One of several kinds of bird in the family Corvidae, especially Pica pica.
MAGPIE.e: From Mag, a nickname for Margaret that was used to denote a chatterer, + archaic pie (“magpie”), from Old French pie, from Latin pīca, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)peyk- (“woodpecker, magpie”). Displaced native Old English agu, "magpie".

MAHOUT.d: An elephant trainer, keeper, and driver.
MAHOUT.e:
PIE word
 *méǵh₂s
The noun is borrowed from Hindustani (Hindi महौत (mahaut)/Urdu مَہَوت (mahaut)), महाउत (mahāut), variants of महावत (mahāvat)/مَہاوَت (mahāvat), from Sanskrit महामात्र (mahāmātra, “elephant keeper; high official; king’s minister”), from महा (mahā, “great”) (ultim...

MAIDAN.d: A marketplace or other open space in or by a city or town; an esplanade.
MAIDAN.e: From Hindustani میدان (medān) / मैदान (maidān), and its source, Persian میدان (meydân, maydān, “town-square or central place of gathering”), from Arabic مَيْدَان (maydān), itself an Iranian borrowing (see the Arabic entry for more), from Proto-Iranian *madyānah, from *mádyah (“mi...

MAIDEN.d: A girl or an unmarried young woman.
MAIDEN.e: From Middle English mayden, meiden, from Old English mæġden (“girl”), originally a diminutive of mæġeþ (“girl”) via diminutive suffix -en, from Proto-West Germanic *magaþ, from Proto-Germanic *magaþs. Equivalent to maid + -en.

MAIMED.d: Past tense of MAIM: To wound seriously; to cause permanent loss of function of a limb or part of the body.
MAIMED.e: From Middle English maymen, mahaymen, from Anglo-Norman maheimer, mahaigner, of Germanic origin; see mayhem.

MAKERS.d: Plural of MAKER: A person or thing that makes.

MAKEUP.e: Deverbal from make up. Sense 2 is a semantic loan from French maquillage, from maquiller (“to make up, fabricate”).

MAKING.d: The act of forming, causing, or constituting; workmanship; construction.
MAKING.e: From Middle English making, from Old English macung (“making”), equivalent to make + -ing. Cognate with dated Dutch making (“making”), Old High German machunga.

MALADY.d: Any ailment or disease of the body; especially, a lingering or deep-seated disorder.
MALADY.e: From Middle English maladie, from Old French maladie (“sickness, illness, disease”), from malade (“ill, sick”), from Latin male habitus (“ill-kept, not in good condition”), 1st century AD. See also malice and habit.

MALATE.d: Any salt or ester of malic acid.

MALICE.d: Intention to harm or deprive in an illegal or immoral way. Desire to take pleasure in another's misfortune.#
MALICE.e: From Middle English malice, borrowed from Old French malice, from Latin malitia (“badness, bad quality, ill-will, spite”), from malus (“bad”).

MALIGN.d: Evil or malignant in disposition, nature, intent or influence.
MALIGN.e: From Middle English maligne, from Old French maligne, from Latin malignus, from malus (“bad”) + genus (“sort, kind”). Compare benign.

MALIST.d: One who subscribes to the theory of malism; someone who thinks the world is inherently evil.

MALLEE.d: A type of scrubland with low-growing thick eucalypts, characteristic of certain parts of Australia.
MALLEE.e: Probably borrowed from Wemba-Wemba mali; compare Woiwurrung mali.

MALLET.d: A type of hammer with a larger-than-usual head made of wood, rubber or similar non-iron material, used by woodworkers for driving a tool, such as a chisel. A kind of maul.
MALLET.e: From Middle English malet, maylet, from Old French mallet, maillet (“a wooden hammer, mallet”), diminutive of mal, mail (“a hammer”), from Latin malleus (“a hammer, mall, mallet”).

MALLOW.d: Any of a group of flowering plants in several genera of the taxonomic family Malvaceae, especially of the genus Malva. Several species are edible by humans.
MALLOW.e: From Middle English malwe, from Old English mealwe, borrowed from Latin malva. Compare the doublet mauve.

MALTED.d: Past tense of MALT: Malted grain (sprouted grain) (usually barley), used in brewing and otherwise.
MALTED.e:
From Middle English malt, from Old English mealt, from Proto-West Germanic *malt, from Proto-Germanic *maltą (“malt”), from *maltaz (“soft; nesh; weak; squashy; melting”), from Proto-Indo-European *meld-, *mled- (“to crush; grind; make weak”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Moalt...

MAMMAL.d: An animal of the class Mammalia.
MAMMAL.e: From Modern Latin Mammalia, coined 1758 by Linnaeus for the class of mammals, from neuter plural of Late Latin mammalis (“of the breast”), from Latin mamma (“breast”), perhaps cognate with mamma (mother).

MAMMON.d: The desire for wealth personified as an evil spirit or a malign influence.
MAMMON.e: From Late Latin mammona (“wealth”), from Hellenistic Ancient Greek μαμωνᾶς (mamōnâs), from Aramaic מָמוֹנָא (māmōnā, “money, wealth”). Compare Hebrew מָמוֹן (mamón, “money”).

MANAGE.d: To direct or be in charge of.
MANAGE.e: From Early Modern English manage, menage, from Middle English *manage, *menage, from Old French manege (“the handling or training of a horse, horsemanship, riding, maneuvers, proceedings”), probably from Old Italian maneggiare (“to handle, manage, touch, treat”), ultimately from ...

MANGEL.e:
* As a German surname, variant of Mangold.
* As a Jewish surname, from German Mangel (“scarcity, lacking, need”).
* As an English surname, variant of Mangnall, from Mankinholes in Lancashire, usually said to be from the Irish name Manchán (compare manach (“monk”)) + Old English h...

MANGLE.d: To change, mutilate, or disfigure by cutting, tearing, rearranging, etc.
MANGLE.e:
From Middle English mangelen, manglen, from Anglo-Norman mangler, mahangler, frequentative of either Old French mangonner (“to cut to pieces”) or mahaigner (“to mutilate”), of Germanic origin, for which see mayhem.
Alternate etymology derives mangle from Middle English *mankelen,...

MANIAC.d: An insane person, especially one who suffers from a mania.
MANIAC.e: From mania + -ac. Borrowed from French maniaque, from Late Latin maniacus, from Ancient Greek μανιακός (maniakós), adjectival form of μανία (manía, “madness”). Compare manic.

MANIOC.d: The tropical plant Manihot esculenta, from which tapioca is prepared; cassava, yuca.
MANIOC.e: From French manioc, through Portuguese mandioca, ultimately from Old Tupi mani'oka.

MANNED.d: Operated by, performed by, or transporting a person; crewed; piloted; staffed.

MANNER.d: Mode of action; way of performing or doing anything.
MANNER.e: From Middle English maner, manere, from Anglo-Norman manere, from Old French maniere, from Vulgar Latin *manāria, from feminine of Latin manuarius (“belonging to the hand”), from manus (“hand”). Compare French manière, Italian mannaia (“ax, axe”), Portuguese maneira and maneiro (...

MANTIS.d: Any of various large insects of the order Mantodea that catch insects or other small animals with their powerful forelegs.
MANTIS.e: From New Latin mantis, from Ancient Greek μάντις (mántis, “soothsayer”). Distant doublet of mind via Proto-Indo-European *méntis.

MANTLE.d: A piece of clothing somewhat like an open robe or cloak, especially that worn by Orthodox bishops.
MANTLE.e: From Middle English mantel, from Old English mæntel, mentel (“sleeveless cloak”), from Proto-West Germanic *mantel; later reinforced by Anglo-Norman mantel, both from Latin mantellum (“covering, cloak”) (French manteau), diminutive of mantum (Spanish manto), probably from Gaulish...

MANTRA.d: The hymn portions of the Vedas; any passage of these used as a prayer.
MANTRA.e: Borrowed from Sanskrit मन्त्र (mantra), from Proto-Indo-Iranian *mántras, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *men- (“to think”). Related to mind.

MANUAL.e: From Middle English manuel, from Old French manuel, from Late Latin manuāle (“handbook, manual”).

MANUKA.d: Leptospermum scoparium, a shrub or small tree native to New Zealand and southeast Australia.

MANURE.d: To cultivate by manual labor; to till; hence, to develop by culture.
MANURE.e: From Middle English maynouren, manuren (“to supervise, toil”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman meinourer and Old French manovrer (whence also English maneuver, or in French manœuvrer) from Vulgar Latin *manuoperare (“work by hand”), from Latin manū (“by hand”) + operārī (“to work”).

MAPPED.d: Past tense of MAP: A visual representation of an area, whether real or imaginary, showing the relative positions of places and other features.
MAPPED.e: Shortening or back-formation of Middle English mappemounde, mapemounde (“world map”), from Old French mapamonde, from Medieval Latin mappa mundī, compound of Latin mappa (“napkin, cloth”) and mundus (“world”). See mop for more on the first component. Doublet of mop, nape, and nap...

MAPPER.d: Comparative form of MAP: A visual representation of an area, whether real or imaginary, showing the relative positions of places and other features.
MAPPER.e: Shortening or back-formation of Middle English mappemounde, mapemounde (“world map”), from Old French mapamonde, from Medieval Latin mappa mundī, compound of Latin mappa (“napkin, cloth”) and mundus (“world”). See mop for more on the first component. Doublet of mop, nape, and nap...

MAQUIS.e: Borrowed from French maquis, from Corsican machja (related to Italian macchia), ultimately from Latin macula. Doublet of macula.

MARACA.d: A Latin American percussion instrument consisting of a hollow-gourd rattle containing pebbles or beans and often played in pairs, as a rhythm instrument.
MARACA.e: From Brazilian Portuguese maraca, derived from Old Tupi maraká or Guaraní mbaraká (“rattle”).

MARAUD.d: To move about in roving fashion looking for plunder; to loiter.
MARAUD.e: From French marauder, derivative of maraud (“rogue, vagabond”), from Middle French maraud (“rascal”), from Old French *marault (“beggar, vagabond”), from marir, marrir (“to trouble, stray, lose ones way, be lost”), from Frankish *marʀijan (“to neglect, hinder”), from Proto-German...

MARBLE.d: A metamorphic rock of crystalline limestone.
MARBLE.e: Inherited from Middle English marble, marbre; from Anglo-Norman and Old French marbre, from Latin marmor, from Ancient Greek μάρμαρος (mármaros), perhaps related to μαρμάρεος (marmáreos, “gleaming”). The forms from French displaced Old English marma, which had previously been bor...

MARCEL.d: A hairstyle characterized by deep waves made by a curling iron.
MARCEL.e: Apparently from the French name Marcel, but accounts vary regarding who invented the style.

MARGAY.d: Leopardus wiedii, a spotted cat native to Central and South America.
MARGAY.e: From Old Tupi marakaîá via Spanish margay, Portuguese maracajá.

MARGIN.d: The edge of the paper, typically left blank when printing but sometimes used for annotations etc.
MARGIN.e: From Middle English margyn, from Latin marginem (possibly via Old French margin), accusative of margō (“edge, brink, border, margin”). Doublet of marge and margo.

MARINA.e: From Latin marinus (“of the sea, marine”), by way of Italian marina and Spanish marina.

MARINE.d: Belonging to or characteristic of the sea; existing or found in the sea; formed or produced by the sea.
MARINE.e: Recorded since c.1420 as Middle English marin, borrowed from Middle French marin, from Old French, from Latin marinus (“of the sea”), itself from mare (“sea”), from Proto-Indo-European *móri (“body of water, lake”) (cognate with Old English mere (“sea, lake, pool, pond”), Dutch m...

MARKED.d: Past tense of MARK: Boundary, land within a boundary.
MARKED.e: From Middle English mark, merk, merke, from Old English mearc (“mark, sign, line of division; standard; boundary, limit, term, border; defined area, district, province”), from Proto-West Germanic *marku, from Proto-Germanic *markō (“boundary; boundary marker”), from Proto-Indo-Eu...

MARKET.d: A gathering of people for the purchase and sale of merchandise, often periodic at a set time.
MARKET.e: From Middle English market, from late Old English market (“market”) and Anglo-Norman markiet (Old French marchié); all ultimately from Latin mercātus (“trade, market”), from mercor (“I trade, deal in, buy”), itself derived from merx (“wares, merchandise”). Cognate with West Frisi...

MARKKA.d: A (Finnish) mark, the currency used in Finland before the introduction of the euro, consisting of 100 penni. Abbreviation FIM.
MARKKA.e: Borrowed from Finnish markka, from a Germanic language, likely German Mark. Doublet of mark.

MARKUP.d: The percentage or amount by which a seller hikes up his buy-in price when determining his selling price.

MARLED.d: Past tense of MARL: A mixed earthy substance, consisting of carbonate of lime, clay, and possibly sand, in very variable proportions, and accordingly designated as calcareous, clayey, or sandy.
MARLED.e: From Middle English marle, from Old French marle, from Late Latin margila, diminutive of marga (“marl”). Doublet of marla.

MARLIN.d: Any species of game fish belonging to either of the genera Tetrapturus or Makaira, with a crested dorsal fin and a pointed, spear-like projection of the upper jaw.
MARLIN.e: A contraction of marlinspike, named so because of its pointed snout.

MARMOT.d: Any of several large ground-dwelling rodents of the genera Marmota and Cynomys in the squirrel family.
MARMOT.e: From Middle French marmote, from Old French marmotaine, marmontaine, murmontain, from Old Franco-Provençal marmotan, from Vulgar Latin *mures montani, the plural form of Latin mus monti (“mountain rat”); akin to Engadin Romansch murmont, Old High German muremunto (dialectal Germa...

MAROON.d: An escaped black slave of the Caribbean and the Americas or a descendant of such a person.
MAROON.e: From French marron (“feral; fugitive”, adjective), from Spanish cimarrón (“fugitive, wild, feral”); see that entry for more.

MARQUE.d: A brand of a manufactured product, especially of a motor car.
MARQUE.e: Borrowed from French marque. Doublet of mark. Ultimately cognate with marquee.

MARRED.d: Past tense of MAR: To spoil; to ruin; to scathe; to damage.
MARRED.e: Inherited from Middle English merren, from Old English mierran (“to mar, disturb, confuse; scatter, squander, waste; upset, hinder, obstruct; err”), from Proto-Germanic *marzijaną (“to disturb, hinder”), from Proto-Indo-European *mers- (“to annoy, disturb, neglect, forget, ignore...

MARRER.d: Comparative form of MAR: To spoil; to ruin; to scathe; to damage.
MARRER.e: Inherited from Middle English merren, from Old English mierran (“to mar, disturb, confuse; scatter, squander, waste; upset, hinder, obstruct; err”), from Proto-Germanic *marzijaną (“to disturb, hinder”), from Proto-Indo-European *mers- (“to annoy, disturb, neglect, forget, ignore...

MARRON.e: Variant form of maroon (“chestnut”), later reinforced by French marron.

MARROW.d: The substance inside bones which produces blood cells.
MARROW.e: From Middle English mary, marow, marwe, marowȝ, from Old English mearg, from Proto-West Germanic *maʀg, from Proto-Germanic *mazgą, *mazgaz, from Proto-Indo-European *mosgʰos. Compare West Frisian moarch, Dutch merg, German Mark, Swedish märg, Icelandic mergur, and also Russian м...

MARSHY.d: Of, or resembling a marsh; boggy.
MARSHY.e: From Middle English mersshy, mershi, equivalent to marsh + -y.

MARTED.d: Past tense of MART: A shop, a store, a market.
MARTED.e: From Middle Dutch mart, markt (“market”) (Modern Dutch markt), from Old Dutch *markat, from Late Latin marcātus, an alternative form of Classical Latin mercātus. See market.

MARTEN.d: Any carnivorous mammal of the genus Martes.
MARTEN.e: From Middle English martren, martryn, from Old French martrine (“marten fur”), from Old Dutch *marthrīn (“of marten fur”), from *marthar (“marten”). Displaced related Old English mearþ, from Proto-Germanic *marþuz.

MARTIN.d: Many of the various passerine birds of the family Hirundinidae, which also includes swallows, that catch insects whilst flying.

MARTYR.d: One who willingly accepts being put to death or willingly accepts challenging and exposing iniquity done to oneself for adhering openly to one's religious beliefs; notably, saints canonized after red martyrdom.
MARTYR.e: From Middle English martir, from Old English martyr, itself a borrowing from Ecclesiastical Latin martyr, from Ancient Greek μάρτυρ (mártur), later form of μάρτυς (mártus, “witness”).

MARVEL.d: That which causes wonder; a prodigy; a portent.
MARVEL.e: First attested from 1300, from Middle English merveile, from Old French merveille (“a wonder”), from Vulgar Latin *miribilia, from Latin mīrābilia (“wonderful things”), from neuter plural of mīrābilis (“strange, wonderful”), from mīror (“I wonder at”), from mīrus (“wonderful”). D...

MASALA.d: Any of many blends of spices used in Indian cuisine, most often containing cardamom, coriander, mace together with pepper, nutmeg, fennel seeds, jeera etc.
MASALA.e: Borrowed from Hindustani مصالحہ (maṣālḥa, maṣāliḥa) / मसाला (masālā, “spice(s)”), from Classical Persian مصالح (masālih, “affairs, materials, spices”), plural of مصلحت (maslahat, “affair, policy, best thing to do”), both from Arabic, derived from صَلَحَ (ṣalaḥa, “be fit, competen...

MASCLE.d: A lozenge-shaped piece of metal, used in making scale mail.
MASCLE.e: From Middle English mascle, maskel, from Old French mascle, macle, from Medieval Latin mascula, from a Germanic source (compare English mesh). Doublet of mail.

MASCON.d: A region within a solid astronomical body that is of higher density than the surrounding material.

MASCOT.d: Something thought to bring good luck.
MASCOT.e: Borrowed from French mascotte, from Occitan mascòta (“sortilege”), feminine diminutive of masca (“witch”), from Old Occitan masca, from Medieval Latin masca (“specter, nightmare”). More at mask.

MASHED.d: Past tense of MASH: A mass of mixed ingredients reduced to a soft pulpy state by beating or pressure; a mass of anything in a soft pulpy state.
MASHED.e: From Middle English mash, from Old English mǣsċ, māsċ, māx, from Proto-Germanic *maiskaz, *maiskō (“mixture, mash”), from Proto-Indo-European *meyǵ-, *meyḱ- (“to mix”). Akin to German Meisch, Maische (“mash”), (compare meischen, maischen (“to mash, wash”)), Swedish mäsk (“mash”),...

MASHES.d: Plural of MASH: A mass of mixed ingredients reduced to a soft pulpy state by beating or pressure; a mass of anything in a soft pulpy state.
MASHES.e: From Middle English mash, from Old English mǣsċ, māsċ, māx, from Proto-Germanic *maiskaz, *maiskō (“mixture, mash”), from Proto-Indo-European *meyǵ-, *meyḱ- (“to mix”). Akin to German Meisch, Maische (“mash”), (compare meischen, maischen (“to mash, wash”)), Swedish mäsk (“mash”),...

MASHIE.d: A metal-headed golf club with a moderate loft, the equivalent of a five iron in a modern set of clubs.

MASJID.e: Borrowed from Arabic مَسْجِد (masjid), from the root س ج د (s j d). Doublet of mosque.

MASKED.d: Past tense of MASK: A cover, or partial cover, for the face, used for disguise or protection.
MASKED.e: Borrowed from Middle French masque (“a covering to hide or protect the face”), from Italian maschera (“mask, disguise”), from (a byform of, see it for more) Medieval Latin masca, mascha, a borrowing of Proto-West Germanic *maskā, from which English mesh and mask (“mesh”) (below a...

MASQUE.d: A dramatic performance, often performed at court as a royal entertainment, consisting of dancing, dialogue, pantomime and song.
MASQUE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French masque. Doublet of mask and mesh.

MASSED.d: Past tense of MAS: A country cottage or farmstead in Occitan-speaking territories.
MASSED.e: From French mas, Occitan mas. Doublet of manse.

MASSER.d: Comparative form of MAS: A country cottage or farmstead in Occitan-speaking territories.
MASSER.e: From French mas, Occitan mas. Doublet of manse.

MASSES.e: In late Middle English (circa 1400) as masse in the sense of "lump, quantity of matter", from Anglo-Norman masse, in Old French attested from the 11th century, via late Latin massa (“lump, dough”), from Ancient Greek μᾶζα (mâza, “barley-cake, lump (of dough)”). The Greek noun may...

MASSIF.e: Borrowed from French massif, from Middle French massif, ultimately from Latin massa, from Ancient Greek μᾶζα (mâza, “barley-cake, lump (of dough)”).

MASTED.d: Past tense of MAST: A tall, slim post or tower, usually tapering upward, used to support, for example, sails or observation platforms on a ship, the main rotor of a helicopter, flags, floodlights, meteorological instruments, or communications equipment, such as an aerial, usually supported by guy-wires (except in the case of a helicopter).
MASTED.e:
From Middle English mast, from Old English mæst (“mast”), from Proto-West Germanic *mast, from Proto-Germanic *mastaz (“mast, sail-pole”), from Proto-Indo-European *mazdos (“pole, mast”).
Cognate with Dutch mast, German Mast, and via Indo-European with Latin mālus, Russian мост (...

MASTER.d: Someone who has control over something or someone.
MASTER.e: From Middle English maister, mayster, meister (noun) and maistren (verb), from Old English mǣster, mæġster, mæġester, mæġister, magister (“master”), from Latin magister (“chief, teacher, leader”), from Old Latin magester, from Proto-Indo-European *méǵh₂s (as in magnus (“great”), ...

MASTIC.d: An evergreen shrub or small tree, Pistacia lentiscus (mastic tree), native to the Mediterranean.
MASTIC.e: From Middle English mastik, from Old French mastic, from Latin mastiche, from Ancient Greek μαστίχη (mastíkhē), from μαστιχάω (mastikháō, “I chew”) (note the chewing gum sense). Related to masticate. The broad sense for cements came via extension from predecessor cements made wit...

MATICO.d: A Peruvian plant (Piper aduncum) allied to the pepper, whose leaves are used as a styptic and astringent.

MATIES.d: Plural of MATY: A native house servant in India.

MATING.d: Fitting into or onto a corresponding part, as a matched plug and socket.

MATRIX.d: The cavity or mold in which anything is formed.
MATRIX.e:
From Middle English matris, matrice, matrix, from Old French matrice (“pregnant animal”), or from Latin mātrīx (“dam, womb”), both ultimately from māter (“mother”). Doublet of mother from Indo-European ancestor.
Slang usage coined with the 1999 sci-fi action film The Matrix.

MATRON.d: A mature or elderly woman, especially one of a higher social rank.
MATRON.e: From Middle English matrone, from Old French matrone, from Latin mātrōna (“married woman”), from māter (“mother”). Doublet of matrona.

MATTED.d: Past tense of MAT: A flat piece of coarse material used for wiping one’s feet, or as a decorative or protective floor covering.
MATTED.e: Inherited from Middle English matte, from Old English meatte, from Late Latin matta, from Punic or Phoenician (compare Hebrew מיטה \ מִטָּה (mitá, “bed, couch”)).

MATTER.e: From Middle English matere, mater, from Anglo-Norman matere, materie, from Old French materie, matiere, from Latin materia (“wood”), from mater (“mother”), in which case cognate with Old Armenian մայր (mayr, “cedar”) and մայրի (mayri, “forest”). Doublet of Madeira, mata, mater, m...

MATURE.d: Fully developed; grown up in terms of physical appearance, behaviour or thinking; ripe.
MATURE.e: From late Middle English mature, from Middle French mature, from Latin mātūrus. Doublet of maduro. Partially displaced ripe, from Old English rīpe (“ripe, mature”).

MAULED.d: Past tense of MAUL: A heavy long-handled hammer, used for splitting logs by driving a wedge into them, or in combat.
MAULED.e: From Middle English malle (“mace, maul”), from Anglo-Norman mail, from Old French mail, from Latin malleus (“hammer”). Doublet of malleus.

MAWING.d: Present participle of MAW: The stomach, especially of an animal.
MAWING.e:
From Middle English mawe, maghe, maȝe, from Old English maga (“stomach; maw”), from Proto-West Germanic *magō, from Proto-Germanic *magô (“belly; stomach”), from Proto-Indo-European *mak-, *maks- (“bag, bellows, belly”).
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian mage, Dutch maag (“stoma...

MAXIMA.d: A music note typically equal to two longae (eight semibreves).
MAXIMA.e: From Latin maxima (“greatest”). Doublet of maxim.

MAYDAY.d: An international distress signal used by shipping and aircraft.
MAYDAY.e: From the distress signal mayday, from French m'aider, short for Venez m'aider! (“Come to help me!”).

MAYFLY.d: Any of the many fragile insects of the order Ephemeroptera that develop in fresh water and live very briefly as winged adults.
MAYFLY.e: From May + fly. Compare Saterland Frisian Moaifljooge (“blowfly”).

MAYHEM.d: A state or situation of great confusion, disorder, trouble or destruction; chaos.
MAYHEM.e: From Middle English mayme, mahaime, from Anglo-Norman mahaim (“mutilation”), from Old French meshaing (“bodily harm, loss of limb”), from Proto-Germanic *maidijaną (“to cripple, injure”) (compare Middle High German meidem, meiden (“gelding”), Old Norse meiða (“to injure”), Gothic...

MAYING.d: Present participle of MAY: To be strong; to have power (over).
MAYING.e:
From Middle English mowen, mayen, moȝen, maȝen, from Old English magan, from Proto-West Germanic *magan, from Proto-Germanic *maganą, from Proto-Indo-European *megʰ-.
Cognate with Dutch mag (“may”, first- and third-person singular of mogen (“to be able to, be allowed to, may”)), ...

MAYORS.d: Plural of MAYOR: The head of a city government.
MAYORS.e: From Old French maire, from Latin māior.

MAZARD.e: Probably from mazer, the head being compared to a large goblet.

MAZIER.d: Comparative form of MAZY: Mazelike; like a maze.

MAZING.d: Present participle of MAZE: A labyrinth; a puzzle consisting of a complicated network of paths or passages, the aim of which is to find one's way through.
MAZING.e: From Middle English mase, from Middle English masen (“to perplex, bewilder”); or perhaps from Old English *mæs (“delusion, bewilderment”); akin to Old English āmasian (“to perplex, confound”), Icelandic masa (“to chatter”). More at amaze.

MEADOW.d: A field or pasture; a piece of land covered or cultivated with grass, usually intended to be mown for hay.
MEADOW.e:
From Middle English medowe, medewe, medwe (also mede > Modern English mead), from Old English mǣdwe, inflected form of mǣd (see mead), from Proto-Germanic *mēdwō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂met- (“to mow, reap”), enlargement of *h₂meh₁-.
See also West Frisian miede, dialectal Du...

MEAGRE.d: An edible fish, of species Argyrosomus regius, of the family Sciaenidae, found from the Black Sea to the eastern Atlantic.

MEALED.d: Past tense of MEAL: Food that is prepared and eaten, usually at a specific time, and usually in a comparatively large quantity (as opposed to a snack).
MEALED.e:
From Middle English mel, from Old English mǣl (“measure, time, occasion, set time, time for eating, meal”), from Proto-West Germanic *māl, from Proto-Germanic *mēlą, from Proto-Indo-European *meh₁- (“to measure”).
Cognate with West Frisian miel, Dutch maal (“meal, time, occurrenc...

MEANED.d: Past tense of MEAN: To intend.
MEANED.e: From Middle English menen (“to intend; remember; lament; comfort”), from Old English mǣnan (“to mean, complain”), Proto-West Germanic *mainijan, from Proto-Germanic *mainijaną (“to mean, think; complain”), from Proto-Indo-European *meyn- (“to think”), or perhaps from Proto-Indo-E...

MEANIE.d: A mean (unkind or miserly) person; a killjoy.

MEASLY.d: Particularly of pigs or pork: infected with larval tapeworms or trichinae (parasitic roundworms).
MEASLY.e: From measle (“singular of measles”) + -y; the word measle is either from Middle Dutch masel (“a blister filled with blood; a pustule, a skin blemish”), or Middle Low German masel (“a red skin blemish”), from Proto-Germanic *masuraz (“a knot or scar in wood; a knarl”), from *mas-,...

MEATED.d: Past tense of MEAT: The flesh (muscle tissue) of an animal used as food, or a food designed to replicate its taste and texture (like plant-based meat).
MEATED.e: From Middle English mete, from Old English mete (“food”), from Proto-West Germanic *mati, from Proto-Germanic *matiz (“food”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to drip, ooze; grease, fat”). Cognate with West Frisian mete, Old Saxon meti, Old High German maz (“food”), Icelandic ...

MEATUS.d: A tubular opening or passage leading to the interior of the body.
MEATUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin meātus (“a going, passing; a way, path, passage”).

MEDDLE.d: To interfere in or with; to concern oneself with unduly.
MEDDLE.e: From Middle English medlen, from Anglo-Norman medler, from Early Medieval Latin misculāre, derived from Latin misceō (“to mix”).

MEDIAL.d: Of or pertaining to a mean or average.
MEDIAL.e: Borrowed from Latin mediālis (“middle”), from medius (“that is in the middle or midst”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix).

MEDIAN.d: A central vein or nerve, especially the median vein or median nerve running through the forearm and arm.
MEDIAN.e: Borrowed from Middle French median, from Latin mediānus (“of or pertaining to the middle”, adjective), from medius (“middle”) (see medium), from Proto-Indo-European *médʰyos (“middle”). Doublet of mean and mizzen. Cognate with Old English midde, middel (“middle”). More at middle.

MEDIAS.d: Plural of MEDIA: Means of mass communication.

MEDICK.d: Any of various European and North African herbs, of the genus Medicago, several of which are grown for fodder etc.
MEDICK.e: From Middle English medike, from Latin mēdica, from Ancient Greek μηδίκη (mēdíkē), short for Μηδικὴ πόα (Mēdikḕ póa, “Median grass”); so called because medick was imported from Media to Greece during the Greco-Persian Wars.

MEDICO.d: A physician or medical doctor; sometimes also a medical student.

MEDIUM.d: The material of the surrounding environment, e.g. solid, liquid, gas, vacuum, or a specific substance such as a solvent.
MEDIUM.e: Borrowed from Latin medium, neuter of medius (“middle”), from Proto-Italic *meðjos, from Proto-Indo-European *médʰyos (“between”). Compare middle. Doublet of mid, medio, media, and meson.

MEDLAR.d: Mespilus germanica, common medlar (now often Crataegus germanica).
MEDLAR.e: From Middle English medler, medeler, from Old French medler, meslier, from medle, mesdle (“medlar fruit”), from Latin mespilum, from Ancient Greek μέσπιλον (méspilon). Related to the rare mesple, via Proto-West Germanic *mespilā. Displaced Old English openærs (“open-arse”) (and s...

MEDLEY.e: From Middle English medle, from Anglo-Norman medlee, Old French medlee, from the feminine past participle of early Medieval Latin misculō (“to mix”). Compare meddle. Doublet of melee.

MEDUSA.d: The youngest and only mortal of the three gorgon sisters, killed by Perseus.
MEDUSA.e: From Middle English Medusa, Meduse, from Latin Medūsa, from Ancient Greek Μέδουσα (Médousa), from μέδω (médō, “rule over”).

MEGILP.d: A mixture of linseed oil with turpentine or mastic varnish, used as a thickener for oil paints but later discredited as a source of cracking and yellowing.

MEGRIM.e: Borrowed from Middle French migraigne, semi-learned borrowing from Late Latin hēmicrānia (“pain in one half of the head”), from Ancient Greek ἡμικρᾱνίᾰ (hēmikrāníă), from ἡμι- (hēmi-, “hemi-, half”) + κρανίον (kraníon, “skull”) (whence also English cranium). Doublet of migraine a...

MEINIE.e: From Middle English meine, meyne, from Anglo-Norman maigne and Old French mesnie (“household”), from Vulgar Latin *mānsiōnāta, from Latin mānsiō, mānsiōnem (“house”). Compare menial.

MELDED.d: Past tense of MELD: To combine (multiple things) together; to blend, to fuse.
MELDED.e:
The verb is probably derived:
* from a blend of melt + weld; or
* from melled (“blended; mingled”), the past participle of mell.
The noun is derived from the verb.
Compare also melting pot.

MELLOW.d: Soft or tender by reason of ripeness; having a tender pulp.
MELLOW.e:
The adjective is derived from Late Middle English melowe, melwe (“ripe, mellow; juicy; sweet”) [and other forms]; further etymology uncertain, possibly:
* from an attributive use of melow, melowe, melewe, mele (“meal from ground grain or legumes; flour; kernel of barley or lentil...

MELODY.d: A sequence of notes that makes up a musical phrase.
MELODY.e: From Middle English melodie, melodye, from Old French melodie, from Latin melodia, from Ancient Greek μελῳδίᾱ (melōidíā, “singing, chanting”), from μέλος (mélos, “musical phrase”) + ἀοιδή (aoidḗ, “song”), contracted form ᾠδή (ōidḗ).

MELTED.d: Past tense of MELT: To change (or to be changed) from a solid state to a liquid state, usually by a gradual heat.
MELTED.e: From Middle English melten, from a merger of Old English meltan (intransitive) and mieltan (transitive), both meaning “to melt, digest,” from Proto-West Germanic *meltan and *maltijan, from Proto-Germanic *meltaną and *maltijaną, both from Proto-Indo-European *(s)meld- (“melt”). ...

MELTON.d: A tough, short-napped material used for making overcoats.
MELTON.e: From Melton Mowbray, where this material was made.

MEMBER.d: One who belongs to a group.
MEMBER.e:
From Middle English membre, from Old French membre, from Latin membrum (“limb, body part”), from Proto-Italic *memzrom, from Proto-Indo-European *mḗms, *mēms-rom (“flesh”). Akin to Gothic 𐌼𐌹𐌼𐌶 (mimz, “meat, flesh”), Crimean Gothic menus.
Coexists with native Middle English lim, l...

MEMOIR.d: An autobiography; a book describing the personal experiences of an author.
MEMOIR.e: From French mémoire (“memoir”), from Latin memoria (“memory”). Doublet of memoria and memory.

MEMORY.d: The ability of the brain to record information or impressions with the facility of recalling them later, usually at will.
MEMORY.e: From Anglo-Norman memorie, Old French memoire etc., from Latin memoria (“the faculty of remembering, remembrance, memory, a historical account”), from memor (“mindful, remembering”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)mer- (to remember), related to Ancient Greek μνήμη (mnḗmē, “memory”)...

MENACE.e: From Middle English manace, from Old French manace, menace, &c., from Late Latin minācia (“threat, menace”), from Latin mināx (“threatening”) + -ia (suffix forming abstract nouns).

MENHIR.d: A single tall standing stone as a monument, especially one dating to prehistoric times.
MENHIR.e:

 *méǵh₂s
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *méǵh₂sder.?
Proto-Celtic *maginos
Proto-Brythonic *maɣɨnder.

Proto-Celtic *sīros
Proto-Brythonic *hirder.

Breton maen-hirbor.
French menhirbor.
Englis...

MENIAL.d: Of or relating to work normally performed by a servant.
MENIAL.e: From Middle English meyneal, from Anglo-Norman mesnal, from maisnee (“household”), from Vulgar Latin *mānsiōnāta, from Latin mānsiō (“house”).

MENINX.d: A membrane, especially one of the three membranes lining the skull and vertebral canal and enclosing the brain and spinal cord in vertebrates.
MENINX.e: Borrowed from New Latin mēninx, from Ancient Greek μῆνῐγξ (mênĭnx, “membrane of the eye; membrane enclosing the brain; eardrum”).

MENSES.d: The discharge of blood and cellular tissue that flows from the inner lining of the uterus out through the vagina, occurring typically once a month in uninseminated women; a menstrual flow.
MENSES.e: From Latin mēnsis (“month”), the plural being mēnsēs (“months”), corresponding to the monthly courses of women. Compare month.

MENTAL.d: Of or relating to the mind or specifically the total emotional and intellectual response of an individual to external reality.
MENTAL.e: Borrowing from Middle French mental, from Late Latin mentālis, from mēns (“mind, disposition; heart, soul”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix).

MENTEE.d: A person who is being mentored.
MENTEE.e: Back-formation from mentor. Although mentor comes from Ancient Greek Μέντωρ (Méntōr), the name of a mythological figure, it was mistakenly analyzed as terminating in the suffix -or (“doer”), leading to a form using the French patientive suffix -ee on the model of pairs such as do...

MENTOR.d: A wise and trusted counselor or teacher.
MENTOR.e: From French mentor, from Ancient Greek Μέντωρ (Méntōr, “Mentor”), a mythological character in the Odyssey, whose name, a historical name from Ancient Greece, shares the same root as English mind. Cognate to Sanskrit मन्तृ (mantṛ, “advisor, counselor”) and Latin monitor (“one who ...

MEOWED.d: Past tense of MEOW: Used to indicate the cry of a cat.
MEOWED.e:
Alteration of earlier mew, from Middle English mewen, mouwen (“to mew, meow”), of onomatopoeic origin.
Compare Saterland Frisian mauje, miauje (“to meow”), West Frisian miaukje (“to meow”), Dutch miauwen (“to meow”), Middle Low German mauwen, mawen, mouwen (“to meow”) (whence mod...

MERCER.d: A merchant dealing in fabrics and textiles, especially silks and other fine cloths.
MERCER.e: From Anglo-Norman marcer, mercer (“merchant, textile merchant”), from merz (“commodity”) (from Latin merx).

MERGEE.d: One who or that which undergoes a merge.

MERINO.d: A sheep of a Spanish breed with long, fine hair.

MERLIN.d: A small falcon, Falco columbarius, that breeds in northern North America, Europe, and Asia.
MERLIN.e: From Middle English merlioun, merlion, marlyon, merlyon, merlinge, from Old French emerillon, esmerillon, from Old Frankish *smiril (“falcon, hawk”), from Proto-Germanic *smirilaz (“falcon, merlin”). Cognate with Old High German smirl (“falcon”), Old Norse smyrill (“falcon”).

MERLON.d: Any of the upright projections between the embrasures of a battlement, originally for archers to shield behind while shooting arrows over the embrasures, or through loopholes in the merlons.
MERLON.e: Borrowed from French merlon, from Italian merlone (“merlon”), from merlo (“merlon”) + -one (suffix forming augmentatives). Merlo is derived from Late Latin merulus, merlus, possibly from Latin merula (“blackbird”) (as merlons resemble a row of birds perched on a wall), from Proto...

MERMAN.d: A legendary creature, human male from the waist up, fishlike from the waist down.
MERMAN.e: From Middle English mereman, from Old English *meremann (“merman”) (suggested by Old English meremenn, meremennen, meremenin (“mermaid, siren”)), equivalent to mer- + man. Cognate with Dutch meerman (“merman”), German Meermann (“merman”).

MERROW.d: A merman or mermaid in Scottish and Irish Gaelic folklore.

MESCAL.d: A Mexican alcoholic drink distilled from the fermented juice of the agave.
MESCAL.e: From Mexican Spanish mezcal, from Nahuatl or Classical Nahuatl mexcalli (“intoxicating drink made from fermented agave juice”), perhaps from metl (“maguey (agave)”) + ixcalli (“stew”).

MESHED.d: Past tense of MESH: A structure made of connected strands of metal, fiber, or other flexible/ductile material, with evenly spaced openings between them.
MESHED.e:
From Middle English mesche, from Old English masc (“net”) (perhaps influenced in form by related Old English mæscre (“mesh, spot”)), from the related Proto-Germanic *maskwǭ and *maskrǭ respectively, from Proto-Indo-European *mezg- (“to knit, twist, plait”).
Akin to Old High Germa...

MESHES.d: Plural of MESH: A structure made of connected strands of metal, fiber, or other flexible/ductile material, with evenly spaced openings between them.
MESHES.e:
From Middle English mesche, from Old English masc (“net”) (perhaps influenced in form by related Old English mæscre (“mesh, spot”)), from the related Proto-Germanic *maskwǭ and *maskrǭ respectively, from Proto-Indo-European *mezg- (“to knit, twist, plait”).
Akin to Old High Germa...

MESIAL.d: Pertaining to the midline of the body.
MESIAL.e: Irregular derivation from Ancient Greek μέσος (mésos).

MESSED.d: Past tense of MES: plural of me

MESSER.d: Comparative form of MES: plural of me

MESSES.d: Plural of MESS: a thing or group of things in a disagreeable, disorganised, or dirty state; hence a bad situation
MESSES.e: Perhaps a corruption of Middle English mesh (“mash”), compare muss, or derived from Etymology 2 "mixed foods, as for animals". Compare also Old English mes (“dung, excrement”).

METALS.d: Plural of METAL: A solid material that conducts heat and electricity.
METALS.e: From Old French metal, from Latin metallum.

METEOR.d: An atmospheric or meteorological phenomenon. These were sometimes classified as aerial or airy meteors (winds), aqueous or watery meteors (hydrometeors: clouds, rain, snow, hail, dew, frost), luminous meteors (rainbows and aurora), and igneous or fiery meteors (lightning and shooting stars).
METEOR.e: From Middle French météore, from Old French, from Latin meteorum, from Ancient Greek μετέωρον (metéōron), from μετέωρος (metéōros, “raised from the ground, hanging, lofty”), from μετά (metá, “in the midst of, among, between”) (English meta) + ἀείρω (aeírō, “to lift, to heave, to ...

METHOD.d: A process by which a task is completed; a way of doing something (followed by the adposition of, to or for before the purpose of the process).
METHOD.e: From Middle French methode, from Latin methodus, from Ancient Greek μέθοδος (méthodos).

METHYL.d: The univalent hydrocarbon radical, CH₃-, formally derived from methane by the loss of a hydrogen atom; a compound or part of a compound formed by the attachment of such a radical.
METHYL.e:
Borrowed from German Methyl; compare French méthyle.
French chemists Jean-Baptiste Dumas and Eugene Peligot, after determining methanol's chemical structure, introduced "methylene" from the Ancient Greek μέθυ (méthu, “wine”) + ὕλη (húlē, “wood, material”) with the intention of hi...

METING.d: Present participle of METE: To dispense, measure in order to dispense, allot (especially punishment, reward etc.).
METING.e:
From Middle English meten, from Old English metan (“to measure, mete out, mark off, compare, estimate; pass over, traverse”), from Proto-West Germanic *metan, from Proto-Germanic *metaną (“to measure”), from Proto-Indo-European *med- (“to measure, consider”).
Cognate with Scots m...

METOPE.d: The architectural element between two triglyphs in a Doric frieze.
METOPE.e: From Latin metopa and its source, Koine Greek μετόπη (metópē), from μετά (metá, “between”) + ὀπή (opḗ, “hole”).

METRIC.d: Of or relating to the metric system of measurement.
METRIC.e: From French métrique (1864), from New Latin metricus (“pertaining to the system based on the meter”), from metrum (“a meter”); see meter. By surface analysis, metre + -ic.

METTLE.d: A quality of courage and endurance.
METTLE.e: From figurative use of metal (since 16th century). The two spellings were originally interchangeable variants, but came to be distinguished by sense in the 18th century.

MEWING.d: Present participle of MEW: A gull, seagull.
MEWING.e: From Middle English mewe, mowe, meau, from Old English mǣw (“seagull”), from Proto-West Germanic *maiwī, from Proto-Germanic *mai(h)waz (“seagull”). See also West Frisian meau, miuw, Dutch meeuw, German Möwe (whence Polish mewa); akin to Latvian maût (“to roar”), Old Church Slavo...

MEWLED.d: Past tense of MEWL: To cry weakly with a soft, high-pitched sound; to whimper; to whine.
MEWLED.e: From 1599 or earlier (1530 in a Scottish document), apparently from Shakespeare with this spelling. Perhaps from Middle English mewen (“to whimper”) + -le (frequentative suffix).

MIASMA.d: A noxious atmosphere or emanation once thought to originate from swamps and waste, and to cause disease.
MIASMA.e: First attested in 1665. From Ancient Greek μίασμα (míasma, “stain; pollution”).

MICKEY.d: A small bottle of liquor, holding 375 ml or 13 oz., typically shaped to fit in one's pocket.
MICKEY.e:
* (potato): From the common Irish name; compare murphy (“a potato”).
* (computer mouse resolution): An allusion to the cartoon character Mickey Mouse.

MICKLE.e: From Middle English mickle, michel, mikel, mochel, muchel, mukel (“much; many; large, tall; great”), from Old English miċel, myċel (“big, large; great; much”), from Proto-Germanic *mikilaz (“great, large; many, much”), from Proto-Indo-European *méǵh₂s (“big, great”). The word is ...

MICRON.d: Synonym of micrometre (“one-millionth of a metre”).
MICRON.e: From French micron, from Ancient Greek μικρόν (mikrón), neuter of μικρός (mikrós, “small”).

MIDDAY.d: Noon; twelve o'clock during the day.
MIDDAY.e: From Middle English midday, from Old English middæġ (“midday, noon”), equivalent to mid- + day. Cognate with Scots midday (“midday”), West Frisian middei (“midday, noon, afternoon”), Dutch middag (“midday, noon, afternoon”), German Mittag (“noon, midday, late morning, early after...

MIDDEN.e: From Middle English midding, myddyng, from Old Danish mykdyngja, (a compound of Old Norse myk, myki (“muck, manure”) and dyngja (“dung, dungpile”)), whence also Danish møgdynge and mødding, Norwegian mødding, dialectal Swedish mödding.

MIDDLE.e: From Middle English middel, from Old English middel (“middle, centre, waist”), from Proto-Germanic *midlą, *midilą, *medalą (“middle”), a diminutive of Proto-Germanic *midjō (“middle, midst”) (compare *midjaz (“mid, middle”, adjective)), from Proto-Indo-European *médʰyos (“betwee...

MIDGET.d: A very small thing; especially one which is conspicuously smaller than expected or by comparison.
MIDGET.e: From midge (chiefly in the figurative sense of “small thing”, literally “small fly”) + -et (diminutive suffix), (from Old English myċġ (“mosquito”), from Proto-Germanic *mugjō, from Proto-Indo-European *mus-, *mu-, *mew-; cognate with Dutch mug (“mosquito”) and German Mücke (“mid...

MIDRIB.d: The strengthened vein down the middle of a flower petal or simple leaf or leaflet.

MIELIE.e: From Afrikaans mielie, from Portuguese milho.

MIFFED.d: Past tense of MIFF: A small argument; a quarrel.
MIFFED.e: Compare German muffeln (“grouse, grumble”) and similar German words with similar meanings such as Muff, mupf, Muffel and Dutch moppen (“growl, grouse”). Probably related to mop (“grimace”).

MIGHTS.d: Plural of MIGHT: Power; past tense of may.

MIGHTY.d: A warrior of great strength and courage.
MIGHTY.e:
From Middle English mighty, mightie, mighti, myghty, miȝty, maȝty, from Old English mihtiġ, mehtiġ, meahtiġ, mæhtiġ (“mighty”), from Proto-West Germanic *mahtīg (“mighty”), from Proto-Germanic *mahtīgaz (“mighty”), equivalent to might + -y.
Cognate with Scots michty, mychty, Sate...

MIGNON.d: Small and cute; pretty in a delicate way; dainty.
MIGNON.e: From French mignon, from Middle French mignon (“lover, darling, favourite”), from Old French mignon (“dainty, pleasing, gentle, kind”), from Frankish *minnjo (“love, friendship, affection, memory”), from Proto-Germanic *minþijō, *mindijō (“affectionate thought, care”), from Proto...

MIHRAB.d: A niche in a mosque that indicates the qibla (direction of Mecca), and into which the imam prays.

MIKADO.d: A former title of the emperors of Japan during a certain period.
MIKADO.e: Borrowed from Japanese 御門 (mikado), from 御 (mi, “honorable”) + 門 (kado, “gate, portal”).

MIKING.d: Present participle of MIKE: A microphone.
MIKING.e: Alteration of mic, clipping of microphone. Attested since 1927.

MILADY.d: An English noblewoman or gentlewoman; the form of address to such a person; a lady.
MILADY.e: Partly representing a colloquial pronunciation of my + lady, partly from French milady, from English my Lady. Compare milord.

MILDEW.d: A growth of minute powdery or webby fungi, whitish or of different colors, found on various diseased or decaying substances.
MILDEW.e: From Middle English myldew, from Old English meledēaw, mildēaw, from Proto-West Germanic *milidauw, from *mili (“honey”) + *dauw (“dew”). Compare West Frisian moaldau, Dutch meeldauw, German Mehltau. More at dew.

MILIEU.d: An environment or setting; a medium; environs
MILIEU.e:
PIE word
 *me
Borrowed from French milieu (“physical or social environment; group of people with a common point of view”), from Middle French milieu, meilleu, mileu, from Old French milliu, meillieu, mileu (“middle”), from mi- (prefix meaning ‘half’) (from Latin medius (“half; mi...

MILKED.d: Past tense of MILK: A white liquid produced by the mammary glands of female mammals to nourish their young. From certain animals, especially cows, it is also called dairy milk and is a common food for humans as a beverage or used to produce various dairy products such as butter, cheese, and yogurt.
MILKED.e:
From Middle English milk, mylk, melk, mulc, from Old English meolc, meoluc (“milk”), from Proto-West Germanic *meluk, from Proto-Germanic *meluks, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂melǵ-.
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian molke, Dutch melk, Dutch Low Saxon melk, German Milch, German L...

MILLET.d: Any of a group of various types of grass or its grains used as food, widely cultivated in the developing world.
MILLET.e: From late Middle English, borrowed from Middle French millet; from Latin milium, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *melh₂- (“to grind, crush”), see also Ancient Greek μελίνη (melínē, “millet”) and Lithuanian málnos (“millet”). Not related to مِلَّة (milla).

MILORD.d: An English nobleman, especially one traveling Europe in grand style; a wealthy British gentleman.
MILORD.e: From French milord, from English my Lord. Compare milady.

MILTED.d: Past tense of MILT: The spleen, especially of an animal bred for food.
MILTED.e: From Middle English milte, from Old English milte, milt (“milt, spleen”), from Proto-West Germanic *miltijā, *meltā, from Proto-Germanic *meltǭ (“spleen”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)meld- (“to beat, grind, crush, weaken”). Cognate with German Milz, Dutch milt, Danish milt, Nor...

MIMBAR.d: A pulpit in a mosque from which the leader of prayers delivers the khutbah.
MIMBAR.e: From Classical Arabic مِنْبَر (minbar), from نَبَرَ (nabara, “raise”).

MIMING.d: Present participle of MIME: A form of acting without words; pantomime.
MIMING.e: Possibly from Middle English *mime, from Old English mīma (“a buffoon, jester, mime”), from Latin mimus, from Ancient Greek μῖμος (mîmos, “imitator, actor”), but more likely re-borrowed in modern times from French mime (“mimic actor”), from the same source.

MIMOSA.d: A plant belonging to the genus Mimosa usually found in tropical climates, their leaves are usually prickly and sensitive to touch or light, and have small white or pink flowers.
MIMOSA.e: From New Latin mimosa, from Latin mimus (“mime, actor”), referring to Mimosa pudica and its habit of shrinking back when touched. The cocktail is named after the bright yellow, fragrant flowers of the mimosa Acacia dealbata.

MINBAR.d: A pulpit in a mosque, usually shaped like a small tower, where the imam stands to deliver sermons.

MINDED.d: Past tense of MIND: The capability for rational thought.
MINDED.e: From Middle English minde, munde, imynde, imunde, ȝemynde, ȝemunde, from Old English mynd, ġemynd (“mind, memory”), from Proto-West Germanic *mundi, *gamundi, from Proto-Germanic *mundiz, *gamundiz (“memory, remembrance”), from Proto-Indo-European *méntis (“thought”) (compare als...

MINDER.d: One who minds, tends, or watches something such as a child, a machine, or cattle; a keeper.
MINDER.e: From Middle English mynder, mendowre (“one who has a good memory; bears in mind; watches over; a keeper”); equivalent to mind + -er.

MINGLE.d: To intermix; to combine or join, as an individual or part, with other parts, but commonly so as to be distinguishable in the product.
MINGLE.e: From earlier mingil, mengle, from Middle English menglen, equivalent to ming + -le. Cognate with Dutch mengelen (“to mingle, mix”), German mengen (“to mingle, mix”). More at ming.

MINIMA.e: Learned borrowing from Latin minima, nominative neuter plural form of minimus (“least, smallest”).

MINING.d: The activity of removing solid valuables from the earth.

MINION.d: A loyal servant of another, usually a more powerful being.
MINION.e: 1490, from Middle French mignon (“lover, royal favourite, darling”), from Old French mignon (“dainty, pleasing, gentle, kind”), from Frankish *minnju (“love, friendship, affection, memory”), from Proto-Germanic *minþijō, *mindijō (“affectionate thought, care”), from Proto-Indo-Eu...

MINIUM.d: Cinnabar, especially when used as a pigment; vermilion.

MINNOW.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English menew, menowe (“small fish; (specifically) common minnow (Phoxinus phoxinus); or stickleback (possibly the three-spined stickleback, Gasterosteus aculeatus)”), from Old English *mynwe, an oblique form of *mynu, a variant of myne (“minn...

MINORS.d: Plural of MINOR: Lesser in importance; a person under legal age.

MINTED.d: Past tense of MINT: A building or institution where money (originally, only coins) is produced under government licence.
MINTED.e: From Middle English mynt, münet (“money, coin”), from Old English mynet (“coin”), from late Proto-West Germanic *munit, from Latin monēta (“place for making coins, coined money”), from the temple of Juno Moneta (named for Monēta mother of the Muses), where coins were made. Double...

MINUET.d: A slow graceful dance consisting of a coupé, a high step, and a balance.
MINUET.e: From French menuet, from menu (“small”) + -et (“diminutive”), from Latin minutus (“very small”).

MINUTE.d: A unit of time which is one sixtieth of an hour (sixty seconds).
MINUTE.e: From Middle English mynute, minute, mynet, from Old French minute, from Medieval Latin minūta (“60th of an hour; note”). Doublet of menu and menudo.

MINXES.d: Plural of MINX: A flirtatious, impudent, or pert young woman.
MINXES.e:
PIE word
 *ǵʰmṓ
The origin of the noun is uncertain. The following possible derivations have been suggested:
* A variation of minikin (“(obsolete) young person, especially a young woman; small or insignificant person, thing, or amount”) + a variation of -s (suffix forming hypocor...

MINYAN.d: The minimum number of ten (male) adult Jews required for a communal religious service.

MIRAGE.d: An optical phenomenon in which light is refracted through a layer of hot air close to the ground, often giving the illusion of a body of water.
MIRAGE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French mirage c. 1812.

MIRIER.d: Comparative form of MIRY: Resembling or characteristic of a mire; swampy, boggy.
MIRIER.e: From Middle English myry, equivalent to mire + -y.

MIRING.d: Present participle of MIRE: Deep mud; moist, spongy earth.
MIRING.e: From Middle English mire, a borrowing from Old Norse mýrr, from Proto-Germanic *miuzijō, whence also Swedish myr, Norwegian myr, Icelandic mýri, Dutch *mier (in placenames, for example Mierlo). Related to Proto-Germanic *meusą, whence Old English mēos, and Proto-Germanic *musą, w...

MIRROR.d: A smooth surface, usually made of glass with reflective material painted on the underside, that reflects light so as to give an image of what is in front of it.
MIRROR.e: From Middle English mirour, from Old French mireor (“mirror”, literally “looker, watcher”), from mirer (“look at”), from Latin mīror (“wonder at”), from mīrus (“wonderful”), from Proto-Indo-European *smey- (“to laugh, to be glad”). Displaced native Middle English schewere, schawe...

MISERY.d: Great unhappiness; extreme pain of body or mind; wretchedness; distress; woe.
MISERY.e: From Middle English miserie, from Old French miserie (modern: misère), from Latin miseria, from miser, equivalent to miser + -y. Doublet of misère and mizeria.

MISHAP.e: From Middle English mishap, myshappe, myssehappe, equivalent to mis- + hap.

MISKEY.d: To key or key in erroneously; make a mistake in typing.

MISSAL.d: A prayer book; a church service (book).
MISSAL.e: From Old French messel (“book of the Mass”).

MISSEE.d: To see incorrectly; to misperceive visually; take a wrong view of; see in a false or distorted light.

MISSES.d: Plural of MISS: To fail to hit, catch, grasp, etc.
MISSES.e: Verb from Middle English missen, from Old English missan (“to miss, escape the notice of a person”), from Proto-West Germanic *missijan, from Proto-Germanic *missijaną (“to miss, go wrong, fail”), from Proto-Indo-European *meyth₂- (“to change, exchange, trade”). Cognate with West...

MISSUS.e: Representing a typical pronunciation of Mrs, a corrupted form of Mistress.

MISTED.d: Past tense of MIST: Water or other liquid finely suspended in air. (Compare fog, haze.)
MISTED.e: The noun is from Middle English mist, from Old English mist (“mist; darkness; dimness (of eyesight)”), from Proto-Germanic *mihstaz (“mist, fog”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃migʰstos, from the root *h₃meygʰ- (“cloud, fog, drizzle”). Cognate with Scots mist (“mist, fog”), West Fr...

MISTER.d: Alternative spelling of Mister, especially when used as a form of address without a name.
MISTER.e: Unaccented variant of master, attested since the 15th century.

MISTRY.e: Borrowed from Hindi मिस्त्री (mistrī). Doublet of master.

MISUSE.d: An incorrect, improper or unlawful use of something.

MITING.d: Present participle of MITE: Any of many minute arachnids which, along with the ticks, comprise subclass Acarina (aka Acari).
MITING.e: From Middle English mite, from Old English mīte (“mite, tiny insect”), from Proto-West Germanic *mītā, from Proto-Germanic *mītǭ (“biting insect”, literally “cutter”), from *maitaną (“to cut”), from Proto-Indo-European *mey- (“small”) or *meh₂y- (“to cut”). Akin to Old High Germa...

MITTEN.d: A type of glove or garment that covers a hand with a separate sheath for the thumb, but not for other fingers, which are either enclosed in a single section or left uncovered.
MITTEN.e: From Middle English myteyne, from Old French mitaine (Modern French mitaine), of unclear origin; possibly from mite, miste (“playful name for cat”) + -aine. Alternatively, mitaine may be from Old High German mittamo (“half”), superlative of mitti (“midpoint”), from Proto-Germanic...

MIZZEN.e: Borrowed from Middle French misaine, modified from Old French migenne (through influence from Italian mezzana), from Old Catalan mitjana, feminine of mitjan, ultimately from Latin medianus. Doublet of mean and median.

MIZZLE.d: To rain in very fine drops.
MIZZLE.e: From Late Middle English misellen (“to drizzle”), cognate with Low German miseln, musseln (“to mizzle”), Dutch miezelen (“to drizzle, rain gently”). Of obscure origin, possibly a frequentative related to the base of mist; or, related to Middle Low German mes (“urine”), Middle Dut...

MOANED.d: Past tense of MOAN: A low, mournful cry of pain, sorrow or pleasure.
MOANED.e:
From Middle English mone, mane, mān, (also as mene), from Old English *mān, *mǣn (“complaint; lamentation”), from Proto-West Germanic *mainu, from Proto-Germanic *mainō (“opinion; mind”).
Cognate with Old Frisian mēne (“opinion”), Old High German meina (“opinion”). Old English *m...

MOATED.d: Past tense of MOAT: A deep, wide defensive ditch, normally filled with water, surrounding a fortified habitation.
MOATED.e: From Middle English mote, from Old French mote (“mound, embankment”); compare also Old French motte (“hillock, lump, clod, turf”), from Medieval Latin mota (“a mound, hill”), of Germanic origin, perhaps via Frankish *mot, *motta (“mud, peat, bog, turf”), from Proto-Germanic *mutô...

MOBBED.d: Past tense of MOB: A large or disorderly group of people; especially one bent on riotous or destructive action.
MOBBED.e: From Middle English mob, short for mobile, from Latin mōbile (vulgus) (“fickle (crowd)”). The video-gaming sense originates from English mobile, used by Richard Bartle for objects capable of movement in an early MUD.

MOBBER.d: Comparative form of MOB: A large or disorderly group of people; especially one bent on riotous or destructive action.
MOBBER.e: From Middle English mob, short for mobile, from Latin mōbile (vulgus) (“fickle (crowd)”). The video-gaming sense originates from English mobile, used by Richard Bartle for objects capable of movement in an early MUD.

MOBILE.d: Capable of being moved, especially on wheels.
MOBILE.e: From Middle English, from Old French, from Latin mōbilis (“easy to be moved, moveable”), from moveō (“move”).

MOCKED.d: Past tense of MOCK: An imitation, usually of lesser quality.
MOCKED.e: From Middle English mokken, from Old French mocquer, moquier (“to deride, jeer”), from Middle Dutch mocken (“to mumble”) or Middle Low German mucken (“to grumble, talk with the mouth half-opened”), both from Proto-West Germanic *mokkijan, *mukkijan (“to low, bellow; mumble”), fro...

MODDER.d: Comparative form of MOD: An unconventionally modern style of fashionable dress originating in England in the 1960s, characterized by ankle-length black trenchcoats and sunglasses.

MODELS.d: Plural of MODEL: A representation; a person who poses.
MODELS.e: From Italian modello, from Latin modulus.

MODERN.d: Pertaining to a current or recent time and style; not ancient.
MODERN.e: From Middle French moderne, from Late Latin modernus; from Latin modo (“just now”), originally ablative of modus (“measure”); hence, by measure, "just now". See also mode.

MODEST.d: Not bragging or boasting about oneself or one's achievements; unpretentious, humble.
MODEST.e: From Middle French modeste, from Latin modestus.

MODIFY.e: From Middle English modifien, from Middle French modifier, from Latin modificare (“to limit, control, regulate, deponent”), from modificari (“to measure off, set bound to, moderate”), from modus (“measure”) + facere (“to make”); see mode.

MODULE.d: A self-contained component of a system, often interchangeable, which has a well-defined interface to the other components.
MODULE.e: Borrowed from French module, from Latin modulus (“a small measure, a measure, mode, meter”), diminutive of modus (“measure”) (whence mode). Doublet of modulus and mold.

MODULO.e: From Latin modulō, ablative of modulus (“a measure”).

MOGGED.d: Past tense of MOG: To be significantly more attractive than (someone or something); to dominate in appearance.
MOGGED.e: Derived from AMOG (“alpha male of group”). The word first appeared on fitness forums and imageboards around 2016 and was popularized around 2021.

MOHAIR.d: Yarn or fabric made from the hair of the angora goat, often as mixed with cotton or other materials.
MOHAIR.e: Earlier mocayre, from Middle French mocayart and Italian mocaiardo, mocaiarro, both from Arabic مُخَيَّر (muḵayyar, “choice”), past participle of خَيَّرَ (ḵayyara, “to choose”). Form influenced by hair through folk etymology. Doublet of moire; compare mockado.

MOIDER.e: Probably from the same source as mither (“to harass, pester”)

MOIETY.e: Borrowed from Middle French moytié, from Old French meitié (“half”) (modern French moitié (“half”)), from Late Latin medietās (“centre, midpoint; half”), from Latin medius (“half; middle”) + -tās (from Proto-Indo-European *-teh₂ts (suffix forming nouns indicating a state of being...

MOKSHA.d: A language of the Finnic branch of the Uralic language family.

MOLEST.d: To sexually assault or sexually harass.
MOLEST.e: From Middle English molesten, from Old French molester, from Latin molestō (“to trouble, annoy, molest”), from molestus (“troublesome”), from moles (“a burden, difficulty, labor, trouble”); see mole.

MOLIES.d: Plural of MOLY: A magic herb or plant used by Odysseus to overcome Circe.
MOLIES.e: From Latin mōly, from Ancient Greek μῶλυ (môlu) (probably a loanword).

MOLING.d: Present participle of MOLE: A naevus, a pigmented, slightly raised, and sometimes hairy spot on the skin.
MOLING.e:
From Middle English mole, mool, from Old English māl (“a mole, spot, mark, blemish”), from Proto-West Germanic *mail, from Proto-Germanic *mailą (“spot, wrinkle”), from Proto-Indo-European *mel-, *melw- (“dark, dirty”), from Proto-Indo-European *mey-, *my- (“to soil, sully”).
Cog...

MOLOCH.d: An ancient Ammonite deity worshiped by the Canaanites, Phoenician and related cultures in North Africa and the Levant, often depicted with the head of a bull.
MOLOCH.e: From the Proto-Semitic *malk- (“king”). The figurative sense derives from the Old Testament, in which it is alleged that the cult of Moloch involved the sacrifice of human children.

MOMENT.d: A particular point, or relatively small region.
MOMENT.e: From Middle English moment, from Old French moment, from Latin mōmentum. Doublet of momentum and movement.

MONEYS.d: Plural of MONEY: A medium of exchange.
MONEYS.e: From Old French moneie, from Latin monēta.

MONGER.d: Chiefly preceded by a descriptive word.
MONGER.e: The noun is derived from Middle English mongere, mangere (“dealer, merchant, trader”), from Old English mangere (“dealer, merchant, trader”), from Proto-West Germanic *mangārī (“dealer, merchant, monger”), from Latin mangō (“dealer, trader”) + Proto-West Germanic *-ārī (suffix fo...

MONGOL.d: Alternative letter-case form of Mongol (“person with Down's syndrome”).

MONIAL.e: From Anglo-Norman, from Old French moinel, noun use of moienel (“middle”), from moien.

MONISM.d: The doctrine of the oneness and unity of reality, despite the appearance of diversity in the world.
MONISM.e: The word was coined by German philosopher Baron Christian von Wolff and first used in English in 1862, from New Latin monismus, from Ancient Greek μόνος (mónos, “alone”). By surface analysis, mon- + -ism.

MONKEY.d: A member of the clade Simiiformes other than those in the clade Hominoidea containing apes, generally (but not universally) distinguished by small size, tails, and cheek pouches.
MONKEY.e: Uncertain. May be derived from monk + -ey (diminutive suffix), or borrowed from Middle Low German Moneke, the name of the son of Martin the Ape in Reynard the Fox (which may represent an unattested colloquial Middle Low German *moneke, *moneken), itself of uncertain origin. Possi...

MONODY.d: An ode, as in Greek drama, for a single voice, often specifically a mournful song or dirge.
MONODY.e: From Latin monodia, from Ancient Greek μονῳδία (monōidía).

MONOID.d: A set which is closed under an associative binary operation, and which contains an element which is an identity for the operation.

MONTHS.d: Plural of MONTH: A period of about 30 days.
MONTHS.e: From Old English mōnaþ, related to moon.

MOOING.d: Present participle of MOO: The characteristic lowing sound made by cattle.

MOONED.d: Past tense of MOON: Alternative letter-case form of Moon (“the Earth's only permanent natural satellite”).
MOONED.e:
From Middle English mone, from Old English mōna (“moon”), from Proto-West Germanic *mānō, from Proto-Germanic *mēnô (“moon”), from Proto-Indo-European *mḗh₁n̥s (“moon, month”), probably from *meh₁- (“to measure”).
cognates and doublets
Cognate with Scots mone, mune, muin (“moon”)...

MOOTED.d: Past tense of MOOT: Subject to discussion (originally at a moot); arguable, debatable, unsolved or impossible to solve.
MOOTED.e: From Middle English mōt, ȝemōt, from Old English *mōt, ġemōt (“meeting”), from Proto-Germanic *mōtą, from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to encounter, come”). Cognate with Scots mut, mote (“meeting, assembly”), Low German Mööt (“meeting”), Moot (“meeting”), archaic Dutch (ge)moet ...

MOPIER.d: Comparative form of MOPY: Alternative spelling of mopey.

MOPING.d: Present participle of MOPE: To carry oneself in a depressed, lackadaisical manner; to give oneself up to low spirits; to pout, sulk.
MOPING.e:
Late Middle English (as a noun meaning "simpleton, fool"), probably related to mop (“young of an animal, moppet”).
Alternatively, of North Germanic origin, related to Swedish mopa (“to sulk”), Danish måbe, themselves borrowed from Low German mopen (“to make faces, gape”), of unce...

MOPPED.d: Past tense of MOP: An implement for washing floors or similar, made of a piece of cloth, or a collection of thrums, or coarse yarn, fastened to a handle.
MOPPED.e: From Middle English mappe (also as mappel), perhaps borrowed from Walloon mappe (“napkin”), from Latin mappa (“napkin, cloth”). Believed to be from a Semitic source, variously claimed as Phoenician or Punic (the latter by Quintilian). Compare Modern Hebrew מַפָּה (mapá, “a map; a...

MOPPER.d: Comparative form of MOP: An implement for washing floors or similar, made of a piece of cloth, or a collection of thrums, or coarse yarn, fastened to a handle.
MOPPER.e: From Middle English mappe (also as mappel), perhaps borrowed from Walloon mappe (“napkin”), from Latin mappa (“napkin, cloth”). Believed to be from a Semitic source, variously claimed as Phoenician or Punic (the latter by Quintilian). Compare Modern Hebrew מַפָּה (mapá, “a map; a...

MOPPET.d: A child. Often used lovingly or in an affectionate way.

MORALE.d: The capacity of people to maintain belief in an institution or a goal, or even in oneself and others.

MORALS.d: Plural of MORAL: Concerned with right and wrong.

MORASS.d: A tract of soft, wet ground; a marsh; a fen.
MORASS.e: From Dutch moeras (“marsh, swamp”), an alteration (with influence from Dutch moer (“moor”)) of a direct descendant of Middle Dutch marasch (“marsh”). The Middle Dutch word is a borrowing from Old French mareis, from Proto-West Germanic *marisk. Doublet of marish and marsh, and li...

MORBID.d: Of, relating to, or afflicted by disease.
MORBID.e: From Latin morbidus (“diseased”), from morbus (“sickness”), itself from the root of morī (“to die”) or directly from Proto-Indo-European *mer- (“to rub, pound, wear away”).

MOREEN.d: A thick woollen fabric, watered or with embossed figures, once used in upholstery, for curtains, etc. It is a variety of camlet.

MORGUE.d: A supercilious or haughty attitude; arrogance.
MORGUE.e: Borrowed from French morgue. The second sense developed from the first, via "a prison examination room", probably with reference to the haughty attitude of the jailers.

MORION.d: A kind of open brimmed helmet used by footsoldiers in the 16th and 17th centuries, having no visor or bevor.
MORION.e: From Middle French morion, from, Spanish morrión, from morra (“upper part of the head”), from morro (“muzzle, snout”), from Vulgar Latin *murrum (“muzzle, snout”). Related to moraine (“an amassment of rocks on a glacier”).

MOROSE.d: Sullen, gloomy; showing a brooding ill humour.
MOROSE.e: From French morose, from Latin mōrōsus (“particular, scrupulous, fastidious, self-willed, wayward, capricious, fretful, peevish”), from mōs (“way, custom, habit, self-will”). See moral.

MORROW.e:
From Middle English morwe, morwen, from Old English morgen, from Proto-West Germanic *morgan, *morgin, from Proto-Germanic *murganaz, *murginaz; compare Dutch morgen and German Morgen.
Doublet of morgen and morn. Both morn and morrow continue earlier Middle English morwen (the fo...

MORSEL.d: A small fragment or share of something, commonly applied to food.
MORSEL.e: From Middle English morsel, from Old French morsel, from Medieval Latin morsellum (“a bit, a little piece”), diminutive of Latin morsum (“a bit”), neuter of morsus, perfect passive participle of mordeo (“I bite”). Compare French morceau, whence the English doublet morceau.

MORTAL.d: Susceptible to death by aging, sickness, injury, or wound; not immortal.
MORTAL.e: From Middle English mortal, mortel, from Old French mortal, and their source Latin mortālis, from mors (“death”). In this sense, displaced native deadly, from Old English dēadlīċ.

MORTAR.d: A mixture of lime or cement, sand and water used for bonding building blocks.
MORTAR.e: From Middle English morter, from Old French mortier, from Latin mortārium. Doublet of mortarium.

MORULA.d: A spherical mass of blastomeres that forms following the splitting of a zygote; it becomes the blastula

MOSAIC.d: A piece of artwork created by placing colored squares (usually tiles) in a pattern so as to create a picture.
MOSAIC.e: From Middle French mosaïque, from Italian mosaico, from Medieval Latin musaicum, from Late Latin musivum (opus), from Latin museum, musaeum, probably from Ancient Greek Μουσεῖον (Mouseîon), shrine of the Muses (Μοῦσα (Moûsa)).

MOSQUE.d: A place of worship for Muslims, often having at least one minaret; a masjid.
MOSQUE.e: From Middle French mosquée, from Italian moschea, ultimately from Arabic مَسْجِد (masjid, literally “place of prostration”). Doublet of masjid.

MOSSED.d: Past tense of MOS: Alternative letter-case form of MOS (“manual of style”).

MOSSER.d: Comparative form of MOS: Alternative letter-case form of MOS (“manual of style”).

MOSSES.d: Plural of MOSS: Any of various small, green, seedless plants growing on the ground or on the surfaces of trees, stones, etc.; now specifically, a plant of the phylum Bryophyta (formerly division Musci).
MOSSES.e:
From Middle English mos, from Old English mos (“bog, marsh, moss”), from Proto-West Germanic *mos (“marsh, moss”), from Proto-Germanic *musą (“marsh, moss”), from Proto-Indo-European *mews- (“moss”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Moas (“moss”), West Frisian moas (“moss”), Dutch ...

MOTHED.d: Past tense of MOTH: Any flying insect of the order Lepidoptera not in the superfamily Papilionoidea, most species of which are nocturnal and can be distinguished from butterflies by feather-like antennae.
MOTHED.e: From Middle English moth, moththe, motthe, moght, mohþe, mouȝte, from Old English moþþe, mohþe, mohþa (“any destructive insect larva”), from Proto-West Germanic *moþþō, *mottō, from Proto-Germanic *muþþô, *muttô (“moth, worm”), from Proto-Indo-European *mutn-, *mut- (“worm”). Cog...

MOTHER.d: A female parent, especially of a human; a female who parents a child (which she has given birth to, adopted, or fostered).
MOTHER.e: From Middle English moder, from Old English mōdor, from Proto-West Germanic *mōder, from Proto-Germanic *mōdēr, from Proto-Indo-European *méh₂tēr. Doublet of Madeira, mata, mater, matrix, and matter.

MOTILE.d: In organisms: having the power to move spontaneously.
MOTILE.e: From Latin mōtus, perfect passive participle of moveō (“I move”) (English move).

MOTION.d: A state of progression from one place to another.
