MOTION.e: Inherited from Middle English mocioun, mocion, from Anglo-Norman motion, Middle French motion, and their etymon Latin mōtiō (“movement, motion”), related to movēre, from Proto-Indo-European *m(y)ewh₁- (“to move”).

MOTIVE.d: An idea or communication that makes one want to act, especially from spiritual sources; a divine prompting.
MOTIVE.e: From Middle English motif, from Anglo-Norman motif, Middle French motif, and their source, Late Latin motivum (“motive, moving cause”), neuter of motivus.

MOTORS.d: Plural of MOTOR: An engine; relating to movement.

MOTTLE.d: To mark with blotches of different color, or shades of color, as if stained; to spot; to maculate.

MOUNTS.d: Plural of MOUNT: A mountain; to climb up.
MOUNTS.e: From Old French mont, from Latin mōns.

MOUSED.d: Past tense of MOUSE: A small rodent; a computer input device.

MOUSES.d: Plural of MOUSE: A small rodent; a computer input device.

MOUSSE.d: An airy pudding served chilled, particularly chocolate mousse.
MOUSSE.e: From French mousse (“foam, froth”), from Old French mosse (“moss”), from Frankish or Old Dutch *mosa (“moss”), from Proto-Germanic *musą (“moss, bog, marsh”). More at moss.

MOUTHS.d: Plural of MOUTH: The opening in the face for eating and speaking.

MOUTON.d: A 14th-century French gold coin, weighing about 70 grains.
MOUTON.e: Borrowed from French mouton (“sheep”). Doublet of mutton.

MOVIES.d: Plural of MOVIE: A motion picture.

MOVING.d: Present participle of MOVE: To change place or posture; to go, in any manner, from one place or position to another.
MOVING.e: From Middle English moven, moeven, meven, borrowed from Old Northern French mover, moveir and Old French mouver, moveir (“to move”) (compare modern French mouvoir from Old French movoir), from Latin movēre (“move; change, exchange, go in or out, quit”), from Proto-Indo-European *...

MOWING.d: present participle and gerund of mow
MOWING.e: From Middle English mowynge; equivalent to mow + -ing.

MUCATE.d: Any salt or ester of mucic acid.

MUCHES.d: Plural of MUCH: A large amount of.
MUCHES.e: From Middle English muche (“much, great”), apocopated variant of muchel (“much, great”), from Old English myċel, miċel (“big, much”), from Proto-West Germanic *mikil, from Proto-Germanic *mikilaz (“great, many, much”), from Proto-Indo-European *meǵh₂- (“big, stour, great”). See a...

MUCKED.d: Past tense of MUCK: Slimy mud, sludge.
MUCKED.e: From Middle English mok, muk, from Old Norse myki, mykr (“dung”) or less likely Old English *moc, *moce (in hlōsmoc (“pigsty dung”) and lustmoce (“lady's smock (Cardamine pratensis)”)) (compare Icelandic mykja and Danish møg ("dung")), from Proto-Germanic *mukį̄ (“dung; manure”),...

MUCKLE.e: From Middle English mukel, muchel, from the same source as (perhaps a variant of) mickle.

MUCOID.d: Having the qualities of mucus; resembling mucus.

MUDDED.d: Past tense of MUD: Acronym of multi-user dungeon, an interactive online environment in which players may jointly engage in fantasy role-playing games.

MUDDER.d: Comparative form of MUD: Acronym of multi-user dungeon, an interactive online environment in which players may jointly engage in fantasy role-playing games.

MUDDLE.d: To mix together, to mix up; to confuse.
MUDDLE.e: From Middle English modelen (attested in present participle modeland (“wallowing”)), from Middle Dutch moddelen (“to make muddy”), from modde, mod (“mud”) (Modern Dutch modder). By surface analysis, mud + -le. Compare German Kuddelmuddel.

MUESLI.d: A breakfast dish based on uncooked rolled oats and fruit.
MUESLI.e: From Alemannic German Müesli, diminutive of Mues (“mashed dish”); compare Dutch moes.

MUFFED.d: Past tense of MUFF: A piece of fur or cloth, usually with open ends, used for keeping the hands warm.

MUFFIN.d: A type of flattish bun, usually cut in two horizontally, toasted and spread with butter, etc., before being eaten.
MUFFIN.e: From earlier moofin, probably a diminutive of Low German Muffe ("small cake"; Muffen (plural)), from Middle Low German muffe (“small pastry”). An alternative, and phonologically less plausible theory suggests a connection to Old French (pain) moflet (“roll”, literally “soft (brea...

MUFFLE.d: Anything that mutes or deadens sound.
MUFFLE.e: From Middle English muflen (“to muffle”), aphetic alteration of Anglo-Norman amoufler, from Old French enmoufler (“to wrap up, muffle”), from moufle (“mitten”), from Medieval Latin muffula (“a muff”), of Germanic origin (—first recorded in the Capitulary of Aachen in 817 C.E.), f...

MUGFUL.d: As much as a mug will contain.

MUGGED.d: Past tense of MUG: A large cup for beverages, usually having a handle and used without a saucer.
MUGGED.e: Early 16th century (originally Scots and northern English, denoting "earthenware, pot, jug"), of unknown origin, perhaps from North Germanic (compare Swedish mugg (“mug, jug”), Norwegian mugge (“pitcher, open can for warm drinks”), Danish mugge), or Low German mokke, mukke (“mug”...

MUGGER.d: Comparative form of MUG: A large cup for beverages, usually having a handle and used without a saucer.
MUGGER.e: Early 16th century (originally Scots and northern English, denoting "earthenware, pot, jug"), of unknown origin, perhaps from North Germanic (compare Swedish mugg (“mug, jug”), Norwegian mugge (“pitcher, open can for warm drinks”), Danish mugge), or Low German mokke, mukke (“mug”...

MUGGLE.e: Origin unknown; first known to have come into use in New Orleans, Louisiana, U.S.A., in the mid-1920s.

MUKLUK.d: A soft knee-high boot of sealskin or reindeer skin, originally worn by Inuit and Yupik.
MUKLUK.e: Borrowed from Yup'ik maklak (“bearded seal”), referring to sealskin used to make boots, originally derived from Proto-Eskimo *makla (“bearded seal, spotted seal”).

MULING.d: Present participle of MULE: The generally sterile male or female hybrid offspring of a male donkey and a female horse.
MULING.e: From Middle English mule, from Anglo-Norman mule and Old English mūl, both from Latin mūlus, from Proto-Indo-European *mukslós. Compare Late Latin muscellus (“young he-mule”), Old East Slavic мъшкъ (mŭškŭ, “mule”), Ancient Greek (Phocian) μυχλός (mukhlós, “he-ass”), and German Ma...

MULISH.d: Characteristic of a mule; stubborn, obstinate, or intractable.

MULLAH.d: An honorific title for a scholar of theology and sharia law.
MULLAH.e: Derived from Classical Persian مُلَّا (mullā), from Arabic مَوْلًى (mawlan, “vicar, guardian”).

MULLED.d: Past tense of MULL: To work (over) mentally; to cogitate; to ruminate.
MULLED.e: Inherited from Middle English molle, mulle (“dust, rubbish”), possibly from Old English myl (“dust, mould”), from Proto-West Germanic *muli, a deverbal formation from *mulljan and thus cognate with Dutch mul (“dust, mould”), German Müll (“rubbish”), Swedish moln (“cloud”) and rel...

MULLER.d: One who, or that which, mulls.
MULLER.e: From mull (“to heat and spice, etc.”, verb) + -er (suffix forming agent nouns).

MULLET.d: A fish of the family Mullidae (order Syngnathiformes), especially the genus Mullus (red mullets or goatfish).
MULLET.e: From Middle English molet, mulett, from Old French mulet (now ‘grey mullet’), from Latin mullus (“red mullet”), from Ancient Greek μύλλος (múllos).

MUMBLE.d: To speak unintelligibly or inaudibly; to fail to articulate.
MUMBLE.e: From Middle English momelen, a frequentative of mum (sense 3) (“silent”). Compare German mümmeln, Middle Dutch mommelen and Dutch mompelen. Perhaps related to Norwegian Nynorsk mumpa (“to gum, to chew without teeth”).

MUMMED.e: Alternative form of mam, or an abbreviation of mummy. Compare mom, mama.

MUMMER.e: Alternative form of mam, or an abbreviation of mummy. Compare mom, mama.

MUNSHI.e: Borrowed from Urdu منشی (munšī, “secretary; munshi”) or directly from its etymon Classical Persian منشی (munšī, “secretary; munshi”), from Arabic مُنْشِئ (munšiʔ, “teacher; writer”).

MUPPET.d: Alternative form of Muppet (“a puppet in the style of Jim Henson's Muppets”).
MUPPET.e: From Muppet, from the Muppets franchise

MURAGE.d: A tax paid for building or repairing the walls of a fortified town.
MURAGE.e: Inherited from Middle English murage, from Anglo-Norman and Middle French murage, from murer (“to wall”), from mur (“wall”), Latin murus. See mure (“wall”).

MURDER.d: The crime of killing a person unlawfully, especially with predetermination.
MURDER.e: From Middle English murder, murdre, mourdre, alteration of earlier murthre (“murder”) (see murther), from Old English morþor (“secret slaying, unlawful killing”) and Old English myrþra (“murder, homicide”), both from Proto-West Germanic *morþr, from Proto-Germanic *murþrą (“death...

MURMUR.d: Any low, indistinct sound, like that of running water.
MURMUR.e: From Middle English murmur, murmor, murmour, from Old French murmure (modern French murmure), from Latin murmur (“murmur, humming, muttering, roaring, growling, rushing etc.”).

MURPHY.d: A common surname from Irish, the anglicized form of Irish Ó Murchadha
MURPHY.e: From Irish Ó Murchadha (“descendant of Murrough”), Mac Murchaidh (“Son of Murrough”), etc. See Muircath.

MUSCLE.d: A contractile form of tissue which animals use to effect movement.
MUSCLE.e: From Middle English muscle, muscule, muskylle, and in part from Middle French muscle, from Latin mūsculus (“a muscle”, literally “little mouse”) because of the mouselike appearance of some muscles, from mūs (“mouse”). Doublet of mussel. More at mouse.

MUSEUM.d: A building or institution dedicated to the acquisition, conservation, study, exhibition, and educational interpretation of objects having scientific, historical, cultural or artistic value.
MUSEUM.e: From Latin mūsēum (“library, study”), from Ancient Greek Μουσεῖον (Mouseîon), shrine of the Muses (Μοῦσα (Moûsa)).

MUSHED.d: Past tense of MUSH: A somewhat liquid mess, often of food; a soft or semisolid substance.
MUSHED.e: Probably a variant of mash, or from a dialectal variant of Middle English mos (“mush, pulp, porridge”); compare Middle English appelmos (“applesauce”), from Old English mōs (“food, victuals, porridge, mush”), from Proto-West Germanic *mōs, from Proto-Germanic *mōsą (“porridge, fo...

MUSHES.d: Plural of MUSH: A somewhat liquid mess, often of food; a soft or semisolid substance.
MUSHES.e: Probably a variant of mash, or from a dialectal variant of Middle English mos (“mush, pulp, porridge”); compare Middle English appelmos (“applesauce”), from Old English mōs (“food, victuals, porridge, mush”), from Proto-West Germanic *mōs, from Proto-Germanic *mōsą (“porridge, fo...

MUSICS.d: Plural of MUSIC: Vocal or instrumental sounds combined pleasingly.
MUSICS.e: From Old French musique, from Latin mūsica, from Greek mousikḗ.

MUSING.d: Present participle of MUSE: Of a person: a source of inspiration.
MUSING.e: From Middle French muse, from Latin Mūsa, from Ancient Greek Μοῦσα (Moûsa).

MUSKED.d: Past tense of MUSK: A greasy secretion with a powerful odour, produced in a glandular sac of the male musk deer and used in the manufacture of perfumes.
MUSKED.e: From Middle English muske, borrowed from Old French musc, from Late Latin muscus, from Ancient Greek μόσχος (móskhos), from Middle Persian [script needed] (mwšk' /⁠muʃk⁠/) whence Persian مشک (mošk). Ultimately from Sanskrit मुष्क (muṣka, “testicle”), the shape of the gland of ani...

MUSKEG.d: A terrain composed of peat bog with tussocky meadow and woody vegetation including spruce.

MUSKET.d: A kind of firearm formerly carried by the infantry of an army, originally fired by means of a match, or matchlock, for which several mechanical appliances (including the flintlock, and finally the percussion lock) were successively substituted; ultimately superseded by the rifle.
MUSKET.e: First attested around 1210 as a surname, and later in the 1400s as a word for the sparrowhawk (Middle English forms: musket, muskett, muskete (“sparrow hawk”)), from Middle French mousquet, from Old Italian moschetto (a diminutive of mosca (“fly”), from Latin musca) used to refer...

MUSKIE.d: muskellunge; a large freshwater gamefish of the pike family.

MUSLIN.d: Any of several varieties of thin cotton cloth.
MUSLIN.e: From French mousseline, from Italian mussolina, from Mussolo (“Mosul”), that is Mosul in northern Iraq (compare 1875 Knight, Edward H., Knight's American Mechanical Dictionary, V2 p1502: "Muslins are so called from Moussol in India."). Doublet of mousseline.

MUSSED.d: Past tense of MUS: plural of mu

MUSSEL.d: Any of several groups of bivalve shellfish with elongated, asymmetrical shells.
MUSSEL.e: From Middle English muscle (“mussel”), from Old English muscle, from Proto-West Germanic *muskulā, from Late Latin muscula, from Latin mūsculus (“mussel, muscle”, literally “little mouse”). Doublet of muscle.

MUSSES.d: Plural of MUSS: To rumple, tousle or make (something) untidy.

MUSTED.d: Past tense of MUST: To do as a requirement; indicates that the sentence subject is required as an imperative or directive to execute the sentence predicate, with failure to do so resulting in a failure or negative consequence.
MUSTED.e: From Middle English moste ("must", literally, "had to", the past tense of Middle English moten (“to have to”)), from Old English mōste (“had to”), 1st & 3rd person singular past tense of mōtan (“to be allowed, be able to, have the opportunity to, be compelled to, must, may”), fro...

MUSTER.e: From Middle English musteren, borrowed from Anglo-Norman mostrer, Middle French monstrer, moustrer (whence the noun monstre, which gave the English noun), from Latin mōnstrō (“to show”), from moneō (“to admonish”). Cognate with French montrer (“to show”), Italian mostrare (“to sh...

MUTANT.d: That which has mutated, with one or more new characteristics from a mutation.
MUTANT.e: From Latin mūtāns, present participle of mūtō. By surface analysis, muta- + -ant.

MUTATE.e: First attested in 1796; back-formation from mutation on the basis of -ate (verb-forming suffix), ultimately from Latin mūtō (“to exchange; to change, to vary”). Doublet of moult.

MUTING.d: Present participle of MUTE: Not having the power of speech; dumb.
MUTING.e: From Middle English muet, from Anglo-Norman muet, moet, Middle French muet, from mu (“dumb, mute”) + -et, remodelled after Latin mūtus.

MUTINY.d: An organized rebellion against a legally constituted authority, especially by seamen against their officers.

MUTISM.d: A psychological disorder in which the sufferer cannot speak in certain situations.
MUTISM.e: From French mutisme, from Latin mutus (“mute”), equivalent to mute + -ism.

MUTTER.d: A repressed or obscure utterance; an instance of muttering.
MUTTER.e:
From Middle English muteren, moteren, of imitative origin.
Compare Low German mustern, musseln (“to whisper”), German muttern (“to mutter; whisper”), Old Norse muðla (“to murmur”). Compare also Latin muttīre, mutīre.

MUTTON.d: The meat of sheep used as food.
MUTTON.e: From Middle English motoun, moton, from Old French mouton (“sheep”), from Vulgar Latin moltō, from Gaulish *multon-, from Proto-Celtic *moltos (“ram, wether”). Doublet of mouton.

MUTUAL.d: Having the same relationship, each to each other.
MUTUAL.e: Borrowed from Middle French mutuel, from Latin mūtuus.

MUTULE.d: Any of the rectangular blocks under the soffit of the cornice of the Greek Doric temple, which are studded with guttae.

MUUMUU.d: A long loose-fitting dress made of lightweight fabric printed with bright, stylized Hawaiian themes (such as flowers and palm branches).

MUZZLE.d: The protruding part of an animal's head which includes the nose, mouth and jaws.
MUZZLE.e: From earlier muzle, musle, mousle, mussel, mozell, from Middle English mosel, from Old French musel, museau, muzeau (modern French museau), from Late Latin mūsus (“snout”), probably expressive of the shape of protruded lips and/or influenced by Latin mūgīre (“to moo, bellow”). Do...

MYELIN.d: A white, fatty material, composed of lipids and lipoproteins, that surrounds the axons of nerves.
MYELIN.e:
From myelo- + -in.
From Ancient Greek μυελός (muelós, “marrow”).

MYOPIA.d: A disorder of the vision where distant objects appear blurred because the eye focuses their images in front of the retina instead of on it.
MYOPIA.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek μυωπία (muōpía, “shortsightedness”), from μύω (múō, “to shut, close”) + ὤψ (ṓps, “eye”) + -ία (-ía).

MYOPIC.d: Near-sighted; unable to see distant objects unaided.

MYOSIN.d: Any of a large family of motor proteins found in eukaryotic tissues, allowing mobility in muscles.
MYOSIN.e: myo- (“relating to muscle”), from Ancient Greek μυός (muós), genitive of μῦς (mûs, “muscle”) + -in.

MYRIAD.e: From French myriade, from Late Latin mȳriadem (accusative of mȳrias), from Ancient Greek μυριάς (muriás, “number of 10,000”), from μυρίος (muríos, “numberless, countless, infinite”).

MYRTLE.d: An evergreen shrub or small tree of the genus Myrtus, native to southern Europe and north Africa.
MYRTLE.e: From Old French myrte, from Latin myrtus, from Ancient Greek μύρτος (múrtos, “myrtle”).

MYSTIC.d: Of, or relating to mystics, mysticism or occult mysteries; mystical.
MYSTIC.e: From Old French mistique, from Latin mysticus, from Ancient Greek μυστικός (mustikós, “secret, mystic”), from μύστης (mústēs, “one who has been initiated”). Doublet of mystique.

MYTHUS.e: Borrowed from Late Latin mythus, from Late Latin mȳthos (“myth”), from Ancient Greek μῦθος (mûthos, “report, tale, story”).

MYXOMA.d: A tumor consisting of primitive connective tissue and mucous elements.
MYXOMA.e: From New Latin myxōma. By surface analysis, myxo- (“mucus”) + -oma.

NABBED.d: Past tense of NAB: To seize, arrest or take into custody (a criminal or fugitive).
NABBED.e:
From dialectal nap (“to seize, lay hold of”), probably of North Germanic origin, from Old Swedish nappa (“to pluck, pinch”).
Related to Danish nappe (“to tweak, snatch at, catch, seize”), Swedish nappa (“to take, grab, pinch”), Norwegian Bokmål nappe (“to grab, snatch, pluck, yan...

NABBER.d: Comparative form of NAB: To seize, arrest or take into custody (a criminal or fugitive).
NABBER.e:
From dialectal nap (“to seize, lay hold of”), probably of North Germanic origin, from Old Swedish nappa (“to pluck, pinch”).
Related to Danish nappe (“to tweak, snatch at, catch, seize”), Swedish nappa (“to take, grab, pinch”), Norwegian Bokmål nappe (“to grab, snatch, pluck, yan...

NAEVUS.d: A pigmented, raised or otherwise abnormal area on the skin, whether congenital or acquired.

NAGGED.d: Past tense of NAG: A small horse; a pony.
NAGGED.e: From Middle English nagg, nage, nagge (“horse, small riding horse, pony”), cognate with Dutch negge, neg (“horse”), German Nickel (“small horse”). Perhaps related to English neigh.

NAGGER.d: Comparative form of NAG: A small horse; a pony.
NAGGER.e: From Middle English nagg, nage, nagge (“horse, small riding horse, pony”), cognate with Dutch negge, neg (“horse”), German Nickel (“small horse”). Perhaps related to English neigh.

NAGING.d: Present participle of NAG: A small horse; a pony.
NAGING.e: From Middle English nagg, nage, nagge (“horse, small riding horse, pony”), cognate with Dutch negge, neg (“horse”), German Nickel (“small horse”). Perhaps related to English neigh.

NAILED.d: Past tense of NAIL: The thin, horny plate at the ends of fingers and toes on humans and some other animals.
NAILED.e:
From Middle English nail, nayl, Old English næġl, from Proto-West Germanic *nagl, from Proto-Germanic *naglaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃nogʰ- (“nail”).
Cognates
Compare North Frisian Nail (“nail”), Saterland Frisian Nail (“nail”), West Frisian neil, Low German Nagel, Dutch nag...

NAIVES.d: Plural of NAIF: Alternative spelling of naïf.

NAMING.d: Present participle of NAME: Any nounal word or phrase which indicates a particular person, place, class, or thing.
NAMING.e:
PIE word
 *h₁nómn̥
From Middle English name, nome, from Old English nama, noma, from Proto-West Germanic *namō, from Proto-Germanic *namô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁nómn̥.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola naame, name, naume (“name”), North Frisian Noom, noome, nööm (“name”), Saterlan...

NAPALM.d: A highly flammable, viscous substance, designed to stick to the body while burning, used in warfare as an incendiary especially in wooded areas.
NAPALM.e: Formed from na(phthenic) palm(itic) acid, the two original components of the substance.

NAPKIN.d: A serviette; a (usually rectangular) piece of cloth or paper used at the table for wiping the mouth and hands for cleanliness while eating.
NAPKIN.e: From Middle English napkyn, equivalent to nape (“cloth”) + -kin.

NAPPED.d: Past tense of NAP: To have a nap; to sleep for a short period of time, especially during the day.
NAPPED.e: From Middle English nappen, from Old English hnappian (“to doze, slumber, sleep”), from Proto-West Germanic *hnappōn (“to nap”). Cognate with Old High German hnaffezan, hnaffezzan (whence Middle High German nafzen (“to slumber”) whence German dialectal napfezen, nafzen (“to nod, ...

NAPPER.d: Comparative form of NAP: To have a nap; to sleep for a short period of time, especially during the day.
NAPPER.e: From Middle English nappen, from Old English hnappian (“to doze, slumber, sleep”), from Proto-West Germanic *hnappōn (“to nap”). Cognate with Old High German hnaffezan, hnaffezzan (whence Middle High German nafzen (“to slumber”) whence German dialectal napfezen, nafzen (“to nod, ...

NARDOO.d: Marsilea drummondii, a four-leaved aquatic fern native to Australia the sporocarps of which are processed for food.

NARKED.d: Past tense of NARK: A police spy or informer.
NARKED.e: Uncertain. Perhaps from Angloromani nok (“nose”), from Romani nakh, from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀡𑀓𑁆𑀓 (ṇakka), ultimately a doublet of nose.

NARROW.d: Having a small width; not wide; having opposite edges or sides that are close, especially by comparison to length or depth.
NARROW.e: From Middle English narow, narowe, narewe, narwe, naru, from Old English nearu (“narrow, strait, confined, constricted, not spacious, limited, petty; limited, poor, restricted; oppressive, causing anxiety (of that which restricts free action of body or mind), causing or accompani...

NASION.d: The point at the root of the nose where the frontal and two nasal bones meet. (It is a cephalometric landmark.)

NATANT.e: Borrowed from Latin natāntem, accusative of natāns. Doublet of naiant.

NATION.d: A historically constituted, stable community of people, formed based on a common language, territory, economic life, ethnicity and/or psychological make-up manifested in a common culture.
NATION.e: From Middle English nacioun, nacion, from Old French nacion, from Latin nātiōnem, accusative of nātiō (“nation”). Displaced native Old English þēod.

NATIVE.e: Inherited from Middle English natif, from Old French natif, from Latin nātīvus, from nātus (“birth”). Doublet of naive and neif.

NATTER.d: To talk casually; to discuss unimportant matters.
NATTER.e: From a Northern England dialectal variant of gnatter (also knatter) ("to chatter, grumble; nibble away at"), ultimately of imitative origin. Cognate with German Low German gnattern (“to mumble, grumble, be grouchy”).

NATURE.d: The way things are, the totality of all things in the physical universe and their order, especially the physical world in contrast to spiritual realms and flora and fauna as distinct from human conventions, art, and technology.
NATURE.e: From Middle English nature, natur, from Old French nature, from Latin nātūra (“birth, origin, natural constitution or quality”), future participle from perfect passive participle (g)natus (“born”), from deponent verb (g)nasci (“to be born, originate”) + future participle suffix -...

NAUGHT.e: From the Middle English naught, nought, naht, nawiht, from Old English nawiht. Cognate with West Frisian neat (“nothing, naught”). Doublet of nought. Equivalent to ne + aught.

NAUSEA.d: A feeling of illness or discomfort in the digestive system, usually characterized by a strong urge to vomit.
NAUSEA.e: From Middle English nausea, a borrowing from Latin nausea, from Ancient Greek ναυσία (nausía, “sea-sickness”), from ναῦς (naûs, “ship”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)neh₂-. Displaced native Old English wlǣtta.

NAVAID.d: Any form of aid to navigation such as a lighthouse or ILS (instrument landing system).

NAVIES.d: Plural of NAVY: A country's entire maritime military force, including ships and personnel.
NAVIES.e: From Middle English nave, navye, from Anglo-Norman, Old French navie, from Latin nāvigia < nāvigium, from Latin nāvigō, nāvis (“boat”), from Proto-Indo-European *néh₂us. Compare Ancient Greek ναῦς (naûs, “ship”), Persian ناو (nâv, “boat, warship”), Sanskrit नाव (nāva, “ship”), Ol...

NAYIKA.d: Any of the eight types of romantic heroine described in the Natya Shastra, an ancient Indian treatise on the performing arts.

NEAPED.d: Past tense of NEAP: The tongue or pole of a cart or other vehicle drawn by two animals.
NEAPED.e: Perhaps of Scandinavian origin: compare dialectal Norwegian neip (“forked pole”).

NEARED.d: Past tense of NEAR: Physically close.
NEARED.e: From Middle English nere, ner, from Old English nēar (“nearer”, comparative of nēah (“nigh”), the superlative would become next), influenced by Old Norse nær (“near”), both originating from Proto-Germanic *nēhwiz (“nearer”), comparative of the adverb *nēhw (“near”), from the adje...

NEATEN.d: To make (someone or something) neat; to arrange (people or things) in an orderly, tidy way; to tidy.

NEBULA.d: A cloud in outer space consisting of gas or dust (e.g. a cloud formed after a star explodes).
NEBULA.e: Borrowed from Latin nebula (“little cloud, mist”). Akin to Ancient Greek νεφέλη (nephélē, “cloud”), German Nebel (“mist, nebula”), Old Norse nifl, Polish niebo (“sky, heaven”), Russian не́бо (nébo, “sky”).

NECKED.d: Past tense of NECK: The part of the body connecting the head and the trunk found in humans and some animals.
NECKED.e: From Middle English nekke, nakke, from Old English hnecca, *hnæcca (“neck, nape”), from Proto-Germanic *hnakkô (“nape, neck”), from Proto-Indo-European *knog-, *kneg- (“back of the head, nape, neck”). Cognate with Scots nek (“neck”), North Frisian neek, neeke, Nak (“neck”), Sater...

NECTAR.e: From Latin nectar, from Ancient Greek νέκταρ (néktar, “nourishment of the gods”), from Proto-Indo-European *neḱ- (“perish, disappear”) + *-tr̥h₂ (“overcoming”), from *terh₂- (“to overcome, pass through, cross over”).

NEDDER.d: Comparative form of NED: A person, usually a youth, of low social standing and education, a violent disposition and with a particular style of dress (typically sportswear or Burberry), speech and behaviour.
NEDDER.e: Unknown. The suggested initialism from "non-educated delinquent" is a backronym and folk etymology. Several other suggestions include a contraction of ne'er-do-well, neanderthal, or some kind of relationship with Teddy Boy although its use much predates the 1950s origin of that p...

NEEDED.d: Past tense of NEED: A requirement for something; something needed.
NEEDED.e:
From Middle English need, nede, a merger of two terms:
* Old English nīed (West Saxon), nēd (Mercian), nēad (“necessity, compulsion, want”), from Proto-West Germanic *naudi, from Proto-Germanic *naudiz, from Proto-Indo-European *neh₂w- (“death”).
* Old English nēod (“desire, long...

NEEDLE.d: A long, thin, sharp implement usually for piercing as in sewing, embroidery, acupuncture, tattooing, body piercing, medical injections, sutures, etc; or a blunt but otherwise similar implement used for forming loops or knots in crafts such as darning, knitting, tatting, etc.
NEEDLE.e:
From Middle English nedle, from Old English nǣdl, from Proto-West Germanic *nāþlu, from Proto-Germanic *nēþlō, from pre-Germanic *neh₁-tleh₂, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)neh₁- (“to spin, twist”).
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Näddele (“sewing needle”), Dutch naald (“ne...

NEGATE.d: To deny the existence, evidence, or truth of; to contradict.
NEGATE.e: From Latin negātus, perfect passive participle of negō (“to deny, refuse, decline”), see -ate (verb-forming suffix).

NEKTON.d: All organisms in the ocean that are capable of swimming independently of currents.
NEKTON.e: From German Nekton which was coined in 1890 by Ernst Haeckel. By surface analysis, Ancient Greek νηκτός (nēktós, “swimming”) + -on.

NELSON.d: A score of 111, sometimes considered to be unlucky.
NELSON.e:
Cricket sense: origin disputed; supposedly from the belief that Lord Nelson had one eye, one arm and one leg.
Wrestling sense: Back-formation from full nelson.

NEONED.d: Past tense of NEON: The chemical element (symbol Ne) with an atomic number of 10. The second of the noble gases, it is a colourless, odorless inert gas.
NEONED.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek νέον (néon), neuter of νέος (néos, “new”), from earlier *νέϝος (*néwos), from Proto-Hellenic *newos, from Proto-Indo-European *néwos. By surface analysis, neo- + -on (suffix used in all noble gases).

NEPHEW.d: A son of one's sibling, brother-in-law, or sister-in-law; either a son of one's brother (fraternal nephew) or a son of one's sister (sororal nephew).
NEPHEW.e: From Middle English nevew, neveu (“nephew, grandson”), from Old French neveu, from Latin nepos, nepōtem, from Proto-Italic *nepōts (“nephew, grandson”), whence also French neveu, Italian nipote. Displaced or absorbed the inherited English neve (“nephew, grandson, male cousin”), f...

NERINE.d: Any of various plants of the genus Nerine, native to South Africa, used ornamentally, and toxic to many mammals.

NEROLI.d: More fully neroli oil or oil of neroli: an essential oil distilled from the blossoms of the bitter orange or Seville orange (Citrus × aurantium subsp. amara) used to make perfumes.
NEROLI.e: Borrowed from French néroli (“neroli”), from Nerola, a town and comune in the Metropolitan City of Rome, Lazio, Italy. Marie Anne de La Trémoille, princesse des Ursins (1642–1722), Princess of Nerola but originally from France, is thought to have made neroli popular as a fragranc...

NERVON.d: A cerebroside present in brain tissue

NESTED.d: Past tense of NEST: A structure built by a bird as a place to incubate eggs and rear young.
NESTED.e: From Middle English nest, nist, nyst, from Old English nest, from Proto-West Germanic *nest, from Proto-Germanic *nestą, from Proto-Indo-European *nisdós (“nest”), literally "where [the bird] sits down", a compound of *ni (“down”) (whence also English nether) + the zero-grade of ...

NESTLE.d: To settle oneself comfortably and snugly.
NESTLE.e: From Middle English nestelen, nestlen, from Old English nistlan, nestlian, nistlian (“to make or build a nest”), from Proto-West Germanic *nistilōn (“to build or occupy a nest; nestle”), equivalent to nest + -le. Cognate with Middle Low German nëstelen (“to build a nest”), Dutch ...

NETFUL.d: As much as a net will hold.

NETTED.d: Past tense of NET: A mesh of string, cord or rope.
NETTED.e: From Middle English net, from Old English net, nett, from Proto-West Germanic *nati, from Proto-Germanic *natją, from Proto-Indo-European *neHd- (“to turn, twist, knot”).

NETTER.d: Comparative form of NET: A mesh of string, cord or rope.
NETTER.e: From Middle English net, from Old English net, nett, from Proto-West Germanic *nati, from Proto-Germanic *natją, from Proto-Indo-European *neHd- (“to turn, twist, knot”).

NETTLE.d: Any plant whose foliage is covered with stinging, mildly poisonous hairs, causing an instant rash.
NETTLE.e: From Middle English netle, netel, from Old English netle, netele, netel, from Proto-West Germanic *natilā (cognate with Old Saxon netila, Middle Dutch netele (modern Dutch netel), German Nessel, Middle Danish nædlæ (“nettle”)), a diminutive of Proto-Germanic *natǭ (of unknown ori...

NEURAL.d: Of, or relating to the nerves, neurons or the nervous system.
NEURAL.e: From Ancient Greek νεῦρον (neûron, “a sinew, nerve”) + -al.

NEURON.d: A cell of the nervous system, which conducts nerve impulses; consisting of an axon and several dendrites. Neurons are connected by synapses.
NEURON.e: From New Latin, from Ancient Greek νεῦρον (neûron, “nerve”), doublet of nerve and sinew. By surface analysis, neuro- + -on.

NEUTER.d: Neutral; on neither side; neither one thing nor another.
NEUTER.e: Inherited from Middle English neutre, from Latin neuter, from ne (“not”) + uter (“whether”), a semantic loan from Koine Greek οὐδέτερος (oudéteros); compare English whether and neither.

NEWBIE.d: A newcomer, someone new to something.
NEWBIE.e: Uncertain: perhaps an alteration of newie with intrusive b (compare freebie), possibly a blend of newborn + baby, or perhaps a shortening of new boy or new beginner.

NEWING.d: Present participle of NEW: Recently made, or created.
NEWING.e:
From Middle English newe, from Old English nīewe, from Proto-West Germanic *niwi, from Proto-Germanic *niwjaz, from Proto-Indo-European *néwyos (“new”), from *néwos. Compare also Old English nū (“now”). More at now. Doublet of nuevo and novuss.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots new (“n...

NEWTON.d: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of force; the force required to accelerate a mass of one kilogram by one metre per second per second.
NEWTON.e: Named after the English scientist Sir Isaac Newton (1642–1726) in 1948.

NIACIN.d: A water-soluble vitamin, a component of vitamin B complex, found in meat, yeast, and dairy products; it is essential to metabolism.
NIACIN.e: in 1942 derived from nicotinic + acid + vitamin, chosen to dissociate it from nicotine, to avoid the perception that vitamins or niacin-rich food contains nicotine, or that cigarettes contain vitamins.

NIBBED.d: Past tense of NIB: The tip of a pen or tool that touches the surface, transferring ink to paper.
NIBBED.e: From a variant of neb, perhaps due to association with nibble.

NIBBER.d: Comparative form of NIB: The tip of a pen or tool that touches the surface, transferring ink to paper.
NIBBER.e: From a variant of neb, perhaps due to association with nibble.

NIBBLE.d: To take a small, quick bite, or several of such bites, of (something).
NIBBLE.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English nebillen, nebyll (“to peck away at (something), nibble; (figurative) to attempt to sing (a part of a song)”); further etymology uncertain, possibly from Middle Low German nibbelen (“to eat in small bites, peck”) (modern German Low Germ...

NICETY.e: From Middle English nicetee, from Old French niceté (“simpleness, foolishness”), from nice (“simple, foolish”); equivalent to nice + -ty.

NICKED.d: Past tense of NICK: A small cut in a surface.
NICKED.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English nik (“notch, tally; nock of an arrow”). Its further etymology is unknown; a connection with nock (“notch in a bow to hold the bowstring; notch at the rear of an arrow that fits the bowstring; cleft in the buttocks”) has not been clearl...

NICKEL.d: A silvery elemental metal with an atomic number of 28 and symbol Ni.
NICKEL.e: Borrowed from German Nickel, first used in a text by the Swedish mineralogist Axel F. Cronstedt as an abbreviation of Kupfernickel (“a mineral containing copper and nickel”), from Kupfer (“copper”) + Nickel (“insignificant person, goblin”), originally nickname of Nikolaus (“Nicho...

NIDIFY.e: First attested in 1656; borrowed from Latin nīdificō (“to build a nest”), from nīdus (“nest”) + -ficō (“to make, build”). Doublet of nidificate and cognate with French nidifier.

NIGGER.d: A black person; a person of black African descent.
NIGGER.e: From Latin niger (“black”). Compare Danish neger, Swedish neger, German Neger, Dutch neger. First use appears c. 1577, in the writings of Edward Hellowes (fl. 1574–1601). The expected Modern English pronunciation would be with /iː/; compare neger. The modern pronunciation with /ɪ...

NIGGLE.e: First attested in 1599. Origin uncertain, but likely borrowed from dialectal Norwegian nigla (“to be stingy, to busy oneself with trifles”), ultimately from Old Norse hnøggr (“stingy; miserly”), related to Old English hnēaw (“stingy; niggardly”). More at niggard.

NIGHTS.d: Plural of NIGHT: The period of darkness.

NILLED.d: Past tense of NIL: Nothing; zero.
NILLED.e:
Borrowed from Latin nīl, a contraction of nihil, nihilum (“nothing”). See
nihilism, nihility.

NIMBLE.e: From Middle English nymyl, nemel, nemyll, nymell (“agile, quick, ready, able, capable”), merger of Old English nǣmel (“receptive, quick to grasp”) and Old English numol (“able to take, capable of holding”), both from niman (“to take”) + -el, -ol (associative suffix), correspondin...

NIMBUS.d: A circle of light; a halo.
NIMBUS.e: Borrowed from Latin nimbus (“dark cloud”). Doublet of nimb.

NINETY.d: The cardinal number occurring after eighty-nine and before ninety-one, represented in Roman numerals as XC and in Arabic numerals as 90.
NINETY.e: From Middle English nynty, nynety, from Old English hundniġontiġ, from Proto-Germanic *newuntēhundą (“ninety”), equivalent to nine + -ty. Cognate with Scots nynty, nynety (“ninety”), Saterland Frisian njuugentich (“ninety”), West Frisian njoggentich (“ninety”), Dutch negentig (“n...

NIPPED.d: Past tense of NIP: To catch and enclose or compress tightly between two surfaces, or points which are brought together or closed; to pinch; to close in upon.
NIPPED.e: From late Middle English nippen, probably of Low German or Dutch origin, probably a byform of earlier *knippen (suggested by the derivative Middle English knippette (“pincers”)), from Middle Low German knîpen, from Old Saxon *knīpan, from Proto-West Germanic *knīpan, ultimately f...

NIPPER.d: Comparative form of NIP: To catch and enclose or compress tightly between two surfaces, or points which are brought together or closed; to pinch; to close in upon.
NIPPER.e: From late Middle English nippen, probably of Low German or Dutch origin, probably a byform of earlier *knippen (suggested by the derivative Middle English knippette (“pincers”)), from Middle Low German knîpen, from Old Saxon *knīpan, from Proto-West Germanic *knīpan, ultimately f...

NIPPLE.d: The projection of a mammary gland from which, on female therian mammals, milk is secreted.
NIPPLE.e: From earlier neple, nypil, neble, believed to be a diminutive of nib, neb (“tip, point”), equivalent to nib + -le. Compare Old English nypel (“elephant trunk”), formed analogously as "a protuberance from one's neb" .

NITROX.d: An industrial process for case hardening (imparting greater surface hardness to) metal objects, involving nitrocarburizing (the diffusion of carbon and nitrogen into the metal) followed by oxidation.
NITROX.e: Blend of nitro(gen) + ox(ygen). Analyzable as nitro- + ox

NITTER.d: Comparative form of NIT: The egg of a louse.
NITTER.e: From Middle English nite, from Old English hnitu, from Proto-Germanic *hnits (compare Dutch neet, German Nisse, Norwegian nit), from Proto-Indo-European *-níd- (compare Scottish Gaelic sneadh, Lithuanian gli̇̀nda, Polish gnida, Albanian thëri, Ancient Greek κονίς (konís)).

NITWIT.e: First attested in the 1910s in the US Northeast. Likely from German nit, dialectal form of nichts (“nothing”), or Yiddish ניט (nit), dialectal form of נישט (nisht, “no”), although some dictionaries give the alternative etymology nit (“louse egg; something very small”) + wit.

NOBBER.d: Comparative form of NOB: The head.
NOBBER.e:
Pronunciation spelling of knob.
Nobleman sense from white-nob (“white-head”) (18th century), referring to the powdered wigs used by those having or affecting upper middle-class status.

NOBODY.d: Not any person; the logical negation of somebody.
NOBODY.e: From Middle English nobody, no-body, no body. By surface analysis, no (“none, not any”, adjective) + body (“one, person, individual”).

NOCKED.d: Past tense of NOCK: Either of the two grooves in a bow that hold the bowstring.
NOCKED.e: From Middle English nokke, attested since the 14th century, probably from a Scandinavian/North Germanic language (compare Swedish nock (“notch”), but compare Dutch nok, from Middle Dutch nocke (“tip, point”). Both could be related to nook (“corner, recess”).

NODDED.d: Past tense of NOD: To incline the head up and down, as to indicate agreement.
NODDED.e: From Middle English nodden, probably from an unrecorded Old English *hnodian (“to nod, shake the head”), from Proto-West Germanic *hnodōn, from Proto-Germanic *hnudōną (“to beat, rivet, pound, push”), from Proto-Indo-European *kendʰ-, from *ken- (“to scratch, scrape, rub”). Compa...

NODDLE.d: The head; the part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth and main sense organs.

NODULE.d: A rounded mass or irregular shape; a small knot or lump.
NODULE.e: Borrowed from Latin nōdulus (“small knot”), from nōdus (“knot”). Doublet of nodulus.

NOETIC.d: Of or pertaining to the mind or intellect.
NOETIC.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek νοητικός (noētikós), ultimately from νοέω (noéō, “I see, understand”).

NOGGIN.d: A small mug, cup or ladle; the contents of such a container.
NOGGIN.e: Uncertain. First use appears c. 1588. Appears in publications in the 1600s (e.g. in The Tincker of Turvey) in several forms including the still-current Irish English form naggin, the rare older Irish, Scottish and Northern English form noggan, used by Jonathan Swift, and the Wexf...

NOISED.d: Past tense of NOISE: A loud or unpleasant sound.

NOISES.d: Plural of NOISE: A loud or unpleasant sound.

NONAGE.d: The state of being under legal age; minority, the fact of being a minor.
NONAGE.e: From Anglo-Norman nounage, corresponding to non- + age.

NOODLE.d: A string or flat strip of pasta or other dough, usually cooked (at least initially) by boiling, and served in soup or in a dry form mixed with a sauce and other ingredients.
NOODLE.e:
Borrowed from Dutch noedel (“noodle”)), or from its etymon German Nudel (“piece of pasta, noodle”); further etymology uncertain, probably a variant of Knödel (“dumpling”), from Middle High German knödel (“dumpling; small knot”), and then either:
* from knode, knote (“knot”) (from...

NOOKED.d: Past tense of NOOK: A small corner formed by two walls; an alcove.
NOOKED.e: From Middle English noke, nok (“nook, corner, angle”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old English hnoc, hnocc (“hook, angle”), from Proto-Germanic *hnukkaz, *hnukkô (“a bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *knewg- (“to turn, press”), from Proto-Indo-European *ken- (“to pinch, pres...

NOONED.d: Past tense of NOON: The time of day when the Sun seems to reach its highest point in the sky; solar noon.
NOONED.e: From Middle English noen, none, non, from Old English nōn (“the ninth hour”), from a Germanic borrowing of classical Latin nōna (“ninth hour”) (short for nōna hōra), feminine of nōnus (“ninth”). Cognate with Dutch noen, obsolete German Non, Norwegian non.

NORMAL.d: According to norms or rules or to a regular pattern.
NORMAL.e: From Latin normālis (“made according to a carpenter's square; later: according to a rule”), from nōrma (“carpenter's square”), of uncertain origin; doublet of normale. The earliest meaning of the word in English was "perpendicular; forming a right angle" like something normālis (...

NORMED.d: Past tense of NORM: That which is normal or typical.
NORMED.e: From Latin norma (“a carpenter's square, a rule, a pattern, a precept”). Doublet of norma.

NORTHS.d: Plural of NORTH: The direction to the left when facing east.

NOSIER.d: Comparative form of NOSY: Prying, inquisitive or curious in other’s affairs; tending to snoop or meddle.

NOSING.d: present participle and gerund of nose

NOSTOC.d: Any member of the genus Nostoc of cyanobacteria, found in a variety of environmental niches, that form colonies composed of filaments of moniliform cells in a gelatinous sheath.

NOTARY.d: A lawyer of noncontentious private civil law who drafts, takes, and records legal instruments for private parties, and provides legal advice, but does not appear in court on his or her clients' behalf.
NOTARY.e: From Middle English notarie, from Old French notarie (French notaire), from Latin notārius.

NOTATE.d: To mark with spots or lines, which are often colored.
NOTATE.e: First attested in 1871; back-formation from notation or from Latin notātus, perfect passive participle of notō; either way, see -ate (verb-forming suffix). By surface analysis, note + -ate.

NOTICE.e: Borrowed from Middle French notice, from the Latin nōtitia. Doublet of notitia.

NOTIFY.e: From Middle English notifien, a borrowing from Old French notifier, notefiier.

NOTING.d: Present participle of NOTE: A symbol or annotation.
NOTING.e: From Middle English note, from Old English not, nōt (“note, mark, sign”) and Old French note (“letter, note”), both from Latin nota (“mark, sign, remark, note”).

NOTION.d: Mental apprehension of whatever may be known, thought, or imagined; idea, concept.
NOTION.e: From Latin nōtiō (“a becoming acquainted, a taking cognizance, an examination, an investigation, a conception, idea, notion”), from nōscō (“to know”). Compare French notion. See know.

NOUGAT.d: A mixture consisting of egg white and a sweetener, variously mixed with (in western Europe) almonds or (in eastern Europe) hazelnuts or (in US) used without nuts as a filler in candy bars.
NOUGAT.e: From French nougat, from Occitan nogat, from noga (“nut”), ultimately from Latin nux (“nut”) + -atus (“-ate, forming adjectives and substantives having or resembling some thing or trait”). Compare Spanish nuégado.

NOUGHT.d: Nothing; something which does not exist.
NOUGHT.e: From Middle English nought, noght, noȝt, from Old English nōwiht, nāwiht, which in turn comes from ne-ā-wiht, which was a phrase used as an emphatic "no", meaning "not anything". Equivalent to ne + ought or ne + a + wight. Doublet of naught and not.

NOUSES.d: Plural of NOUS: The mind or intellect, reason, both rational and emotional
NOUSES.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek νοῦς (noûs) or νόος (nóos, “mind”).

NOVELS.d: Plural of NOVEL: A long fictional story; new and original.

NOVENA.d: A recitation of prayers and devotions for nine consecutive days, especially one to a saint to ask for their intercession.
NOVENA.e: From Ecclesiastical Latin novēna, from Latin novēnus (“nine [each]”).

NOVICE.d: A beginner; one who is not very familiar or experienced in a particular subject.
NOVICE.e: From Middle English novice, novys, from Anglo-Norman novice, Middle French novice, itself borrowed from Latin novīcius, later novitius (“new, newly arrived”) (in Late Latin as a noun, masculine novicius, feminine novicia (“one who has newly entered a monastery or a convent”)), fr...

NOYADE.d: A murder by drowning, especially one of those carried out during the French Reign of Terror.

NOZZLE.d: A short tube, usually tapering, forming the vent of a hose or pipe.
NOZZLE.e: From Middle English noselle, equivalent to nose + -le (diminutive suffix).

NUANCE.e:
Borrowed from French nuance (“nuance, shade, hue”). Several steps omitting from Latin nūbēs.
Compare typologically Italian sfumatura (< Latin fūmus).

NUBBLE.d: Alternative spelling of knubble (“small knob or lump”).
NUBBLE.e: Compare Low German nubben (“to knock, cuff”).

NUBILE.d: Of an age suitable for marriage; marriageable (principally of a young woman).
NUBILE.e: From French nubile, from Latin nūbilis (“marriageable”), from nūbō (“marry, to take as husband”), from Proto-Indo-European *snewbʰ- (“to marry, to wed”). Possibly cognate with Ancient Greek νύμφη (númphē, “bride, young wife, nymph”) (English nymph), but this is disputed.

NUCHAL.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin nuchālis, from nucha + -ālis, from Arabic نُخَاع (nuḵāʕ, “spinal cord”).

NUDISM.d: The belief in or practice of going nude in social, nonsexualized and frequently mixed-gender groups specifically in cultures where going nude in the social situation is not the norm.
NUDISM.e: From French nudisme. By surface analysis, nude + -ism.

NUDITY.d: The state or quality of being without clothing on the body; specifically, the quality of being without clothing on the genitals.
NUDITY.e: From nude + -ity. Compare Late Latin nūditās.

NUGGAR.d: An Arab sailing boat used for trading and transporting supplies.

NUGGET.d: A small, compact chunk or clump.
NUGGET.e: Uncertain, first attested in reference to animals & people in Scotland and in reference to ore chunks in Australia. Possibly from southern English nug (“lump, block”) or Scottish knudge/nudge (“short, sturdy person or animal”) + -et (“forming diminutives”) or from rebracketed alt...

NUMBAT.d: A small marsupial carnivore, Myrmecobius fasciatus, endemic to western Australia, that eats almost exclusively termites.

NUMBED.d: Past tense of NUMB: Physically unable to feel, not having the power of sensation.
NUMBED.e: From the past participle of nim (“to take”). Compare German benommen (“dazed, numb”) and Old Norse numinn. The final ⟨b⟩ is a later addition; it was never pronounced, and did not appear in the original word.

NUMBER.e: From Middle English number, nombre, numbre, noumbre, from Anglo-Norman noumbre, Old French nombre, from Latin numerus (“number”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *nem- (“to divide”). Compare Saterland Frisian Nummer, Nuumer, West Frisian nûmer, Dutch nummer (“number”), German...

NUMDAH.d: An Indian rug or mat made with chain stitch.
NUMDAH.e: From Urdu نمدا (namdā), from Persian [script needed] (namad, “carpet”), probably related to Sanskrit नमत (namata, “something woolen”), नवत (navata, “woolen cloth”).

NUMMUS.d: Any of a range of low-value copper coins issued by the Roman and Byzantine empires during Late Antiquity.
NUMMUS.e: Borrowed from Latin nummus. Doublet of luma.

NUMNAH.d: A pad, often of sheepskin, placed under a horse's saddle; a saddle blanket

NUNCIO.d: The ecclesiastic title of a permanent diplomatic representative of the Roman Catholic Church to a sovereign state or international organization, who is accorded a rank equivalent to an accredited ambassador, and may also be given additional privileges including recognition as Dean in a country's diplomatic corps.
NUNCIO.e:
From Spanish nuncio,
from Latin nūntius (“envoy”).

NUNNED.d: Past tense of NUN: A member of a Christian religious community of women who live by certain vows and usually wear a habit, (Roman Catholicism, specifically) those living together in a cloister.
NUNNED.e: From Middle English nonne, nunne, from Old English nunne (“nun”), from Late Latin nonna (“nun, tutor”), originally (along with masculine form nonnus (“man”)) a term of address for elderly persons, perhaps from children's speech, reminiscent of nana, like papa etc. Doublet of nonn...

NUTATE.e: First attested in 1880; back-formation from nutation (1610s) on the basis of -ate (verb-forming suffix), from Latin nūtātiō (“a nodding”), from nūtō (“to nod”), from Proto-Indo-European *neu-. Compare mutate.

NUTMEG.d: An evergreen tree (Myristica fragrans) cultivated in the East Indies for its spicy seeds.
NUTMEG.e:
From Middle English notemege, notemuge, a partial translation of Medieval Latin nux muga, a variant of Medieval Latin nux muscata (“musky nut”). Compare also Old French nois mugede.
For the term used in various ball sports, see Wikipedia.

NUTRIA.e: From Spanish nutria (“otter”), from Latin lutra.

NUTTED.d: Past tense of NUT: Any of various hard-shelled seeds or hard, dry fruits from various families of plants.
NUTTED.e: From Middle English nute, note, from Old English hnutu, from Proto-West Germanic *hnut, from Proto-Germanic *hnuts (“nut”), from a root *knu- possibly shared with Proto-Celtic *knūs and Latin nux (“nut”). Based on the form of the nouns and the restriction of the root to Germanic,...

NUTTER.e: From Middle English nutter, notere, equivalent to nut + -er.

NUZZLE.d: To push or thrust (the nose or snout, face or muzzle, or head, or an object) against or into something.
NUZZLE.e:
PIE word
 *néh₂s
The verb is derived from Middle English noselen (“to bend down”); further etymology uncertain, possibly:
* a back-formation from noseling, noselyng (“on the back, supine; with the face downward, prone”, adverb), from nose (“nose”) (from Old English nosu, ultimate...

NYMPHA.e: From Latin nympha, from Ancient Greek νύμφη (númphē, “bride, nymph”). Doublet of nymph.

OAFISH.d: Characteristic of or resembling an oaf; clumsy, stupid.

OARAGE.d: The act of using oars; rowing.

OARING.d: Present participle of OAR: A type of lever used to propel a boat, having a flat blade at one end and a handle at the other, and pivoted in a rowlock atop the gunwale, whereby a rower seated in the boat and pulling the handle can pass the blade through the water by repeated strokes against the water's resistance, thus moving the boat.
OARING.e: From Middle English ore (“oar”), from Old English ār, from Proto-West Germanic *airu, from Proto-Germanic *airō (“oar”). Cognate with Old Norse ár.

OATHED.d: Past tense of OATH: A solemn pledge or promise that invokes a deity, a ruler, or another entity (not necessarily present) to attest the truth of a statement or sincerity of one's desire to fulfill a contract or promise.
OATHED.e: From Middle English ooth, oth, ath, from Old English āþ (“oath”), from Proto-West Germanic *aiþ (“oath”), from Proto-Germanic *aiþaz (“oath”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁óytos (“oath”). Cognate with Scots aith, athe (“oath”), North Frisian ith, iss (“oath”), Saterland Frisian Ee...

OBECHE.d: Triplochiton scleroxylon, a tropical tree of Africa.

OBELIA.d: Any of various colonial marine hydroids of the genus Obelia.
OBELIA.e: From Ancient Greek ὀβελία (obelía, “a round cake”).

OBELUS.d: A symbol resembling a horizontal line (–), sometimes together with one or two dots (for example, ⨪ or ÷), which was used in ancient manuscripts and texts to mark a word or passage as doubtful or spurious, or redundant; an obelisk.
OBELUS.e: From Middle English obelus, obelo, from Old English obelus, from Late Latin obelus (“critical mark”), from Koine Greek ὀβελός (obelós, “critical mark”), Ancient Greek ὀβελός (obelós, “rod, spit; obelisk; critical mark”). The further etymology is uncertain; a derivation from βέλος...

OBEREK.d: A lively Polish dance with many lifts and jumps.

OBEYED.d: Past tense of OBEY: To do as ordered by (a person, institution etc), to act according to the bidding of.
OBEYED.e: From Middle English obeyen, from Anglo-Norman obeir, obeier et al., Old French obeir, from Latin oboediō (also obēdiō (“to listen to, harken, usually in extended sense, obey, be subject to, serve”)), from ob- (“before, near”) + audiō (“to hear”). Compare audient. In Latin, ob + a...

OBJECT.d: A thing that has physical existence but is not alive.
OBJECT.e: From Old French object, from Medieval Latin obiectum (“object”, literally “thrown against”), from obiectus, perfect passive participle of obiciō (“I throw against”), from ob- (“against”) + iaciō (“I throw”), as a calque of Ancient Greek ἀντικείμενον (antikeímenon). Doublet of obj...

OBLAST.d: A region or province in Slavic or Slavic-influenced countries.
OBLAST.e: From a Slavic language, probably Russian о́бласть (óblastʹ, “region, province”), borrowed from Old Church Slavonic область (oblastĭ), from Proto-Slavic *obolstь, from earlier *obvolstь, *obvoldtь, a compound of *o(b)- (“over”) + *volstь (“rule, power, authority”), thus originally...

OBLATE.d: A person dedicated to a life of religion or monasticism, especially a member of an order without religious vows or a lay member of a religious community.
OBLATE.e: From French oblat and its source, post-classical Latin oblātus (“person dedicated to religious life”), a nominal use of the past participle of offerō (“I offer”).

OBLIGE.d: To constrain someone by force or by social, moral or legal means.
OBLIGE.e: From Middle English obligen, from Old French obligier, obliger, from Latin obligō, obligāre, from ob- + ligō. Doublet of obligate, taken straight from Latin.

OBLONG.d: Having a length and width that are different; not square or circular.
OBLONG.e: From Middle English oblong, oblonge, borrowed from Latin oblongus.

OBOLUS.d: A silver coin minted in Ancient Greece, valued at a sixth of a drachma.
OBOLUS.e: From Latin obolus, from Ancient Greek ὀβολός (obolós), from ὀβελός (obelós). Doublet of obole and pul.

OBSESS.d: To be preoccupied with a single topic or emotion.
OBSESS.e: From Latin obsessus, perfect passive participle of obsideō (“sit on or in, remain, besiege”), from ob (“before”) + sedeō (“I sit”); see sit, session, etc.; compare assess, possess.

OBTAIN.d: To get hold of; to gain possession of, to procure; to acquire, in any way.
OBTAIN.e: From Middle English obteinen, from Anglo-Norman obtenir, optiner et al., and Middle French obtenir, from Latin obtinēre (“to gain, achieve, succeed, possess”), from ob- + tenēre (“to hold”).

OBTUND.d: To reduce the edge or effects of; to mitigate; to dull.
OBTUND.e: Latin obtundere (“to dull", "deaden", "deafen”), from ob- (see ob-) + tundere. More at obtuse.

OBTUSE.d: Blunt; not sharp, pointed, or acute in form.
OBTUSE.e: From Middle English obtuse, from Latin obtūsus (“blunt, dull; obtuse”), past participle of obtundere, from obtundō (“to batter, beat, strike; to blunt, dull”), from ob- (“against”) (see ob-) + tundō (“to beat, strike; to bruise, crush, pound”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European...

OBVERT.d: To turn so as to show another side.

OCCULT.d: To cover or hide from view.

OCCUPY.e: From Middle English occupien, occupyen, borrowed from Old French occuper, from Latin occupāre (“to take possession of, seize, occupy, take up, employ”), from ob (“to, on”) + capiō (“to take”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p- (“to seize, grab”). Doublet of occupate, no...

OCCURS.d: Plural of OCCUR: To happen; to be found.
OCCURS.e: From Latin occurrere (to run to meet).

OCEANS.d: Plural of OCEAN: A vast body of salt water.
OCEANS.e: From Latin ōceanus, from Greek Ōkeanós.

OCELOT.d: An American feline carnivore (Leopardus pardalis, syn. Felis pardalis) covered with blackish ocellated spots and blotches which are variously arranged.
OCELOT.e: From French ocelot, a word formed by Buffon from Classical Nahuatl ōcēlōtl (“jaguar”).

OCICAT.d: A domestic cat of a breed that is spotted like a wild cat, established from Siamese and Abyssinian stock.

OCTANE.d: Any of the eighteen isomeric aliphatic hydrocarbons (C₈H₁₈) found in petroleum, especially an iso-octane 2,2,4 trimethyl-pentane; they are used as fuels and solvents.

OCTANT.d: The eighth part of a circle; an arc of 45 degrees.
OCTANT.e: From Latin octāns. Doublet of Octans.

OCTAVE.d: An interval of twelve semitones spanning eight degrees of the diatonic scale, representing a doubling or halving in pitch frequency.
OCTAVE.e: From Latin octavus (“eighth”). Doublet of octavo, ochava, and oitava.

OCTAVO.d: A sheet of paper 7 to 10 inches (= 17.78 to 25.4 cm) high and 4.5 to 6 inches (= 11.43 to 15.24 cm) wide, the size varying with the large original sheet used to create it. It is made by folding the original sheet three times to produce eight leaves.
OCTAVO.e: From Latin octavo. Doublet of octave, oitava, and ochava.

OCTILE.d: Any of the quantiles that divide an ordered sample population into eight equally numerous subsets.

OCTOSE.d: A sugar or saccharide containing eight carbon atoms.

OCTROI.d: A privilege granted by the sovereign authority, such as the exclusive right of trade granted to a guild or society; a concession.
OCTROI.e: Borrowed from French octroi, from Middle French octroy, alteration of Old French otroi, from otroier (“to grant”), from Late Latin auctōrizāre.

OCULAR.d: Of, or relating to the eye, or the sense of sight
OCULAR.e: Derived from the Latin oculāris (“of the eye”), from oculus (“eye”).

OCULUS.d: A window or other opening that has an oval or circular shape (as of an eye).
OCULUS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin oculus (“eye”). Doublet of occhio.

ODDITY.d: An odd or strange thing or opinion.

ODIOUS.d: Arousing or meriting strong dislike, aversion, or intense displeasure.
ODIOUS.e: From Middle English odious, from Old French odieus, from Latin odiōsus, from odium (“hate”).

OEUVRE.d: A work of art, music or literature.
OEUVRE.e: From French œuvre, from Old French uevre, from Latin opera (plural of Latin opus), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃ep- (“work”). Doublet of opera, opus, and ure.

OFFEND.d: To hurt the feelings of; to displease; to make angry; to insult.
OFFEND.e: From Middle French offendre, from Latin offendō (“strike, blunder, commit an offense”), from ob- (“against”) + *fendō (“strike”).

OFFERS.d: Plural of OFFER: To present for acceptance; a proposal.
OFFERS.e: From Old English offrian, from Latin offerre.

OFFICE.d: A ceremonial duty or service, particularly
OFFICE.e: From Middle English office, from Old French office, from Latin officium (“personal, official, or moral duty; official position; function; ceremony, esp. last rites”), contracted from opificium (“construction: the act of building or the thing built”), from opifex (“doer of work, c...

OFFING.d: The area of the sea in which a ship can be seen in the distance from land, excluding the parts nearest the shore, and beyond the anchoring ground.
OFFING.e: From off + -ing. Attested since before 1600. Early texts also spell the term offin and offen.

OFFSET.d: Anything that acts as counterbalance; a compensating equivalent.
OFFSET.e: From off- + set, used to construct the noun form of the verb to set off. Compare Middle English ofsetten (“to encumber, harass, beset, besiege”), from Old English ofsettan (“to press, oppress, overwhelm, crush”).

OFTENS.d: Plural of OFTEN: Frequently; many times.

OGLING.d: Present participle of OGLE: To stare at (someone or something), especially impertinently, amorously, or covetously.
OGLING.e: 17th century. Probably from Low German ögeln (“to ogle, to flirt with one's eyes”), from Middle Low German ö̂gelen, frequentative of Middle Low German ö̂gen, from Old Saxon ōgian, from Proto-West Germanic *augijan (“to show”). Alternatively from an equivalent Dutch *ogelen, but t...

OGRESS.e: Borrowed in the early 1700s from French ogresse, equivalent to ogre + -ess. Piecewise doublet of orcess.

OHMAGE.d: An amount of electrical resistance measured in ohms.

OILCAN.d: A container with a long spout, for holding oil and delivering it in drops or small quantities for lubrication.

OILERY.d: The business of producing oil from plants or animals.

OILIER.d: Comparative form of OILY: Covered with or containing oil.
OILIER.e: From Middle English oylei, equivalent to oil + -y. Compare German ölig (“oily”), Swedish oljig (“oily”).

OILING.d: Present participle of OIL: Liquid fat.
OILING.e: From Middle English oyle, oile (“olive oil”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman olie, from Latin oleum (“oil, olive oil”), from Ancient Greek ἔλαιον (élaion, “olive oil”), from ἐλαία (elaía, “olive”). Compare Proto-Slavic *lojь. More at olive. Doublet of oleum. Supplanted Middle English...

OINKED.d: Past tense of OINK: Representing the grunting sound made by a pig.

OKAYED.d: Past tense of OKAY: Alternative spelling of OK.

OLEATE.d: Any salt or ester of oleic acid.

OLEFIN.d: Any of a class of unsaturated open-chain hydrocarbons such as ethylene; an alkene with only one carbon-carbon double bond.

OMASUM.d: The third compartment of the stomach of a ruminant; the lining of said compartment, regarded as a foodstuff.

OMENED.d: Past tense of OMEN: Something which portends or is perceived to portend either a good or evil event or circumstance in the future, or which causes a foreboding; a portent or augury.

ONAGER.d: The Asiatic wild ass or hemione (Equus hemionus), an animal of the horse family native to Asia; specifically, the Persian onager, Persian wild ass, or Persian zebra (Equus hemionus onager).
ONAGER.e: From Middle English onager, onagir (“wild ass; military catapult”), from Anglo-Norman onager, Middle French onager, onagre, Old French onager, onagre (“wild ass; military catapult”) (modern French onagre), from Late Latin onager (“large siege engine”), Latin onager (“wild ass”), ...

ONESIE.e: From the Gerber Childrenswear brand name Onesies. The name became generic and was reinterpreted as a plural, hence the new singular and decapitalized onesie. Equivalent to one + -sie.

ONFALL.d: A falling on or upon; an attack, onset, or assault.
ONFALL.e: From Middle English onfal, onfalle, equivalent to on- + fall. Cognate with Dutch aanval (“an attack, assault”), German Anfall (“an attack, seizure, fit”), Swedish anfall (“an attack, offensive, assault”). Compare also Middle English onfallynge (“an onslaught, attack”).

ONRUSH.d: A forceful rush or flow forward.
ONRUSH.e: From on- + rush. Compare Middle English onresen (“to rush upon; attack”), from Old English onrǣsan (“to rush, rush on”); Old English onrǣs (“an onrush, assault, attack”).

ONUSES.d: Plural of ONUS: A legal obligation.
ONUSES.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *h₃enh₂-
Proto-Indo-European *-os
Proto-Indo-European *h₃énh₂os
Proto-Italic *onos
Latin onuslbor.
English onus
Learned borrowing from Latin onus (literally “burden”).

ONYXES.d: Plural of ONYX: A banded variety of chalcedony, a cryptocrystalline form of quartz.
ONYXES.e: From Middle English onix (c. 1300), earlier oniche (c. 1250), from Old French oniche or onix, from Latin onyx, from Ancient Greek ὄνυξ (ónux, “onyx”). Doublet of unguis.

OOCYTE.d: A cell that develops into an egg or ovum; a female gametocyte.

OOGAMY.d: A form of anisogamy (heterogamy) in which the female gamete (e.g. ovum) is significantly larger than the male gamete (sperm) and is non-motile.

OOHING.d: Present participle of OOH: An expression of surprise.

OOLITE.d: A rock consisting of spherical grains within a mineral cortex accreted around a nucleus, often of quartz grains.

OOLOGY.e: From oo- (prefix meaning ‘relating to eggs or ova’) + -logy (suffix indicating a branch of learning or study of a subject). The word is cognate with French oologie, Late Latin oologia.

OOLONG.d: A partially fermented tea, often roasted, which combines the characteristics of green tea and black tea.
OOLONG.e: 1850s. From either Mandarin 烏龍 /乌龙 (wūlóng) due to hypercorrection, or directly from Hokkien 烏龍 /乌龙 (o͘-liông), from 烏 /乌 (o͘, “black”) + 龍 /龙 (liông, “dragon”). See also pouchong from Hokkien 包種茶 /包种茶 (pau-chióng-tê, literally “tea of the wrapped kind”).

OOZIER.d: Comparative form of OOZY: Of or pertaining to the quality of something that oozes.

OOZING.d: Present participle of OOZE: Tanning liquor, an aqueous extract of vegetable matter (tanbark, sumac, etc.) in a tanning vat used to tan leather.
OOZING.e:
* (Noun) Middle English wose (“sap”), from Old English wōs (“sap, froth”), from Proto-Germanic *wōsą (cf. Middle Low German wose (“scum”), Old High German wasal (“rain”), Old Swedish os, oos), from Proto-Indo-European *wóseh₂ (“sap”) (cf. Sanskrit वसा (vásā, “fat”)).
* (Verb) Mid...

OPALED.d: Past tense of OPAL: A mineral consisting, like quartz, of silica, but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific gravity, of the chemical formula SiO₂·nH₂O.
OPALED.e: In Florio’s A World of Words 1598 as opale, from French opale, from Latin opalus, from Byzantine Greek ὀπάλλιος (opállios), from Sanskrit उपल (upala, “gem, stone”), from उपरि (upári, “the upper millstone”). Distantly related to over.

OPANKA.d: A kind of sandal worn in Eastern Europe.

OPAQUE.e: From Middle English opake, from Latin opacus (“shaded, shady, dark”) (of unknown origin), later reinforced from Middle French opaque. Doublet of ubac.

OPCODE.d: A mnemonic used to refer to a microprocessor instruction in assembly language.
OPCODE.e: From op + code (in sense of operation).

OPENED.d: simple past and past participle of open

OPERAD.d: A set of operations, each one having a fixed finite number of arguments and one output, which can be composed with others.

OPERON.d: A unit of genetic material that functions in a coordinated manner by means of an operator, a promoter, and structural genes that are transcribed together.

OPHITE.d: Any of various rocks having snake-like markings, such as a mottled greenish porphyry.
OPHITE.e: From Latin ophites, from Ancient Greek ὀφίτης (ophítēs) (Etymology 2, below). Compare Ophite.

OPIATE.d: Relating to, resembling, or containing opium.
OPIATE.e: From Middle English opiate, from Medieval Latin opiātus.

OPIOID.d: A substance that has effects similar to opium:
OPIOID.e: Attested 1963; from opium + -oid, to distinguish from opiate.

OPPOSE.d: To attempt to stop the progression of; to resist or antagonize by physical means, or by arguments, etc.; to contend against.
OPPOSE.e: From Middle English opposen, from Old French opposer, from Latin ob (“before, against”) + Medieval Latin pono (“to put”), taking the place of Latin opponere (“to oppose”).

OPPUGN.d: To contradict or controvert; to oppose; to challenge or question the truth or validity of a given statement.
OPPUGN.e: From Middle French oppugner Latin oppugno (“fight against, to attack, assail, assault, storm, besiege, war with”).

OPTANT.d: A person who lives in a region undergoing a change of sovereignty and thus may choose between retaining their old citizenship or opting for the citizenship of the new sovereignty.
OPTANT.e: Partly (sense 1) borrowed from German Optant or Danish optant (both attested since 1907), partly from opt + ant.

OPTIME.d: A student who graduates with second class ("senior optime") or third class ("junior optime") honours in mathematics, or (loosely) in any other subject.
OPTIME.e: Borrowed from Latin optimē (“very well”), in the phrase optimē disputāstī (“you have disputed very well”), formerly used in reporting results at Cambridge.

OPTING.d: Present participle of OPT: To choose; select.
OPTING.e: First attested in 1853; borrowed from French opter, from Latin optō (“to choose; to select”). Doublet of optate.

OPTION.d: One of a set of choices that can be made.
OPTION.e: From French option, from Latin optiō (“choice; option; act of choosing”), from optō (“I choose, select”). Equivalent to opt + -ion.

OPUSES.d: Plural of OPUS: A work of music or set of works with a specified rank in an ordering of a composer's complete published works.

ORACLE.d: A shrine dedicated to some prophetic deity.
ORACLE.e: From Middle English oracle, from Old French oracle m, from Latin ōrāculum n.

ORANGE.d: An evergreen tree of the genus Citrus such as Citrus sinensis which yields oranges (the fruit).
ORANGE.e:
Etymology tree

Latin mālum
Italian mela
Proto-Austroasiatic *ŋaːmder.?

Italian arancia

ORATOR.d: Someone who orates or delivers an oration.
ORATOR.e: From Middle English oratour, from Anglo-Norman oratour, from Latin ōrātor.

ORBING.d: Present participle of ORB: A spherical body; a sphere, especially one of the celestial spheres; a sun, planet, or star
ORBING.e: From Middle English orbe, from Old French orbe, from Latin orbis (“circle, orb”). Compare orbit.

ORCEIN.d: a dye, related to litmus, that is extracted from the lichen Rocella tinctoria; used as a microscopic stain and as a food colouring
ORCEIN.e: From French orcéine, modification of orcinol. See also orchil.

ORCHID.d: A plant of the orchid family (Orchidaceae), bearing unusually-shaped flowers of beautiful colours.
ORCHID.e: From New Latin Orchideae, Orchidaceae, an irregular formation from Latin orchis, from Ancient Greek ὄρχις (órkhis, “orchid, testicle”) (ostensibly from the shape of the roots). Supplanted Middle English ballokwort (literally “testicle plant”).

ORCHIL.d: Any of several lichens, especially those of the genera Roccella and Lecanora.
ORCHIL.e: From Middle English orchell, from Old French orchel, orseil, from Old Catalan orxella (influenced by dialectal Arabic [script needed] ('urjālla)), from Italian oricello, from Latin ōricilla, diminutive of ōricula (variant of auricula), both diminutives of auris (“ear”)) + illa (a...

ORDAIN.e: From Middle English ordeynen, from Old French ordiner, from Latin ordinare (“to order”), from ordo (“order”). Doublet of ordinate.

ORDEAL.d: A trial in which the accused was subjected to a dangerous test (such as ducking in water), divine authority deciding the guilt of the accused.
ORDEAL.e: From Middle English ordel, ordal, from Medieval Latin ordālium or inherited from its source Old English ordēl, ordāl (“ordeal, judgement”), from Proto-West Germanic *uʀdailī (“judgement”, literally “an out-dealing”), from *uʀdailijan (“to deal out; dispense”), equivalent to or- +...

ORDERS.d: Plural of ORDER: An arrangement; a command.
ORDERS.e: From Old French ordre, from Latin ōrdō.

ORDURE.e: From Middle English ordure, ordure, borrowed from Middle French ordure and Anglo-Norman ordure, ordeur(e), ordor(e), ordour from Old French ordure (“dirt, filth, refuse; dung, excrement; moral filth”) (modern French ordure), from ord (“filthy”) + -ure (suffix forming nouns descri...

ORGASM.e: From French orgasme or New Latin orgasmus, from Ancient Greek ὀργασμός (orgasmós, “excitement, swelling”), from ὀργάω (orgáō, “to swell with moisture”).

ORGEAT.d: A sweet syrup made from sugar and almonds (or originally barley) and rose water or orange-flower water.
ORGEAT.e:
From French orgeat, derived from orge (“barley”), from Latin hordeum.
Doublet of horchata and orzo. Cognate to Surinamese Dutch orgeade.

ORGIES.d: Plural of ORGY: A secret rite or ceremony, typically involving riotous and dissolute behavior, including dancing, drunkenness and indiscriminate sexual activity, undertaken in honor of various pagan gods or goddesses (such as Attis, Bacchus, Ceres, Dionysus, Osiris, etc).
ORGIES.e: Originally in plural from French orgies, from Latin orgia, from Ancient Greek ὄργια (órgia, “secret rites, mysteries”).

ORGONE.d: In the psychoanalytic theory of Wilhelm Reich, a form of sexual energy or life force distributed throughout the universe and available for collection, storage, and further use.
ORGONE.e: Blend of organism + hormone, after German Orgon.

ORIENT.d: Usually preceded by the: alternative letter-case form of Orient (“a region or a part of the world to the east of a certain place; countries of Asia, the East (especially East Asia)”)
ORIENT.e: The noun is derived from Middle English orient, oriente, oryent, oryente, oryentte (“the east direction; eastern horizon or sky; eastern regions of the world, Asia, Orient; eastern edge of the world”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman orient, oriente, and Old French orient (“east direc...

ORIGAN.d: Alternative form of oregano (“wild marjoram, Origanum vulgare”).

ORIGIN.e: From Middle English origine, origyne, from Old French origine, orine, ourine, from Latin origo (“beginning, source, birth, origin”), from orior (“to rise”); see orient. Doublet of origo.

ORIOLE.d: Any of various colourful passerine birds, New World orioles of the genus Icterus (family Icteridae) and Old World orioles of the family Oriolidae.
ORIOLE.e: A borrowing from Middle French oriol, from Old French oriol, from Latin aureolus, diminutive of aureus (“golden”). Doublet of aureole. First use appears c. 1776 in the writings of Thomas Pennant.

ORISON.e: From Middle English orisoun, from Anglo-Norman oreison, oresoun etc. and Old French oraisun etc., from Latin ōrātiō, ōrātiōnem (“discourse, prayer”) (whence also English oration).

ORMOLU.d: Golden or gilded brass or bronze used for decorative purposes.

ORNATE.e: Learned borrowing from Latin ōrnātus, perfect passive participle of ōrnō (“to equip, adorn”), see -ate (adjective-forming suffix). Doublet of orné.

OROGEN.d: Rock deformed by orogeny; a belt of such rock(s).

OROIDE.d: An alloy of copper and zinc or tin that has a gold color, used in making inexpensive jewelry.
OROIDE.e: From French, from or (“gold”) + Ancient Greek εἶδος (eîdos, “appearance”, “shape”, “form”).

ORPHAN.d: A person, especially a minor, both or (rarely) one of whose parents have died.
ORPHAN.e:
Late Middle English, from Late Latin orphanus, from Ancient Greek ὀρφανός (orphanós, “without parents, fatherless”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃órbʰos.
 PIE word
 *h₃órbʰos
Cognate with Sanskrit अर्भ (árbha), Latin orbus (“orphaned”), Old High German erbi, arbi (German Erbe (“he...

ORRERY.d: A clockwork model of any given solar system.
ORRERY.e: Named after Charles Boyle, 4th Earl of Orrery (1676–1731), for whom such a device was made. The placename is from Irish Orbhraighe, originally the name of a tribe (Orbh-raighe (“Orb's people”)), and then of a territory and a barony.

OSCINE.d: Of or pertaining to songbirds (suborder Passeri).

OSMIUM.d: A chemical element (symbol Os) with atomic number 76: a hard, brittle, heavy, bluish-white transition metal found as a trace element in alloys, mostly in platinum ores.
OSMIUM.e: From Ancient Greek ὀσμή (osmḗ, “smell”) (because of the strong smell of its oxide) + -ium.

OSPREY.d: A bird of prey of genus Pandion that feeds on fish and has white underparts and long, narrow wings each ending in four finger-like extensions.
OSPREY.e: From Late Middle English ospray, from Anglo-Norman ospriet, from Medieval Latin avis praedae (“bird of prey”), a generic term apparently confused with this specific bird in Old French on its similarity to ossifrage.

OSSIFY.d: To transform (or cause to transform) from a softer animal substance into bone; particularly the processes of growth in humans and animals.
OSSIFY.e: Back-formation from ossification, or modeled on French ossifier and formed from Latin os, ossis (“bone”) + -ify.

OSTIUM.d: A small opening or orifice, as in a body organ or passage.

OSTLER.d: A person employed at an inn, hostelry, or stable to look after horses; a groom
OSTLER.e: Phonetic spelling of hostler, from late 14th century.

OSTOMY.d: A surgical procedure to provide an exit point for the waste of an organism.
OSTOMY.e: Back-formation from colostomy, ileostomy, gastrostomy, and similar terms.

OUCHES.d: Plural of OUCH: An expression of one's own physical pain.
OUCHES.e: Uncertain. Some sources say the interjection is attested since 1838 (and specifically in American English) and derives ultimately from German autsch, perhaps specifically via Pennsylvania German outch (“cry of pain”), as early attestations of the interjection are from Pennsylvani...

OUGHTS.d: Plural of OUGHT: Used to indicate duty or correctness.

OUSTED.d: Past tense of OUST: To expel; to remove.
OUSTED.e: From Anglo-Norman ouster, oustier, from Old French oster (modern French ôter), from post-classical Latin obstare (“to remove”), classical obstāre (“to obstruct, stand in the way of”). Not related to out.

OUTAGE.d: A temporary suspension of operation, especially of electrical power supply.
OUTAGE.e: From out + -age, on the model of shortage.

OUTBID.d: To bid more than (somebody else) in an auction.

OUTBOX.d: A box holding papers to be transmitted to others, usually by mail.

OUTCRY.e:
From Middle English outcry, outcri, outcrye, equivalent to out- + cry.
The verb is from Middle English outcrien.

OUTFIT.e: Variant of earlier out-fit, from fit out. Equivalent to out- + fit.

OUTFLY.d: To fly better, faster, or further than.

OUTFOX.d: To beat (someone) in a competition of wits with superior cleverness or cunning; to outsmart.

OUTGAS.d: To release gaseous substances into the air, especially of a polymer material as it is aged or heated.

OUTGUN.d: To defeat in terms of firepower.

OUTING.e: From out + -ing. Compare Old English yting ("outing, journey").

OUTLAW.e: From Middle English outlawe, outlagh, utlaȝe, from Old English ūtlaga (“outlaw”), borrowed from Old Norse útlagi (“outlaw, fugitive”), equivalent to out- + law. Cognate with Icelandic útlagi (“outlaw”).

OUTLAY.d: A laying out or expending; that which is laid out or expended.

OUTLET.d: A vent or similar passage to allow the escape of something.
