OUTLET.e: From Middle English outlete, outeleate, ut-lete, derived from Middle English outleten (“to allow, let out, emit”), equivalent to out- + let. Compare West Frisian útlit (“outlet”), Dutch uitlaat (“outlet”), German Auslass (“outlet”).

OUTLIE.d: To tell more or better lies than.
OUTLIE.e: From out- + lie (in the sense of "tell an untruth").

OUTMAN.d: To have more people than (one's competitor); to outnumber in men.

OUTPUT.d: That which is produced by something, especially that which is produced within a particular time period or from a particular effort.
OUTPUT.e: From out + (verb) put; nominalisation of put out.

OUTWIT.d: To get the better of; to outsmart, to beat in a competition of wits.

OVENED.d: Past tense of OVEN: A chamber used for baking or heating.
OVENED.e: From Middle English oven, from Old English ofn, from Proto-West Germanic *ofn, from Proto-Germanic *uhnaz, *uhwnaz (compare Dutch oven, Low German Aven, West Frisian ûne, German Ofen, Danish ovn, Norwegian Bokmål ovn, Norwegian Nynorsk omn, Swedish ugn, Icelandic ofn, Finnish uun...

OVERDO.d: To do too much; to exceed what is proper or true in doing; to carry too far.
OVERDO.e: From Middle English overdon, from Old English oferdōn, equivalent to over- + do.

OVERED.d: Past tense of OVER: Finished; ended; concluded.
OVERED.e:
From Middle English over, from Old English ofer, from Proto-West Germanic *obar, from Proto-Germanic *uber (“over”), from Proto-Indo-European *upér, related to *upó.
Akin to Scots ower (“over”), Yola oer, ower, owr (“over”), Saterland Frisian uur (“over”), West Frisian oer (“over...

OVULAR.d: Of or pertaining to an ovule.
OVULAR.e: From ovule + -ar. In the feminist sense, chosen as an opposite to seminar because of that term's etymological link with semen, the male sexual fluid.

OWLDOM.d: The realm or sphere of owls.

OWLING.d: Present participle of OWL: Any of various birds of prey of the order Strigiformes, families Strigidae and Tytonidae, that are primarily nocturnal and have forward-looking, binocular vision, limited eye movement, and good hearing.
OWLING.e: From Middle English oule, owle, from Old English ūle, from Proto-West Germanic *uwwilā, from Proto-Germanic *uwwalǭ (compare West Frisian ûle, Dutch uil, Danish and Norwegian ugle, German Eule), diminutive of *uwwǭ (“eagle-owl”) (compare German Uhu), of imitative origin or a vari...

OWLISH.d: Resembling or characteristic of an owl.

OWLISM.d: Affected or pretentious wisdom; pompous dullness; bombast.

OWNERS.d: Plural of OWNER: A person who owns something.

OWNING.d: Present participle of OWN: Belonging to; possessed; acquired; proper to; property of; titled to; held in one's name; under/using the name of. Often marks a possessive determiner as reflexive, referring back to the subject of the clause or sentence.
OWNING.e:
From Middle English owen, aȝen, from Old English āgen (“own, proper, peculiar”), originally the past participle of āgan; from Proto-West Germanic *aigan (“own”), from Proto-Germanic *aiganaz (“own”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eyḱ- (“to have, possess”).
Cognates
Cognate with Sco...

OXALIS.d: Any of various ornamental flowering plants of the genus Oxalis

OXBACK.d: The back of an ox (being ridden, or laden with luggage, as a means of transportation).
OXBACK.e: From ox + back, modelled on horseback.

OXCART.d: A cart designed to be drawn by an ox or oxen.

OXGANG.d: The area of land that could be plowed by an ox in a year, ¹⁄₈ hide or carucate and notionally 15 acres.
OXGANG.e: From Middle English oxegang, from Old English oxangang (“¹⁄₈ hide or ploughland”), equivalent to ox + gang.

OXHERD.e: From Middle English oxeherde, oxherd, oxhyrde, from Old English oxanhierde, equivalent to ox + herd. Cognate with German Ochsenhirt (“oxherd”).

OXISOL.d: A soil type, containing at all depths no more than ten percent weatherable minerals, and low cation exchange capacity. They are always red or yellowish and best known for their occurrence in tropical rainforest.

OXTAIL.d: The tail of an ox or cow.
OXTAIL.e: From Middle English ox tayll, from Old English oxan tæġl (literally “ox's tail”), equivalent to ox + tail.

OXYGEN.d: The chemical element (symbol O) with an atomic number of 8 and relative atomic mass of 15.9994. It is a colorless and odorless gas.
OXYGEN.e: Borrowed from French oxygène (originally in the form principe oxygène, a variant of principe oxigine ‘acidifying principle’, suggested by Lavoisier), from Ancient Greek ὀξύς (oxús, “sharp”) + γένος (génos, “birth”), referring to oxygen's supposed role in the formation of acids. B...

OYSTER.d: Any of certain marine bivalve mollusks, especially those of the family Ostreidae (the true oysters), usually found adhering to rocks or other fixed objects in shallow water along the seacoasts, or in brackish water in the mouth of rivers.
OYSTER.e: From Middle English oystre, from Old English ostre, reinforced or superseded by Anglo-Norman oistre, which is from Old French oistre, uistre (compare modern French huître); both lines (Old English and Old French) from Latin ostrea, from Ancient Greek ὄστρεον (óstreon). Doublet of...

PACIFY.d: To bring peace to (a place or situation), by ending war, fighting, violence, anger or agitation.
PACIFY.e: From Middle French pacifier, from Latin pāx (“peace”) + faciō (“I do, make”). Cognate with pay and peacify.

PACING.d: Present participle of PACE: A step.
PACING.e: From Middle English pase, from Anglo-Norman pas, Old French pas, and their source, Latin passus. Doublet of pas and fathom; compare also pass. Cognate with Spanish pasear.

PACKED.d: Past tense of PACK: A bundle made up and prepared to be carried; especially, a bundle to be carried on the back, but also a load for an animal, a bale.
PACKED.e:
From Middle English pak, pakke, from Old English *pæcca and/or Middle Dutch pak, packe; both ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *pakkō, from Proto-Germanic *pakkô (“bundle, pack”).
Cognate with Dutch pak (“pack”), Low German Pack (“pack”), German Pack (“pack”), Swedish packe (“p...

PACKET.d: A small pack or package; a little bundle or parcel
PACKET.e: From Middle English pacquet; either from Middle French pacquet, or formed independently from pak and -et.

PADAUK.d: Any of the trees of the pantropical genus Pterocarpus.
PADAUK.e: From Burmese ပိတောက် (pi.tauk).

PADDED.d: Past tense of PAD: A flattened mass of anything soft, to sit or lie on.
PADDED.e: 1554, "bundle of straw to lie on", probably from Low German or West Flemish pad (“sole of the foot”), perhaps ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *pent- (“to pass”), which would make it related to both path and find.

PADDER.d: Agent noun of pad; one who pads.

PADDLE.d: A two-handed implement consisting of a shaft with one or two blades attached to the end(s) used to propel a canoe, kayak or a small boat. A paddle is unattached to the boat and freely operated with the hands, compared with an oar which is attached to the boat at a pivot point.
PADDLE.e:
Partly from the verb paddle ("to splash, dabble"; see below) and partly from Middle English padell (“small spade”).
Middle English padell is from Medieval Latin padela, itself of uncertain origin: perhaps an alteration of Middle English *spaddle (see also spaddle), a diminutive o...

PAELLA.d: A savory Valencian dish made of rice, cooked in a frying pan with vegetables and meat or shellfish.
PAELLA.e: Borrowed from Catalan paella (“pot; pan”), from Old French paelle, from Latin patella (“plate, small pan”). Doublet of patella and possibly pail.

PAGING.d: Present participle of PAGE: One of the many pieces of paper bound together within a book or similar document.
PAGING.e: Borrowed from Middle French page, from Latin pāgina, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ǵ-. Doublet of pagina.

PAGODA.d: A religious building in South and Southeast Asia, especially a multi-storey tower erected as a Hindu or Buddhist temple.
PAGODA.e: From Portuguese pagode, which is via Malayalam പകോതി (pakōti) from Sanskrit भगवती (bhagavatī, name of a goddess).

PAINTS.d: Plural of PAINT: A coloured substance; to apply paint.
PAINTS.e: From Old French peint, from Latin pingere.

PAIRED.d: Past tense of PAIR: Two similar or identical things taken together; often followed by of.
PAIRED.e: From Middle English paire, from Old French paire, from Latin paria (“equals”), neuter plural of par (“pair”). Related to pār (“equal”, adjective). Compare Saterland Frisian Poor (“pair”), West Frisian pear (“pair”), Dutch paar (“pair”), German Paar (“pair”), Italian paio (“pair”)

PAKORA.d: A piece of vegetable, or sometimes meat, deep-fried in a batter flavoured with spices.

PALACE.d: Official residence of a head of state or other dignitary, especially in a monarchical or imperial governmental system.
PALACE.e: From Middle English paleys, from Old French palais, which comes from Latin palātium, from Palātium, in reference to the Palatine (Palatine Hill), one of the seven hills of Rome, where the aristocracy of the Roman Republic—and later, Roman emperors—built large, splendid residences...

PALATE.d: The roof of the mouth, separating the cavities of the mouth and nose in vertebrates.
PALATE.e: From Middle English palate, from Latin palātum (“roof of the mouth, palate”), perhaps of Etruscan origin.

PALING.d: present participle and gerund of pale

PALLED.d: Past tense of PAL: Acronym of phase alternating/alternation/alternated line (TV standard).

PALLET.e: From Middle English paillet, from Anglo-Norman paillete (“bundle of straw”), from Old French paille (“straw, chaff”), from Latin palea (“chaff”).

PALLID.e: From Latin pallidus. Doublet of pale.

PALLOR.d: Unnatural paleness, especially as a sign of sickness or distress.
PALLOR.e: From Middle English pallour, from Old French palor (“paleness, pallor”), from Latin pallor, from palleō (“to look pale, blanch”).

PALMED.d: Past tense of PALM: Any of various evergreen trees from the family Palmae or Arecaceae, which are mainly found in the tropics.
PALMED.e: From Middle English palme, from Old English palm, palma (“palm-tree, palm-branch”), from Latin palma (“palm-tree, palm-branch, palm of the hand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₂meh₂, *pl̥h₂emeh₂ (“palm of the hand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₂- (“flat”). Cognate with Dutch ...

PALMER.d: An English surname transferred from the nickname.
PALMER.e: From Middle English palmer (“a pilgrim from the Holy Land”), from Old French.

PALPED.d: Past tense of PALP: Synonym of pedipalp.
PALPED.e:
* (verb): From French palper.
* (noun): From New Latin palpus (“a feeler”).
* Both ultimately from Latin palpō (“to stroke, touch softly, feel”).

PALTER.d: To talk insincerely; to prevaricate or equivocate in speech or actions.
PALTER.e: Probably from Middle English *palter (“rag, trifle, worthless thing”), from Middle Low German palter (“rag, cloth”). More at paltry.

PALTRY.e: From Middle Low German paltrig (“ragged, rubbishy, worthless”), from palter, palte (“cloth, rag, shred”), from Old Saxon *paltro, *palto (“cloth, rag”), from Proto-Germanic *paltrô, *paltô (“scrap, rag, patch”). Of uncertain ultimate origin, but perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *...

PAMPAS.d: The extensive plains of South America south of the Amazon.
PAMPAS.e: From (plural of) American Spanish pampa, from Quechua pampa (“land, ground”).

PAMPER.d: To treat with excessive care, attention or indulgence.
PAMPER.e:
From Middle English pamperen (“to cram with food”), from Middle Dutch *pamperen (“to cram with food”), frequentative of *pampen (“to stuff”), from Proto-Germanic *pamp- (“to swell”), from Proto-Indo-European *bamb- (“round object”), equivalent to pamp + -er.
Cognate with West Fle...

PANADA.d: A dish made by boiling bread in water and combining the pulp with milk, stock, butter or sometimes egg yolks.

PANAMA.d: A country in Central America. Official name: Republic of Panama.
PANAMA.e: Borrowed from Spanish Panamá, of unknown origin. Possibly from a Chibchan language such as Kuna, or another indigenous language of the region (such as Cueva, which is barely attested and is now extinct).

PANDAN.d: A screw pine, screw palms (Pandanus spp.).
PANDAN.e: Borrowed from Malay pandan, ultimately from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *paŋdan. Doublet of hala via Hawaiian.

PANDER.d: A person who furthers the illicit love-affairs of others; a pimp or procurer.
PANDER.e: From Middle English pandare, from Chaucer’s character Pandare (in Troilus and Criseyde; see also Shakespeare’s Troilus and Cressida), from Italian Pandaro (found in Boccaccio), from Latin Pandarus (found in Greek mythology), from Ancient Greek Πάνδαρος (Pándaros).

PANDIT.d: An honorary title for a learned man or scholar.
PANDIT.e: From Sanskrit पण्डित (paṇḍita). Doublet of pundit.

PANELS.d: Plural of PANEL: A flat section; a group of experts.
PANELS.e: From Old French panel, from Latin pannus (cloth).

PANFUL.d: As much as a pan will hold.
PANFUL.e: From Middle English panne vol; equivalent to pan + -ful.

PANGED.d: Past tense of PANG: A paroxysm of extreme physical pain or anguish; a feeling of sudden and transitory agony; a throe.
PANGED.e: The origin of the noun is uncertain; it is possibly derived from Middle English *pange, perhaps an altered form of prange, prōnge (“affliction, agony, pain; pointed instrument”) as in prongys of deth (“pangs of death, death throes”), from Anglo-Latin pronga, of unknown origin. Pe...

PANINI.e: Borrowed from Italian panini, plural of panino (literally “small bread”).

PANINO.d: A type of grilled sandwich made of a small loaf of bread, cut horizontally, filled with meat such as salami or ham, cheese or other food.

PANNED.d: Past tense of PAN: Greek god of nature, often visualized as half goat and half man playing pipes. His Roman counterpart is Faunus.
PANNED.e: From Middle English Pan, from Latin Pān, from Ancient Greek Πάν (Pán).

PANNER.d: Comparative form of PAN: Greek god of nature, often visualized as half goat and half man playing pipes. His Roman counterpart is Faunus.
PANNER.e: From Middle English Pan, from Latin Pān, from Ancient Greek Πάν (Pán).

PANTED.d: Past tense of PANT: A quick breathing; a catching of the breath; a gasp: the panting of animals such as a dog with their tong hung out- as a form of thermoregulation.
PANTED.e:
From Middle English panten, whence also English dialectal pank.
Possibly from Old French pantoyer, a byform or of Old French pantoisier (“to be breathless”) (compare modern French panteler (“to gasp for breath”)), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Vulgar Latin *pantasiō (“strugg...

PANTRY.d: A small room, closet, or cabinet usually located in or near the kitchen, dedicated to shelf-stable food storage or storing kitchenware, like a larder, but smaller.
PANTRY.e: From Middle English panetrie, from Old French paneterie, related to Latin panis (“bread”).

PAPACY.e: Circa 14th century, from Middle English papacie, papassie, from Medieval Latin pāpātia, from Latin pāpa (“pope”) + -tia (“office, rank”) (English -cy).

PAPAIN.d: A proteolytic enzyme in papaya fruit which can be used to tenderize meat.
PAPAIN.e: Attested since the late 1800s. From papaya + -in.

PAPAYA.d: A tropical American evergreen tree, Carica papaya, having large, yellow, edible fruit.
PAPAYA.e: Borrowed from Spanish papaya, from Lokono papáia. Possibility a doublet of pawpaw.

PAPERS.d: Plural of PAPER: Material for writing on.
PAPERS.e: From Anglo-Norman papir, from Latin papȳrus.

PAPERY.d: Of, similar to, or related to paper.

PAPIST.d: A Roman Catholic, especially one whose loyalties are seen to be with the papacy in Rome.
PAPIST.e: From Middle French papiste, from Latin pāpa (“pope”).

PAPPUS.d: The markedly reduced sepals of an Asteraceae floret that take the form of trichomes or scale attached to the ovary or seed.
PAPPUS.e: Via Latin pappus from Ancient Greek πάππος (páppos), an affectionate term for elderly men (referencing beards).

PAPULA.d: A pimple; a small, usually conical, elevation of the cuticle, produced by congestion, accumulated secretion, or hypertrophy of tissue; a papule.

PAPULE.d: A small, inflammatory, irritated spot on the skin, similar in appearance to a pimple, but not containing pus.

PARADE.d: An organized display of a group of people, particularly
PARADE.e: From French parade (“an ostentatious display, a military display”), from parer (“to beautify, prepare, take pride in”) + -ade probably under influence from earlier Italian parata (“preparation, a military parade, an ostentatious display”) and Latin magnō parātū (“with great prepa...

PARANG.d: A short, heavy, straight-edged knife used in Malaysia and Indonesia as a tool and weapon.

PARCEL.e: From Middle English parcel, from Old French parcelle (“a small piece or part, a parcel, a particle”), from Late Latin particella, diminutive of Latin particula (“particle”), diminutive of partem (“part, piece”). Doublet of particle.

PARDON.e: From Middle English pardonen, from Old French pardoner (modern French pardonner), from Late Latin perdonare, from per- + donare, possibly a calque (if not vice-versa) of a Germanic word represented by Frankish *firgeban (“to forgive, give up completely”), from *fir- + *geban. Aki...

PARENT.d: A person who raises a child (which they have made, adopted, fostered, taken as their own, etc.).
PARENT.e: From Middle English parent, borrowed from Anglo-Norman parent, Middle French parent, from Latin parentem, accusative of parēns (“parent”), present participle of pariō (“I breed, bring forth”).

PARGET.d: To coat with gypsum; to plaster, for example walls, or the interior of flues.
PARGET.e: From Middle English pargetten, from Old French pargeter, parjeter (“to throw about”), from par- (intensive prefix) (from Latin per-) + jeter (“to throw”) (from Latin iactō, frequentative of iaciō). The noun is derived from the verb.

PARIAH.d: Synonym of outcast: A person despised and excluded by their family, community, or society, especially a member of the untouchable castes in Indian society.
PARIAH.e: From Tamil பறையர் (paṟaiyar), from பறையன் (paṟaiyaṉ, “drummer”), from பறை (paṟai, “drum”) or from Malayalam പറയർ (paṟayaṟ), from പറയൻ (paṟayaṉ, “drummer”), from പറ (paṟa, “drum”). Parai in Tamil or Para in Malayalam refers to a type of large drum designed to announce the king’s n...

PARING.d: present participle and gerund of pare

PARISH.d: An administrative part of a diocese that has its own church.
PARISH.e: From Middle English parisshe, from Old French paroisse (compare the obsolete variant paroch, from Anglo-Norman paroche, parosse), from Late Latin parochia, from Ancient Greek παροικία (paroikía, “a dwelling abroad”).

PARITY.d: Equality; comparability of strength or intensity.
PARITY.e: From Middle French parité, from Late Latin paritās, from Latin pār (“equal”). Equivalent to pari- + -ty.

PARKED.d: Past tense of PARK: An area of land set aside for environment preservation or recreation.
PARKED.e: From Middle English park, from Old French parc (“livestock pen”), from Medieval Latin parcus, parricus, from Frankish *parrik (“enclosure, pen, fence”). Cognate with Dutch perk (“enclosure; flowerbed”), Old High German pfarrih, pferrih (“enclosure, pen”), Old English pearroc (“en...

PARKIN.d: A traditional soft cake of Northern England, usually made with oatmeal and treacle.
PARKIN.e: From Parkin, a diminutive of Peter.

PARLAY.d: To carry forward the stake and winnings from a bet on to a subsequent wager or series of wagers.
PARLAY.e: The verb is derived from paroli (“cumulative bet in card games”), possibly modified under the influence of French parler (“to speak, talk”). Paroli is derived from French paroli (“double stake”), from Italian paroli, plural of parolo (first-person singular present indicative of p...

PARLEY.d: A conference, especially one between enemies.
PARLEY.e: From Middle English parlai (“speech, parley”), from Old French parler (“to talk; to speak”), from Late Latin parabolō, from Latin parabola (“comparison”), from Ancient Greek παραβολή (parabolḗ), from παρά (pará, “beside”) with βολή (bolḗ, “throwing”). Doublet of palaver.

PARODY.d: A work or performance that imitates another work or performance with ridicule or irony.
PARODY.e: From Latin parōdia, from Ancient Greek παρῳδία (parōidía, “parody”), from παρά (pará, “besides”) + ᾠδή (ōidḗ, “song”).

PAROLE.d: Originally, one's oath or word of honour, given as a condition of release from custody; now specifically, describing the release of a former prisoner under certain conditions, especially the promise of good behaviour.
PAROLE.e: Borrowed from Middle French parole (“word, formal promise”), from Old French parole, from Late Latin parabola (“speech”), from Ancient Greek παραβολή (parabolḗ). Doublet of parabola, parable, and palaver.

PARRED.d: Past tense of PAR: Abbreviation of paragraph.

PARROT.d: A kind of bird, many species of which are colorful and able to mimic human speech, of the order Psittaciformes or (narrowly) of the family Psittacidae.
PARROT.e: First attested in 1525. From Middle French perrot, either a diminutive of Pierre or a shortened form of perroquet (whence also parakeet). Compare French pierrot and Occitan parrat. A number of origins have been suggested for perroquet, such as Spanish periquito and Italian parroc...

PARSES.d: Plural of PARS: plural of par

PARSON.d: An Anglican cleric having full legal control of a parish under ecclesiastical law.
PARSON.e: From Middle English persoun, from Anglo-Norman, Old French persone (“parson, person”), from Medieval Latin persona (“parson, person”), from Latin persona (“person”). Doublet of person and persona.

PARTED.d: simple past and past participle of part

PARTER.d: A work in a specified number of parts.

PARVIS.d: An enclosed courtyard in front of a building, especially a cathedral.
PARVIS.e: From Middle English parvis, parvise, parvys, borrowed from Old French parvis, parevis, from Latin paradīsus, from Ancient Greek παράδεισος (parádeisos), ultimately from Proto-Iranian *paridayjah. Used since the Middle Ages to describe the court in front of St Peter's in Rome, and...

PASCAL.d: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of pressure and stress; one newton per square metre. Symbol: Pa.
PASCAL.e: Borrowed from French pascal, named after French scientist and philosopher Blaise Pascal. Doublet of Paschal.

PASHED.d: Past tense of PASH: To snog, to make out, to kiss.

PASHES.d: Plural of PASH: To snog, to make out, to kiss.

PASSED.d: simple past and past participle of pass

PASSER.d: Comparative form of PAS: The right of going foremost; precedence.

PASTEL.d: Any of several subdued tints of colors, usually associated with pink, peach, yellow, green, blue, and lavender.
PASTEL.e: Borrowed from French pastel, from Italian pastello (“pastel”), from Medieval Latin pastellum (“dough, paste”), from Latin pasta (“dough, paste”), ultimately from Ancient Greek πάστη (pástē, “dough, paste”). Doublet of pastegh, pastiglia, pastila, pastilla, and pastille.

PASTOR.d: Someone who tends to a flock of animals: synonym of shepherd.
PASTOR.e: From Middle English pastour, from Old French pastor (Modern French pasteur), from Latin pāstor.

PASTRY.d: A baked food item made from flour and fat pastes such as pie crust; also tarts, bear claws, napoleons, puff pastries, etc.
PASTRY.e: From Middle English pastre, pastri, from pastree (variant of pasterie, from Old French pastaierie and Medieval Latin pasteria, from Late Latin pasta, from Ancient Greek παστά (pastá)) or paste + -ri (modern paste + -ry).

PATCHY.d: Full of, or covered with, patches; abounding in patches.

PATENT.d: An official document granting an appointment, privilege, or right, or some property or title; letters patent.
PATENT.e:
The noun is derived from Middle English patent (“document granting an office, property, right, title, etc.; document granting permission, licence; papal indulgence, pardon”) [and other forms], which is either:
* a clipping of lettre patent, lettres patente, lettres patentes [and ...

PATERA.d: A broad, shallow dish used for drinking, primarily in ritual contexts such as libations.

PATHED.d: Past tense of PATH: A trail for the use of, or worn by, pedestrians.
PATHED.e: From Middle English path, peth, from Old English pæþ (“path, track”), from Proto-West Germanic *paþ, from Proto-Germanic *paþaz (“path”). The Proto-Germanic term is possibly borrowed from Iranian, from Proto-Iranian *pántaHh, from Proto-Indo-Iranian *pántaHs, from Proto-Indo-Euro...

PATHIA.d: A hot, sweet, and sour curry, developed and predominantly available in the curry houses of the United Kingdom, whose main ingredients are chillies, white wine vinegar, fresh ginger, sugar, garlic, coriander, and (optionally) tamarind.

PATHIC.d: Synonym of bottom: a passive usually-male partner in homosexual anal intercourse.
PATHIC.e: From Latin pathicus, from Ancient Greek παθικός (pathikós), from πάθος (páthos, “suffering, feeling”), from πάσχω (páskhō, “I feel, I suffer”).

PATHOS.d: The quality or property of anything which touches the feelings or excites emotions and passions, especially that which awakens tender emotions, such as pity, sorrow, and the like; contagious warmth of feeling, action, or expression; pathetic quality.

PATINA.d: A paten, flat type of dish.
PATINA.e: Borrowed from Italian patina, from Latin patina (“dish, pan”), itself a borrowing from Ancient Greek πατάνη (patánē), either from Proto-Indo-European *peth₂- (“to spread”) or from Pre-Greek . Doublet of paten, patena, and patine.

PATOIS.d: A regional dialect (usually one considered substandard) of a language (especially French).
PATOIS.e: Borrowed from French patois (“regional dialect or language”), c. 1635.

PATROL.d: A going of the rounds along the chain of sentinels and between the posts, by a guard, usually consisting of three or four men, to insure greater security from attacks on the outposts.
PATROL.e: From French patrouille, from Old French patrouille, patouille (“a night-watch”, literally “a tramping about”), from patrouiller, patouiller, patoiller (“to paddle or pudder in water, dabble with the feet, begrime, besmear”), from patte, pate (“paw, foot of an animal”), from Vulga...

PATRON.d: One who protects or supports; a defender or advocate.
PATRON.e: From Middle English patroun, patrone, from Old French patron, from Latin patrōnus, derived from pater (“father”). Doublet of padrone, Patronus, patroon, and pattern.

PATTED.d: Past tense of PAT: The sound of a light slap or tap with a soft flat object, especially of a footstep.
PATTED.e: From Middle English *patten, alteration (with loss of medial l) of platten, pletten (“to pat”), from Old English plættan (“to buffet, strike, slap, smack, give a sounding blow”), from Proto-Germanic *plat- (“to strike, beat”), from Proto-Indo-European *blod-, *bled- (“to strike, ...

PATTEN.d: Any of various types of footwear with thick soles, often used to elevate the foot, especially wooden clogs.
PATTEN.e: From Middle English patyn, patin, pateyn, from Old French patin, from patte (“paw, hoof”), from Latin patta, of imitative origin.

PATTER.d: A soft repeated sound, as of rain falling, or feet walking on a hard surface.

PAUNCH.d: The first compartment of the stomach of a ruminant, the rumen.
PAUNCH.e: From Middle English paunche, from Old Northern French panche, Old French pance (French panse), from Latin pantex.

PAUPER.e: Learned borrowing from Latin pauper (“poor”). Originally a legal term. Doublet of poor.

PAVEED.d: Past tense of PAVE: To cover something with paving slabs.
PAVEED.e: From Old French paver (“to pave, to cover”), from Vulgar Latin *pavāre (“to beat down, to smash”), from Latin pavīre (“to beat, strike, ram, tread down”).

PAVING.d: present participle and gerund of pave

PAWING.d: Present participle of PAW: The soft foot of a mammal or other animal, generally a quadruped, that has claws or nails; comparable to a human hand or foot.
PAWING.e: From Middle English pawe, from Old French poue, poe, from Frankish *pōta (compare Dutch poot, Low German Pote, German Pfote), from Frankish *pōtōn (“to put, stick, plant”) (compare Dutch poten (“to plant”)), from Proto-Germanic *putōną (compare Old English potian (“to push”), pȳt...

PAWNED.d: Past tense of PAWN: The state of being held as security for a loan, or as a pledge.
PAWNED.e: From Middle English paun, pawyn, pawnd, from Old French pan, pant (“pledge for a payment”), from a Germanic language, perhaps Frankish *pand (“deposit, security, pledge”), further origin uncertain. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Pound (“deposit, pledge, pawn”), West Frisian pân (...

PAWPAW.d: Any of several types of trees having edible fruit:
PAWPAW.e:
Via Portuguese and Spanish papaya (which is botanically unrelated) from Lokono papáia; compare also Kari'na kapaja. Doublet of papaya.
Alternatively from Yuchi pahpah.

PAYDAY.d: The day of the week or month, or the specific day, on which an employee's wages or salary is paid.

PAYING.d: present participle and gerund of pay

PAYNIM.d: A pagan or heathen, especially a Muslim, or a Jew.
PAYNIM.e: From Middle English paynym, paynyme, from Anglo-Norman paienime, peinime et al., from Late Latin paganismus (“paganism”), from Latin paganus (“pagan”). Doublet of paganism.

PAYOUT.d: An amount of money paid out.

PEACED.d: Past tense of PEACE: Freedom from disturbance; tranquility.
PEACED.e: From Anglo-Norman pes, from Latin pāx.

PEACES.d: Plural of PEACE: Freedom from disturbance; tranquility.
PEACES.e: From Anglo-Norman pes, from Latin pāx.

PEAHEN.e: From Middle English pehenne, equivalent to pea (“peafowl”) + hen. Compare Icelandic páhæna (“peahen”). See also peacock, peafowl, peachick, etc.

PEAKED.d: Past tense of PEAK: A point; the sharp end or top of anything that terminates in a point; as, the peak, or front, of a cap.
PEAKED.e:
From earlier peake, peek, peke, from Middle English pek (in place names), itself an alteration of pike, pyke, pyk (“a sharp point, pike”), from Old English pīc, piic (“a pike, needle, pin, peak, pinnacle”), from Proto-West Germanic *pīk, from Proto-Germanic *pīkaz (“peak”).
Cogna...

PEALED.d: Past tense of PEAL: A loud sound, or a succession of loud sounds, as of bells, thunder, cannon, shouts, laughter, of a multitude, etc.
PEALED.e: From Middle English pele, peil, probably an apheretic variant of Middle English apel, appel, from Old French apel (“an appeal; pealing of bells”). Compare appeal.

PEANUT.d: A legume resembling a nut, the fruit of the plant Arachis hypogaea, native to South America.
PEANUT.e: From pea + nut, perhaps a folk etymology of pinda, pinder (still found in Southern US dialects).

PEARLY.d: A pale greyish white colour, tinted with blue.

PEBBLE.d: A small stone, especially one rounded by the action of water.
PEBBLE.e: From Middle English pibel (also in pibleston), from Old English papolstān (“pebble-stone”), from Old English *papol, *pyppel, *pæbbel of unknown origin + Old English stān. Compare Albanian popël.

PECKED.d: Past tense of PECK: To strike or pierce with the beak or bill (of a bird).
PECKED.e: From Middle English pecken, pekken, variant of Middle English piken, picken, pikken (“to pick, use a pointed implement”). More at pick.

PECTEN.d: The bones in the hand between the wrist and the fingers.

PECTIN.d: A polysaccharide extracted from the cell walls of plants, especially of fruits; under acidic conditions it forms a gel. It is often used in processed foods, especially jellies and jams where it causes thickening (setting).
PECTIN.e: From French pectine, coined in the 1830s by Henri Braconnot, from acide pectique "pectic acid", from Ancient Greek πηκτικός (pēktikós, “curdling”), from πηκτός (pēktós, “curdled”), from πήγνυμι (pḗgnumi, “stiffen”).

PEDALO.d: A small boat propelled by pedals that directly turn external paddles, used for recreation.
PEDALO.e: Borrowed from French pédalo, a genericized trademark. By surface analysis, pedal + -o.

PEDANT.d: A person who makes an excessive or tedious show of their knowledge, especially regarding rules of vocabulary and grammar.
PEDANT.e: From Middle French pedant, pedante, from Italian pedante (“a teacher, schoolmaster, pedant”), associated with unrelated Italian pedagogo (“teacher, pedagogue”). Compare French pédant.

PEDDLE.d: To sell things, especially door to door or in insignificant quantities.
PEDDLE.e: Back-formation from pedlar. (Compare burgle from burglar.)

PEDLAR.e: From Middle English pedlare, variant of Middle English pedare. More at peddler.

PEEING.e: The initial letter of piss. Compare eff.

PEENED.d: Past tense of PEEN: The (often spherical) end of the head of a hammer opposite the main hammering end.
PEENED.e: Probably from a North Germanic source, compare dialectal Norwegian penn (“peen”), Danish pind (“peg”), German Pinne (“the peen of a hammer”), Old Swedish pæna (“to pound iron with a hammer”).

PEEPED.d: Past tense of PEEP: A short, soft, high-pitched sound, as made by a baby bird.
PEEPED.e: From Middle English pepen. Compare Dutch piepen (“peep”), German Low German piepen (“to peep”), German piepen and pfeifen, all probably onomatopoeic.

PEEPUL.e: Borrowed from Hindi पीपल / Urdu پیپل (pīpal), from Sanskrit पिप्पल (pippala). Doublet of falafel and pepper.

PEERED.d: Past tense of PEER: To look with difficulty, or as if searching for something.
PEERED.e: From Middle English peren, pyren, piren (“to peer, gaze”), perhaps from Old English *pȳran (“to look, peer”), from Proto-West Germanic *pūrijan (“to look”), related to Saterland Frisian pierje (“to look”), Dutch Low Saxon piren (“to look”), West Flemish pieren (“to look with narr...

PEEWEE.d: A short or small person; a small object.

PEEWIT.e: Onomatopoeic; for the pronunciation /ˈpjuːɪt/ and corresponding form pewit, compare leeward, Seward, steward.

PEGBOX.d: The part of a violin or similar stringed instrument that holds the tuning pegs.

PEGGED.d: Past tense of PEG: A cylindrical wooden or metal object used to fasten or as a bearing between objects.
PEGGED.e: From Middle English pegge, from Middle Dutch pegge (“pin, peg”), from Old Dutch *pigg-, *pegg-, from Proto-Germanic *pig-, *pag- (“peg, stake”), from Proto-Indo-European *bak-, *baḱ- (“club, pointed stick, peg”). Cognate with Dutch dialectal peg (“pin”), Low German pig, pigge (“p...

PEGGER.d: Comparative form of PEG: A cylindrical wooden or metal object used to fasten or as a bearing between objects.
PEGGER.e: From Middle English pegge, from Middle Dutch pegge (“pin, peg”), from Old Dutch *pigg-, *pegg-, from Proto-Germanic *pig-, *pag- (“peg, stake”), from Proto-Indo-European *bak-, *baḱ- (“club, pointed stick, peg”). Cognate with Dutch dialectal peg (“pin”), Low German pig, pigge (“p...

PEKING.d: Present participle of PEKE: A Pekingese dog.

PELAGE.d: Fur, hair, or any other form of the coat of a mammal.

PELHAM.d: A type of bit used on the bridle of a horse, consisting of a mouthpiece, a shank, and two rings on each side.

PELLET.d: A small, compressed, hard chunk of matter.
PELLET.e: Inherited from Middle English pelote, pelet, from Old French pelote (“small ball”), from Vulgar Latin *pilotta, diminutive of Latin pila (“ball”). Doublet of pelota.

PELMET.d: A decorative item that is placed above a window to hide the curtain mechanisms, visually similar to a cornice or valance.

PELTED.d: Past tense of PELT: The skin of an animal with the hair or wool on; either a raw or undressed hide, or a skin preserved with the hair or wool on it (sometimes worn as a garment with minimal modification).
PELTED.e:
The noun is inherited from Middle English pelt (“skin of a sheep, especially without the wool”); further etymology uncertain, possibly:
* from Middle English pellet (“skin of an animal, especially a sheep”), from Anglo-Norman pelette, pellet, and Old French pelete, pelette (“thin...

PELTRY.d: Pelts or skins, collectively; skins with the fur on them; furs.
PELTRY.e: From Old French peleterie, the trade of a skinner or peltmonger (peletier). Equivalent to pelt + -ry.

PELVES.d: Plural of PELF: Money, riches; gain, especially when dishonestly acquired; lucre, mammon.
PELVES.e: From Late Middle English pelf, pelfe (“stolen goods, booty, spoil; forfeited property; money, riches; property; valuable object”), possibly from Anglo-Norman pelf (a variant of pelfre (“booty, loot”)) and Old French peufre (“frippery; rubbish”); further etymology uncertain, possi...

PELVIC.d: Of, pertaining to, or in the region of, the pelvis

PELVIS.d: The large compound bone structure at the base of the spine that supports the legs in hominids.
PELVIS.e: From Latin pēlvis (“basin”), from Old Latin pēluis (“basin”), further etymology uncertain.

PENCIL.e: From Anglo-Norman and Old French pincil (see the variant pincel, which gave rise to Modern French pinceau (“paintbrush”)), from Latin pēnicillum, diminutive of pēniculus (“brush”), itself a diminutive of pēnis (“tail; penis”). Not related to pen.

PENDED.d: Past tense of PEND: To hang down; to cause something to hang down
PENDED.e: Borrowed from Middle French pendre (“to hang”), from Late Latin pendĕre, from Latin pendēre.

PENMAN.d: A scribe, or a person who copies texts.

PENNED.d: Past tense of PEN: An enclosure (enclosed area) used to contain domesticated animals, especially sheep or cattle.
PENNED.e:
From Middle English pen, penne (“enclosure for animals”), from Old English penn (“enclosure, fold, pen”), from Proto-Germanic *pennō, *pannijō (“pin, bolt, nail, tack”), from Proto-Indo-European *bend- (“pointed peg, nail, edge”). Related to pin.
Sense “prison” originally figurat...

PENNER.d: Comparative form of PEN: An enclosure (enclosed area) used to contain domesticated animals, especially sheep or cattle.
PENNER.e:
From Middle English pen, penne (“enclosure for animals”), from Old English penn (“enclosure, fold, pen”), from Proto-Germanic *pennō, *pannijō (“pin, bolt, nail, tack”), from Proto-Indo-European *bend- (“pointed peg, nail, edge”). Related to pin.
Sense “prison” originally figurat...

PENNON.d: A thin, often triangular flag or streamer, especially as hung from the end of a lance or spear.
PENNON.e: Inherited from Middle English penoun, pennon, from Anglo-Norman penun, penoun, from Old French penne (“feather”) + -on (diminutive suffix).

PENTAD.d: Synonym of quintet: A group of five things, particularly
PENTAD.e: From Ancient Greek πεντάς (pentás), from πέντε (pénte, “five”) + -άς (-ás, “-ad”), equivalent to pent- + -ad.

PENTYL.d: Any of several isomeric univalent hydrocarbon radicals, C₅H₁₁, formally derived from pentane by the loss of a hydrogen atom.

PENULT.d: The next-to-last syllable of a word.

PENURY.d: Extreme need or want; destitution, poverty; (countable) an instance of this.
PENURY.e: From Late Middle English penuri, penurie (“destitution, need, poverty; dearth, lack, scarcity”), borrowed from Latin pēnūria (“need, scarcity, want”) + Middle English -i, -ie (suffix forming abstract and collective nouns); further etymology uncertain, possibly related to paene (“...

PEOPLE.d: plural of person: a body of persons considered generally or collectively; a group of two or more persons.
PEOPLE.e: From Middle English puple, peple, peeple, from Anglo-Norman people, from Old French pueple, peuple, pople, from Latin populus (“a people, nation”), from Old Latin populus, from earlier poplus, from even earlier poplos, from Proto-Italic *poplos (“army”) of unknown origin. Doublet...

PEPLUM.d: A peplos, an Ancient Greek garment formed of a tubular piece of cloth folded back upon itself halfway down so that the top of the tube is worn around the waist, and the bottom covers the legs down to the ankles; the open top is then worn over the shoulders, and draped, in folds, down to the waist. Compare the Roman palla.
PEPLUM.e: From Latin peplum, from Ancient Greek πέπλον (péplon), neuter of πέπλος (péplos).

PEPPED.d: Past tense of PEP: To inject with energy and enthusiasm.

PEPPER.d: A plant of the family Piperaceae.
PEPPER.e: From Middle English peper, piper, from Old English piper, from Proto-West Germanic *pipar, from Latin piper, from an Indo-Aryan source; compare Sanskrit पिप्पलि (pippali, “long pepper”). The name was given to the capsicum fruit because of its unusual spicy taste, not unlike the O...

PEPSIN.d: A digestive enzyme that chemically digests, or breaks down, proteins into shorter chains of amino acids.
PEPSIN.e: From German Pepsin, corresponding to Ancient Greek πέψις (pépsis, “digestion”) + -in.

PEPTIC.d: Of, pertaining to, capable of, or aiding digestion.
PEPTIC.e: From Latin pepticus, from Ancient Greek πέψις (pépsis, “digestion”), a form of πέσσω (péssō).

PERIOD.e: From Middle English periode, from Middle French periode, from Medieval Latin periodus, from Ancient Greek περίοδος (períodos, “circuit, orbit, a recurring interval of time, path around”), from περι- (peri-, “around”) + ὁδός (hodós, “way”). Displaced native Middle English tide (“i...

PERISH.d: To decay and disappear; to waste away to nothing.
PERISH.e: From Middle English perishen, borrowed from Old French perir (via the stem periss- used in various conjugations), from Latin perīre (“pass away, perish”), from per (“through”) + īre (“pass, go”).

PERMIT.d: To allow (something) to happen, to give permission for.
PERMIT.e: From Middle English permitten, borrowed from Middle French permettre, from Latin permittō (“give up, allow”), from per (“through”) + mittō (“send”).

PERRON.d: A stone block used as the base of a monument, marker, etc.
PERRON.e: From Middle French pierre (“stone”), from Anglo-Norman perron.

PERSON.d: An individual who has been granted personhood; usually a human being.
PERSON.e: From Middle English persoun, personne et al., from Anglo-Norman parsone, persoun et al. (Old French persone (“human being”), French personne), and its source Latin persōna (“mask used by actor; role, part, character”), perhaps a loanword from Etruscan 𐌘𐌄𐌓𐌔𐌖 (φersu, “mask”). In th...

PERUKE.d: A wig, especially one with long hair on the sides and back, worn mainly by men in the 17th and 18th centuries.
PERUKE.e: From French perruque. Doublet of periwig.

PERUSE.d: To examine or consider with care.
PERUSE.e: From either Medieval Latin perūtor, perūsitō (“wear out”)) or Anglo-Norman peruser (“use up”)), originally leading to two concurrent meanings, but only those derived from "to examine" survive today. By surface analysis, per- + use.

PESETA.d: The former currency of the Spanish Empire and Andorra, divided into 100 céntimos.
PESETA.e: From Spanish peseta, from peso (“coin or weight”).

PESHER.d: An interpretive commentary on scripture, especially one in Hebrew.
PESHER.e: Transliteration of Hebrew פֵּשֶׁר (pēšer, “interpretation, solution”). Popularised after the discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls in 1947.

PESTER.d: To bother, harass, or annoy persistently.
PESTER.e: In the senses of “overcrowd (a place)” and “impede (a person)”: from Middle French and Old French empestrer (“encumber”), influenced by English pest. The modern sense is an extension of the sense “infest”. Comparable to English construction pest + -er (used to form frequentative ...

PESTLE.d: A club-shaped, round-headed stick used in a mortar to pound, crush, rub or grind things.
PESTLE.e: From Middle English pestel, pestell, from Old French pestel, from Latin pistillum, from pīnsō (“pound, beat”). Doublet of pistil and pistillum.

PETARD.d: A small, hat-shaped explosive device, used to breach a door or wall.
PETARD.e: From Middle French petard; see Modern French pétard (“firecracker”).

PETITE.d: Fairly short and of slim build.
PETITE.e: Borrowed from French petite f, feminine of petit m (“small, little”).

PETREL.d: Any of various species of black, grey, or white seabirds in the order Procellariiformes.
PETREL.e:
From earlier pitteral. Perhaps a diminutive of Peter, with reference to St. Peter's walking on the water (Matthew 14:29).
A derivation from patter or pitter-patter has been suggested, for instance by ornithologist Elliott Ladd Coues.

PETROL.d: A fluid consisting of a mixture of refined petroleum hydrocarbons, primarily consisting of octane, commonly used as a motor fuel.
PETROL.e: Borrowed from French (essence de) pétrole, from Medieval Latin petroleum, from Ancient Greek πετρέλαιον (petrélaion, “oil of the rock”), from πέτρα (pétra, “stone, rock”)+ ἔλαιον (élaion, “olive oil, any oily substance”). Doublet of petroleum.

PETTED.d: Past tense of PET: An animal kept as a companion or otherwise for pleasure, rather than for some practical benefit or use.
PETTED.e: Originally northern dialectal, from Scots pet (“an animal that has been tamed and is kept as a pet; a darling or favourite; a petted or spoiled child”), probably from Scottish Gaelic peata (“pet, tamed animal, spoiled child”), from Middle Irish petta, peta (“pet, lap-dog”), of un...

PETTER.d: Comparative form of PET: An animal kept as a companion or otherwise for pleasure, rather than for some practical benefit or use.
PETTER.e: Originally northern dialectal, from Scots pet (“an animal that has been tamed and is kept as a pet; a darling or favourite; a petted or spoiled child”), probably from Scottish Gaelic peata (“pet, tamed animal, spoiled child”), from Middle Irish petta, peta (“pet, lap-dog”), of un...

PEWING.d: Present participle of PEW: One of the long benches in a church, seating several persons, usually fixed to the floor and facing the chancel.
PEWING.e: From Middle English pewe, from Old French puiee, puïe (“balustrade, balcony”), from Latin podia, plural of podium (“parapet, podium”), from Ancient Greek πόδιον (pódion, “little foot”), from πούς (poús, “foot”). Doublet of podia.

PEWTER.d: An alloy of approximately 93–98% tin and 1–2% copper, and the balance of antimony.
PEWTER.e: From Middle English peutre, from Old French peautre, from Vulgar Latin *peltrum (“pewter”), which is of uncertain origin. Possibly related to spelter.

PEYOTE.d: A small, spineless cactus (Lophophora williamsii) found from southwest United States to central Mexico that produces buttonlike tubercles that can be chewed for their psychedelic effect, primarily from the drug mescaline.
PEYOTE.e: From Spanish peyote, from Classical Nahuatl peyotl.

PHAROS.d: An ancient lighthouse or beacon to guide sailors.

PHASOR.d: A representation of a complex number in terms of a complex exponential.

PHENOL.d: A caustic, poisonous, white crystalline compound, C₆H₅OH, derived from benzene and used in resins, plastics, and pharmaceuticals and in dilute form as a disinfectant and antiseptic; once called carbolic acid
PHENOL.e:
From French phène, from Ancient Greek φαίνω (phaínō, “to clear”), as it was used for illumination, name given by Auguste Laurente in 1836.
By surface analysis, pheno- + -ol.

PHENOM.d: Someone or something that is phenomenal, especially a promising young player in sports like baseball, American football, basketball, tennis, and golf.
PHENOM.e: Clipping of phenomenon (“remarkable occurrence”). American English, c. 1890s.

PHENYL.d: A univalent hydrocarbon radical, C₆H₅ (benzene minus one hydrogen atom), and the basis of an immense number of aromatic derivatives.
PHENYL.e: Borrowed from French phényle, derived from the root of Ancient Greek φαίνω (phaínō, “to shine”) plus ὕλη (húlē, “wood; material, substance”). Equivalent to phen- + -yl.

PHLEGM.d: One of the four humors making up the body in ancient and mediaeval medicine; said to be cold and moist, and often identified with mucus.
PHLEGM.e: From Middle English flewme, fleume, fleme, from Old French fleume, Middle French flemme (French flegme), and their source, Latin phlegma, from Ancient Greek φλέγμα (phlégma, “flame; inflammation; clammy humor in the body”), from φλέγειν (phlégein, “to burn”). Possible burning sen...

PHLOEM.d: A vascular tissue in land plants primarily responsible for the distribution of sugars and nutrients manufactured in the shoot.
PHLOEM.e: First attested in 1872. From German Phloëm, coined by Swiss botanist Carl Nägeli in 1858 from Ancient Greek φλόος (phlóos, “husk, bark”) + a Greek-sounding ending -em (cf. System).

PHOBIA.d: An irrational, abnormal, or obsessive fear (of something).
PHOBIA.e: First attested in c. 1790, from words ending in -phobia, ultimately from Ancient Greek φόβος (phóbos, “fear”). Compare ism, from -ism, itis, from -itis, and ana, from -ana.

PHOEBE.d: Any of several birds of the genus Sayornis.
PHOEBE.e: From early 18th c. Imitative, influenced by the name Phoebe.

PHONED.d: Past tense of PHONE: A telephone.

PHONON.d: The quantum of acoustic or vibrational energy (sound), considered a discrete particle rather than a wave.
PHONON.e: From phono- + -on. From Ancient Greek φωνή (phōnḗ, “sound”). Modelled after photon.

PHOOEY.d: An expression of disgust, rejection, or disappointment.
PHOOEY.e: Probably from Yiddish פֿוי (foy), from German pfui, influenced by phoo.

PHOTON.d: The quantum of light and other electromagnetic energy, regarded as a discrete particle having zero rest mass, no electric charge, and an indefinitely long lifetime. It is a gauge boson.
PHOTON.e: From photo- + -on. Coined by American physicist Leonard Troland in 1916 as a unit of light hitting the retina, and later popularized in a more modern sense by Gilbert N. Lewis, with the term gaining acceptance in the physics community by the late 1920s.

PHRASE.d: A short written or spoken expression.
PHRASE.e: From Late Latin phrasis (“diction”), from Ancient Greek φράσις (phrásis, “manner of expression”), from φράζω (phrázō, “I tell, express”).

PHREAK.d: A person who engages in phone phreaking.

PHYLUM.d: A rank in the classification of organisms, below kingdom and above class; also called a divisio or a division, especially in describing plants; a taxon at that rank
PHYLUM.e: From Latin phylum, from Ancient Greek φῦλον (phûlon, “tribe, race”).

PHYSES.d: Plural of PHYS: plural of Phy

PHYSIC.d: Relating to or concerning existent materials; physical.
PHYSIC.e: From Middle English phisik, from Latin physicus, from Ancient Greek φῠσῐκός (phŭsĭkós, “natural; physical”), from φύσις (phúsis, “origin, birth; nature, quality; form, shape; type, kind”), from φῠ́ω (phŭ́ō, “grow”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to appear, become, ...

PHYSIO.e: Clippings. Ultimately from Ancient Greek φύσις (phúsis, “nature”).

PIANOS.d: Plural of PIANO: A large keyboard musical instrument.

PIAZZA.d: A public square, especially in Italian cities.
PIAZZA.e: From Italian piazza. Doublet of piatza, place, and plaza.

PICKED.d: Past tense of PICK: A tool used for digging; a pickaxe.
PICKED.e: From Middle English piken, picken, pikken, from Old English *piccian, *pīcian (attested in pīcung (“a pricking”)), and pīcan, pȳcan (“to pick, prick, pluck”), both from Proto-West Germanic *pikkōn, from Proto-Germanic *pikkōną (“to pick, peck, prick, knock”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

PICKET.d: A stake driven into the ground.
PICKET.e: From French piquet, from piquer (“to pierce”).

PICKLE.d: A cucumber preserved in a solution, usually a brine or a vinegar syrup.
PICKLE.e: From Middle English pikel (“spicy sauce served with meat or fish”), borrowed from Middle Dutch, Middle Low German pekel (“brine”). Cognate with Scots pikkill (“salt liquor, brine”), Saterland Frisian Piekele (“pickle, brine”), Dutch pekel (“pickle, brine”), Low German pekel, peck...

PICKUP.d: An electronic device for detecting sound, vibration, etc., such as one fitted to an electric guitar or record player.

PICNIC.d: An informal social gathering, usually in a natural outdoor setting, to which the participants bring their own food and drink.

PIDDLE.e: Unknown, although possibly originally paw + -le (suffix forming verbs involving continuous or repeated movement). In later use, a euphemistic diminutive of piss. The noun derives from the verb.

PIDGIN.d: An amalgamation of two disparate languages, used by two populations having no common language as a lingua franca to communicate with each other, lacking formalized grammar and having a small, utilitarian vocabulary and no native speakers.
PIDGIN.e: From pidgin English, from a Chinese Pidgin English pronunciation of English business during trade in the Far East. All attestations of pidgin from the first half of the nineteenth century given in the third edition of the Oxford English Dictionary mean “business; an action, occup...

PIECED.d: Past tense of PIECE: A portion; a single item.

PIECES.d: Plural of PIECE: A portion; a single item.

PIEING.d: present participle and gerund of pie

PIEMAN.e:
* From Middle English pyman (attested as a surname), equivalent to pie + -man.
* (caller in gambling games): Such games were once often run by sellers of pies as a sideline.

PIERCE.e: From Middle English perce, from conjugated forms of Old French percier such as (jeo) pierce (“I pierce”), probably from Vulgar Latin *pertūsiō, from Latin pertūsus, past participle of pertundō (“thrust or bore through”), from per- (“through”) + tundō (“beat, pound”). Displaced na...

PIFFLE.e: Unknown, 1847. Perhaps blend of piddle + trifle, perhaps puff (“(onomatopoeia, puff of air)”) + -le (“diminutive”).

PIGEON.d: One of several birds of the family Columbidae within the order Columbiformes.
PIGEON.e:
Etymology tree
Latin pīpiō
Proto-Indo-European *-h₃onh₂-der.
Latin -ō
Latin pipio
Old French pyjonbor.
Middle English pygeoun
English pigeon
Inherited from Middle English pygeoun, borrowed from Old French pyjon, inherited from Late Latin pīpiōnem (“chirping bird”), derived from L...

PIGGED.d: Past tense of PIG: Any of several mammalian species of the family Suidae, having cloven hooves, bristles and a snout adapted for digging; especially the domesticated animal Sus domesticus.
PIGGED.e: From Middle English pigge (“pig, pigling”) (originally a term for a young pig, with adult pigs being swyn (“swine”)), apparently from Old English *picga (attested only in compounds, such as picgbrēad (“mast, pig-fodder”)), from Proto-West Germanic *piggō, *puggō (“piglet”). Compa...

PIGLET.e: From pig + -let (diminutive suffix). Attested from 1855. Displaced Old English fearh.

PIGMAN.d: A farm worker who looks after pigs.

PIGNUT.d: The edible tuber of Conopodium majus, native to western Europe.

PIGSTY.d: An enclosure where pigs are kept, either a building or part of one.

PIKING.d: Present participle of PIKE: A very long spear used two-handed by infantry soldiers for thrusting (not throwing), both for attacks on enemy foot soldiers and as a countermeasure against cavalry assaults.
PIKING.e: From Middle English pyke, pyk, pik, pike (“pike; sharp point, iron tip of a staff or spear, pointed toe of an item of footwear; sharp tool; mountain, peak”), from Old English pīc (“pointed object, pick axe”), and Middle French pique (“long thrusting weapon”), from Old French pic ...

PILFER.d: To steal in small quantities, or articles of small value; to practise petty theft.
PILFER.e: From earlier pilfre, from Middle English pilfre (“booty”), from Old French pelfre (“plunder, booty, spoils”), of unknown origin. Compare pelf.

PILING.d: A structural support comprising a length of wood, steel, or other construction material.

PILLAR.d: A large post, often used as supporting architecture.
PILLAR.e: From Middle English piler, from Old French pilier, from Medieval Latin or Vulgar Latin *pilāre (“a pillar”), from Latin pila (“a pillar, pier, mole”).

PILLOW.d: A soft cushion used to support the head in bed.
PILLOW.e:
From Middle English pilwe, from Old English pyle, pylu (“pillow”), from Proto-West Germanic *pulwī (“pillow”), from Latin pulvīnus (“cushion”), derived from pulvis (“dust, powder”) + -īnus (“-ine”), for the filler of a pillow. Doublet of pulvinus.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian P...

PILOTS.d: Plural of PILOT: A person who operates an aircraft.
PILOTS.e: From French pilote, from Italian pilota.

PIMPED.d: Past tense of PIMP: Someone who solicits customers for prostitution and acts as manager for a group of prostitutes; a pander.
PIMPED.e: Origin unknown. Perhaps from French pimpant (“smart, sparkish”) or German Pimpf (“boy, youth, young squirt”). The Old English near-synonym was rendered by Old English forspennend (literally “solicitor”).

PIMPLE.d: An inflamed (raised and colored) spot on the surface of the skin that is usually painful and fills with pus.
PIMPLE.e: Early Modern English pimple, pumple, from Middle English pymple, pympyl, of uncertain origin but probably a nasalized variant of Old English *pipel, *pypel, from Old English piplian, pyplian (“to break out in pimples, show eruptions”), probably related to Latin papula (“pimple, p...

PINEAL.d: In the shape of a pine cone.
PINEAL.e: From French pinéal, from Middle French, from Latin pīnea (“pine cone, pine nut”), from pīneus (“of the pine”).

PINERY.d: A hothouse or (tropical) area used as a plantation for the cultivation of pineapple plants (genus Ananas) and production of their homonymous fruit.

PINIER.d: Comparative form of PINY: Of, pertaining to, or having many pines.

PINING.d: Present participle of PINE: Any coniferous tree of the genus Pinus.
PINING.e: From Middle English pyne, from Old English *pīne, from Proto-West Germanic *pīnā, from Latin pīnus, see there for more. Doublet of pinus. Possibly related to fat.

PINION.e: From Middle English pynyon, from Old French pignon, from Latin penna (“feather”).

PINKED.d: Past tense of PINK: A color reminiscent of pinks, the flowers.
PINKED.e: Origin uncertain; perhaps from Dutch pinken (“blink”) or the English verb pink from the same source. Perhaps from the notion of the petals being pinked.

PINKIE.d: A little finger, the finger furthest on a hand from the thumb.
PINKIE.e: From Dutch pinkje (literally “little finger”), which in the Holland dialects takes the form pinkie.

PINNED.d: Past tense of PIN: A needle without an eye (usually) made of drawn-out steel wire with one end sharpened and the other flattened or rounded into a head, used for fastening.
PINNED.e:
From Middle English pinne, from Old English pinn (“pin, peg, bolt”), from Proto-Germanic *pinnaz, *pinnō, *pint- (“protruding point, peak, peg, pin, nail”), from Proto-Indo-European *bend- (“protruding object, pointed peg, nail, edge”). Related to pen (“enclosure”).
Cognate with ...

PINNER.d: Comparative form of PIN: A needle without an eye (usually) made of drawn-out steel wire with one end sharpened and the other flattened or rounded into a head, used for fastening.
PINNER.e:
From Middle English pinne, from Old English pinn (“pin, peg, bolt”), from Proto-Germanic *pinnaz, *pinnō, *pint- (“protruding point, peak, peg, pin, nail”), from Proto-Indo-European *bend- (“protruding object, pointed peg, nail, edge”). Related to pen (“enclosure”).
Cognate with ...

PINOUT.d: The manner in which an electrical connector or device is wired; the list of signals that correspond to each pin or output.

PINTLE.e: From Middle English pyntel, from Old English pintel (“penis”), from Proto-West Germanic *pint(i), from Proto-Germanic *pint- (“protrusion”), from Proto-Indo-European *bend- (“peg, tip, protruding point, edge”), equivalent to pin + -le. Cognate with North Frisian pint (“male membe...

PIOLET.e: Borrowed from French piolet, or its source, Franco-Provençal piolet (“small axe”).

PIONED.d: Past tense of PION: Any of three semistable mesons, having positive, negative or neutral charge, composed of up and down quarks/antiquarks.
PIONED.e: From pi + -on, as alteration of pi-meson.

PIPING.d: present participle and gerund of pipe

PIPPED.d: Past tense of PIP: Any of various respiratory diseases in birds, especially infectious coryza.
PIPPED.e: From Middle English pippe, from Middle Dutch pip, from post-classical Latin pipita, from Latin pītuīta (“mucus, phlegm, head cold”). Doublet of pituita.

PIPPER.d: Comparative form of PIP: Any of various respiratory diseases in birds, especially infectious coryza.
PIPPER.e: From Middle English pippe, from Middle Dutch pip, from post-classical Latin pipita, from Latin pītuīta (“mucus, phlegm, head cold”). Doublet of pituita.

PIPPIN.e: From Middle English pipin, from Old French pepin (“a seed”) (French pépin). See pip.

PIQUET.d: A game of cards for two people, with thirty-two cards, all the deuces, threes, fours, fives, and sixes being set aside.

PIRACY.d: Robbery at sea, a violation of international law; taking a ship away from the control of those who are legally entitled to it.
PIRACY.e: From Medieval Latin pīrātia, from Classical Latin pīrāta + ia, or Ancient Greek πειρατεία (peirateía).

PIRATE.d: A criminal who plunders at sea; commonly attacking merchant vessels, though often pillaging port towns.
PIRATE.e: From Middle English pirate, pirat, pyrat, from Old French pirate, from Latin pīrāta (“pirate”), from Ancient Greek πειρατής (peiratḗs), from πεῖρα (peîra, “trial, attempt, plot”). Displaced native Old English wīċing, which was the word for both "pirate" and "viking".

PISHED.d: Past tense of PISH: Expressing disdain.
PISHED.e: Expressive; perhaps partly from Scots pish (“piss”).

PISHES.e: Expressive; perhaps partly from Scots pish (“piss”).

PISSES.e: From Middle English pisse (noun) and pissen (verb), from Old French pissier, possibly from Vulgar Latin *pīssiāre, probably of imitative origin. Compare Old Norse pissa (“to urinate, piss”). Displaced Old English micge.

PISTIL.d: A discrete organ in the center of a flower capable of receiving pollen and producing a fruit, it is divided into an ovary, style and stigma.
PISTIL.e: Borrowed from French pistil. Doublet of pestle and pistillum.

PISTOL.e:
Probably from Middle French pistole, or via Middle English pistolet, from Middle French pistolet (“small firearm or small dagger”).
The origin is unclear.
If via German to Romance probably from Middle High German forms like pischulle from Czech píšťala (“firearm”, literally “tube...

PISTON.d: A solid disk or cylinder that fits inside a hollow cylinder, and moves under pressure (as in an engine) or displaces fluid (as in a pump)

PITHED.d: Past tense of PITH: The soft, spongy substance inside plant parts; specifically, the parenchyma in the centre of the roots and stems of many plants and trees.
PITHED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English pith, pithe (“central tissue of a plant’s stem or a tree’s trunk and branches; other spongy inner tissue in a plant; flesh of a fruit, pulp; inner tissue in a body; inner part of an object; essential part, essence, quintessence; importance,...

PITIED.d: Past tense of PITY: A feeling of sympathy at the misfortune or suffering of someone or something.
PITIED.e: From Middle English pitye, pitie, pittye, pitee, pite, from Anglo-Norman pité, pittee etc., from Old French pitet, pitié, from Latin pietās. See also the doublets pietà and piety.

PITIER.d: Comparative form of PITY: A feeling of sympathy at the misfortune or suffering of someone or something.
PITIER.e: From Middle English pitye, pitie, pittye, pitee, pite, from Anglo-Norman pité, pittee etc., from Old French pitet, pitié, from Latin pietās. See also the doublets pietà and piety.

PITIES.d: Plural of PITY: A feeling of sympathy at the misfortune or suffering of someone or something.
PITIES.e: From Middle English pitye, pitie, pittye, pitee, pite, from Anglo-Norman pité, pittee etc., from Old French pitet, pitié, from Latin pietās. See also the doublets pietà and piety.

PITMAN.d: One who works in a pit, as in mining, in sawing timber, etc.

PITPAN.d: A type of dugout canoe used in Central America

PITTED.d: Past tense of PIT: A hole in the ground.
PITTED.e: From Middle English pit, pet, püt, from Old English pytt, from Proto-West Germanic *puti, from Latin puteus (“trench, pit, well”), although there are phonetic difficulties.

PITTER.d: Comparative form of PIT: A hole in the ground.
PITTER.e: From Middle English pit, pet, püt, from Old English pytt, from Proto-West Germanic *puti, from Latin puteus (“trench, pit, well”), although there are phonetic difficulties.

PIXMAP.d: A grid of pixels; a bitmap, especially one having more than one bit (binary digit) assigned to each pixel, allowing for multiple shades or colors.

PIZZLE.e: From Dutch Low Saxon pesel or West Flemish pezel, diminutive of Middle Dutch pese (“a sinew, tendon, string, pizzle”), from Old Dutch *pisa (“sinew, string, fibre”), possibly ultimately related to vezel (“fiber”), from Proto-West Germanic *fas-il-, from Proto-Indo-European *pē̆s-...

PLACED.d: simple past and past participle of place

PLACET.d: A vote of assent, as of the governing body of a university, an ecclesiastical council, etc.
PLACET.e: Latin placet (“it is pleasing”), inflection of placeō (“I am pleasing”).

PLACID.e: From French placide, from Latin placidus (“peaceful, calm, placid”), from placeō (“please, satisfy”).

PLAGUE.d: The bubonic plague, the pestilent disease caused by the virulent bacterium Yersinia pestis.
PLAGUE.e: From Middle English plage, borrowed from Old French plage, from Latin plāga (“blow, wound”), from plangō (“to strike”). Cognate with Middle Dutch plāghe (> Dutch plaag), plāghen (> Dutch plagen); Middle Low German plāge; Middle High German plāge, pflāge (> German Plage); plāgen (...

PLAICE.d: Several similar marine flatfish of the righteye flounder family Pleuronectidae:
PLAICE.e: Inherited from Middle English playce, plays, from Old French plaiz, from Late Latin platessa, from Ancient Greek πλατύς (platús, “broad”). See platy-, plat and flat.

PLAINS.d: Plural of PLAIN: Simple; a flat area of land.
PLAINS.e: From Old French plain, from Latin plānus.

PLAINT.e: From Middle English plainte, borrowed from Anglo-Norman plainte (“lamentation”), plaint (“lament”), and Old French pleinte (“lamentation”), pleint (“lament”) (modern French plainte), from Medieval Latin plancta (“plaint”), from Latin planctus (“a beating of the breast in lamentat...

PLANED.d: Past tense of PLANE: An aircraft; a flat surface.

PLANES.d: Plural of PLANE: An aircraft; a flat surface.

PLANET.d: Each of the seven major bodies which move relative to the fixed stars in the night sky—the Moon, Mercury, Venus, the Sun, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn.
PLANET.e: From Middle English planete, from Old French planete, from Latin planeta, planetes, from Ancient Greek πλανήτης (planḗtēs, “wanderer”) (itself an ellipsis of ἀστέρες πλανῆται (astéres planêtai, “wandering stars”)), from Ancient Greek πλανάω (planáō, “wander about, stray”), of unk...

PLANTA.e: Borrowed from Latin planta (“sole of the foot”). Doublet of clan and plant.

PLANTS.d: Plural of PLANT: A living organism; a factory.

PLAQUE.d: Any flat, thin piece of clay, ivory, metal, etc., used for ornament, or for painting pictures upon, as a dish, plate, slab, etc., hung upon a wall; also, a smaller decoration worn by a person, such as a brooch.
PLAQUE.e: Unadapted borrowing from French plaque (“plate, sheet (of metal); slab (of marble); bacteria on teeth”), from French plaquer, Middle French plaquer (“to plate”), from Middle Dutch placken (“to patch, beat metal into a thin plate”), from placke (“disk, patch, stain”), from Old Dut...

PLASMA.d: A state of matter consisting of partially ionized gas and electrons.
PLASMA.e: From Late Latin plasma (“mold”), from Ancient Greek πλάσμα (plásma, “something formed”).

PLATED.d: Past tense of PLATE: A flat dish; a flat piece of metal.

PLATEN.d: The part of a printing press which presses the paper against the type and by which the impression is made.
PLATEN.e: From French platine, from plat (“flat”). See plate, and compare platin.

PLATES.d: Plural of PLATE: A flat dish; a flat piece of metal.

PLAYED.d: Past tense of PLAY: To act in a manner such that one has fun; to engage in activities expressly for the purpose of recreation or entertainment.
PLAYED.e: From Middle English pleyen, playen, pleȝen, plæien, also Middle English plaȝen, plawen (compare English plaw), from Old English pleġan, pleoġan, plæġan, and Old English plegian, pleagian, plagian (“to play, exercise, etc.”), from Proto-West Germanic *plehan (“to care about, be co...

PLAYER.e: From Middle English pleyer, playere, from Old English pleġere (“player, athlete, wrestler”), from Proto-West Germanic *plegārī. Equivalent to play + -er.

PLAZAS.d: Plural of PLAZA: A public square.
PLAZAS.e: From Spanish plaza, from Latin platea.

PLEACH.d: To unite by interweaving, as (horticulture) branches of shrubs, trees, etc., to create a hedge; to interlock, to plash.
PLEACH.e: The verb is from Late Middle English pleshe, Middle English plechen, pleche (“to layer; to propagate (a plant) by layering, to pleach”), possibly from Anglo-Norman and Middle French plesser, plessier, Middle French plescer, variants of Middle French, Old French plaissier, plessie...

PLEASE.d: To make happy or satisfy; to give pleasure to.
PLEASE.e: From Middle English plesen, plaisen, borrowed from Old French plaise, conjugated form of plaisir or plaire, from Latin placeō (“to please, to seem good”), from the Proto-Indo-European *pleHk- (“pleasingness, permission”). In this sense, displaced native Old English līcian, whence...

PLEDGE.d: To make a solemn promise (to do something).
PLEDGE.e: From Middle English plege, from Anglo-Norman plege, from Old French plege (Modern French pleige) from Medieval Latin plevium, plebium, from plebiō (“I pledge”), from Frankish *plehan (“to pledge; to support; to guarantee”). Akin to Old High German pflegan (“to take care of, be ac...

PLENTY.e: From Middle English plentie, plentee, plente, from Anglo-Norman plenté, from Old French plenté, from Latin plenitatem, accusative of plenitas (“fullness”), from plenus (“complete, full”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós (“full”), from which English full also comes, via Proto-G...

PLENUM.d: A space that is completely filled with matter.
PLENUM.e: From Latin plēnum, noun use of neuter of plēnus (“full”). The sense of "legislative meeting" is a semantic loan from Russian пле́нум (plénum, “plenary session”), from the same Latin source.

PLEURA.d: Each of a pair of smooth serous membranes which line the thorax and envelop the lungs in humans and other mammals.
PLEURA.e: From Middle English, borrowed from Medieval Latin pleura.

PLEXOR.d: A hammer (or other instrument) used to test a person's reflexes.
PLEXOR.e: From Hellenistic Ancient Greek πλῆξις (plêxis, “stroke”) + -or, after flexor etc.

PLEXUS.d: A network of anastomosing or interwoven nerves, blood vessels, or lymphatic vessels.
PLEXUS.e: Borrowed from Latin plexus (“a twining, plaiting, braid”).

PLIANT.d: Capable of plying or bending; readily yielding to force or pressure without breaking.
PLIANT.e: From Middle English pliaunt, from Old French ploiant, present participle of ploiier (“to fold”).

PLIGHT.e: From Middle English plit (“fold, wrinkle, bad situation”), conflation of Middle English pliht, plight (“risky promise, peril”) (from Old English pliht "danger, risk"; see Etymology 2) and Anglo-Norman plit, plyte (“fold, condition”), from Old French pleit (“condition, manner of f...

PLINTH.d: A block or slab upon which a column, pedestal, statue or other structure is based.
PLINTH.e: From French plinthe, from Latin plinthus, from Ancient Greek πλίνθος (plínthos, “brick”).

PLOIDY.d: The number of homologous sets of chromosomes in a cell.
PLOIDY.e: From the ending of words such as haploidy, polyploidy etc.

PLOUGH.d: A device pulled through the ground in order to break it open into furrows for planting.
PLOUGH.e: From Middle English plouh, plow, plugh(e), plough(e), plouw, from Old English plōh (“hide of land, ploughland”) and Old Norse plógr (“plough (the implement)”), both from Proto-Germanic *plōgaz, *plōguz (“plough”). Cognate with Scots pleuch, plou, North Frisian plog, West Frisian ...

PLOVER.d: Any of various wading birds of the subfamily Charadriinae.
PLOVER.e: Inherited from Middle English plover, from Anglo-Norman plover, plovier, from Medieval Latin plovarius, pluviārius, of disputed origin; perhaps from Latin pluvia (“rain”).

PLOYED.d: Past tense of PLOY: A tactic, strategy, or scheme.
PLOYED.e: Possibly from a shortened form of employ or deploy. Or from earlier ploye, from Middle English, borrowed from Middle French ployer (compare modern plier), from Latin plicāre.

PLUCKY.d: Having or showing pluck, courage or spirit in trying circumstances.

PLUMMY.d: Of, pertaining to, containing, or characteristic of plums.
PLUMMY.e: From plum + -y. In the sense of a voice, because of the supposed similarity to speaking with a plum in one's mouth.

PLUNGE.d: To thrust into liquid, or into any penetrable substance; to immerse.
PLUNGE.e: From Middle English plungen, ploungen, Anglo-Norman plungier, from Old French plongier, (Modern French plonger), from unattested Late Latin frequentative *plumbicō (“to throw a leaded line”), from plumbum (“lead”). Compare plumb, plounce.

PLURAL.d: Consisting of or containing more than one of something.
PLURAL.e: From Middle English plurelle, from Old French plurel (“plural”), Borrowed from Latin plūrālis (“of or belonging to more than one, belonging to many”, adjective), from plūs, plūris (“more”) + -ālis.

PLUSES.d: Plural of PLUS: And; sum of the previous one and the following one.

PLUTON.d: A body of igneous rock formed beneath the surface of the earth by consolidation of magma

PLYING.d: Present participle of PLY: A layer of material.
PLYING.e: From Middle English pleit, plit, plite (“a fold, pleat, wrinkle; braid, strand in a braided cord, ply”), from Anglo-Norman pli, plei, pleit, and Middle French pli, ploy, ply (“a fold, pleat; joint in armour; situation, state”) (modern French pli (“a fold, pleat”)), from plier, pl...

POCKED.d: Past tense of POCK: A pus-filled swelling on the surface on the skin caused by an eruptive disease.
POCKED.e: From Middle English pok, from Old English poc, pocc (“pock; pustule; ulcer”), from Proto-West Germanic *pokk, from Proto-Germanic *pukkaz, *pukkǭ (“pock; swelling”), from Proto-Indo-European *bew-, *bʰew- (“to grow; swell”). Cognate with Dutch pok (“pock”), Low German Pocke (“poc...

POCKET.d: A bag stitched to an item of clothing, used for carrying small items.
POCKET.e: From Middle English pocket (“bag, sack”), from Anglo-Norman poket, Old Northern French poquet, poquete, diminutive of poque, poke (“bag, sack”) (compare modern Norman pouquette and modern French pochette from Old French pochete, from puche), from Frankish *pokō (“pouch”), from Pr...

PODDED.d: Past tense of POD: A seed case for legumes (e.g. peas, beans, peppers); a seedpod.
PODDED.e: Origin uncertain. Perhaps from Middle English *pod ("seed-pod, husk, shell, outer covering"; attested in pod-ware (“legume seed; seed grain”)), itself possibly from Old English pād (“an outer garment, covering, coat, cloak”), from Proto-West Germanic *paidu, from Proto-Germanic *...

PODDER.d: Comparative form of POD: A seed case for legumes (e.g. peas, beans, peppers); a seedpod.
PODDER.e: Origin uncertain. Perhaps from Middle English *pod ("seed-pod, husk, shell, outer covering"; attested in pod-ware (“legume seed; seed grain”)), itself possibly from Old English pād (“an outer garment, covering, coat, cloak”), from Proto-West Germanic *paidu, from Proto-Germanic *...

PODIUM.d: A platform on which to stand, as when conducting an orchestra or preaching at a pulpit; any low platform or dais.
PODIUM.e: Borrowed from Latin podium, from Ancient Greek πόδιον (pódion, “base”), a diminutive of πούς (poús, “foot”). Doublet of pew.

PODZOL.d: The typical soil of coniferous or boreal forests.
PODZOL.e: Borrowed from Russian подзо́л (podzól), consisting of под (pod) "under" and зола́ (zolá) "ash".

POETIC.e: From Middle French poetique, from Latin poeticus, from Ancient Greek ποιητικός (poiētikós) from ποιέω (poiéō, “make”). Doublet of poietic.

POETRY.d: Literature composed in verse or language exhibiting conscious attention to patterns and rhythm.
POETRY.e: From Middle English poetrye, poetrie, a borrowing from Old French pöeterie, pöetrie, from Medieval Latin poētria, from poēta (“poet”), from Ancient Greek ποιητής (poiētḗs, “poet; author; maker”). Displaced native Old English lēoþcræft.

POGROM.d: A riot aimed at persecution or massacre of a particular ethnic or religious group, usually Jews.
POGROM.e: Borrowed from Yiddish פּאָגראָם (pogrom), from Russian погро́м (pogróm).

POINTE.d: The tip of the toe; a ballet position executed with the tip of the toe.
POINTE.e: From French pointe (“point, tip”). Doublet of point, ponto, puncto, punctum, punt, and punto.

POINTS.d: Plural of POINT: A sharp end; a location; to indicate.
POINTS.e: From Old French point, from Latin pūnctum.

POINTY.d: Pointed in shape; having a point or points.

POISON.d: A substance that is harmful or lethal to a living organism when ingested.
POISON.e: From Middle English poisoun, poyson, poysone, puyson, puisun, from Old French poison, poisun, from Latin pōtiōnem (“drink, a draught, a poisonous draught, a potion”), from pōtō (“I drink”). See also potion and potable (from the same root). Mostly displaced native Old English ātor...

POKIER.d: Comparative form of POKY: A gambling device based on the card game poker.
POKIER.e: By shortening from poker machine (“gambling device”).

POKIES.d: Plural of POKY: A gambling device based on the card game poker.
POKIES.e: By shortening from poker machine (“gambling device”).

POKING.d: Present participle of POKE: To prod or jab with an object such as a finger or a stick.
POKING.e: From Middle English poken, perhaps from Middle Dutch poken or Middle Low German poken, both from Proto-West Germanic *pukōn or similar, which is itself of uncertain origin, but may be from an imitative Proto-Germanic root *puk-. Doublet of poach.

POLDER.d: An area of ground reclaimed from a sea or lake by means of dikes.
POLDER.e: Borrowed from Dutch polder, from Middle Dutch polre, from Old Dutch polra, of uncertain origin.

POLICE.d: A public agency charged with enforcing laws and maintaining public order, usually being granted special privileges to do so, particularly
POLICE.e: From Middle French police, from Latin polītīa (“state, government”), from Ancient Greek πολιτεία (politeía). Doublet of policy and polity.

POLICY.d: A principle of behaviour, conduct which an entity (government, organization, etc.) applies or seeks to follow, especially as formally expressed by an authoritative body.
POLICY.e: From Middle English policie, from Old French policie, pollicie and police, from Late Latin politia (“citizenship; government”), classical Latin polītīa (in Cicero), from Ancient Greek πολιτεία (politeía, “citizenship; polis, (city) state; government”), from πολίτης (polítēs, “cit...

POLING.d: Present participle of POLE: Originally, a stick; now specifically, a long and slender piece of metal or (especially) wood, used for various construction or support purposes.
POLING.e: From Middle English pole, pal, from Old English pāl (“a pole, stake, post; a kind of hoe or spade”), from Proto-West Germanic *pāl (“pole”), from Latin pālus (“stake, pale, prop, stay”), perhaps from Old Latin *paxlos, from Proto-Italic *pākslos, ultimately from Proto-Indo-Europe...

POLISH.d: Of, from or native to Poland, or relating to the Polish language.

POLITE.e: From Latin polītus (“polished”), past participle of poliō (“I polish, smooth”); see polish.

POLITY.d: Organizational structure and governance, especially of a state or a religion.
POLITY.e: From Middle French politie, from Latin polītīa, from Ancient Greek πολιτεία (politeía, “polity, policy, the state”). Doublet of policy and police.

POLLAN.d: A freshwater fish, Coregonus pollan, resembling a herring

POLLEN.d: A fine, granular substance produced in flowers.
POLLEN.e: From Latin pollen (“fine flour”). Used by Linnaeus in the 18th century to describe the spores produced in the anthers of flowers.

POLONY.d: A kind of sausage made of meat that has been only partly cooked.
