POLYOL.d: Any organic compound having multiple hydroxyl functional groups, such as polyhydric alcohols.

POMADE.d: A greasy or waxy substance that is used to style hair, making it look slick and shiny.
POMADE.e: From French pommade, from Italian pomata (“ointment, pomade”), from pomo (“apple”) + -ata (“-ade, -ate: forming nouns”), from Latin pōmum (“fruit, apple”). Doublet of pomatum, pomate, and pomace. Early pomades tended to be various kinds of fat mixed with apples for a more pleasin...

POMELO.d: The large fruit of the Citrus maxima (syn. C. grandis), native to South Asia and Southeast Asia, with a thick green or yellow rind, a thick white pith, and semi-sweet translucent pale flesh.
POMELO.e: Of uncertain etymology, though possibly a variant of earlier pampelmoes, from French, Dutch, Portuguese sources ultimately equivalent to "thick lemon" or transcribing the Tamil பம்ப ளிமாசு (pampa ḷimācu, “big citrus”). Alternatively, possibly from pome (“apple”) + melon or some c...

POMMEL.d: The upper front brow of a saddle.
POMMEL.e: From Middle English pomel, from Old French pomel and Medieval Latin pomellum, pumellum, presumedly via Vulgar Latin *pomellum (“ball, knob”), the diminutive of Late Latin pōmum (“apple”). Compare French pommeau, Spanish pomo, and Swedish pumla.

POMPOM.d: A decorative ball made of pieces of soft fabric, tinsel, plastic, or paper streamers bound at the center, most notably held, waved, and shaken in cheerleading.
POMPOM.e: Alteration of pompon, from French pompon (“ornamental tuft”); of unknown origin, perhaps related to Old French pomp.

POMPON.d: A bundle of yarn, string, ribbon, etc. tied in the middle and left loose at the ends, so as to form a puff or ball, as for decoration or a showy prop for cheerleading.

PONCHO.d: A simple garment, made from a rectangle of cloth, with a slit in the middle for the head.
PONCHO.e: Borrowed from Spanish poncho, from Quechua punchu. In sense “rubber rain poncho”, attested 1845, used for non-South American garments in the United States and England from 1850s, popularized by US Western expeditions and military from 1850s, particularly after World War II (1940s...

PONDER.e: From Middle English ponderen, from Old French ponderer (“to weigh, balance, ponder”) from Latin ponderare (“to weigh, ponder”), from pondus (“weight”), from pendere (“to weigh”); see pendent and pound.

PONGEE.d: A soft unbleached silk, from China or India, from silkworms that feed on oak leaves.
PONGEE.e: From Mandarin 本機／本机 (běnjī, literally “one’s own loom; home-woven; homemade”).

PONIED.d: Past tense of PONY: A small horse; specifically, any of several small breeds of horse under 14.2 hands at the withers.
PONIED.e: 1659 from Scots powny, apparently from Middle French poulenet (“little foal”), ultimately from Late Latin pullanus (“young of an animal”), from pullus (cognate to English foal). Sense “small serving of alcohol” from 19th century, both for small sizes generally and for a quarter p...

PONIER.d: Comparative form of PONY: A small horse; specifically, any of several small breeds of horse under 14.2 hands at the withers.
PONIER.e: 1659 from Scots powny, apparently from Middle French poulenet (“little foal”), ultimately from Late Latin pullanus (“young of an animal”), from pullus (cognate to English foal). Sense “small serving of alcohol” from 19th century, both for small sizes generally and for a quarter p...

PONIES.d: Plural of PONY: A small horse; specifically, any of several small breeds of horse under 14.2 hands at the withers.
PONIES.e: 1659 from Scots powny, apparently from Middle French poulenet (“little foal”), ultimately from Late Latin pullanus (“young of an animal”), from pullus (cognate to English foal). Sense “small serving of alcohol” from 19th century, both for small sizes generally and for a quarter p...

PONTIL.d: Alternative form of punty (“rod used in glassblowing”).

POODLE.d: A breed of dog originating in Europe as hunting dogs, and having heavy, curly coat in a solid color; their shoulder height indicates their classification as standard, medium, miniature, or toy.
POODLE.e:
From German Pudel, a shortened form of Pudelhund, a compound of Hund (“dog”) and the German Low German term Pudel, Pūdel (“puddle”), from the onomatopoeic term pudeln (“to splash about”). First attested in 1773 in the sense 1.
The verb sense references the appearance a poodle wit...

POOHED.d: Past tense of POOH: Short for Winnie the Pooh.

POOLED.d: Past tense of POOL: A small and rather deep area of (usually) fresh water, as one supplied by a spring, or occurring in the course of a stream or river; a reservoir for water.
POOLED.e:
From Middle English pool, pole, pol, from Old English pōl (“pool”), from Proto-West Germanic pōl, from Proto-Germanic *pōlaz (“pool, pond”), from Proto-Indo-European *bōlos (“bog, marsh”).
Cognate with Scots puil (“pool”), Saterland Frisian Pol (“pool”), West Frisian poel (“pool”...

POOPED.d: Past tense of POOP: To make a short blast on a horn.
POOPED.e: Uncertain, possibly from Middle English poupen (“to make a gulping sound while drinking, blow on a horn, toot”). Compare Dutch poepen (“to defecate”), German Low German pupen (“to fart; break wind”). Also representing poo pronounced with the mouth snapped closed at the end.

POOTLE.e: Apparently an alteration of poodle, from German Low German Pudel, from the onomatopoeic term pudeln (“to splash about”) by its merging with tootle. Alternatively, a blending of doodle (to draw aimlessly) with potter (to move aimlessly)—as reported by 1970s English visitors to Aus...

POPISH.d: of or pertaining to Roman Catholicism

POPLAR.d: Any of various deciduous trees of the genus Populus.
POPLAR.e: From Middle English popler, from Anglo-Norman popler and Old French poplier (compare French peuplier), from Latin pōpulus, with a suffix later added.

POPLIN.d: A fabric of many varieties, usually made of silk and worsted; used especially for women's dresses.
POPLIN.e: An alteration (taken as related to Pope) of French papeline, a distortion of Poperinge, a town in Flanders which was a centre for textile production.

POPPED.d: Past tense of POP: A loud, sharp sound, as of a cork coming out of a bottle, especially when the contents are pressurized by fizziness.
POPPED.e: From Middle English pop, poppe (“a blow; strike; buffet”) (> Middle English poppen (“to strike; thrust”, verb)), of onomatopoeic origin – used to describe the sound, or short, sharp actions. The physics sense is part of a facetious sequence "snap, crackle, pop", after the mascots...

POPPER.d: Comparative form of POP: A loud, sharp sound, as of a cork coming out of a bottle, especially when the contents are pressurized by fizziness.
POPPER.e: From Middle English pop, poppe (“a blow; strike; buffet”) (> Middle English poppen (“to strike; thrust”, verb)), of onomatopoeic origin – used to describe the sound, or short, sharp actions. The physics sense is part of a facetious sequence "snap, crackle, pop", after the mascots...

POPPET.d: An endearingly sweet or beautiful child.

POPPLE.e: From Middle English popul, popil, from Old English popul, from Latin populus.

PORING.d: Present participle of PORE: A tiny opening in the skin.
PORING.e: From Middle English pore, from Old French pore, from Latin porus, from Ancient Greek πόρος (póros, “passage”). Displaced native English sweat hole from Middle English swet hole, which might have been a reformation of Old English swātþȳrel (literally “sweat hole”), which competed ...

POROUS.d: Full of tiny pores that allow fluids or gasses to pass through.
POROUS.e: From Old French poros, from Latin porus (“an opening”). By surface analysis, pore + -ous.

PORTAL.d: An entrance, entry point, or means of entry.
PORTAL.e: From Middle English portal, porttol, from Old French portal and Medieval Latin portāle, from porta.

PORTED.d: simple past and past participle of port

PORTER.d: A person who carries luggage and related objects.
PORTER.e: From Middle English porter, portere, portier, borrowed from Anglo-Norman portour and Old French porteor, from Late Latin portātor, from past participle of Latin portāre (“to carry”). By surface analysis, port (“to carry”) + -er.

PORTLY.e: From an archaic sense of port (“manner in which a person carries himself; bearing; deportment; carriage”) + -ly.

POSEUR.d: One who affects some behaviour, style, attitude or other condition, often to impress or influence others.

POSIED.d: Past tense of POSY: A flower; a small bouquet; a nosegay.

POSIES.d: Plural of POSY: A flower; a small bouquet; a nosegay.

POSING.d: Present participle of POSE: Common cold, head cold; catarrh.
POSING.e: From Middle English pose, from Old English ġeposu pl (“cold in the head; catarrh”, literally “(the) sneezes; (the) snorts”), from Old English pos, ġepos (“sneeze, snort”), from Proto-West Germanic *pos, from Proto-Germanic *pusą (“sneeze, snort”), from Proto-Germanic *pusōną, *pu...

POSSET.d: A beverage composed of hot milk curdled by some strong infusion, such as wine.
POSSET.e: From Middle English posset, possot, possate, poshet, posthot, of unclear origin. Perhaps from Welsh posel. A connection to Latin pōsca (medieval/dialectal poscada) has also been suggested.

POSSUM.d: An opossum, a marsupial of the family Didelphidae of the Americas.

POSTAL.d: Relating to the collection, sorting and delivery of mail.
POSTAL.e: From post + -al, modelled on French postal.

POSTED.d: simple past and past participle of post

POSTER.d: A picture of a celebrity, an event etc., intended to be attached to a wall.

POSTIL.d: A Bible commentary written in its margins.
POSTIL.e: From French postille (“marginal note”), from Late Latin postilla, probably from post illa (verba) (“after those (words)”).

POTAGE.d: A thick soup, especially a creamy one.
POTAGE.e: Borrowed from French potage, and from earlier borrowing pottage.

POTASH.d: The water-soluble part of wood ash, used for making soap and glass and as a fertilizer (chemically speaking, an impure form of potassium carbonate (K₂CO₃) mixed with other potassium salts).
POTASH.e: From pot + ash, because the substance was originally obtained by leaching ash in water and then boiling down the resulting solution in a pot. Compare Dutch potas, German Pottasche.

POTATO.d: A plant of species Solanum tuberosum or its edible starchy tuber.
POTATO.e: Borrowed from Spanish patata, itself borrowed from Taíno batata (“sweet potato”).

POTENT.e: From Middle English potent, borrowed from Latin potens, potentis (“powerful, strong, potent”), present participle of posse (“to be able”), from potis (“able, powerful, originally a lord, master”).

POTFUL.d: as much as a pot will hold
POTFUL.e: From Middle English potful; equivalent to pot + -ful.

POTHER.e: Origin uncertain. Compare Dutch peuteren (“to rummage, poke”), and English potter, pudder.

POTION.d: A small portion or dose of a liquid which is medicinal, poisonous, or magical.
POTION.e: From Middle English pocioun, borrowed from Old French pocion, from Latin pōtiō (“a drinking”), pōtiōnis, from pōtāre (“to drink”). Doublet of poison.

POTTED.d: Past tense of POT: A flat-bottomed vessel (usually metal) used for cooking food, possibly excluding saucepans (see usage notes).
POTTED.e:
From Middle English pot, potte, from Old English pott (“pot”) and Old French pot (“pot”) (probably from Frankish *pott); both Old English and Frankish from Proto-Germanic *puttaz (“pot”), from Proto-Indo-European *budnós (“a type of vessel”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Pot (“...

POTTER.d: One who makes pots and other ceramic wares.
POTTER.e: From Middle English pottere, from Old English pottere (“potter”, in placenames), from Proto-West Germanic *pottārī (“pot-maker”), equivalent to pot + -er. Influenced by Anglo-Norman poter, Old French potier (“potter”). Cognate with Dutch potter (“potter”), German Low German Pötte...

POUNCE.d: A type of fine powder, as of sandarac, or cuttlefish bone, sprinkled over wet ink to dry the ink after writing or on rough paper to smooth the writing surface.
POUNCE.e: From French ponce, from Latin pūmex. Doublet of pumice.

POUNDS.d: Plural of POUND: A unit of weight; British currency.
POUNDS.e: From Old English pund, from Latin pondō.

POURED.d: Past tense of POUR: To cause (liquid, or liquid-like substance) to flow in a stream, either out of a container or into it.
POURED.e:
From Middle English pouren (“to pour”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old Northern French purer (“to sift (grain), pour out (water)”), from Latin pūrō (“to purify”), from pūrus (“pure”). Compare Middle Dutch afpuren (“to pour off, drain”).
To pour displaced several Middle Eng...

POUTED.d: Past tense of POUT: To push out one's lips.
POUTED.e: From Middle English pouten, probably from Scandinavian (compare Norwegian pute (“pillow, cushion”), dial. Swedish puta (“to be puffed out”), Danish pude (“pillow, cushion”)), from Proto-Germanic *pūto (“swollen”) (compare English eelpout, Dutch puit, Low German puddig (“inflated”...

POWDER.d: The fine particles which are the result of reducing a dry substance by pounding, grinding, or triturating, or the result of decay; dust.
POWDER.e: From Middle English poudre, pouder, pouldre, borrowed from Old French poudre, poldre, puldre, from Latin pulverem, accusative singular of Latin pulvis (“dust, powder”). Doublet of pulver. Compare pollen (“fine flour”), polverine, pulverize.

POWERS.d: Plural of POWER: The ability to do something; strength.

POWWOW.d: A ritual conducted by a Native American shaman.
POWWOW.e: From an Eastern Algonquian language, probably Massachusett pauwau (“he uses divination; he practices magic or sorcery”) or Narragansett powwáw (“sorcerer, shaman”), ultimately from Proto-Algonquian *pawe·wa (“one who dreams”).

POXING.d: Present participle of POX: A disease characterized by purulent skin eruptions that may leave pockmarks.
POXING.e: From the plural of Middle English pocke. See also pock.

PRAISE.e: From Middle English praise, preyse, from the verb (see below). Doublet of prize. Displaced native Middle English lof from Old English lof (“praise”) and Middle English loenge, loange from Old French löenge, löange (“praise”).

PRANCE.d: To spring forward on the hind legs.
PRANCE.e: From Middle English prancen, prauncen (“to prance”, literally “to show off”), variant of Middle English pranken (“to prank”), thus probably from the same ultimate root as prank. Cognate with Bavarian prangezen, prangssen (“to put on airs”), Alemannic German pranzen (“to strut”).

PRANNY.e: Uncertain; perhaps compare prat, fanny, prannet.

PRAXIS.d: The practical application of any branch of learning.
PRAXIS.e: Partly from Latin prāxis and partly from its etymon Ancient Greek πρᾶξις (prâxis, “action, activity, practice”).

PRAYED.d: Past tense of PRAY: To direct words, thoughts, or one's attention to a deity or any higher being, for the sake of adoration, thanks, petition for help, etc.
PRAYED.e:
From Middle English preien, from Anglo-Norman preier, from Old French preier, proier (French prier), from Latin precārī, from prex, precis (“a prayer, a request”), from Proto-Italic *preks, from Proto-Indo-European *preḱ- (“to ask, woo”). Displaced native Old English gebiddan.
Co...

PRAYER.d: A practice of communicating with one's God, or with some spiritual entity.
PRAYER.e: From Middle English preiere, from Old French preiere, from Early Medieval Latin precāria, derived from Latin precem. Displaced native Old English ġebed.

PREACH.e:
From Middle English prechen, from Old French prëechier, precchier (Modern French prêcher), from Latin praedicō (“to proclaim, announce”, literally “to fore-assign, pre-dedicate”). Doublet of predicate.
The Latin word is also the source of Old English predician (“to preach”), Sate...

PREFER.d: To be in the habit of choosing something rather than something else; to favor; to like better.
PREFER.e: From Middle English preferren, from Anglo-Norman preferer, from Latin praeferō. Displaced native Old English foresettan and foreberan. Doublet of prelate. See also infer, relate and refer, delate and defer, as well as collate and confer among others.

PREFIX.e: Borrowed from Late Latin praefīxum, from Latin praefīxus, past participle of praefīgō (“I (fix, fasten, set up) in front”, “I fix on the (end, extremity)”) (from prae- (“before”) + fīgō (“I fix”, “I fasten”, “I affix”)), equivalent to pre- + -fix. Doublet of the archaic synonym p...

PRELIM.e:
Clipping of preliminary.
Sense 2 ("clipping of preliminary examination") was originally Oxford University slang, now in common use.

PREPAY.d: To pay in advance, or beforehand

PRESET.d: Set in advance, or as a default.

PRESTO.d: Very fast or quickly; a directive for the musician(s) to play in a very quick tempo.

PRETTY.d: Pleasant to the sight or other senses; attractive, especially of women or children.
PRETTY.e: From Middle English prety, preti, praty, prati, from Old English prættiġ (“tricky, crafty, sly, cunning, wily, astute”), from Proto-West Germanic *prattug, from Proto-Germanic *prattugaz (“boastful, sly, slick, deceitful, tricky, cunning”), corresponding to prat (“trick”) + -y. D...

PREYED.d: Past tense of PREY: That which is or may be seized by animals to be devoured.
PREYED.e: From Middle English preye, prei, preyȝe, borrowed from Anglo-Norman and Old French preie, one of the variants of proie, from Latin praeda. Compare predator. Doublet of prede.

PRICED.d: Past tense of PRICE: The amount of money required.
PRICED.e: From Old French pris, from Latin pretium.

PRICER.d: One who, or that which, prices.

PRICES.d: Plural of PRICE: The amount of money required.
PRICES.e: From Old French pris, from Latin pretium.

PRIDED.d: Past tense of PRIDE: A feeling of satisfaction.

PRIDES.d: Plural of PRIDE: A feeling of satisfaction.

PRIEST.d: A religious clergyman (clergywoman, clergyperson) who is trained to perform services or sacrifices at a church or temple.
PRIEST.e: From Middle English prest, preest, from Old English prēost (“priest”), from Late Latin presbyter, from Ancient Greek πρεσβύτερος (presbúteros), from πρέσβυς (présbus, “elder, older”). Reinforced in Middle English by Old French prestre, also from Latin presbyter. Doublet of presby...

PRIMED.d: Past tense of PRIME: Of first importance; the best time.

PRIMES.d: Plural of PRIME: Of first importance; the best time.

PRIMUS.d: One of the bishops of the Scottish Episcopal Church, who presides at the meetings of the bishops, and has certain privileges but no metropolitan authority.
PRIMUS.e: From Latin prīmus (“[the] first”); related to prior, the comparative form. Partially cognate to foremost, from Proto-Indo-European [Term?]. Doublet of prime and primo.

PRINCE.d: A (male) ruler, a sovereign; a king, monarch.
PRINCE.e:
From Middle English prince, from Anglo-Norman prince, from Latin prīnceps (“first head”), from prīmus (“first”) + capiō (“seize, take”). Cognate with Old English fruma (“prince, ruler”). Doublet of princeps and principe.
Displaced native Middle English atheling, from Old English ...

PRINTS.d: Plural of PRINT: To produce text by pressing; printed matter.

PRIORS.d: Plural of PRIOR: Existing before; more important.

PRIORY.d: A monastery or convent governed by a prior or prioress.

PRISON.d: A place or institution where people are held against their will, in the US especially for long-term confinement, as of those convicted of serious crimes or otherwise considered undesirable by the government.
PRISON.e: From Middle English prisoun, prison, from Old English prisūn, a borrowing from Old French prison, from Latin prehensiōnem, accusative singular of prehensiō, from the verb prehendō. Doublet of prehension.

PRISSY.d: Prim and fussy; too precise; overparticular.
PRISSY.e: 1895, either an alteration of precise, blend of prim + sissy, or a blend of prim + fussy; first attested in a work of American writer Joel Chandler Harris.

PRIVET.d: Any of various shrubs and small trees in the genus Ligustrum.
PRIVET.e: Unknown origin, but possibly connected to prime.

PRIZED.d: Past tense of PRIZE: A reward for achievement.

PRIZES.d: Plural of PRIZE: A reward for achievement.

PROBIT.d: A unit, derived from a standard distribution, used in measuring the responses to doses
PROBIT.e: Blend of probability + unit. Coined by Chester Ittner Bliss in 1934: “These arbitrary probability units have been termed ‘probits’…”

PROFIT.d: Total income or cash flow minus expenditures. The money or other benefit a non-governmental organization or individual receives in exchange for products and services sold at an advertised price.
PROFIT.e: From Middle English profit, from Old French profit (Modern French profit), from Latin prōfectus (“advance, progress, growth, increase, profit”), from proficiō (“to go forward, advance, make progress, be profitable or useful”). Doublet of profect.

PROLEG.d: An appendage of the abdomen of some insect larvae, such as caterpillars, which is used like a leg.

PROLIX.d: Tediously lengthy; dwelling on trivial details.
PROLIX.e: From Old French prolixe, from Latin prōlixus (“stretched out; courteous, favorable”). The verb is derived from the adjective.

PROMPT.e: The adjective is from Middle English prompte, from Middle French prompt and its etymon Latin prōmptus (“visible, apparent, evident”), past participle of prōmō (“to take or bring out or forth, produce, bring to light”), from prō (“forth, forward”) + emō (“to take, acquire, buy”). ...

PROOFS.d: Plural of PROOF: Evidence establishing a fact.

PROPEL.d: To provide an impetus for motion or physical action; to cause to move in a certain direction; to drive or push forward.
PROPEL.e: From Middle English propellen (“drive out, expel”), from Latin propellō, from pro- (“forward”) and pellō (“I push, I move”).

PROPER.e: From Middle English propre, from Anglo-Norman proper, propre, Old French propre (French: propre), from Latin proprius.

PROPYL.d: Either of two isomeric univalent hydrocarbon radicals, C₃H₇, formally derived from propane by the loss of a hydrogen atom.
PROPYL.e: From the chemical prefix propyl-, from propylic or directly from earlier French propylique, from prop(ionique) + -yle + -ique, where -yle, as in French méthylène, is from ὕλη (húlē, “wood, substance”).

PROSES.d: Plural of PROS: plural of pro

PROTEA.d: Any of many South African flowering plants, of the genus Protea, having colourful cone-shaped flower heads.
PROTEA.e: Named after Proteus, the Greek warden of sea-beasts, renowned for his ability to change shape.

PROTON.d: A positively charged subatomic particle forming part of the nucleus of an atom and determining the atomic number of an element, composed of two up quarks and a down quark.
PROTON.e:
Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek πρῶτον (prôton), neuter of πρῶτος (prôtos, “first”).
(physics): Coined by New Zealand-British scientist Ernest Rutherford in 1920, in analogy with electron (1891), and with an additional intention of honoring English chemist William Prout. Ana...

PROVED.d: simple past and past participle of prove

PROVEN.d: Having been proved; having proved its value or truth.
PROVEN.e: From Scottish English, as past participle of preve, a Middle English variant of prove – compare woven (from weave) and cloven (from cleave), both of which feature -eve → -oven. Preve died out in England, but survived in Scotland, where proven developed, initially in a legal conte...

PROVES.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of prove

PROWED.d: Past tense of PROW: The front part of a vessel.
PROWED.e: From Middle French proue, proe, from Ligurian prua, proa, from Latin prōra, from Ancient Greek πρῷρα (prōîra).

PRYING.d: Present participle of PRY: To peer closely and curiously, especially at something closed or not public.
PRYING.e: The verb is inherited from Middle English prien, pryen (“to look closely, peer into, pry, spy”) [and other forms], from Old English *prīwan, *prēowian (“to look narrowly, to squint at”), attested by Old English beprīwan, beprēwan (“to wink”); further etymology unknown, but probab...

PSEUDO.d: An intellectually pretentious person; a pseudointellectual.
PSEUDO.e: From Middle English, derived from prefix pseudo-, itself derived from Ancient Greek ψευδής (pseudḗs, “false, lying”).

PSYCHE.d: The human soul, mind, or spirit.
PSYCHE.e: Learned borrowing from Latin psychē, itself a borrowing from Ancient Greek ψυχή (psukhḗ, “soul”).

PSYCHO.e: Clipping of psychotic or psychopath + -o (“person with characteristic”). Compare sicko.

PTOSIS.d: The prolapse of a bodily organ, especially drooping of the eyelid or the breasts.
PTOSIS.e: From Ancient Greek πτῶσις (ptôsis, “falling, fall”), from πίπτω (píptō, “to fall down”) + -σις (-sis, nominal suffix). First used in 1710.

PUBLIC.d: Able to be known or seen by everyone; happening without concealment; open to general view.
PUBLIC.e: The adjective and noun are derived from Late Middle English publik, publike (“(adjective) generally observable, public; relating to the general public or public affairs; (noun) a generally observable place or situation”), from Anglo-Norman public, publik, publique, Middle French ...

PUCKER.d: To pinch or wrinkle (especially a body part); to squeeze inwardly, to dimple or fold.
PUCKER.e:
Origin obscure. Perhaps continuing Middle English pukkeren (“to hoard, save”, literally “to sack, stow away in a poke or bag”) with a change in meaning (compare purse (“to pucker”)).
Alternatively, perhaps a direct alteration of poke (verb, or the noun meaning "a small bag"). By ...

PUDDLE.d: A small, often temporary, pool of water, usually on a path or road.
PUDDLE.e: From Middle English podel, diminutive of Old English pudd (“ditch”), from Proto-Germanic *puddaz (compare Low German Pudel (“puddle”), Middle High German podel (“quagmire, mudhole”), Hunsrik Puttel, dialectal German Pfudel (“puddle”), German pudeln (“to splash about”)), ultimatel...

PUEBLO.d: A community in Spain or Spanish America, especially one of Pueblo Indians living in a stone or adobe multi-storey building.
PUEBLO.e: Borrowed from Spanish pueblo, from Latin populus. Doublet of people.

PUFFED.d: Past tense of PUFF: A sharp exhalation of a small amount of breath through the mouth.
PUFFED.e: From Middle English puff, puf, from Old English pyf (“a blast of wind, puff”), imitative. Cognate with Middle Low German puf, pof.

PUFFIN.d: The young of the Manx shearwater (Puffinus puffinus), especially eaten as food.
PUFFIN.e: From Middle English poffin, poffoun, puffon, equivalent to puff + -ing, or perhaps ultimately from Middle Cornish (compare Breton poc'han (“puffin”)).

PUGGED.d: Past tense of PUG: Senses relating to someone or something small.
PUGGED.e: Origin unknown, possibly related to West Flemish pugge (“(adjective) small; (noun) short person; pet name derived from the first name Pugge”); though it is uncertain whether sense 1 (“senses relating to someone or something small”) and sense 2 (“senses relating to people”) are de...

PUGGER.d: Comparative form of PUG: Senses relating to someone or something small.
PUGGER.e: Origin unknown, possibly related to West Flemish pugge (“(adjective) small; (noun) short person; pet name derived from the first name Pugge”); though it is uncertain whether sense 1 (“senses relating to someone or something small”) and sense 2 (“senses relating to people”) are de...

PUISNE.e: From Anglo-Norman puisné (“later, more recent; junior; weakly”) [and other forms] and Middle French puisné (“born after (a specified person); younger, youngest; one who is born after (a specified person)”) (modern French puîné (“cadet (born after a sibling); a cadet (someone born...

PUKING.e: Probably imitative; or, alternatively from Proto-Germanic *pukaną (“to spit, puff”), from Proto-Indo-European *bew- (“to blow, swell”). If so, then cognate with German pfauchen, fauchen (“to hiss, spit”). Compare also Dutch spugen (“to spit, spit up”), German spucken (“to spit, p...

PULING.d: Present participle of PULE: A plaintive melancholy whine.
PULING.e: From French piauler, a variant of French piailler (“to chirp, cheep”). Compare Italian pigolare (“to cheep as a chicken”).

PULLET.d: A young hen, especially one less than a year old.
PULLET.e: From Middle English polet, pulet, from Anglo-Norman pullet, Old French poulet (“young chicken”); polette (“young hen”), from poule (“hen”). Doublet of poult. Compare also Middle English pulle.

PULLEY.d: One of the simple machines; a sheave, a wheel with a grooved rim, in which a pulled rope or chain lifts an object (more useful when two or more pulleys are used together, as in a block and tackle arrangement, such that a small force moving through a greater distance can exert a larger force through a smaller distance).
PULLEY.e: From Middle English puly, poley, from Old French poulie, polie (“a pulley, windlass”), from Medieval Latin polidia, plural mistaken for the feminine of neuter polidium, from Ancient Greek πολίδιον (polídion, “little pivot”), diminutive of πόλος (pólos, “pivot, hinge, axis”), from...

PULPED.d: Past tense of PULP: A soft, moist, shapeless mass or matter.
PULPED.e: From Middle English pulpe, from Latin pulpa.

PULPIT.d: A raised platform in a church, sometimes enclosed, where the minister or preacher stands when giving the sermon; also, the lectern on such a platform.
PULPIT.e: From Middle English pulpit, from Old French pulpite and Latin pulpitum (“platform”). Doublet of pulpitum.

PULQUE.d: A milk-colored, somewhat viscous Mexican alcoholic drink made from the fermented sap of certain agave plants.
PULQUE.e: From Mexican Spanish pulque, possibly from Nahuatl.

PULSAR.d: A rotating neutron star that emits radio pulses periodically.
PULSAR.e: Blend of pulsating + (radio) star, patterned after quasar. Coined by British astronomers Antony Hewish and Jocelyn Bell in 1968, and first used in print in The Daily Telegraph. By surface analysis, pulse + -ar

PUMICE.d: A light, porous type of pyroclastic igneous rock, formed during explosive volcanic eruptions when liquid lava is ejected into water or air as a froth containing masses of gas bubbles, which are frozen into the rock as the lava solidifies.
PUMICE.e: From Anglo-Norman and Old French pomis (“pumice stone”), from Latin pūmex (“pumice stone”). Doublet of pounce.

PUMMEL.d: To hit or strike heavily and repeatedly.

PUMPED.d: Past tense of PUMP: A device for moving or compressing a liquid or gas.
PUMPED.e:
From Middle English pumpe, possibly from Middle Dutch pompe (“pipe, water conduit”) or Middle Low German pumpe (“pump”), probably ultimately imitative.
Compare Dutch pompen, German pumpen, and Danish pompe; also Spanish bomba (“pump”).

PUNCHY.d: Having a punch; effective; forceful; spirited; vigorous.

PUNDIT.d: An expert in a particular field, especially as called upon to provide comment or opinion in the media; a commentator, a critic.
PUNDIT.e: Borrowed from Hindi पंडित (paṇḍit) / Urdu پنڈت (panḍit), from Sanskrit पण्डित (paṇḍita, “scholar, learned man, teacher, philosopher”). Doublet of pandit.

PUNIER.d: Comparative form of PUNY: Of inferior significance, size, or strength; ineffective, small, weak.
PUNIER.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *pós
Proto-Indo-European *-ti
Proto-Indo-European *pós-ti
Proto-Italic *posti
Latin poste
Latin post
Proto-Indo-European *íh₂
Latin ea
Latin posteā
Vulgar Latin *postius
Old French puis
Proto-Indo-European *ǵenh₁-
Proto-Indo-European *-tós
Proto...

PUNISH.d: To cause (a child, student, or someone else being looked after, or a suspect or criminal) to suffer for crime or misconduct, to administer disciplinary action, typically by an authority or a person in authority (for example: a parent, teacher, or police officer).
PUNISH.e: From Middle English punischen, from Anglo-Norman, Old French puniss-, stem of some of the conjugated forms of punir, from Latin puniō (“I inflict punishment upon”), from poena (“punishment, penalty”); see pain. Displaced Old English wītnian and (mostly, in this sense) wrecan.

PUNKAH.d: A fan, particularly a large fan made of leaf or cloth and hung from the ceiling, (historical) formerly often operated by a servant.
PUNKAH.e: Borrowed from Hindi पंखा (paṅkhā, “fan”), from Sanskrit पक्षक (pakṣaka), from पक्ष (pakṣa, “wing”).

PUNKIE.d: A small two-winged fly or midge of the family Ceratopogonidae, which bites and then sucks the blood of mammals; a biting midge or sandfly.
PUNKIE.e: From Jersey Dutch *punkje + English -ie (diminutive suffix). *Punkje is derived from Delaware Munsee *pónkwes + Dutch -je (diminutive suffix); and *pónkwes from Proto-Algonquian *penkw- (“ashes; dust”) (whence Unami punkw (“dust”); probably referring to the insects’ small size) +...

PUNNED.d: Past tense of PUN: To beat; strike with force; to ram; to pound, as in a mortar; reduce to powder, to pulverize.
PUNNED.e: From Middle English ponnen, ponen, punen, from Old English punian, pūnian (“to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush, grind”), from Proto-Germanic *punōną (“to break to pieces, pulverize”). See pound. As a kind of word play, from the notion of "beating" the words into place.

PUNNET.d: A small basket or receptacle for collecting and selling fruit, particularly strawberries.
PUNNET.e: Uncertain. First appears in the 1820s. Perhaps a diminutive of pun, a dialect variant of pound, the weight + -et. The suggestion that it is an eponym of Reginald Crundall Punnett (1875–1967), geneticist and grower of strawberries, is not chronologically possible. The suggestion i...

PUNTED.d: Past tense of PUNT: A pontoon; a narrow shallow boat propelled by a pole.
PUNTED.e: From Old English [Term?], from Latin pontō (“Gaulish flat-bottomed boat, pontoon”), from pons (“bridge”); readopted from Middle Low German punte (“ferry boat”) or Middle Dutch ponte (“ferry boat”) of the same origin.

PUPPED.d: Past tense of PUP: A young dog, wolf, fox, seal, bat or shark, or the young of certain other animals.

PUPPET.d: Any small model of a person or animal able to be moved by strings or rods, or in the form of a glove.
PUPPET.e: From Middle English popet, probably from, though attested earlier than, Middle French poupette, diminutive of poupée (cf. also Medieval Latin *pupata), ultimately derived from Latin pupa (“doll, puppet; girl”). The nominal form first appears c. 1531, and the verbal form c. 1635. ...

PURDAH.d: A curtain, especially one used in some Hindu or Muslim traditions to conceal women from the gaze of people, particularly men and strangers.
PURDAH.e: Borrowed from Hindustani پردہ / पर्दा (pardā), and its etymon Classical Persian پرده (pardah, “curtain; screen; (archaic) veil”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₂- (“flat”).

PUREED.d: Past tense of PURE: Free of flaws or imperfections; unsullied.
PUREED.e: From Middle English pure, pur, from Old French pur, from Latin pūrus (“clean, free from dirt or filth, unmixed, plain”), from Proto-Indo-European *pewH- (“to cleanse, purify”). Displaced native Middle English lutter (“pure, clear, sincere”) (from Old English hlūtor, hluttor), Mid...

PURELY.e: From Middle English purely, equivalent to pure + -ly.

PUREST.d: superlative form of pure: most pure

PURFLE.d: An ornamental border on clothing, furniture or a violin; beading, stringing.
PURFLE.e: From Old French porfiler, from Latin pro- + filum (“thread”). Doublet of profile.

PURIFY.d: To cleanse, or rid of impurities.
PURIFY.e: From Middle English purifien, purifyen, from Old French purifier, purifiier, from Latin pūrificō, pūrificāre, from pūrus (“pure; clean”).

PURINE.d: Any of a class of organic heterocyclic compounds, composed of fused pyrimidine and imidazole rings, that constitute one of the two groups of organic nitrogenous bases (the other being the pyrimidines) and are components of nucleic acids.

PURISM.d: An insistence on pure or unmixed forms.
PURISM.e: From French purisme. By surface analysis, pur(e) + -ism.

PURIST.e: Borrowed from French puriste. By surface analysis, pur(e) + -ist.

PURITY.d: The state or degree of being pure.
PURITY.e: From pure + -ity, from Old French purete, from Latin puritas.

PURLED.d: Past tense of PURL: A particular stitch in knitting in which the working yarn is pulled through an existing stitch from front to back.
PURLED.e: Unknown; apparently related to Scots and dialect pirl (“twist, ripple, whirl, spin”), and possibly to Older Scots pyrl ("thrust or poke at"). Compare Venetan pirlo, an embellishment where the woven threads are twisted together. May be unrelated to purfle, though the meanings are ...

PURLIN.d: A longitudinal structural member bridging two or more rafters of a roof.
PURLIN.e: Uncertain. Information on the etymology is scant at best. According to Websters it comes from 15th-century English. According to the Oxford Concise Dictionary, it is "Middle English, perhaps of French origin". Other sources reference Middle English or 15th-century English.

PURPLE.d: A colour between red and blue; violet, though often closer to magenta.
PURPLE.e: From Middle English purple, purpel, from Old English purpul (“purple”, adjective), taken from Old English purpure (“purple colour”, noun), from Latin purpura (“purple dye, shellfish”), from Ancient Greek πορφύρα (porphúra, “purple-fish”), perhaps of Semitic origin. Doublet of pur...

PURSUE.d: To follow urgently, originally with intent to capture or harm; to chase.
PURSUE.e: From Middle English pursuen, from Anglo-Norman pursure, poursuire etc., from Latin prōsequor (though influenced by persequor). Doublet of prosecute.

PURVEY.d: To prepare in advance (for or to do something); to plan, make provision.
PURVEY.e: From Middle English purveyen, from Anglo-Norman purveer, purveir et al., Old French porveeir, porveoir, from Latin prōvidēre (“to provide”). Doublet of provide; compare prudent.

PUSHED.d: Past tense of PUSH: To apply a force to (an object) such that it moves away from the person or thing applying the force.
PUSHED.e: From Middle English pushen, poshen, posson, borrowed from Middle French pousser (Modern French pousser) from Old French poulser, from Latin pulsare (“to beat, strike”), frequentative of pellere (past participle pulsus). Doublet of pulsate and pulse (verb). Partly displaced native...

PUSHES.d: Plural of PUSH: To apply a force to (an object) such that it moves away from the person or thing applying the force.
PUSHES.e: From Middle English pushen, poshen, posson, borrowed from Middle French pousser (Modern French pousser) from Old French poulser, from Latin pulsare (“to beat, strike”), frequentative of pellere (past participle pulsus). Doublet of pulsate and pulse (verb). Partly displaced native...

PUTING.d: Present participle of PUT: To physically place (something or someone somewhere).
PUTING.e: From Middle English putten, puten, poten, from Old English putian, *pūtian ("to push, put out"; attested by derivative putung (“pushing, impulse, instigation, urging”)) and potian (“to push, thrust, strike, butt, goad”), both from Proto-West Germanic *putōn, from Proto-Germanic *...

PUTLOG.d: One of the pieces of timber, or metal, on which the planks forming the platform of scaffolding are supported, one end resting on the ledger of the scaffold, and the other in a hole made in the wall (a putlog hole) for that purpose.

PUTRID.d: Rotting, rotten, being in a state of putrefaction.
PUTRID.e: From Middle English, borrowed from Old French putride or directly from Latin putridus (“rotten, decayed”), from putreō (“I am rotten or putrid”), from puter (“rotten, decaying, putrid”).

PUTSCH.d: A coup d'état; an illegal effort to forcibly overthrow the current government.
PUTSCH.e: Borrowed from German Putsch, from Alemannic German Putsch (“knock, thrust, blow”), of imitative origin.

PUTTED.d: simple past and past participle of putt

PUTTEE.d: A strip of cloth wound round the leg, worn for protection or support by hikers, soldiers etc.
PUTTEE.e: From Hindi पट्टी (paṭṭī, “bandage, strip of cloth”), from Sanskrit पट्टिका (paṭṭikā) of similar meaning.

PUTTER.d: To be active, but not excessively busy, at a task or a series of tasks.

PUZZLE.d: To cause (oneself or someone, or their mind, etc.) to feel confused or mystified because they cannot understand a complicated matter, a problem, etc.; to confuse, to mystify, to perplex.
PUZZLE.e:
The origin of the verb is uncertain.
* An early form of the word is pusle, which is similar to Old English puslian (“to pick out the best bits”). It is possible that the meaning of the word evolved from “to pick out the best bits”, to “to think long and carefully in bewilderment ...

PYGARG.d: An unidentified large animal with horns, possibly the addax, mentioned in the Bible (Deuteronomy 14:5) as one of the animals permitted for food.
PYGARG.e: From Latin pygargus from Ancient Greek πύγαργος (púgargos), a compound of Ancient Greek πῡγή (pūgḗ, “rump”) + ἀργός (argós, “white”).

PYKNIC.e: From Ancient Greek πυκνός (puknós, “thick”) + -ic, as a calque of German pyknisch.

PYRENE.d: A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon containing four fused benzene rings; first isolated from coal tar

PYRITE.d: The common mineral iron disulfide (FeS₂), of a pale brass-yellow color and brilliant metallic luster, crystallizing in the isometric system.
PYRITE.e: Recorded since 1555, from Old French pyrite (12th century), from Latin pȳritēs, from Ancient Greek πυρίτης λίθος (purítēs líthos, “stone of fire, flint”) (so called because it glitters), notably the first part: adjective πυρίτης (purítēs, “of or in fire”), from πῦρ (pûr, “fire”)....

PYROPE.d: A variety of garnet, of a poppy or blood-red color, frequently with a tinge of orange. It is used as a gemstone.
PYROPE.e: From Latin pyrōpus, from Ancient Greek πυρωπός (purōpós, “fiery-eyed, fire-colored”), from Ancient Greek πῦρ (pûr, “fire”) + ὤψ (ṓps, “eye”); compare French pyrope.

PYTHON.d: The earth-dragon of Delphi, represented as a serpent, killed by Apollo.
PYTHON.e:
From Ancient Greek Πύθων (Púthōn), from Πῡθώ (Pūthṓ), the early name of Delphi, from πύθω (púthō, “to rot, to decay”).
The programming language is named after Monty Python.

PYURIA.d: The presence of pus in the urine.

QUAERE.d: To ask or query; used imperatively to introduce a question or signify doubt.
QUAERE.e: From Latin quaere, second-person singular present active imperative of quaerō (“seek, look for; ask”).

QUAGGA.d: A southern-African subspecies of plains zebra, Equus quagga quagga, which went extinct in 1883. The upper parts of the animal were reddish brown, becoming paler behind and beneath, while the face, neck, and fore part of the body were marked by dark stripes.
QUAGGA.e: From Dutch quagga (whence also Afrikaans kwagga), from a Khoisan term, probably Haiǁom, Khoekhoe ǁkoaah, apparently of imitative origin.

QUAICH.d: A traditional shallow, two-handled cup of Scottish origin symbolizing friendship, originally used to toast the arrival or departure of a visitor.
QUAICH.e: From Scots quaich, from Scottish Gaelic cuach (“bowl, goblet”), from Old Irish cuäch (“goblet”), from Proto-Celtic *kaɸukos (“cup, bowl, vessel”).

QUAINT.e: From Middle English queynte, quoynte, from Anglo-Norman cointe, queinte and Old French cointe (“pretty, clever, knowing”), from Latin cognitus, past participle of cognōscō (“I know”).

QUANGO.d: An organization that, although financed by a government, acts independently of it.
QUANGO.e: From the initial letters (the first two letters for the first word) of quasi-autonomous non-governmental organization. Coined by American president of the Carnegie Foundation Alan Pifer in 1967.

QUARRY.d: A site for mining stone, such as limestone, or slate.
QUARRY.e: From Middle English quarere, from Medieval Latin quarreria (1266), literally a “place where stones are squared”, from Old French quarrière (compare modern French carrière), from Vulgar Latin *quadraria, from Latin quadrō (“I square”), itself from quadra (“a square”), from quattuo...

QUARTE.d: The fourth defensive position, with the sword hand held at chest height, and the tip of the sword at neck height, the palm of the hand facing upwards.

QUARTO.d: A size of paper (7.5"-10" x 10"-12.5" or 190-254 x 254-312 mm). Formed by folding and cutting one of several standard sizes of paper (15"-20" x 20"-25" or 381-508 x 508-635 mm) twice to form 4 leaves (eight sides).

QUARTZ.d: The most abundant mineral on the earth's surface, of chemical composition silicon dioxide, SiO₂. It occurs in a variety of forms, both crystalline and amorphous. Found in every environment.
QUARTZ.e: From German Quarz, from Middle High German (Central East German) quarz, twarc, from a West Slavic language [compare Polish twardy (“hard”), Czech tvrdý (“hard”)], from Proto-Slavic *tvьrdъ ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *twerH- (“to enclose, grab”).

QUASAR.d: An extragalactic object, starlike in appearance, that is among the most luminous and (putatively) the most distant objects in the universe.
QUASAR.e: Blend of quasi- + stellar, from quasi-stellar radio source. Coined by American astrophysicist Hong-Yee Chiu in 1964 in an article in Physics Today. By surface analysis, quasi- + -ar.

QUATRE.d: A card, die, or domino with four spots or pips.
QUATRE.e: Borrowed from French quatre. Doublet of cuatro and four.

QUAVER.e: From Middle English quaveren, frequentative form of quaven, cwavien (“to tremble”), equivalent to quave + -er. Cognate with Low German quabbeln (“to quiver”), German quabbeln, quappeln (“to quiver”). More at quave, quab, quiver.

QUAYED.d: Past tense of QUAY: A stone or concrete structure on navigable water used for loading and unloading vessels; a wharf.
QUAYED.e: The current spelling replaced the spelling key in the 1690s to emulate the spelling but (at least originally) not the pronunciation of the equivalent modern French quai. From Middle English kay, key, kaye, keye, from Old French kay, cail, from Gaulish *kagyum, cagiíun (“enclosure...

QUEASY.d: Experiencing or causing nausea or uneasiness, often characterized by an unsettled stomach.
QUEASY.e: From Middle English coysy, possibly from Old Norse kveisa (“boil”) ( > Norwegian kveise/kvise), perhaps influenced by Anglo-Norman queisier, from Old French coisier (“to wound, hurt, make uneasy”).

QUEENS.d: Plural of QUEEN: A female monarch.

QUENCH.d: To satisfy, especially a literal or figurative thirst.
QUENCH.e: From Middle English quenchen, from Old English cwenċan, from Proto-Germanic *kwankijaną.

QUICHE.d: A pie made primarily of egg and cream, perhaps mixed with chopped meat or vegetables, in a pastry crust.
QUICHE.e: Borrowed from French quiche, from Lorraine Rhine Franconian Küeche (“cake”), from Middle High German kuoche (German Kuchen, English kuchen), from Old High German kuocho, kuohho, from Proto-Germanic *kōkô (English cookie), from Proto-Indo-European *gog- (“ball-shaped object”), whe...

QUICKS.d: Plural of QUICK: Moving fast; done rapidly.

QUIETS.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of quiet

QUINCE.d: The pear-shaped fruit of a small tree of the rose family, Cydonia oblonga.
QUINCE.e: From Middle English quynce, coince, a variant of coins, coin (“quince”), from Old French cooing (modern coing), from Late Latin cotōneum, from Latin mālum cotōneum, a variant of mālum Cydonium (“Cydonian apple”), translating Ancient Greek μηλοκυδώνιον (mēlokudṓnion).

QUINOA.d: A goosefoot (Chenopodium quinoa) native to the Andes and cultivated for its edible seeds.
QUINOA.e: Borrowed from Spanish quinua, from Quechua kinwa.

QUINSY.d: A peritonsillar abscess; a painful pus-filled inflammation or abscess of the tonsils and surrounding tissues, usually a complication of tonsillitis, caused by bacterial infection and often accompanied by fever.
QUINSY.e: From Middle English quinesye, from Old French quinencie, from Medieval Latin quinancia, from Ancient Greek κυνάγχη (kunánkhē, “canine quinsy”), from κύων (kúōn, “dog”) + ἄγχω (ánkhō, “throttle”). Doublet of cynanche.

QUINTE.d: The fifth defensive position, with the sword hand held at waist height, and the tip of the sword at knee height.

QUIRKY.d: Given to quirks or idiosyncrasies; strange in a somewhat silly, awkward manner, potentially cute.

QUITCH.e: From Middle English quicchen, quytchen, quecchen, from Old English cweċċan (“to shake, swing, move, vibrate, shake off, give up”), from Proto-West Germanic *kwakkjan, from Proto-Germanic *kwakjaną (“to shake, swing”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷog- (“to shake, swing”). Related t...

QUIVER.d: A container for arrows, crossbow bolts or darts, such as those fired from a bow, crossbow or blowgun.
QUIVER.e: From Middle English quiver, from Anglo-Norman quivre, from Old Dutch cocare (source of Dutch koker, and cognate to Old English cocer (“quiver, case”)), from Proto-West Germanic *kokar (“container”), said to be from Hunnic, possibly from Proto-Mongolic *kökexür (“leather vessel fo...

QUIZZY.e: From quiz + -y. Sense 2 possibly influenced by English inquisitive.

QUORUM.d: The minimum number of members required for a group to officially conduct business and to cast votes, often but not necessarily a majority or supermajority.
QUORUM.e: From Latin quōrum, genitive plural form of quī (“who, which”), used as standard wording in written commissions.

QUOTED.d: Past tense of QUOTE: To repeat someone's words; a quotation.

QUOTES.d: Plural of QUOTE: To repeat someone's words; a quotation.

RABBET.d: A longitudinal channel, groove, or recess cut out of the edge or face of a plank of wood or other material; especially, one intended to fit another member to form a joint.
RABBET.e:
From Middle English rabeten, from Old French raboter, rabouter (“to thrust back”, verb), from Old French re- + boter, bouter.
The noun is from Middle English rabet, from Old French rabot, from the verb.

RABBIT.d: A mammal of most genera of the family Leporidae, with long ears, long hind legs and a short, fluffy tail.
RABBIT.e: From Middle English rabet, rabette, from Anglo-Latin rabettus, from dialectal Old French rabotte, probably a diminutive of Middle Dutch or West Flemish robbe (“rabbit, seal”), of uncertain origin; possibly some imitative verb, maybe robben, rubben (“to rub”) is used here to allud...

RABBLE.d: To speak in a confused manner; talk incoherently; utter nonsense
RABBLE.e: First attested since 1300s, from Middle English rablen (“to ramble; rave; speak in a confused manner”), cognate with Middle Dutch rabbelen (“to talk; chatter; trifle”), Low German rabbeln, robbeln (“to chatter; prattle”).

RACEME.d: An indeterminate inflorescence in which the flowers are arranged along a single central axis.
RACEME.e: Borrowed from Latin racēmus (“cluster, bunch”). Doublet of raisin.

RACIAL.d: Of or relating to a race (or a people).

RACIER.d: Comparative form of RACY: Mildly risqué.
RACIER.e: From race (“having a characteristic taste (of wines, fruits, etc.)”) + -y.

RACING.d: Present participle of RACE: A contest between people, animals, vehicles, etc. where the goal is to be the first to reach some objective.
RACING.e: From Middle English race, partially from Old English rǣs (“a race, swift or violent running, rush, onset”), from Proto-West Germanic *rās; and partially from Old Norse rás (“a running, race”); both from Proto-Germanic *rēsō (“a course”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reh₁s- (“to fl...

RACISM.d: The belief that there are distinct human races with inherent differences which determine their abilities, and generally that some are superior and others inferior.
RACISM.e: Borrowed from French racisme, equivalent to race + -ism.

RACKED.d: Past tense of RACK: A series of one or more shelves, stacked one above the other.
RACKED.e: From Middle English rakke, rekke, from Middle Dutch rac, recke, rec (Dutch rek), see rekken.

RACKET.d: An implement with a handle connected to a round frame strung with wire, sinew, or plastic cords, and used to hit a ball, such as in tennis or a shuttlecock in badminton.
RACKET.e:
From Middle English raket, of uncertain origin.
Possibly cognate with Middle French rachette, requette (“palm of the hand”). From Arabic رَاحَةْ اَلْيَد (rāḥat al-yad, “palm of the hand”).
Alternatively, the term might be derived from Dutch raketsen instead, from Middle French ra...

RADDED.d: Past tense of RAD: Clipping of radical (“excellent”).

RADDLE.e: From a variation of reddle, ruddle. Related to red.

RADIAL.d: Arranged like rays that radiate from, or converge to, a common centre.
RADIAL.e: From Medieval Latin radiālis (“radial”), from Latin radius. By surface analysis, radius + -al.

RADIAN.d: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of plane angle: the angle subtended at the centre of a circle by an arc of its circumference equal in length to the radius of the circle.

RADIOS.d: Plural of RADIO: The transmission of programs by electromagnetic waves.

RADISH.d: A plant of the Brassicaceae family, Raphanus sativus or Raphanus raphanistrum subsp. sativus, having an edible root.
RADISH.e:
PIE word
 *wréh₂ds
From Middle English radiche, from Old English rǣdiċ, from Proto-West Germanic *rādik, borrowed from Latin rādīcem (“root of a plant; radish”); later influenced by Anglo-Norman radich and Middle French radice, borrowed from Italian radice, from the same Latin so...

RADIUM.d: The chemical element (symbol Ra) with an atomic number of 88. It is a soft, shiny and silvery radioactive alkaline earth metal.
RADIUM.e: Borrowed from French radium, from rad(ioactif) (“radioactive”) + -ium (suffix used to form the names of metallic elements).

RADIUS.d: The long bone in the forearm, on the side of the thumb.
RADIUS.e: Borrowed from Latin radius (“ray”). Doublet of ray.

RADOME.e: Blend of radar + dome, originating from the 1940s.

RADULA.d: The rasping tongue of snails and all other mollusks except bivalves.

RAFFIA.d: A fibrous material used for tying plants, originating from the leaves of raffia palm trees (genus Raphia).

RAFFLE.d: A drawing, often held as a fundraiser, in which tickets or chances are sold to win a prize.
RAFFLE.e: From Middle English rafle, from Old French rafle, raffle (“dice game", also "plundering”), from rafler (“to snatch, seize, carry off”), from Frankish *raffolōn, from Proto-Germanic *hrapōną, *hrēpōną (“to scratch, touch, pluck out, snatch”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kreb(h)-,...

RAFTED.d: Past tense of RAFT: A flat-bottomed craft able to float and drift on water, used for transport or as a waterborne platform.
RAFTED.e: Late Middle English, of North Germanic origin, from West Old Norse raptr, from Proto-Germanic *raf-tra-, from Proto-Indo-European *rap-tro-, from *rep- (“stake, beam”). See also Norwegian raft (“beam, rafter”), Danish raft (“thin pole”). Compare also Albanian trap (“raft, ferry”)...

RAGBAG.d: A bag of rags and scraps.

RAGGED.d: In tatters, having the texture broken.
RAGGED.e: From Middle English ragged, from North Germanic. Compare with Old Norse rǫgvaðr (“tufted”) and Norwegian ragget (“shaggy”).

RAGGER.d: Comparative form of RAG: Tattered clothes (clothing).
RAGGER.e: From Middle English ragge, from Old English ragg (suggested by derivative raggiġ (“shaggy; bristly; ragged”)), from Old Norse rǫgg (“tuft; shagginess”), from Proto-Germanic *rawwa-, probably related to *rūhaz. Cognate with Swedish ragg. Related to rug.

RAGING.d: Present participle of RAGE: Violent uncontrolled anger.
RAGING.e:
From Middle English rage, from Anglo-Norman rage, from Late Latin rabia, from Classical Latin rabiēs (“anger, fury”). Doublet of rabies.
Displaced native Middle English wode, from Old English wōd ("madness, fury, rage"; compare Modern dialectal English wood (“mad, insane, furious...

RAGLAN.d: Being or having a kind of sleeve that continues in one piece up to the neck of a garment, without a shoulder seam.
RAGLAN.e: Named after Lord Raglan (1788–1855), a British commander in the Crimean War.

RAGOUT.d: a stew of meat and vegetables mixed together
RAGOUT.e: Borrowed from French ragoût. Compare ragù of the same origin, borrowed from Italian.

RAGTAG.d: Unkempt, shabby, or in a state of disrepair.
RAGTAG.e: From earlier tag-rag and tag and rag, from rag + tag.

RAIDED.d: Past tense of RAID: A quick hostile or predatory incursion or invasion in a battle.
RAIDED.e: From Scots raid, from Northern Middle English rade, from Old English rād (“a riding, an expedition on horseback, road”), whence also the inherited English road (“way, street”). The earlier senses of “a riding, expedition, raid” fell into disuse in Early Modern English, but were r...

RAILED.d: Past tense of RAIL: A horizontal bar extending between supports and used for support or as a barrier; a railing.
RAILED.e: From Middle English rail, rayl, *reȝel, *reȝol (found in reȝolsticke (“a ruler”)), partly from Old English regol (“a ruler, straight bar”) and partly from Old French reille; both from Latin regula (“rule, bar”), from regō (“to rule, to guide, to govern”); see regular. Doublet of ...

RAINED.d: Past tense of RAIN: Condensed water falling from a cloud.
RAINED.e:
From Middle English reyn, rein, from Old English reġn, from Proto-West Germanic *regn, from Proto-Germanic *regną, of uncertain origin. Possibly from pre-Germanic *Hréǵ-no-, from Proto-Indo-European *Hreǵ- (“to flow”), although the consonant reflexes don't match.
Cognates
Cognate...

RAISED.d: Past tense of RAISE: To lift up; to increase.

RAISIN.e: From Middle English raysyn, borrowed from Anglo-Norman reysin (“grape, raisin”), from Late Latin racīmus, from Latin racēmus. Possibly a distant cognate of Persian رز (raz, “vine”). Doublet of raceme.

RAKING.d: Present participle of RAKE: A garden tool with a row of pointed teeth fixed to a long handle, used for collecting debris, grass, etc., for flattening the ground, or for loosening soil; also, a similar wheel-mounted tool drawn by a horse or a tractor.
RAKING.e:
From Middle English rake [and other forms], from Old English raca, racu, ræce (“tool with a row of pointed teeth, rake”), from Proto-Germanic *rakō, *rekô (“tool with a row of pointed teeth, rake”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃reǵ- (“to straighten, right oneself”).
Cognates
The E...

RAKISH.d: Dashingly, carelessly, or sportingly unconventional or stylish; jaunty; characterized by a devil-may-care unconventionality; having a somewhat disreputable quality or appearance.
RAKISH.e: From rake (“man habituated to immoral conduct”) + -ish.

RAMBLE.d: A leisurely stroll; a recreational walk in the countryside.
RAMBLE.e: An altered form (with dissimilation of mm to mb) of dialectal rammle, from Middle English *ramlen, *ramelen, frequentative of Middle English ramen (“to roam, ramble”); compare Swedish ramla (“to stumble; fall; make a noise; rumble”), Danish ramle (“to stumble; collapse; thunder; ...

RAMIFY.d: To divide into branches or subdivisions.
RAMIFY.e: Borrowed from Middle French ramifier, from Medieval Latin ramificō (“to branch, ramify”), from Latin rāmus (“a branch”) + -ficō (causative suffix).

RAMJET.d: A jet engine in which forward motion forces air into an inlet, compressing it (as opposed to having a pump type device compressing the air for combustion with fuel), and where combustion is subsonic.

RAMMED.d: Past tense of RAM: Acronym of random-access memory.

RAMMER.d: A device used to ram; a ramrod.

RAMPED.d: Past tense of RAMP: An inclined surface that connects two levels; an incline.
RAMPED.e: From French rampe, from Middle French rampe, deverbal of ramper, from Old French ramper (“to crawl, climb, scale up”), from Frankish *hrampōn (“to contract oneself, wrinkle, rumple, crumple, curve”), from Proto-Germanic *hrimpaną (“to shrivel, shrink”). Cognate with German Rampf ...

RAMROD.d: Device used with muzzleloaders to push the projectile up against the propellant.

RANCID.e: Learned borrowing from Latin rancidus (“stinking, rank, rancid, offensive”).

RANDAN.e: From a conflation of rand (“to storm, rave”) and obsolete random (“impetuosity, force”).

RANDOM.d: A roving motion; course without definite direction; lack of rule or method; chance.
RANDOM.e: From earlier randon, from Middle English randoun, raundon, from Old French randon, from randir (“to run, gallop”) (whence French randonnée (“long walk, hike”)), from Frankish *randiju (“a run, race”) or Old Norse rend (“a run, race”), both from Proto-Germanic *randijō, from *rinn...

RANGED.d: Past tense of RANGE: The extent; a variety.

RANGES.d: Plural of RANGE: The extent; a variety.

RANKED.d: That has been arranged or organized in ranks or by rank.

RANKLE.d: To cause irritation, bitterness or acrimony.
RANKLE.e: From Middle English ranklen, ranclen, from Old French rancler, räoncler, draoncler (“to ulcerate, to form a boil”), from Old French draoncle (“a boil”), from Latin dracunculus (“little serpent”), diminutive of Latin dracō (“serpent, dragon”).

RANSOM.d: Money paid for the freeing of a hostage.
RANSOM.e: From the Middle English ransoun, from the Old French raençon, from stem of Latin redemptio. Entered English ca. the 13th century. Doublet of redemption.

RANTED.d: Past tense of RANT: To speak or shout at length in uncontrollable anger.
RANTED.e: From Dutch ranten, randen (“to talk nonsense, rave”), from Middle Dutch ranten (“to rant, babble, goof around”), of uncertain origin; but apparently related to Middle High German ranzen (“to dance, jump around, frolic”), German ranzen (“to be ardent, be in heat, copulate, mate, r...

RAPIDS.e: From Latin rapidus, from rapere (to seize).

RAPIER.d: A slender, straight, sharply pointed sword (double-edged, single-edged or edgeless), designed predominantly for thrusting; used during the Renaissance period of Europe for civilian duelling
RAPIER.e: Borrowed from Middle French rapiere, from Middle French (espee) rapiere, from Old French rapiere, raspiere, from Spanish raspadera (“poker; raker; scraper”), from Spanish raspar (“to scrape”), of Germanic origin. More at rasp.

RAPINE.d: The seizure of someone's property by force; pillage; plunder.
RAPINE.e: From Middle English rapyne, from Old French rapine, from Latin rapīna, from rapiō. Doublet of rape and ravine.

RAPING.d: Present participle of RAPE: The act of forcing sex upon another person without their consent or against their will; originally coitus forced by a man on a woman, but now generally any sex act forced by any person upon another person, regardless of gender; by extension, any non-consensual sex act forced on, perpetrated by, or forced to penetrate any being.
RAPING.e: From Middle English rapen, rappen (“to abduct; ravish; seduce; rape; seize; snatch; carry off; transport”), probably from Latin rapiō (verb), possibly through or influenced by Anglo-Norman rap, rape (noun) (compare also ravish). But compare Swedish rappa (“to snatch, seize, carry...

RAPPED.d: Past tense of RAP: A sharp blow with something hard.
RAPPED.e: From Middle English rap, rappe, of North Germanic origin, related to Norwegian rapp (“a blow, strike, lash”), Swedish rapp (“a blow, lash, crack”), Danish rap (“a tap, smart, blow”). Compare Old English hreppan (“to touch, treat”). More at rape.

RAPPEE.d: A dark, coarse, strongly flavoured snuff.
RAPPEE.e: From French (tabac) râpé (“grated (tobacco)”), past participle of râper (“to grate”), from Old French rasper "to scrape"; of Germanic origin.

RAPPEL.d: Descending by means of a rope, abseiling.
RAPPEL.e: Borrowed from French rappeler (“to pull through (a rope)”).

RAPPER.d: Comparative form of RAP: A sharp blow with something hard.
RAPPER.e: From Middle English rap, rappe, of North Germanic origin, related to Norwegian rapp (“a blow, strike, lash”), Swedish rapp (“a blow, lash, crack”), Danish rap (“a tap, smart, blow”). Compare Old English hreppan (“to touch, treat”). More at rape.

RAPTOR.e: From Middle English raptour, from Latin raptor (“kidnapper, thief”).

RAREFY.d: To make rare, thin, porous, or less dense.
RAREFY.e: From Middle English rarefien, from Old French rarefier (French raréfier), from Latin rarefacere (“make rare”). By surface analysis, rare + -fy.

RARING.d: Present participle of RARE: Very uncommon; scarce.
RARING.e: From Middle English rare, from Old French rare, rere (“rare, uncommon”), from Latin rārus (“loose, spaced apart, thin, infrequent”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reh₁- (“friable, thin”). Replaced native Middle English gesen (“rare, scarce”) (from Old English gǣsne), Middle English...

RARITY.d: A measure of the scarcity of an object.
RARITY.e: From rare + -ity, borrowed from Middle French rarité, from Latin rāritās; compare French rareté. See also rare.

RASCAL.d: A dishonest person; a rogue, a scoundrel, a trickster.
RASCAL.e: Recorded since c.1330, as Middle English rascaile (“people of the lowest class, rabble of an army”), derived from 12th century Old French rascaille (“outcast, rabble”) (modern French racaille), perhaps from rasque (“mud, filth, scab, dregs”), from Vulgar Latin *rasicō (“to scrape...

RASHES.d: Plural of RASH: Acting too quickly without considering the consequences and risks; not careful; hasty.
RASHES.e: The adjective is derived from Middle English rash, rasch (“hasty, headstrong, rash”) [and other forms], probably from Old English *ræsċ (“rash”) (found in derivatives such as ræsċan (“to move rapidly; to flicker; to flash; to glitter; to quiver”), ræsċettan (“to crackle, sparkle”...

RASING.d: Present participle of RASE: To be extremely angry; to rage; specifically, of a dog or wolf: to snarl in rage.
RASING.e: From Late Middle English rasen, rasyn (“to rage; to enrage (?)”), probably from Middle Dutch râsen, râzen (“to be extremely angry, rage; to be mad, rave; to talk nonsense; of a dog: to be rabid”), from Old Dutch *rāson (modern Dutch razen), from Proto-West Germanic *rāsōn (“to ru...

RASPED.d: Past tense of RASP: A coarse file or filelike tool, on which the cutting prominences are distinct points raised by the oblique stroke of a sharp punch, instead of lines raised by a chisel, as on the true file.
RASPED.e:
From Middle English raspen, from Old French rasper, from Frankish *hraspōn, from Proto-Germanic *hraspōną, related to Proto-Germanic *hrespaną (“to tear”). Compare Old High German raspōn (“to gather, rake”), Old English ġehrespan (“to tear”).
The noun is from Middle French raspe.

RASTER.d: A scanning pattern of parallel lines that form the display of an image projected on a cathode-ray tube of a television set or display screen.
RASTER.e: From German Raster, from Latin rāster, from rāstrum (“rake”, noun), from rādō (“to scrape”, verb).

RATIFY.d: To give formal consent to; make officially valid, sign off on.
RATIFY.e: From Old French ratifier, from Medieval Latin ratifico, from Latin ratus (“reckoned”).

RATING.d: present participle and gerund of rate

RATION.d: A portion of some limited resource, especially food, allocated to a person or group.
RATION.e: From French ration. Doublet of reason and ratio.

RATIOS.d: Plural of RATIO: A quantitative relation between two amounts.

RATITE.d: Pertaining to running, flightless birds with no keels on their sternums (as opposed to carinate).
RATITE.e: From Latin ratis (“raft”) + -ite; ratites (unlike other birds) lack a keel on their sternum, and rafts are vessels that lack keels.

RATOON.d: A shoot sprouting from the root of a cropped plant, especially sugar cane.

RATTAN.d: Any of several species of climbing palm of the genus Calamus.

RATTED.d: Past tense of RAT: A medium-sized rodent belonging to the genus Rattus.
RATTED.e: From Middle English ratte, rat, rotte, from Old English rætt, from Proto-West Germanic *ratt, from Proto-Germanic *rattaz, *rattō (compare West Frisian rôt, Dutch rat), of uncertain origin, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *Hreh₃d- (“to scrape, scratch, gnaw”). However, the rat ...

RATTER.d: Comparative form of RAT: A medium-sized rodent belonging to the genus Rattus.
RATTER.e: From Middle English ratte, rat, rotte, from Old English rætt, from Proto-West Germanic *ratt, from Proto-Germanic *rattaz, *rattō (compare West Frisian rôt, Dutch rat), of uncertain origin, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *Hreh₃d- (“to scrape, scratch, gnaw”). However, the rat ...

RATTLE.d: To create a rattling sound by shaking or striking.
RATTLE.e: From Middle English ratelen, of uncertain origin; perhaps borrowed from Middle Dutch ratelen or of native origin related to Old English hratele, hrætele (“a plant known for its rustling or rattling sound”), ultimately imitative. The noun (c. 1500) is from the verb.

RAUNCH.d: Low class condition or content; inferiority; inadequacy.

RAVAGE.d: To devastate, destroy or lay waste to something.
RAVAGE.e: From French ravage (“ravage, havoc, spoil”), from ravir (“to bear away suddenly”), from Latin rapere (“to snatch, seize”), akin to Ancient Greek ἁρπάζω (harpázō, “to seize”).

RAVINE.d: A deep narrow valley or gorge in the earth's surface worn by running water.
RAVINE.e: Borrowed from French ravin (“a gully”), from Old French raviner (“to pillage, sweep down, cascade”), from ravine (“robbery, rapine; violent rush of water, waterfall, avalanche; impetuosity, spirit”), from Latin rapīna (cf. rapine).

RAVING.d: Present participle of RAVE: An enthusiastic review (such as of a play).
RAVING.e: From Middle English raven (“to rave; talk like a madman”), from Old French raver, variant of resver, of uncertain origin. Compare rave below, and rove.

RAVISH.d: To seize and carry away by violence; to snatch by force.
RAVISH.e: From Middle English ravyschen, from Anglo-Norman, from Old French ravis-, present participle stem of ravir (“to seize; to take away hastily”), from Vulgar Latin *rapire, from Latin rapere. See also rape.

RAWING.d: Present participle of RAW: (of food) Not cooked.
RAWING.e:
From Middle English rawe, raw, rau, from Old English hrēaw (“raw, uncooked”), from Proto-West Germanic *hrau, from Proto-Germanic *hrawaz, *hrēwaz (“raw”), from Proto-Indo-European *krewh₂- (“raw meat, fresh blood”).
Cognate with Scots raw (“raw”), Dutch rauw (“raw”), German roh ...

RAYING.d: Present participle of RAY: A beam of light or radiation.
RAYING.e: Via Middle English, borrowed from Old French rai, from Latin radius (“staff, stake, spoke”). Doublet of radius.

RAZEED.d: Past tense of RAZE: To level or tear down (a building, a town, etc.) to the ground; to demolish.
RAZEED.e: The verb is derived from Middle English rasen, racen, rase (“to scrape; to shave; to erase; to pull; to strip off; to pluck or tear out; to root out (a tree, etc.); to pull away, snatch; to pull down; to knock down; to rend, tear apart; to pick clean, strip; to cleave, slice; to ...

RAZING.d: Present participle of RAZE: To level or tear down (a building, a town, etc.) to the ground; to demolish.
RAZING.e: The verb is derived from Middle English rasen, racen, rase (“to scrape; to shave; to erase; to pull; to strip off; to pluck or tear out; to root out (a tree, etc.); to pull away, snatch; to pull down; to knock down; to rend, tear apart; to pick clean, strip; to cleave, slice; to ...

RAZZIA.d: A plundering and destructive incursion; a foray; a raid.
RAZZIA.e: Borrowed from French razzia, from Algerian Arabic غَزِيَّة (ḡaziya), equalling Arabic غَزْوَة (ḡazwa, “raid, military campaign”). Doublet of ghazwa.

REACTS.d: Plural of REACT: To respond to something.

READER.e: From Middle English reder, redar, redere, redare, from Old English rēdere, rǣdere (“a reader; scholar; diviner”), from Proto-West Germanic *rādāri, equivalent to read + -er. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Räider (“advisor”), Dutch rader (“advisor”), German Rater (“advisor”).

REALMS.d: Plural of REALM: A kingdom; a field of activity.

REAMED.d: Past tense of REAM: Cream; also, the creamlike froth on ale or other liquor; froth or foam in general.
REAMED.e:
From Middle English reme, rem, from Old English rēam (“cream”), from Proto-West Germanic *raum, from Proto-Germanic *raumaz (“cream”), from Proto-Indo-European *réwgʰmn̥ (“to sour [milk]”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Room (“cream”), West Frisian rjemme (“cream”), Dutch room (...

REAPED.d: Past tense of REAP: To cut (for example a grain) with a sickle, scythe, or reaping machine
REAPED.e: From Middle English repen, from Old English rēopan, rēpan, variants of Old English rīpan (“to reap”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīpan, from Proto-Germanic *rīpaną (compare West Frisian repe, Norwegian ripa (“to score, scratch”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyb- (“to snatch”).

REARED.d: Past tense of REAR: To bring up to maturity, as offspring; to educate; to instruct; to foster.
REARED.e: From Middle English reren (“to raise”), from Old English rǣran (“to raise, set upright, promote, exalt, begin, create, give rise to, excite, rouse, arouse, stir up”), from Proto-West Germanic *raiʀijan, from Proto-Germanic *raizijaną, *raisijaną (“to cause to rise, raise”), from ...

REASON.e: From Middle English resoun, reson, from Anglo-Norman raisun (Old French raison), from Latin ratiō, from ratus, past participle of reor (“reckon”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂reh₁- (“to think”), reanalysed root of *h₂er- (“to put together”). Displaced native Middle Eng...

REBASE.d: To replace the base of a denture.

REBATE.d: A deduction from an amount that is paid; an abatement.
REBATE.e: From Old French rabatre < batre. See also abate.

REBORE.d: To bore through an existing hole, generally to correct its shape, or to enlarge.

REBUFF.e: From obsolete French rebuffer, from Middle French rebuffer (compare French rebiffer (“to rise up, revolt”)), from Italian ribuffare.

REBUKE.e: From Middle English rebuken, from Anglo-Norman rebuker (“to beat back, repel”), from re- + Old French *buker, buchier, buschier (“to strike, hack down, chop”), from busche (“wood”), from Vulgar Latin *busca (“wood, grove”), from Frankish *busk (“grove”), from Proto-Germanic *busk...

RECALL.d: To withdraw, retract (one's words etc.); to revoke (an order).
RECALL.e: From re- + call, probably modelled on Latin revocāre, French rappeler, English withcall.

RECANT.d: To withdraw or repudiate a statement or opinion formerly expressed, especially formally and publicly.
RECANT.e: First attested in 1535, from Latin recantare (“to sing back, reecho, sing again, repeat in singing, recant, recall, revoke, charm back or away”), from re- (“back”) + canto (“to chant, to sing”), frequentative of cano.

RECENT.d: Having happened a short while ago.

RECESS.d: A depressed, hollow, or indented space; also, a hole or opening.
RECESS.e: The noun is borrowed from Latin recessus (“act of going back, departure, receding, retiring; (figuratively) retreat, withdrawal; (metonymically) distant, secluded, or secret spot, corner, nook, retreat; recessed part, indentation”) (also Late Latin recessus (“decree or resolution...

RECIPE.d: A formula for preparing or using a medicine; a prescription; also, a medicine prepared from such instructions.
RECIPE.e: Borrowed from Middle French récipé, from Latin recipe, second person singular imperative of Latin recipiō (“receive”). Doublet of recept and receipt.

RECITE.d: To repeat aloud (some passage, poem or other text previously memorized, or in front of one's eyes), often before an audience.
RECITE.e: From Middle English reciten, from Old French reciter, from Latin recitō.

RECKED.d: Past tense of RECK: To take account of (someone or something); to care for; to consider, to heed, to regard.
RECKED.e: From Middle English recken, rekken, reken, from Old Norse rœkja (compare Old English rēċċan, rēċan (“to care, reck, take care of, be interested in, care for, desire”); whence English retch), from Proto-Germanic *rōkijaną (“to care, take care”), from Proto-Indo-European *rēǵ-, *rē...

RECKON.d: To count; to enumerate; to number; also, to compute; to calculate.
RECKON.e: From Middle English rekenen, from Old English recenian (“to pay; arrange, dispose, reckon”) and ġerecenian (“to explain, recount, relate”); both from Proto-West Germanic *rekanōn (“to count, explain”), from Proto-West Germanic *rekan (“swift, ready, prompt”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

RECOIL.d: A starting or falling back; a rebound; a shrinking.
RECOIL.e: From Old French reculer. Further from Latin re- + cūlus.

RECOIN.d: To coin (money, or an expression) again.

RECORD.d: An item of information put into a temporary or permanent physical medium.
RECORD.e: From Middle English recorde, borrowed from Old French record, from recorder. See record (verb).

RECOUP.d: To make back (an investment or similar).

RECTAL.d: Of, via or related to the rectum.

RECTOR.d: In the Anglican Church, a cleric in charge of a parish and who owns the tithes of it.
RECTOR.e: Inherited from Middle English rectour, rector, from Old French rector, rectour and Latin rēctor.

RECTUM.d: The terminal part of the large intestine through which feces pass after exiting the colon, but before leaving the body through the anus or cloaca.
RECTUM.e: Borrowed from New Latin rectum, clipping of Latin rectum intestinum (literally “the straight intestine”), rectum, neuter of rectus (“straight”). See right.

RECTUS.d: Any of several straight muscles in various parts of the body, as of the abdomen, thigh, eye etc.
RECTUS.e: Borrowed from Latin rēctus (“straight, upright”), clipping of mūsculus rēctus (“straight muscle”).

RECURS.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of recur

REDACT.d: To censor, to black out or remove parts of a document while leaving the remainder.
REDACT.e: From Old French redacter, from Latin redactus, perfect passive participle of redigō (“drive, lead, collect, reduce”), from re- (“back”) + agō (“put in motion, drive”). Piecewise doublet of react.

REDATE.d: To change the date assigned to (something); to date in a new way

REDBUD.d: Any of several small trees, of the genus Cercis, having purple-pink flowers that appear before the leaves; the Judas tree.

REDCAP.d: A member of the Royal Military Police a unit in the British army.
REDCAP.e:
From red + cap.
In sense of "porter", 1890s US; compare contemporary Japanese 赤帽 (akabō), Chinese 小紅帽 /小红帽 (Xiǎo Hóng Mào). On Labor Day, 1890, John Williams, an African-American railway porter, tied a red ribbon to his black uniform cap to stand out from the crowd at Grand Centr...

REDDED.d: Past tense of RED: The colour of the setting sun, blood, and strawberries; the colour which is evoked by the longest visible wavelengths (between about 625–740 nm), and a primary additive colour.
REDDED.e:
From Middle English red, from Old English rēad, from Proto-West Germanic *raud, from Proto-Germanic *raudaz from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rowdʰós, from the root *h₁rewdʰ-.
Cognates
See also West Frisian read, Low German root, rood, rot, rod, Dutch rood, German rot, Danish and Norwe...

REDDER.d: Comparative form of RED: The colour of the setting sun, blood, and strawberries; the colour which is evoked by the longest visible wavelengths (between about 625–740 nm), and a primary additive colour.
REDDER.e:
From Middle English red, from Old English rēad, from Proto-West Germanic *raud, from Proto-Germanic *raudaz from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rowdʰós, from the root *h₁rewdʰ-.
Cognates
See also West Frisian read, Low German root, rood, rot, rod, Dutch rood, German rot, Danish and Norwe...

REDDLE.d: Red ochre, historically used to mark sheep
REDDLE.e: Apparently a variation of ruddle, though not certainly.

REDEEM.d: To recover ownership of something by buying it back.
REDEEM.e: From Middle English redemen, modified from Old French redimer, from Latin redimō (“release; obviate; atone for”), itself from red- (“back; again”) + emō (“buy; gain, take, procure”).

REDUCE.d: To bring down the size, quantity, quality, value or intensity of something; to diminish, to lower.
REDUCE.e: From Middle English reducen, from Old French reduire, from Latin redūcō (“reduce”); from re- (“back”) + dūcō (“lead”). See duke, and compare with redoubt.
