REEDED.d: Past tense of REED: Any of various types of tall stiff perennial grass-like plants growing together in groups near water.
REEDED.e:
From Middle English red, reed, from Old English hrēod, from Proto-West Germanic *hreud, of uncertain origin.
Akin to Saterland Frisian Rait (“reed”), West Frisian reid (“reed”), Dutch riet (“reed”), German Ried (“reed”). No cognates in North Germanic languages, but the existence ...

REEFED.d: Past tense of REEF: A chain or range of rocks, sand, or coral lying at or near the surface of the water.
REEFED.e: From earlier riff, from Middle English rif, from Old Norse rif (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Germanic *ribją (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rebʰ- (“arch, ceiling, cover”). Dutch rif (“reef”), Low German riff, reff (“reef”), German Riff (“reef, ledge”) are also borrowed fr...

REEKED.d: Past tense of REEK: A strong unpleasant smell.
REEKED.e:
From Middle English rek, reke (“smoke”), from Old English rēc, from Proto-West Germanic *rauki, from Proto-Germanic *raukiz, from Proto-Indo-European *rowgi-.
See also West Frisian reek, riik, Dutch rook, Low German Röök, German Rauch, Danish røg, Norwegian Bokmål røyk; also Lith...

REELED.d: Past tense of REEL: A shaky or unsteady gait.
REELED.e: From Middle English reel, reele, from Old English rēol, hrēol, from Proto-West Germanic *hrehul, from Proto-Germanic *hrehulaz, *hrahilaz, from Proto-Indo-European *krek- (“to weave, beat”). Cognate with Icelandic ræl, hræll.

REEVES.d: Plural of REEF: A chain or range of rocks, sand, or coral lying at or near the surface of the water.
REEVES.e: From earlier riff, from Middle English rif, from Old Norse rif (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Germanic *ribją (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rebʰ- (“arch, ceiling, cover”). Dutch rif (“reef”), Low German riff, reff (“reef”), German Riff (“reef, ledge”) are also borrowed fr...

REFFED.d: Past tense of REF: Clipping of referee.

REFILL.d: That which serves to refill or replace something.

REFINE.d: To purify; reduce to a fine, unmixed, or pure state; to free from impurities.

REFLEX.d: An automatic response to a simple stimulus which does not require mental processing.
REFLEX.e: From Late Latin reflexus, past participle of reflectere (“to bend back”), equivalent to re- + flex. Photography sense is from noun sense meaning “reflection”. Compare English reflect.

REFORM.d: The change of something that is defective, broken, inefficient or otherwise negative, in order to correct or improve it
REFORM.e: From Middle English reformen, from Old French reformer, from Latin reformo, reformare. As a noun since 1660s, from French réforme.

REFUGE.d: A state of safety, protection or shelter.
REFUGE.e: From Middle English refuge, from Old French refuge, from Latin refugium, from re- + fugiō (“flee”). Doublet of refugium.

REFUND.e: From Middle English refunden, refounden, from Old French refondre, refonder, refunder (“to restore; pay back”), from Latin refundere; prefix re- (“re-”) + fundere (“to pour”): compare French refondre, refonder. See fuse (“to melt”), and compare refound (“to cast again”), and refu...

REFUSE.e: Borrowed into late Middle English from Middle French refusé, past participle of refuser (“to refuse”). Displaced native Middle English wernen (“to refuse”)

REFUTE.d: To prove (something) to be false or incorrect.

REGALE.e: From French régaler (“to entertain, feast”), from Old French regale, rigale, from gale (“merriment”), probably of Germanic origin (see Old French galer). Influenced by Old French se rigoler (“amuse oneself, rejoice”), of unknown origin. Compare Middle High German begalen (“to cha...

REGARD.e: From Middle English regard, regarde, reguard, from Anglo-Norman reguard, from regarder, reguarder. Attested in Middle English starting around the mid 14th century. Piecewise doublet of reward; compare also guard, ward, guardian, and so on.

REGGAE.d: A music genre that originated in Jamaica in the late 1960s and is heavily associated with Rastafarianism, featuring a heavy bass line and percussive rhythm guitar on the offbeat, often with close vocal harmonies.
REGGAE.e: From Jamaican Creole rege (“rags; a quarrel”), see rag; originally used in the 1960s to describe a Jamaican dance. Compare ragtime. Broader musical sense popularized by the 1968 Maytals song “Do the Reggay”.

REGIME.e: From Middle English regime, regyme, from Middle French regime, from Latin regimen (“direction, government”). Doublet of regimen.

REGION.d: Any considerable and connected part of a space or surface; specifically, a tract of land or sea of considerable but indefinite extent; a country; a district; in a broad sense, a place without special reference to location or extent but viewed as an entity for geographical, social or cultural reasons.
REGION.e: From Middle English regioun, from Anglo-Norman regiun, from Latin regiō, from regō. Doublet of regio.

REGRET.d: To feel sorry about (a thing that has or has not happened), afterthink: to wish that a thing had not happened, that something else had happened instead.
REGRET.e: From Middle English regretten, regreten, from Old French regreter, regrater (“to lament”), from re- (intensive prefix) + *greter, *grater (“to weep”), from Frankish *grātan (“to weep, mourn, lament”), from Proto-Germanic *grētaną (“to weep”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰreh₁d- (“...

REGROW.d: To grow again a part that has been lost, shed or destroyed.

REINED.d: Past tense of REIN: A strap or rope attached to a bridle or bit, used to control a horse, animal or young child.
REINED.e:
From Middle English rein, reyne, from Anglo-Norman reyne, resne, from Early Medieval Latin retina, ultimately from Classical Latin retineō (“hold back”), from re- + teneō (“keep, hold”). Compare modern French rêne.
Displaced native Old English brīdel (“bridle, rein”), Old English...

REJECT.d: To refuse to accept; to forswear.
REJECT.e: From Late Middle English rejecten, from Latin rēiectus, past participle of reicere (“to throw back”), from re- (“back”) + iacere (“to throw”). Displaced native Old English āweorpan (literally “to throw out”).

REJOIN.d: To join again; to unite after separation.
REJOIN.e: From Middle English rejoynen, partly from Middle French rejoin- (stem of rejoindre, from re- (“again”) + joindre (“to join”)) and partly from re- + joynen. By surface analysis, re- + join. Doublet of rejoinder.

RELATE.d: To tell in a descriptive way.
RELATE.e: From Latin relātus, perfect passive participle of referō (“carry back; report”), see -ate (verb-forming suffix). Doublet of refer. See also infer, collate and confer, delate and defer, as well as prefer and prelate among others.

RELENT.e: From Middle English relenten, from Anglo-Norman relentir, from Latin re- + lentare (“to bend”), from lentus (“soft, pliant, slow”). Earliest recording dates to 1526.

RELICT.d: Something that, or someone who, survives or remains or is left over after the loss of others; a relic.
RELICT.e: Inherited from Middle English relicte (“widow”), from Middle French relicte (“widow”), from Late Latin relicta (“widow”), from Latin relictus, past participle of relinquō (“I abandon, I relinquish, I leave (behind)”), from re- + linquō (“I leave, quit, forsake, depart from”). Dou...

RELIED.d: Past tense of RELY: to trust; to have confidence in; to depend.
RELIED.e: From Middle English relien, from Old French relier (“fasten, attach, rally, oblige”), from Latin religo (“fasten, bind fast”), from re- + ligo.

RELIEF.d: The removal of stress or discomfort.
RELIEF.e: From Old French relief (“assistance”), from Old French relever (“to relieve”), from Latin relevare (“to raise up, make light”). See also relieve.

RELIER.d: Comparative form of RELY: to trust; to have confidence in; to depend.
RELIER.e: From Middle English relien, from Old French relier (“fasten, attach, rally, oblige”), from Latin religo (“fasten, bind fast”), from re- + ligo.

RELIES.d: Plural of RELY: to trust; to have confidence in; to depend.
RELIES.e: From Middle English relien, from Old French relier (“fasten, attach, rally, oblige”), from Latin religo (“fasten, bind fast”), from re- + ligo.

RELISH.e: Alteration of reles (“scent, taste, aftertaste”), from Old French relais, reles (“something remaining, that which is left behind”), from relaisser (“to leave behind”).

RELIVE.d: To experience (something) again; to live over again.

RELUME.d: To rekindle; to relight (literally or figuratively).

REMAIN.d: That which is left; relic; remainder.
REMAIN.e:
From Middle English remainen, from Old French remain-, stressed stem of remanoir, from Latin remaneō, maneō, from Proto-Indo-European *men- (“to stay”).
Displaced native Middle English beliven, bliven (“to remain”) (from Old English belīfan (“to remain, stay”)) due to confluence ...

REMAND.d: The act of sending an accused person back into custody whilst awaiting trial.
REMAND.e: From Middle English remaunden (“to send back”), from Middle French remander (“to send back”), from Late Latin remandare (“to send backward”), from Latin remandare (“to order”). Compare countermand.

REMARK.d: An act of pointing out or noticing; notice or observation.
REMARK.e: From Middle French remarquer, from Old French remarquer, from re- (“again”) + marquer (“to mark”); see mark.

REMEDY.e: From Middle English remedie, from Old French *remedie, remede, from Latin remedium (“a remedy, cure”), from re- (“again”) + mederi (“to heal”). Doublet of remeid.

REMIND.d: To cause one to experience a memory (of someone or something); to bring to the notice or consideration (of a person).
REMIND.e: From mid 17th century, equivalent to re- + mind (“to remember”). Probably suggested by obsolete rememorate with the same sense. Displaced Old English myndgian.

REMINT.d: To mint (create money) again or repeatedly.

REMISE.e: From Anglo-Norman remis, Middle French remis, past participle of remettre (“to remit”); Middle French remise (noun), from feminine past participle of remettre (“to remit”).

REMISS.d: At fault; failing to fulfill responsibility, duty, or obligations.
REMISS.e: From Middle English remisse, remysse, from Latin remissus (“languid, negligent”), perfect passive participle of remittere (“remit”).

REMORA.d: Any of various elongate fish from the family Echeneidae, the dorsal fin of which is in the form of a suction disc that can take a firm hold against the skin of larger marine animals.
REMORA.e: Borrowed from Latin remora (“delay, hindrance, passive resistance”), from the belief that the fish would attach themselves to ships and slow them down, from re- (prefix meaning ‘back, backwards’) + mora (“delay”) (from Proto-Indo-European *mere (“to delay, hinder”), from *(s)mer-...

REMOTE.e: From Middle English remote, from Old French remot, masculine, remote, feminine, from Latin remotus, past participle of removere (“to remove”), from re- + movere (“to move”).

RENDED.d: Past tense of REND: To separate into parts with force or sudden violence; to split; to burst.
RENDED.e: From Middle English renden, from Old English rendan (“to rend, tear, cut, lacerate, cut down”), from Proto-West Germanic *(h)randijan (“to tear”), of uncertain origin. Believed by some to be the causative of Proto-Germanic *hrindaną (“to push”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱret-, *...

RENDER.e: From Middle English renderen, rendren, from Old French rendre (“render, give back”), from Late Latin rendere, from Latin reddere (“make, give back”).

RENEGE.d: To break a promise or commitment; to go back on one's word.
RENEGE.e: Borrowed from Latin renegō, from negō (“I deny”). Possibly influenced by renegotiate. Doublet of renay. See also renegade.

RENNET.d: An enzyme used as the first step in making cheese, to curdle the milk and coagulate the casein in it, derived by soaking the fourth stomach of a milk-fed calf in brine.
RENNET.e: From Middle English rennet, from Old English *rynnet, *ġerynnet, from Proto-West Germanic *garunniþu (“coagulation, curdling, rennet”), cognate with Old Saxon girunnida (“a running together, coagulation”), Old High German girunnida (“rennet, coagulation”), Middle High German geri...

RENNIN.d: A proteolytic enzyme, obtained from the gastric juice of the abomasum of calves, used to coagulate milk and make cheese.

RENOWN.e: From Old French renoun (compare with Modern French renom), equivalent to re- + noun.

REPAIR.d: To restore to good working order, fix, or improve damaged condition; to mend; to remedy.
REPAIR.e: Coined between 1300 and 1350 from Middle English repairen, from Middle French reparer, from Latin reparō (“renew, repair”).

REPASS.d: To pass (back) again, especially in the opposite direction; to return.
REPASS.e: Partly from Anglo-Norman repasser, partly from re- + pass.

REPAST.e: From Middle English repast, repaste (“feast, meal; food, nourishment; the Eucharist; refreshment, rest”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman, Middle French, Old French repast, Middle French, Old French repas (“meal, repast; spiritual nourishment”) (modern French repas), probably...

REPEAT.d: To do or say again (and again).
REPEAT.e: From Middle English repeten, from Old French repeter, from Latin repetō, repetere, from the prefix re- (“again”) + peto (“attack, beseech”).

REPENT.d: To feel pain, sorrow, or regret for what one has done or omitted to do; the cause for repenting may be indicated with "of".
REPENT.e: From Middle English repenten, from Old French repentir, from Vulgar Latin *repaenitīre, from Late Latin paenitīre, from Classical Latin paenitēre. Compare Modern French repentir.

REPORT.d: To relate details of (an event or incident); to recount, describe (something).
REPORT.e: From Middle English reporten, from Anglo-Norman reporter, from Latin reportāre (“to carry back, return, remit, refer”), from re- + portāre.

REPOSE.d: To lay (someone, or part of their body) down to rest.
REPOSE.e: The verb is derived from Middle English reposen (“to rest”), from Anglo-Norman reposer, reposir, and Middle French reposer, from Old French reposer, repauser (“to become calm; to be peaceful; to rest; to be immobile; to lie or be placed; to cease, stop; to neglect”) (modern Frenc...

REPPED.d: Past tense of REP: Clipping of reputation.
REPPED.e: Clippings of various words beginning with rep.

REPUTE.e: From Old French reputer, from Latin reputo (“I count over, reckon, calculate, compute, think over, consider”), from re- (“again”) + puto (“I think”).

RESCUE.d: To save from any violence, danger or evil.
RESCUE.e: From Middle English rescouen, from Old French rescoure, rescurre, rescorre; from Latin prefix re- (“re-”) + excutere (“to shake or drive out”), from ex (“out”) + quatiō (“I shake”).

RESEAL.d: To seal (something) again (in any sense of "apply a seal to").

RESECT.d: To remove (some part of an organ or structure) by surgical means.
RESECT.e: Borrowed from Latin resectus, past participle of resecare (“to cut off”), formed in turn from re- + secare (“to cut”).

RESEED.d: To sow seeds again; to apply seed to (a plot of land) again.

RESENT.d: To feel resentment over; to consider as an affront.
RESENT.e: From Middle French ressentir, resentir, from Old French resentir (Modern ressentir), from re- + sentir (“to feel”).

RESIDE.d: To dwell permanently or for a considerable time; to have a settled abode for a time; to remain for a long time.
RESIDE.e: From Middle English residen, from Old French resider, from Latin resideō (“remain behind, reside, dwell”), from re- (“back”) + sedeō (“sit”).

RESIGN.d: To give up; to relinquish ownership of.
RESIGN.e: From Anglo-Norman resigner, Middle French resigner, and its source, Latin resignāre (“to unseal, annul, assign, resign”), from re- + signāre (“to seal, stamp”). Piecewise doublet of re-sign.

RESILE.d: To start back; to recoil; to recede from a purpose.
RESILE.e: From Middle French resiler (compare French résilier), from Latin resiliō (“spring back”), from re- (“back”) + saliō (“I jump”).

RESIST.d: To attempt to counter the actions or effects of.
RESIST.e: From Middle English resisten, from Middle French resister and Old French resistre, and their source, Latin resistere, from re- + sistere (“cause to stand”).

RESITE.d: To move to another site or place.

RESKIN.d: To replace or repair the skin of a motor vehicle, aircraft, etc., especially so as to market the same car under different brands

RESORB.e: From Latin resorbere, from re- (“again”) + sorbere (“to suck in”).

RESTED.d: Past tense of REST: Relief from work or activity by sleeping; sleep.
RESTED.e: From Middle English rest, reste, from Old English ræst, from Proto-West Germanic *rastu, from Proto-Germanic *rastō, from Proto-Indo-European *ros-, *res-, *erH- (“rest”). Cognate with West Frisian rêst (“rest”), Dutch rust (“rest”), German Rast (“rest”), Swedish rast (“rest”), N...

RESULT.d: To proceed, spring up or rise, as a consequence, from facts, arguments, premises, combination of circumstances, consultation, thought or endeavor.
RESULT.e: Recorded since 1432 as Middle English resulten, from Medieval Latin resultare, in Classical Latin "to spring forward, rebound", the frequentative of the past participle of resilio (“to rebound”), from re- (“back”) + salio (“to jump, leap”).

RESUME.e: From Anglo-Norman resumer, Middle French resumer, from Latin resumere, from re- + sumere (“to take”).

RETAIL.d: The sale of goods directly to the consumer, encompassing the storefronts, mail-order, websites, etc., and the corporate mechanisms, branding, advertising, etc. that support them.
RETAIL.e: From the Old French verb retaillier.

RETAIN.d: Often followed by from: to hold back (someone or something); to check, to prevent, to restrain, to stop.
RETAIN.e: From Late Middle English reteinen, retein (“to continue to keep, retain; to continue to possess; to possess; to contain; to draw back, retire; to hold back, restrain; to keep in mind, remember; to take back, repossess; to appoint; to engage in one’s service, employ, hire”) [and o...

RETARD.e: From Middle English retarden, from Anglo-Norman or Latin, from Anglo-Norman retarder, from Latin retardāre (“to retard”), from re- + tardus (“slow”).

RETASK.d: To cause to perform a new task; to change the work or mission of.

RETELL.d: To tell again, often differently, what one has read or heard; to paraphrase.

RETINA.d: The thin layer of cells at the back of the eyeball that contains rods and cones sensitive to light, which trigger nerve impulses that pass via the optic nerve to the brain, where a visual image is formed.
RETINA.e: From Middle English rethina, borrowing from Medieval Latin rētīna (“retina”, feminine noun), ellipsis of tunica rētīna (“net-like tunic”), used to describe the blood vessel system at the back of the eye. The phrase is attested in the 12th century in Guillelmus the abbot and Gerar...

RETIRE.d: To stop working on a permanent basis, usually because of old age or illness.
RETIRE.e: From Middle French retirer (“draw back”), from Old French retirer, built from re- (“back”) + tirer (“draw, pull”), the latter from Vulgar Latin *tīrāre, of highly uncertain origin.

RETORT.d: A sharp or witty reply, or one which turns an argument against its originator; a comeback.
RETORT.e: From Middle English retorte, from Latin retortus, from retorquēre (“to be forced to twist back”).

RETTED.d: Past tense of RET: To prepare (flax, hemp etc.) for further processing by soaking, which facilitates separation of fibers from the woody parts of the stem.
RETTED.e: From Middle English retten, reten; perhaps from Middle Dutch rēten, reeten (compare Middle Low German rōten; Middle High German rōzen), or from Old Norse reyta (compare Norwegian røyta, Swedish röta); all from Proto-Germanic *rautijaną (“to make mellow or soft”), from Proto-Indo-...

RETTER.d: Comparative form of RET: To prepare (flax, hemp etc.) for further processing by soaking, which facilitates separation of fibers from the woody parts of the stem.
RETTER.e: From Middle English retten, reten; perhaps from Middle Dutch rēten, reeten (compare Middle Low German rōten; Middle High German rōzen), or from Old Norse reyta (compare Norwegian røyta, Swedish röta); all from Proto-Germanic *rautijaną (“to make mellow or soft”), from Proto-Indo-...

RETUBE.d: To fit with a new tube or tubes.

RETURN.d: To come or go back (to a place or person).
RETURN.e: From Middle English returnen, retornen, from Anglo-Norman returner, from Old French retourner, retorner, from Medieval Latin retornare (“to turn back”), from re- + tornare (“to turn”). Compare beturn.

REVEAL.d: The outer side of a window or door frame.
REVEAL.e: From Middle English revēlen, from Old French reveler, from Latin revēlāre (“to reveal, uncover”), from re- (“back, again”) + vēlāre (“to cover”), from vēlum (“a cloth, covering, curtain, veil, awning, sail”) (whence also English veil, English unveil, English voile, Russian вуаль ...

REVERB.d: An electronic effect which simulates echoes or reverberations in the sound signal being processed.

REVERE.d: To regard someone or something with great awe or devotion.
REVERE.e: Borrowed from French révérer, ultimately from Latin revereor, from re- + vereor (“to fear”).

REVERT.d: One who, or that which, reverts.
REVERT.e: From Old French revertir, from Vulgar Latin *revertiō, variant of Latin revertō.

REVIEW.d: A second or subsequent reading of a text or artifact in an attempt to gain new insights.
REVIEW.e: From Middle English revewe, reveue, from Old French reveüe, revue (Modern French: revue), feminine form of reveü, past participle of reveoir (French: revoir), from Latin revideō, from re- +videō (“see, observe”) (English: video). Equivalent to re- + view. Compare retrospect. Doub...

REVILE.e: From Middle English revilen, from re + Old French aviler (“to make vile or cheap, disprize, disesteem”), from a- (“to”) + vil (“vile, cheap”); see vile.

REVISE.d: To review, alter and amend, especially of written material.
REVISE.e: Borrowed from Middle French réviser, from Latin revīsō, from re- + vīsō (“examine”), frequentative of videō (“see”).

REVIVE.d: To cause (a person or animal) to recover from a faint; to cause (a person or animal) to return to a state of consciousness.
REVIVE.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English reviven, revyven (“to recover from illness; to regain consciousness; to return to life after death; to happen again, recur; to be rejuvenated, renewed; (figurative) to bring back; (alchemy) of a metal: to be restored to its original fo...

REVOKE.d: To cancel or invalidate by withdrawing or reversing.
REVOKE.e: Borrowed from Middle French révoquer, from Latin revocare, from re- + voco, vocare. Doublet of revocate.

REVOLT.e:
Borrowed from French révolter, from Italian rivoltare, itself either from ri- with the verb voltare, or possibly from a Vulgar Latin *revoltāre < *revolvitāre, for *revolūtāre, frequentative of Latin revolvō (“roll back”) (through its past participle revolūtus).
Compare typologic...

REVVED.d: Past tense of REV: To increase the speed of a motor, or to operate at a higher speed.

REWARD.d: Something of value given in return for an act.
REWARD.e: From Middle English reward, rewarde, from Old French reward (“reward”) (compare Old French regard, whence modern French regard, and also English regard through Middle French), from rewarder (“to reward”) (compare Old French reguarder), from re- + warder (“to guard, keep”) (compar...

REWARM.d: To warm again; to bring back to a state of warmth.

REWILD.d: To return an area to a more wild state, especially to repopulate it with wild animals that have become extirpated.

REWIRE.d: To replace or reconnect the wires of a device or installation.

REWORK.d: The act of redoing, correcting, or rebuilding.

RHEBOK.d: A medium-sized, deerlike South African antelope, Pelea capreolus, having pale-gray, curly fur and straight horns.
RHEBOK.e: Earlier rabock, reebok, rhebuck, rheeboc, raybuck, rehboc, borrowed from Afrikaans reebok (“rhebok”), ribbok (“rhebok”), from Dutch reebok (“roebuck”), compound of ree + bok, from Middle Dutch reeboc. Unetymological h present since 1775 though the spelling and pronunciation has v...

RHETOR.e: From Middle English rethor, from Old French retor and Latin rhētor, rētor, rēthor (“teacher of rhetoric, rhetorician”), from Ancient Greek ῥήτωρ (rhḗtōr).

RHEUMY.d: Of, relating to, or made of rheum (“thin or watery discharge of mucus or serum”); watery.
RHEUMY.e: From rheum + -y (suffix forming adjectives meaning ‘having the quality of’).

RHOTIC.d: That allows the phoneme /ɹ/ even when not followed by a vowel, as in bar (/bɑːɹ/) and bard or barred (/bɑːɹd/); (of an English speaker) who speaks with such an accent.
RHOTIC.e: Back-formation from rhotacism, coined in 1968 by John C. Wells.

RHYTHM.d: The variation of strong and weak elements (such as duration, accent) of sounds, notably in speech or music, over time; a beat or meter.
RHYTHM.e: First coined in 1557, from Latin rhythmus, from Ancient Greek ῥυθμός (rhuthmós, “any measured flow or movement, symmetry, rhythm”), from ῥέω (rhéō, “I flow, run, stream, gush”).

RIBALD.d: Coarsely, vulgarly, or lewdly amusing; referring to sexual matters in a rude or irreverent way.
RIBALD.e: From Middle English ribald, from Old French ribaud, ribauld (“rogue, scoundrel”) ( > English ribaud), from Old French riber (“to be licentious”), from Frankish *rīban (“to copulate, be in heat”, literally “to rub”), from Proto-Germanic *wrībaną (“to turn, twist, writhe”), from Pr...

RIBBED.d: Past tense of RIB: Any of a series of long curved bones occurring in 12 pairs in humans and other animals and extending from the spine to or toward the sternum.
RIBBED.e:
From Middle English rib, ribbe, from Old English ribb (“rib”), from Proto-West Germanic *ribi, from Proto-Germanic *ribją (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rebʰ- (“arch, ceiling, cover”).
Cognate with Dutch rib (“rib”), Norwegian ribbe (“sparerib”), Norwegian ribben (“ri...

RIBBER.d: Comparative form of RIB: Any of a series of long curved bones occurring in 12 pairs in humans and other animals and extending from the spine to or toward the sternum.
RIBBER.e:
From Middle English rib, ribbe, from Old English ribb (“rib”), from Proto-West Germanic *ribi, from Proto-Germanic *ribją (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rebʰ- (“arch, ceiling, cover”).
Cognate with Dutch rib (“rib”), Norwegian ribbe (“sparerib”), Norwegian ribben (“ri...

RIBBIT.d: The vocal sound made by a frog or toad.

RIBBON.d: A long, narrow strip of material used for decoration of clothing or the hair or gift wrapping.
RIBBON.e: From Middle English riban, ryban, ryband, from Old French riban, ruban ( > modern French ruban), of uncertain origin. Likely from a Germanic compound whose second element is cognate with English band. Compare Middle Dutch ringhband (“necklace”, literally “ring-band”).

RIBLET.d: Boneless processed pork or beef rib meat, served at restaurants and fast food places.

RIBOSE.d: A naturally occurring pentose sugar, which is a component of the nucleosides and nucleotides that constitute the nucleic acid biopolymer, RNA. It is also found in riboflavin.
RIBOSE.e: From German Ribose, formed from Ribonsäure, the first element of which comes from a rearrangement of English arabinose.

RICHEN.d: To make or render rich or richer.

RICHES.d: Plural of RICH: Wealthy: having a lot of money and possessions.
RICHES.e: From Middle English riche (“strong, powerful, rich”), from Old English rīċe (“powerful, mighty, great, high-ranking, rich, wealthy, strong, potent”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīkī (“powerful, rich”), from Proto-Germanic *rīkijaz (“kingly, powerful, rich”), from Proto-Germanic *r...

RICING.d: Present participle of RICE: Cereal plants, Oryza sativa of the grass family whose seeds are used as food.
RICING.e: From Middle English rys, from Old French ris, from Old Italian riso, risi, from Byzantine Greek ὄρυζα (óruza), from an Eastern Iranian language related to Middle Persian blnc (*brinǰ), Northern Kurdish riz (beyond Euphrates) and Zazaki riz. Theorized to come to Iranian languages ...

RICKED.d: Past tense of RICK: Straw, hay etc. stored in a stack for winter fodder, commonly protected with thatch.
RICKED.e: From Middle English *rykke, from Old English hrycce (“rick, heap, pile”), cognate with Scots ruk (“rick”), Norwegian ruka (“rick, haystack”). Related also to Old English hrēac (“rick, stack”), from Proto-Germanic *hraukaz (“heap”). Further relations: Dutch rook, Icelandic hraukur...

RICKEY.d: A variant of Ricky, diminutive of the male given name Richard.

RIDDED.d: Past tense of RID: Followed by of: to free (oneself or someone, or a place) from an annoyance or hindrance.
RIDDED.e: The verb is derived from Middle English ridden (“to remove debris, obstructions, etc., from (a place), to clear; to complete (something unfinished); to free (someone or something); to relieve (someone); etc.”), probably from Old English *ryddan (“to remove debris, obstructions, e...

RIDDER.d: Comparative form of RID: Followed by of: to free (oneself or someone, or a place) from an annoyance or hindrance.
RIDDER.e: The verb is derived from Middle English ridden (“to remove debris, obstructions, etc., from (a place), to clear; to complete (something unfinished); to free (someone or something); to relieve (someone); etc.”), probably from Old English *ryddan (“to remove debris, obstructions, e...

RIDDIM.d: An instrumental version of a song in Jamaican or Caribbean music, usually with a drum pattern and a prominent bassline, meant to be reused as a backing track in other productions.
RIDDIM.e: From Jamaican Creole riddim, from rhythm.

RIDDLE.d: A verbal puzzle, mystery, or other problem of an intellectual nature.
RIDDLE.e: From Middle English redel, redels, from Old English rǣdels, rǣdelse (“counsel, opinion, imagination, riddle”), from Proto-West Germanic *rādislī (“counsel, conjecture”). Analyzable as rede (“advice”) + -le. Akin to Old English rǣdan (“to read, advise, interpret”). Cognate with Du...

RIDING.d: present participle and gerund of ride
RIDING.e: From Middle English rydyng; equivalent to ride + -ing.

RIFFED.d: Past tense of RIFF: A repeated melody line in a song, usually instrumental but sometimes vocal.
RIFFED.e: Uncertain. Perhaps a clipping of riffle, or an alteration of refrain.

RIFFLE.d: A swift, shallow part of a stream causing broken water.
RIFFLE.e: Possible alteration of ruffle, from Middle English ruffelen, akin to Low German ruffelen (“to crumple”).

RIFTED.d: Past tense of RIFT: A chasm or fissure.
RIFTED.e: From Middle English rift, of North Germanic origin; akin to Danish rift, Norwegian Bokmål rift (“breach”), Old Norse rífa (“to tear”). More at rive.

RIGGED.d: Past tense of RIG: The rigging of a sailing ship or other such craft.
RIGGED.e: From Early Modern English rygge, probably of North Germanic origin. Compare Norwegian rigge (“to bind up; wrap around; rig; equip”), Swedish dialectal rigga (“to rig a horse”), Faroese rigga (“to rig; to equip and fit; to make s.th. function”). Possibly from Proto-Germanic *rik- ...

RIGGER.d: One who rigs or dresses; as:

RIGHTS.d: Plural of RIGHT: Correct; the opposite of left.

RIGOUR.e: From Middle English rigour, from Anglo-Norman, from Old French rigor, from Latin rigor (“stiffness, rigidity, rigor, cold, harshness”), from rigere (“to be rigid”). Compare French rigueur.

RILING.d: Present participle of RILE: To stir or move from a state of calm or order.
RILING.e: From a dialectal pronunciation of roil.

RIMING.d: Present participle of RIME: Archaic in the form rimes: originally, any frozen dew forming a white deposit on exposed surfaces; hoar frost (sense 1).
RIMING.e: The noun is derived from Middle English rim, rime, rym, ryme (“hoar frost; rime”), from Old English hrīm (“frost”), from Proto-West Germanic *hrīm (“rime; hoar frost”), from Proto-Germanic *hrīmą (North Germanic), *hrīmaz, *hrīmô (“rime; hoar frost”), probably from Proto-Indo-Eur...

RIMMED.d: Past tense of RIM: An edge around something, especially when circular.
RIMMED.e: From Middle English rim, rym, rime, from Old English rima (“rim, edge, border, bank, coast”), from Proto-Germanic *rimô, *rembô (“edge, border”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *rem-, *remə- (“to rest, support, be based”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Rim (“plank, wooden cro...

RIMMER.d: Comparative form of RIM: An edge around something, especially when circular.
RIMMER.e: From Middle English rim, rym, rime, from Old English rima (“rim, edge, border, bank, coast”), from Proto-Germanic *rimô, *rembô (“edge, border”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *rem-, *remə- (“to rest, support, be based”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Rim (“plank, wooden cro...

RIOTED.d: Past tense of RIOT: A tumultuous disturbance of the public peace by a large group of people, often involving violence or damage to property.
RIOTED.e:
From Middle English riot (“debauched living, dissipation”), from Old French riote (“debate”), from rioter (“to quarrel”), perhaps related to riboter or from Latin rugio (“I roar”).
Compare French riotte and Occitan riòta.

RIPING.d: Present participle of RIPE: Ready for reaping or gathering; having attained perfection; mature.
RIPING.e: From Middle English ripe, rype, from Old English rīpe (“ripe, mature”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīpī, from Proto-Germanic *rīpijaz, *rīpiz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyb- (“to snatch”). Cognate with West Frisian ryp (“ripe”), Dutch rijp (“ripe”), German reif (“ripe”). Relate...

RIPPED.d: Past tense of RIP: To divide or separate the parts of (especially something flimsy, such as paper or fabric), by cutting or tearing; to tear off or out by violence.
RIPPED.e:
From Middle English rippen, from earlier ryppen (“to pluck”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *rupjaną, *ruppōną, intensive of *raupijaną, causative of Proto-Indo-European *roub- ~ *reub-, variant of *Hrewp- (“to break”).
See also West Frisian rippe, ripje, roppe, ropje (“to rip”)...

RIPPER.d: Comparative form of RIP: To divide or separate the parts of (especially something flimsy, such as paper or fabric), by cutting or tearing; to tear off or out by violence.
RIPPER.e:
From Middle English rippen, from earlier ryppen (“to pluck”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *rupjaną, *ruppōną, intensive of *raupijaną, causative of Proto-Indo-European *roub- ~ *reub-, variant of *Hrewp- (“to break”).
See also West Frisian rippe, ripje, roppe, ropje (“to rip”)...

RIPPLE.d: A moving disturbance, or undulation, in the surface of a fluid.

RIPSAW.d: A saw that is designed to cut wood along its grain, i.e. to rip, to execute a rip cut.

RISING.d: Present participle of RISE: To move, or appear to move, physically upwards relative to the ground.
RISING.e:
From Middle English risen, from Old English rīsan, from Proto-West Germanic *rīsan, from Proto-Germanic *rīsaną, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rey- (“to rise, arise”). According to Kroonen (2013), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃er- (“to stir, rise”). See also raise.
Cognates
Cognate w...

RISKED.d: Past tense of RISK: The probability of a negative outcome to a decision or event.
RISKED.e:
From earlier risque, from Middle French risque, from Old Italian risco (“risk”) (modern Italian rischio) and rischiare (“to run into danger”). Displaced native Old English pleoh (“risk”) and plēon (“to risk”).
speculation on earlier roots
Most dictionaries consider the etymology ...

RITUAL.d: Related to a rite or repeated set of actions.

RIVERS.d: Plural of RIVER: A large natural stream of water.

RIVING.d: Present participle of RIVE: To tear apart by force; to rend; to split; to cleave.
RIVING.e:
From Middle English riven (“to rive”), of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse rífa (“to rend, tear apart”), from Proto-Germanic *rīfaną (“to tear, scratch”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyp- (“to crumble, tear”).
Cognate with Danish rive (“to tear”), Old Frisian rīva (“to tear...

ROADED.d: Past tense of ROAD: A way used for travelling between places, originally one wide enough to allow foot passengers and horses to travel, now (US) usually one surfaced with asphalt or concrete and designed to accommodate many vehicles travelling in both directions. In the UK both senses are heard: a country road is the same as a country lane.
ROADED.e: From Middle English rode, rade (“ride, journey”), from Old English rād (“riding, hostile incursion”), from Proto-West Germanic *raidu, from Proto-Germanic *raidō (“a ride”), from Proto-Indo-European *reydʰ- (“to ride”). Doublet of raid, acquired from Scots. Cognates include West ...

ROADIE.d: One of the crew for a musical group or other travelling stage production, especially a stagehand or technician.

ROAMED.d: Past tense of ROAM: To wander or travel freely and with no specific destination.
ROAMED.e: From Middle English romen, from Old English rāmian, from Proto-Germanic *raimōną (“to wander”), from *raim- (“to move, raise”), from *h₃reyH- (“to move, lift, flow”). Akin to Old English ārǣman (“to arise, stand up, lift up”), Old High German rāmēn (“to aim”) ( > archaic German r...

ROARED.d: Past tense of ROAR: To make a loud, deep cry, especially from pain, anger, or other strong emotion.
ROARED.e:
From Middle English roren, raren, from Old English rārian (“to roar; wail; lament”), from Proto-West Germanic *rairōn, from Proto-Germanic *rairōną (“to bellow; roar”), from Proto-Indo-European *rey- (“to shout; bellow; yell; bark”), perhaps of imitative origin.
Cognate with Sate...

ROBBED.d: Past tense of ROB: To steal from, especially using force or violence.
ROBBED.e: From Middle English robben, from Anglo-Norman robber, from Late Latin raubāre, from Frankish *raubōn (compare Dutch roven) and Old High German roubōn, raubōn (“to rob, steal, plunder”), from Proto-Germanic *raubōną. Doublet of reave.

ROBBER.d: Comparative form of ROB: To steal from, especially using force or violence.
ROBBER.e: From Middle English robben, from Anglo-Norman robber, from Late Latin raubāre, from Frankish *raubōn (compare Dutch roven) and Old High German roubōn, raubōn (“to rob, steal, plunder”), from Proto-Germanic *raubōną. Doublet of reave.

ROBING.d: Present participle of ROBE: A long loose outer garment, often signifying honorary stature.
ROBING.e: From Middle English robe, roobe, from Old French robe, robbe, reube (“booty, spoils of war, robe, garment”), from Frankish *rouba, *rauba (“booty, spoils, stolen clothes”, literally “things taken”), from Proto-Germanic *raubō, *raubaz, *raubą (“booty, that which is stripped or ca...

ROBOTS.d: Plural of ROBOT: A machine capable of carrying out actions automatically.

ROCKED.d: Past tense of ROCK: A formation of minerals, specifically:
ROCKED.e: Inherited from Middle English rocke, rokke (“rock formation”), from Old English *rocc (“rock”), as in Old English stānrocc (“high stone rock, peak, obelisk”), and also later from Anglo-Norman roque, (compare Modern French roc, roche, rocher), from Medieval Latin rocca (attested 7...

ROCKET.e: From Italian rocchetta, from Old Italian rocchetto (“rocket”, literally “a bobbin”), diminutive of rocca (“a distaff”), from Lombardic rocko (“spinning wheel”), from Proto-West Germanic *rokkō, from Proto-Germanic *rukkô (“a distaff, a staff with flax fibres tied loosely to it, u...

ROCOCO.d: A style of baroque architecture and decorative art, from 18th-century France, having elaborate ornamentation.

RODDED.d: Past tense of ROD: A straight, round stick, shaft, bar, cane, or staff.
RODDED.e: From Middle English rodde, from Old English *rodd or *rodde (attested in dative plural roddum (“rod, pole”)), of uncertain origin, but probably from Proto-Germanic *rudd- (“stick, club”), from Proto-Indo-European *rewdʰ- (“to clear land”). Compare Old Norse rudda (“club”). For th...

RODDER.d: Comparative form of ROD: A straight, round stick, shaft, bar, cane, or staff.
RODDER.e: From Middle English rodde, from Old English *rodd or *rodde (attested in dative plural roddum (“rod, pole”)), of uncertain origin, but probably from Proto-Germanic *rudd- (“stick, club”), from Proto-Indo-European *rewdʰ- (“to clear land”). Compare Old Norse rudda (“club”). For th...

RODENT.d: A mammal of the order Rodentia, characterized by long incisors that grow continuously and are worn down by gnawing.
RODENT.e: From Latin rōdēns, rōdēnt- (“gnawer; one who gnaws”), present participle of rōdō (“I gnaw”).

RODING.d: Present participle of RODE: simple past of ride

ROILED.d: Past tense of ROIL: To render turbid by stirring up the dregs or sediment of.
ROILED.e: Origin uncertain. Possibly from French or Middle French rouiller (“to rust, make muddy”), from Old French rouil (“mud, rust”), from Vulgar Latin *robicula, from Latin robigo (“rust, blight”)

ROLLED.d: Past tense of ROLL: To revolve by turning over and over; to move by turning on a horizontal axis; to impel forward with a revolving motion on a supporting surface.
ROLLED.e: From Middle English rollen, partly from Old French roller, roler, röeler, röoler, from Medieval Latin rotulāre (“to roll; to revolve”), from Latin rotula (“a little wheel”), diminutive of rota (“a wheel”); partly from Anglo-Latin rollāre, from the same ultimate source.

ROLLER.e:
* From Middle English rollere, equivalent to roll + -er.
* (credits in TV or film): These were originally printed on a physical cylinder that was rotated in front of the camera.

ROMCOM.e: Shortening of romantic comedy. Probably based on the earlier sitcom.

ROMPED.d: Past tense of ROMP: To play about roughly, energetically or boisterously.

RONDEL.d: A metric form of verse using two rhymes, usually fourteen 8- to 10-syllable lines in three stanzas, with the first lines of the first stanza returning as refrain of the next two.
RONDEL.e: From Middle English rondel, from Old French rondel, a diminutive of ronde, the feminine of ront, reont (“round (in shape)”), from Latin rotundus (“round, circular; spherical”), related to rota (“wheel”).

ROOFED.d: Past tense of ROOF: The external covering at the top of a building.
ROOFED.e: From Middle English rof, from Old English hrōf (“roof, ceiling; top, summit; heaven, sky”), from Proto-Germanic *hrōfą (“roof”).

ROOKED.d: Past tense of ROOK: A European bird, Corvus frugilegus, of the crow family.
ROOKED.e: * Inherited from Middle English rok, roke, from Old English hrōc, from Proto-West Germanic *hrōk, from Proto-Germanic *hrōkaz (compare Old Norse hrókr, Saterland Frisian Rouk, Dutch roek, obsolete German Ruch), from Proto-Indo-European *kerk- (“crow, raven”) (compare Old Irish ce...

ROOKIE.d: An inexperienced recruit, especially in the police or armed forces.
ROOKIE.e: Thought to be an alteration of recruit + -ie, or from rook (“a cheat”) + -ie. Another possible origin is Dutch broekie (short for broekvent (“a boy still in short trousers”)), a common term for a shipmate. Also suggested is Irish rúca (“an inexperienced person”).

ROOMED.d: Past tense of ROOM: An opportunity or scope (to do something).
ROOMED.e: From Middle English roum, from Old English rūm (“room, space”), from Proto-West Germanic *rūm (“room”), from Proto-Germanic *rūmą (“room”), from Proto-Indo-European *(H)rewH-.

ROOTED.d: Past tense of ROOT: The part of a plant, generally underground, that anchors and supports the plant body, absorbs and stores water and nutrients, and in some plants is able to perform vegetative reproduction.
ROOTED.e:
PIE word
 *wréh₂ds
From Middle English rote, root, roote (“the underground part of a plant”), from late Old English rōt, from Old Norse rót (Icelandic rót), from Proto-Germanic *wrōts, from Proto-Indo-European *wréh₂ds (“root”); Doublet of wort, radish, and radix.

ROPING.d: Present participle of ROPE: Thick strings, yarn, monofilaments, metal wires, or strands of other cordage that are twisted together to form a stronger line.
ROPING.e: From Middle English rop, rope, from Old English rāp (“rope, cord, cable”), from Proto-West Germanic *raip, from Proto-Germanic *raipaz, *raipą (“rope, cord, band, ringlet”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁roypnós (“strap, band, rope”), from *h₁reyp- (“to peel off, tear; border, edge...

ROSARY.d: Prayer beads, a string of beads used to keep track of repetitions in prayer, particularly of the Roman Catholic Marian prayer "Hail Mary" (Ave Maria).
ROSARY.e: From Middle English rosarie, from Latin rosārium, here in its sense as a garland of roses. The coin usage referred to the laurel wreath appearing on the obverse bust, as opposed to the bare head on the pollard. Doublet of Rosario and rosarium.

ROSIED.e: From Middle English rosy; equivalent to rose + -y.

ROSIER.e: From Middle English rosy; equivalent to rose + -y.

ROSING.d: Present participle of ROSE: A shrub of the genus Rosa, with red, pink, white or yellow flowers.
ROSING.e:
From Middle English rose, roose, from Old English rōse, but with its vowel influenced by Old French rose, both from Latin rosa.
cognates and more remote and uncertain etymology
The Latin is of uncertain origin, but likely via Oscan from Ancient Greek ῥόδον (rhódon, “rose”) (Aeoli...

ROSTER.d: A list of individuals or groups, usually for an organization of some kind such as military officers and enlisted personnel enrolled in a particular unit; a muster roll; a sports team, with the names of players who are eligible to be placed in the lineup for a particular game; or a list of students officially enrolled in a school or class.
ROSTER.e: Borrowed from Dutch rooster (“gridiron, table, list”), from Middle Dutch roosten (“to roast”). More at roast.

ROTARY.e: Attested mid 18th century, from Medieval Latin rotarius, from Latin rota (“wheel”).

ROTATE.e: Borrowed from Latin rotātus, perfect passive participle of rotō (“revolve”) (see -ate (verb-forming suffix) and -ate (adjective-forming suffix)), from rota (“wheel”) + -ō (verb-forming suffix).

ROTTED.d: Past tense of ROT: To suffer decomposition due to biological action, especially by fungi or bacteria.
ROTTED.e: Inherited from Middle English roten, rotten, from Old English rotian (“to rot, become corrupted, ulcerate, putrefy”), from Proto-West Germanic *rotēn, from Proto-Germanic *rutāną (“to rot”).

ROTTEN.d: Of perishable items, overridden with bacteria and other infectious agents.
ROTTEN.e: From Middle English roten, from Old Norse rotinn (“decayed, rotten”), past participle of an unrecorded verb related to Old Norse rotna (“to rot”) and Old English rotian (“to rot”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *rutāną (“to rot”). See rot. By surface analysis, rot + -en (past pa...

ROTTER.d: Comparative form of ROT: To suffer decomposition due to biological action, especially by fungi or bacteria.
ROTTER.e: Inherited from Middle English roten, rotten, from Old English rotian (“to rot, become corrupted, ulcerate, putrefy”), from Proto-West Germanic *rotēn, from Proto-Germanic *rutāną (“to rot”).

ROTUND.d: Having a round, spherical or curved shape; circular; orbicular.
ROTUND.e: Learned borrowing from Latin rotundus (“round”), from Latin rota (“wheel”), from Proto-Indo-European *Hreth₂- (“to run, to roll”). Doublet of round.

ROUGHS.d: Plural of ROUGH: Having an uneven surface; approximate.

ROUNDS.d: Plural of ROUND: Shaped like a circle; a series.
ROUNDS.e: From Old French roond, from Latin rotundus.

ROUTED.d: Past tense of ROUTE: A way or course taken.
ROUTED.e: From Old French rute, from Latin rupta via (broken way).

ROUTES.d: Plural of ROUTE: A way or course taken.
ROUTES.e: From Old French rute, from Latin rupta via (broken way).

ROVING.d: Present participle of ROVE: To shoot with arrows (at).
ROVING.e: Probably from Middle English *roven, a Midlands variant of Northern Middle English raven (“to wander”), from Old Norse ráfa (“to rove; stray about”). Cognate with Icelandic ráfa (“to wander”), Scots rave (“to wander; stray; roam”).

ROWING.d: Present participle of ROW: A line of objects, often regularly spaced, such as seats in a theatre, vegetable plants in a garden, etc.
ROWING.e:
From Middle English rewe, rowe, rawe, from Old English rǣw, rāw, probably from Proto-Germanic *raiwō, *raigwō, *raih- (“row, streak, line”), from Proto-Indo-European *reyk- (“to carve, scratch, etch”).
Cognate with Scots raw (“row”), dialectal Norwegian rå (“boundary line”), Sate...

ROYALS.d: Plural of ROYAL: Relating to a king or queen.
ROYALS.e: From Old French roial, from Latin rēgālis.

RUBATO.d: A tempo in which strict timing is relaxed, the music being played near, but not on, the beat.
RUBATO.e: Borrowed from Italian rubato (“robbed, stolen”), since the time is "borrowed".

RUBBED.d: Past tense of RUB: An act of rubbing.
RUBBED.e:
Inherited from Middle English rubben, of unknown origin; possibly ultimately from Proto-Germanic *rubbōną, related to *reufaną (“to tear”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian rubje (“to rub, scrape”), German Low German rubben (“to rub”), Low German rubblig (“rough, uneven”), Dutch ro...

RUBBER.d: Pliable material derived from the sap of the rubber tree; a hydrocarbon biopolymer of isoprene.
RUBBER.e:
From rub + -er.
The sense of the substance comes from its ability to function as an eraser, displacing earlier caoutchouc. The senses not pertaining to rubbing or erasing are secondarily derived from the name of the substance.

RUBBLE.d: The broken remains of an object, usually rock or masonry.
RUBBLE.e: Inherited from Middle English rouble, rubel, robel, robeil, from Anglo-Norman *robel (“bits of broken stone”). Presumably related to rubbish, originally of same meaning (waste material, bits of stone, rubble). Ultimately presumably from Old Norse rubba (“to huddle, crowd together...

RUBIED.d: Past tense of RUBY: A clear, deep, red variety of corundum, valued as a precious stone.
RUBIED.e:
From Middle English ruby, rube, from Old French rubi, from Medieval Latin rubīnus. Doublet of rubi and rubine.
Sense 7 (“pronunciation guide”) is from the British 5½-point type size (sense 6), used for annotations in printed documents.

RUBIER.d: Comparative form of RUBY: A clear, deep, red variety of corundum, valued as a precious stone.
RUBIER.e:
From Middle English ruby, rube, from Old French rubi, from Medieval Latin rubīnus. Doublet of rubi and rubine.
Sense 7 (“pronunciation guide”) is from the British 5½-point type size (sense 6), used for annotations in printed documents.

RUBIES.d: Plural of RUBY: A clear, deep, red variety of corundum, valued as a precious stone.
RUBIES.e:
From Middle English ruby, rube, from Old French rubi, from Medieval Latin rubīnus. Doublet of rubi and rubine.
Sense 7 (“pronunciation guide”) is from the British 5½-point type size (sense 6), used for annotations in printed documents.

RUBIFY.d: to make red; to cause to redden

RUBOUT.d: An instance of erasing with a rubber.

RUBRIC.d: A heading in a book highlighted in red.
RUBRIC.e: From Middle English rubriche, rubrike, from Old French rubrique, from Latin rūbrīca (“red ochre”), the substance used to make red letters, from ruber (“red”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rewdʰ-.

RUCKED.d: Past tense of RUCK: A throng or crowd of people or things; a mass, a pack.
RUCKED.e: From Middle English ruke, from or related to Old Norse hraukr, which is from Proto-Germanic *hraukaz (“haystack, heap”). Compare Icelandic hrúka, Swedish ruka.

RUCKUS.e: Recorded since 1890; probably a blend of ruction (“disturbance”) + rumpus (“disturbance, fracas”).

RUCOLA.e: From Italian. See rocket for other cognates.

RUDDER.d: An underwater vane used to steer a vessel. The rudder is controlled by means of a wheel, tiller or other apparatus (modern vessels can be controlled even with a joystick or an autopilot).
RUDDER.e: From Middle English rodder, rother, ruder, from Old English rōþor (“oar, rudder”), from Proto-West Germanic *rōþr, from Proto-Germanic *rōþrą (“oar, rudder”) (compare Dutch and West Frisian roer, German Ruder), from Proto-Germanic *rōaną, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reh₁- (“to ro...

RUDERY.d: Crudeness; the use of crude language.

RUFFLE.d: Any gathered or curled strip of fabric added as trim or decoration.
RUFFLE.e: From Middle English ruffelen, perhaps from Old Norse hrufla (“to graze, scratch”) or Middle Low German ruffelen (“to wrinkle, curl”). Further origin unknown. Related to Middle Dutch ruyffelen, German Low German ruffeln. See English ruff.

RUGGED.d: Past tense of RUG: A partial covering for a floor.
RUGGED.e: Uncertain; probably of North Germanic origin; perhaps inherited via Middle English *rugge (suggested by Middle English ruggy (“hairy, shaggy, bristly”) and rugged (“hairy, shaggy, rugged”)), from Old Norse rǫgg (“shagginess, tuft”), from Proto-Germanic *rawwō (“long wool”), proba...

RUGGER.d: Comparative form of RUG: A partial covering for a floor.
RUGGER.e: Uncertain; probably of North Germanic origin; perhaps inherited via Middle English *rugge (suggested by Middle English ruggy (“hairy, shaggy, bristly”) and rugged (“hairy, shaggy, rugged”)), from Old Norse rǫgg (“shagginess, tuft”), from Proto-Germanic *rawwō (“long wool”), proba...

RUGOSE.d: Having rugae or wrinkles, creases, ridges, or corrugation.

RUINED.d: Past tense of RUIN: The remains of a destroyed or dilapidated construction, such as a house or castle.
RUINED.e: From Middle English ruyne, ruine, from Old French ruine, from Latin ruīna (“overthrow, ruin”), from ruō (“I fall down, tumble, sink in ruin, rush”).

RULING.d: That rules; predominant; chief; reigning; controlling.

RUMBLE.d: A low, heavy, continuous sound, such as that of thunder or a hungry stomach.
RUMBLE.e: From Middle English rumblen, romblen, rummelyn, frequentative form of romen (“to roar”), equivalent to rome + -le. Cognate with Dutch rommelen (“to rumble”), Low German rummeln (“to rumble”), German rumpeln (“to be noisy”), Danish rumle (“to rumble”), all of imitative origin.

RUMMER.d: Comparative form of RUM: A distilled spirit derived from fermented cane sugar and molasses.
RUMMER.e:
In common use since by at least 1654, of uncertain origin. Theories include:
* that it derives from rum (“fine, good”), or from the last syllable of Latin saccharum (given the harsh taste of earlier rum, the first theory is now considered unlikely),
* that it is a shortening of r...

RUMOUR.d: British, Canada, New Zealand, Australia, and Ireland spelling of rumor.
RUMOUR.e: From Middle English rumour, from Old French rumour, rumor, from Latin rūmor (“common talk”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *rewH- (“to shout, roar”).

RUMPLE.e: From Middle English rimplen (“to become wrinkled”). Compare German rumpeln (“to din, to make the welkin ring”) and Dutch rommelen (“to rumble”).

RUMPUS.d: A noisy, sometimes violent disturbance; noise and confusion; a noisy quarrel or brawl.
RUMPUS.e: Unknown. First use appears c. 1745. The OED indicates: "perhaps an arbitrary formation". Possibly an alteration of rumbustical or rumbustious (“boisterous, noisy”) + Latin -us (“nominative suffix”). The use of the verbal form first appears c. 1839.

RUNNEL.e: From Middle English runel, rennel, rinel, from Old English rynel (“that which runs; runner; stream”), from Proto-Germanic *runilaz, equivalent to run + -el. Cognate with Scots rinel, rinnal (“stream; runnel”), Swedish rännel (“runner; runnel”).

RUNNER.d: Agent noun of run; one who runs.
RUNNER.e: From Middle English rennere, rynner, urnare, equivalent to run + -er. Cognate with Old Norse rennari (“runner; messenger”). Displaced earlier Middle English runel (“runner”), from Old English rynel (“runner”; also “messenger, courier”).

RUNTED.d: Past tense of RUNT: The smallest animal of a litter.
RUNTED.e: The OED classifies this word as "of obscure origin". Some see a connection to Middle Dutch runt (“ox”), but the OED considers this to be unlikely.

RUNWAY.d: A defined, narrow section of land or an artificial structure used for access.

RUPIAH.d: The unit of currency in Indonesia.
RUPIAH.e: Borrowed from Indonesian rupiah, in turn from Sanskrit रूप्यक (rūpyaka, “silver coin”), from रूप्य (rūpya, “wrought silver”). Doublet of rupee and rufiyaa.

RUSHED.d: Past tense of RUSH: A sudden forward motion.
RUSHED.e: Perhaps from Middle English ruschen, russchen (“to rush, startle, make a loud rushing noise”), from Old English hrysċan (“to jolt, startle”), from Proto-West Germanic *hurskijan, from Proto-Germanic *hurskijaną (“to startle, drive”), from *hurskaz (“fast, rapid, quick”), from Pro...

RUSHES.d: Plural of RUSH: A sudden forward motion.
RUSHES.e: Perhaps from Middle English ruschen, russchen (“to rush, startle, make a loud rushing noise”), from Old English hrysċan (“to jolt, startle”), from Proto-West Germanic *hurskijan, from Proto-Germanic *hurskijaną (“to startle, drive”), from *hurskaz (“fast, rapid, quick”), from Pro...

RUSSET.e: From Middle English russet, from Anglo-Norman russet, rossat, roset, and Middle French rosset, rousset (“reddish, reddish-brown; a rough wool cloth”), from Middle French rous, rus (“to rouse”) + -et (diminutive suffix); compare Late Latin rossetum, russetum, russeta (“rough wool ...

RUSTED.d: Past tense of RUST: The deteriorated state of iron or steel as a result of moisture and oxidation; it consists mostly of iron(III) oxide (ferric oxide) and iron(II) oxide (ferrous oxide).
RUSTED.e:
From Middle English rust, rost, roust, from Old English rust, rūst (“rust”), from Proto-West Germanic *rust, from Proto-Germanic *rustaz (“rust”), from Proto-Indo-European *rudʰso- (“red”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rewdʰ- (“red”).
Cognate with Scots roust (“rust”), Saterland F...

RUSTIC.e: From Latin rūsticus. Doublet of roister.

RUSTLE.d: A soft crackling sound similar to the movement of dry leaves.
RUSTLE.e: From Middle English rustelen, russelen, of uncertain origin, but probably from Old English hrūxlian, hristlan, hrystlan, hristlian (“to make a noise”). Compare also Scots reesle (“to crackle; rattle; rustle”), West Frisian risselje, Dutch ritselen (“to rustle”), Afrikaans ritsel ...

RUSTRE.d: A lozenge with a smaller round hole in the centre, showing the field (rarely used).
RUSTRE.e: From French rustre, from German Raute.

RUTILE.d: The most frequent of the three polymorphs of titanium dioxide, crystalizing in the tetragonal system, TiO₂.
RUTILE.e: From Latin rutilus (“red”) because of its common color, named in 1803.

RUTTED.d: Past tense of RUT: Sexual desire in any of many mammals, often specific to mating season.
RUTTED.e: From Middle English rutte (noun) and rutten (verb), from Old French rut (“noise, roar, bellowing”), from Latin rugītus, from rugīre (“to roar”).

RUTTER.d: Comparative form of RUT: Sexual desire in any of many mammals, often specific to mating season.
RUTTER.e: From Middle English rutte (noun) and rutten (verb), from Old French rut (“noise, roar, bellowing”), from Latin rugītus, from rugīre (“to roar”).

RYOKAN.d: A traditional Japanese inn with communal baths and other public areas.
RYOKAN.e:
From Japanese 旅館(りょかん) (ryokan), which is from Middle Chinese 旅館 (MC ljoX kwanH, “inn, traveller's lodge”).
Compare modern Chinese 旅館／旅馆 (lǚguǎn, “hotel”), from 旅 (lǚ, “travel”) + 館／馆 (guǎn, “lodging-house”).

SABICU.d: a West Indian tree Lysiloma sabicu

SACHEM.d: A chief of one or several Native American tribe(s), especially of the Algonquians; a sagamore.
SACHEM.e: Borrowed from Narragansett sachem; compare Mi'kmaq saqamaw (“chief”) and Unami sakima (“chief”), all ultimately from Proto-Algonquian *sa·kima·wa. Doublet of sagamore.

SACHET.d: A small scented cloth bag filled with fragrant material such as herbs or potpourri.

SACKED.d: Past tense of SACK: A bag; especially a large bag of strong, coarse material for storage and handling of various commodities, such as potatoes, coal, coffee; or, a bag with handles used at a supermarket, a grocery sack; or, a small bag for small items, a satchel.
SACKED.e: From Middle English sak, sek, sach, zech (“bag, sackcloth”), from Old English sacc (“sack, bag”) and sæċċ (“sackcloth, sacking”); both from Proto-West Germanic *sakku, from late Proto-Germanic *sakkuz (“sack”), borrowed from Latin saccus (“large bag”), from Ancient Greek σάκκος (...

SACRED.d: Characterized by solemn religious ceremony or religious use, especially, in a positive sense; consecrated, made holy.
SACRED.e: From Middle English sacred, isacred, past participle of sacren, sakeren (“to make holy, hallow”), equivalent to sacre + -ed.

SACRUM.d: A large triangular bone at the base of the spine, located between the two ilia (wings of the pelvis) and formed from vertebrae that fuse in adulthood.
SACRUM.e: From Latin os sacrum (“holy bone”), a calque of Ancient Greek ἱερὸν ὀστέον (hieròn ostéon). Apparently so called either because the sacrum was the part of the animal offered in sacrifice or because of a putative belief that it is where a person's soul resides. A third explanation...

SADDEN.e: From Middle English saddenen, equivalent to sad + -en.

SADDER.d: Comparative form of SAD: Emotionally negative.
SADDER.e:
From Middle English sad, from Old English sæd (“satisfied, full, sated, unable to handle more, weary”), from Proto-West Germanic *sad, from Proto-Germanic *sadaz (“sated, satisfied”), from Proto-Indo-European *seh₂- (“to satiate, satisfy”).
Cognate to Saterland Frisian sääd, West...

SADDLE.d: A seat for a rider, typically made of leather and raised in the front and rear, placed on the back of a horse or other animal, and secured by a strap around the animal's body.
SADDLE.e: From Middle English sadel, from Old English sadol, from Proto-West Germanic *sadul, from Proto-Germanic *sadulaz (“saddle”). Further etymology uncertain, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *sod-dʰlo-, from *sed- (“to sit”) + *-dʰlom (a variant of *-trom (suffix forming nouns denoti...

SADISM.d: The enjoyment of inflicting pain or humiliation without pity.
SADISM.e: From French sadisme and German Sadismus. Named after the Marquis de Sade, famed for his libertine writings depicting the pleasure of inflicting pain to others. The word for "sadism" (sadisme) was coined or acknowledged in the 1834 posthumous reprint of French lexicographer Boiste...

SADIST.d: One who derives pleasure through cruelty or pain to others.
SADIST.e: From the name of the Marquis de Sade; see sadism.

SAFARI.d: A trip into any undeveloped area to see, photograph or to hunt wild animals in their own environment.
SAFARI.e: From Swahili safari (“journey”), from Arabic سَفَر (safar).

SAFETY.d: The condition or feeling of being safe; security; certainty.
SAFETY.e: Inherited from Middle English savete, from Old French sauveté, from earlier salvetet, from Medieval Latin salvitās, salvitātem, from Latin salvus.

SAGGAR.d: A ceramic container used inside a fuel-fired kiln to protect pots from the flame.
SAGGAR.e: Uncertain; possibly a contracted form of safeguard.

SAGGED.d: Past tense of SAG: The state of sinking or bending; a droop.
SAGGED.e:
From late Middle English saggen, probably of North Germanic/Scandinavian/Old Norse origin, akin to Old Norse sokkva (“to sink”), from a denasalized derivative of Proto-Germanic *sinkwaną (“to sink”).
Compare Norwegian Nynorsk sagga (“move slowly”)); probably akin to Danish and No...

SAILED.d: Past tense of SAIL: A piece of fabric attached to a boat and arranged such that it causes the wind to drive the boat along. The sail may be attached to the boat via a combination of mast, spars and ropes.
SAILED.e: From Middle English saile, sayle, seil, seyl, from Old English seġl, from Proto-West Germanic *segl, from Proto-Germanic *seglą. Cognate with West Frisian seil, Low German Segel, Dutch zeil, German Segel, Danish sejl, Swedish segel.

SAILOR.d: A person who sails; one whose occupation is sailing or navigating ships or other waterborne craft.
SAILOR.e: Alteration of earlier sailer, from Middle English sailer, sayler, saylere, equivalent to sail + -or. Cognate with German Segler (“sailor”). Eclipsed non-native Middle English marinel, marynell (“sailor”) borrowed from Old French marinel (“sailor”). See mariner.

SAINTS.d: Plural of SAINT: A holy person.
SAINTS.e: From Old French saint, from Latin sānctus.

SAITHE.d: The pollock or coalfish or coley (Pollachius virens).
SAITHE.e: From Old Norse seiðr; compare Norwegian sei and Swedish and Danish sej.

SALAAM.d: A respectful ceremonial greeting used mostly by Muslims.
SALAAM.e: From Arabic سَلَام (salām, “peace”). Doublet of shalom, a borrowing from Hebrew.

SALADE.d: Alternative form of sallet, a kind of helmet.

SALAMI.d: A large cured meat sausage of Italian origin, served in slices.
SALAMI.e: From Italian salami, plural of salame (“salami”), from sale (“salt”), from Latin sal.

SALARY.d: A fixed amount of money paid to a worker, usually calculated on a monthly or annual basis, not hourly, as wages. Implies a degree of professionalism and/or autonomy.
SALARY.e: From Middle English salarie, from Anglo-Norman salarie, from Old French salaire, from Latin salārium (“wages”), the neuter form of the adjective salārius (“related to salt”), from sal (“salt”). There have been various attempts to explain how the Latin term for “wages” came from t...

SALINA.d: A salt marsh, or salt pond, enclosed from the sea.

SALINE.e:
PIE word
 *séh₂ls
From Middle English salyne, from Medieval Latin salīna and Middle French salin, from Latin sal (“salt”).

SALIVA.d: A clear, slightly alkaline liquid secreted into the mouth by the salivary glands and mucous glands, consisting of water, mucin, protein, and enzymes. It moistens the mouth, lubricates ingested food, and begins the breakdown of starches.
SALIVA.e: A learned borrowing from Latin salīva (“spittle”), replacing or merging with Middle English salive, salve (“saliva”), from the same Latin source. Further origin uncertain. Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *salw-, *sal- (“dirt, dirty”), cognate with Old English salu (“dark, dusky”...

SALLET.d: A type of light spherical combat helmet used in the 15th century.
SALLET.e: From Middle French salade, from Spanish celada, thought to be from Latin caelāta (“ornamentally engraved (helmet)”) (although the Latin word is not attested in this sense).

SALLOW.e:
From Middle English salowe, from Old English salu, from Proto-West Germanic *salu, from Proto-Germanic *salwaz, from Proto-Indo-European *selH-.
See also Dutch zaluw, dialectal German sal; also Irish salach (“dirty”), Welsh halog, Latin salīva, Russian соло́вый (solóvyj, “cream-c...

SALMON.d: One of several species of fish, typically of the Salmoninae subfamily, brownish above with silvery sides and delicate pinkish-orange flesh; they ascend rivers to spawn.
SALMON.e: From Middle English samoun, samon, saumon, from Anglo-Norman saumon, from Old French saumon, from Latin salmō, salmōn-. Widely displaced native Middle English lax, from Old English leax (whence modern dialectal lax). The unpronounced l was later inserted to make the word appear c...

SALOON.d: A tavern, especially in an American Old West setting.
SALOON.e: From Occitan salon, French salon, either augmentative of salle (“room”), or borrowed from Italian salone (“hall”), augmentative form of sala, salla (“room”); in both cases borrowed from a Germanic source such as Old High German sal (“house, hall”), from Proto-Germanic *salą, from...

SALTED.d: Past tense of SALT: A common substance, chemically consisting mainly of sodium chloride (NaCl), used extensively as a food ingredient, seasoning, condiment, and preservative.
SALTED.e:
PIE word
 *séh₂ls
From Middle English salt, from Old English sealt, from Proto-West Germanic *salt, from Proto-Germanic *saltą, from Proto-Indo-European *séh₂ls (“salt”). Doublet of sal, ultimately from Latin sāl (“salt”), which it superseded as the general term for "salt".

SALTUS.d: A break of continuity in time.
SALTUS.e: From Latin saltus (“a leap”). Doublet of salto.

SALUKI.d: An ancient sighthound breed of dog with a silky coat originating in the Middle East, once sacred to the Egyptians.
SALUKI.e: From Arabic سَلُوقِيّ (salūqiyy). Doublet of sloughi.

SALUTE.d: An utterance or gesture expressing greeting or honor towards someone, (now especially) a formal, non-verbal gesture made with the arms or hands in any of various specific positions.
SALUTE.e: Borrowed from Latin salūtō (“to greet; to wish health to”), from salūs (“greeting, good health”), related to salvus (“safe”).

SALVIA.d: A plant in the genus Salvia, such as sage.
SALVIA.e: Borrowed from translingual Salvia, in turn from Latin salvia (“sage”). Doublet of sage.

SAMARA.d: The winged indehiscent fruit of trees such as the ash, elm or maple.
SAMARA.e: From Latin samara (“elm seed”), from a Gaulish term derived from Proto-Celtic *samos (“summer”).

SAMBAR.e: Borrowed from Hindi सांभर (sāmbhar), साँभर (sāmbhar), from Sanskrit शम्बर (śambara, “a kind of deer”).

SAMITE.d: A material of rich silk, sometimes with gold threads, especially prized during the Middle Ages.
SAMITE.e: From Old French samit, from Medieval Latin samitum, examitum, from Byzantine Greek ἑξάμιτον (hexámiton), from ἕξ (héx, “six”) + μίτος (mítos, “thread”).

SAMOSA.d: A South Asian snack consisting of a deep-fried triangular turnover filled with vegetables (especially potatoes) or meat.
SAMOSA.e:
Borrowed from Hindustani سموسہ (samosa) / समोसा (samosā), from Classical Persian سنبوسه (sanbōsa /⁠sambōsa⁠/), from Middle Persian *sambōsag.
Doublet of sambusa, sambusak, sambuseh, sambuusa, and samsa.

SAMPAN.d: A Chinese flat-bottomed wooden boat propelled by two oars.
SAMPAN.e: From Sinitic, likely Cantonese 三板 (saam¹ baan²) or Hokkien 舢板 (sam-pán).

SAMPLE.d: A part or snippet of something taken or presented for inspection, or shown as evidence of the quality of the whole; a specimen.
SAMPLE.e: Inherited from Middle English saumple, sample, from Old French essample (“example”), from Latin exemplum. Doublet of example and exemplum.

SANDAL.d: A type of open shoe made up of straps or bands holding a sole to the foot
SANDAL.e: From Middle English sandal (“sandal”), from Old French sandale, from Latin sandalium, from Ancient Greek σανδάλιον (sandálion), diminutive of σάνδαλον (sándalon, “sandal”), of unknown origin. Often mistakenly parsed as related to sand.

SANDED.d: Past tense of SAND: Rock that is ground more finely than gravel, but is not as fine as silt (more formally, see grain sizes chart), forming beaches and deserts and also used in construction.
SANDED.e:
From Middle English sond, sand, from Old English sand, from Proto-West Germanic *samd, from Proto-Germanic *samdaz, from Proto-Indo-European *sámh₂dʰos, from *sem- (“to pour”).
See also North Frisian sun, Sön, sönj (“sand”), Saterland Frisian Sound (“sand”), West Frisian sân (“sa...

SANDHI.d: Any of a wide variety of phonological processes that occur at morpheme or word boundaries, such as the fusion of sounds across word boundaries and the alteration of sounds due to neighboring sounds or due to the grammatical function of adjacent words.
SANDHI.e: Learned borrowing from Sanskrit संधि (saṃdhí, “junction, union”). Partial piecewise doublet of synthesis and synth.

SANELY.d: In a sane manner; sensibly; logically; rationally.

SANGAR.d: A stone breastwork; a fortified niche or look-out post.
SANGAR.e: From Pashto سنګر (sangar) or from Persian سنگر (sangar).

SANING.d: Present participle of SANE: Being in a healthy condition; not deranged; thinking rationally.
SANING.e: Learned borrowing from Latin sānus (“healthy; sane”). Doublet of sound.

SANITY.e: From Middle English sanite, sanyte, sanytee, from Middle French sanité, from Latin sānitās, from sānus (“healthy”) + -itās (“-ity”). By surface analysis, sane + -ity.

SAPELE.d: Entandrophragma cylindricum, a large tree native to tropical Africa.

SAPPED.d: Past tense of SAP: The juice of plants of any kind, especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating fluid essential to nutrition.
SAPPED.e: From Middle English sap, from Old English sæp (“juice, sap”), from Proto-West Germanic *sap (“sap, juice”) (compare Dutch sap, German Saft, Icelandic safi), from Proto-Indo-European *sab-, *sap- (“to taste”) (compare Welsh syb-wydd (“fir”), Latin sapa (“must, new wine”), Russian ...

SAPPER.d: Comparative form of SAP: The juice of plants of any kind, especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating fluid essential to nutrition.
SAPPER.e: From Middle English sap, from Old English sæp (“juice, sap”), from Proto-West Germanic *sap (“sap, juice”) (compare Dutch sap, German Saft, Icelandic safi), from Proto-Indo-European *sab-, *sap- (“to taste”) (compare Welsh syb-wydd (“fir”), Latin sapa (“must, new wine”), Russian ...

SARNIE.e: From sarn- (“perhaps from a dialectal pronunciation of the first syllable of sandwich”) + -ie. Alternatively, perhaps a misreading or an intentional dissimilation of samie (i.e. sammie), where the 'm' is mistaken for or replaced with 'rn'.

SARONG.d: A garment made of a length of printed cloth wrapped about the waist that is commonly worn by men and women in South and Southeast Asia, also in the Pacific islands.

SARSEN.d: Any of various blocks of sandstone found in various locations in southern England.

SASHED.d: Past tense of SASH: A piece of cloth designed to be worn around the waist.

SASHES.d: Plural of SASH: A piece of cloth designed to be worn around the waist.

SATEEN.d: A type of cotton cloth with a shiny surface and dull back, woven using the technique that, when applied to silk or nylon, results in cloth called satin.
SATEEN.e: A 19th century variant of satin, perhaps influenced by velveteen.

SATING.d: Present participle of SATE: To satisfy the appetite or desire of; to fill up.
SATING.e: Alteration (after words such as satiate and satisfy) of earlier sade (“to weary, satiate, satisfy”), from Middle English saden (“to weary, satisfy, become wearied or satiated”), from Old English sadian (“to satisfy, satiate, fill, be sated, become wearied”), from Proto-West Germa...

SATIRE.d: A literary device of writing or art which principally ridicules its subject often as an intended means of provoking or preventing change or highlighting a shortcoming in the work of another. Imitation, humor, irony, and exaggeration are often used to aid this.
SATIRE.e: From Middle French satire, from Old French, from Latin satira, from earlier satura, from lanx satura (“full dish”), from feminine of satur. Altered in Latin by influence of Ancient Greek σάτυρος (sáturos, “satyr”), on the mistaken notion that the form is related to the Greek σατυ...

SATORI.d: A sudden inexpressible feeling of spiritual awakening or enlightenment, the result of meditation and study.
SATORI.e: Borrowed from Japanese 悟り (satori, “understanding; (Buddhism) enlightenment, satori”), from 悟る (satoru, “to perceive; to comprehend, understand; to come to enlightenment”), from Middle Chinese 悟 (nguH, “to become aware, apprehend, realize; to awaken”) (modern Mandarin 悟 (wù)), us...

SATRAP.d: A governor of a Persian province.
SATRAP.e: From Middle English satrape, from Latin satrapēs (“governor”), from Ancient Greek σατράπης (satrápēs), from Old Median *xšaθrapāvan (literally “kingdom-protector”), which is cognate with Old Persian 𐎧𐏁𐏂𐎱𐎠𐎺𐎠 (xšaçapāvā); see there for more.

SAUGER.d: A freshwater perciform fish, of species Sander canadensis

SAVAGE.e: From Middle English savage, from Old French sauvage, salvage (“wild, untamed”), from Late Latin salvāticus, alteration of Latin silvāticus (“wild”, literally “of the woods”), from silva (“forest; grove”). Doublet of sylvatic.

SAVANT.d: A person of learning, especially one who is versed in literature or science.
SAVANT.e: Borrowed from French savant, from Latin sapiō. Doublet of sapient. Sense 3 is a clipping of idiot savant, literally ‘wise idiot’.

SAVING.d: Present participle of SAVE: To prevent harm or difficulty.
SAVING.e: From Middle English saven, sauven, a borrowing from Old French sauver, from Late Latin salvāre (“to save”).

SAVOUR.e: From Middle English savour, from Anglo-Norman saveur, savor, savour, and Old French saveur, savor, savour (modern French saveur), from Latin sapor, from sapiō (“to taste of (something); to have a flavour”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *seh₁p-, *sep- (“to taste; to try out...

SAWFLY.d: Any of various flying insects of the suborder Symphyta, within the order Hymenoptera, whose ovipositor is long and often serrated and is used to cut into plants to lay eggs.

SAWING.d: Present participle of SAW: A tool with a toothed blade used for cutting hard substances, in particular wood or metal.
SAWING.e:
The noun from Middle English sawe, sawgh, from Old English saga, sagu (“saw”), from Proto-West Germanic *sagu, from Proto-Germanic *sagô, *sagō (“saw”), from Proto-Indo-European *sek- (“to cut”).
Cognate with West Frisian seage (“saw”), Dutch zaag (“saw”), German Säge (“saw”), Da...

SAWLOG.d: The part of a tree stem that will be processed at a sawmill, rather than becoming pulpwood.

SAWYER.d: One who saws timber, especially in a sawpit.
SAWYER.e: From Middle English sawyer, sawier, sawior, equivalent to saw + -yer. Doublet of sawer.

SAXONY.d: A state of modern Germany, located in the east, far from historical Saxon lands. Official name: Free State of Saxony.
SAXONY.e: From Middle English Saxonie, from Latin Saxōnia, from Saxō (stem Saxōn-) + -ia. By surface analysis, Saxon + -y.

SAYING.d: present participle and gerund of say

SCABBY.d: Affected with scabs; full of scabs.
SCABBY.e: From Middle English scabby, scabbie, equivalent to scab + -y. Doublet of shabby.

SCALAR.e: Borrowed from Latin scālāris, adjectival form from scāla (“a flight of steps, stairs, staircase, ladder, scale”), for *scadla, from scandere (“to climb”); compare scale. The mathematics sense was coined by Irish mathematician and astronomer William Rowan Hamilton in 1846.

SCALED.d: Past tense of SCALE: A range of values; to climb.

SCALER.d: An electronic circuit that aggregates many signals into one.

SCALES.d: Plural of SCALE: A range of values; to climb.

SCAMPI.e: Borrowed from Italian scampi, plural of scampo (“prawn”).

SCANTY.d: Somewhat less than is needed in amplitude or extent.

SCARAB.d: A beetle of the species Scarabaeus sacer, sacred to the ancient Egyptians.
SCARAB.e: From Middle French scarabée, from Latin scarabaeus (“beetle”). Doublet of scarabaeus, now obsolete.

SCARCE.d: Uncommon, rare; difficult to find; insufficient to meet a demand.
SCARCE.e: From Middle English scars, scarse, from Old Northern French scars, escars ("sparing, niggard, parsimonious, miserly, poor"; > French échars, Medieval Latin scarsus (“diminished, reduced”)), of uncertain origin. One theory is that it derives originally from a Late Latin *scarpsus,...

SCATHE.e: From Middle English scath, scathe [and other forms], from Old Norse skaði (“damage, harm; loss; death; murder”), from Proto-Germanic *skaþô (“damage, scathe; one who causes damage, injurer”, noun) (whence Old English sċeaþa, sċeaþu (“scathe, harm, injury”)), from Proto-Indo-Europ...

SCENES.d: Plural of SCENE: A place where an event occurs; a view.
SCENES.e: From Latin scēna, from Greek skēnḗ.

SCHEMA.d: An outline or image universally applicable to a general conception, under which it is likely to be presented to the mind (for example, a body schema).
SCHEMA.e: Unadapted borrowing from Latin schēma, from Ancient Greek σχῆμα (skhêma, “form, shape”). Doublet of scheme.

SCHEME.d: An artful deviation from the ordinary arrangement of words.
SCHEME.e: Borrowed from Medieval Latin schēma (“figure, form”), from Ancient Greek σχῆμα (skhêma, “form, shape”), from ἔχω (ékhō, “I hold”). Doublet of schema. Compare sketch.

SCHISM.d: A split or separation within a group or organization, typically caused by discord.
SCHISM.e:
From Middle English scisme, from Old French cisme or scisme, from Ancient Greek σχίσμα (skhísma, “division”), from σχίζω (skhízō, “I split”). Doublet of schisma. Compare chasm.
This word was historically pronounced /ˈsɪzəm/ (and still is among the clergy); the pronunciations /ˈʃɪ...
