SCHIST.d: Any of a variety of coarse-grained crystalline metamorphic rocks with a foliated structure that allows easy division into slabs or slates.
SCHIST.e: From French schiste, from Latin schistos lapis (“the stone that is easy to split”), from Ancient Greek σχιστός (skhistós, “splittable”), from σχίζω (skhízō, “to split”).

SCHLEP.e:
From Yiddish שלעפּן (shlepn, “to drag”), from Middle High German slepen, from Middle Low German slêpen, from or related to Old High German sleifen (“to drag”) and slifan (“to slip”), from Proto-West Germanic *sleupan.
Compare German schleppen (“to haul”) and its inherited doublet...

SCHOOL.d: An institution dedicated to teaching and learning; an educational institution.
SCHOOL.e: From Middle English scole, from Old English scōl (“place of education”), from Proto-West Germanic *skōlu, from Late Latin schola, scola (“learned discussion or dissertation, lecture, school”), from Ancient Greek σχολή (skholḗ, “spare time, leisure”), from Proto-Indo-European *seǵ...

SCILLA.d: A plant of the genus Scilla; a squill.
SCILLA.e: Borrowed from Latin scilla, from Ancient Greek σκίλλα (skílla). Doublet of squill.

SCONCE.d: A fixture for a light, which holds it and provides a screen against wind or against a naked flame or lightbulb.
SCONCE.e: From Middle English sconce, sconse (“candlestick or lantern (with screen)”), from Old French esconse (“lantern”), from Latin absconsus (“hidden”), perfect passive participle of abscondō (“hide”). Cognate with abscond.

SCOPED.d: Past tense of SCOPE: The extent; an instrument for viewing.
SCOPED.e: From Italian scopo, from Greek skopós (target).

SCOPES.d: Plural of SCOPE: The extent; an instrument for viewing.
SCOPES.e: From Italian scopo, from Greek skopós (target).

SCORCH.e: From Middle English scorchen, scorcnen (“to make dry; parch”), perhaps an alteration of earlier *scorpnen, from Old Norse skorpna (“to shrivel up”).

SCORED.d: Past tense of SCORE: The number of points; to achieve.

SCORES.d: Plural of SCORE: The number of points; to achieve.

SCOTCH.e: From Middle English scocchen (“to cut”), perhaps from Anglo-Norman escocher (“to notch”), from es- (“intensive prefix”) (from Latin ex-) + Old French coche (“notch”). Not related to Scotch.

SCRAPE.d: To draw (an object, especially a sharp or angular one), along (something) while exerting pressure.
SCRAPE.e:
From Middle English scrapen, from Old Norse skrapa (“to scrape, scratch”) and Old English scrapian (“to scrape, scratch”), both from Proto-Germanic *skrapōną, *skrepaną (“to scrape, scratch”), from Proto-Indo-European *skrebʰ- (“to engrave”).
Cognate with Dutch schrapen (“to scra...

SCRAWL.e:
Possibly from Middle English scraulen (“to spread out one's limbs; sprawl”), itself an alteration of spraulen (“to sprawl”) or craulen, crawlen (“to crawl”).
Alternatively, from scrall, a contraction of scrabble.

SCREAM.d: A loud, emphatic, exclamation of extreme emotion, especially horror, fear, excitement, or anger; it may comprise a word or a sustained, high-pitched vowel sound.
SCREAM.e: From Middle English scremen, scræmen, probably from a fusion of Middle Dutch scremen (“to yell; shout”) and Old Norse skræma (“to terrify; scare”); compare Dutch schremen (“to shout; yell; cry”), Swedish skrämma (“to spook; frighten”), Danish skræmme (“to scare”), West Frisian sk...

SCREED.d: A piece of writing (such as an article, letter, or list) or a speech, especially if long.
SCREED.e: From Middle English screde [and other forms], a variant of shrede (“fragment, scrap; strip of cloth; strip cut off from a larger piece; band or thread woven into fabric; element, streak”) (whence shred (noun)), from Old English sċrēad, sċrēade (“a piece cut off; paring, shred”), ...

SCREEN.d: A physical divider intended to block an area from view, or provide shelter from something dangerous.
SCREEN.e: From Middle English scren, screne (“windscreen, firescreen”), from Anglo-Norman escren (“firescreen, the tester of a bed”), Old French escren, escrein, escran (modern French écran (“screen”)), from Middle Dutch scherm, from Old Dutch skirm, from Proto-West Germanic *skirmi, from ...

SCREWY.e: From screw + -y. 1820, original meaning “tipsy, slightly drunk”; meaning “crazy, ridiculous” first recorded 1887.

SCRIBE.d: Someone who writes; a draughtsperson; a writer for another; especially, an official or public writer; an amanuensis, secretary, notary, or copyist.
SCRIBE.e: From Middle English scribe, from Old French scribe (“scribe”), from Late Latin usage of scrība (“secretary”) (used in the Vulgate Bible translation to render Ancient Greek γραμματεύς (grammateús, “scribe, secretary”), which had been used in its turn to render the Hebrew סופר (“wr...

SCRIMP.e: From Scots scrimp (“meager”), from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German schrimpen (“to shrivel up, wrinkle”), from Old Dutch *scrimpan, from Frankish *skrimpan, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *skrimpaną (“to shrink”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to cut off”), related to Old ...

SCRIPT.e: From Middle English scrit, borrowed from Old French escrit, from Latin scriptum (something written), from scrībō (“write”).

SCROLL.d: A roll of paper or parchment; a writing formed into a roll.
SCROLL.e: From Middle English scrowle, scrolle, from earlier scrowe, scrouwe (influenced by Middle English rolle), from Old French escroe, escrowe, escrouwe (“scroll, strip of parchment”), from Frankish *skrōda (“a shred”), from Proto-Germanic *skraudō, from *skrew- (“to cut; cutting tool”...

SCROTA.d: plural of scrotum (“sac of skin and muscle enclosing the male testicles in mammals”)

SCRUMP.e: From a dialectal variation of scrimp, probably from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German schrimpen (“to shrivel up, shrink”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *skrimpaną, *skrimbaną (“to shrink”), related to Old English sċrimman (“to shrink, draw up, contract”). Related to dialectal E...

SCRYER.d: One who divines, sees or predicts the future by means of a scrying tool; especially a crystal ball.

SCULPT.e: From French sculpter, from Latin sculpō (“to cut out, carve in stone”).

SCURFY.d: Characterized by scurf; covered with scurf.

SCURRY.d: To run with quick light steps, to scamper.
SCURRY.e: Perhaps from hurry-skurry, a reduplication of hurry.

SCURVY.d: Affected or covered with scurf (“skin disease causing flakes of skin to fall off”) or scabs; scurfy, scabby; also, of or relating to a skin disease causing scurf or to scurvy (noun sense 1).
SCURVY.e: The adjective is derived from Late Middle English scurvi, scurvy, variants of scurfi (“having scurf, scabby”), from scurf (“skin disease causing scabs or scales; flakes of skin that fall off due to a skin disease, etc.”) + -i (suffix forming adjectives). Scurf is derived from Old...

SCUTCH.d: To beat or whip; to drub.
SCUTCH.e: From Middle English *scucchen, from Anglo-Norman escucher, from Vulgar Latin *excuticāre.

SCUTUM.d: An oblong shield made of boards or wickerwork covered with leather, with sometimes an iron rim; carried chiefly by the heavily armed infantry of the Roman army.
SCUTUM.e: Borrowed from Latin scūtum (“shield”). Doublet of escudo, scudo, scute, and écu.

SCUZZY.e: Probably a blend of scummy + fuzzy 1960s, US, colloquial, expressive coinage, with influence from scum, fuzzy, lousy, sleazy.

SCYTHE.d: An instrument for mowing grass, grain, etc. by hand, composed of a long, curving blade with a sharp concave edge, fastened to a long handle called a snath.
SCYTHE.e:
From Middle English sythe, sithe, from Old English sīþe, sīgþe, sigdi (“sickle”), from Proto-West Germanic *sigiþi, from Proto-Germanic *sigiþiz, *sigiþō, derived from *seg- (“saw”), from Proto-Indo-European *sek- (“to cut”).
Immediate Germanic cognates include Middle Low German ...

SEABED.d: The floor or bottom of the sea or ocean.

SEALED.d: Past tense of SEAL: A pinniped (Pinnipedia), particularly an earless seal (true seal) or eared seal.
SEALED.e: From Middle English sele, from an inflectional form of Old English seolh, from Proto-West Germanic *selh, from Proto-Germanic *selhaz (compare Scots selch,selkie, North Frisian selich, Middle Dutch seel, zēle, Old High German selah, Danish sæl, Middle Low German sale), Icelandic ...

SEALER.d: A tool used to seal something.

SEAMAN.d: Synonym of sailor, particularly on a maritime vessel.
SEAMAN.e: From Middle English seeman, seman, from Old English sǣmann. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Seemon (“seaman, sailor”), West Frisian seeman (“seaman, sailor”), Dutch zeeman (“seaman, sailor”), German Low German Seemann (“seaman, sailor”), German Seemann (“seaman, sailor”), Swedish ...

SEAMED.d: Past tense of SEAM: A folded-back and stitched piece of fabric; especially, the stitching that joins two or more pieces of fabric.
SEAMED.e: From Middle English seem, seme, from Old English sēam (“seam”), from Proto-West Germanic *saum, from Proto-Germanic *saumaz (“that which is sewn”).

SEARCH.e: From Middle English serchen, borrowed from Anglo-Norman sercher, Old French cerchier, from Late Latin circō, circāre (“to circle; go around; search for”), from Latin circa, circus. Not related to German suchen, which is cognate with English seek.

SEARED.d: Past tense of SEAR: Dry; withered, especially of vegetation.
SEARED.e:
From Middle English sere, seer, seere, from Old English sēar, sīere (“dry, sere, sear, withered, barren”), from Proto-West Germanic *sauʀ(ī), from Proto-Germanic *sauzaz (“dry”), from Proto-Indo-European *sh₂ews- (“dry, parched”) (also reconstructed as *h₂sews-).
Cognate with Dut...

SEASON.d: Each of the four divisions of a year: spring, summer, autumn (fall) and winter
SEASON.e: From Middle English sesoun, seson (“time of the year”), from Old French seson, saison (“time of sowing, seeding”), from Latin satiō (“act of sowing, planting”) from satum, past participle of serō (“to sow, plant”) from Proto-Indo-European *seh₁- (“to sow, plant”). Akin to Old Eng...

SEATED.d: Past tense of SEAT: Something to be sat upon.
SEATED.e:
From Middle English sete, from Old English sǣte, possibly from (or simply cognate with) Old Norse sæti (“seat”), both from Proto-Germanic *sētiją (“seat”), from Proto-Indo-European *sed- (“to sit”); compare Old English set (“seat”).
Sense 2 (“location or site”) is probably derive...

SEAWAY.d: A lane or route at sea that is regularly used by ships; a sea lane or trade route.
SEAWAY.e: From Middle English seewey, from Old English sǣweġ (“a seaway, a path through the sea”), equivalent to sea + way. Compare Saterland Frisian Seegong (“seaway, swell”), German Seegang (“seaway, swell”).

SECANT.d: A straight line that intersects a curve at two or more points.
SECANT.e: From Latin secāns, present participle of secō (“to cut”).

SECEDE.d: To split from or to withdraw from membership of a political union, an alliance or an organisation.
SECEDE.e: From Latin secedere, from se- (“apart”) + cēdō (“to go”).

SECOND.d: Number-two; following after the first one with nothing between them. The ordinal number corresponding to the cardinal number two.
SECOND.e: From Middle English secunde, second, secound, secund, borrowed from Old French second, seond, from Latin secundus (“following, next in order”), from root of sequor (“I follow”), from Proto-Indo-European *sekʷ- (“to follow”). Doublet of secund and secundo. Displaced native twoth a...

SECRET.d: A piece of knowledge that is hidden and intended to be kept hidden.
SECRET.e:
The noun is from Middle English secret, from Latin sēcrētum. Doublet of secretum. Displaced Old English dēagolnes (“a secret”).
The verb is from the noun.

SECURE.d: Free from attack or danger; protected.
SECURE.e: Borrowed from Latin sēcūrus (“of persons, free from care, quiet, easy; in a bad sense, careless, reckless; of things, tranquil, also free from danger, safe, secure”), from sē- (“without”) + cūra (“care”); see cure. Doublet of sure and the now obsolete or dialectal sicker (“certai...

SEDATE.d: Remaining composed and dignified, and avoiding too much activity or excitement.
SEDATE.e: The verb is first attested in 1646, the adjective in 1661; borrowed from Latin sēdātus, perfect passive participle of sēdō (“to settle”), see -ate (adjective-forming suffix) and -ate (verb-forming suffix).

SEDUCE.d: To beguile or lure (someone) away from duty, accepted principles, or proper conduct; to lead astray.
SEDUCE.e: Borrowed from Latin sēdūcō (“to lead apart or astray”), from sē- (“aside, away, astray”) + dūcō (“to lead”); see duct. Compare adduce, conduce, deduce, etc. and Middle English seduct.

SEEING.d: present participle and gerund of see

SEEMED.d: Past tense of SEEM: To appear; to look outwardly; to be perceived as.
SEEMED.e: From Middle English semen (“to seem, befit, be becoming”), from Old Norse sœma (“to conform to, beseem, befit”), from Proto-Germanic *sōmijaną (“to unite, fit”), from Proto-Indo-European *sem- (“one; whole”). Cognate with Scots seme (“to be fitting; beseem”), Danish sømme (“to be...

SEEMLY.d: Of behavior, appropriate; suited to the occasion or purpose; becoming.
SEEMLY.e: From Middle English semly, semely, semelich, from Old Norse sœmiligr (“seemly”); equivalent to seem + -ly. Cognate with Icelandic sæmilegur (“seemly, passable”), Danish sømmelig (“seemly”).

SEEPED.d: Past tense of SEEP: To ooze or pass slowly through pores or other small openings, and in overly small quantities; said of liquids, etc.
SEEPED.e:
Variant of sipe, from Middle English *sipen, from Old English sipian, from Proto-Germanic *sipōną, derivative of *sīpaną, from Proto-Indo-European *seyb-, *sib- (“to pour out, drip, trickle”).
See also Middle Dutch sīpen (“to drip”), German Low German siepern (“to seep”), archaic...

SEETHE.d: Of a liquid or other substance, or a container holding it: to be boiled (vigorously); to become boiling hot.
SEETHE.e: The verb is derived from Middle English sethen, seeth (“to boil, seethe; to cook; etc.”) [and other forms], from Old English sēoþan (“to boil, seethe; to cook; etc.”), from Proto-West Germanic *seuþan, from Proto-Germanic *seuþaną (“to boil, seethe”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂...

SEISIN.d: An entitlement to a freehold estate with a right to immediate possession.
SEISIN.e: From Middle English seisin, seysen, from Old French seisin, from the verb seisir, from Early Medieval Latin sacīre, from the same Proto-Indo-European root as Gothic 𐍃𐌰𐍄𐌾𐌰𐌽 (satjan) and Old English settan. More at seize, seise.

SELECT.e: From Latin sēlēctus, perfect passive participle of sēligō (“choose out, select”), from sē- (“without; apart”) + legō (“gather, select”).

SELFED.d: Past tense of SELF: Himself, herself, itself, themself, themselves; that specific (person mentioned).
SELFED.e: From Middle English self, silf, sulf, from Old English self, seolf, sylf, from Proto-Germanic *selbaz. Cognates include Gothic 𐍃𐌹𐌻𐌱𐌰 (silba), German selbst and Dutch zelf.

SELFIE.d: A photographic self-portrait, especially one taken manually (not using a timer, tripod etc.) with a small camera or mobile phone.
SELFIE.e: From self + -ie. Attested since 2002, originally Australian English.

SELLER.d: Someone who sells; a vendor; a clerk.
SELLER.e: From Middle English seller, sellere, (also siller, sullar, sullere), from Old English *sellere, *syllere, equivalent to sell + -er (agent noun) (sense 1) and sell + -er (patient) (sense 2). Cognate with Danish sælger, Swedish säljare, Icelandic seljari (“a seller; dealer”).

SELVES.d: Plural of SELF: Himself, herself, itself, themself, themselves; that specific (person mentioned).
SELVES.e: From Middle English self, silf, sulf, from Old English self, seolf, sylf, from Proto-Germanic *selbaz. Cognates include Gothic 𐍃𐌹𐌻𐌱𐌰 (silba), German selbst and Dutch zelf.

SENARY.e: From the Latin sēnārius (“consisting of six each”), from sēnī (“six each, six at a time”) + -ārius (whence the English suffix -ary).

SENATE.d: In some bicameral legislative systems, the upper house or chamber.
SENATE.e: From Middle English senat, from Old French senat, from Latin senātus (“council of elders; a senate”), from senex (“old”). Doublet of Senedd.

SENHOR.e: From Portuguese senhor. Doublet of seigneur, seignior, senior, señor, senyor, signore, sir, and sire.

SENILE.d: Of, or relating to old age.
SENILE.e: 1660s; borrowed from French sénile, from Middle French senile, from Old French senile, from Latin senīlis (“of or pertaining to old age”), from senex (“old man”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *sénos (“old”).

SENIOR.e: From Middle English senior, from Latin senior (“older”), comparative form of senex (“old”); see senate. Doublet of seigneur, seignior, senhor, señor, senyor, signore, sir, and sire.

SENNET.d: a signal call given on a cornet or trumpet for entrance or exit on a theatrical stage
SENNET.e: Probably an alteration of the obsolete signet (“signal”)

SENNIT.d: braided cord or fabric of such small stuff as plaited rope yarns
SENNIT.e: Perhaps from French coussinet, diminutive of coussin (“cushion”) because it is used to protect cables from fraying

SENSED.d: Past tense of SENSE: A faculty of perception; meaning.

SENSEI.d: A martial arts instructor; especially one for a Japanese martial art.
SENSEI.e: Borrowed from Japanese 先生(せんせい) (sensei, “teacher; elder”), from Middle Chinese 先生 (MC sen sraeng, “master, elder”), from 先 (MC sen, “earlier, first”) + 生 (MC sraeng, “born”). Compare modern Mandarin 先生 (xiānshēng, “Mr.”). Doublet of sinseh, from Hokkien 先生 (sin-seⁿ).

SENSES.d: Plural of SENSE: A faculty of perception; meaning.

SENSOR.d: A device or organ that detects certain external stimuli and responds in a distinctive manner.
SENSOR.e: Originated 1925–30, formed as a Latin loanword from sentiō (“to feel”) + -tor (“-er”). By surface analysis, sense + -or.

SENTRY.d: A guard, particularly on duty at the entrance to a military base.
SENTRY.e: From earlier sentrie, sentery, of uncertain origin. Perhaps an alteration of sentinel or sanctuary; or perhaps from Old French senteret (“a path”), diminutive of sentier, from Medieval Latin semitarius (“a path”).

SEPSIS.d: A serious medical condition in which the whole body is inflamed, causing injury to its own tissues and organs as a response to infection.
SEPSIS.e: coined by Hippocrates From Ancient Greek σῆψις (sêpsis, “putrefaction”), from σήπειν (sḗpein, “to make rotten”), from σήψ (sḗps, “a kind of lizard; also a kind of serpent whose bite was alleged to cause putrefaction”).

SEPTIC.e: From Ancient Greek σηπτικός (sēptikós, “characterized by putridity”), from σηπτός (sēptós), from σήπω (sḗpō).

SEPTUM.d: A wall separating two cavities; a partition.
SEPTUM.e: Borrowed from Latin sēptum (“enclosure, wall, fence”).

SEQUEL.d: The events, collectively, which follow a previously mentioned event; the aftermath.
SEQUEL.e: From Middle English sequele, sequelle, sequile, from Middle French sequele, sequelle and its etymon, Latin sequēla, from sequī (“to follow”). Doublet of sequela.

SEQUIN.d: Any of various small gold coins minted in Italy and Turkey.
SEQUIN.e: Borrowed from French sequin, from Italian zecchino, from zecca (“mint”), from Arabic سِكَّة (sikka, “die for coining, coin”). Doublet of zecchin.

SERANG.d: A native Indian boatswain; a lascar captain.

SERAPE.d: A type of blanket worn as a cloak, especially by Spanish-Americans, or used as a saddle blanket.

SERAPH.d: A burning serpent, often winged, with human hands and sometimes feet; one of God's entourage. On Earth, they strike with burning poison; in Heaven, with burning coal. A description can be found at the beginning of Isaiah chapter 6.
SERAPH.e:
Back-formation of singular from plural seraphim, from Latin seraphim, from Biblical Hebrew שְׂרָפִים (sərāp̄īm), plural form of שָׂרָף (sārāp̄). The plural "seraphims" occurs in the King James Bible (Isaiah chapter 6).
According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the singular "ser...

SERENE.e: From Middle English, borrowed from Latin serēnus (“clear, cloudless, untroubled”).

SERIAL.d: Having to do with or arranged in a series.
SERIAL.e: Formed as series + -al, on model of Latin seriālis, from seriēs + -ālis. Cognate to Italian seriale. First use appears c. 1823. See cite below.

SERIES.d: A number of things that follow on one after the other or are connected one after the other.
SERIES.e: Attested from the 1610s; borrowed from Latin seriēs, from serere (“to join together, bind”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ser- (“to bind, put together, to line up”). Related to desert, insert, sermon, and sorcerer.

SERINE.d: A nonessential amino acid, CH₂OH.CH(NH₂)COOH, found in most animal proteins, notably silk.
SERINE.e: From Latin sericus (“silken”). The compound was first obtained from silk protein, a particularly rich source, in 1865. See also serge.

SERING.d: Present participle of SERE: Without moisture; dry.
SERING.e: From Middle English ser, sere, seare, seer, seere, seir, seyr (“dry, withered; emaciated, shrivelled; brittle; bare; dead, lifeless; barren, useless”), from Old English sēar, sīere (“dry, withered; barren; sere”), from Proto-West Germanic *sauʀ(ī), from Proto-Germanic *sauzaz (“d...

SERMON.d: Religious discourse; a written or spoken address on a religious or moral matter.
SERMON.e: From Middle English sermoun, from Anglo-Norman sermun and/or Old French sermon, from Latin sermō, sermōnem, from Proto-Indo-European *sermō, from *ser- (“to bind”) + *-mō.

SERPIN.d: Any of a family of proteins that inhibit serine proteases (especially trypsin)

SERVAL.d: A medium-sized African wild cat, Leptailurus serval, formerly Felis serval.
SERVAL.e: From French serval, from Portuguese (lobo) cerval (“Iberian lynx”), from Latin lupus cervārius (literally “stag wolf”), i.e. "wolf that hunts stags", from cervus (“deer, stag”).

SERVED.d: Past tense of SERVE: To work for; to be useful.
SERVED.e: From Old French servir, from Latin servīre.

SERVER.d: A program that provides services to other programs or devices, either in the same computer or over a computer network.
SERVER.e: From Middle English servere, equivalent to serve + -er.

SERVES.d: Plural of SERF: A partially free peasant of a low hereditary class, attached like a slave to the land owned by a feudal lord and required to perform labour, enjoying minimal legal or customary rights.
SERVES.e: From Middle English serf, from Old French serf, from Latin servus (“slave, serf, servant”).

SESAME.d: A tropical Asian plant (Sesamum indicum) bearing small flat seeds used as food and as a source of oil.
SESAME.e: From late Middle English sisamie, from Latin sīsamum, sēsamum, from Ancient Greek σήσαμον (sḗsamon), from Aramaic שושמא (šūššmā), shortening of שומשומא (šumššumā), from Akkadian 𒊭𒈦𒌑𒈬 (šamaššammū, “oil plant”), compound of 𒉌𒄑 (šaman, “oil”) and 𒌑 (šammum, “plant”). The modern pron...

SETTEE.d: A long seat with a back, made to accommodate several persons at once; a sofa.
SETTEE.e: Unclear, possibly from settle (“seat, long bench”) + -ee (diminutive suffix).

SETTER.d: Comparative form of SET: To put (something) down, to rest.
SETTER.e: From Middle English setten, from Old English settan, from Proto-West Germanic *sattjan, from Proto-Germanic *satjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *sodéyeti, causative of *sed- (“to sit”).

SETTLE.e:
From a merger of two verbs:
* Middle English setlen, from Old English setlan (“to settle, seat, put to rest”), from Old English setl (“seat”) (compare Dutch zetelen (“to be established, settle”)) and
* Middle English sahtlen, seihtlen (“to reconcile, calm, subside”), from Old Eng...

SEVERE.e: From Middle French, from Latin severus (“severe, serious, grave in demeanor”).

SEWAGE.d: A suspension of water and solid waste, transported by sewers to be disposed of or processed.
SEWAGE.e: From sewer (“system of pipes used to remove human waste and to provide drainage”) + -age or from sew (“to drain or draw off water”) + -age.

SEWING.d: Present participle of SEW: To use a needle to pass thread repeatedly through (pieces of fabric) in order to join them together.
SEWING.e: From Middle English sewen, seowen, sowen, from Old English siwian, seowian, seowan (“to sew, mend, patch, knit together, link, unite”), from Proto-Germanic *siwjaną (“to sew”), from Proto-Indo-European *syewh₁- (“to sew”). Cognate with Scots sew, North Frisian saie, sei, Saterlan...

SEXIER.d: Comparative form of SEXY: Having sex appeal; attractive.

SEXINE.d: The outer part of the exine, the outer covering of a pollen grain

SEXING.d: Present participle of SEX: A category into which sexually-reproducing organisms are divided on the basis of their reproductive roles in their species; the system of such categories, which can differ by organism or by taxonomic branch.
SEXING.e: From Middle English sexe (“gender”), from Old French sexe (“genitals; gender”), from Latin sexus (“gender; gender traits; males or females; genitals”), from Proto-Italic *seksus, from Proto-Indo-European *séksus, from *sek- (“to cut, cut off, sever”), thus meaning "section, divis...

SEXISM.d: The belief that people of one sex (or gender) are inherently different from those of another sex, and generally that one sex is superior to others.

SEXTET.d: Any group of six people or things.
SEXTET.e: From French sextette, from Italian sestetto.

SEXTON.d: A church official who looks after a church building and its graveyard and may act as a gravedigger and bell ringer.
SEXTON.e: From Old French segrestien, from Medieval Latin sacristanus, based on Latin sacer (“sacred”). Doublet of sacristan.

SEXUAL.d: Arising from the fact of being male or female; pertaining to sex or gender, or to the social relations between the sexes.
SEXUAL.e: From Latin sexuālis, from sexus (“sex”), equivalent to sex + -ual.

SHABBY.d: Of clothing, a place, etc.: unkempt and worn or otherwise in poor condition due to age or neglect; scruffy.
SHABBY.e:
The adjective is derived from shab (“(obsolete except UK, dialectal) scaly skin disease; skin disease of sheep; crust forming over wound, scab”) + -y (suffix meaning ‘having the quality of’ forming adjectives).
The verb is derived from the adjective.
Cognates
* Dutch schabbig (“p...

SHADOW.d: A dark image projected onto a surface where light (or other radiation) is blocked by the shade of an object.
SHADOW.e: From Middle English schadowe, schadewe, schadwe (also schade > shade), from Old English sċeaduwe, sċeadwe, oblique form of sċeadu (“shadow, shade; darkness; protection”), from Proto-West Germanic *skadu, from Proto-Germanic *skadwaz (“shade, shadow”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s...

SHAGGY.d: Having long, thick, and uncombed hair, fur or wool.

SHAKTI.d: The Hindu concept or personification of the divine feminine aspect, sometimes referred to as 'The Divine Mother'. Shakti represents the active, dynamic principles of feminine power.

SHAMAN.e: Borrowed from German Schamane, from Russian шама́н (šamán), from Evenki шама̄н (şamān), сама̄н (samān), from Proto-Tungusic *samān. The Evenki word is possibly derived from the root ша- (şa-, “to know”); or else a loanword from Tocharian B ṣamāne (“monk”) or Chinese 沙門 /沙门 (shāmé...

SHAMMY.e: From chamois with an initial sh to represent the sound /ʃ/ in English.

SHANDY.d: A drink made by mixing beer and lemonade.

SHANTY.e:
From Canadian French chantier (“lumberjack's headquarters”). An alternative theory that the word derives from Irish seantí (meaning "old house") is not considered likely by lexicologists.
* (unlicensed pub): New Zealand from 1848.

SHAPED.d: Past tense of SHAPE: The external form; to mold.

SHAPER.d: Any agent that shapes (something), whether literally or figuratively.
SHAPER.e: From Middle English shapper, shapere, schapare, scaper, scheppere, schuppere, alteration (perhaps due to Old Norse skaperi, skapari) of Old English sċyppend, sċieppend (“shaper; maker; creator”), equivalent to shape + -er. Cognate with Dutch schepper, German Schöpfer, Danish skab...

SHAPES.d: Plural of SHAPE: The external form; to mold.

SHARED.d: Past tense of SHARE: A portion; to give a part of.

SHARES.d: Plural of SHARE: A portion; to give a part of.

SHARPS.d: Plural of SHARP: Having a cutting edge; quick-witted.

SHEATH.d: A holster for a sword; a scabbard.
SHEATH.e: From Middle English sheth, shethe (“holder for a sword, knife, etc., scabbard, sheath”) [and other forms], from Old English sċēaþ (“sheath”), from Proto-West Germanic *skaiþiju, from Proto-Germanic *skaiþiz (“sheath; covering”), from Proto-Indo-European *skey- (“to dissect, split...

SHEAVE.d: A wheel having a groove in the rim for a rope to work in, and set in a block, mast, or similar; the wheel of a pulley.
SHEAVE.e: From Middle English, from a Germanic base akin to German Scheibe, late Old Norse skífa (“slice”), all ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *skey- (“to split”). For more see shive.

SHEENY.e: Seems to have originated in 1820s London. Could be a mockery of Yiddish שיין (sheyn, “beautiful, nice”), much used in praising wares.

SHEETS.d: Plural of SHEET: A large piece of fabric; a piece of paper.

SHEKEL.d: A currency unit of both ancient and modern Israel.
SHEKEL.e: From Hebrew שֶׁקֶל (shékel, “shekel”), from שָׁקַל (shakál, “to weigh”), from Akkadian 𒂅 (šiqlum).

SHELLS.d: Plural of SHELL: A hard outer covering.

SHELVE.d: To furnish (a place) with shelves; especially, to furnish (a library, etc.) with bookshelves.
SHELVE.e:
The verb is a back-formation from shelves, the plural of shelf (“flat, rigid structure, fixed at right angles to a wall or forming a part of a cabinet, desk, etc., and used to display, store, or support objects”).
The noun is derived from sense 2 (“(obsolete) to hang over or proj...

SHERRY.d: A fortified wine produced in Jerez de la Frontera in Spain, or a similar wine produced elsewhere.
SHERRY.e: Back-formation of earlier sherris (interpreted as a plural), from Spanish (vino de) Xeres (“wine of Xeres”), Xeres being the former spelling of Jerez (pronounced /ʃeˈɾes/ in early modern Andalusian Spanish).

SHIELD.d: Anything that protects or defends; defense; shelter; protection.
SHIELD.e: From Middle English scheld, shelde, from Old English scield (“shield”), from Proto-West Germanic *skeldu, from Proto-Germanic *skelduz (“shield”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kelH- (“cut, split”). Cognate with West Frisian skyld, Dutch schild (“shield”), German Schild (“shield”)...

SHIEST.d: Superlative form of SHY: Easily frightened; timid.
SHIEST.e:
From Middle English shy (“shy”), from Old English sċēoh (“shy”), from Proto-West Germanic *skeuh (“shy, fearful”), from Proto-Germanic *skeuhaz (“shy, fearful”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian skjou (“shy”), Dutch schuw (“shy”), German scheu (“shy”), Danish sky (“shy”).
Etymology...

SHIFTS.d: Plural of SHIFT: To move; a change.

SHIFTY.d: Subject to frequent changes in direction.

SHIMMY.d: A dance move involving thrusting the shoulders back and forth alternately.
SHIMMY.e: A back-formation from chemise (mistaken for a plural).

SHINDY.e: Uncertain; compare shinney, shinty. Tentatively suggested to be a compound of the Irish words seinn (“play, sing”) and tí (“house”).

SHINED.d: Past tense of SHINE: To emit light; to excel.

SHINES.d: Plural of SHINE: To emit light; to excel.

SHINTY.d: A game derived from hurling, and resembling hockey, played in Scotland.

SHIRTS.d: Plural of SHIRT: A garment for the upper body.

SHIRTY.e: From shirt + -y, probably based on the phrase get one's shirt out.

SHISHA.e: Borrowed from Egyptian Arabic شيشة (šīša), from Ottoman Turkish شیشه şişe, from Classical Persian شیشه (šīša, “glass, mirror”).

SHITTY.e: From shit + -y. Cognate with German Low German schittig (“dirty, shitty”), German scheißig (“shitty”).

SHIVER.d: To tremble or shake, especially when cold or frightened.
SHIVER.e: Origin uncertain, perhaps an alteration of chavel, or a frequentive of sheaf.

SHOCKS.d: Plural of SHOCK: A sudden disturbance; to surprise.

SHODDY.e:
* Unknown, but possibly from shoad (“loose stone and rubble; fragments”), equivalent to shoad + -y; or possibly from the Arabic word for reuse. Shoad was of inferior quality for building.
* The modern adjectival sense was apparently derived from inexpensive shoddy (“fabric from w...

SHOFAR.d: A ram’s-horn trumpet, used for Jewish ritual purposes.

SHOGUN.d: The supreme generalissimo of feudal Japan.
SHOGUN.e: From Japanese 将軍 (shōgun), itself the short form of 征夷大将軍 (seii taishōgun, literally “general who overcomes the barbarians”), ultimately from Middle Chinese. Doublet of jiangjun.

SHOOED.d: Past tense of SHOO: To induce someone or something to leave.
SHOOED.e: From Middle English schew, schowe, show, showe, scou (“shoo!”, interjection). Compare Middle High German schū, schuo (“shoo!”, interjection) (modern German scheu! (“shoo!”)), Dutch schuwen (“to shun”), German scheuchen (“to scare, drive away”).

SHOOTS.d: Plural of SHOOT: To fire a weapon; to photograph.

SHORED.d: Past tense of SHORE: The land along the edge of water.

SHORES.d: Plural of SHORE: The land along the edge of water.

SHORTS.d: Plural of SHORT: Having little length; brief.

SHOULD.e: From Middle English scholde, from Old English sċolde, first and third person preterite form of sċulan (“should,” “have to,” “to owe”), the ancestor of English shall. By surface analysis, shall + -ed. Cognate with German sollte, Gothic 𐍃𐌺𐌿𐌻𐌳𐌰 (skulda), Swedish skulle. Related to M...

SHOVEL.d: A hand tool with a handle, used for moving portions of material such as earth, snow, and grain from one place to another, with some forms also used for digging. In strict usage differentiated from a spade, which is designed solely for small-scale digging and incidental tasks such as chopping of small roots.
SHOVEL.e:
From Middle English shovele, schovel, showell, shoule, shole (> English dialectal shoul, shool), from Old English scofl (“shovel”), from Proto-Germanic *skuflō, *skūflō (“shovel”), equivalent to shove + -el (instrumental/agent suffix).
Cognate with Scots shuffle, shule, shuil (“s...

SHOWED.d: Past tense of SHOW: To display, to have somebody see (something).
SHOWED.e: From Middle English schewen, from Old English scēawian (“to look, look at, exhibit, display”), from Proto-West Germanic *skauwōn, from Proto-Germanic *skawwōną (“to look, see”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewh₁- (“to heed, look, feel, take note of”); see haw, gaum, caveat, caut...

SHOWER.d: A brief fall of precipitation (spell of rain, or a similar fall of snow, sleet, or cascade); burst of hefty precipitation.
SHOWER.e: From Middle English schour, from Old English sċūr, from Proto-West Germanic *skūru, from Proto-Germanic *skūrō, probably from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ḱēwer- (“north; north wind; cold wind; rain shower”). Cognate with Dutch schoer, German Schauer, Old Norse skúr, Norwegian Bokmål ...

SHREWD.d: Showing clever resourcefulness in practical matters.
SHREWD.e:
From Middle English schrewed (“depraved; wicked”, literally “accursed”), from schrewen (“to curse; beshrew”), from schrewe, schrowe, screwe (“evil or wicked person/thing”), from Old English sċrēawa (“wicked person”, literally “biter”). Equivalent to shrew + -ed. More at shrew.
Th...

SHRIEK.d: A sharp, shrill outcry or scream; a shrill wild cry caused by sudden or extreme terror, pain, or the like.
SHRIEK.e: From obsolete shrick (1567), shreke, variants of earlier screak, skricke (before 1500), from Middle English scrycke, from a North Germanic/Scandinavian language (compare Swedish skrika, Danish skrige, Icelandic skríkja), from Proto-Germanic *skrīkijaną, *skrik- (compare English s...

SHRIFT.d: The act of going to or hearing a religious confession.
SHRIFT.e: From Middle English shrift (“confession to a priest; act or instance of this; sacrament of penance; penance assigned by a priest; penitence, repentance; punishment for sin”) [and other forms], from Old English sċrift (“penance, shrift; something prescribed as punishment, penalty;...

SHRIKE.d: Any of various passerine birds of the family Laniidae which are known for their habit of catching other birds and small animals and impaling the uneaten portions of their bodies on thorns.
SHRIKE.e: From Middle English *schrike, *schryke, from Old English sċrīc (“shrike, thrush”), from the same root as shriek and screech, named after the bird's cry. Compare Icelandic skríkja (“shrieker, shrike”), Swedish skrika (“jay”).

SHRILL.e: From Late Middle English schrille, shirle, shrille (“of a sound: high-pitched, piercing; producing such a sound”), possibly from the earlier shil, schille (“loud, resounding; high-pitched”), from Old English scill (“sonorous sounding”), of Germanic origin and probably ultimately ...

SHRIMP.d: Any of many swimming, often edible, crustaceans, chiefly of the infraorder Caridea or the suborder Dendrobranchiata, with slender legs, long whiskers and a long abdomen.
SHRIMP.e:
From Middle English schrimpe (“shrimp, puny person”), possibly from or related to Middle Low German schrempen (“to wrinkle”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *skrimpaz (“shrivelled”), from Proto-Germanic *skrimpaną (“to shrivel”), from Proto-Indo-European *skremb-, *skr̥mb-.
See a...

SHRINE.d: A holy or sacred place dedicated to a specific deity, ancestor, hero, martyr, saint, or similar figure of awe and respect, at which said figure is venerated or worshipped.
SHRINE.e: From Middle English shryne, from Old English scrīn (“reliquary, ark of the covenant”), from Medieval Latin scrīnium (“reliquary”), “case or chest for books or papers” in Classical Latin. Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to turn, bend”). Compare Old Norse skrín, Old ...

SHRINK.e:
From Middle English schrynken, from Old English sċrincan, from Proto-Germanic *skrinkwaną. Cognate with Dutch schrinken (“to shrink”).
The sense “psychologist, psychotherapist” is a clipping of head-shrinker.

SHRIVE.d: To hear or receive a confession (of sins etc.).
SHRIVE.e: From Middle English shryven, shriven, schrifen, from Old English sċrīfan (“1. to decree, pass judgement, prescribe, 3. (of a priest) to prescribe penance or absolution”), from Proto-West Germanic *skrīban, from late Proto-Germanic *skrībaną, a borrowing from Latin scrībō (“write”...

SHROUD.d: That which clothes, covers, conceals, or protects; a garment.
SHROUD.e: From Middle English shroud, from Old English sċrūd, from Proto-Germanic *skrūdą. Cognate with Old Norse skrúð (“the shrouds of a ship”) ( > Danish, Norwegian skrud (“splendid attire”)).

SHTICK.e: Borrowed from Yiddish שטיק (shtik, “shtick, act, piece”). Cognate with German Stück, Dutch stuk. Doublet of shtuka, steck, and styca.

SHUFTI.e: UK 1940s, originally military slang. From Egyptian Arabic شُفْتِ، شُفْتِي (šufti, “have you seen?”, literally “you saw”), a conjugation of شَاف (šāf, “to see”).

SHYING.d: Present participle of SHY: Easily frightened; timid.
SHYING.e:
From Middle English shy (“shy”), from Old English sċēoh (“shy”), from Proto-West Germanic *skeuh (“shy, fearful”), from Proto-Germanic *skeuhaz (“shy, fearful”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian skjou (“shy”), Dutch schuw (“shy”), German scheu (“shy”), Danish sky (“shy”).
Etymology...

SIBBED.d: Past tense of SIB: Having kinship or relationship; related by same-bloodedness; kindred.
SIBBED.e: From Middle English sib, from Old English sibb (“related, akin, sib”), from Proto-Germanic *sibjaz (“related”), from Proto-Indo-European *sebʰ-, *swebʰ- (“one's own”). Cognate with West Frisian besibbe (“related”), Middle Dutch sibbe (“related”), Middle Low German sibbe (“related...

SIBBER.d: Comparative form of SIB: Having kinship or relationship; related by same-bloodedness; kindred.
SIBBER.e: From Middle English sib, from Old English sibb (“related, akin, sib”), from Proto-Germanic *sibjaz (“related”), from Proto-Indo-European *sebʰ-, *swebʰ- (“one's own”). Cognate with West Frisian besibbe (“related”), Middle Dutch sibbe (“related”), Middle Low German sibbe (“related...

SICCED.d: Past tense of SIC: Thus; as written; used to indicate, for example, that text is being quoted as it is from the source.
SICCED.e: Learned borrowing from Latin sīc (“thus, so”).

SICKED.d: Past tense of SICK: In poor health; ill.
SICKED.e:
From Middle English sik, sike, seek, seke, seok, from Old English sēoc (“sick, ill”), from Proto-West Germanic *seuk, from Proto-Germanic *seukaz, from Proto-Indo-European *sewg- (“to be troubled or grieved”).
See also West Frisian siik, Dutch ziek, German siech, Norwegian Bokmål...

SICKEN.e: From Middle English sekenen, equivalent to sick + -en. Cognate with Danish sygne (“to pine”), Swedish sjukna (“to fall ill; become sick”), Norwegian sykne, Icelandic sjúkna (“to sicken; become sick”).

SICKIE.d: A day, or time, off work due to (supposed) illness.

SICKLE.d: An implement having a semicircular blade and short handle, used for cutting long grass and cereal crops.
SICKLE.e: From Middle English sikel (also assibilated in sichel), from Old English sicol, siċel, from Proto-West Germanic *sikilu, itself borrowed from Latin sēcula (“sickle”) or sīcīlis (“sickle”). Cognate with Dutch sikkel, German Sichel. Remotely related with English scythe and saw.

SICKLY.d: Frequently ill or in poor health; weakly.
SICKLY.e: From Middle English seekly, sekely, siklich, sekeliche, equivalent to sick + -ly. Possibly a modification of Old English sīcle (“sickly”) and/or derived from Old Norse sjúkligr (“sickly”). Cognate with Dutch ziekelijk, Middle High German siechlich, Danish sygelig, Swedish sjuklig...

SIDDHA.d: One who has achieved a high degree of physical and spiritual development.

SIDING.d: A building material which covers and protects the sides of a house or other building.

SIENNA.d: A form of clay containing iron and manganese.
SIENNA.e: From Italian terra di Siena (“earth of Siena”), Siena being the most notable Renaissance location of the clay.

SIERRA.e: Borrowed from Spanish sierra, from Latin serra (“saw”), referring to the saw-tooth profile of the crestline of the range seen from a distance.

SIESTA.d: A nap, especially an afternoon one taken during the hottest part of the day in some cultures.
SIESTA.e: Borrowed from Spanish siesta, from Latin sexta (“the sixth hour from dawn, noon, midday”). Doublet of sext.

SIFAKA.d: Any of several endangered medium-sized lemurs that comprise genus Propithecus.

SIFTED.d: Past tense of SIFT: To sieve or strain (something).
SIFTED.e: From Middle English syften, from Old English siftan, from Proto-West Germanic *siftijan.

SIGGER.d: Comparative form of SIG: A signature, especially one on emails or newsgroup postings.

SIGHED.d: Past tense of SIGH: To inhale a larger quantity of air than usual, and immediately expel it; to make a deep single audible respiration, especially as the result or involuntary expression of fatigue, exhaustion, grief, sorrow, frustration, or the like.
SIGHED.e: From Middle English sighen (“to sigh”), back-formation from sighte, past tense form of siken, from Old English sīcan, from Proto-West Germanic *sīkan, perhaps ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *seykʷ- (“to pour out”).

SIGHTS.d: Plural of SIGHT: The faculty of seeing; a view.

SIGLUM.d: A letter or other symbol that stands for a name or word; specifically, one used in a modern literary work to refer to an early version of a text.
SIGLUM.e:
Learned borrowing from Late Latin siglum (“abbreviation”), possibly a contracted form of:
* sigillum (“figurine, statuette; seal”), from signum (“figure, statue; seal, signet; mark, sign”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *sek- (“to cut, sever; to cut off”) or *sekʷ- (“to fol...

SIGNAL.d: A sequence of states representing an encoded message in a communication channel.
SIGNAL.e: From Old French segnal, seignal or Medieval Latin signāle; noun use of the neuter of Late Latin signālis, from Latin signum; verb use from 1805, as a shortened from signalize (1650s).

SIGNET.d: An object (especially a ring) formerly used to impress a picture into the sealing wax of a document as a proof of its origin.
SIGNET.e: From Old French signet (“small seal”), from Medieval Latin signētum, diminutive of Latin signum (“sign”).

SIGNOR.d: Alternative form of signore, a courtesy title used towards an Italian man.
SIGNOR.e: Borrowed from Italian signor, apocopic form of signore. Doublet of senior and señor.

SIGNUM.e: Learned borrowing from Latin signum. Doublet of sign.

SILAGE.d: Fermented green forage fodder stored in an airtight silo or clamp.
SILAGE.e: Alteration (probably by influence of silo) of ensilage (1881), itself from French ensilage, from ensiler (“put in a silo”), from Spanish ensilar.

SILANE.d: Any of a group of silicon hydrides that are analogous to alkanes (the paraffin hydrocarbons); especially the parent compound SiH₄.

SILENT.d: Free from sound or noise; absolutely still; perfectly quiet.
SILENT.e: From Latin silēns (“silent”), present participle of sileō (“be silent”), from Proto-Indo-European *seyl- (“still, windless, quiet, slow”). Related to Gothic 𐌰𐌽𐌰𐍃𐌹𐌻𐌰𐌽 (anasilan, “to cease, grow still, be silent”), Old English sālnes (“silence”).

SILICA.e: From New Latin silica, from Latin silex (“hard stone, flint”), on model of alumina, soda.

SILKED.d: Past tense of SILK: A fine fiber excreted by the silkworm or other arthropod (such as a spider).
SILKED.e: From Middle English silk, sylk, selk, selc, from Old English sioloc, seoloc, seolc (“silk”). The immediate source is uncertain; it probably reached English via the Baltic trade routes (cognates in Old Norse silki (> Danish silke, Swedish silke (“silk”)), Russian шёлк (šolk), obso...

SILOED.d: Past tense of SILO: A vertical building, usually cylindrical, used for the production of silage.
SILOED.e: From Spanish silo, of unclear origin. See Spanish silo for more.

SILTED.d: Past tense of SILT: Mud or fine earth deposited from running or standing water.
SILTED.e:
PIE word
 *séh₂ls
From Middle English silte, cilte, cylte, perhaps from Middle English silen ("to filter; strain"; equivalent to sile + -t), or cognate with Norwegian and Danish sylt (“salt marsh”), Middle Low German sulte (“salt-marsh”), German Sülze (“meat in aspic”), ultimatel...

SILVER.d: A lustrous, white, metallic element, atomic number 47, atomic weight 107.87, symbol Ag.
SILVER.e:
From Middle English silver, selver, sulver, from Old English seolfor, from Proto-West Germanic *silubr, from Proto-Germanic *silubrą (“silver”), of uncertain origin.
cognates and etymology discussion
Cognate with Scots siller (“silver”), Saterland Frisian Säälwer (“silver”), West...

SIMIAN.d: Of or pertaining to apes and monkeys.
SIMIAN.e: From Latin sīmia (“ape, monkey”), from Ancient Greek σιμός (simós, “snub-nosed”).

SIMILE.d: A figure of speech in which one thing is explicitly compared to another, using e.g. like or as.
SIMILE.e: From Latin simile (“comparison, likeness, parallel”) (first attested 1393), originally from simile, neuter form of similis (“like, similar, resembling”). Compare English similar.

SIMMER.d: To cook or undergo heating slowly at or below the boiling point.
SIMMER.e: From alteration of dialectal simper, from Middle English simperen (“to simmer”), of possibly imitative origin. First attested in the intransitive sense. The noun is from the verb. First attested in the late 15ᵗʰ century.

SIMONY.d: The buying or selling of spiritual or sacred things, such as ecclesiastical offices, pardons, or consecrated objects.
SIMONY.e: From Old French simonie, from Late Latin simonia, named after Simon Magus (Hebrew שִׁמְעוֹן (Šimʻôn, “Simon”)), with reference to Acts 8:18–20.

SIMOOM.d: A hot, dry, suffocating, dust-laden wind of the desert, particularly of Arabia, Syria, and neighboring countries, generated by the extreme heat of the parched deserts or sandy plains.
SIMOOM.e: From Arabic سَمُوم (samūm, “hot wind”), from سَمَّ (samma, “to poison”).

SIMPER.d: To smile in a foolish, frivolous, self-conscious, coy, obsequious, or smug manner.
SIMPER.e: Uncertain; compare (probably from) Danish simper / semper (“coy”), German zimper (“elegant, dainty”).

SIMPLE.d: Uncomplicated; lacking complexity; taken by itself, with nothing added.
SIMPLE.e: Inherited from Middle English symple, simple, from Old French and French simple, from Latin simplex (“simple”, literally “onefold”) (as opposed to duplex (“double”, literally “twofold”)), from semel (“the same”) + plicō (“I fold”). See same and fold. Compare single, singular, sim...

SINFUL.e: From Middle English synful, senful, sunful, from Old English synful (“sinful, guilty, wicked, corrupt”), equivalent to sin + -ful. Compare Dutch zondevol (“sinful”), German sündevoll (“sinful”), Danish syndefuld (“sinful”), Swedish syndfull (“sinful”), Icelandic syndfullur (“sinf...

SINGLE.d: Not accompanied by anything else; one in number.
SINGLE.e: From Middle English single, sengle, from Old French sengle, saingle, sangle, from Latin singulus, a diminutive derived from Proto-Indo-European *sem- (“one”). Akin to Latin simplex (“simple”). See simple, and compare singular.

SINKED.d: Past tense of SINK: To move or be moved into something.
SINKED.e:
From Middle English synken, from Old English sincan, from Proto-West Germanic *sinkwan, from Proto-Germanic *sinkwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *sengʷ- (“to fall, sink”).
Compare West Frisian sinke, Low German sinken, Dutch zinken, German sinken, Danish and Norwegian Bokmål synke...

SINNED.d: Past tense of SIN: A violation of divine will or religious law.
SINNED.e: From Middle English sinne, synne, sunne, zen, from Old English synn (“sin”), from Proto-West Germanic *sunnju, from Proto-Germanic *sunjō (“truth, excuse”) and *sundī, *sundijō (“sin”), from , from *h₁sónts ("being, true", implying a verdict of "truly guilty" against an accusatio...

SINNER.d: Comparative form of SIN: A violation of divine will or religious law.
SINNER.e: From Middle English sinne, synne, sunne, zen, from Old English synn (“sin”), from Proto-West Germanic *sunnju, from Proto-Germanic *sunjō (“truth, excuse”) and *sundī, *sundijō (“sin”), from , from *h₁sónts ("being, true", implying a verdict of "truly guilty" against an accusatio...

SINTER.d: An alluvial sediment deposited by a mineral spring.
SINTER.e: From German Sinter. Doublet of cinder.

SIPHON.d: A bent pipe or tube with one end lower than the other, in which hydrostatic pressure exerted due to the force of gravity moves liquid from one reservoir to another.
SIPHON.e: From Middle French siphon, from Old French sifon, from Latin sipho, from Ancient Greek σίφων (síphōn, “pipe, tube”), of uncertain origin; possibly related to Latin tibia (“pipe, flute of bone”), with the irregular forms suggesting a non-Indo-European loan source, perhaps of the s...

SIPING.d: Present participle of SIPE: Slit in a tire to drain away surface water and improve traction.
SIPING.e:
From Old English sipian, related to seep.
* around 888 AD, K Aelfred, translation of Boethius, Chapter 33, para.5 ,
: "Seo eorþe hit helt & be sumum dæle swilgþ, & for þam sype heo biþ geleht."

SIPPED.d: Past tense of SIP: A small mouthful of drink
SIPPED.e: Inherited from Middle English sippen, of uncertain origin. Compare with Low German sippen (“to sip”). Possibly from a variant of Middle English suppen (“to drink, sip”) (see sup) or perhaps from Old English sipian, sypian (“to take in moisture, soak, macerate”), from Proto-German...

SIPPER.d: Comparative form of SIP: A small mouthful of drink
SIPPER.e: Inherited from Middle English sippen, of uncertain origin. Compare with Low German sippen (“to sip”). Possibly from a variant of Middle English suppen (“to drink, sip”) (see sup) or perhaps from Old English sipian, sypian (“to take in moisture, soak, macerate”), from Proto-German...

SIPPET.d: A small piece of something, especially a piece of toast or fried bean eaten with soup or gravy.
SIPPET.e: First attested in the 16th century, as a diminutive of sop. See -et.

SIRDAR.d: A high-ranking person in India and other areas of west-central Asia; a chief, a headman.
SIRDAR.e: Borrowed from Urdu سردار, Hindi सरदार (sardār), from Persian سردار (sardâr). Doublet of serdar and Sardar.

SIRING.d: Present participle of SIRE: A lord, master, or other person in authority, most commonly used vocatively: formerly in speaking to elders and superiors, later only when addressing a sovereign.
SIRING.e: From Middle English sire, from Old French sire, the nominative singular of seignor; from Latin senior, from senex. Doublet of seigneur, seignior, senhor, senior, señor, senyor, signore, and sir. Cognate with French monsieur.

SIRRAH.d: A term of address to an inferior male or more commonly a child. A modern-day equivalent would be "little man".
SIRRAH.e: An extended form of sir; the source of the final vowel is unclear. See also siree.

SISKIN.d: A small green and yellow European finch, Carduelis spinus spinus or Carduelis spinus, now Spinus spinus.
SISKIN.e: From dialectal German Sisschen, Zeischen, diminutive form of Middle High German zīsec, apparently ultimately from Proto-Slavic *čižь (compare e.g. Polish czyżyk).

SISSOO.d: A leguminous tree (Dalbergia sissoo) of northern India.
SISSOO.e: From Hindi [Term?] / Urdu [Term?]. Doublet of shisham.

SISTER.d: A daughter of the same parents as another person; a female sibling.
SISTER.e:
PIE word
 *swésōr
From Middle English sister, suster, from Old English swustor, sweoster, sweostor (“sister, nun”); from Proto-Germanic *swestēr (“sister”), from Proto-Indo-European *swésōr (“sister”).
Doublet of soror. Cognate with Scots sister, syster (“sister”), West Frisian s...

SITING.d: Present participle of SITE: The place where anything is fixed; situation; local position
SITING.e: From Middle English site, from Anglo-Norman site, from Latin situs (“position, place, site”), from sinere (“to put, lay, set down, usually let, suffer, permit”). Doublet of sitio and situs.

SITREP.d: A situation report: a periodic report on the current military situation.

SITTER.d: Comparative form of SIT: To be in a position in which the upper body is upright and supported by the buttocks.
SITTER.e: From Middle English sitten, from Old English sittan, from Proto-West Germanic *sittjan, from Proto-Germanic *sitjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *sed- (“sit”).

SIXING.d: Present participle of SIX: A numerical value equal to 6; the number following five and preceding seven. This number of dots: (••••••).
SIXING.e:
PIE word
 *swéḱs
From Middle English six, from Old English six, from Proto-West Germanic *sehs, from Proto-Germanic *sehs, from Proto-Indo-European *swéḱs. Compare West Frisian seis, Dutch zes, Low German söss, sess, German sechs, Norwegian and Danish seks, also Latin sex, Ancien...

SIXTHS.d: Plural of SIXTH: The ordinal number 6th.

SIZING.d: Present participle of SIZE: The dimensions or magnitude of a thing; how big something is.
SIZING.e: Attested since the 14th century, originally meant a “law or regulation that determines the amount to be paid”, from Middle English syse, sise (“regulation, control, limit”), from Old French cise, sise, aphetism of assise (“assize”), from the verb asseoir (“to sit down”), from Lat...

SIZZLE.d: To make the sound of water boiling on a hot surface.
SIZZLE.e: Probably a derivative of Middle English sissen (“to hiss; buzz; hum”), equivalent to siss + -le (frequentative suffix).

SKERRY.d: A small rocky island which may be covered by the sea at high tide or during storms.
SKERRY.e: From dialectal Scots (Shetlandic and Orcadian) skerry, from Old Norse sker (whence Danish skær and Norwegian Bokmål skjær).

SKETCH.d: To make a brief, basic drawing.
SKETCH.e: From Dutch schets or German Skizze, from Italian schizzo, from Latin schedium, from Ancient Greek σχέδιος (skhédios, “made suddenly, off-hand”), from σχεδόν (skhedón, “near, nearby”), from ἔχω (ékhō, “I hold”). Compare scheme.

SKEWED.d: Past tense of SKEW: To form or shape in an oblique way; to cause to take an oblique position.
SKEWED.e: The verb is derived from Middle English skeuen, skewe, skewen (“to run at an angle or obliquely; to escape”), from Old Northern French escuer [and other forms], variants of Old French eschuer, eschever, eschiver (“to escape, flee; to avoid”) (modern French esquiver (“to dodge (a ...

SKEWER.d: A long pin, normally made of metal or wood, used to secure food during cooking.
SKEWER.e: From Middle English skeuier, skuer, likely a variant of Middle English *skever, *skiver (compare Modern English skiver), probably of North Germanic origin, compare Icelandic skífa (“to slice”), Norwegian skive, Swedish skiva, Swedish skifer (“a slate”).

SKIBOB.d: A bicycle-type frame attached to skis instead of wheels, used in the sport of skibobbing.

SKIING.d: Present participle of SKI: One of a pair of long flat runners designed for gliding over snow or water.
SKIING.e: From Norwegian ski, from Old Norse skíð (“stick of wood, snowshoe”), from Proto-Germanic *skīdą (“stick”), from Proto-Indo-European *skey- (“to cut, split”) (see also shed). Cognate with Old English sċīd (“stick of wood”) (modern shide), Old High German skit (Modern German Scheit...

SKILLS.d: Plural of SKILL: The ability to do something well.

SKIMPY.d: Small or inadequate; not generous; diminutive.

SKINNY.d: Thin, generally in a negative sense (as opposed to slim, which is thin in a positive sense).
SKINNY.e: From Middle English skinny (“resembling skin”), equivalent to skin + -y. The meaning associated with lack of fat or muscle possibly derives from the phrase skin and bones; the meaning associated with nudity refers to the exposed skin.

SKIVVY.d: A female domestic servant, especially one employed for menial work.

SKYING.d: Present participle of SKY: The atmosphere above a given point, especially as visible from the surface of the Earth as the place where the sun, moon, stars, and clouds are seen.
SKYING.e: The noun is derived from Middle English sky (“sky; cloud; mist”), also spelled ski, skie, [and other forms], from Old Norse ský (“cloud”), from Proto-Germanic *skiwją (“cloud; sky”), from *skiwô (“cloud; cloud cover, haze; sky”) (whence Old English sċēo (“cloud”) and Middle Engli...

SLALOM.d: The sport of skiing in a zigzag course through gates.
SLALOM.e: From Norwegian sla (“steep, hill side”) and låm (“trail”).

SLATER.d: One who lays slates, or whose occupation is to slate buildings.
SLATER.e: From Middle English sclater, equivalent to slate + -er.

SLAVER.d: To drool saliva from the mouth; to slobber.
SLAVER.e: From Middle English slaveren, from Old Norse slafra (“to slaver”), probably imitative. Doublet of slabber.

SLAYED.d: Past tense of SLAY: To kill; to murder.
SLAYED.e:
From Middle English sleen, slayn, from Old English slēan (“to strike, beat, smite, stamp, forge, sting, slay, kill, impact”), from Proto-West Germanic *slahan, from Proto-Germanic *slahaną (“to fight, strike, kill”), from Proto-Indo-European *slak- (“to hit, strike, throw”).
Cogn...

SLEAZE.e: Back-formation from sleazy, originally used to describe the thinness and low quality of cloth.

SLEAZY.d: Marked by low quality; inferior; inadequate.
SLEAZY.e: Origin obscure. Possibly a corruption of Silesia, through a word meaning Silesian cloth. Silesia was formerly the most important location of Germany’s weaving industry.

SLEDGE.d: A heavy, long handled maul or hammer used to drive stakes, wedges, etc.
SLEDGE.e: From Middle English slegge, from Old English sleċġ (“sledgehammer; mallet”), from Proto-Germanic *slagjǭ. Cognate with Dutch slegge (“sledge”), Swedish slägga (“sledge”), Norwegian Bokmål slegge (“sledge”), Norwegian Nynorsk sleggje (“sledge”), Icelandic sleggja (“sledge”), Germa...

SLEEPS.d: Plural of SLEEP: A state of rest with reduced consciousness.

SLEEPY.d: Tired; feeling the need for sleep.
SLEEPY.e: From Middle English slepy, from Old English *slǣpiġ (attested in unslǣpiġ (“sleepless”)), from Proto-West Germanic *slāpag (“sleepy”), equivalent to sleep + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian släipich (“sleepy”), West Frisian sliepich (“sleepy”), dialectal Dutch slapig, slepig (“...

SLEETY.d: Covered in sleet; full of sleet.

SLEEVE.d: The part of a garment that covers the arm.
SLEEVE.e:
From Middle English sleve, slefe, from Old English slīef and slīefe (“sleeve”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Sleeuwe (“sleeve”), West Frisian slúf, Dutch sloof (“apron”), Low German sluve, dialectal German Schlaube.
The Canadian sense of “measure smaller than a pint” is due to ...

SLEIGH.d: A vehicle, generally pulled by an animal, which moves over snow or ice on runners, used for transporting persons or goods. (contrast "sled", which is smaller)
SLEIGH.e: From Modern Dutch slee, from Middle Dutch slede, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *slidô. Doublet of sled and further related to slide.

SLEWED.d: Past tense of SLEW: The act, or process of slewing.
SLEWED.e: In all senses, a mostly British spelling of slue.

SLEYED.d: Past tense of SLEY: Reed (of a loom).
SLEYED.e: From Middle English slay, from Old English slege.

SLIDED.d: Past tense of SLIDE: To move smoothly along a surface.

SLIDES.d: Plural of SLIDE: To move smoothly along a surface.

SLIGHT.e: From Middle English slight (“bad, of poor quality, unimportant, trivial, slender, slim, smooth, level”), from Old English sliht (“smooth, level”), from Proto-Germanic *slihtaz (“slippery, flat, level, plain”), related to English slick. Cognate with Scots slicht (“bad, of poor qua...

SLIVER.d: A long piece cut or rent off; a sharp, slender fragment.
SLIVER.e: From Middle English slivere, sliver from Middle English sliven (“to cut, cleave, split”), from Old English slīfan (as in tōslīfan (“to split, split up”)).

SLOGAN.d: A distinctive phrase of a person or group of people (such as a movement or political party); a motto.
SLOGAN.e: From earlier sloggorne, slughorne, slughorn (“battle cry”), borrowed from Scottish Gaelic sluagh-ghairm (“battle cry”), from Old Irish slóg (“army; (by extension) assembly, crowd”) + gairm (“a call, cry”). Slóg is derived from Proto-Celtic *slougos (“army, troop”), from Proto-Ind...

SLOOSH.d: A splash or rush of water

SLOPED.d: Past tense of SLOPE: A surface at an angle.
SLOPED.e: From Old English āslūpan (to slip away).

SLOPES.d: Plural of SLOPE: A surface at an angle.
SLOPES.e: From Old English āslūpan (to slip away).

SLOPPY.d: Very wet; covered in or composed of slop.

SLOUCH.d: A hanging down of the head; a drooping posture; a limp appearance
SLOUCH.e: Unclear. Perhaps from Middle English slugge, from Old Norse slókr (“lazy fellow”). See also Swedish sloka (“to slouch, wilt”), related to Swedish slak (“slack, soft and flexible”) and Latin laxus (“loose, slack”).

SLOUGH.d: The skin shed by a snake or other reptile.
SLOUGH.e:
From Middle English slogh, slugh, slouh, from Proto-Germanic *sluk-, perhaps related to *sleupaną (“to slip, sneak”) (compare Gothic 𐍃𐌻𐌹𐌿𐍀𐌰𐌽 (sliupan)).
Akin to Middle Low German slô (“sheath, skin on a hoof”). Perhaps also related with Old Saxon slūk (“snakeskin”), Middle High G...

SLOVEN.d: A habitually dirty or untidy man or boy; the male equivalent of slattern, or slut.
SLOVEN.e: From Middle English sloveyn, from Middle Flemish sloovin (“a scold”). Related to Middle Dutch sloef (“untidy, shabby”), from Proto-Germanic *slup- + Old French -ain, from Latin -anus.

SLOWED.d: Past tense of SLOW: Taking a long time to move or go a short distance, or to perform an action; not quick in motion; proceeding at a low speed.
SLOWED.e:
From Middle English slow, slaw, from Old English slāw (“sluggish, inert, slothful, late, tardy, torpid, slow”), from Proto-West Germanic *slaiw, from Proto-Germanic *slaiwaz (“blunt, dull, faint, weak, slack”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *sleyH-u- (“bad”).
Cognate with Sco...

SLUDGE.d: Solids separated from suspension in a liquid.

SLUDGY.d: Characteristic of sludge; slimy or mucky

SLUICE.d: An artificial passage for water, fitted with a valve or gate, for example in a canal lock or a mill stream, for stopping or regulating the flow.
SLUICE.e: From Middle English sluse, alteration of scluse, from Anglo-Norman escluse (“sluice, floodgate”), from Late Latin exclusa (“extrusion, gate”), from Latin exclūsus, form of exclūdō (“I shut out, I exclude”) (English exclude). Cognate to Dutch sluis.

SLUING.d: Present participle of SLUE: To rotate something on an axis.
SLUING.e: Unknown. Attested from the late 18th century.

SLUMMY.d: Like a slum; run-down, dirty, decrepit.

SLURRY.d: Any flowable suspension of small particles in liquid.
SLURRY.e: Unclear; probably related to Middle English sloor (“thin or fluid mud”); compare slur. From mid-15th c.

SLUSHY.e: From slush + -y. In the sense of a cook, from the sense of slush meaning to refuse grease and fat collected in cooking.

SLUTTY.d: Of, resembling, or suitable for, a slut.

SMALLS.d: Plural of SMALL: Of limited size.

SMARMY.d: Falsely earnest, smug, ingratiating, or pious.
SMARMY.e: From smarm + -y. Apparently coined by "B.R.L., of Brighton" with sense "saying treacly things which do not sound genuine" in a competition for neologisms in The Academy (London) published on 14 January 1899.

SMARTS.e: From Old English smeortan (to cause pain).

SMARTY.d: An obnoxiously clever or quick-witted person.

SMEGMA.d: A whitish sebaceous secretion that collects between the glans penis and foreskin or in the vulva.
SMEGMA.e: From Latin, borrowed from Ancient Greek σμῆγμα (smêgma), alternative form of σμῆμα (smêma, “soap, detergent”), from σμάω (smáō, “I wipe, clean”).

SMILAX.d: Any member of the Smilax genus of greenbriers.
SMILAX.e: From the genus name, translingual Smilax. Further from Latin smīlax f and Ancient Greek σμῖλαξ f (smîlax).

SMILED.d: Past tense of SMILE: A facial expression of pleasure.

SMILES.d: Plural of SMILE: A facial expression of pleasure.

SMILEY.e: From smile + -y (adjectival suffix). The noun is from the adjective, after smiley face.

SMIRCH.e: From Middle English *smorchen ("to spatter, soil"; attested in besmorchid (“bespattered, soiled all over”)), of uncertain origin. Perhaps a derivative of Middle English smeoren, smuren, smeren (“to smear”) or related to Middle English smotry (“sooty, grimy”). Compare also Middle ...

SMITHY.d: The location where a smith (particularly a blacksmith) works, a forge.
SMITHY.e: From Middle English smythy, from Old Norse smiðja, from Proto-Germanic *smiþjǭ. Cognate with Old English smiþþe (whence the obsolete modern doublet smithe). See the Proto-Germanic entry for further cognates.

SMOGGY.e: From smog, the fumes given off from large industrial areas and buildings, for which Middlesbrough is famous.

SMOKED.d: Past tense of SMOKE: Visible vapor from burning material.

SMOKES.d: Plural of SMOKE: Visible vapor from burning material.

SMOOCH.d: A kiss, especially that which is on the cheek.
SMOOCH.e: Perhaps from a dialectal variation of smack. Compare also Low German smok (“a kiss, a smouch/smooch”), Alemannic German Schmutz, Schmützle (“a kiss, a smooch”).

SMOOTH.d: Having a texture that lacks friction. Not rough.
SMOOTH.e: From Middle English smothe, smethe, from Old English smēþe, smōþ, both from Proto-West Germanic *smanþī, of unknown origin. Cognate with Scots smuith (“smooth”), Saterland Frisian smoud (“smooth”), Low German smood and smödig (“smooth, malleable, ductile”), Dutch smeuïg (“smooth”...

SMRITI.d: A specific body of Hindu religious scripture.

SMUDGE.d: A blemish or smear, especially a dark or sooty one.
SMUDGE.e: Derived from the verb (see below). Doublet of smutch.

SMUDGY.e: From smudge (“blemish; dense smoke; to obscure by smearing; to stifle”) + -y. (The sense "rainy" is related to dialectal use of smudge to mean drizzling rain.)

SMUTTY.e: From smut + -y. Related to German schmutzig (“filthy, dirty, smutty”).

SNAGGY.d: Covered in snags, or similar sharp projections.

SNATCH.e:
From Middle English snacchen, snecchen, from Old English *snæċċan, *sneċċan or from Middle Dutch snacken, from Proto-West Germanic *snakkijan, from Proto-Germanic *snakkijaną, *snakkōną (“to nibble, snort, chatter”); see *snūtaz (“snout”).
Cognate with Dutch snakken (“to sob, pan...

SNAZZY.d: Appealing or stylish in appearance or manner; classy, flashy.
SNAZZY.e:
Origin unknown; the following etymologies have been suggested:
* A blend of sna(ppy) + (ja)zzy.
* From Irish snas (“finish, polish; good appearance”) + English -y (suffix forming adjectives meaning ‘having the quality of’).

SNEAKY.d: Elusive; difficult to capture or observe due to constantly outwitting the adversaries.

SNEEZE.d: To expel air as a reflex induced by an irritation in the nose.
SNEEZE.e: From Middle English snesen (“to sneeze”), alteration of earlier fnesen (“to sneeze”), from Old English fnēosan (“to sneeze, snort”), from Proto-West Germanic *fneusan, from Proto-Germanic *fneusaną, from Proto-Indo-European *pnew- (“to breathe, pant, snort, sneeze”). Cognate with...

SNEEZY.d: Prone to sneeze with little (if any) nasal agitation.
SNEEZY.e: From Middle English fnesy, equivalent to sneeze + -y. For change of initial f to s see sneeze.

SNIPPY.e: From snip + -y. Compare Saterland Frisian snippig, snippich (“short, brief, blunt”), Dutch snippig (“snippy, shrill”), German Low German snippig (“snippy, snappy”), German schnippisch (“snippy, snappy”).

SNITCH.d: To inform on, especially in betrayal of others.
SNITCH.e: Origin uncertain. Perhaps an alteration of Middle English snacche (“a trap, snare”), snacchen (“to seize (prey)”, whence modern English snatch). Compare also Middle English snik snak (“a sudden blow, snap”). Alternatively, perhaps from a dialectal variant of sneak, from Middle En...

SNIVEL.d: To breathe heavily through the nose while it is congested with nasal mucus.
SNIVEL.e: From Middle English snivelen, snevelen, snyvelen, snuvelen, from Old English *snyflan (attested in the verbal noun snyflung (“mucus”)), from Proto-West Germanic *snuflijan, related to Old English snofl (“mucus”), ultimately from the root of snout. Akin to sniff, snuff. Compare sn...

SNOOPY.d: Charlie Brown's pet beagle in the comic strip Peanuts, by Charles M. Schulz; often representing doggish soulfulness.

SNOOTY.d: Haughty, pompous, snobbish; inclined to turn up one's nose.
SNOOTY.e: The adjective is derived from snoot (“(UK, dialectal, and slang) snout; nose”) + -y (suffix forming adjectives meaning ‘having the quality of’), probably referring to a snobbish person often having their nose in the air (that is, acting disdainfully towards others). Snoot is a di...

SNOOZE.d: To sleep, especially briefly; to nap, doze.
SNOOZE.e: Unknown, attested since 18th century. Compare Dutch snoezelen (“to snooze”) or Swedish snusa (“to snore lightly”). Confer also Ancient Greek νυστάζω (nustázō, “to doze, drowse”) and Russian сон (son, “sleep, dream”).

SNOWED.d: Past tense of SNOW: The partly frozen, crystalline state of water that falls from the atmosphere as precipitation in flakes; also, the falling of such flakes; and the accumulation of them on the ground or on objects as a white layer.
SNOWED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English snaw, snou, snow (“snow; accumulation of snow; snowfall; snowstorm; whiteness”), from Old English snāw (“snow”), from Proto-West Germanic *snaiw (“snow”), from Proto-Germanic *snaiwaz (“snow”), from Proto-Indo-European *snóygʷʰos (“snow”), ...

SOAKED.d: Past tense of SOAK: To be saturated with liquid by being immersed in it.
SOAKED.e: From Middle English soken, from Old English socian (“to soak, steep”, literally “to cause to suck (up)”), from Proto-Germanic *sukōną (“to soak”), causative of Proto-Germanic *sūkaną (“to suck”). Cognate with Middle Dutch soken (“to cause to suck”). More at suck.

SOAPED.d: Past tense of SOAP: A metallic salt derived from a fatty acid, commonly used in cleaning products.
SOAPED.e:
From Middle English sope, sape, from Old English sāpe (“soap, salve”), from Proto-West Germanic *saipā, from Proto-Germanic *saipǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *seyb-, *seyp- (“to pour out, drip, trickle, strain”).
Cognate with Scots saip, sape (“soap”), Saterland Frisian Seepe (“so...

SOARED.d: Past tense of SOAR: To fly high with little effort, like a bird.
SOARED.e: From Middle English soren, from Old French essorer (“to fly up, soar”), from Vulgar Latin *exaurare (“to rise into the air”), from Latin ex (“out”) + aura (“the air, a breeze”), from Ancient Greek αὔρα (aúra, “breath”). Compare aura, and exhale.

SOBBED.d: Past tense of SOB: Initialism of son of a bitch.

SOBBER.d: Comparative form of SOB: Initialism of son of a bitch.

SOCCER.e:
Originally British English; as an abbreviation for association football, via abbreviation assoc. + -er (suffix); earlier socker (1885), also socca (1889), with soccer attested 1888.
Compare contemporary rugger, from Rugby. Similarly constructed coinages from the same period inclu...

SOCIAL.e: From Middle French social, from Latin sociālis (“of or belonging to a companion or companionship or association, social”), from socius (“a companion, fellow, partner, associate, ally”), from sequor (“follow”). Cognate with English seg (“man, companion, fellow”). More at seg.

SOCKED.d: Past tense of SOCK: A knitted or woven covering for the foot.
SOCKED.e: From Middle English socke, sokke, sok, from Old English socc (“sock, light shoe, slipper”), a West Germanic borrowing from Latin soccus (“a light shoe or slipper, buskin”), from Ancient Greek σύκχος (súkkhos, “a kind of shoe”), probably from Phrygian or from an Anatolian language...

SOCKET.d: Any of various concave objects (or portions of larger objects) that envelop a counterpart object.
SOCKET.e: From Middle English socket, soket, from Anglo-Norman soket (“spearhead”), diminutive of Old French soc (“plowshare”), from Vulgar Latin *soccus, a word borrowed from Gaulish, from Proto-Celtic *sukkos (compare modern Welsh swch (“plowshare”)), literally "pig's snout", from Proto-...

SODDED.d: Past tense of SOD: The stratum of the surface of the soil which is filled with the roots of grass, or any portion of that surface; turf; sward.
SODDED.e: From Middle English sod, sodde first attested in the mid-15th century, from Middle Dutch zoden (“turf”) or Middle Low German sôde, soede (“turf”), both related to Dutch zode (“turf”), German Sode (“turf”), Old Frisian sātha (“sod”), all being of uncertain ultimate origin.

SODDEN.d: Soaked or drenched with liquid; soggy, saturated.
SODDEN.e: From Middle English sodden, soden, from Old English soden, ġesoden, from Proto-Germanic *sudanaz, past participle of Proto-Germanic *seuþaną (“to seethe; boil”). Cognate with West Frisian sean, Dutch gezoden (“seethed, boiled”) (related to Dutch zode (“swampy land”)), Low German ...

SODIUM.d: The chemical element (symbol Na) with an atomic number of 11 and atomic weight of 22.990. It is a soft, waxy, silvery, reactive alkali metal that is never found unbound in nature.
SODIUM.e: Coined by British chemist Humphry Davy in 1808, from soda + -ium.

SODOMY.d: Any of several forms of sexual intercourse held to be unnatural, particularly bestiality or homosexuality, but also (sometimes) anal, oral, or manual sex.
SODOMY.e: From Sodom, where the Bible, in Genesis chapters 18 and 19 and elsewhere, suggests sexual depravity.

SOFFIT.d: The visible underside of an arch, balcony, beam, cornice, staircase, vault or any other architectural element.
SOFFIT.e: From French soffite, from Italian soffitto, from Vulgar Latin *suffīctus, perfect passive participle of Latin suffīgō (“to fasten or fix onto”).

SOFTEN.d: To make something soft or softer.
SOFTEN.e: From Middle English softenen, softnen, equivalent to soft + -en.

SOILED.d: Past tense of SOIL: A mixture of mineral particles and organic material, used to support plant growth.
SOILED.e: From Middle English soile, soyle, sule (“ground, earth”), partly from Anglo-Norman soyl (“bottom, ground, pavement”), from Latin solium (“seat, chair; throne”), mistaken for Latin solum (“ground, foundation, earth, sole of the foot”); and partly from Old English sol (“mud, mire, ...

SOLACE.d: Comfort or consolation in a time of loneliness or distress.
SOLACE.e: From Old French solas, from Latin sōlācium (“consolation”), root from Proto-Indo-European *selh₂- (“mercy, comfort”).

SOLDER.d: Any of various easily-melted alloys, commonly of tin and lead, that are used to mend, coat, or join metal objects, usually small.
SOLDER.e: From Middle English souder, soudere, soudur (noun), from Old French soldure, soudeure (noun), from Old French souder, solder (“to solder”, verb) (> Middle English souden (“to solder”)), from Latin solidāre (“make solid”).

SOLEMN.d: Of or pertaining to religious ceremonies and rites; (generally) religious in nature; sacred.
SOLEMN.e: From Middle English solempne, solemne (“performed with religious ceremony or reverence; devoted to religious observances, sacred; ceremonious, formal; of a vow: made under a religious sanction, binding; religious celebration, celebration of a feast day; famous, well-known; import...

SOLIDS.d: Plural of SOLID: Firm; not liquid or gas.
SOLIDS.e: From Old French solide, from Latin solidus.

SOLLER.d: Comparative form of SOL: In a movable-do or tonic sol-fa system: the fifth step in a scale, preceded by fa and followed by la.
SOLLER.e: From Glover's solmization, from Middle English sol (“fifth degree or note of Guido of Arezzo's hexachordal scales”), Italian sol in the solmization of Guido of Arezzo, from the first syllable of Latin solve (“wash away”) in the lyrics of the scale-ascending hymn Ut queant laxis b...

SOLOED.d: Past tense of SOLO: A piece of music for one performer.
SOLOED.e: Borrowed from Italian solo, from Latin sōlus, probably related to se (“himself”).

SOLUTE.e: Borrowed from Latin solutus, past participle of solvo.

SOLVED.d: Past tense of SOLVE: To find an answer to.

SOLVES.d: Plural of SOLVE: To find an answer to.

SOMBRE.e: Borrowed from French sombre (“dark”), from Old French sombre, from a verb *sombrer or Latin sub- + umbra. Compare Spanish sombra (“shade; dark part of a picture; ghost”).

SOMITE.d: One of the paired masses of mesoderm distributed along the sides of the neural tube that will eventually become dermis, skeletal muscle, or vertebrae.

SONANT.d: Of or pertaining to sound; sounding.

SONATA.d: A musical composition for one or a few instruments, one of which is frequently a piano, in three or four movements that vary in key and tempo.
SONATA.e: From Italian sonata, from the feminine past participle of sonare (modern suonare), from Latin sonāre (“to make sound”). Doublet of sounded.

SONICS.d: The science and technology of sound.

SONING.d: Present participle of SONE: a subjective unit of loudness for an average listener equal to the loudness of a 1000-hertz sound that has an intensity 40 decibels above the listener's own threshold of hearing

SONNET.d: A fixed verse form of Italian origin consisting of fourteen lines that are typically five-foot iambics and rhyme according to one of a few prescribed schemes.
SONNET.e: Borrowed from Middle French sonnet, from Italian sonetto, from Old Occitan sonet (“a song”), diminutive of son (“song, sound”), from Latin sonus (“sound”).

SOOTED.d: Past tense of SOOT: Fine black or dull brown particles of amorphous carbon and tar, produced by the incomplete combustion of coal, oil etc.
SOOTED.e: Inherited from Middle English soot, soote, sote, sot, from Old English sōt, from Proto-Germanic *sōtą (“soot”), from Proto-Indo-European *sed- (“to sit”). Cognate with dated Dutch zoet (“soot”), German Low German Soot (“soot”), Danish sod (“soot”), Swedish sot (“soot”), Icelandic...

SOOTHE.d: To restore to ease, comfort, or tranquility; relieve; calm; quiet; refresh.
SOOTHE.e: From Middle English sothen (“to verify, prove the validity of”), from Old English sōþian (“to verify, prove, confirm, bear witness to”), from Proto-West Germanic *sanþōn, from Proto-Germanic *sanþōną (“to prove, certify, acknowledge, testify”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁es- (“t...

SOPPED.d: Past tense of SOP: Something entirely soaked.
