SOPPED.e: From Middle English sop, soppe, sope, from Old English sopa (“sopped bread”), from Proto-Germanic *supô (compare Dutch sop, Old High German sopfa), deverbative of *sūpaną (“to sup”). Doublet of soup; more at sup.

SOPPER.d: Comparative form of SOP: Something entirely soaked.
SOPPER.e: From Middle English sop, soppe, sope, from Old English sopa (“sopped bread”), from Proto-Germanic *supô (compare Dutch sop, Old High German sopfa), deverbative of *sūpaną (“to sup”). Doublet of soup; more at sup.

SORBED.d: Past tense of SORB: The service tree, Sorbus domestica.
SORBED.e: Borrowed from Middle French sorbier (the tree), sorbe (the fruit), from Latin sorbus (the tree), sorbum (the fruit). See service tree.

SORBET.d: Frozen fruit juice, sometimes mixed with egg whites, eaten as dessert or between courses of a meal.
SORBET.e: Borrowed from Middle French sorbet, borrowed from Italian sorbetto, borrowed from Ottoman Turkish شربت (şerbet), borrowed from Classical Persian شَرْبَت (šarbat), borrowed from Arabic شَرْبَة (šarba), from شَرِبَ (šariba).

SORDID.e:
From Middle English sordide, from Latin sordidus.
Alternatively from French sordide.

SORDOR.e: Possibly from an unattested Latin *sordor, or by back-formation of a noun from sordidus (“dirty, vile”).

SORREL.d: Any of various plants with acidic leaves of the genus Rumex, especially
SORREL.e: From Middle English sorel, from Old French sorel, surele (“sorrel”), from Old French sur (“sour”), of Germanic origin, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *sūraz (“sour”); equivalent to sour + -el (diminutive suffix). Compare Old English sūre (“sorrel”), Icelandic súra (“sorrel”), Dut...

SORROW.e: From Middle English sorwe, sorow, sorewe, from Old English sorg, sorh (“care, anxiety, sorrow, grief”), from Proto-West Germanic *sorgu, from Proto-Germanic *surgō (compare West Frisian soarch, Dutch zorg, German Sorge, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian sorg), from Proto-Indo-Europea...

SORTED.d: simple past and past participle of sort

SORTIE.d: An attack made by troops from a besieged position; a sally.
SORTIE.e:
PIE word
 *upó
The noun is borrowed from French sortie (“act of exiting; exit, way out; (military) sally, sortie”), the feminine past participle of sortir (“to exit, go out”), from Old French sortir, from Latin sortīrī, the present active infinitive of sortior (“to cast or draw l...

SOTTED.d: Past tense of SOT: Stupid person; fool.
SOTTED.e:
From Middle English sot, from Old English sot, sott (“foolish, stupid”), from Medieval Latin sottus (“foolish”), of obscure origin and relation. Possibly an expressive interjection, similar to French zut! (“damn it!”).
Compare Middle Low German sot (“insane, foolish, stupid”), Mi...

SOTTER.d: Comparative form of SOT: Stupid person; fool.
SOTTER.e:
From Middle English sot, from Old English sot, sott (“foolish, stupid”), from Medieval Latin sottus (“foolish”), of obscure origin and relation. Possibly an expressive interjection, similar to French zut! (“damn it!”).
Compare Middle Low German sot (“insane, foolish, stupid”), Mi...

SOULED.d: Past tense of SOUL: The spirit or essence of a person usually thought to consist of one's thoughts and personality, often believed to live on after the person's death.
SOULED.e:
From Middle English soule, sowle, saule, sawle, from Old English sāwol (“soul, life, spirit, being”), from Proto-West Germanic *saiwalu, from Proto-Germanic *saiwalō (“soul”), of uncertain ultimate origin (see there for further information).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots saul, sowe...

SOUNDS.d: Plural of SOUND: Vibrations heard by the ear; healthy.
SOUNDS.e: From Old French son / Old English gesund.

SOUPED.d: Past tense of SOUP: Any of various dishes commonly made by combining liquids, such as water or stock, with other ingredients, such as meat and vegetables, that contribute the food value, flavor, and texture.
SOUPED.e:
The noun is from Middle English soupe, sowpe, from Old French soupe, souppe, sope, from Late Latin suppa (“sopped bread”), from Proto-Germanic *supô (compare Middle Dutch sope (“broth”)). Doublet of sop and zuppa. See also sup and supper.
The verb is from the noun.

SOURCE.d: The person, place, or thing from which something (information, goods, etc.) comes or is acquired.
SOURCE.e: From Middle English sours, from Old French sorse (“rise, beginning, spring, source”), from sors, past participle of sordre, sourdre, from Latin surgō (“to rise”), which is composed of sub- (“up from below”) + regō (“lead, rule”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₃réǵeti (“to...

SOURED.d: Past tense of SOUR: Tasting of acidity.
SOURED.e:
From Middle English sour, from Old English sūr (“sour”), from Proto-West Germanic *sūr, from Proto-Germanic *sūraz (“sour”), from Proto-Indo-European *súHros (“sour”).
Cognate with West Frisian soer, Dutch zuur (“sour”), Low German suur, German sauer (“sour”), Danish, Swedish and...

SOUSES.d: Plural of SOUS: plural of sou

SOUTER.e: Inherited from Middle English soutere, from Old English sūtere, from Latin sūtor (“shoemaker, cobbler”).

SOUTHS.d: Plural of SOUTH: The direction opposite to north.

SOVIET.d: A workers' council, an institution first formed during the 1905 Russian Revolution and then instituted as the main form of communist government at all levels in the Soviet Union; by extension, a similar organization in early Chinese communism and elsewhere.
SOVIET.e: Borrowed from Russian сове́т (sovét, “council”), from Old Russian borrowed from Old Church Slavonic съвѣтъ (sŭvětŭ, “advice”). Compounded from съ- (sŭ-) + вѣтъ (větŭ, “agreement”), from Proto-Slavic *větъ (“council, talk”). Related words include наве́т (navét), изве́т (izvét), от...

SOWING.d: Present participle of SOW: A female pig.
SOWING.e:
From Middle English sowe, from Old English sugu, from Proto-West Germanic *sugu, from Proto-Germanic *sugō, probably from Proto-Indo-European *su(H)kéh₂, from *suH- (“pig”).
See also West Frisian sûch, Dutch zeug, Low German Söög, German Sau, Swedish sugga, Norwegian sugge; also ...

SPACED.d: Past tense of SPACE: A continuous area; the universe beyond Earth.
SPACED.e: From Old French espace, from Latin spatium.

SPACES.d: Plural of SPACE: A continuous area; the universe beyond Earth.
SPACES.e: From Old French espace, from Latin spatium.

SPADIX.d: A fleshy spike (inflorescence) with reduced flowers, usually enclosed by a spathe, characteristic of aroids.
SPADIX.e: Via Latin spādīx from Ancient Greek σπᾱ́δῑξ (spā́dīx, “palm branch”).

SPARED.d: Past tense of SPARE: Additional; to refrain from harming.

SPARES.d: Plural of SPARE: Additional; to refrain from harming.

SPARKY.d: A nickname for a person who is lively and animated.

SPATHE.d: A large bract that envelops or subtends a whole inflorescence, typically a spadix.
SPATHE.e: From Latin spatha, from Ancient Greek σπάθη (spáthē, “blade”). Doublet of epee, spatha, and spade.

SPAVIN.d: A bony swelling which develops in a horse's leg where the shank and splint bone meet, caused by inflammation of the cartilage connecting those bones; also, a similar swelling caused by inflammation of the hock bones.
SPAVIN.e: The noun is derived from Middle English spavein, spaveine (“swelling on horse’s leg causing lameness; disease causing lameness in horses”), from Old French espavain, a variant of esparvain, esprevain, esprevin (modern French éparvin, épervin). The further etymology is unknown; on...

SPAYED.d: Past tense of SPAY: To destroy or remove the ovaries or uterus (of a female animal) to prevent pregnancy.
SPAYED.e: From Middle English spayen, spaien, from the Anglo-Norman espeier, equivalent to the Old French espeer (“to cut with a sword”), from espee (“sword”), whence the Modern French épée.

SPEAKS.d: Plural of SPEAK: To say words; to communicate.

SPECIE.d: Type or kind, in various uses of the phrase in specie.
SPECIE.e: Originally in the phrase in specie; from Latin speciē, ablative singular of species. Compare in kind.

SPEECH.d: The ability to speak; the faculty of uttering words or articulate sounds and vocalizations to communicate.
SPEECH.e: From Middle English speche, from Old English spǣċ, sprǣċ (“speech, discourse, language”), from Proto-West Germanic *sprāku (“speech, language”), from Proto-Indo-European *spereg-, *spreg- (“to make a sound”). Cognate with Dutch spraak (“speech”), German Sprache (“language, speech...

SPEEDO.d: A speedometer, particularly one in a race car or other automobile.

SPEEDS.d: Plural of SPEED: The rate of movement.

SPEEDY.d: Proceeding with or characterized by high speed; rapid.
SPEEDY.e: From Middle English spedy, spedi, from Old English spēdiġ (“having good speed, lucky, prosperous; having means, wealthy, opulent, rich in material wealth; rich in, abounding in, abundant, plenteous, copious; powerful”), from Proto-Germanic *spōdigaz (“successful, hurried”), equiv...

SPEISS.d: A mixed arsenide of iron (and cobalt, nickel, and copper) produced during the smelting of lead

SPENCE.d: Short form of the male given name Spencer.

SPENDS.d: Plural of SPEND: To pay out money; to use time.

SPEWED.d: Past tense of SPEW: To eject forcibly and in a stream,
SPEWED.e:
From Middle English spewen, from Old English spīwan, from Proto-West Germanic *spīwan, from Proto-Germanic *spīwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ptyēw- (“to spit, vomit”).
Germanic cognates include English spit, West Frisian spije, Dutch spuwen, Low German speen, spiien, German ...

SPHERE.d: A surface in three dimensions consisting of all points equidistant from a center. .
SPHERE.e: From Middle English spere, from Old French sphere, from Late Latin sphēra, earlier Latin sphaera (“ball, globe, celestial sphere”), from Ancient Greek σφαῖρα (sphaîra, “ball, globe”), of unknown origin. Not related to superficially similar Persian سپهر (sepehr, “sky”) .

SPHINX.d: A creature with the head of a person and the body of an animal, commonly a lion.
SPHINX.e: From Middle English Spynx, from Latin Sphinx, from Ancient Greek Σφίγξ (Sphínx), perhaps either from σφίγγω (sphíngō, “to squeeze, to strangle”) (whence also sphincter), of Pre-Greek origin, or from Egyptian Szp:p-A53-anx-n:x (šzp-ꜥnḫ, “divine image”, literally “living image”).

SPIDER.d: Any of various eight-legged, predatory arthropods, of the order Araneae, most of which spin webs to catch prey.
SPIDER.e:
From Middle English spiþre, spydyr, spider, spiþer, from Old English spīþra (“spider”), from Proto-West Germanic *spinþrijō, from Proto-Germanic *spinnaną (“to spin”). Mostly displaced attercop (“spider, unpleasant person”), now a dialectal term.
Compare typologically Proto-Slavi...

SPIFFY.d: Dapper; fine or neat, especially in style of clothing or other appearance.
SPIFFY.e: Unknown. Attested in print from 1852 (see quotations below). Compare the noun spiff, attested from 1859, as well as spiffing (1872) and spiffed (1881), suggesting participle forms of a related verb. Compare also spiv (“a smartly-dressed criminal”), attested from the 20th century.

SPIGOT.d: A pin or peg used to stop the vent in a cask.
SPIGOT.e: From Middle English spigot (“wooden stopper”). Probably ultimately from Latin spīca via Old Occitan espiga and one or more dialects of Middle French [Term?].

SPILTH.e: From spill + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Compare Old English *spilþ, spild (“annihilation, destruction, ruin”).

SPINAL.d: Of or relating to the spine.
SPINAL.e: Borrowed from Late Latin spīnālis (“of or belonging to the spine”), from spīna (“a prickle, spine”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix). By surface analysis, spine + -al.

SPINEL.d: Any of several hard minerals of cubic symmetry that are mixed oxides of magnesium and aluminium and are used as gemstones of various colours.
SPINEL.e: French spinelle, perhaps from Latin spina (“a thorn, a prickle”), in allusion to its pointed crystals.

SPINET.d: A short, compact harpsichord or piano.

SPINOR.d: An element of the fundamental representation of a Clifford algebra that transforms to its negative when the space is rotated through a complete turn from 0° to 360°.

SPIRAL.d: A curve that is the locus of a point that rotates about a fixed point while continuously increasing its distance from that point.
SPIRAL.e: From Middle French spirale, from Medieval Latin spiralis, from Latin spīra, from Ancient Greek σπεῖρα (speîra, “wreath, coil, twist”).

SPIRIT.d: The soul of a person or other creature.
SPIRIT.e: From Middle English spirit, from Old French espirit (“spirit”), from Latin spīritus (“breath; spirit”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)peys- (“to blow, breathe”). Compare inspire, respire, transpire, all ultimately from Latin spīrō (“I breathe, blow, respire”). In this sense, displ...

SPIVVY.d: Of, related to, or resembling a spiv; flashy but often also seedy.

SPLAKE.d: A hybrid fish derived from a male brook trout and a female lake trout.

SPLASH.d: The sound made by an object hitting a liquid.
SPLASH.e: Probably an alteration of plash (compare spatter, spill for the initial s-).

SPLEEN.d: In vertebrates, including humans, a ductless vascular gland, located in the left upper abdomen near the stomach, which destroys old red blood cells, removes debris from the bloodstream, acts as a reservoir of blood, and produces lymphocytes.
SPLEEN.e: From Middle English splene, splen, from Anglo-Norman espleen and Old French esplein, esplen, from Latin splēn (“milt”), from Ancient Greek σπλήν (splḗn, “the spleen”). Doublet of lien. Partially displaced the native English term milt.

SPLICE.d: A junction or joining of ropes made by splicing them together.
SPLICE.e: Circa 1525, borrowed from Middle Dutch splissen (Modern Dutch splitsen); akin to Middle Dutch splitten (“to split”), German spleißen (“to split, splice”), Spliss (“split ends, hair breakage”), French épisser (also from Dutch). The Dutch word originally referred only to the frayin...

SPLIFF.e: From Jamaican Creole, possibly a blend of split, referring to the ready-made wrap, + whiff, referring to the smell of the smoke.

SPLINE.d: A long, thin piece of metal or wood.
SPLINE.e: Mid-1700s East Anglian dialect. Origin uncertain but perhaps from Old Danish splind or North Frisian splinj and ultimately related to the root of splinter.

SPLINT.d: A narrow strip of wood split or peeled from a larger piece.
SPLINT.e: From Middle English splint, splent, splente, from Middle Low German splinte, splente or Middle Dutch splint, splinte. Cognate with Old High German splinza (“bar, bolt, latch”). All ultimately from Proto-Germanic *splintǭ, *splintō (“piece of wood, splinter”), from Proto-Germanic ...

SPLISH.e: Onomatopoeic. Connected with splash and splosh.

SPLITS.d: Plural of SPLIT: To divide; a division.

SPLOSH.d: To splash with a heavy splashing sound.
SPLOSH.e: Onomatopoeic. Connected with splash and splish; compare also slosh.

SPOKED.d: Past tense of SPOKE: Past tense of speak; a rod.

SPOKES.d: Plural of SPOKE: Past tense of speak; a rod.

SPONGE.d: Any of various marine invertebrates of the phylum Porifera, that have a porous skeleton often of silica.
SPONGE.e: From Middle English sponge, from Old English spunge, taken from Latin spongia, from Ancient Greek σπογγιά (spongiá), from σπόγγος (spóngos).

SPONGY.d: Having the characteristics of a sponge, namely being absorbent, squishy or porous.

SPOOKY.d: Eerie, or suggestive of ghosts or the supernatural.

SPOONY.d: Enamored in a silly or sentimental way; having a crush (on someone).
SPOONY.e: From spoon + -y. See notes at spoonie.

SPORTS.d: Plural of SPORT: An athletic activity.

SPOTTY.e: From Middle English spotty, equivalent to spot + -y.

SPOUSE.d: A person in a marriage or marital relationship.
SPOUSE.e:
From Middle English spous, spouse, from Anglo-Norman espus m, espuse f and Old French espos m, espose f and by aphesis from Latin spōnsus m (“bridegroom”), spōnsa f (“bride”), from spondeō (“I vow, pledge”), from Proto-Indo-European *spend-. Displaced native Old English ġemaca.
R...

SPRAIN.d: To weaken, as a joint, ligament, or muscle, by sudden and excessive exertion, as by wrenching; to overstrain, or stretch injuriously, but without luxation
SPRAIN.e: 1601, verb attested 1622. Possibly borrowed from Middle French espraindre (“to press out, to wring”), from Latin exprimere, in which case cognate to express.

SPRAWL.d: To sit with the limbs spread out.
SPRAWL.e: From Middle English spraulen, from Old English spreawlian (“move convulsively”), ultimately through a Proto-Germanic form cognate with *spreutaną (“to sprout”) from Proto-Indo-European *sper- (“to strew”). Compare North Frisian spraweli, Norwegian sprala, Swedish sprala.

SPREAD.d: To stretch out, open out (a material etc.) so that it more fully covers a given area of space.
SPREAD.e:
From Middle English spreden, from Old English sprǣdan (“to spread, expand”), from Proto-Germanic *spraidijaną (“to spread”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)per- (“to strew, sow, sprinkle”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian spreede (“to spread”), West Frisian spriede (“to spread”), No...

SPRING.e: From Middle English springen, from Old English springan (“to spring, leap, bounce, sprout forth, emerge, spread out”), from Proto-West Germanic *springan, from Proto-Germanic *springaną (“to burst forth”), from Proto-Indo-European *spre(n)ǵʰ- (“to move, race, spring”), from *sper...

SPRINT.d: A short race at top speed.
SPRINT.e: Alteration of earlier sprent (“to leap; bound; dart”), from Northern Middle English sprenten, from Old Norse *sprenta (for later spretta), from Proto-Germanic *sprantijaną, causative of Proto-Germanic *sprintaną (“to jump up; bounce”), from Proto-Indo-European *sprend-, *sprendʰ-...

SPRITE.d: Any of various supernatural beings, loosely defined:
SPRITE.e:
From Middle English sprite, spryt, spreyte, from Old French esprit (“spirit”), from Latin spīritus. Doublet of spirit, spiritus, spirytus, spright, and esprit.
(computer graphics): First used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
(meteorology): An acronym for St...

SPROUT.d: A new growth of or on a plant, whether from seed or other parts.
SPROUT.e: From Middle English sproute, either from Middle English sprouten (“to sprout”) (see below); or from Middle Dutch sprute or Middle Low German sprûte (“sprout”), all related to Proto-West Germanic *spreutan. Doublet of spruit.

SPRUCE.d: Any of various large coniferous evergreen trees or shrubs from the genus Picea, found in northern temperate and boreal regions; originally and more fully spruce fir.
SPRUCE.e: From Middle English Spruce, an alteration of Pruce (“Prussia”), from Medieval Latin, from a Baltic language, probably Old Prussian; for more, see Prussia. Spruce, spruse (1412), and Sprws (1378) were terms for commodities brought to England by Hanseatic merchants (beer, wood, lea...

SPURGE.d: Any plant of the genus Euphorbia, a diverse genus of over 2,000 species.
SPURGE.e:
Etymology tree
Old French espurgebor.
Middle English spurge
English spurge
Inherited from Middle English spurge, from Old French espurge, from espurgier (“to purge”), from Latin expurgo (“I purge”); the bitter milky sap of these plants was formerly used as a purgative.

SPUTUM.d: Matter coughed up and expectorated from the mouth, composed of saliva and discharges from the respiratory passages such as mucus, phlegm or pus.
SPUTUM.e: From New Latin, from Latin sputum (“that which is spit out, spittle”), from spuere (“to spit”).

SPYING.d: Present participle of SPY: A person who secretly watches and examines the actions of other individuals or organizations and gathers information on them (usually to gain an advantage).
SPYING.e: From Middle English spien, aphetic variant of earlier espien (“to espy”), from Old French espier (“to spy”), from Frankish *spehōn (“to spy”), from Proto-Germanic *spehōną (“to see, look”), from Proto-Indo-European *speḱ- (“to look”). Akin to German spähen (“to spy”), Dutch spied...

SQUALL.e:
From Middle English *squalen and squelen (“to cry, scream, squall”), from Old Norse skvala (“to cry out”), probably ultimately imitative with influence from squeal and bawl.
Cognate with Swedish skvala (“to gush, pour down”), Norwegian skval (“sudden rush of water”). The noun is ...

SQUARE.d: A polygon with four straight sides of equal length and four right angles; an equilateral rectangle; a regular quadrilateral.
SQUARE.e:
From Middle English square, sqware, squyre; from Old French esquarre, esquerre, (modern French équerre), from Vulgar Latin *exquadra, from Latin ex- + quadro, from quadrus (compare English quad and quadra). Doublet of squad and squadra.
Displaced Old English fēowerecge (fēower no...

SQUASH.d: A sport played in a walled court with a soft rubber ball and bats like tennis racquets.
SQUASH.e: From Middle English squachen, squatchen, from Old French esquacher, escachier, from Vulgar Latin *excoāctiāre, from Latin ex + coāctāre. Probably influenced by Middle English quashen, quassen, from Old French esquasser, escasser (“to crush, shatter, destroy, break”), from Vulgar ...

SQUAWK.d: A shrill noise, especially made by a voice or bird. If made by a bird, it typically signals discomfort or anger; a yell, scream, or call.
SQUAWK.e: First attested in 1821. Unknown, but probably of imitative origin (compare dialectal Italian squacco (“small-crested heron”) and English quack).

SQUEAK.d: A short, high-pitched sound, as of two objects rubbing together, or the sounds made by mice and other small animals.

SQUEAL.d: A high-pitched sound, such as the scream of a child or a female person, or noisy worn-down brake pads.
SQUEAL.e: Inherited from Middle English squelen, probably from Old Norse skvala (“to squeal, bawl”), from Proto-Germanic *skwel- (“to chatter, babble, scream”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *skel-, from *kelh₁- (“to ring, resound, cry”). Compare Old Norse skval (“a squeal”, noun), Swed...

SQUILL.d: A European bulbous liliaceous plant, of the genus Scilla, used in medicine for its acrid, expectorant, diuretic, and emetic properties
SQUILL.e: From French scille, from Latin scilla. Doublet of scilla.

SQUINT.d: To look with the eyes partly closed, as in bright sunlight, or as a threatening expression.
SQUINT.e: Derived from asquint (“obliquely, with a sidelong glance”).

SQUIRE.d: A shield-bearer or armor-bearer who attended a knight.
SQUIRE.e: From Middle English esquire, from Old French escuier, from Latin scūtārius (“shield-bearer”), from scūtum (“shield”).

SQUIRM.d: To twist one's body with snakelike motions.
SQUIRM.e: First recorded 1690's, originally used of eels; cognate with Scots squimmer (“to wriggle, squirm”). Of uncertain origin. Compare dialectal quirm, whirm (“to disappear quickly, vanish suddenly and mysteriously”), Norwegian kverva (“to turn around, take away, remove, shrink”), from...

SQUIRT.d: An instrument from which a liquid is forcefully ejected in a small, quick stream.
SQUIRT.e: From Middle English squirten, squyrten, of uncertain origin; probably onomatopoeic. Akin to swirl. Compare Low German swirtjen (“to squirt”) and Swedish water onomatopoeias skvala, skvalp, skvimpa, and skvätta; Icelandic skvetta; and Norwegian skvette.

SQUISH.d: The sound or action of something, especially something moist, being squeezed or crushed.
SQUISH.e: Apparently an alteration of squash, influenced by obsolete squiss (“to squeeze”). Cognate with Scots squische, squies (“to crush, squeeze”). Compare also French esquicher from Old Occitan esquichar (“to squeeze, squish”). See also squeeze, squelch.

STABLE.d: A building, wing or dependency set apart and adapted for lodging and feeding (and training) ungulates, especially horses.
STABLE.e: From Middle English stable, borrowed from Anglo-Norman stable, from Latin stab(u)lum.

STADIA.d: A level staff or graduated rod used by surveyors to measure differences in level, or to measure horizontal distances by sighting the stadia hairs (graduations) through a telescope.

STAFFS.d: Plural of STAFF: Employees; a stick.

STAGED.d: Past tense of STAGE: A raised platform; a phase.

STAGES.d: Plural of STAGE: A raised platform; a phase.

STAKED.d: Past tense of STAKE: A pointed post; a share.

STAKES.d: Plural of STAKE: A pointed post; a share.

STAMEN.d: In flowering plants, a male reproductive structure in a flower that produces pollen, typically consisting of an anther and a filament.
STAMEN.e: From New Latin stāmen, from Ancient Greek στη̃μα (stē̃ma).

STANCE.d: The manner, pose, or posture in which one stands.
STANCE.e: From Middle English staunce (“place to stand; battle station; position; standing in society; circumstance, situation; stanchion”), from Old French estance (“predicament; situation; sojourn, stay”) (compare modern French stance (“stanza; position one stands in when golfing”)), fro...

STANDS.d: Plural of STAND: To be upright; a position.

STANZA.d: A unit of a poem, written or printed as a paragraph; equivalent to a verse.
STANZA.e: From Italian stanza, from Vulgar Latin *stantia (“standing, stopping-place”), from Latin stāns, stantis, from stō, stāre, from Proto-Italic *staēō, from Proto-Indo-European *sth₂éh₁yeti, stative verb from *steh₂- (whence English stand). Doublet of stance.

STAPLE.d: A town containing merchants who have exclusive right, under royal authority, to purchase or produce certain goods for export; also, the body of such merchants seen as a group.
STAPLE.e: From Middle English staple, from Anglo-Norman estaple, Old French estaple (“market, (trading) post”), from Late Latin stapula, from Frankish *stapul, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *stapulaz (“post”), from Proto-Indo-European *stebʰ- (“post, stem”). Compare staff. Doublet of étap...

STARCH.d: A widely diffused vegetable substance, found especially in seeds, bulbs and tubers, as extracted (e.g. from potatoes, corn, rice, etc.) in the form of a white, glistening, granular or powdery substance, without taste or smell, and giving a very peculiar creaking sound when rubbed between the fingers. It is used as a food, in the production of commercial grape sugar, for stiffening linen in laundries, in making paste, etc.
STARCH.e:
From Middle English starche, sterche, from Old English *stierċe (“stiffness, rigidity, strength”), from Proto-West Germanic *starkī (“stiffness, rigidity, fortitude, strength”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *sterg- (“stiff, rigid”).
Cognate with dialectal Dutch sterk (“str...

STARRY.e: From Middle English sterry, equivalent to star + -y.

STARTS.d: Plural of START: To begin; the beginning.

STARVE.d: To die because of lack of food or of not eating.
STARVE.e: From Middle English sterven (“to die, perish”), from Old English steorfan (“to die, perish”), from Proto-West Germanic *sterban, from Proto-Germanic *sterbaną (“to become stiff, die”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)terp- (“to lose strength, become numb, be motionless”); or from Pr...

STASIS.d: A slackening or arrest of the blood current, due not to a lessening of the heart’s beat, but to some abnormal resistance of the capillary walls.
STASIS.e: From New Latin stasis, from Ancient Greek στάσις (stásis). See the doublet stead.

STATED.d: Past tense of STATE: A condition; a nation.

STATER.d: A gold, silver or electrum coin of ancient Greece.

STATIC.d: Unchanging; that cannot or does not change.
STATIC.e: Modern Latin staticus, from Ancient Greek στατικός (statikós), from ἵστημι (hístēmi, “to make stand”). By surface analysis, stasis + -tic.

STATIN.d: Any of a class of drugs (chiefly lactones or pyrroles) that lower the amount of cholesterol in the blood by inhibiting an enzyme involved in its biosynthesis.
STATIN.e: From the suffix -statin, from terms such as lovastatin and simvastatin.

STATOR.d: The stationary part of a motor or other machine.
STATOR.e: From stationary or static by analogy with rotor; alternatively from a hypothetical Latin stātor (literally “stander”); all ultimately from stāre (“to stand”).

STATUE.d: A three-dimensional work of art, usually representing a person or animal, usually created by sculpting, carving, molding, or casting.
STATUE.e: From Old French statue, from Latin statua, derived from statuō (“set up or erect”). Doublet of statua.

STATUS.d: A person’s condition, position or standing relative to that of others.
STATUS.e: A learned borrowing from Latin status. A doublet of state and estate.

STAYED.d: Past tense of STAY: To remain in a particular place, especially for a definite or short period of time; sojourn; abide.
STAYED.e: From Middle English steyen, staien, from Old French estayer, estaier (“to fix, prop up, support, stay”), from estaye, estaie (“a prop, stay”), from Middle Dutch staeye (“a prop, stay”), a contracted form of staede, stade (“a prop, stay, help, aid”) (compare Middle Dutch staeyen, ...

STAYER.d: One who, or that which, upholds or supports; a prop.

STEADY.d: Firm in standing or position; not tottering or shaking; fixed; firm.
STEADY.e: From Middle English stedy, studi, stidiȝ, perhaps continuing Old English stæþþiġ, ġestæþþiġ (“steadfast, stable, firm, staid”), equivalent to stead + -y; or calquing Middle Low German or Middle Dutch stēdig. Cognate with Saterland Frisian stoadig (“constant, continual”), West Fri...

STEALS.d: Plural of STEAL: To take without permission.

STEAMY.d: Warm and humid; full of steam.

STEELS.d: Plural of STEEL: A strong alloy of iron.

STEELY.d: Having qualities resembling those of steel, especially hardness and resoluteness.

STENCH.d: a strong foul smell; a stink.
STENCH.e: From Middle English stench, from Old English stenċ (“stench, odor, fragrance”), from Proto-Germanic *stankwiz (“smell, fragrance, odor”), from Proto-Indo-European *stengʷ- (“to push, thrust”). Cognate with Dutch stank (“stench, odor”), German Stank, Gestank (“stench, odor, smell”...

STEPPE.d: The grasslands of Eastern Europe and Asia.
STEPPE.e: From German Steppe or French steppe, in turn from Russian степь (stepʹ, “flat grassy plain”). There is no generally accepted earlier etymology, but there is a speculative Old East Slavic reconstruction *сътепь (sŭtepĭ, “trampled place, flat, bare”), related to топот (topot), топт...

STEREO.d: A system of recording or reproducing sound that uses two or more channels, each playing a portion of the original sound at different locations in order to simulate the separation of sources along at least one spatial dimension.
STEREO.e: A shortened form of stereotype, stereoscope or stereophonic, all originally derived, via stereo-, from Ancient Greek στερεός (stereós, “solid”).

STERIC.d: Relating to or involving the arrangement of atoms in space.

STEROL.d: Any steroid that contains a hydroxyl group in the 3-position of the A-ring.

STEVIA.d: Any of the sweet herbs of genus Stevia, native to tropical and subtropical regions of South America and western North America.
STEVIA.e: Borrowed from translingual Stevia, after 16th century Spanish botanist Pedro Jaime Esteve (latinized as Petrus Jacobus Stevus).

STEWED.d: Past tense of STEW: A cooking-dish used for boiling; a cauldron.
STEWED.e: From Middle English stewe, stue, from Anglo-Norman estouve, Old French estuve (“bath, bathhouse”) (modern French étuve), from Medieval Latin stupha, of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Vulgar Latin *extufāre, from ex- + Ancient Greek τῦφος (tûphos, “smoke, steam”), from τύφω (túphō...

STICKS.d: Plural of STICK: A thin piece of wood; to adhere.

STICKY.d: Tending to stick; able to adhere via the drying of a viscous substance.

STIFLE.d: To make (an animal or person) unconscious or cause (an animal or person) death by preventing breathing; to smother, to suffocate.
STIFLE.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English stuflen (“to have difficulty breathing due to heat, stifle; to suffocate by drowning, drown”) [and other forms]; further etymology uncertain, perhaps from stuffen (“to kill by suffocation; to stifle from heat; to extinguish, suppress (...

STIGMA.d: A mark of infamy or disgrace.
STIGMA.e: From Latin stigma, from Ancient Greek στίγμα (stígma, “brand”), from στίζω (stízō, “I mark”). Distantly related to stick. (Compare Middle English stigme, from the same Latin source.)

STILLS.d: Plural of STILL: Not moving; up to now.

STINGY.d: Unwilling to spend, give, or share; ungenerous; mean.
STINGY.e: Uncertain, possibly from stinge, a dialectal variation of sting (verb).

STINKY.d: Having a strong, unpleasant smell; stinking.
STINKY.e: From Middle English stinky, stynky, equivalent to stink + -y. Compare Dutch stinkig (“stinky, foul, rotten”), German stinkig (“stinky”), Hunsrik stinkich.

STITCH.d: A single pass of a needle in sewing; the loop or turn of the thread thus made.
STITCH.e: From Middle English stiche, from Old English stiċe (“a prick, puncture, stab, thrust with a pointed implement, pricking sensation, stitch, pain in the side, sting”), from Proto-West Germanic *stiki, from Proto-Germanic *stikiz (“prick, piercing, stitch”), from Proto-Indo-European...

STIVER.d: A small Dutch coin worth one twentieth of a guilder.
STIVER.e: From Dutch stuiver, cognate with Middle Low German stüver.

STOCKS.d: Plural of STOCK: Goods for sale; shares.

STOCKY.d: Sturdy; solidly built; heavy and compact.

STODGE.e: Late 17th century, of "symbolic" origin, suggested by stuff and podge. Compare stog.

STODGY.e: Unknown, but possibly from stodge (“to stuff”), from stog, or a blend of stuffy + podgy.

STOLID.d: Having or revealing little emotion or sensibility.
STOLID.e: From Middle French stolide, from Latin stolidus (“foolish, obtuse, slow”).

STOLON.d: A shoot that grows along the ground and produces roots at its nodes; a runner.
STOLON.e: From Latin stolō. Doublet of stole.

STOMPY.d: Of a stomping style of dance, or music appropriate to such a dance.

STONED.d: Past tense of STONE: A piece of rock.

STONES.d: Plural of STONE: A piece of rock.

STOOGE.d: One who knowingly allows himself or herself to be used for another's profit; a dupe.
STOOGE.e: Perhaps an abbreviation of Russian студе́нт (studént) [stʊˈdʲent]; the original meaning was “stage assistant, actor who assists a comedian”. It may have been a Yiddish vaudeville term.

STORAX.d: Any member of the genus Styrax of about 130 species of large shrubs or small trees, mostly native to temperate or tropical regions of the Northern Hemisphere.
STORAX.e: From Middle English storace, storage, storax, storaxe, storrax, from Latin storax, styrax, from Ancient Greek στύραξ (stúrax). Doublet of styrax.

STORED.d: Past tense of STORE: A shop; to keep for future use.

STORER.d: One who lays up or forms a store.

STORES.d: Plural of STORE: A shop; to keep for future use.

STOREY.d: A floor or level of a building or ship.
STOREY.e: From Middle English story, via Medieval Latin historia (“narrative, illustraton, frieze”) from Ancient Greek ἱστορίᾱ (historíā, “learning through research”). The current sense arose from narrative friezes on upper levels of medieval buildings, esp. churches. Doublet of story and ...

STORMS.d: Plural of STORM: A violent weather disturbance.

STORMY.e: From Middle English stormy, stormi, from Old English *stormiġ (“stormy”), equivalent to storm + -y. Cognate with Dutch stormig (“stormy”), German stürmisch (“stormy”), Swedish stormig (“stormy”).

STOWED.d: Past tense of STOW: A place, stead.
STOWED.e: From Middle English stowe, from Old English stōw (“place, location”), from Proto-West Germanic *stōu, from Proto-Germanic *stōō (“a place, stowage”), from Proto-Indo-European *steh₂- (“to stand, place, put”). Cognate with Old Frisian stō (“place”), Icelandic stó (“fireplace”), Du...

STRAFE.d: To attack (ground targets) with automatic gunfire from a low-flying aircraft.
STRAFE.e: From German strafe (“punish”) (a conjugated form of strafen), from phrases like Gott strafe England (“God punish England”) which the British saw during the First World War.

STRAIN.e: From Middle English streen, strene, streon, istreon (“race, stock, generation”), from Old English strēon, ġestrēon (“gain, wealth”), from Proto-Germanic *streuną (“heap, treasure, profit, gain”), from Proto-Indo-European *strew- (“to spread, strew”) (cognate with Old Saxon gistri...

STRAIT.d: Narrow; restricted as to space or room; close.
STRAIT.e: From Middle English streit, from Old French estreit (modern form étroit), from Latin strictus, perfect passive participle of stringō (“compress, tighten”). Doublet of stretto and strict.

STRAKE.d: An iron fitting of a traditional wooden wheel, such as a hub component or bearing (e.g., box, bushel), a cleat, or a rim covering.
STRAKE.e: From Middle English strake, from Old English *straca (> Anglo-Latin straca), from Proto-West Germanic *strakō, from Proto-Germanic *strakaz (“straight”). Akin to Old English streċċan (“to make straight, stretch”).

STRAND.d: The shore or beach of the sea or ocean.
STRAND.e: * From Middle English strand, strond, from Old English strand (“strand, sea-shore, shore”), from Proto-West Germanic *strand, from Proto-Germanic *strandō (“edge, rim, shore”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)trAnt- (“strand, border, field”), from Proto-Indo-European *sterh₃- (“to b...

STRATH.e: From Scottish Gaelic srath, from Old Irish srath, from Proto-Celtic *stratos, from Proto-Indo-European *sterh₃-. The meaning was likely influenced by a Cumbric/Pictish cognate (cf. Welsh ystrad). Doublet of stratus.

STREAK.d: An irregular line left from smearing or motion.
STREAK.e: From Middle English streke, from Old English strica, from Proto-Germanic *strikiz, from Proto-Indo-European *streyg- (“line”). Related to North Frisian strijck, Old Saxon striki, Middle Low German streke, Low German streek, Danish streg, Swedish streck, Norwegian Bokmål strek, Ic...

STREAM.d: A small river; a large creek; a body of moving water confined by banks.
STREAM.e:
From Middle English streem, strem, from Old English strēam, from Proto-West Germanic *straum, from Proto-Germanic *straumaz (“stream”), from Proto-Indo-European *srowmos (“river”), from Proto-Indo-European *srew- (“to flow”). Doublet of rheum.
Cognate with Scots strem, streme, st...

STREET.d: A paved part of road, usually in a village or a town.
STREET.e: From Middle English strete, from Anglian Old English strēt (“street”) (cognate West Saxon Old English strǣt) from Proto-West Germanic *strātu (“street”), an early borrowing from Late Latin (via) strāta (“paved (road)”), from Latin strātus, past participle of sternō (“stretch out,...

STRESS.d: A physical, chemical, infective agent aggressing an organism.
STRESS.e: From a shortening of Middle English destresse, borrowed from Old French destrecier, from Latin distringō (“to stretch out”). This form probably coalesced with Middle English stresse, from Old French estrece (“narrowness”), from Vulgar Latin *strictia, from Latin strictus (“narrow...

STRICT.e: Borrowed from Latin strictus, past participle of stringere (“to draw tight, bind, contract”). Doublet of strait and stretto. See stringent, strain. Related to strong.

STRIDE.e: From Middle English striden, from Old English strīdan (“to get by force, pillage, rob; stride”), from Proto-West Germanic *strīdan, from Proto-Germanic *strīdaną. Cognate with Low German striden (“to fight, to stride”), Dutch strijden (“to fight”), German streiten (“to fight, to ...

STRIFE.e: From Middle English strif, stryf, striffe, from Old French estrif, noun derived from estriver, from Frankish *strīban; compare Dutch strijven. More at strive.

STRIKE.d: To delete or cross out; to scratch or eliminate.
STRIKE.e:
From Middle English stryken, from Old English strīcan, from Proto-West Germanic *strīkan, from Proto-Germanic *strīkaną, from Proto-Indo-European *streyg- (“to stroke, rub, press”).
Cognate with Dutch strijken, German streichen, Danish stryge, Icelandic strýkja, strýkva.

STRING.d: A long, thin and flexible structure made from threads twisted together.
STRING.e:
From Middle English string, streng, strynge, from Old English strenġ, from Proto-West Germanic *strangi, from Proto-Germanic *strangiz (“string”), from Proto-Indo-European *strengʰ- (“rope, cord, strand; to tighten”).
Cognate with Scots string (“string”), Dutch streng (“cord, str...

STRIPE.d: A long region of a single colour in a repeating pattern of similar regions.
STRIPE.e: From Middle English stripe, strype, from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German strîpe, from Proto-West Germanic *strīpā, *strīpō, from Proto-Germanic *strīpô. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Striepe (“stripe, strip”), West Frisian stripe (“stripe”), Dutch streep (“stripe”), German Low...

STRIPS.d: Plural of STRIP: A long narrow piece; to remove.

STRIVE.d: To try to achieve a result; to make strenuous effort; to try earnestly and persistently.
STRIVE.e:
From Middle English striven (“to strive”), from Old French estriver (“to compete, quarrel”), from Frankish *strīban (“to exert, make an effort”) from Proto-Germanic *strībaną, or from Frankish *stribēn (“to strive”) from Proto-Germanic *stribāną.
As this verb is conjugated as if ...

STROBE.d: A stroboscopic lamp: a device used to produce regular flashes of light.

STROKE.d: An act of hitting; a blow, a hit.
STROKE.e:
The noun is derived from Middle English strok, stroke (“blow from a weapon, cut”), from Old English strāc, from Proto-West Germanic *straik, from Proto-Germanic *straikaz (“stroke”), from Proto-Indo-European *streyg- (“to rub, stroke; to shear; to strike”).
Sense 3.6.2.2 (“the ob...

STROLL.d: A wandering on foot; an idle and leisurely walk; a ramble; a saunter.
STROLL.e: Borrowed from German strollen, a variant of Alemannic German strolchen, from Strolch (“vagabond; rascal”).

STROMA.d: The tissue structure of an organ, etc., that serves to support it.
STROMA.e: From Latin strōma (“mattress, bed covering”), from Ancient Greek στρῶμα (strôma, “bed”), from στόρνυμι (stórnumi, “to stretch out”).

STRONG.d: Capable of producing great physical force.
STRONG.e: From Middle English strong, strang, from Old English strang, from Proto-West Germanic *strang, from Proto-Germanic *strangaz (“tight, strict, straight, strong”), from Proto-Indo-European *strengʰ- (“taut, stiff, tight”). Cognate with Scots strang (“strong”), Saterland Frisian str...

STRUNG.d: simple past and past participle of string

STUCCO.d: A plaster that is used to coat interior or exterior walls, or used for mouldings.
STUCCO.e: Borrowed from Italian stucco (“coating made of pulverised gypsum, plaster, stucco”) from Old Italian stucco, from Lombardic stucki, *stucchi (“crust, fragment, piece”) from Proto-Germanic *stukkiją (“stump, piece”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tewg- (“to shock, butt, impact”). A...

STUDIO.d: An artist’s or photographer’s workshop or the room in which an artist works.
STUDIO.e:
From Italian studio (“room for study”), from Latin studium.
Doublet of study and etude.

STUDYS.d: Plural of STUDY: The acquisition of knowledge.
STUDYS.e: From Old French estudie, from Latin studium.

STUMPY.d: Like or resembling a stump; short and cut off.

STUPID.e: From Middle French stupide, from Latin stupidus (“struck senseless, amazed”), from stupeō (“be amazed or confounded, be struck senseless”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tup-, *(s)tewp- (“to push, stick”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tew- (“to push, hit”). Cognate with Old High G...

STUPOR.d: A state of greatly dulled or completely suspended consciousness or sensibility; (particularly medicine) a chiefly mental condition marked by absence of spontaneous movement, greatly diminished responsiveness to stimulation, and usually impaired consciousness.
STUPOR.e: Late Middle English, borrowed from Latin stupor (“insensibility, numbness, dullness”). Distantly related (from Proto-Indo-European, via Proto-Germanic) to stint, stub, and steep.

STURDY.d: Of firm build; stiff; stout; strong.
STURDY.e: From Middle English sturdy, stourdy, stordy (“bold, valiant, strong, stern, fierce, rebellious”) (perhaps influenced by Middle English sture, stoure, stor (“strong, robust, harsh, stern, violent, fierce, sturdy”); see English stour), from Old French estourdi (“dazed”), form of es...

STYING.d: Present participle of STY: A pen or enclosure for swine.
STYING.e:
From Middle English sty, from Old English stī, stiġ (“sty, pen, a wooden enclosure; hall”, chiefly in compounds).
Cognate with German Stiege (“wooden crate”), dialectal German Steige (“hen-coop”), Danish sti (“sty, enclosure for swine, sheep, hens, etc.”), Swedish stia (“sty for ...

STYLED.d: Past tense of STYLE: A manner of doing something; fashion.

STYLES.d: Plural of STYLE: A manner of doing something; fashion.

STYLET.e: From French stylet (“stiletto”), from Middle French stilet (“stiletto”), from Old Italian stiletto. Doublet of stiletto.

STYLUS.d: An ancient writing implement consisting of a small rod with a pointed end for scratching letters on clay, wax-covered tablets or other surfaces, and a blunt end for obliterating them.
STYLUS.e: Borrowed from Latin stylus (“a stake or pale”). Probably not directly related to Ancient Greek στῦλος (stûlos, “a pillar”). Doublet of style.

STYMIE.d: A situation where an opponent's ball is directly in the way of one's own ball and the hole, on the putting green (abolished 1952).
STYMIE.e: From the meaning in golf (where the stymie ball blocks the other ball from "seeing" the hole), perhaps from Scots stymie, stimie (“person with poor eyesight”), from Scots stime (“the least bit”). Or from Scots styme (“tiny bit, glimmer”) as in se nocht ane styme (“not to see a gl...

SUBBED.d: Past tense of SUB: Abbreviation of submarine.
SUBBED.e: * Shortened form of any of various words beginning with sub-.

SUBDUE.d: To overcome, quieten, or bring under control.
SUBDUE.e: From Middle English subdewen, subduen, sodewen, from Old French souduire, from Latin subdūcō (“to draw away”), perhaps influenced by subdō (“to subdue, subject”).

SUBFIX.d: One or more letters or sounds added at the bottom of a word to modify its meaning, found in Maya script.

SUBLET.d: To grant a sublease out of property held under a lease.

SUBMIT.d: To yield or give way to another.
SUBMIT.e: From Middle English submitten, borrowed from Latin submittere, infinitive of submittō (“place under, yield”), from sub (“under, from below, up”) + mitto (“to send”). Compare upsend.

SUBORN.d: To induce (someone) to commit an unlawful or malicious act, especially in a corrupt manner.
SUBORN.e:
PIE word
 *upó
Borrowed from Anglo-Norman suburner, subhorner, and Middle French suborner, subourner (“to induce (someone) to commit a crime (specifically perjury) or wrongdoing”) (modern French suborner (“to suborn; to bribe”)), and from its etymon Latin subōrnāre, the present a...

SUBSET.d: A set A such that every element of A is also an element of S.

SUBTLE.e: The adjective is derived from Middle English sotil, soubtil, subtil (“of a person, the mind, etc.: clever, ingenious, penetrating; cunning, sly; insidious; delicate, fine; not dense, light, thin; finely powdered; narrow, slender; etc.”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman sotel, subtil, ...

SUBURB.d: A residential area located on the outskirts of a city or large town that usually includes businesses that cater to its residents; such as schools, grocery stores, shopping centers, restaurants, convenience stores, etc.
SUBURB.e: From Old French suburbe, subburbe, from Latin suburbium (from sub- + urbs (“city”)). Displaced native Old English underburg (literally “sub-” or “under-city”).

SUBWAY.d: An underground railway, especially for mass transit of people in urban areas.

SUBWEB.d: A web making up part of a larger web.

SUCKED.d: Past tense of SUCK: An instance of drawing something into one's mouth by inhaling.
SUCKED.e: From Middle English souken, suken, from Old English sūcan (“to suck”), from Proto-West Germanic *sūkan, from Proto-Germanic *sūkaną (“to suck, suckle”), from Proto-Indo-European *sewg-, *sewk- (“to suck”). Cognate with Scots souke (“to suck”), obsolete Dutch zuiken (“to suck”), L...

SUCKER.d: A person or animal that sucks, especially a breast or udder; especially a suckling animal, young mammal before it is weaned.
SUCKER.e: From Middle English souker, sokere, sukkere, soukere, equivalent to suck (verb) + -er. Compare Saterland Frisian Suuger, West Frisian sûker (“sucker”), Dutch zuiger (“sucker”), German Sauger (“dummy; vacuum”).

SUCKLE.e: From Middle English sukelen; probably a back-formation of Middle English sukeling (“a suckling; infant”), formally equivalent to suck + -le (frequentative suffix). See suckling.

SUDDEN.d: Occurring quickly with little or no warning or expectation; instantly.
SUDDEN.e: From Middle English sodeyn, sodain, from Anglo-Norman sodein, from Old French sodain, subdain (“immediate, sudden”), from Vulgar Latin *subitānus (“sudden”), from Latin subitāneus (“sudden”), from subitus (“sudden", literally, "that which has come stealthily”), originally the pas...

SUDOKU.d: A type of pencil puzzle played on a square grid, requiring each of the columns, each of the rows, and each of the subregions (called "boxes" or "regions") to contain the lowest whole numbers up to the dimension of the puzzle, usually 1 to 9, once each. The subregions are rectangular or square except in variants.

SUDSED.d: Past tense of SUDS: Lather; foam or froth formed by mixing soap and water.
SUDSED.e: From the plural of sud, a variant of sod (“a bubbling or boiling”), equivalent to sud + -s. Related to seethe.

SUDSES.d: Plural of SUDS: Lather; foam or froth formed by mixing soap and water.
SUDSES.e: From the plural of sud, a variant of sod (“a bubbling or boiling”), equivalent to sud + -s. Related to seethe.

SUFFER.e: From Middle English suffren, from Anglo-Norman suffrir, from Latin sufferre (“to offer, hold up, bear, suffer”), from sub- (“up, under”) + ferō (“I carry”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer- (“to bear, carry”). Displaced native Old English þrōwian.

SUFFIX.d: A morpheme added at the end of a word to modify the word's meaning.
SUFFIX.e: Borrowed from Latin suffīxus (“suffix”), from sub- (“under”) + fīxus (perfect passive participle of fīgere (“to fasten, fix”)), equivalent to sub- + -fix.

SUGARS.d: Plural of SUGAR: A sweet crystalline substance.
SUGARS.e: From Old French sucre, from Arabic sukkar.

SUITED.d: Past tense of SUITE: A set of rooms; a set of pieces.

SUITES.d: Plural of SUITE: A set of rooms; a set of pieces.

SUITOR.d: One who pursues someone, especially a woman, for a romantic relationship or marriage; a wooer; one who falls in love with or courts someone.
SUITOR.e: From Middle English sutour, from Anglo-Norman suytour, seuter, from Late Latin secutor (“follower, pursuer”).

SULCUS.d: A furrow or groove in an organ or a tissue, especially that marking the convolutions of the surface of the brain.
SULCUS.e: Borrowed from Latin sulcus (“a furrow made by a plow”). Doublet of sullow ("plough").

SULKED.d: Past tense of SULK: To express ill humor or offence by remaining sullenly silent or withdrawn.
SULKED.e: Back-formation from sulky, of uncertain origin. Probably from Middle English *sulke, *solke (attested in solcenesse (“idleness; laziness”), from Old English āsolcennys (“idleness; slothfulness; sluggishness; laziness”), from āsolcen (“sulky, languid”), from past participle of Old...

SULLEN.d: Having a brooding ill temper; sulky.
SULLEN.e: From Middle English soleyn, from Anglo-Norman soleyn (“alone”), from Old French sole (“single, sole, alone”), from Latin sōlus (“by oneself alone”). The change in meaning from "single" to morose occurred in Middle English.

SULTAN.d: The holder of a secular office, formally subordinate to, but de facto the power behind the throne of, the caliph.
SULTAN.e: Borrowed from Middle French sultan or Medieval Latin sultanus, from Ottoman Turkish سلطان (sultan), from Arabic سُلْطَان (sulṭān, “strength, authority, ruler”). Compare Hebrew שִׁלְטוֹן (shiltón) and סוּלְטָן (sultán). Doublet of soldan.

SULTRY.e: From sulter (“verb (obsolete), a variant of swelter”) + -y; compare sweltry.

SUMMED.d: Past tense of SUM: A quantity obtained by addition or aggregation.
SUMMED.e: From Middle English summe, from Old French summe, from Latin summa (“highest point; sum”), from summus (“highest”).

SUMMER.d: One of four seasons, traditionally the second, marked by the longest and typically hottest days of the year due to the inclination of the Earth and thermal lag. Typically regarded as spanning the months of June, July, and August in the Northern Hemisphere and the months of December, January and February in the Southern Hemisphere.
SUMMER.e:
From Middle English somer, sumer, from Old English sumor (“summer”), from Proto-West Germanic *sumar, from Proto-Germanic *sumaraz (“summer”), from Proto-Indo-European *sm̥-h₂-ó-, oblique of *semh₂- (“summer, year”).
Cognate with Scots somer, sumer, simer (“summer”), West Frisian...

SUMMIT.d: The topmost point or surface of a thing; the apex, the peak.
SUMMIT.e:
PIE word
 *upó
The noun is derived from Late Middle English somet, somete (“head, top”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman sumet and Middle French sommet (masculine), somete, sommette (“top of a thing; highest point of a mountain”) (feminine) (modern French sommet), from Old Fr...

SUMMON.d: To call people together; to convene; to convoke.
SUMMON.e: From Anglo-Norman somoundre, from Old French sumundre, from Latin summonēre, itself from sub + monēre, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *monéyeti, causative from *men- (“to think”).

SUNBED.d: A device emitting ultraviolet radiation used to produce a cosmetic suntan.

SUNBOW.d: A bow or arc of prismatic colors like a rainbow, caused by refraction through a spray of water from a cataract, waterfall, fountain, etc., rather than through droplets of rain.

SUNDAE.d: A dessert consisting of ice cream with various toppings.

SUNDER.e: From Middle English sunder, from Old English sundor- (“separate, different”), from Proto-Germanic *sundraz (“isolated, particular, alone”), from Proto-Indo-European *snter-, *seni-, *senu-, *san- (“apart, without, for oneself”). Cognate with Old Saxon sundar (“particular, special...

SUNDEW.d: Any of a group of insectivorous plants in the genus Drosera that catch insects by sticky droplets ("dew") at the end of hairs on the leaves and grow in boggy ground all over the world.
SUNDEW.e: From sun + dew. Cognate with Dutch zonnedauw, Icelandic sóldögg, German Sonnentau.

SUNDRY.d: More than one or two but not very many; a number of, several.
SUNDRY.e: The adjective is derived from Middle English sondri, sondry, syndry (“individually; occasionally; separately; variously”) [and other forms], from Old English syndriġ (“alone, distinct, separate, single; sundry, various; concerning a single person, own, particular, peculiar, priva...

SUNNED.d: Past tense of SUN: The star that is closest to the Earth.
SUNNED.e: From Middle English sonne, sunne, from Old English sunne, from Proto-West Germanic *sunnā, from Proto-Germanic *sunnǭ, from heteroclitic inanimate Proto-Indo-European *sh₂wen-, oblique of Proto-Indo-European *sóh₂wl̥ (“sun”). See also Saterland Frisian Sunne, West Frisian sinne, ...

SUNSET.d: The moment each evening when the sun disappears below the western horizon.
SUNSET.e: From Middle English son-sett, Sonne set, equivalent to sun + set. In Gower's Confessio Amantis, before 1393.

SUNTAN.d: A darkening of the skin resulting from exposure to sunlight or similar light sources.

SUPERB.d: First-rate; of the highest quality; exceptionally good.

SUPINE.e: The adjective is borrowed from Latin supīnus, from *sup- (see sub (“under”)) + -īnus (“of, pertaining to”). The word is cognate with Catalan supí, Italian supino, Old French sovin, Middle French souvin, Anglo-Norman supin, Old Occitan sobin, sopin, Portuguese supino, Spanish supi...

SUPPED.d: Past tense of SUP: To sip; to take a small amount of food or drink into the mouth, especially with a spoon.
SUPPED.e: The verb is from Middle English soupen, from Old English sūpan (“to sip, drink, taste”), from Proto-Germanic *sūpaną (compare Dutch zuipen (“to drink, tipple, booze”), German saufen (“to drink, booze”), Swedish supa (“to drink, swallow”)), from Proto-Indo-European *sub-, compare ...

SUPPER.d: Comparative form of SUP: To sip; to take a small amount of food or drink into the mouth, especially with a spoon.
SUPPER.e: The verb is from Middle English soupen, from Old English sūpan (“to sip, drink, taste”), from Proto-Germanic *sūpaną (compare Dutch zuipen (“to drink, tipple, booze”), German saufen (“to drink, booze”), Swedish supa (“to drink, swallow”)), from Proto-Indo-European *sub-, compare ...

SUPPLE.e: From Middle English souple, from Old French souple, soupple (“soft, lithe, yielding”), from Latin supplic-, supplex (“suppliant, submissive, kneeling”), of uncertain formation. Either from sub + plicō (“bend”) (compare complex), or from sub + plācō (“placate”). More at sub-, plac...

SUPPLY.d: To provide (something), to make (something) available for use.
SUPPLY.e:
From Middle English supplien, borrowed from Old French soupleer, souploier, from Latin suppleo (“to fill up, make full, complete, supply”).
The Middle English spelling was modified to conform to Latin etymology.

SURETY.e: From Middle English surete, attested since the early 1300s in the sense "guarantee, promise, pledge, assurance", from Anglo-Norman seurté/Old French seurté with the same meaning (whence modern French sûreté), from Latin sēcūritās. Equivalent to sure + -ty. The senses "security, s...

SURFED.d: Past tense of SURF: Waves that break on an ocean shoreline.
SURFED.e: Probably from earlier suff, suffe (“the inrush of the sea towards the shore”), possibly from Middle English suffe. Compare sough, surf (“a gutter, drain, sewer, trench”) and sough (“a soothing, gentle, murmuring sound of wind or water”). Alternatively, possibly of Indo-Aryan orig...

SURREY.d: An inland county of South East England, bordered clockwise by Greater London, Kent, East Sussex, West Sussex, Hampshire and Berkshire.
SURREY.e: From Old English Sūþrigē, Sūþrigēa (“southern region”), from sūþerne (“southern”) + -gē (“district, region”).

SURVEY.d: The act of surveying; a general view.
SURVEY.e: From Middle English surveyen, from Old French sourveoir, surveer (“to oversee”), from sour-, sur- (“over”) + veoir, veeir (“to see”), from Latin videre. See sur- and vision. Related to supervision.

SUSLIK.d: Any of several large Eurasian squirrels, of the genera Citellus or Spermophilus.

SUTLER.d: A person who follows an army, selling provisions.

SUTTEE.d: The traditional custom of a Hindu woman giving herself up to be cremated on her husband’s funeral pyre as a sign of her devotion.
SUTTEE.e: From Sanskrit सती (satī́, “good and virtuous or faithful wife”), from सत् (sát, “true, good, right etc.”). In English usage since 1786. Doublet of sin.

SUTURE.d: A seam formed by sewing two edges together, especially to join pieces of skin in surgically treating a wound.
SUTURE.e: From Middle English suture, from Latin sūtūra (“suture”), from suere (“sew, join or tack together”) + -tūra (forms action nouns).

SVELTE.e: From French svelte, from Italian svelto (“stretched out”), past participle of svellere (“to pluck out, root out”), from Vulgar Latin *exvellere, from ex + vellere (“to pluck, stretch”).

SWAMPY.d: Soggy and marshy; wet like a swamp.
SWAMPY.e: From swamp + -y. Compare Saterland Frisian sumpich (“swampy”), Dutch sompig, zompig (“swampy, soggy”), German sumpfig (“swampy”), Swedish sumpig (“swampy”).

SWATCH.d: A piece, pattern, or sample, generally of cloth or a similar material.
SWATCH.e: From earlier Northern England dialectal swache (“the counterfoil or counterstock of a tally”) (1512); further etymology unknown. Cognate with Scots swach, swatch. Compare English swath, swathe. Compare also Old English swæcc (“taste; flavour; odour; fragrance”).

SWATHE.e: From Middle English swathe, swath, from Old English swaþu, swæþ (“bandage”), probably akin to Old English swaþul, sweþel (“a swathe, wrap, band, bandage”).

SWAYED.d: Past tense of SWAY: The act of swaying; a swaying motion; a swing or sweep of a weapon.
SWAYED.e: From earlier swey (“to fall, swoon”), from Middle English sweyen, from Old English *swǣġan (“to bend, bow”), from Proto-West Germanic *swaigijan, from Proto-Germanic *swaigijaną (compare Saterland Frisian swooie (“to swing, wave, wobble”)), from Proto-Indo-European *sweh₁- (compa...

SWEATY.e: From Middle English swety, equivalent to sweat + -y.

SWEETS.d: Plural of SWEET: Having the taste of sugar.

SWERVE.d: To stray; to wander; to rove.
SWERVE.e: From Middle English swerven, swarven, from Old English sweorfan (“to file; rub; polish; scour; turn aside”), from Proto-Germanic *swerbaną (“to rub off; wipe; mop”), from Proto-Indo-European *swerbʰ- (“to turn; wipe; sweep”). Cognate with West Frisian swerve (“to wander; roam; sw...

SWIFTS.d: Plural of SWIFT: Happening quickly; a bird.

SWITCH.d: A device to turn electric current on and off or direct its flow.
SWITCH.e: Perhaps from Middle Dutch swijch (“twig”), first attested in c. 1592. The mechanical device for altering the direction of something sense is first attested in c. 1797, pertaining to pivoted rails on minecart railways, which were once wooden.

SWIVEL.d: A piece, such as a ring or hook, attached to another piece by a pin, in such a manner as to permit rotation about the pin as an axis.
SWIVEL.e: From Middle English swyvel, swivel, from a derivative of Old English swīfan (“to revolve”), + -el, an instrumental suffix, equivalent to swive + -el.

SWOOSH.d: To move with a rushing or swirling sound

SYMBOL.d: A character or glyph representing an idea, concept or object.
SYMBOL.e: From French symbole, from Latin symbolus, symbolum (“a sign, mark, token, symbol, in Late Latin also a creed”), from Ancient Greek σύμβολον (súmbolon, “a sign by which one infers something; a mark, token, badge, ticket, tally, check, a signal, watchword, outward sign”), from συμβ...

SYNCED.d: Past tense of SYNC: Clipping of synchronization or synchrony.

SYNDIC.d: A government official having different duties depending on the country; also, a magistrate, especially one of the Chief Magistrates of Geneva, Switzerland.
SYNDIC.e: Borrowed from French syndic (“delegated representative; a chief magistrate of Geneva; a censor; critic (obsolete)”), from Late Latin syndicus (“representative of a corporation or town, syndic”), from Ancient Greek σύνδικος (súndikos, “advocate of a defendant”), from σῠν- (sŭn-, p...

SYNTAX.d: A set of rules that govern how words are combined to form phrases and sentences.
SYNTAX.e: Partly from Late Latin syntaxis and partly from its etymon, Ancient Greek σύνταξις (súntaxis), from σύν (sún, “together”) + τάξις (táxis, “arrangement”), from τάσσω (tássō, “I arrange”). Doublet of syntaxis.

SYSTEM.d: A group or set of related things that operate together as a complex whole.
SYSTEM.e: Partly borrowed from Middle French sisteme, systeme, partly directly from its etymon Late Latin systēma (“harmony; musical scale; set of celestial objects; set of troops; system”), from Ancient Greek σύστημα (sústēma, “musical scale; organized body; whole made of several parts or...

SYZYGY.d: An alignment of three celestial bodies (for example, the Sun, Earth, and Moon) such that one body is directly between the other two, such as occurs at an eclipse.
SYZYGY.e: From Late Latin sȳzygia (“conjunction”), from Ancient Greek συζυγία (suzugía, “union, yoke, pair”). This word was recognized as English in 1847 (in its astronomical meaning).

TABARD.d: A silk banner attached to a bugle or trumpet.
TABARD.e: From Old French tabart (“simple sleeveless overtunic; heavy overmantel”), of unknown origin.

TABBED.d: Past tense of TAB: A small flap or strip of material attached to or inserted into something, for holding, manipulation, identification, opening etc.

TABBER.d: Comparative form of TAB: A small flap or strip of material attached to or inserted into something, for holding, manipulation, identification, opening etc.

TABLED.d: Past tense of TABLE: A piece of furniture with a flat top.
TABLED.e: From Old English tabule, from Latin tabula.

TABLES.d: Plural of TABLE: A piece of furniture with a flat top.
TABLES.e: From Old English tabule, from Latin tabula.

TABLET.d: A slab of clay, stone or wood used for inscription.
TABLET.e: From Middle English tablet, from Old French tablete (Modern French tablette), diminutive of table (“table”).

TACKED.d: Past tense of TACK: A small nail with a flat head.
TACKED.e: From Middle English tak, takke (“hook; staple; nail”), from Old Northern French taque (“nail, pin, peg”), from Frankish *takkō, from Proto-Germanic *takkô (“tip; point; protrusion; prong; tine; jag; spike; twig”), of unknown origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dHgʰ-n-,...

TACKLE.d: A device for grasping an object and an attached means of moving it, as a rope and hook.
TACKLE.e: From Middle English takel (“gear, apparatus”), from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German takel (“ship's rigging”), perhaps related to Middle Dutch taken (“to grasp, seize”). Akin to Danish takkel (“tackle”), Swedish tackel (“tackle”). More at take.

TACTIC.d: A maneuver, or action calculated to achieve some end.
TACTIC.e: Borrowed from New Latin tactica, from Ancient Greek τακτικός (taktikós, “fit for ordering”), from τάσσω (tássō, “to order, to arrange”).

TAGGED.d: Past tense of TAG: Physical appendage.
TAGGED.e: From Middle English tagge (“small piece hanging from a garment”), probably of North Germanic origin. Compare Norwegian tagg (“point; prong; barb; tag”), Swedish tagg (“thorn; prickle; tine”), Icelandic tág (“a willow-twig”). Compare also tack.

TAGGER.d: Comparative form of TAG: Physical appendage.
TAGGER.e: From Middle English tagge (“small piece hanging from a garment”), probably of North Germanic origin. Compare Norwegian tagg (“point; prong; barb; tag”), Swedish tagg (“thorn; prickle; tine”), Icelandic tág (“a willow-twig”). Compare also tack.

TAHINI.d: A paste made from ground sesame seeds, and used to make hummus, baba ghanoush etc.
TAHINI.e: From Arabic طَحِينَة (ṭaḥīna), from the root ط ح ن (ṭ-ḥ-n) related to grinding. Final -i most probably from Levantine dialects or from Greek ταχίνι (tachíni).

TAHSIL.d: An administrative division in India and Pakistan.
TAHSIL.e: From Hindi तहसील (tahsīl) and Urdu تحصیل.

TAILED.d: Past tense of TAIL: The caudal appendage of an animal that is attached to its posterior and near the anus.
TAILED.e: From Middle English tail, tayl, teil, from Old English tæġl (“tail”), from Proto-West Germanic *tagl, from Proto-Germanic *taglą (“hair, fiber; hair of a tail”), from Proto-Indo-European *doḱ- (“hair of the tail”), from Proto-Indo-European *deḱ- (“to tear, fray, shred”). Cognate ...

TAILOR.d: A person who makes, repairs, or alters clothes professionally, especially suits and men's clothing.
TAILOR.e: Inherited from Middle English taillour, from Anglo-Norman taillour, from Old French tailleor, from taillier, from Late Latin tāliō, from Latin tālea (“a cutting”). Doublet of tailleur.

TAIPAN.d: A foreign businessman in China; a tycoon.
TAIPAN.e: From Cantonese 大班 (daai⁶ baan¹, “big shot, rich businessman”), originally as taepan. Related to tycoon, from Japanese 大君(たいくん) (taikun).

TAJINE.d: An earthenware cooking pot of North African origin, consisting of a shallow, round dish without handles and a tall, conical or dome-shaped lid.
TAJINE.e: From Moroccan Arabic طَجِين (ṭajīn), from Arabic طَاجِن (ṭājin, “shallow earthen pot”), from Ancient Greek τάγηνον (tágēnon, “frying pan, saucepan”), further etymology unknown.

TALBOT.d: An English surname thought to be of Norman (Germanic) origin.
TALBOT.e: From Middle English talbot, from Old French talebot (“bandit”); a Norman nickname applied to robbers who blackened their faces to avoid recognition, from Old High German *Talbald (personal name), from Old High German tal (“valley, dale”) + bald (“bold, courageous”).

TALCED.d: Past tense of TALC: Originally a large range of transparent or glistening foliated minerals. Examples include mica, selenite and the hydrated magnesium silicate that the term talc generally has referred to in modern times (see below). Also an item made of such a mineral and depending for its function on the special nature of the mineral (see next). Medieval writers adopted the term from the Arabic.
TALCED.e: From Middle French talc, from Arabic طَلْق (ṭalq), from Persian تلک (talk), from Middle Persian [Term?] (“medicament”).

TALCUM.d: Powdered and perfumed talc for toilet use.
TALCUM.e: From talc + -um, from Medieval Latin talcum, from Arabic طَلْق (ṭalq).

TALENT.d: A marked natural ability or skill.
TALENT.e: From Middle English talent, from Old English talente, borrowed from the plural of Latin talentum (“a Grecian weight; a talent of money”), from Ancient Greek τάλαντον (tálanton, “balance, a particular weight, especially of gold, sum of money, a talent”). Compare Old High German ta...

TALKED.d: Past tense of TALK: To communicate, usually by means of speech.
TALKED.e: From Middle English talken, talkien, from Old English *tealcian (“to talk, chat”), from Proto-West Germanic *talkōn, from Proto-Germanic *talkōną (“to talk, chatter”), frequentative form of Proto-Germanic *talōną (“to count, recount, tell”), from Proto-Indo-European *dol-, *del- ...

TALKIE.d: A movie with sound, as opposed to a silent film.
TALKIE.e: Clipping of talking picture, via + -ie, and thus morphologically parallel with movie.

TALLOW.d: A hard animal fat obtained from suet, etc.; used in cooking as well as to make candles, soap and lubricants.
TALLOW.e: From Middle English talow, talgh, from Old English *tealh, *tealg, (compare Old English tælg, telg (“dye”)), from Proto-West Germanic *talg, from Proto-Germanic *talgaz (compare Dutch talg, German Talg), from Proto-Indo-European *del- (“to flow”) (compare Middle Irish delt (“dew”...

TALOSE.d: The aldohexose 6-(hydroxymethyl)oxane-2,3,4,5-tetrol that is the 2-epimer of galactose.

TAMALE.d: A Mexican dish of cornmeal dough shell filled with various ingredients (e.g. chopped beef, pork, sweet filling) then steamed in corn husks.
TAMALE.e: Back-formation from the plural tamales, derived from Latin American Spanish tamales, plural of tamal, derived from Nahuatl tamalli (“wrapped”), derived from Proto-Uto-Aztecan [Term?]. Compare O'odham čïmait (“tortilla”), Hopi tïma (“stone griddle for cooking corn flatbread”), Ute...

TAMING.d: Present participle of TAME: Accustomed to human contact.
TAMING.e: From Middle English tame, tome, weak inflection forms of Middle English tam, tom, from Old English tam, tom (“domesticated, tame”), from Proto-West Germanic *tam (“tame”), from Proto-Germanic *tamaz (“brought into the home, tame”), from Proto-Indo-European *demh₂- (“to tame, domi...

TAMPED.d: Past tense of TAMP: To plug up with clay, earth, dry sand, sod, or other material, as a hole bored in a rock.
TAMPED.e: Probably a back-formation from tampin (misinterpreted as tamping), a variant of tampion.

TAMPER.d: A person or thing that tamps.

TAMPON.d: A plug of cotton or other absorbent material inserted into a body cavity or wound to absorb fluid, especially one inserted in the vagina during menstruation.
TAMPON.e: First attested in 1848. Borrowed from French tampon, from Middle French tampon, a nasalised variant of tapon, a diminutive or augmented form of Old French tape (“plug, bung, tap”), from Frankish *tappō (“stopper, plug”), from Proto-Germanic *tappô (“plug, tap”). Cognate with Old ...

TANDEM.d: A carriage pulled by two or more draught animals (generally draught horses) harnessed one behind the other, both providing pulling power but only the animal in front being able to steer.
TANDEM.e:
PIE word
 *téh₂m
The noun is borrowed from Latin tandem (“of time: at last, at length, finally”), applied humorously in English to two horses harnessed “at length” (that is, in a single line) instead of side-by-side. Tandem is derived from tam (“so, to such an extent”) + -dem (de...

TANGED.d: Past tense of TANG: A refreshingly sharp aroma or flavor.
TANGED.e: From Middle English tange, variant of tonge (“tongs, fang”), from Old Norse tangi (“pointed metal tool”), perhaps related to Old Norse tunga (“tongue”). But see also Middle Dutch tanger (“sharp, tart, pinching”).

TANGLE.e: From Middle English tanglen, probably of North Germanic origin, compare Swedish taggla (“to disorder”), Old Norse þǫngull, þang (“tangle; seaweed”), see Etymology 2 below.

TANIST.d: The heir presumptive to the chieftainship or kingship of a Celtic clan in ancient Ireland, Scotland or Mann.
TANIST.e: From Irish tánaiste (“second-in-command”). Doublet of Tánaiste.

TANKED.d: Past tense of TANK: A closed container for liquids or gases.
TANKED.e:
From Portuguese tanque (“tank, liquid container”), from an Indo-Aryan language such as Gujarati ટાંકી (ṭā̃kī, “cistern”) or Marathi टांकी (ṭāṅkī). Compare the Arabic verb اِسْتَنْقَعَ (istanqaʕa, “to become stagnant, to stagnate”).
In the sense of armoured vehicle, first attested...

TANNED.d: Past tense of TAN: A light, brown-like colour.
TANNED.e: From Middle English tan, from Old French tan (“tanbark”), from Gaulish *tannos (“green oak”) – compare Breton tann (“red oak”), Old Cornish tannen –, from Proto-Celtic *tannos (“green oak”), of uncertain origin, but perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *(s)dʰonu (“fir”). Per this hyp...

TANNER.d: Comparative form of TAN: A light, brown-like colour.
TANNER.e: From Middle English tan, from Old French tan (“tanbark”), from Gaulish *tannos (“green oak”) – compare Breton tann (“red oak”), Old Cornish tannen –, from Proto-Celtic *tannos (“green oak”), of uncertain origin, but perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *(s)dʰonu (“fir”). Per this hyp...

TANNIN.d: Tannic acid or any of its derivatives.
TANNIN.e: From French tannin, from Latin tannum (“oak bark”), from Gaulish *tannos (“oak”). Related to tan.

TANNOY.e: A genericised trademark of Tannoy Ltd, a manufacturer of public address systems. "Tannoy" is a syllabic abbreviation of tantalum alloy, which was the material used in a type of electrolytic rectifier developed by the company.

TANTRA.d: A Hindu or Buddhist religious or esoteric text.
TANTRA.e: From Sanskrit तन्त्र (tantra), from Proto-Indo-European *ten-tlo- /*tn̥-tlo-, from *ten-. Doublet of tar (“string instrument”).

TAPING.d: Present participle of TAPE: Flexible material in a roll with a sticky surface on one or both sides; adhesive tape.
TAPING.e: From Middle English tape, tappe, from Old English tæppa, tæppe (“ribbon, tape”); further origin unclear. Probably akin to Old Frisian tapia (“to pull, rip, tear”), Middle Low German tappen, tāpen (“to grab, pull, rip, tear, snatch”), Middle High German zāfen, zāven (“to pull, tea...

TAPPED.d: Past tense of TAP: A conical peg or pin used to close and open the hole or vent in a container.
TAPPED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English tappe (“hollow device for controlling the flow of liquid from a hole, cock, faucet, spigot; hole through which the liquid flows; the liquid which thus flows”), from Old English tæppa, from Proto-West Germanic *tappō, from Proto-Germanic *ta...

TAPPER.d: Comparative form of TAP: A conical peg or pin used to close and open the hole or vent in a container.
TAPPER.e: The noun is derived from Middle English tappe (“hollow device for controlling the flow of liquid from a hole, cock, faucet, spigot; hole through which the liquid flows; the liquid which thus flows”), from Old English tæppa, from Proto-West Germanic *tappō, from Proto-Germanic *ta...

TAPPET.d: A lever or projection which is moved by some other piece, as a cam, or intended to tap or touch something else, in order to produce change or regulate motion.
TAPPET.e: From tap + -et, possibly influenced by homophony with "tap it."

TARGET.d: A butt or mark to shoot at, as for practice, or to test the accuracy of a firearm, or the force of a projectile.
TARGET.e: From Middle French targette, targuete, diminutive of targe (“light shield”), from Old French, from Frankish *targa (“buckler”), akin to Old Norse targa (“small round shield”) (whence also Old English targe, targa (“shield”)) from Proto-Germanic *targǭ (“edge”), from Proto-Indo-Eu...

TARIFF.d: A system of government-imposed duties levied on imported or exported goods; a list of such duties, or the duties themselves.
TARIFF.e: From French tarif, from Italian tariffa, from Ottoman Turkish تعرفه (ta'rife), from Classical Persian تَعْرِفَه (ta'rifa), from Arabic تَعْرِفَة (taʕrifa, “tariff, rate”), from the root ع ر ف (ʕ r f).

TARING.d: Present participle of TARE: A vetch, or the seed of a vetch (genus Vicia, esp. Vicia sativa)
TARING.e: From Middle English tare (“vetch”), from Old English *taru, from Proto-West Germanic *taru.

TARMAC.e: Clipping of tarmacadam, which is from tar + macadam (“crushed stones”). Originally a trademark owned by its inventor, Edgar Hooley.

TARPAN.d: An extinct Northern European wild horse, Equus ferus ferus.
TARPAN.e: Borrowed from Russian тарпа́н (tarpán), from Turkic (Kazakh тарпаң (tarpañ) or Kyrgyz тарпан (tarpan)).

TARPIT.d: A lake of asphalt formed when subterranean bitumen leaks to the ground surface. Such pits are important in forming fossil fuel reserves; they are also apt to trap passing animals, which become fossilized in the tar.

TARPON.d: Any of several fishes of the family Elopidae or Megalopidae, especially a large silvery game fish.
TARPON.e: Compare Dutch tarpoen. Suggestions that the term derives from a Native American term are unlikely.

TARRED.d: Past tense of TAR: A black, oily, sticky, viscous substance, consisting mainly of hydrocarbons derived from organic materials such as wood, peat, or coal.
TARRED.e:
PIE word
 *dóru
From Middle English ter, terr, tarr, from Old English teoru, from Proto-West Germanic *teru, from Proto-Germanic *terwą, from Proto-Indo-European *derwo-, from *dóru (“tree”).
See also Saterland Frisian Taar, West Frisian tarre, tar, Dutch teer, German Teer; also ...

TARRER.d: Comparative form of TAR: A black, oily, sticky, viscous substance, consisting mainly of hydrocarbons derived from organic materials such as wood, peat, or coal.
TARRER.e:
PIE word
 *dóru
From Middle English ter, terr, tarr, from Old English teoru, from Proto-West Germanic *teru, from Proto-Germanic *terwą, from Proto-Indo-European *derwo-, from *dóru (“tree”).
See also Saterland Frisian Taar, West Frisian tarre, tar, Dutch teer, German Teer; also ...

TARSAL.d: Of or relating to the tarsus.
TARSAL.e: From tarsus + -al, cognate to New Latin tarsālis.

TARSUS.d: The part between the main part of the hindlimb and the metatarsus in terrestrial vertebrates.

TARTAN.d: Woven woollen fabric with a distinctive pattern of coloured stripes intersecting at right angles originally associated with Scottish Highlanders, now with different clans (though this only dates from the late 18th century) and some Scottish families and institutions having their own patterns; (countable) a particular type of such fabric.
TARTAN.e: The noun is an unadapted borrowing from Scots tartan, from Old Scots tartane, tertane, probably from Old French tertaine, tiretaine (“cloth of wool mixed with cotton or linen”), probably from tiret (“kind of precious cloth”) + -aine modelled after futaine (“woven cloth made from ...

TARTAR.d: A red compound deposited during wine making; mostly potassium hydrogen tartrate — a source of cream of tartar.
TARTAR.e: From Old French tartre, from Medieval Latin tartarum, from Byzantine Greek τάρταρον (tártaron), said to be from Arabic دُرْدِيّ (durdiyy), though it is already found in Pelagonius’s Ars veterinaria 46 in the adjective tartarālis, if the reading is correct. Arabic etymon from Pers...

TASKED.d: Past tense of TASK: A piece of work done as part of one’s duties.
