TASKED.e: From Middle English taske (“task, tax”), from Old Northern French tasque, (compare Old French variant tasche), from Medieval Latin tasca, alteration of taxa, from Latin taxō (“to censure; to charge”). Doublet of tax.

TASSEL.d: A ball-shaped bunch of plaited or otherwise entangled threads from which at one end protrudes a cord on which the ball is hung, and which may have loose, dangling threads at the other end (often used as decoration along the bottom of garments, curtains or other hangings).
TASSEL.e: From Middle English tassel, from Old French tassel, from Latin taxillus (“small cube”), from tālus (“ankle”).

TASSES.d: Plural of TASS: A heap, pile.
TASSES.e: Partly from Middle English tas (“heap”), from Old French tas (“heap”), from Frankish *tas (“mass, pile”); and partly from Middle English taas (“heap, mow of corn”), from Old English tas (“heap, mow of grain”); both from Proto-Germanic *tasaz, *tassaz (“heap, mow, stack”), from Pr...

TASTED.d: Past tense of TASTE: The sensation of flavor; to sample.

TASTER.d: An object in which, or by which, food or drink is tasted, such as a small cup.
TASTER.e: From Middle English taster; equivalent to taste + -er.

TASTES.d: Plural of TASTE: The sensation of flavor; to sample.

TATAMI.d: Straw matting, in a standard size, used as a floor covering in Japanese houses.

TATTED.d: Past tense of TAT: Cheap and vulgar tastelessness; sleaze.

TATTER.d: Comparative form of TAT: Cheap and vulgar tastelessness; sleaze.

TATTLE.e: From Middle Dutch tatelen, tateren (“to babble, chatter”) (modern Dutch tatelen, tateren (“to talk, chatter”)), originally imitative. The word is cognate with Saterland Frisian tätelje (“to talk nonsense, babble”), Middle Low German tāteren, tadderen (“to babble, chatter”) (whenc...

TATTOO.d: An image made on a body part, usually the skin with ink and a needle.
TATTOO.e: From earlier tattaow, tattow, a borrowing from a Polynesian language, e.g. Samoan tatau (“tattoo; to tap, to strike”).

TAUGHT.d: simple past and past participle of teach
TAUGHT.e: From Middle English taught(e), tau(h)t(e), from Old English tāhte, tǣhte, from Proto-Germanic *taihtē.

TAUTED.d: Past tense of TAUT: Under tension, like a stretched bowstring, rope, or sail; tight.
TAUTED.e: The adjective is derived from Middle English taught [and other forms], Early Middle English tohte, towehte (“strained, stretched; distended; tight; firm”), probably from tough, touth, touʒth, toʒt (“powerful, strong; fierce, violent; not tender, tough; hardy, resilient; steadfast...

TAUTOG.d: A fish of the wrasse family found in salt water off of eastern North America from Nova Scotia to South Carolina (Tautoga onitis).
TAUTOG.e: Borrowed from Narragansett tautauog, plural of taut.

TAVERN.e: From Middle English taverne, from Old French taverne (“wine shop”), from Latin taberna (“inn”). Doublet of taberna and taverna.

TAWDRY.e: Shortened from tawdry lace; originally a corruption and rebracketing of Saint Audrey lace (from Old English Æðelþrȳð). The lace necklaces sold to pilgrims to Saint Audrey fell out of fashion in the 17th century, and so tawdry was reinterpreted as meaning “cheap” or “vulgar”.

TAWING.d: Present participle of TAW: To prepare or dress, as hemp, by beating; to tew.
TAWING.e:
From Middle English tawen, from Old English tawian (“to do, make”), from Proto-West Germanic *tawōn, a variant of Proto-West Germanic *tauwjan, from Proto-Germanic *tawjaną (“to make, prepare”), from Proto-Indo-European *dewh₂- (“to tie to, secure”).
Cognate with Dutch touwen (“t...

TAXING.d: Present participle of TAX: Money or goods collected by a government (or an entity to whom the government has delegated this power, e.g. in tax farming) to fund itself and its services, for example by levying a charge on income, purchases (sales), property or harvest, other than that money which is collected by the government in exchange for specific goods (e.g. the purchase of surplus vehicles).
TAXING.e: From Middle English taxe, from Middle French taxe, from Medieval Latin taxa, from Latin taxō (“to appraise, value, estimate; (medieval) to tax”). Doublet of task. Displaced native Old English gafol, which was also the word for “tribute” and “rent”.

TEABAG.d: A cloth or paper sachet containing tea leaves or herbal tea, designed to act as an infuser when submerged in hot water.

TEACUP.d: A small cup, usually with a handle, commonly used for drinking tea; normally sits in a saucer as part of a tea set.

TEAING.d: Present participle of TEA: The tea plant (Camellia sinensis); (countable) a variety of this plant.
TEAING.e: First appears c. 1655, in the writings of Álvaro Semedo. From Dutch thee, from Hokkien 茶 (tê) (Amoy dialect), from Old Chinese, ultimately from Proto-Sino-Tibetan *s-la (“leaf, tea”). Introduced to English and other Western European languages by the Dutch East India Company, who ...

TEAMED.d: Past tense of TEAM: A set of draught animals, such as two horses in front of a carriage.
TEAMED.e: From Middle English tem, teem, teme, from Old English tēam (“child-bearing, offspring, brood, set of draught animals”), from Proto-West Germanic *taum, from Proto-Germanic *taumaz (“that which draws or pulls”), from Proto-Germanic *taugijaną, *tugōną, *teuhōną, *teuhaną (“to lead...

TEAPOT.d: A vessel for brewing and serving tea, typically with a handle and spout.

TEAPOY.d: Originally, a three-legged decorative stand or table; now, especially, one with recesses for holding tea caddies and/or a tea service.
TEAPOY.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
Borrowed from Hindi तिपाई (tipāī), Urdu تپائی (tipāi, “teapoy”), from a merger of Sanskrit त्रिपाद (tripāda, “tripod”) + Classical Persian سه پای (sih-pāy, “tripod”), with the spelling of the first element influenced by association with tea. Sanskrit त्रि (tri, ...

TEARED.d: Past tense of TEAR: To rend (a solid material) by holding or restraining in two places and pulling apart, whether intentionally or not; to destroy or separate.
TEARED.e:
From Middle English teren, from Old English teran (“to tear, lacerate”), from Proto-Germanic *teraną (“to tear, tear apart, rip”), from Proto-Indo-European *der- (“to tear, tear apart”).
Cognate with Scots tere, teir, tair (“to rend, lacerate, wound, rip, tear out”), Dutch teren ...

TEASEL.d: Any of several plants of the genus Dipsacus.
TEASEL.e: From Middle English tasel, tesel, from Old English tǣsel, tǣsl, from Proto-West Germanic *taisilu.

TEASES.d: Plural of TEAS: plural of tea

TEATED.d: Past tense of TEAT: The projection of a mammary gland from which, on female therian mammals, milk is secreted.
TEATED.e: From Middle English tete, from Old French tete (“teat”) (compare French tette), from Frankish *tittā, *tittō, from Proto-Germanic *tittaz (“teat; nipple; breast”), ultimately of expressive origin. Compare Old High German zizza ("teat"; modern German Zitze), whence also Italian zi...

TECHED.e: Clipping of technology, technician, and technique.

TECHIE.d: One who works with, or has an interest in, technology or computers.
TECHIE.e: From tech + -ie, q.v. Compare techy and yuppie.

TECHNE.d: craft; practice; making or doing, as contrasted with episteme or knowing

TECHNO.d: A repetitive style of music originally produced for use in a continuous DJ set. The central rhythmic component is most often in common time (4/4), where time is marked with a bass drum on each quarter note pulse, a backbeat played by snare or clap on the second and fourth pulses of the bar, and an open hi-hat sounding every second eighth note.

TEDIUM.e: From Latin taedium, from taedēre (“to weary”).

TEEING.d: Present participle of TEE: The name of the Latin-script letter T/t.
TEEING.e:
* From Middle English [Term?], from Old English te, from Latin tē (the name of the letter T).
* (computing): By analogy with a T-shaped pipe that sends fluids in two directions.

TEEMED.d: Past tense of TEEM: To be stocked to overflowing.
TEEMED.e: From Middle English temen (“to bear, to support”), from Anglian Old English tēman (“to give birth”) (West Saxon Old English tīeman), from Proto-West Germanic *taumijan (“to bridle”), from Proto-Germanic *taumijaną, from *taumaz ("bridle", continued in Modern English as team).

TEENSY.e: Baby-talk alteration of teeny, from tiny, probably modelled after itsy, itsy-bitsy, etc.; see -sy.

TEEPEE.d: A cone-shaped tent traditionally used by many native peoples of the Great Plains of North America.
TEEPEE.e: From the Lakota word thípi (/ˈtʰipi/), which consists of two elements: the verb thí (“to dwell”), and pi, a pluralising enclitic (a suffix-like ending that marks the subject of the verb as plural), which means they dwell. Lakota verbs can be used as nouns and this is the case wit...

TEETER.d: To tilt back and forth on an edge.

TELNET.d: A network protocol that enables one computer to communicate with another via a local area network or the Internet.

TELSON.d: The part of an arthropod or crustacean posterior to the last segment, often resembling an armored tail or tip of the tail.

TEMPER.d: A general tendency or orientation towards a certain type of mood, a volatile state; a habitual way of thinking, behaving or reacting.
TEMPER.e: From Middle English temperen, tempren, from Old English ġetemprian, temprian, borrowed from Latin temperō (“I divide or proportion duly, I moderate, I regulate; intransitive senses I am moderate, I am temperate”), from tempus (“time, fit season”). Compare also French tempérer. Do...

TEMPLE.e: From Middle English temple, from Old English templ, tempel, borrowed from Latin templum (“shrine, temple, area for auspices”). Compare Old High German tempal (“temple”), also a borrowing from the Latin.

TENACE.d: An interrupted sequence of high cards of the same suit, such as the king and jack or the ace and queen.

TENANT.d: One who holds a lease (a tenancy).
TENANT.e: From Middle English tenaunt, from Anglo-Norman tenaunt and Old French tenant, present participle of tenir (“to hold”), from Latin tenēre (“hold, keep”).

TENDED.d: simple past and past participle of tend

TENDER.d: Sensitive or painful to the touch.
TENDER.e: From Middle English tender, tendere, from Anglo-Norman tender, Old French tendre, from Latin tener, tenerum (“soft, delicate”).

TENDON.d: A tough band of flexible but inelastic fibrous collagen tissue that connects a muscle with its bony attachment and transmits the force which the muscle exerts.
TENDON.e: Borrowed from French tendon or Medieval Latin tendō, from Ancient Greek τένων (ténōn, “sinew, tendon”), modified by association with the verb tendō (“to stretch”). Compare Middle English thenoun.

TENNER.d: A monetary note (bill) whose face value is ten basic units of currency. Originally, a ten-shilling (half pound) note.

TENNIS.d: A sport played by two players (or four in doubles), who alternately strike the ball over a net using racquets.
TENNIS.e: From Middle English tennys, teneys, tenis, from Old French tenez (second-person plural imperative of tenir (“to hold”)).

TENPIN.d: Any of the bottle-shaped targets used in tenpin bowling.

TENREC.d: Any of several diverse small mammals, of the family Tenrecidae, many native to Madagascar.
TENREC.e: From French tanrec, from Malagasy tàndraka or trandraka related to Malay landak (“porcupine”); English from 18th century.

TENSES.d: Plural of TENS: plural of ten

TENSOR.d: A muscle that tightens or stretches a part, or renders it tense.
TENSOR.e:
Borrowed from New Latin tensor (“that which stretches”), equivalent to tense + -or. Anatomical sense from 1704.
Introduced in the 1840s by William Rowan Hamilton as an algebraic quantity unrelated to the modern notion of tensor.
The contemporary mathematical meaning was introduce...

TENTED.d: Past tense of TENT: A pavilion or portable lodge consisting of skins, canvas, or some strong cloth, stretched and sustained by poles, used for sheltering people from the weather.
TENTED.e: From Middle English tente, borrowed from Old French tente, from Vulgar Latin *tenta (“tent”), from the feminine of Latin tentus, ptp. of tendere (“to stretch, extend”), or contracted from *tendita as an alternate past participle. Displaced native Middle English tild, tilt (“tent,...

TENTER.d: A framework upon which cloth is stretched and dried.
TENTER.e: Via Old French, perhaps from Latin tentorium.

TENURE.d: A status of possessing a thing or an office; an incumbency.
TENURE.e: From Middle English tenure, from Anglo-Norman, from Old French tenure, from Vulgar Latin *tenitura, from *tenitus, from Latin tentus (from teneō) + -ura.

TERCET.d: a three-line stanza in a poem

TEREDO.d: A mollusc of the genus Teredo, especially of species Teredo navalis.
TEREDO.e: From Latin terēdō (“woodworm”), from Ancient Greek τερηδών (terēdṓn, “wood-worm”). Compare Ancient Greek: τέρην (térēn, “smooth, gentle”).

TERGUM.d: The upper or dorsal surface of an articulated animal such as an arthropod.
TERGUM.e: Borrowed from Latin tergum (“back, rear; surface”).

TERMED.d: Past tense of TERM: That which limits the extent of anything; limit, extremity, bound, boundary, terminus.
TERMED.e:
From Middle English terme, borrowed from Old French terme, from Latin terminus (“a bound, boundary, limit, end; in Medieval Latin, also a time, period, word, covenant, etc.”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *térmn̥ (“stump, end, boundary”).
Doublet of terminus and termon. Ol...

TERROR.e: From late Middle English terrour, from Old French terreur f (“terror, fear, dread”), from Latin terror m (“fright, fear, terror”), from terrēre (“to frighten, terrify”), from Old Latin tr̥reō, from Proto-Italic *trozeō, from Proto-Indo-European *tre- (“to shake”), *tres- (“to tre...

TESTEE.d: Someone who is tested or examined.

TESTER.e: From Middle English tester, from Old French testre, from Latin testura.

TETANY.d: A condition characterized by painful muscular spasms, caused by faulty calcium metabolism.
TETANY.e: Borrowed from French tétanie, from New Latin tetania.

TETCHY.d: Synonym of touchy: easily annoyed or irritated, peevish, testy, irascible; also (figurative) extremely sensitive, difficult to manage, use, or work.
TETCHY.e: Uncertain, first attested as teachie in the 1597 first quarto versions of Romeo and Juliet and Richard III. Perhaps coined by Shakespeare. Also variously derived from English tetch (“tantrum, fit of anger”); from Scots tache (“blotch, fault”); from Middle English tatch (“blemish”...

TETHER.d: A rope, cable etc. that holds something in place whilst allowing some movement.
TETHER.e: From Middle English tether, teder, from Old English *tēoder and/or Old Norse tjóðr ( > Danish tøjr, Swedish tjuder); both from Proto-Germanic *teudrą (“rope; cord; shaft”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *dewtro-, from Proto-Indo-European *dew- (“to tie”), ...

TETRAD.e: From Ancient Greek τετράς (tetrás), analysable as tetra- + -ad.

TETTER.d: Any of various pustular skin conditions.
TETTER.e: From Middle English teter, from Old English teter, tetr, tetra, from Proto-West Germanic *tetru, from Proto-Germanic *tetruz, *tetruhaz, from Proto-Indo-European *dedru-, from Proto-Indo-European *der- (“to flay, split, crack”).

THALER.d: A monetary unit used in a number of central and northern European countries, known locally as daalder (Netherlands), daler (Scandinavia), Taler, Thaler (Germany), etc.
THALER.e: From German Thaler, an abbreviation of Joachimsthaler, after Sankt Joachimsthal, the German city in which some of the earliest thalers were minted in 1518. Doublet of tolar.

THANKS.d: Plural of THANK: To express gratitude.

THATCH.d: Straw, rushes, or similar, used for making or covering the roofs of buildings, or of stacks of hay or grain.
THATCH.e:
Variant of thack, from Middle English thache, thach, from Old English þæc (“roof-covering”), from Proto-West Germanic *þak, from Proto-Germanic *þaką (“covering”), from (o-grade of) Proto-Indo-European *(s)teg- (“cover”).
Cognate with Icelandic þak, Dutch dak, German Dach, Norweg...

THAWED.d: Past tense of THAW: To gradually melt, dissolve, or become fluid; to soften from frozen.
THAWED.e:
From Middle English thowen, thawen, from Old English þawian, *þāwan (“to thaw”), from Proto-West Germanic *þauwjan, from Proto-Germanic *þawjaną (“to thaw”), from Proto-Indo-European *teh₂- (“to melt”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian daie, dauje (“to thaw”), West Frisian teie (“t...

THEIRS.d: Plural of THEIR: Belonging to them.

THEISM.d: Belief in the existence of at least one deity.
THEISM.e: Coined, theo- + -ism. ultimately from Ancient Greek θεός (theós, “god”). Attested in English from 1678, theist being attested 16 years earlier in 1662. Cognate French théisme, as in Diderot Principes de la philosophie morale (1745), which was probably borrowed from English.

THEIST.d: One who believes in the existence of a god or gods.

THEMED.d: Past tense of THEME: A subject or topic.
THEMED.e: From Latin thēma, from Greek théma.

THEMES.d: Plural of THEME: A subject or topic.
THEMES.e: From Latin thēma, from Greek théma.

THENAR.d: The palm of the hand or sole of the foot.

THEORY.d: A description of an event or system that is considered to be accurate.
THEORY.e: From Middle French théorie, from Late Latin theōria, from Ancient Greek θεωρία (theōría, “contemplation, divine perspective, speculation, a looking at, a seeking”), from θεωρέω (theōréō, “I look at, view, see, consider, examine”), from θεωρός (theōrós, “spectator”), from θέα (thé...

THERED.d: Past tense of THERE: In or at that place.

THERES.d: Plural of THERE: In or at that place.

THESES.d: Plural of THESE: Plural of this.

THESIS.d: Senses relating to logic, rhetoric, etc.
THESIS.e: From Late Middle English thesis (“lowering of the voice”) and also borrowed directly from its etymon Latin thesis (“proposition, thesis; lowering of the voice”), from Ancient Greek θέσῐς (thésĭs, “arrangement, placement, setting; conclusion, position, thesis; lowering of the voic...

THICKS.d: Plural of THICK: Having great depth; dense.

THIEVE.e: From Middle English *theven [found in Middle English thevinge (“thieving”)], from Old English þēofian, ġeþēofian, ġeþīefian (“to thieve, steal”).

THINGS.d: Plural of THING: An object; a matter.

THINGY.d: A thing (used to refer to something vaguely or when one cannot recall or does not wish to mention its name).

THINKS.d: Plural of THINK: To have thoughts; to believe.

THIRDS.d: Plural of THIRD: The ordinal number 3rd.

THIRST.d: A sensation of dryness in the throat associated with a craving for liquids, produced by deprivation of drink, or by some other cause (such as fear, excitement, etc.) which stops the secretion of the pharyngeal mucous membrane.
THIRST.e:
From Middle English thirst, thurst, from Old English þurst, from Proto-West Germanic *þurstu, from Proto-Germanic *þurstuz, from Proto-Indo-European *ters- (“dry”).
Germanic cognates include Old High German thurst, Middle High German durst, German Durst, Old Saxon thurst, Old Dut...

THIRTY.d: The cardinal number occurring after twenty-nine and before thirty-one, represented in Arabic numerals as 30.
THIRTY.e: From Middle English thirty, metathetic alternant of Middle English thriti, þrittiȝ, from Old English þrītiġ (“thirty”), from Proto-Germanic *þrīz tigiwiz (“thirty”, literally “three tens”), equivalent to three + -ty. Cognate with Scots therty, tretty (“thirty”), West Frisian trit...

THOLIN.d: Any of several poorly classified heteropolymers derived from simple hydrocarbons and ammonia formed by solar irradiation in the atmospheres of icy planets and moons.
THOLIN.e: From Ancient Greek θολός (tholós, “muddy”) + -in. Coined by Carl Sagan and by Bishun Khare in 1979. From the muddy coloration that this class of chemical compounds appear to have, when observed on the Saturnian moon Titan, and from Miller–Urey-style experiments.

THORAX.d: The region of the mammalian body between the neck and abdomen as well as the cavity containing the heart and lungs.
THORAX.e: From Latin thorax, from Ancient Greek θώραξ (thṓrax, “a breastplate, cuirass, corslet”).

THORNY.e: From Middle English thorny, þorny, þorni, from Old English þorniġ, from Proto-West Germanic *þornag. By surface analysis, thorn + -y.

THORON.d: Radon-220 (²²⁰₈₆Rn; symbol Tn), an isotope of radon

THRALL.d: Slave; one under the control of another.
THRALL.e: From Middle English thral, thralle, threl, threlle, from Old English þrǣl (“thrall, slave, servant”), from Old Norse þræll (“slave”), from Proto-Germanic *þrahilaz, *þragilaz, *þrigilaz (“runner, gofer, servant”), from Proto-Indo-European *trāgʰ- (“to pull, drag, race, run”); acc...

THRASH.e: From Middle English thrasshen, a dialectal variant of thresshen, threshen (whence the modern English thresh), from Old English þrescan, from Proto-Germanic *þreskaną, whence also Old High German dreskan, Old Norse þreskja.

THREAD.d: A cord formed by spinning or twisting together textile fibers or filaments into one or more continuous strands, typically used in needlework.
THREAD.e:
From Middle English thred, þred, threed, from Old English þrǣd, from Proto-Germanic *þrēduz, from Proto-Indo-European *treh₁-tu-s, from *terh₁- (“rub, twist”).
Cognates
Cognate with Yola dreade (“thread”), Saterland Frisian Träid (“thread, wire”), Cimbrian draat (“string, thread”...

THREAT.d: An expression of intent to injure or punish another.
THREAT.e: From Middle English threte, thret, thrat, thræt, threat, from Old English þrēat (“crowd, swarm, troop, army, press; pressure, trouble, calamity, oppression, force, violence, threat”), from Proto-Germanic *þrautaz, closely tied to Proto-Germanic *þrautą (“displeasure, complaint, g...

THRESH.d: To separate the grain from the straw or husks (chaff) by mechanical beating, with a flail or machinery, or by driving animals over them.
THRESH.e: From Middle English thresshen, threshen, threschen, from Old English þrescan, from Proto-Germanic *þreskaną.

THRIFT.d: The characteristic of using a minimum of something (especially money).
THRIFT.e: From Middle English thrift, thryfte, þrift, from Old Norse þrift (“thriving condition, prosperity”). Equivalent to thrive + -t.

THRILL.d: To suddenly excite someone, or to give someone great pleasure; to (figuratively) electrify; to experience such a sensation.
THRILL.e: From Old English þȳrlian (“to pierce”), derived from þȳrel (“hole”) (archaic English thirl). Doublet of thirl (verb).

THRIVE.d: To grow or increase stature; to grow vigorously or luxuriantly, to flourish.
THRIVE.e: From Middle English thryven, thriven, from Old Norse þrífa (“to seize, grasp, take hold, prosper”), from Proto-Germanic *þrībaną (“to seize, prosper”), from Proto-Indo-European *trep-, *terp- (“to satisfy, enjoy”). Cognate with Swedish trivas, Danish trives, Norwegian Bokmål triv...

THROAT.d: The front part of the neck.
THROAT.e: From Middle English throte, from Old English þrote, þrota, þrotu (“throat”), from Proto-West Germanic *þrotu, from Proto-Germanic *þrutō (“throat”), from Proto-Indo-European *trud- (“to swell, become stiff”). Cognate with Dutch strot (“throat”), German Drossel (“throttle, gorge o...

THRONE.d: An impressive seat used by a monarch, often on a raised dais in a throne room and reserved for formal occasions.
THRONE.e: From Middle English trone, from Old French trone, from Latin thronus, from Ancient Greek θρόνος (thrónos, “chair, throne”). Superseded earlier seld (“seat, throne”).

THRONG.d: A group of people crowded or gathered closely together.
THRONG.e: From Middle English throng, thrang, from Old English þrang, ġeþrang (“crowd, press, tumult”), from Proto-Germanic *þrangwą, *þrangwō (“throng”), from *þrangwaz (“pressing, narrow”), from Proto-Indo-European *trenkʷ- (“to beat; pound; hew; press”). Cognate with Dutch drang, German...

THROWN.e:
From Middle English throwen, from Old English þrāwen, ġeþrāwen, from Proto-Germanic *þrēanaz, from Proto-Germanic *þrēaną. Doublet of thran.
Morphologically throw + -n.

THROWS.d: Plural of THROW: To propel through the air.

THRUSH.d: Any of numerous species of songbirds of the cosmopolitan family Turdidae, such as the song thrush, mistle thrush, bluebird, and American robin.
THRUSH.e: From Middle English thrusche, þrusch, þresche, from a combination of Old English þrysċe (from Proto-Germanic *þruskijǭ, a diminutive of Proto-Germanic *þruskō) and Old English þræsċe (from Proto-Germanic *þrauskǭ and/or *þrastuz); all from Proto-Indo-European *trosdos (“thrush”)....

THRUST.d: An attack made by moving the sword parallel to its length and landing with the point.
THRUST.e: From Middle English þrusten, from Old Norse þrysta, from Proto-Germanic *þrustijaną, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *trewd-.

THWACK.d: To hit (someone or something) hard, especially with a flat implement or a stick; to thrash, to whack.
THWACK.e:
The verb is probably:
* partly onomatopoeic, from the sound of something being beaten (compare whack); and
* partly derived from Late Middle English twakken, twake (“to hit (someone) with something; to pat; to stroke”), probably from Middle English thakken, thakke (“to dab; to pa...

THWART.d: Placed or situated across something else; cross, oblique, transverse.
THWART.e: The adjective is derived from Early Middle English thwert, thwerte, thuart, thurt, thurte, thwart, thwarte, twart, twarte, twhart, twhert, twort, þuert, þwerrt, þwert, þwerte, ðwert (“crosswise, transverse; counter, opposing; contrary, obstinate”), borrowed from Old Norse þvert (...

THYMOL.d: a monoterpene phenol, C₁₀H₁₃OH, found in the oil extracted from thyme; used as in perfume, as an antiseptic and fungicide, and in embalming

THYMUS.d: Ellipsis of thymus gland (“A ductless gland, consisting mainly of lymphatic tissue, located behind the top of the breastbone. It is most active during puberty, after which it shrinks in size. It plays an important role in the development of the immune system and produces lymphocytes.”).
THYMUS.e: From New Latin thymus, from Ancient Greek θύμος (thúmos, “warty excrescence, (also, as used by Galen) thymus gland”).

TICKED.d: Past tense of TICK: A tiny woodland arachnid of the suborder Ixodida.
TICKED.e: From Middle English tyke, teke, from Old English ticia (“parasitic animal, tick”), from Proto-West Germanic *tīkō, compare Dutch teek, German Zecke.

TICKET.d: A small document that acts as proof of something, often thereby granting the holder some ability.
TICKET.e: Borrowed from Middle Scots tikkat, tikket, from Middle French etiquet m, estiquet m, and etiquette f, estiquette f (“a bill, note, label, ticket”), from Old French estechier, estichier, estequier (“to attach, stick”), (compare Picard estiquier (“to stick, pierce”)), from Frankish...

TICKLE.e: From Middle English tiklen, tikelen, of uncertain origin. Perhaps from a frequentative form of Middle English tikken (“to touch lightly”), thus equivalent to tick + -le; or perhaps related to Old English tinclian (“to tickle”). Compare North Frisian tigele (“to tickle”) (Hallig d...

TICKLY.d: Having an itchy sensation like that of being tickled.

TIDIED.d: Past tense of TIDY: Arranged neatly and in order.
TIDIED.e: From Middle English tidy, tydy, tidi (“timely, seasonal, opportune”), from tide (“time”) + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian tiedig (“timely, early”), Dutch tijdig (“timely”), German Low German tiedig (“timely”), German zeitig (“seasonal, timely”), Danish tidig (“timely”), Swedi...

TIDIES.d: Plural of TIDY: Arranged neatly and in order.
TIDIES.e: From Middle English tidy, tydy, tidi (“timely, seasonal, opportune”), from tide (“time”) + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian tiedig (“timely, early”), Dutch tijdig (“timely”), German Low German tiedig (“timely”), German zeitig (“seasonal, timely”), Danish tidig (“timely”), Swedi...

TIDILY.d: In a tidy manner; neatly; cleanly.
TIDILY.e: From Middle English tidili, tidily, equivalent to tidy + -ly.

TIDING.d: Present participle of TIDE: The daily fluctuation in the level of the sea caused by the gravitational influence of the moon and the sun.
TIDING.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *deh₂y-
Proto-Indo-European *-tis
Proto-Indo-European *déh₂itis
Proto-Germanic *tīdiz
Proto-West Germanic *tīdi
Old English tīd
Middle English tyde
English tide
Inherited from Middle English tyde, from Old English tīd, from Proto-West Germanic *...

TIEING.d: Present participle of TIE: A knot; a fastening.
TIEING.e: From Middle English teye (“cord, chain”), from Old English tēag, tēah (“cord, chain”), from Proto-West Germanic *taugu, from Proto-Germanic *taugō, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *dewk-. Compare Danish tov, Icelandic taug.

TIERED.d: Past tense of TIER: One who ties (knots, etc.).

TIFFED.d: Past tense of TIFF: A (generally small) argument or disagreement; a petty quarrel, a spat.
TIFFED.e: The origin of the noun is unknown; it is possibly originally dialectal and may be onomatopoeic, representing the sound of a small puff of air or gas. The verb is derived from the noun.

TIFFIN.d: A (light) midday meal or snack; luncheon.
TIFFIN.e: Apparently from English tiffing, present participle of tiff (“to take a small drink, to sip”) (slang).

TIGHTS.d: Plural of TIGHT: Fixed firmly; close-fitting.

TILING.d: Present participle of TILE: A regularly-shaped slab of clay or other material, affixed to cover or decorate a surface, as in a roof-tile, glazed tile, stove tile, carpet tile, etc.
TILING.e:
From Middle English tile, tyle, tigel, tiȝel, teȝele, from Old English tieġle, tiġle, tiġele (“tile; brick”), from Proto-West Germanic *tigulā, from Proto-Germanic *tigulǭ (“tile”), from Latin tēgula. Doublet of tegula.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Tichel (“tile”), Wes...

TILLER.d: A person who tills; a farmer.
TILLER.e: From Middle English tilier; equivalent to till + -er.

TILTED.d: Past tense of TILT: To slope or incline (something); to slant.
TILTED.e: From Middle English tilte, from Old English *tyltan, *tieltan (“to be unsteady”), related to the adjective tealt (“unsteady”), from Proto-West Germanic *talt, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *del-, *dul- (“to shake, hesitate”), see also Dutch touteren (“to tremble”), North Fr...

TIMBER.d: Trees in a forest regarded as a source of wood.
TIMBER.e:
From Middle English tymber, from Old English timber, from Proto-West Germanic *timr, from Proto-Germanic *timrą, from Proto-Indo-European *dem- (“build, house”) (see Proto-Indo-European *dṓm).
Cognates include Dutch timmer, Old High German zimbar (German Zimmer), Norwegian tømmer...

TIMBRE.d: The quality of a sound independent of its pitch and volume.
TIMBRE.e: From French timbre, ultimately from Ancient Greek τύμπανον (túmpanon, “drum”). Doublet of tympanum, timpani, timbal, and tymbal.

TIMELY.d: Done at the proper time or within the proper time limits; prompt.
TIMELY.e: From Middle English timely, tymely, timliche, from Old English *tīmlīc (adjective) and tīmlīċe (“in good time; timely; soon”, adverb), equivalent to time + -ly. Cognate with Danish timelig, Swedish timlig, Icelandic tímalegur, tímanlegur.

TINDER.d: Small dry sticks and finely-divided fibrous matter etc., used to help light a fire.
TINDER.e: From Middle English tinder, tunder, tender, tonder, from Old English tynder, from Proto-Germanic *tundrą, *tundrǭ (“tinder”). Compare Saterland Frisian Tunder (“tinder”), Dutch tonder (“tinder”), German Zunder (“tinder”), Swedish tända (“to light, to set on fire”). More at tind.

TINGLE.d: To feel a prickling or mildly stinging sensation.
TINGLE.e: From Middle English tinglen, a variant of tinclen (“to tinkle”). More at tinkle.

TINIER.d: Comparative form of TINY: Very small.
TINIER.e: From Middle English tine, tyne (“very small”) + -y. Perhaps from tine.

TINING.d: Present participle of TINE: A spike or point on an implement or tool, especially a prong of a fork or a tooth of a comb.
TINING.e: From Middle English tine, alteration of Middle English tinde, tind, from Old English tind, from Proto-West Germanic *tind, Proto-Germanic *tindaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃dénts (“tooth, peg”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Tiende, Tiene (“prong, tine”), German Zind, Zint (“p...

TINKER.d: An itinerant tinsmith and mender of household utensils made of metal.
TINKER.e: From Middle English tynkere, perhaps from Old English *tincere, from tin (“tin”) + *cere, as in bēocere (“beekeeper”).

TINKLE.d: To make light metallic sounds, rather like a very small bell.
TINKLE.e: From Middle English tinclen, equivalent to tink + -le (frequentative suffix).

TINNED.d: Past tense of TIN: A malleable, ductile, metallic element, resistant to corrosion, with atomic number 50 and symbol Sn.
TINNED.e: From Middle English tin, from Old English tin, from Proto-West Germanic *tin, from Proto-Germanic *tiną.

TINNER.d: Comparative form of TIN: A malleable, ductile, metallic element, resistant to corrosion, with atomic number 50 and symbol Sn.
TINNER.e: From Middle English tin, from Old English tin, from Proto-West Germanic *tin, from Proto-Germanic *tiną.

TINSEL.d: A shining fabric used for ornamental purposes.
TINSEL.e:
The noun is derived from Middle English tinsel (“cloth containing gold or silver thread”) [and other forms], probably from Anglo-Norman tincel, tincelle, tencele, and then:
* from Old French estincelle, estencele (“a spark”) (modern French étincelle), from Vulgar Latin *stincilla...

TINTED.d: Past tense of TINT: A slight coloring.
TINTED.e: Alteration of earlier tinct, influenced by French teinte (“tint”), from Latin tinctus (“dyed”), past participle of verb tingō (“tinge”). Doublet of tent (“kind of red wine”). Cognate with Dutch tint, Estonian tint, French teinte, German Tinte, Hungarian tinta, Italian tinta, Luxe...

TIPCAT.d: An old game in which a small piece of wood pointed at both ends is tipped, or struck with a stick or bat, to make it travel through the air as far as possible.

TIPPED.d: Past tense of TIP: The extreme end of something, especially when pointed; e.g. the sharp end of a pencil.
TIPPED.e: From Middle English tip, typ, tippe (“tip”), related to Saterland Frisian Tip (“tip”), West Frisian tippe, tip (“tip”), Dutch tip (“tip”), German Low German Tip, Tippel (“tip”), dialectal German Zipf (“tip”) (diminutive Zipfel used in Standard German), Danish tip (“tip”), Swedish...

TIPPER.d: Comparative form of TIP: The extreme end of something, especially when pointed; e.g. the sharp end of a pencil.
TIPPER.e: From Middle English tip, typ, tippe (“tip”), related to Saterland Frisian Tip (“tip”), West Frisian tippe, tip (“tip”), Dutch tip (“tip”), German Low German Tip, Tippel (“tip”), dialectal German Zipf (“tip”) (diminutive Zipfel used in Standard German), Danish tip (“tip”), Swedish...

TIPPET.d: A shoulder covering, typically the fur of a fox, with long ends that dangle in front.
TIPPET.e: From Middle English tippet, Old English tæppet, from Latin tapete (“cloth”).

TIPPLE.d: An area near the entrance of mines which is used to load and unload coal.
TIPPLE.e: Unknown but possibly from a Scandinavian source (see Norwegian tipla), or from tip + -le.

TIPTOE.e: From Middle English tipto, typto; equivalent to tip + toe. Compare fingertip.

TIRADE.d: A long, angry or violent speech.

TIRING.d: Present participle of TIRE: To become sleepy or weary.
TIRING.e: From Middle English tiren, tirien, teorien, from Old English tȳrian, tēorian (“to fail, cease, become weary, be tired, exhausted; tire, weary, exhaust”), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Proto-West Germanic *teuʀōn (“to cease”), which is possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dews-...

TISANE.d: A medicinal drink, originally made from barley soaked in water.
TISANE.e: From Anglo-Norman tysanne, Middle French ptisane, tisane (“barley water, medicinal drink”), and their source, Latin tisana, variant of ptisana, from Ancient Greek πτισάνη (ptisánē, “peeled barley, barley gruel”), from πτίσσειν (ptíssein, “to peel, to crush”).

TISSUE.e: From Middle English tissu, from Old French tissu (“woven”), past participle of tistre (“to weave”), from Latin texō (“to weave”).

TITHER.e: From Middle English tither; equivalent to tithe + -er.

TITLED.d: Past tense of TITLE: A name; a right to property.
TITLED.e: From Old French title, from Latin titulus.

TITLER.d: One who gives a title to something.

TITLES.d: Plural of TITLE: A name; a right to property.
TITLES.e: From Old French title, from Latin titulus.

TITTER.d: To laugh or giggle in a somewhat subdued or restrained way, as from nervousness or poorly-suppressed amusement.
TITTER.e: First attested in the 1610s. Probably from Middle English *titeren, *titren (attested in Middle English titering (“hesitation, vacillation”)), probably a frequentative of Middle English titten (“to waver”), related to Old Norse titra (“to shake, shiver, quiver”), dialectal Swedis...

TITTLE.d: Any small dot, stroke, or diacritical mark, especially if part of a letter, or of a letter-like abbreviation; in particular, the dots over the Latin letters i and j.
TITTLE.e: From Middle English tytle, titel, titele, from Anglo-Norman titil, titule and Medieval Latin titulus (“small stroke, diacritical mark, accent”), from Latin titulus (“title”). Doublet of tilde, titer/titre, title, titlo, and titulus.

TOCSIN.d: An alarm or other signal sounded by a bell or bells, originally especially with reference to France.
TOCSIN.e: Borrowed from Middle French, from Old French toquesain (modern tocsin), from Old Occitan tocasenh, from tocar (“strike, touch”) + senh (“bell”).

TODAYS.d: Plural of TODAY: This present day.

TODDER.d: Comparative form of TOD: A male fox.
TODDER.e: From Middle English tod, of unknown origin. Possibly influenced by Etymology 2, due to its bushy tail.

TODDLE.d: To walk unsteadily, as a small child does.
TODDLE.e: Of unknown origin. Possibly a byform of totter.

TOECAP.d: A piece of leather or other material on a shoe or boot that covers the toes.

TOEING.d: Present participle of TOE: Each of the five digits on the end of the human foot.
TOEING.e:
From Middle English to, from Old English tā, (Mercian) tāhe, from Proto-West Germanic *taihā, from Proto-Germanic *taihwǭ, from *tīhwaną (“to show, announce”), from Proto-Indo-European *deyḱ- (“to show”).
See also Dutch teen, German Zehe, Danish tå, Swedish tå; also Old English t...

TOFFEE.d: A type of confectionery made by boiling sugar (or treacle, etc) with butter or milk, then cooling the mixture so that it becomes hard.

TOGGED.d: Past tense of TOG: A cloak.
TOGGED.e: Shortened from earlier togemans, togeman (“cloak, loose coat”), from Middle English tog, toge, togue, from Old French togue, from Latin toga (“cloak, mantle”) (compare the doublets toga and toge). Togeman(s) was an old thieves' and vegabonds' cant for "cloak; coat". By the 1700s ...

TOGGER.d: Comparative form of TOG: A cloak.
TOGGER.e: Shortened from earlier togemans, togeman (“cloak, loose coat”), from Middle English tog, toge, togue, from Old French togue, from Latin toga (“cloak, mantle”) (compare the doublets toga and toge). Togeman(s) was an old thieves' and vegabonds' cant for "cloak; coat". By the 1700s ...

TOGGLE.d: A wooden or metal pin, short rod, crosspiece or similar, fixed transversely in the eye of a rope or chain to be secured to any other loop, ring, or bight, e.g. a sea painter to a lifeboat.
TOGGLE.e: Of uncertain origin. Possible alteration of tug (“to pull”) + -le

TOILET.d: A room, enclosed area or single-purpose building containing a fixture or fixtures used for urination and defecation; a bathroom or water closet.
TOILET.e: From Middle French toilette, diminutive of toile (“cloth”), from their use to protect clothing while shaving or arranging hair. From its use as a private room, toilet came to refer euphemistically to lavatories and then to its fixtures, beginning in the United States in the late ...

TOKENS.d: Plural of TOKEN: A symbol; a voucher.

TOKING.d: Present participle of TOKE: A gratuity.

TOMATO.d: A widely cultivated plant, Solanum lycopersicum, having edible fruit.
TOMATO.e: Variant of earlier tomate, from Spanish tomate, from Classical Nahuatl tomatl, from Proto-Nahuan *tomatl. Compare tomatillo.

TOMBOY.d: A girl who behaves in a typically boyish manner.
TOMBOY.e: From tom + boy. First attested in Ralph Roister Doister (published 1567, written circa 1552), where it is used to describe a boisterous girl; the OED says the citation is however "generally taken" to mean a boisterous boy, and says that a use in The Old Law (published 1656, thoug...

TOMCAT.e: From Tom + cat, popularised by The Life and Adventures of a Cat (1760), by an anonymous author, in which the male cat was called Tom.

TOMCOD.d: Any of species Microgadus tomcod, of edible cod found in the Atlantic.
TOMCOD.e: From French tacaud?, probably influenced by Tom, tom.

TOMMED.d: Past tense of TOM: The male of the domesticated cat, especially if not neutered.
TOMMED.e: From generic use of the proper name Tom.

TOMMER.d: Comparative form of TOM: The male of the domesticated cat, especially if not neutered.
TOMMER.e: From generic use of the proper name Tom.

TONGED.d: Past tense of TONG: An instrument or tool used for manipulating things in a fire without touching them with the hands.
TONGED.e: From Middle English tonge (“tongs, fang”), tange, from Old English tange, from Proto-West Germanic *tangu, from Proto-Germanic *tangō, from Proto-Indo-European *denḱ- (“to bite”). Cognate with Old Norse tǫng (modern Icelandic töng), Old High German zanga (modern German Zange). Ot...

TONGUE.d: The flexible muscular organ in the mouth that is used to move food around, for tasting and that is moved into various positions to modify the flow of air from the lungs in order to produce different sounds in speech.
TONGUE.e: From Middle English tonge, tunge, tung, from Old English tunge, from Proto-West Germanic *tungā, from Proto-Germanic *tungǭ (“tongue”) (compare Scots tung (“tongue”), West Frisian tonge (“tongue”), Saterland Frisian Tunge (“tongue”), Cimbrian zung (“tongue”), Dutch tong (“tongue”...

TONING.d: Present participle of TONE: A specific pitch.
TONING.e: From Middle English ton, tone, from Latin tonus (“sound, tone”) (possibly through Old French ton), from Ancient Greek τόνος (tónos, “strain, tension, pitch”), from τείνω (teínō, “I stretch”). Doublet of tune, ton, tonos, and tonus.

TONNER.d: Comparative form of TON: Any of various units of mass, originally notionally equal to the contents of a tun
TONNER.e: Variant of tun (“cask”), influenced by Old French tonne (“ton”).

TONSIL.e: Late 16th century borrowing from French tonsille or Latin tonsillae (“the tonsils in the throat”, plural).

TOOLED.d: Past tense of TOOL: Any physical device meant to ease or do a task.
TOOLED.e: From Middle English tool, tol, from Old English tōl (“tool, implement, instrument”, literally “that with which one prepares something”), perhaps borrowed from Old Norse tól, but at any rate ultimately from Proto-Germanic *tōlą (“that which is used in preparation, tool”), from Pro...

TOOTED.d: Past tense of TOOT: The noise of a horn or whistle.
TOOTED.e:
Probably onomatopoeic in origin. Compare Dutch toeteren (“to blow a horn”), German tuten, Swedish tuta, Danish tude.
Noun sense 7 ("Mastodon post") and verb sense 10 ("to post on Mastodon") are influenced by tweet (“Twitter post”).

TOOTLE.d: To make a soft toot sound.

TOPHUS.d: A deposit of monosodium urate crystals in the body, caused by high levels of uric acid in the blood.

TOPICS.d: Plural of TOPIC: A subject of discussion.
TOPICS.e: From Latin topica, from Greek topikós.

TOPING.d: Present participle of TOPE: To drink excessively; to get drunk.
TOPING.e: Alteration of obsolete top (“to drink”), as in top (off).

TOPMAN.d: The man stationed in the top on a sailing vessel, responsible for the setting of the sails

TOPPED.d: Past tense of TOP: The highest or uppermost part of something.
TOPPED.e: From Middle English top, toppe, from Old English topp (“top, highest part; summit; crest; tassel, tuft; (spinning) top, ball; a tuft or ball at the highest point of anything”), from Proto-West Germanic *topp, from Proto-Germanic *tuppaz (“braid, pigtail, end”), of unknown ultimat...

TOPPER.d: Comparative form of TOP: The highest or uppermost part of something.
TOPPER.e: From Middle English top, toppe, from Old English topp (“top, highest part; summit; crest; tassel, tuft; (spinning) top, ball; a tuft or ball at the highest point of anything”), from Proto-West Germanic *topp, from Proto-Germanic *tuppaz (“braid, pigtail, end”), of unknown ultimat...

TOROID.d: A surface generated by a closed curve (especially a circle) rotating about, but not intersecting or containing, an axis in its own plane.

TORPOR.d: A state of being inactive or stuporous.
TORPOR.e: From Latin torpor (“numbness”), from torpeō (“I am numb”).

TORQUE.d: A rotational or twisting effect of a force; a moment of force, defined for measurement purposes as an equivalent straight line force multiplied by the distance from the axis of rotation (SI unit newton-metre or N·m; imperial unit pound-foot or lb·ft, not to be confused with the foot pound-force, commonly "foot-pound", a unit of work or energy)

TORRID.e: From Latin torridus, from torreō (“parch, scorch”).

TORSEL.d: A plate of timber for the end of a beam or joist to rest on.

TOSHES.d: Plural of TOSH: Copper; items made of copper.
TOSHES.e:
From 19th-century British thieves' cant, of uncertain origin. Perhaps from *tarsh, a metathetic alteration of trash; or from toss.
Sense of nonsense possibly influenced by tush (“nonsense! tsk tsk!”) attested from 15th century.

TOSSES.d: Plural of TOSS: A throw, a lob, of a ball etc., with an initial upward direction, particularly with a lack of care.
TOSSES.e: From Middle English tossen (“to buffet about, agitate, toss; to sift or winnow”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old Norse (compare dialectal Norwegian tossa, dialectal Swedish tossa (“to strew, spread”)), or perhaps from an alteration of Middle English tosen (“to tease, pull ...

TOTALS.d: Plural of TOTAL: The whole amount; complete.

TOTING.d: Present participle of TOTE: A tote bag.
TOTING.e: Possibly from Middle Low German tûte, tǖte (“horn, conical paper bag”), whence also German Tute (“horn, bugle”) and German Tüte (“bag, paper bag”). Compare also Scots tout (“a drinking vessel”), Saterland Frisian Tüütje (“paper bag”), West Frisian tút (“spout, toot, kiss”), Dutch...

TOTTED.d: Past tense of TOT: A small child.
TOTTED.e:
Borrowed from Scots tot, a shortened form of totum (“small child; tot”), of uncertain origin, perhaps shortened from totter (“to move in an unsteady way”),
Compare tottle, also Old Norse tottr (“name of a dwarf”), Swedish tutte (“small child”), Danish tommeltot (“little child”).

TOTTER.d: To walk, move or stand unsteadily or falteringly; threatening to fall.
TOTTER.e: From Middle English totren, toteren, from earlier *tolteren (compare dialectal English tolter (“to struggle, flounder”); Scots tolter (“unstable, wonky”)), from Old English tealtrian (“to totter, vacillate”), from Proto-Germanic *taltrōną, a frequentative form of Proto-Germanic *...

TOUCAN.d: Any of various neotropical frugivorous birds from the family Ramphastidae, with a large colorful beak.
TOUCAN.e: Borrowed from French toucan, borrowed from Old Tupi tukana, from Proto-Tupi-Guarani *tũkãn, from Proto-Tupian *jɨokãn.

TOUCHY.d: Extremely sensitive or volatile; easily disturbed to the point of becoming unstable; requiring caution or tactfulness.
TOUCHY.e: A variant of earlier tetchy (“cranky, easily annoyed, difficult to handle”), under influence from some senses of touch (“affect, disturb”) and simulating touch + -y.

TOUGHS.d: Plural of TOUGH: Strong and durable; difficult.

TOUPEE.d: A wig of false hair worn to cover a bald spot, especially as worn by a man.
TOUPEE.e: 1727, from French toupet (“small tuft of hair, forelock”), from Middle French toupet (“small tuft of hair, forelock”), from Old French toupet (“small tuft of hair, forelock”), diminutive of toupe, top (“tuft of hair”), from Frankish *topp (“summit, crest, tuft of hair”), from Pro...

TOURED.d: Past tense of TOUR: A journey through a particular building, estate, country, etc.
TOURED.e: From Old French tour, tourn, from the verb torner, tourner.

TOURER.d: An open-top or soft-top motor car suitable for touring.

TOUSLE.d: To put into disorder; to tumble; to touse; to muss.
TOUSLE.e: From Middle English touselen, equivalent to touse + -le. Cognate with German Low German tuseln, Bavarian zusseln, züsseln.

TOUTED.d: Past tense of TOUT: Someone advertising for customers in an aggressive way.
TOUTED.e: From Middle English touten (“to jut out, protrude, gaze upon, observe, peer”), from Old English *tūtian (“to be sticking out, protrude”), related to Old English tȳtan (“to stand out, be conspicuous, shine”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *tut(t)- (“to stick out, project”). Compa...

TOWARD.e: From Middle English toward, from Old English tōweard, from Proto-West Germanic *tōward, equivalent to to + -ward. Cognate with Middle Low German tôwart, Middle Dutch toewaert (Modern Dutch toewaarts), Middle High German zuowart, zūwart (Modern German zuwärts). Compare also Middle...

TOWERS.d: Plural of TOWER: A tall narrow building.
TOWERS.e: From Old French tur, from Latin turris.

TOWING.d: Present participle of TOW: To pull something behind one, such as by using a line, chain, or tongue.
TOWING.e:
From Middle English towen, from Old English togian, from Proto-West Germanic *togōn, from Proto-Germanic *tugōną, from Proto-Indo-European *dewk-.
See also Middle High German zogen, German ziehen, Dutch tijgen, Old Norse toga.

TOWNED.d: Past tense of TOWN: A settlement; an area with residential districts, shops and amenities, and its own local government; especially one larger than a village and smaller than a city, historically enclosed by a fence or walls, with total populations ranging from several hundred to more than a hundred thousand (as of the early 21st century)
TOWNED.e:
From Middle English toun, from Old English tūn (“enclosure, garden”), from Proto-West Germanic *tūn, from Proto-Germanic *tūną (“fence, enclosure”), of Celtic origin, from Proto-Celtic *dūnom, from Proto-Indo-European *dewh₂- (“to finish, come full circle”).
Cognate with Saterlan...

TOWNIE.d: A person living in a university area who is not associated with the university.

TOYING.d: Present participle of TOY: Something to play with, especially as intended for use by a child.
TOYING.e: Inherited from Middle English toye (“amorous play, piece of fun or entertainment”), probably from Middle Dutch toy, tuyg (“tools, apparatus, utensil, ornament”) as in Dutch speel-tuig (“play-thing, toy”), from Old Dutch *tiug, from Proto-West Germanic *tiugī̆, *teug, from Proto-G...

TRACER.d: A compound, element, or isotope used to track the progress or history of a natural process.

TRACKS.d: Plural of TRACK: A path; to follow.

TRADED.d: Past tense of TRADE: The buying and selling of goods.

TRADES.d: Plural of TRADE: The buying and selling of goods.

TRAGIC.e: From Ancient Greek τραγικός (tragikós, “of or relating to tragedy”), from τράγος (trágos, “male goat”), a reference to the goat-satyrs of the theatrical plays of the Dorians.

TRAGUS.d: The small piece of thick cartilage on the inner side of the external ear that is immediately in front of and partly closing the ear canal.
TRAGUS.e: Borrowed from Late Latin tragus, from Ancient Greek τράγος (trágos, “he-goat; part of the ear”); with reference to a tuft of hair, likened to a goat’s beard, that may grow on the tragus, especially in older men.

TRAILS.d: Plural of TRAIL: A path; to drag behind.

TRAINS.d: Plural of TRAIN: A connected line of vehicles; to teach.

TRANCE.e: From Middle English traunce, from Anglo-Norman transe (“fear of coming evil; passage from life to death”), from transir (“to be numb with fear; to die, pass on”), from Latin trānseō (“to cross over”).

TRANNY.d: A transgender person, especially a trans woman.
TRANNY.e: All are shortened forms of the indicated terms (most of which start with the prefix trans-) + -y.

TRASHY.d: Like trash; having low quality and a perceived lack of depth, especially of books and films.

TRAUMA.d: Any serious injury to the body, often resulting from violence or an accident.

TRAVEL.d: To be on a journey, often for pleasure or business and with luggage; to go from one place to another.
TRAVEL.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Middle English travelen (“to make a laborious journey, travel”) from Middle Scots travailen (“to toil, work, travel”), alteration of Middle English travaillen (“to toil, work”), from Old French travailler (“to trouble, suffer, be worn out”). See the doublet...

TREATS.d: third-person singular simple present indicative of treat

TREATY.d: A formal binding agreement concluded by subjects of international law, namely, states and international organizations; a convention, a pact.
TREATY.e: The noun is derived from Middle English trete, trety (“bargaining, negotiation; discussion; conference, meeting; entreaty, persuasion; agreement, contract, covenant; arrangement, settlement; agreement between two rulers, states, etc.; written work on a particular subject, treatis...

TREBLE.d: Pertaining to the highest singing voice or part in harmonized music.
TREBLE.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Middle English treble, from Old French treble, from Latin triplus. Doublet of triple.

TREMOR.e: From Middle English tremour (“fright”), from Anglo-Norman tremour and Old French tremor, from Latin tremor.

TRENCH.d: A long, narrow ditch or hole dug in the ground.
TRENCH.e: Borrowed into Middle English from Old French trenche. Doublet of tranche and traunch. Possible doublet of English: truncate

TRENDS.d: Plural of TREND: A general direction; a fashion.

TRENDY.d: Of, or in accordance with the latest trend, fashion or hype.

TREPAN.d: A tool used to bore through rock when sinking shafts.
TREPAN.e: Borrowed into Middle English from Old French trepan, from Latin trepanum, from Ancient Greek τρύπανον (trúpanon, “auger, borer”). Doublet of trephine.

TRIAGE.d: Assessment or sorting according to quality, need, etc., especially to determine how resources will be allocated.
TRIAGE.e: From French triage, from trier (“to sort”).

TRIBAL.e: From Latin tribālis. By surface analysis, tribe + -al, first attested in the 1630s. The specific adjectival sense under the defunct theory of recapitulation derives from tribal history as an overly literal learned borrowing from German Stammesgeschichte; ordinarily, Stamm would o...

TRIBES.d: Plural of TRIBE: A social group.

TRICAR.d: three-wheeler; motor vehicle with three wheels

TRICKS.d: Plural of TRICK: A cunning act; to deceive.

TRICOT.e: From French tricot, from tricoter (“to knit”).

TRIFLE.d: An English dessert made from a mixture of thick custard, fruit, sponge cake, jelly and whipped cream.
TRIFLE.e: From Middle English trifle, trifel, triful, trefle, truyfle, trufful, from Old French trufle (“mockery”), a byform of trufe, truffe (“deception”), of uncertain origin.

TRILBY.d: narrow-brimmed type of felt hat, described as having a "shorter brim which is angled down at the front and slightly turned up at the back" in comparison to the fedora
TRILBY.e: From the stage adaptation of George du Maurier's novel Trilby, in which such hats were worn.

TRIODE.d: A thermionic valve containing an anode, a cathode, and a control grid; small changes to the charge on the grid control the flow from cathode to anode, which makes amplification possible.

TRIOSE.d: A sugar or saccharide containing three carbon atoms. Trioses are the smallest monosaccharides. Dihydroxyacetone and L-/D-glyceraldehyde are the only trioses.

TRIPLE.d: Made up of three related elements, often matching
TRIPLE.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Middle English triple (also þripell), from Latin triplus. Doublet of treble.

TRIPLY.d: At three times the severity or degree.

TRIPOD.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
Borrowed from Latin tripūs, tripodis, from Ancient Greek τρίπους (trípous); equivalent to tri- + -pod. Doublet of tripus and teapoy.

TRIPOS.e:
Alteration of tripus, as though with a Greek ending. For the examination: the word is supposed to refer to the three-legged stool formerly used at the examinations for these honours, though some derive it from the three brackets formerly printed on the back of the paper.
The etym...

TRIPPY.d: Strange, surreal, similar to the effects of a hallucinogen.

TRITON.d: the nucleus of a tritium atom, consisting of a proton and two neutrons.
TRITON.e: From trito- + -on. From tritium, from Ancient Greek τρίτος (trítos, “third”).

TRIVET.d: A stand with three short legs, especially for cooking over a fire.
TRIVET.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Middle English trevet, from Old English trefet, borrowed from Latin tripēs, tripedis (“tripod”).

TRIVIA.d: Insignificant trifles of little importance, especially items of unimportant information; froth.
TRIVIA.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
From Latin trivia, plural of trivium (“place where three roads meet”). The term came to be used for any public place, and then for anything commonplace. Furthermore, because the beginners' course at university was called trivium, the word came to be used only fo...

TROGON.d: A bird in the family Trogonidae from the order Trogoniformes, most of which live in Central and South America, have colorful feathers, and nest in holes in trees.
TROGON.e: Present active participle of Ancient Greek τρώγω (trṓgō, “chew, gnaw”).

TROIKA.d: A Russian carriage drawn by a team of three horses abreast.
TROIKA.e: From Russian тро́йка (trójka, “a group of three”).

TROJAN.d: Malware that appears to perform or actually performs a desired task for a user while performing a harmful task without the user's knowledge or consent.

TROMPE.e: From French trompe. Doublet of trump and tulumba.

TROPHY.d: An object, usually in the form of a statuette, cup, or shield, awarded for success in a competition or to mark a special achievement.
TROPHY.e: From Middle French trophée, from Latin trophaeum (“a sign of victory, a monument”), tropaeum, from Ancient Greek τρόπαιον (trópaion, “monument of an enemy's defeat”), from neuter of τροπαῖος (tropaîos, “of defeat”), from τροπή (tropḗ, “a rout, a turning of an enemy”).

TROPIC.d: Either of the two parallels of latitude 23°26′ north and south of the equator; the farthest points at which the sun can be directly overhead; the boundaries of the torrid zone or tropics.
TROPIC.e: From Late Latin tropicus (“of or pertaining to the solstice, as a noun, one of the tropics”), from Ancient Greek τροπικός (tropikós, “of or pertaining to a turn or change; or the solstice; or a trope or figure; tropic; tropical; etc.”), from τροπή (tropḗ, “turn; solstice; trope”)...

TROUGH.d: A long, narrow container, open on top, for feeding or watering animals.
TROUGH.e:
PIE word
 *dóru
From Middle English trogh, from Old English troh, trog (“a trough, tub, basin, vessel for containing liquids or other materials”), from Proto-West Germanic *trog, from Proto-Germanic *trugą, *trugaz, from Proto-Indo-European *drukós, enlargement of *dóru (“tree”)....

TROUPE.d: A company of, often touring, actors, singers or dancers.
TROUPE.e: Attested 1825; Unadapted borrowing from French troupe, which see for more. Doublet of troop, and possibly also of thorp and dorp.

TROWEL.d: A mason’s tool, used in spreading and dressing mortar, and breaking bricks to shape them.
TROWEL.e: From Middle English trowell, trouel, truel, from Middle French truelle, from Late Latin truella, from Classical Latin trulla, the diminutive of trua (“ladle”). Doublet of trullo.

TRUANT.d: Shirking or wandering from business or duty; straying; hence, idle; loitering.
TRUANT.e: The adjective and noun are derived from Middle English truant, truand, truaund (“(adjective) idle; tending to vagrancy (uncertain; may be a use of the noun); (noun) beggar; mendicant friar; vagrant, wanderer; worthless person, rogue, scoundrel; one who is absent without leave, tr...

TRUDGE.d: A tramp, i.e. a long and tiring walk.
TRUDGE.e: Mid-16th century. Original meaning was somewhat idiomatic, meaning "to walk using snowshoes." Probably of Scandinavian origin, compare Icelandic þrúga (“snowshoe”), Norwegian truga (“snowshoe”) and dialectal Swedish trudja (“snowshoe”).

TRUING.d: Present participle of TRUE: Conforming to the actual state of reality or fact; factually correct.
TRUING.e: From Middle English trewe, from Old English trīewe, (Mercian) trēowe (“trusty, faithful”), from Proto-Germanic *triwwiz (compare Saterland Frisian trjou (“honest”), Dutch getrouw and trouw, German treu, Norwegian and Swedish trygg (“safe, secure’”)), from pre-Germanic *drewh₂yos,...

TRUSTS.d: Plural of TRUST: Firm belief; to believe in.

TRUSTY.e: From Middle English trusty, tristy, tresty, equivalent to trust + -y.

TRUTHS.d: Plural of TRUTH: The quality of being true.

TSETSE.d: Any fly of the genus Glossina, native to Africa, that feeds on human and animal blood; known primarily as a carrier of parasitic trypanosomes.

TUBBED.d: Past tense of TUB: A flat-bottomed vessel, of width similar to or greater than its height, used for storing or packing things, or for washing things in.
TUBBED.e: From Middle English tubbe, tobbe, from Middle Dutch tubbe or Middle Low German tubbe, tobbe, further etymology unknown. Considered to be unrelated to tube.

TUBBER.d: Comparative form of TUB: A flat-bottomed vessel, of width similar to or greater than its height, used for storing or packing things, or for washing things in.
TUBBER.e: From Middle English tubbe, tobbe, from Middle Dutch tubbe or Middle Low German tubbe, tobbe, further etymology unknown. Considered to be unrelated to tube.

TUBFUL.d: an amount that would fill a tub

TUBULE.d: A small pipe or fistular body; a little tube.
TUBULE.e: Learned borrowing from Latin tubulus, diminutive of tubus.

TUCKED.d: Past tense of TUCK: To pull or gather up (an item of fabric).
TUCKED.e: From Middle English tuken, touken (“to torment, to stretch (cloth)”), from Old English tūcian (“to torment, vex”) and Middle Dutch tucken (“to tuck”), both from Proto-Germanic *teuh-, *teug- (“to draw, pull”) (compare also *tukkōną), from Proto-Indo-European *dewk- (“to pull”). A...

TUCKET.d: A fanfare played on one or more trumpets, bugles or similar.
TUCKET.e: From tuck (“a blow, a drum beat”), from Old French touchet (“stroke, blow”). Compare toccata. Compare also Middle French toquer from Old French *toquer (“to strike”).

TUFFET.d: A clump of grass or similar vegetation; a small grass-covered mound.
TUFFET.e: From Old French touffel, diminutive of touffe (“tuft”). Regarding etymological and semantic uncertainty, see Wikipedia at Little Miss Muffet § Tuffet and §§ Uncertain meaning.

TUFTED.d: Past tense of TUFT: A bunch of feathers, grass or hair, etc., held together at the base.
TUFTED.e: From Middle English tuft, toft, tofte, an alteration of earlier *tuffe (> Modern English tuff), from Old French touffe, tuffe, toffe, tofe (“tuft”) (modern French touffe), from Late Latin tufa (“helmet crest”) (near Vegezio). Compare Old English þūf (“tuft”), Old Norse þúfa (“mou...

TUGGED.d: Past tense of TUG: To pull or drag with great effort.
TUGGED.e:
From Middle English tuggen, toggen, from Old English togian (“to draw, drag”), from Proto-West Germanic *togōn, from Proto-Germanic *tugōną (“to draw, tear”), from Proto-Indo-European *dewk- (“to pull”).
Cognate with Middle Low German togen (“to draw”), Middle High German zogen (...

TUGGER.d: Comparative form of TUG: To pull or drag with great effort.
TUGGER.e:
From Middle English tuggen, toggen, from Old English togian (“to draw, drag”), from Proto-West Germanic *togōn, from Proto-Germanic *tugōną (“to draw, tear”), from Proto-Indo-European *dewk- (“to pull”).
Cognate with Middle Low German togen (“to draw”), Middle High German zogen (...

TULWAR.d: A type of curved sword used in India and throughout South Asia.

TUMBLE.d: A fall, especially end over end.
TUMBLE.e: From Middle English tumblen (“to fall over and over again, tumble”), frequentative of Middle English tumben (“to fall, leap, dance”), from Old English tumbian, from Proto-Germanic *tūmōną (“to turn, rotate”). Cognate with Middle Dutch tumelen (whence Dutch tuimelen), Middle Low G...

TUMEFY.e: From French tuméfier, from Latin tumefaciō, ultimately from tumeō, from Proto-Indo-European *tum-éh₁- (“to be swelling”), stative stem of *tum- (“to swell”).

TUMMED.d: Past tense of TUM: shortened form of tummy

TUMMER.d: Comparative form of TUM: shortened form of tummy

TUMOUR.e: From Middle English tumour, from Old French tumour, from Latin tumor (“swelling”), from tumeō (“bulge, swell”, verb), from Proto-Indo-European *tewh₂- (“to swell”). Related to English thumb.

TUMULT.d: Confused, agitated noise as made by a crowd.
TUMULT.e: From Old French tumulte, from Latin tumultus (“noise, tumult”).

TUNDRA.d: A flat and treeless Arctic biome.
TUNDRA.e: Borrowed from Russian ту́ндра (túndra), from Kildin Sami тӯндрэ (tūndre), the accusative and genitive form of тӯндар (tūndar).

TUNICA.e: From Latin tunica. Doublet of tunic and maybe distantly related to chiton.

TUNING.d: Action of the verb to tune.

TUNNED.d: Past tense of TUN: A large cask; an oblong vessel bulging in the middle, like a pipe or puncheon, and girt with hoops; a wine cask. (See a diagram comparing cask sizes.)
TUNNED.e:
From Middle English tunne, tonne (“cask, barrel”), from Old English tunne (“tun, cask, barrel”), from Proto-Germanic *tunnǭ, *tunnō (“tun, barrel, cask”), from Latin tunna, probably of Gaulish origin.
Cognate with North Frisian tenn (“tun, barrel, cask”), Dutch ton (“tun, barrel,...

TUNNEL.e: From Middle French tonnelle (“net”) or tonel (“cask”), diminutive of Old French tonne (“cask”), a word of uncertain origin and affiliation. Related to Old English tunne (“tun; cask; barrel”). More at tun.

TUNNER.d: Comparative form of TUN: A large cask; an oblong vessel bulging in the middle, like a pipe or puncheon, and girt with hoops; a wine cask. (See a diagram comparing cask sizes.)
TUNNER.e:
From Middle English tunne, tonne (“cask, barrel”), from Old English tunne (“tun, cask, barrel”), from Proto-Germanic *tunnǭ, *tunnō (“tun, barrel, cask”), from Latin tunna, probably of Gaulish origin.
Cognate with North Frisian tenn (“tun, barrel, cask”), Dutch ton (“tun, barrel,...

TUPELO.d: Any of several trees of the genus Nyssa which grow in swampy regions on the eastern, southern and midwestern United States.

TURBAN.d: A man's headdress made by winding a length of cloth round the head.
TURBAN.e: From Middle French turbant, from Italian turbante, from Ottoman Turkish دلبند (tülbent), from Classical Persian دلبند (dulband), also the root of tulip.

TURBID.d: Having the lees or sediment disturbed; not clear. (of a liquid)
TURBID.e: From Middle English turbide, borrowed from Latin turbidus (“disturbed”), from turba (“mass, throng, crowd, tumult, disturbance”).

TURBIT.d: A kind of pigeon developed over many years of selective breeding, known for its peaked crest, short beak, and frill of feathers on the breast.

TURBOT.d: Any of species Scophthalmus maximus (syn. Psetta maxima) of flatfish native to Europe.
TURBOT.e: From Middle English turbot, turbut, from Anglo-Norman turbut, Old French turbot, torbot, from Old Swedish tornbut, from törn (“thorn”) + but (“butt, flatfish”).

TUREEN.d: A broad, deep serving dish used for serving soup or stew.
TUREEN.e: From earlier terrene (thus pronunciations with /tj/, /t͡ʃ/ are spelling pronunciations), borrowed from French terrine. Doublet of terrine.

TURFED.d: Past tense of TURF: A layer of earth covered with grass; sod.
TURFED.e:
From Middle English turf, torf, from Old English turf (“turf, sod, soil, piece of grass covered earth, greensward”), from Proto-West Germanic *turb, from Proto-Germanic *turbz (“turf, lawn”), from Proto-Indo-European *derbʰ- (“tuft, grass”).
Cognate with Dutch turf (“turf”), Midd...

TURGID.d: Distended beyond the natural state by some internal agent, especially fluid, or expansive force.
TURGID.e: From Latin turgidus (“swollen, inflated”), from turgeō (“to swell”).

TURKEY.e: Clipping of turkey-cock and turkey-hen, originally denoting the guinea fowl, an African bird that was first imported to Europe through Turkey. The word was then transferred to the superficially similar North American bird Meleagris gallopavo.

TURNED.d: Past tense of TURN: To make a non-linear physical movement.
TURNED.e: From Middle English turnen, from Old English turnian, tyrnan (“to turn, rotate, revolve”), from From Proto-West Germanic *turnēn (“to turn, lathe”) (also the source of German turnen and its derivatives) and Old French torner (“to turn”), both from Latin tornāre (“to round off, tu...

TURNER.d: One who or that which turns.
TURNER.e: From Middle English turner, torner, tornere, turnere, turnare, equivalent to turn + -er. Also from Middle English turnour, tornour, tournour, turnoure, from Old French tornour, tourneour, tourneur, tornëor (“one who fashions something by turning”).

TURNIP.d: The white root of a yellow-flowered plant, Brassica rapa, grown as a vegetable and as fodder for cattle.
TURNIP.e: From Middle English turnepe, probably from turn + Middle English nepe, from Old English nǣp, from Latin nāpus. The component turn may be due to the round shape of the plant as though turned on a lathe, or because it must be turned and twisted to be harvested. Cognate to neep. See...

TURRET.d: A little tower, frequently a merely ornamental structure at one of the corners of a building or castle.
TURRET.e: From Middle English touret, from Old French torete (French tourette), diminutive of tour (“tower”), from Latin turris. Doublet of tor, tourelle, and tower. See tower.

TURTLE.d: Any land or marine reptile of the order Testudines, characterised by a protective shell enclosing its body. See also tortoise.
TURTLE.e: Modification of Middle English tortou, tortu, from Old French tortüe (under the influence of Middle English turtel, turtur (“turtledove”), see Etymology 2 below), from Medieval Latin tortuca (compare Spanish tortuga), the same source of tortoise (see there for more). Displaced na...

TURVES.d: Plural of TURF: A layer of earth covered with grass; sod.
TURVES.e:
From Middle English turf, torf, from Old English turf (“turf, sod, soil, piece of grass covered earth, greensward”), from Proto-West Germanic *turb, from Proto-Germanic *turbz (“turf, lawn”), from Proto-Indo-European *derbʰ- (“tuft, grass”).
Cognate with Dutch turf (“turf”), Midd...

TUSHED.d: Past tense of TUSH: A tusk.
TUSHED.e: From Middle English tusshe, tusche, tussch, tossche, tosch, from Old English tūsc, from Proto-Germanic *tunþskaz. Doublet of tusk.

TUSHES.e: From Middle English tusshe, tusche, tussch, tossche, tosch, from Old English tūsc, from Proto-Germanic *tunþskaz. Doublet of tusk.

TUSKED.d: Past tense of TUSK: One of a pair of elongated pointed teeth that extend outside the mouth of an animal such as walrus, elephant or wild boar, and which continue to grow throughout the animal's life.
TUSKED.e: From Middle English tusk (also tux, tusch), from Old English tūx, tūsc (“canine tooth, tusk, molar”), from Proto-West Germanic *tų̄sk, *tunsk, from Proto-Germanic *tunþskaz (“canine tooth”), extended form of *tanþs (“tooth”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃dónts (“tooth”). Cognate w...

TUTSAN.d: Hypericum androsaemum, a Eurasian perennial shrub.

TUTTED.d: Past tense of TUT: Tut tut; an expression of disapproval.

TWEEDY.d: made of tweed, or having a similar rough texture

TWEEZE.d: To pluck or grasp using tweezers.

TWELVE.d: The cardinal number occurring after eleven and before thirteen, represented in Arabic numerals as 12 and in Roman numerals as XII.
TWELVE.e: From Middle English twelve, from Old English twelf (“twelve”), from Proto-Germanic *twalif, an old compound of *twa- (“two”) and *-lif (“left over”) (i.e., two left over after having already counted to ten), from Proto-Indo-European *leyp- (“leave, remain”). Cognate with Saterlan...

TWENTY.d: The cardinal number 20, occurring after nineteen and before twenty-one.
TWENTY.e: From Middle English twenty, twenti, from Old English twēntiġ (“twenty”, literally “two tens”), from Proto-Germanic *twaintigiwiz, *twai tigiwiz, an old compound of *twain- (“two”) + *-tigaz (“group of ten”), equivalent to two + -ty, or twain + -ty. Cognate with Scots twenty, tuen...

TWINGE.d: To have a sudden, pinching or sharp pain in a specific part of the body, like a twitch.
TWINGE.e: The verb is derived from Middle English twengen (“to nip, pinch, tweak; to tear at”), from Old English twenġan (“to pinch, squeeze”), from Proto-West Germanic *twangijan (“to pinch, squeeze”), from Proto-Germanic *twangijaną (“to pinch, squeeze”), the causative form of *twinganą ...

TWITCH.d: A brief, small (sometimes involuntary) movement out of place and then back again; a spasm.
TWITCH.e:
From Middle English twicchen, from Old English *twiċċan, from Proto-West Germanic *twikkijan (“to nail, pin, fasten, clasp, pinch”).
Cognate with English tweak, Low German twikken, German Low German twicken (“to pinch, pinch off”), zweckōn and gizwickan (> German zwicken (“to pin...

TYCOON.d: A wealthy and powerful business person.
TYCOON.e: Borrowed from Japanese 大君(たいくん) (taikun, “great lord, prince”), a title for the shōgun. Related to taipan, from Cantonese 大班 (daai⁶ baan¹). The game sense was derived from the use of tycoon in titles of games in which one plays a tycoon (e.g., RollerCoaster Tycoon).

TYKING.d: Present participle of TYKE: A mongrel dog.
TYKING.e:
From Middle English tike, tyke, from Old Norse tík (“female dog”), from Proto-Germanic *tīkō. Compare Icelandic tík, Faroese tík, and Swedish tik, all meaning “bitch”.
Sense 5 (“Roman Catholic”) is an alteration of taig, and was first used in writing in the early 20ᵗʰ century.

TYMPAN.d: A piece of cloth padding placed under the platen of a letterpress to distribute the pressure on the sheet being printed.

TYPHUS.d: Any of several similar diseases, characterised by high recurrent fever, caused by Rickettsia bacteria. Not to be confused with typhoid fever.
TYPHUS.e: From New Latin typhus, from Ancient Greek τῦφος (tûphos, “fever, stupor”), from τύφω (túphō, “to smoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ-, extended form of *dʰew- (“scatter like dust”).

TYPIFY.d: To embody, exemplify; to represent by a form, image, model, or resemblance.

TYPING.d: Present participle of TYPE: A grouping based on shared characteristics; a class.
TYPING.e: From Middle English type (“symbol, figure, emblem”), from Latin typus, from Ancient Greek τύπος (túpos, “mark, impression, type”), from τύπτω (túptō, “I strike, beat”).

TYRANT.d: A usurper; one who gains power and rules extralegally, distinguished from kings elevated by election or succession.
TYRANT.e: From Middle English tyraunt, tiraunt, tyrant, tyrante, from Old French tyrant, from the addition of a terminal -t to tiran (cp. French tyran) via a back-formation related to the development of French present participles out of the Latin -ans form, from Latin tyrannus (“despot”), ...

TYRING.d: Present participle of TYRE: The ring-shaped protective covering around a wheel which is usually made of rubber or plastic composite and is either pneumatic or solid.
TYRING.e: The Oxford English Dictionary suggests that the word derives from attire, while other sources suggest a connection with the verb to tie. George Sturt in The Wheelwright's Shop (1923) makes a case for the latter derivation in that the metal tyre ('tyer') pulled the wooden wagon wh...

UGLIER.d: Comparative form of UGLY: Displeasing to the eye; aesthetically unpleasing.
UGLIER.e: Inherited from Middle English ugly, uggely, uglike, borrowed from Old Norse uggligr (“fearful, dreadful, horrible in appearance”), from uggr (“fear, apprehension, dread”) (possibly related to agg (“strife, hate”)), equivalent to ug + -ly. Cognate with Scots ugly, uglie, Icelandic...

UGLIFY.d: To make ugly; to destroy or worsen the appearance or attractiveness of.
UGLIFY.e: From ugly + -fy. Sense 3 by analogy with prettify.

ULLAGE.d: In a wine bottle, the empty space between the cork and the top of the wine.
ULLAGE.e: From Middle English ulage, from Anglo-Norman ulliage, from *ullier (“to fill a partially empty cask”), from Old French oel (“bunghole”, literally “eye”), from Latin oculus (“eye”). See French ouillage.

ULSTER.d: The northern province of Ireland, made up of all six Northern Irish counties and three counties in the Republic of Ireland.
ULSTER.e: Possibly from Old Norse Uladztir, itself from Old Irish Ulaid (“Ulstermen”). More at Ulster.

UMLAUT.d: An assimilatory process whereby a vowel is pronounced more like a following vocoid that is separated by one or more consonants.
UMLAUT.e: Borrowed from German Umlaut in the 19ᵗʰ century, from um- or um (“around, re-, trans-”) + Laut (“sound”), from Old High German hlūt. More at loud.

UMPIRE.d: An official who presides over a sports match.
UMPIRE.e: From a Middle English rebracketing of a noumpere as an oumpere, from Old French nonper (“odd number, not even (as a tie-breaking arbitrator)”), from non (“not”) + per (“equal”), from Latin par (“equal”). Doublet of nonpareil.

UNBELT.e: From Middle English unbelten, equivalent to un- + belt.

UNBIND.e: From Middle English unbinden, from Old English unbindan, onbindan (“to unbind; untie”), from Proto-West Germanic *andabindan, from Proto-Germanic *andabindaną, equivalent to un- + bind. Cognate with Dutch ontbinden, German entbinden, Gothic 𐌰𐌽𐌳𐌱𐌹𐌽𐌳𐌰𐌽 (andbindan).

UNBURY.d: To dig up, to remove from the ground.
UNBURY.e: From Middle English unburien, unbirien, from Old English *unbyrġan (compare Old English unbyrġed (“unburied”)), equivalent to un- + bury.

UNCAGE.d: To take out of or release from a cage.

UNCIAL.d: Of or relating to an ounce, or an inch, especially to letters printed an inch high.
UNCIAL.e: Attested 1650, from Latin uncia (“a twelfth part, ounce, inch”).

UNCLES.d: Plural of UNCLE: The brother of one's parent.
UNCLES.e: From Old French oncle, from Latin avunculus.

UNCLIP.d: To release something by removing a clip.

UNCOOL.d: Not in accord with the current fashion, standards, or mores of a particular group; not cool.

UNCORD.d: To remove or untie cords; to unbind.

UNCORK.d: To open (a bottle or other container sealed with a cork or stopper) by removing the cork or stopper from.

UNCURL.d: To straighten out from being curled up.

UNDINE.e: From German Undine, from New Latin undīna, from Latin unda (“wave”).

UNDOCK.d: To remove (a ship) from a dock.

UNDRAW.d: To draw aside or open; to pull back a layer of fabric, e.g. a curtain.

UNEASE.d: Trouble; misery; a feeling of disquiet or concern.
UNEASE.e: From Middle English unese, equivalent to un- + ease. Compare disease.

UNEVEN.d: Of a surface, not even; covered with raised spots, pits and grooves.
UNEVEN.e: From Middle English uneven, from Old English unefen (“unequal, unlike, dissimilar, diverse, irregular”), equivalent to un- + even. Cognate with Dutch oneven (“unequal, uneven, odd”), German uneben (“uneven, rough, irregular, bumpy”).

UNFAIR.e: From Middle English unfair (“unattractive, unseemly”), from Old English unfæġer (“ugly”), equivalent to un- + fair.

UNFOLD.e: From Middle English unfolden, from Old English unfealdan (“to unfold”), equivalent to un- + fold.

UNGLUE.d: to separate that which was held by glue

UNHAND.d: To release from the hand; to let go.

UNHOLY.d: Not holy; (by extension) evil, impure, or otherwise perverted.
UNHOLY.e: From Middle English unholi, unhaliȝ, from Old English unhāliġ, from Proto-Germanic *unhailagaz, equivalent to un- + holy. Cognate with Scots unhaly, Dutch onheilig, German Low German unhillig, German unheilig, Danish uhellig, Swedish ohelig.
