UNIPED.d: A person or creature with only one foot or leg.

UNIQUE.d: Being the only one of its kind; unequaled, unparalleled or unmatched.
UNIQUE.e: Borrowed from French unique. Piecewise doublet of any.

UNISON.d: A public-sector trade union in the United Kingdom.

UNKIND.d: Lacking kindness, sympathy, benevolence, gratitude, or similar; cruel, harsh or unjust; ungrateful.
UNKIND.e: Inherited from Middle English unkynde; equivalent to un- + kind.

UNKNIT.e: From Middle English unknitten, unknetten, uncnütten, from Old English uncnyttan, equivalent to un- + knit.

UNKNOT.d: In knot theory, a loop that is not knotted.

UNLIKE.d: Not like; dissimilar (to); having no resemblance; unalike.
UNLIKE.e: From Middle English unlic, unlich, from Old English unlīċ, unġelīċ (“unlike, different, dissimilar, diverse”), from Proto-Germanic *ungalīkaz. By surface analysis, un- + like. Cognate with Dutch ongelijk, German ungleich, Old Norse úlíkr (see there for North Germanic descendants)...

UNLINK.d: To decouple; to remove a link from, or separate the links of.

UNLOAD.d: To remove the load or cargo from (a vehicle, etc.).

UNLOCK.d: To undo or open a lock or something locked by, for example, turning a key, or selecting a combination.
UNLOCK.e: From Middle English unloken, unlouken, onlouken, from Old English onlūcan (“to unlock”), equivalent to un- + lock. Cognate with Dutch ontluiken (“to unlock”).

UNMASK.d: To remove a mask from someone.

UNMATE.d: To detach (a part) from its corresponding part, as a plug from a socket.

UNMEET.e: From Middle English unmete, vnmete, unimete, from Old English unġemǣte, unmǣte (“immense, enormous; unsuitable”), equivalent to un- + meet (“fit, right”).

UNMESH.d: To (cause to) cease to be meshed together.

UNMOOR.d: To unfix or unsecure (a moored boat).

UNMUTE.d: To restore the sound output (on a speaker or other audio device), having previously muted it.

UNPAIR.d: To change from a paired to a non-paired state.

UNPICK.e: From Middle English unpiken, equivalent to un- + pick.

UNPLUG.d: To disconnect from a supply, especially an electrical socket.

UNREAL.d: Not real or substantial; having no actual presence in reality; lacking the characteristics of reality.

UNREEL.d: To remove or uncoil from a reel.

UNREST.d: A state of trouble, confusion and turbulence, especially in a political context; a time of riots, demonstrations and protests.
UNREST.e: From Middle English unreste, equivalent to un- + rest. Cognate with West Frisian ûnrêst (“unrest”), Dutch onrust (“unrest”), German Low German Unrüst (“unrest”). Compare also Saterland Frisian Uunraue (“unrest”), German Unruhe (“unrest”), Danish uro (“unrest”), Swedish oro (“unre...

UNROOF.d: To remove a roof from, e.g. a building.

UNROOT.d: To tear up by the roots; to uproot.

UNROPE.d: To remove the rope or ropes from.

UNRULY.e: From Middle English unruly (“unquiet, restless”), equivalent to un- + rule + -ly (compare Middle English ruly, reuli (“subject to a religious rule, regular”)), but also representing a modified continuation of earlier Middle English unrouly, unroly (“unquiet, restless”), equivalen...

UNSEAM.d: To open the seam or seams of; to rip; to cut open.

UNSHIP.d: To unload cargo from a ship or other vessel.

UNSNAP.e: From un- + snap. Compare Dutch ontsnappen (“to elude; escape”, literally “to snap out of; break free from”).

UNTICK.d: (UK) To uncheck; to remove a tick mark from.

UNTUCK.d: To remove something from a relatively hidden location or position where it is tucked.

UNWISE.e: From Middle English unwis, from Old English unwīs (“unwise, foolish, ignorant, uninformed, insane”), equivalent to un- + wise. Cognate with Dutch onwijs (“unwise”), German unweise (“unwise”), Danish uvis (“unwise”), Swedish ovis (“unwise”), Icelandic óvís (“unwise”).

UNWRAP.d: To open or undo, as what is wrapped or folded.
UNWRAP.e: From Middle English unwrappen, equivalent to un- + wrap.

UPBEAT.d: Having a fast pace, tempo, or beat.

UPCAST.e: From Middle English upcasten, equivalent to up- + cast.

UPDATE.d: An advisement providing more up-to-date information than currently known.
UPDATE.e: From up- + date. Earliest usages from 1940s (see Citations).

UPHILL.d: Up a slope, towards higher ground.

UPHOLD.d: To hold up; to lift on high; to elevate.
UPHOLD.e: From Middle English upholden, equivalent to up- + hold. Compare Dutch ophouden (“to stop, cease, hold up”), German aufhalten (“to stop, halt, detain”). Compare also Middle Low German upholt, Old Norse upphald (“uphold, support”).

UPKEEP.d: Maintenance; the act or effort of keeping something in good and working condition.

UPLAND.d: The area in the interior of a country with a generally higher elevation.
UPLAND.e:
From Middle English upland, from Old English ūpland (“the country”); equivalent to up- + land.
The word as an adjective developed in Middle English.

UPLIFT.d: To raise something or someone to a higher physical, social, moral, intellectual, spiritual or emotional level.

UPLINK.d: The portion of a communications link used for the transmission of signals from an Earth terminal to a satellite or to an airborne platform. An uplink is the converse of a downlink. An uplink or downlink is distinguished from reverse link or forward link.

UPLOAD.d: To transfer data to a computer on a network, especially to a server on the Internet.

UPPERS.d: Plural of UPPER: Higher in position.

UPRATE.d: To give a higher rating to.

UPREAR.d: To raise something up; to rise up; to erect
UPREAR.e: From Middle English upreren, equivalent to up- + rear.

UPROAR.e: Calque of Dutch oproer or German Aufruhr, as up + roar.

UPROOT.d: To tear up (a plant, etc.) by the roots, or as if by the roots; to extirpate, to root up.
UPROOT.e:
PIE word
 *wréh₂ds
From up- (prefix indicating a higher direction or position) + root (“to tear up by the roots; (figuratively) to remove forcibly from a place; to eradicate, exterminate”, verb). Root is derived from root (“underground part of a plant”, noun), from Middle English...

UPSETS.d: Plural of UPSET: Unhappy; to disturb.

UPSIDE.d: The highest or uppermost side or portion of something.

UPSIZE.d: To make larger or more numerous.

UPTAKE.e: From Middle English uptaken (“to take up, lift”), partial calque of earlier Middle English upnimen (“to take up, lift”), equivalent to up- + take. Compare Swedish upptaga, uppta (“to take up”).

UPTURN.d: An upward turn or trend, especially in business activity or profit.
UPTURN.e: From Middle English upturnen, equivalent to up- + turn.

UPVOTE.d: A vote for something that increases a cumulative tally of popularity.

UPWARD.d: In a direction from lower to higher; toward a higher place; in a course toward the source or origin.
UPWARD.e: From Old English upweardes, equivalent to up + -ward.

UPWELL.d: To rise from a lower source; to well up.

URACIL.d: One of the bases of RNA, pairing with adenine.
URACIL.e: From uro- + ac(etic) + -ile. Coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.

URANYL.d: The divalent radical UO₂²⁺, conveniently regarded as a residue of many uranium compounds.

URBANE.d: Of a person (usually a man): having refined manners; courteous, polite, suave.
URBANE.e: A variant of urban + -ane (a variant of -an (suffix meaning ‘of or pertaining to’ forming adjectives)). Urban is borrowed from Middle French urbain (“belonging to a city, urban; courteous, refined, urbane”) (modern French urbain), or from its etymon Latin urbānus (“of or belongin...

URCHIN.e: From Middle English yrchoun, irchoun (“hedgehog; sea urchin”), from Old Northern French irechon, from Vulgar Latin *ērīciōnem, from Latin ericius. Compare modern French hérisson, whence the English doublet herisson.

URETER.d: Either of the two long, narrow ducts that carry urine from the kidneys to the urinary bladder.

URGENT.e: Borrowed from Middle French urgent (“pressing, impelling”), from Latin urgēns, from urgēre (“to press”), from Proto-Indo-European *werǵʰ- (“bind, squeeze”). Equivalent to urge + -ent. Related to German würgen (“to strangle”), Lithuanian ver̃žti (“to string, tighten, constrict”), ...

URGING.d: Present participle of URGE: A strong desire; an itch to do something.

URINAL.d: A device or fixture used for urination, particularly
URINAL.e: From Middle English urinal, urynal, orynal, from Old French urinal, orinal (“vessel for urination”), from Latin ūrīnālis (“urinary”). Use for plumbing fixtures attested from 1851.

URNFUL.d: As much as an urn will hold.

URNING.d: Present participle of URN: A vase with a footed base.
URNING.e: From Middle English urne, from Old French urne, from Latin urna (“vessel”). Doublet of urna.

URSINE.d: Of, pertaining to, or characteristic of bears.
URSINE.e: Mid 16th century, from Latin ursīnus, adjectival form of ursus (“bear”) + -ine.

URUSES.e: From Latin ūrus. Doublet of ure (“aurochs”).

USABLE.e: From Old French usable, from the verb user (“to use”).

USEFUL.d: Having a practical or beneficial use.

USUALS.d: Plural of USUAL: Happening regularly; normal.

USURER.d: A person who loans money to others and charges interest, particularly at an exorbitant, exploitative, or illegal rate.
USURER.e: Anglo-Norman, from Old French usurier, Latin ūsūra (“interest”).

UTERUS.d: A reproductive organ of therian mammals in which the young are conceived and develop until birth.
UTERUS.e: From Latin uterus (“womb, belly”), from Proto-Indo-European *úderos (“abdomen, stomach”), from *úd (“out, outward”) + *-eros (contrastive suffix).

UTOPIA.d: A world in which everything and everyone works in perfect harmony.
UTOPIA.e: From New Latin Ūtopia, the name of a fictional island possessing a seemingly perfect socio-politico-legal system in the book Utopia (1516) by Sir Thomas More. Coined from Ancient Greek οὐ (ou, “not”) + τόπος (tópos, “place, region”) + -ία (-ía). Compare English topos and -ia.

UVULAR.d: Of or relating to the uvula.
UVULAR.e: From Latin ūvulāris. By surface analysis, uvula + -ar.

VACANT.e: From Old French vacant, from Latin vacāns.

VACATE.d: To move out of a dwelling or other property, either by choice or by eviction.
VACATE.e: Originally used in the legal sense "to annul", a denominal from Early Modern English vacat (“legal annulment”), a development from Middle English vacat (“absence or cancellation noted in a register”), from Latin vacat, third-person singular present active indicative of vacō (“to ...

VACUUM.d: A region of space that contains no matter.
VACUUM.e:
Borrowed from New Latin vacuum (“vacuum”), a subsense of Classical Latin vacuum (“empty space”), a substantivised form of vacuus (“empty”); related to vacāre (“to be empty”).
The exercise sense comes from analogy to the sucking action of a vacuum cleaner.

VAGARY.d: An erratic, unpredictable occurrence or action.
VAGARY.e: From Italian vagare (“wander”) and/or its source Latin vagārī (“to wander”), from Latin vagus (“wandering”). Later apparently reinterpreted in English as vague + -ery but without changing the spelling.

VAGINA.d: A sex organ leading from the vulval vestibule/urogenital sinus to the cervix of the uterus for copulation and birth in female therian mammals.
VAGINA.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Italic *wāgīnā
Latin vāgīnalbor.
English vagina
Learned borrowing from Latin vāgīna (“a sheath, scabbard; a covering, sheath, holder”).

VAILED.d: Past tense of VAIL: Profit; return; proceeds.
VAILED.e: From Middle English vayle, from Old French vail, from valoir (“to be worth”), from Latin valeō (“I am worth”).

VALINE.d: An essential amino acid 2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid found in most animal proteins.

VALISE.d: A piece of hand luggage such as a suitcase or travelling bag.

VALLEY.d: An elongated depression cast between hills or mountains, often with a river flowing through it.
VALLEY.e: From Middle English valey, valeye, from Anglo-Norman valey, Old French valee (compare French vallée), from Latin vallēs/vallis. Doublet of vlei and vly. Displaced native dene, from dene and partially displaced native dale, from dæl.

VALOUR.e: From Middle English valour, from Anglo-Norman valour, from Latin valor. Doublet of valure.

VALUER.d: A person who valuates; an assessor or appraiser.

VAMPED.d: Past tense of VAMP: The top part of a boot or shoe, above the sole and welt and in front of the ankle seam, that covers the instep and toes; the front part of an upper; the analogous part of a stocking.
VAMPED.e: From Middle English vaumpe, vaum-pei, vampe (“covering for the foot, perhaps a slipper or understocking; upper of a boot or shoe”), or from Anglo-Norman vampe, *vaumpé (“part of a stocking covering the top of the foot”), from Old French avantpied, avantpiet, variants of avantpié,...

VANDAL.d: A person who needlessly destroys, defaces, or damages things, especially other people's property.
VANDAL.e: 1660s, “willful destroyer of what is beautiful or venerable”, from Vandal, referring to a member of an ancient Germanic people, the Vandals, who are associated with senseless destruction as a result of their sack of Rome under King Genseric in 455. During the Enlightenment, Rome ...

VANISH.d: To become invisible or to move out of view unnoticed.
VANISH.e: Aphetic for obsolete evanish, from Middle English vanyshen, evaneschen, from Old French esvanir, esvaniss- (modern French évanouir), from Vulgar Latin *exvanire (“to vanish, disappear, to fade out”), from Latin evanescere, from vanus (“empty”). Doublet of evanesce.

VANITY.d: That which is vain, futile, or worthless; that which is of no value, use or profit.
VANITY.e: From va(i)n + -ity, from Middle English vanite, from Old French vanité, from Latin vānitas, from vānus, whence English vain. Doublet of vanitas.

VANNED.d: Past tense of VAN: A covered motor vehicle used to carry goods or (normally less than ten) persons, usually roughly cuboid in shape, Depending on the type of van, it can be bigger or smaller than a pickup truck and SUV, and longer and higher than a car but relatively smaller than a truck/lorry or a bus.

VANNER.d: Comparative form of VAN: A covered motor vehicle used to carry goods or (normally less than ten) persons, usually roughly cuboid in shape, Depending on the type of van, it can be bigger or smaller than a pickup truck and SUV, and longer and higher than a car but relatively smaller than a truck/lorry or a bus.

VARIED.d: Past tense of VARY: To change with time or a similar parameter.
VARIED.e: From Middle English varien, from Old French varier, from Latin variō (“to change, alter, make different”), from varius (“different, various”); see various.

VARIER.d: Comparative form of VARY: To change with time or a similar parameter.
VARIER.e: From Middle English varien, from Old French varier, from Latin variō (“to change, alter, make different”), from varius (“different, various”); see various.

VARIES.d: Plural of VARY: To change with time or a similar parameter.
VARIES.e: From Middle English varien, from Old French varier, from Latin variō (“to change, alter, make different”), from varius (“different, various”); see various.

VARLET.e: From Middle English varlet, varlette, from Old French varlet, variant of vadlet, vallet, vaslet. Doublet of valet.

VASSAL.d: The grantee of a fief, a subordinate granted use of a superior's land and its income in exchange for vows of fidelity and homage and (typically) military service.
VASSAL.e: From Middle English vassal, from Old French vassal, from Medieval Latin vassallus (“manservant, domestic, retainer”), from Latin vassus (“servant”), from Gaulish *wassos (“young man, squire”), from Proto-Celtic *wastos (“servant”) (compare Old Irish foss and Welsh gwas).

VATTED.d: Past tense of VAT: A large tub, such as is used for making wine or for tanning.
VATTED.e:
Inherited from Middle English vat, a dialectal variant of fat (“vat, vessel, cask”), from Old English fæt (“vat, vessel”), from Proto-West Germanic *fat, from Proto-Germanic *fatą (“vessel”), from Proto-Indo-European *pod- (“vessel”).
Cognate with Scots fat, vat, vautt (“vat, cas...

VATTER.d: Comparative form of VAT: A large tub, such as is used for making wine or for tanning.
VATTER.e:
Inherited from Middle English vat, a dialectal variant of fat (“vat, vessel, cask”), from Old English fæt (“vat, vessel”), from Proto-West Germanic *fat, from Proto-Germanic *fatą (“vessel”), from Proto-Indo-European *pod- (“vessel”).
Cognate with Scots fat, vat, vautt (“vat, cas...

VEALED.d: Past tense of VEAL: The flesh of a calf (i.e. a young bovine) used for food.
VEALED.e: From Middle English veel, from Anglo-Norman veel, from Latin vitellus, diminutive of vitulus (“calf”). Doublet of vitellus.

VECTOR.d: A directed quantity, one with both magnitude and direction; the signed difference between two points.
VECTOR.e:
Learned borrowing from Latin vector (“carrier, transporter”), from vehō (“I carry, I transport, I bear”), also ultimately the root of English vehicle.
The “person or entity that passes along an urban legend or other meme” sense derives from the disease sense.
The mathematics sens...

VEERED.d: Past tense of VEER: To let out (a sail-line), to allow (a sheet) to run out.
VEERED.e: Borrowed from Middle Dutch vieren (“to slacken”).

VEILED.d: Past tense of VEIL: Something hung up or spread out to hide or protect the face, or hide an object from view; usually of gauze, crepe, or similar diaphanous material.
VEILED.e: From Middle English veil, veyl, from Anglo-Norman and Old Northern French veil (“sail, veil, shroud”) (Francien Old French voil, French voile), Latin vēlum (“cloth, covering”). Displaced Middle English scleire, scleyre, sleyre, slyre (“veil”) (compare German Schleier). Doublet of...

VEINED.d: Past tense of VEIN: A blood vessel that transports blood from the capillaries back to the heart.
VEINED.e: From Middle English veyne, borrowed from Anglo-Norman veine, from Latin vēna (“a blood-vessel; vein; artery”) of uncertain origin. See vēna for more. Doublet of vena. Displaced native edre, from ǣdre (whence edder).

VELLUM.d: A type of parchment paper made from the skin of a lamb, baby goat, or calf.
VELLUM.e: From Old French velin (French vélin), from Latin vitulinus (“of a calf”), as if derived from Old French veel (“veal”).

VELOUR.d: A knit fabric similar to velvet, but usually somewhat coarser.

VELVET.d: A closely woven fabric (originally of silk, now also of cotton or man-made fibres) with a thick short pile on one side.
VELVET.e: From Middle English velvet, velwet, veluet, from Old Occitan veluet, from Vulgar Latin *villutittus, diminutive of villūtus, from Latin villus (“shaggy hair, tuft of hair”). Cognate with French velours.

VENDED.d: Past tense of VEND: Synonym of sell, now especially to sell through a vending machine.
VENDED.e: From French vendre, from Old French vendre, from Latin vendere, from vēnum (“(something for) sale”) + dare (“to give”).

VENDOR.d: A person or a company that vends or sells.
VENDOR.e: Borrowed from Anglo-Norman vendor (Old French vendeor), from Latin venditor (“seller”), from vendere (“to sell, cry up for sale, praise”), contraction of venundare, venumdare, also, as originally, two words venum dare (“to sell”), from venum (“sale, price”) + dare (“to give”).

VENEER.d: A thin decorative covering of fine material (usually wood) applied to coarser wood or other material.
VENEER.e: From German Furnier, from furnieren (“to inlay, cover with a veneer”), from French fournir (“to furnish, accomplish”), from Middle French fornir, from Old French fornir, furnir (“to furnish”), from Old Frankish frumjan (“to provide”), from Proto-Germanic *frumjaną (“to further, p...

VENERY.e: From Middle English venerie, borrowed from Middle French venerie, from Old French venerie (“hunting”), derived from vener, from Latin vēnor (“I hunt”).

VENIAL.d: Able to be forgiven; worthy of forgiveness.
VENIAL.e: From Old French venial, borrowed from Late Latin veniālem (“pardonable”), from Latin venia (“forgiveness”).

VENOUS.e: Morphologically vein + -ous, which is a borrowing from Latin vēnōsus (“full of veins, veiny”), from vēna (“a blood vessel, vein”) + -ōsus (“-ous, -ose”, adjectival suffix). Doublet of venose.

VENTED.d: simple past and past participle of vent

VENULE.d: A small vein, especially one that connects capillaries to a larger vein.

VERBAL.e: From Old French verbal, from Late Latin verbālis (“belonging to a word”). Equivalent to verb + -al.

VERIER.d: Comparative form of VERY: True, real, actual.
VERIER.e:
From Middle English verray, from Old French verai (“true”), from Early Medieval Latin vērāgus, from Classical Latin vērāx, derived from vērus, from Proto-Italic *wēros, from Proto-Indo-European *weh₁ros.
Distantly cognate with the Old English wǣr (“true”). Over time displaced the...

VERIFY.d: To substantiate or prove the truth of something.
VERIFY.e: From Old French verifier (French: vérifier), from Medieval Latin vērificāre (“make true”), from Latin vērus (“true”) + faciō (“do, make”); see -fy.

VERITY.d: Truth, fact or reality, especially an enduring religious or ethical truth; veracity.
VERITY.e: From Middle English verite, from Anglo-Norman verité or Middle French verité, from Old French verité, from Latin vēritās, from the adjective vērus (“true”).

VERMIN.d: Any of various common types of small insects or other animals which cause harm and annoyance.
VERMIN.e: From Middle English vermyn, vermyne, from Old French vermine, from Vulgar Latin *verminum (“vermin”), collective noun formed from Latin vermis (“worm”). Compare vermiculate and vermivorous. See also worm.

VERMIS.d: A narrow, worm-like structure found in animal brains between the hemispheres of the cerebellum; it is the site of termination of the spinocerebellar pathways that carry subconscious proprioception.
VERMIS.e: From Latin vermis (“worm”). Doublet of worm.

VERNAL.d: Pertaining to or occurring in spring.
VERNAL.e:
PIE word
 *wósr̥
From Latin vernālis (“(rare) of or pertaining to spring; vernal”), from vērnus (“of or pertaining to spring; vernal”) + -ālis (suffix forming adjectives of relationship). Vērnus is derived from vēr (“season of spring”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *wósr̥ ...

VERSET.d: A very short organ interlude or prelude.
VERSET.e: From Middle English verset, from Old French verset; equivalent to verse + -et.

VERTEX.d: The highest point, top or apex of something.
VERTEX.e: Late Middle English, borrowed from Latin vertex (“whirl, eddy; top, crown, peak, summit”). Doublet of vortex.

VERVET.d: A small African monkey, Chlorocebus pygerythrus, having a long tail, a black face with white cheek tufts and a greenish-brown coat
VERVET.e: From French vervet (1821, F. Cuvier), further origin obscure.

VESPER.d: The bell that summons worshippers to vespers; the vesper-bell.
VESPER.e: From Old French vespre, from Latin vesper (“evening star”).

VESSEL.d: A craft for transportation on or in water, air, or space.
VESSEL.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Italic *wāss
Late Latin vās
Proto-Indo-European *-lós
Proto-Italic *-elom
Late Latin -ulum
Late Latin -culum
Late Latin vāsculum
Proto-Indo-European *-lós
Proto-Italic *-elos
Late Latin -lus
Late Latin vāscellum
Old French vaisselbor.
Middle English vessel
En...

VESTAL.d: Of or pertaining to Vesta, the virgin goddess of the hearth.

VESTED.d: Past tense of VEST: A sleeveless garment that buttons down the front, worn over a shirt, and often as part of a suit; a waistcoat.
VESTED.e: From French veste (“a vest, jacket”), from Latin vestis (“a garment, gown, robe, vestment, clothing, vesture”), from Proto-Indo-European *wéstis, from *wes- (“to be dressed”) (English wear). Cognate with Sanskrit वस्त्र (vastra) and Spanish vestir.

VESTRY.d: A room in a church where the clergy put on their vestments and where these are stored; also used for meetings and classes; a sacristy.
VESTRY.e: From Anglo-Norman vesterie, from Old French vestiaire (“room for vestments, dressing room”), from Latin vestiarium (“wardrobe”). Doublet of vestiary.

VETOED.d: Past tense of VETO: A political right to disapprove of (and thereby stop) the process of a decision, a law etc.

VETTED.d: Past tense of VET: A veterinarian or veterinary surgeon.

VEXING.d: Present participle of VEX: To annoy, irritate.
VEXING.e: From Middle English vexen, from Old French vexer, from Latin vexāre (“disturb, agitate, annoy”). Doublet of quake. Displaced native Old English dreċċan and gremman.

VIABLE.d: Able to live on its own (as for a newborn).
VIABLE.e: Borrowed from French viable, with semantic influence of Latin viābilis (“passable”).

VIALED.d: Past tense of VIAL: A glass or plastic vessel or bottle, especially a small tube-shaped bottle used to store medicine, perfume or other chemicals.
VIALED.e: From Middle English vial, viole, a variant of fiole, phiole, phial (“small bowl or cup for liquids, etc.; flask”) [and other forms]: see further at phial. Doublet of phiale.

VICING.d: Present participle of VICE: Bad or immoral behaviour.
VICING.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English vice, from Old French vice, from Latin vitium (“fault or blemish”). Displaced native Old English unþēaw.

VICTIM.d: One that is harmed—killed, injured, subjected to oppression, deceit, or otherwise adversely affected—by someone or something, especially another person or event, force, or condition; in particular
VICTIM.e: From Middle French victime, from Latin victima (“sacrificial animal”).

VICTOR.d: The winner in a fight or contest.
VICTOR.e: Inherited from Middle English victour, victor, from Anglo-Norman victor, Latin victor (“conqueror”). Doublet of Victor.

VIDEOS.d: Plural of VIDEO: A recording of moving images.

VIEWED.d: simple past and past participle of view

VIEWER.d: Someone who views a spectacle; an onlooker or spectator.
VIEWER.e: From Middle English vewer; equivalent to view + -er.

VIGOUR.d: Active strength or force of body or mind; capacity for exertion, physically, intellectually, or morally; energy.
VIGOUR.e:
From Middle English vigour, from Old French vigour, from vigor, from Latin vigor, from vigeō (“thrive, flourish”), from Proto-Indo-European *weǵ- (“to be lively”).
Related to vigil, vegetable, vajra, and waker.

VILIFY.d: To say defamatory things about someone or something; to speak ill of.
VILIFY.e: From Late Latin vīlificāre (“vilify”). Equivalent to vile + -ify. Compare vilipend.

VILLUS.d: A small projection from a membrane, particularly those found in the mucous membranes of the intestines.

VIMANA.d: A mythological flying palace or chariot described in Hindu texts and Sanskrit epics.

VINING.d: Present participle of VINE: Any plant whose stem requires support and which climbs by tendrils or twining.
VINING.e: From Middle English vīne, from Anglo-Norman vigne, from Vulgar Latin vīnia, from Latin vīnea (“vines in a vineyard”), from vīneus (“related to wine”), from vīnum (“wine”), from Proto-Italic *wīnom, from Proto-Indo-European *wóyh₁nom (“vine, wine”), from *weh₁y- (“to twist, wrap”)...

VINOUS.d: Pertaining to or having the characteristics of wine.
VINOUS.e: From Late Middle English vinous, vinose (“consisting of, containing, or made of wine”), from Latin vīnōsus (“fond of wine; wine-flavoured”), from vīnum (“wine”) + -ōsus (adjective-forming suffix meaning ‘full of, prone to’).

VIOLET.d: A plant or flower of the genus Viola, especially the fragrant Viola odorata; (inexact) similar-looking plants and flowers.
VIOLET.e:
Etymology tree
Latin viola
Old French -ette
Old French violettebor.
Middle English violet
English violet
Inherited from Middle English violet, vyolet, vyolette, from Old French violette, from Latin viola (“violet”). Cognate with Lithuanian violetinė (“purple, violet”) and Spanish...

VIOLIN.d: A small unfretted stringed instrument with four strings tuned (lowest to highest) G-D-A-E, usually held against the chin and played with a bow.
VIOLIN.e: From Italian violino (“little viola”), from viola + -ino (forming diminutives).

VIRAGO.d: A woman given to undue belligerence or ill manner at the slightest provocation.
VIRAGO.e: Borrowed from Latin virāgō (“warlike or heroic woman”, literally “manlike”).

VIRGIN.d: A person who has never had sexual intercourse, or (uncommonly) an animal that has never mated.
VIRGIN.e: From Middle English virgine, from Old French virgine, from Latin virginem, accusative of virgō. Doublet of Virgo. Displaced native Old English fǣmne.

VIRION.d: A single individual particle of a virus (the viral equivalent of a cell).
VIRION.e: From French virion. By surface analysis, virus + -on.

VIROID.d: A short section of RNA but without the protein coat typical of viruses, that are plant pathogens

VIRTUE.d: (uncountable) The idea of all that is good or excellent (in every sense of those terms) in a human being, collectively instantiated by a varying number of human traits known as "the virtues", the enumeration of which vary by the many virtue systems which have developed within different cultures, religions, and historical periods.
VIRTUE.e: From Middle English vertu, virtue, borrowed from Anglo-Norman vertu, virtu, from Latin virtus (“manliness, bravery, worth, moral excellence”), from vir (“man”). Doublet of vertu. See virile. In this sense, displaced Old English cræft, whence Modern English craft.

VISAED.d: Past tense of VISA: A permit to enter and leave a country, normally issued by the authorities of the country to be visited.
VISAED.e: From 1831, "official signature or endorsement on a passport," from French visa, from Latin charta vīsa (“paper that has been seen”) from feminine perfect passive of Latin vidēre (“to see”). Compare vision, video, vista.

VISAGE.e: From Middle English visage, from Anglo-Norman visage, from Vulgar Latin *vīsāticum, derived from Latin vīsus (“appearance, sight”), derived from vidēre (“to see”). Compare vision.

VISCID.e: From Late Latin viscidus, from viscum (“birdlime”).

VISCUS.d: One of the organs, as the brain, heart, or stomach, in the great cavities of the body of an animal; especially used in the plural, and applied to the organs contained in the abdomen.
VISCUS.e: From Latin vīscus (“any internal organ of the body”).

VISION.d: The sense or ability of sight.
VISION.e: From Middle English visioun, from Anglo-Norman visioun, from Old French vision, from Latin vīsiō (“vision, seeing”), noun of action from the perfect passive participle visus (“that which is seen”), from the verb videō (“I see”) + action noun suffix -iō.

VISITS.d: Plural of VISIT: To go to see.
VISITS.e: From Old French visiter, from Latin vīsitāre.

VISUAL.d: Related to or affecting the vision.
VISUAL.e: From Middle English vysual, from Old French, from Late Latin visualis (“of sight”), from Latin visus (“sight”), from videre (“to see”), past participle visus; see visage.

VITALS.d: Plural of VITAL: Essential; relating to life.

VIVIFY.d: To bring to life; to enliven.
VIVIFY.e: Late Latin vivificō via Old French vivifier.

VIZARD.d: A mask (cover for the face, used for disguise, protection, etc.)
VIZARD.e: An alteration of visor by confusion of the ending.

VIZIER.d: A high-ranking official or minister in an Islamic government, especially in the Ottoman Empire.
VIZIER.e: From Ottoman Turkish وزیر (vezir) (Turkish vezir) (via French vizir), from Arabic وَزِير (wazīr, “helper, aide, minister”, literally “one who bears (the burden of office)”). Doublet of wazir.

VIZSLA.d: A dog breed originating in Hungary.
VIZSLA.e: From Hungarian vizsla, itself probably a borrowing from a Slavic language; compare Serbo-Croatian vižao/вижао, Czech vyžle, Polish wyżeł, wyga (“old dog”), Russian выжла (vyžla).

VOCODE.d: To analyse or synthesize (speech) by means of a vocoder.

VOICED.d: Past tense of VOICE: Sound produced by speaking.
VOICED.e: From Old French vois, from Latin vōx.

VOICES.d: Plural of VOICE: Sound produced by speaking.
VOICES.e: From Old French vois, from Latin vōx.

VOIDED.d: Past tense of VOID: Containing nothing; empty; not occupied or filled.
VOIDED.e: From Middle English voide, voyde, from Old French vuit, voide, vuide (modern vide), in turn from Vulgar Latin *vocitum, ultimately from Latin vacuus.

VOLING.d: Present participle of VOLE: Any of a large number of species of small rodents of the tribes Arvicolini, Ellobiusini, Clethrionomyini, Pliomyini, Phenacomyini and Prometheomyini.
VOLING.e: Borrowed from Norn vollj, from Old Norse vǫllr (“field”), from Proto-Germanic *walþuz (“forest”). The Orkney dialectal term vole mouse, lit. “field mouse”, was introduced to general English by George Barry in 1805; John Fleming in 1828 was first to refer to the creature by the ep...

VOLLEY.d: The simultaneous firing of a number of missiles or bullets; the projectiles so fired.
VOLLEY.e: From Middle French volée (“flight”), from Vulgar Latin volta, from Late Latin volatus.

VOLUME.d: A three-dimensional measure of space that comprises a length, a width and a height. It is measured in units of cubic centimeters in metric, cubic inches or cubic feet in English measurement.
VOLUME.e: From Middle English volume, from Old French volume, from Latin volūmen (“book, roll”), from volvō (“roll, turn about”).

VOLUTE.d: The characteristic spiral curve on an Ionic capital, widely copied in other styles and in neoclassical architecture.
VOLUTE.e: From French volute, from Italian voluta, from Latin volūta, from the feminine of volūtus, perfect passive participle of volvō. Doublet of vault.

VOLVOX.d: Any of the genus Volvox of chlorophytes.
VOLVOX.e: From translingual Volvox, from Latin volvō (“to roll”).

VOODOO.d: Any of a group of related religious practices found chiefly in and around the Caribbean, particularly in Haiti and Louisiana.
VOODOO.e: From Louisiana Creole voudou, from Haitian Creole Vodou, from a West African language, such as Ewe vódũ (“deity, idol”), Fon vòdún (“fetish”) or the Kwa languages vodũ.

VORTEX.d: A whirlwind, whirlpool, or similarly moving matter in the form of a spiral or column.
VORTEX.e: Learned borrowing from Latin vortex. Doublet of vertex.

VOTARY.d: Consecrated by a vow or promise; consequent on a vow; devoted; promised.
VOTARY.e: From Latin votus, past participle of vovere (“to vow, to devote”).

VOTING.d: Having an associated right for the holder to vote as an owner of business.

VOTIVE.d: Dedicated or given in fulfillment of a vow or pledge.
VOTIVE.e: From Middle French votif, from Latin vōtīvus (“votive”), from vōtum (“vow”).

VOWING.d: Present participle of VOW: A solemn promise to perform some act, or behave in a specified manner, especially a promise to live and act in accordance with the rules of a religious order.
VOWING.e: Inherited from Middle English vowe, voue, that from Old French vut, in turn from Latin vōtum (“a promise, dedication, vow”), from vovēre (“to promise, vow”). Not related to avow. Doublet of vote.

VOYAGE.d: A long journey, especially by ship.
VOYAGE.e: From Middle English viage, borrowed from Anglo-Norman viage and Old French voiage, from Latin viaticum. The modern spelling is under the influence of Modern French voyage. Doublet of viaticum.

VOYEUR.d: A person who derives sexual pleasure from observing other people engaging in some intimate or sexual activity; one who engages in voyeurism.
VOYEUR.e: From French voyeur, from voir (“to see”).

VULGAR.e: From Middle English vulgare, from Latin vulgāris, from volgus, vulgus (“mob; common folk”), from Proto-Indo-European *wl̥k-. Compare Welsh gwala (“plenty, sufficiency”), Ancient Greek ἁλία (halía, “assembly”), εἰλέω (eiléō, “to compress”), Old Church Slavonic великъ (velikŭ, “gre...

WADDED.d: Past tense of WAD: An amorphous, compact mass.
WADDED.e:
Probably short for Middle English wadmal (“woolen cloth”), from Old Norse váðmál (“woolen stuff”), from váð (“cloth”) + mál (“measure”). See wadmal.
Cognate with Swedish vadd (“wadding, cotton wool”), German Wat, Watte (“wad, padding, cotton wool”), Dutch lijnwaad, gewaad, watten...

WADDER.d: Comparative form of WAD: An amorphous, compact mass.
WADDER.e:
Probably short for Middle English wadmal (“woolen cloth”), from Old Norse váðmál (“woolen stuff”), from váð (“cloth”) + mál (“measure”). See wadmal.
Cognate with Swedish vadd (“wadding, cotton wool”), German Wat, Watte (“wad, padding, cotton wool”), Dutch lijnwaad, gewaad, watten...

WADDLE.e:
From Middle English wadelen, frequentative form of waden, equivalent to wade + -le. Compare Saterland Frisian wuttelje (“to waddle”), Old High German wadalōn (“to roam; wander”), Middle High German wadelen, wedelen (“to wander; rove”), German wedeln (“to waggle”).
First known use...

WADING.d: Present participle of WADE: To walk through water or something that impedes progress.
WADING.e: From Middle English waden, from Old English wadan, from Proto-West Germanic *wadan, from Proto-Germanic *wadaną (“to go, pass through”), from Proto-Indo-European *weh₂dʰ- (“to go”). Cognates include Saterland Frisian waadje (“to wade”), West Frisian wâdzje (“to wade”), Dutch wade...

WAFFLE.d: A flat pastry pressed with a grid pattern, often eaten hot with butter and/or honey or syrup.
WAFFLE.e: The noun is borrowed from Dutch wafel (“waffle; wafer”), from Middle Dutch wafel, wafele, wavel, from Old Dutch *wāvila, from Proto-Germanic *wēbilǭ, *wēbilō, possibly related to Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“to braid, weave”) (whence Dutch weven (“to weave”) and English weave; co...

WAFTED.d: Past tense of WAFT: To (cause to) float easily or gently through the air.
WAFTED.e:
From Middle English waften, of uncertain origin. Possibly from unattested Old English *wafettan, from wafian (“to wave”) + -ettan, or perhaps borrowed from Middle Dutch wachten (“to guard, provide for”).
See also German wabern (“to waft”), Faroese veiftra (“to wave”) and Icelandi...

WAGGED.d: Past tense of WAG: To swing from side to side, as an animal's tail, or someone's head to express disagreement or disbelief.
WAGGED.e:
From Middle English waggen, probably from Old English wagian (“to wag, wave, shake”) with reinforcement from Old Norse vaga (“to wag, waddle”); both from Proto-Germanic *wagōną (“to wag”). Related to English way.
The verb may be regarded as an iterative or emphatic form of waw (v...

WAGGER.d: Comparative form of WAG: To swing from side to side, as an animal's tail, or someone's head to express disagreement or disbelief.
WAGGER.e:
From Middle English waggen, probably from Old English wagian (“to wag, wave, shake”) with reinforcement from Old Norse vaga (“to wag, waddle”); both from Proto-Germanic *wagōną (“to wag”). Related to English way.
The verb may be regarded as an iterative or emphatic form of waw (v...

WAGGLE.d: To move (something) with short, quick motions; to wobble.
WAGGLE.e: From Middle English wagelen (attested in wagelyng), possibly a borrowing of Middle Low German wagelen; equivalent to wag + -le (“(frequentative)”). Compare continental equivalents Middle High German wacken ( > Danish vakle, German wackeln), Swedish vagla, West Frisian waggelje, L...

WAGING.d: Present participle of WAGE: An amount of money paid to a worker for a specified quantity of work, usually calculated on an hourly basis and expressed in an amount of money per hour.
WAGING.e: From Middle English wage, from Anglo-Norman wage, from Old Northern French wage, a northern variant of Old French gauge, guage (whence modern French gage), Medieval Latin wadium, from Frankish *waddī (cognate with Old English wedd), from Proto-Germanic *wadją (“pledge”), from Pro...

WAIFED.d: Past tense of WAIF: An article of movable property which has been found, and of which the owner is not known, such as goods washed up on a beach or thrown away by an absconding thief; such items belong to the Crown, which may grant the right of ownership to them to a lord of a manor.
WAIFED.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English weif (“ownerless property subject to seizure and forfeiture; the right of such seizure and forfeiture; revenues obtained from such seizure and forfeiture”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman waif, weif [and other forms] (compare Angl...

WAILED.d: Past tense of WAIL: To cry out, as in sorrow or anguish.
WAILED.e:
c. 1300, Middle English weilen, waylen (“to sob, cry, wail”), from Old Norse væla (“to wail”), from væ, vei (“woe”), from Proto-Germanic *wai (whence also Old English wā (“woe”) (English woe)), from Proto-Indo-European *wáy.
The verb is first attested in the intransitive sense; t...

WAITED.d: Past tense of WAIT: To delay movement or action until some event or time; to remain neglected or in readiness.
WAITED.e: From Middle English waiten, from Anglo-Norman waiter, waitier (compare French guetter from Old French gaitier, guaitier), from Frankish *wahtwēn (“to watch, guard”), derivative of Frankish *wahtu (“guard, watch”), from Proto-Germanic *wahtwō (“guard, watch”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

WAIVES.d: Plural of WAIF: An article of movable property which has been found, and of which the owner is not known, such as goods washed up on a beach or thrown away by an absconding thief; such items belong to the Crown, which may grant the right of ownership to them to a lord of a manor.
WAIVES.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English weif (“ownerless property subject to seizure and forfeiture; the right of such seizure and forfeiture; revenues obtained from such seizure and forfeiture”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman waif, weif [and other forms] (compare Angl...

WAKEUP.d: An act or instance of waking up.

WAKING.d: Present participle of WAKE: (often followed by up) To stop sleeping.
WAKING.e:
A merger of two verbs of similar form and meaning:
* Middle English waken, Old English wacan, from Proto-West Germanic *wakan, from Proto-Germanic *wakaną.
* Middle English wakien, Old English wacian, from Proto-West Germanic *wakēn, from Proto-Germanic *wakāną.

WALING.d: Present participle of WALE: A ridge or low barrier.
WALING.e: The noun is from Middle English wāle (“planking, welt”), from Old English walu (“ridge, bank; rib, comb (of helmet); metal ridge on top of helmet; weal, mark of a blow”), from Proto-Germanic *waluz (“stick, root”), from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, wind, roll”). Akin to ...

WALKED.d: Past tense of WALK: To move on the feet by alternately setting each foot (or pair or group of feet, in the case of animals with four or more feet) forward, with at least one foot on the ground at all times. Compare run.
WALKED.e: From Middle English walken (“to move, walk, roll, turn, revolve, toss”), a conflation of Old English wealcan (“to move round, revolve, roll, turn, toss”) (ġewealcan (“to go, traverse”)) and Old English wealcian (“to curl, roll up”); both from Proto-West Germanic *walkan, from Pro...

WALLED.d: Past tense of WALL: A rampart of earth, stones etc. built up for defensive purposes.
WALLED.e: From Middle English wal, from Old English weall (“wall, dike, earthwork, rampart, dam, rocky shore, cliff”), from Proto-West Germanic *wall (“wall, rampart, entrenchment”), from Latin vallum (“wall, rampart, entrenchment, palisade”), from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, win...

WALLET.d: A small case, often flat and often made of leather, for keeping money (especially paper money), credit cards, etc.
WALLET.e: From Middle English walet (“bag, knapsack”), of uncertain origin. Possibly from an assumed Old Northern French *walet (“roll; bag; knapsack”), from Proto-Germanic *wal- (“to roll”). More at walk, well, wallow.

WALLOP.e: From Middle English wallopen (“gallop”), from Anglo-Norman [Term?], from Old Northern French walop (“gallop”, noun) and waloper (“to gallop”, verb) (compare Old French galoper, whence modern French galoper), from Frankish *wala hlaupan (“to run well”) from *wala (“well”) + *hlaup...

WALLOW.d: To roll oneself about in something dirty, for example in mud.
WALLOW.e: From Middle English walowen, walewen, walwen, welwen, from Old English wealwian (“to roll”), from Proto-West Germanic *walwōn, variant of *walwijan, from Proto-Germanic *walwijaną (“to roll”), from Proto-Indo-European *welw-, from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, wind, roll”...

WALNUT.d: A hardwood tree of the genus Juglans.
WALNUT.e: From Middle English walnote, walnutte, walnotte, from Old English wealhhnutu (“walnut”, literally “foreign nut”), from Proto-Germanic *walhaz (“foreigner”) + *hnuts (“nut”). Cognate with Dutch walnoot, German Walnuss, Swedish valnöt, Icelandic valhneta. Compare more recent term W...

WALRUS.d: A large Arctic marine mammal related to seals and having long tusks, tough, wrinkled skin, and four flippers, Odobenus rosmarus.
WALRUS.e: Probably borrowed from Dutch walrus, a compound of wal (“whale”) and ros (“horse”). Displaced native Old English horshwæl (literally “horse-whale”). Compare similar constructions in Danish hvalros, Old Norse hrosshvalr, and German Walross.

WAMPUM.d: Small cylindrical beads made from polished shells (especially white ones) which have been strung together, formerly used by Native American peoples of eastern North America for various purposes including as jewellery and money, and for record-keeping; (countable, archaic) one such bead.
WAMPUM.e:
Clipping of wampumpeag (“wampum”), probably borrowed from Massachusett wampompeage (“string of white beads used as money”).
Compare peag (“string of white beads used as money”), also a clipping of wampumpeag.
Sense 3 (“common kingsnake”) is from the similarity of the snake’s appe...

WANDER.d: To move without purpose or specified destination; often in search of livelihood.
WANDER.e: From Middle English wandren, from Old English wandrian (“to wander, roam, fly around, hover; change; stray, err”), from Proto-West Germanic *wandarōn (“to wander”), from *wandōn (“to turn, change”) + *-rōn (frequentative suffix). Cognate with Scots wander (“to wander”), German wa...

WANGLE.d: To obtain through deceitful or manipulative methods.
WANGLE.e: Blend of wag + dangle, first attested 1810–1820. Alternatively, from an alteration of waggle or wankle.

WANING.d: Present participle of WANE: A gradual diminution in power, value, intensity etc.
WANING.e:
From Middle English wane, from Old English wana (“defect, shortage”), from Proto-West Germanic *wanō, from Proto-Germanic *wanô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weh₂- (“to leave, abandon; empty, deserted”).
Cognates
See also wan-, want, and waste. Compare also Dutch waan (“insanity”)...

WANNED.d: Past tense of WAN: Pale, sickly-looking.
WANNED.e: From Middle English wan, wanne (“grey, leaden; pale grey, ashen; blue-black (like a bruise); dim, faint; dark, gloomy”), from Old English wann (“dark, dusky”), from Proto-Germanic *wannaz (“dark, swart”), of uncertain origin. Cognate with Old Frisian wann, wonn (“dark”).

WANNER.d: Comparative form of WAN: Pale, sickly-looking.
WANNER.e: From Middle English wan, wanne (“grey, leaden; pale grey, ashen; blue-black (like a bruise); dim, faint; dark, gloomy”), from Old English wann (“dark, dusky”), from Proto-Germanic *wannaz (“dark, swart”), of uncertain origin. Cognate with Old Frisian wann, wonn (“dark”).

WANTED.d: Past tense of WANT: To wish for or desire (something); to feel a need or desire for; to crave, hanker, or demand.
WANTED.e: From Middle English wanten (“to lack, to need”), from Old Norse vanta (“to lack”), from Proto-Germanic *wanatōną (“to be wanting, lack”), from *wanô (“lack, deficiency”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weh₂- (“empty”). Cognate with Middle High German wan (“not full, empty”), Middle ...

WANTON.d: Undisciplined, unruly; not able to be controlled.
WANTON.e: From Middle English wantoun, wantowen, wantoȝen, wantowe (“uneducated; unrestrained; licentious; sportive; playful”), from wan- (“not, un-, mis-”) + towen, i-towen (“educated”, literally “towed; led; drawn”), from Old English togen, ġetogen, past participle of tēon (“to train, di...

WAPITI.d: The American elk (Cervus canadensis). It was formerly considered to be in the same species as the European red deer, which it somewhat exceeds in size.

WARDED.d: Past tense of WARD: A warden; a guard; a guardian or watchman.
WARDED.e: From Middle English ward, from Old English weard (“keeper, watchman, guard, guardian, protector; lord, king; possessor”), from Proto-Germanic *warduz (“guard, keeper”), from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to heed, defend”). Cognate with Dutch waard, German Wart.

WARDEN.e: From Middle English wardein, from Anglo-Norman wardein, from warder (“to guard”), variant of Old French guarder (“to guard”) (whence modern French garder, also English guard), from Proto-Germanic *ward-; related to Old High German wartēn (“to watch”). Compare guardian, French gar...

WARDER.d: A guard, especially in a prison.
WARDER.e: From Middle English warder, wardere, perhaps in part continuing Old English weardere (“one who holds a country; inhabitant”), from Proto-West Germanic *wardārī (“guard, follower, watchman, lookout”), equivalent to ward + -er. Cognate with Dutch waarder (“inspector”), German Low G...

WARIED.d: Past tense of WARY: Cautious of danger; carefully watching and guarding against deception, trickery, and dangers; suspiciously prudent

WARIER.d: Comparative form of WARY: Cautious of danger; carefully watching and guarding against deception, trickery, and dangers; suspiciously prudent

WARING.d: Present participle of WARE: Goods or a type of goods offered for sale or use.
WARING.e:
From Middle English ware, from Old English waru, from Proto-West Germanic *waru, from Proto-Germanic *warō (“attention”) as in beware, in the sense of “an object of care, a valuable”, from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to watch, keep guard”), whence also ward.
Cognate with Saterlan...

WARMED.d: Past tense of WARM: Of a somewhat high temperature, often but not always connoting that the high temperature is pleasant rather than uncomfortable.
WARMED.e: From Middle English warm, werm, from Old English wearm, from Proto-West Germanic *warm, from Proto-Germanic *warmaz, either from Proto-Indo-European *wór-mo-s, from *wer- (“to burn”), or Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰor-mo-s, from the root *gʷʰer- (“warm, hot”). Cognate with West Frisi...

WARMTH.d: A moderate degree of heat; the sensation of being warm.
WARMTH.e: From Middle English warmth, warmeth, wermþe, from Old English *wiermþu (“warmth”), from Proto-West Germanic *warmiþu (“warmness; warmth”), corresponding to warm + -th (abstract nominal suffix). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Waarmte (“warmth”), West Frisian waarmte (“warmth”), Du...

WARNED.d: Past tense of WARN: To make (someone) aware of (something impending); especially:
WARNED.e: From Middle English warnen, warnien (“to warn; admonish”), from Old English warnian (“to take heed; warn”), from Proto-Germanic *warnōną (“to warn; take heed”), from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to be aware; give heed”). Cognate with Dutch waarnen (obsolete), German Low German war...

WARPED.d: Past tense of WARP: The state, quality, or condition of being twisted, physically or mentally:
WARPED.e:
From Middle English warp, werp, from Old English wearp, warp (“a warp, threads stretched lengthwise in a loom, twig, osier”), from Proto-Germanic *warpą (“a warp”), from Proto-Indo-European *werb- (“to turn, bend”).
Cognate with Middle Dutch warp, Middle Low German warp, German w...

WARRED.d: Past tense of WAR: Organized, large-scale, armed conflict between countries or between national, ethnic, or other sizeable groups, usually but not always involving active engagement of military forces.
WARRED.e: From Middle English werre, from Late Old English werre, wyrre (“armed conflict”), from Old Northern French werre (compare modern French guerre), from Medieval Latin werra, from Frankish *werru (“confusion; quarrel”), from Proto-Indo-European *wers- (“to mix up, confuse, beat, thr...

WARREN.d: A system of burrows in which rabbits live.
WARREN.e: From Middle English warenne, from Anglo-Norman and Old Northern French warenne (compare Old French guarenne, garenne (“game-park”)), probably ultimately from Frankish *warjan, from Proto-Germanic *warjaną (“ward off, defend against”); compare also Old French warir, guarir, a borr...

WARRER.d: Comparative form of WAR: Organized, large-scale, armed conflict between countries or between national, ethnic, or other sizeable groups, usually but not always involving active engagement of military forces.
WARRER.e: From Middle English werre, from Late Old English werre, wyrre (“armed conflict”), from Old Northern French werre (compare modern French guerre), from Medieval Latin werra, from Frankish *werru (“confusion; quarrel”), from Proto-Indo-European *wers- (“to mix up, confuse, beat, thr...

WARTED.d: Past tense of WART: A type of deformed growth occurring on the skin caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV).
WARTED.e: From Middle English warte, werte, from Old English wearte, from Proto-West Germanic *wartā, from Proto-Germanic *wartǭ. Cognate with Dutch wrat, German Warze, Hunsrik Waarz, Swedish vårta and Danish vorte.

WASABI.d: A plant of the species Eutrema japonicum, cultivated for its edible root.

WASHED.d: Past tense of WASH: To clean with water.
WASHED.e:
From Middle English wasshen, waschen, weschen, from Old English wascan, from Proto-West Germanic *waskan, from Proto-Germanic *waskaną, *watskaną (“to wash, get wet”), from Proto-Indo-European *wed- (“wet; water”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian waaske (“to wash”), West Frisian w...

WASHER.d: Something that washes; especially an appliance such as a washing machine or dishwasher.
WASHER.e: From Middle English wasshere, wassher, equivalent to wash + -er. Cognate with Dutch wasser, German Wäscher.

WASHES.d: Plural of WASH: To clean with water.
WASHES.e:
From Middle English wasshen, waschen, weschen, from Old English wascan, from Proto-West Germanic *waskan, from Proto-Germanic *waskaną, *watskaną (“to wash, get wet”), from Proto-Indo-European *wed- (“wet; water”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian waaske (“to wash”), West Frisian w...

WATERS.d: Plural of WATER: A transparent liquid essential for life.

WATERY.e: From Middle English watery, wattry, from Old English wæteriġ (“watery”), from Proto-West Germanic *watarīg. Equivalent to water + -y.

WATTLE.d: A construction of branches and twigs woven together to form a wall, barrier, fence, or roof.
WATTLE.e: From Middle English wattel, watel, from Old English watel, watul (“hurdle”). Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *wey- (“to turn, wind, bend”).

WAVIER.d: Comparative form of WAVY: Rising or swelling in waves.

WAVIES.d: Plural of WAVY: Rising or swelling in waves.

WAVING.d: Present participle of WAVE: To move back and forth repeatedly and somewhat loosely.
WAVING.e:
From Middle English waven, from Old English wafian (“to wave, fluctuate, waver in mind, wonder”), from Proto-West Germanic *wabōn, from Proto-Germanic *wabōną, *wabjaną (“to wander, sway”), from Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“to move to and from, wander”).
Cognate with Middle High ...

WAXIER.d: Comparative form of WAXY: Resembling wax in texture or appearance.
WAXIER.e: From Middle English waxi, wexy, equivalent to wax (“soft oily substance”) + -y.

WAXING.e:
From Middle English wax, from Old English weax, from Proto-Germanic *wahsą, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *woḱ-so-.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Woaks (“wax”), West Frisian waaks (“wax”), Dutch was (“wax”), German Wachs (“wax”), German Low German Wass (“wax”), Luxembourgish...

WAYING.d: Present participle of WAY: To do with a place or places.
WAYING.e:
From Middle English way, wey, from Old English weġ, from Proto-West Germanic *weg, from Proto-Germanic *wegaz, from Proto-Indo-European *weǵʰ-. Doublet of voe and possibly via.
Cognates
Cognate with North Frisian wai, wäi (“way”), Saterland Frisian Wai (“way”), West Frisian wei (...

WAYLAY.d: To lie in wait for and attack from ambush.
WAYLAY.e: From way + lay, likely a calque of Middle Dutch wegelagen (“besetting of ways, lying in wait with evil or hostile intent along public ways”). Compare Middle Low German wegelagen, German wegelagern (“to waylay; rob”).

WEAKEN.d: To make weaker or less strong.

WEALTH.d: Riches; a great amount of valuable assets or material possessions.
WEALTH.e: Inherited from Middle English welth, welthe (“happiness, prosperity”), from Old English *welþ, *welþu, from Proto-West Germanic *waliþu (“wealth”). Alternatively, possibly an alteration (due to similar words in -th: compare helth (“health”), derth (“dearth”)) of wele (“wealth, we...

WEANED.d: Past tense of WEAN: To cease giving breast milk to an offspring; to accustom and reconcile (a child or young animal) to a want or deprivation of mother's milk; to take from the breast or udder.
WEANED.e:
From Middle English wenen, from Old English wenian (“to accustom; habituate; train; prepare; make fit”), from Proto-West Germanic *wannjan, from Proto-Germanic *wanjaną (“to make wont; accustom”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to strive for; wish; love”).
Cognate with Dutch ...

WEAPON.d: An instrument of attack or defense in combat or hunting, e.g. most guns, missiles, or swords.
WEAPON.e: From Middle English wepen, from Old English wǣpn, from Proto-West Germanic *wāpn, from Proto-Germanic *wēpną (“weapon”), of unknown origin, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *wēbnom. Cognate with Scots wapyn, wappen (“weapon”), Saterland Frisian Woapen (“weapon”), West Frisian an...

WEARED.d: Past tense of WEAR: To have on:
WEARED.e:
Inherited from Middle English weren, werien, from Old English werian (“to clothe, cover over; put on, wear, use; stock (land)”), from Proto-West Germanic *waʀjan, from Proto-Germanic *wazjaną (“to clothe”), from Proto-Indo-European *wes- (“to dress, put on (clothes)”).
Cognate to...

WEARER.e: From Middle English werer, werere, equivalent to wear + -er.

WEASEL.d: Any of the carnivorous mammals of the genera Mustela, Neogale, Poecilogale, and Lyncodon, having a slender body, a long tail and usually a light brown upper coat and light-coloured belly.
WEASEL.e:
From Middle English wesele, from Old English weosule, from Proto-West Germanic *wisulā, from Proto-Germanic *wisulǭ.
The verb is from c. 1900, from the supposed cunningness of the weasel.

WEAVER.d: A person who weaves; especially, one who weaves cloth for a living.
WEAVER.e: From Middle English wevere, wever, from Old English *wefere, *wifre, *wæfre (“weaver”, in compounds), from Proto-West Germanic *webārī. By surface analysis, weave + -er. Compare Saterland Frisian Weeuwer (“weaver”), Dutch wever (“weaver”), German Low German Wever (“weaver”), Germ...

WEBBED.d: Past tense of WEB: The silken structure which a spider builds using silk secreted from the spinnerets at the caudal tip of its abdomen; a spiderweb.
WEBBED.e: From Middle English web, webbe, from Old English webb, from Proto-Germanic *wabją, from Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“weave”).

WEBBER.d: Comparative form of WEB: The silken structure which a spider builds using silk secreted from the spinnerets at the caudal tip of its abdomen; a spiderweb.
WEBBER.e: From Middle English web, webbe, from Old English webb, from Proto-Germanic *wabją, from Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“weave”).

WEBCAM.d: A video camera whose output may be viewed in real time over a computer network, originally the World Wide Web.
WEBCAM.e: From Web + cam, shortened from camera.

WEBIFY.d: To convert (content or information) into a format capable of being displayed on the World Wide Web.

WEBLOG.d: A website in the form of an ongoing journal.

WEDDED.e:
From Middle English wedden, weddien, from Old English weddian (“to pledge; wed”), from Proto-West Germanic *waddjōn, from Proto-Germanic *wadjōną (“to pledge”), from *wadją (“pledge”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *wedʰ- (“to pledge”).
Cognate with Scots wed, wod, wad (“to...

WEDDER.d: Comparative form of WED: To perform the marriage ceremony for; to join in matrimony.
WEDDER.e:
From Middle English wedden, weddien, from Old English weddian (“to pledge; wed”), from Proto-West Germanic *waddjōn, from Proto-Germanic *wadjōną (“to pledge”), from *wadją (“pledge”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *wedʰ- (“to pledge”).

WEEDED.d: Past tense of WEED: Any plant unwanted at the place where and at the time when it is growing.
WEEDED.e:
From Middle English weed, weod, from Old English wēod (“weed”), from Proto-West Germanic *weud (“weed”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Jood (“weed”), West Frisian wjûd (“weed”), Dutch wied (“unwanted plant, weed”), German Low German Weed (“weed”), Old High German wiota (“fern”)....

WEEPED.d: Past tense of WEEP: To cry; to shed tears, especially when accompanied with sobbing or other difficulty speaking, as an expression of emotion such as sadness or joy.
WEEPED.e:
From Middle English wepen, from Old English wēpan (“to weep, complain, bewail, mourn over, deplore”), from Proto-West Germanic *wōpijan, from Proto-Germanic *wōpijaną (“to weep”), from Proto-Indo-European *weh₂b- (“to call, cry, complain”).
Cognate with Scots weep (“to weep”), Sa...

WEEPIE.d: A sad or sentimental film, often portraying troubled romance, designed to elicit a tearfully emotional response from its audience.

WEEVIL.d: Any of many tens of thousands of species of herbivorous beetles, ranging in size from tiny to large, in the superfamily Curculionoidea, the most characteristic species having the head projecting in a distinctive snout with the mouthparts at the tip.
WEEVIL.e: From Middle English wevel, from Old English wifel (“beetle”), from Proto-West Germanic *wibil, from Proto-Germanic *wibilaz, from Proto-Indo-European *webʰel-, from *(h₁)webʰ- (“to wave, to weave”), said to be from the woven appearance of a weevil’s larval case, + *-el-, *-l̥- (d...

WEFTED.d: Past tense of WEFT: The horizontal threads that are interlaced through the warp in a woven fabric.
WEFTED.e: From Middle English wefte, from Old English wefan (“to weave”), from Proto-West Germanic *weban, from Proto-Germanic *webaną. Equivalent to weave + -t (abstract nominal suffix).

WEIGHT.d: The downwards force an object experiences due to gravity.
WEIGHT.e:
From Middle English weight, weiȝte, weght, wight, from Old English wiht, ġewiht (“weight”), from Proto-Germanic *wihtiz ("weight"; compare *weganą (“to move”)), from Proto-Indo-European *weǵʰ- (“to move; pull; draw; drive”). Equivalent to weigh + -t (abstract nominal suffix).
Cog...

WELDED.d: Past tense of WELD: A surname from Old English possibly deriving from the Old English word for woodland. The family is mainly located in the Southern regions of England.

WELKIN.d: The sky which appears to an observer on the Earth as a dome in which celestial bodies are visible; the firmament.
WELKIN.e: Inherited from Middle English welken, wolken (“weather; heavens; earlier cloud”), from Old English wolcnu (“sky, heavens”), plural form of wolcn (“cloud”), from Proto-West Germanic *wolkn (“cloud”), from Proto-Germanic *wulkną (“cloud”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *wĺ̥ɡ-no...

WELLED.d: Past tense of WELL: Accurately, competently, satisfactorily.
WELLED.e:
From Middle English wel, wal, wol, wele, from Old English wel (“well, abundantly, very, very easily, very much, fully, quite, nearly”), from Proto-Germanic *wela, *wala (“well”, literally “as wished, as desired”), from Proto-Indo-European *welh₁- (“wish, desire”).
