WELTED.d: Past tense of WELT: A surname from German.

WELTER.d: A general confusion or muddle, especially of a large number of items.
WELTER.e: From Middle English welteren, equivalent to welt + -er (frequentative suffix). Cognates include German Low German weltern (“to wallow; roll”), Old Norse velta (Danish vælte), German wälzen, Gothic 𐍅𐌰𐌻𐍄𐌾𐌰𐌽 (waltjan). Akin to wallow and Latin volvō.

WESTER.d: A strong westerly wind, a wind blowing from the west.

WETTED.d: Past tense of WET: Made up of liquid or moisture, usually (but not always) water.
WETTED.e: From Middle English wet (“wet, moistened”), wett, wette, past participle of Middle English weten (“to wet”), from Old English wǣtan (“to wet, moisten, water”), from Proto-West Germanic *wātijan, from Proto-Germanic *wētijaną (“to wet, make wet”), from Proto-Indo-European *wed- (“...

WETTER.d: Comparative form of WET: Made up of liquid or moisture, usually (but not always) water.
WETTER.e: From Middle English wet (“wet, moistened”), wett, wette, past participle of Middle English weten (“to wet”), from Old English wǣtan (“to wet, moisten, water”), from Proto-West Germanic *wātijan, from Proto-Germanic *wētijaną (“to wet, make wet”), from Proto-Indo-European *wed- (“...

WHAMMO.d: Used to emphasize the suddenness of an event.

WHEELS.d: Plural of WHEEL: A circular object that rotates.

WHEEZE.d: To breathe hard, and with an audible piping or whistling sound, as persons affected with asthma.
WHEEZE.e: From Middle English whesen, perhaps from Old Norse hvæsa (“to hiss”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ḱwes- (“to pant”).

WHERED.d: Past tense of WHERE: In what place.

WHERES.d: Plural of WHERE: In what place.

WHERRY.d: A light ship used to navigate inland waterways.
WHERRY.e: From Middle English whery (“small boat”), of obscure origin but cognate to French houari and Breton ouari, as well as Welsh chweri (“small boat”).

WHILED.d: Past tense of WHILE: A period of time; during the time that.

WHILES.d: Plural of WHILE: A period of time; during the time that.

WHIMSY.d: A quaint and fanciful idea; a whim; playfully odd behaviour.
WHIMSY.e: Probably from whims + -y. Related to whim-wham, whim.

WHINGE.d: To whine; to complain, especially in an annoying or persistent manner.
WHINGE.e: From a northern variant of Old English hwinsian (“to whine”), from Proto-West Germanic *hwinisōn (“to whine”), from Proto-West Germanic *hwīnan (“to whine”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱwey- (“to hiss, whistle, whisper”). Cognate with German winseln (“to whine, whimper”).

WHINNY.e: From Middle English whynyen, whinien, akin to Middle English whinen (“to whine”).

WHISKY.d: Alternative form of whiskey, an alcoholic liquor distilled from fermented grain, usually aged in oak barrels, (particularly) Scotch; a drink of this liquor.
WHISKY.e: Variant of usque, abbreviation of usquebaugh (compare obsolete whiskybae), from Scottish Gaelic uisge-beatha (“water of life”), calque of Medieval Latin aqua vitae. Compare akvavit, aquavit, aqua vitae, eau de vie, and water of life from the same source.

WHITED.d: Past tense of WHITE: The lightest colour.

WHITEN.d: (To cause) to become white or whiter; to bleach or blanch.
WHITEN.e: From Middle English whitenen, whitnen, from Old Norse hvítna (“to whiten”), from Proto-Germanic *hwītnōną (“to whiten, become white”), from Proto-Indo-European *kwind-, *kwint- (“bright”), equivalent to white + -en. Cognate with Icelandic hvítna (“to whiten”), Swedish vitna, hvit...

WHITES.d: Plural of WHITE: The lightest colour.

WHITEY.e: From white (“bright and colorless; a white-skinned person”) + -y (“forming diminutives”).

WHIZZY.d: Nifty; impressive, often in a superficial or showy way.

WHOOSH.d: A breathy sound like that of an object passing at high speed.

WHYDAH.d: Any of various black and white African birds with distinctive drooping long tailfeathers on males in mating season, suitable as cage birds.
WHYDAH.e: Alteration of the first component of widow bird, after Whydah (now Ouidah) in Benin.

WICKED.d: Evil or mischievous by nature; morally reprehensible.
WICKED.e: From Middle English wicked, wikked, an alteration of Middle English wicke, wikke (“morally perverse, evil, wicked”). Of uncertain origin. Possibly from an adjectival use of Old English wiċċa (“wizard, sorcerer”), from Proto-West Germanic *wikkō (“necromancer, sorcerer”), though t...

WICKET.d: A small door or gate, especially one beside a larger one.
WICKET.e: From Anglo-Norman, Old Northern French wiket, from Old Norse (specifically, Old East Norse) víkjas, diminutive of vík. Compare modern French guichet, ultimately from the same Old Norse source.

WIDGET.d: A placeholder name for an unnamed, unspecified, or hypothetical manufactured good or product, typically as an example for purposes of explaining concepts.
WIDGET.e: Coined by American playwright George S. Kaufman in 1924 in his play Beggar on Horseback (1924). The preface to the 1924 play credits an earlier German work from 1911 https://digital.ulb.hhu.de/download/pdf/5670231.pdf where there is an actor Elisabeth Wigge.

WIDTHS.d: Plural of WIDTH: The measurement from side to side.

WIFELY.d: Of, befitting, pertaining to, or characteristic of a wife or wives.
WIFELY.e: From Middle English wifly, wyfly, from Old English wīflīc (“womanly, wifely”), from Proto-Germanic *wībalīkaz (“wifely”). Cognate with Scots wifely (“womanly, wifely”), Dutch wijflijk, wijfelijk, German weiblich (“feminine, female”). By surface analysis, wife + -ly.

WIFING.d: Present participle of WIFE: A married woman, especially in relation to her spouse.
WIFING.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Germanic *wībą
Proto-West Germanic *wīb
Old English wīf
Middle English wyf
English wife
Inherited from Middle English wyf, wif, from Old English wīf (“woman, wife”), from Proto-West Germanic *wīb, from Proto-Germanic *wībą (“woman, wife”).
Germanic cognates i...

WIGEON.d: Any of three freshwater dabbling ducks.
WIGEON.e: Early 16th century. Probably from Middle French vigeon, from Old French vigeon, vingeon (“wigeon”), from Old French vignier (“to whine or shout”) + -on (“noun suffix”).

WIGGED.d: Past tense of WIG: A head of real or synthetic hair worn on the head to disguise baldness, for cultural or religious reasons, for fashion, or by actors to help them better resemble the character they are portraying.
WIGGED.e: Clipping of periwig, itself an alteration of French perruque. The meaning of "to reprimand" perhaps came from this being something a bigwig would do or perhaps from the expressions to flip one's wig, wigs on the green, or dash my wig!

WIGGER.d: Comparative form of WIG: A head of real or synthetic hair worn on the head to disguise baldness, for cultural or religious reasons, for fashion, or by actors to help them better resemble the character they are portraying.
WIGGER.e: Clipping of periwig, itself an alteration of French perruque. The meaning of "to reprimand" perhaps came from this being something a bigwig would do or perhaps from the expressions to flip one's wig, wigs on the green, or dash my wig!

WIGGLE.d: To move with irregular, back and forward or side to side motions; to shake or jiggle.
WIGGLE.e: From Middle English wiglen, probably from Middle Dutch wigelen (“to wiggle”) and perhaps Middle Low German wigelen, frequentative of wiegen (“to rock”), from wiege (“cradle”). See wain, and Dutch wieg (“cradle”). Cognate to Dutch wiggelen (“to wiggle”).

WIGGLY.d: Constantly moving, especially with small, undirected movements.
WIGGLY.e: From wiggle + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian wiggelg, wiggelch (“wiggly”), German Low German wiggelig (“wiggly, restless, fidgety”).

WIGWAG.d: Any of a number of mechanical or electrical devices which cause a component to oscillate between two states.
WIGWAG.e: From wig (“to wag, waggle”) + wag (“to swing”). The noun is derived from the verb.

WIGWAM.d: A dwelling having an arched framework overlaid with bark, hides, or mats, used by Native Americans in the northeastern United States.
WIGWAM.e: Borrowed from Abenaki wigwôm (“house”) or Penobscot wigwom (“house”), from Proto-Algonquian *wi·kiwa·ʔmi (“house”). Doublet of wickiup.

WIKIFY.d: To adapt to the standards and facilities of an existing wiki, such as by marking up with wikitext.

WILDED.d: Past tense of WILD: Untamed; not domesticated.
WILDED.e:
From Middle English wild, wilde, from Old English wilde, from Proto-West Germanic *wilþī, from Proto-Germanic *wilþijaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂welh₁- (“hair, wool, grass, ear (of corn), forest”).
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian wyld, Dutch wild, German wild, Danish vild,...

WILDER.d: comparative form of wild: more wild

WILFUL.e: From Middle English wilful; equivalent to will + -ful.

WILIER.d: Comparative form of WILY: Sly, cunning, full of tricks.
WILIER.e: From Middle English wily, wiley, wyly. By surface analysis, wil(e) + -y.

WILING.d: Present participle of WILE: A trick or stratagem practiced for ensnaring or deception; a sly, insidious artifice
WILING.e: From Middle English wile, wyle, from Old Northern French wile (“guile”) and Old English wīl (“wile, trick”) and wiġle (“divination”), from Proto-Germanic *wīlą (“craft, deceit”) (from Proto-Indo-European *wey- (“to turn, bend”)) and Proto-Germanic *wigulą, *wihulą (“prophecy”) (f...

WILLED.d: Past tense of WILL: Used to express the future tense, sometimes with an implication of volition or determination when used in the first person. Compare shall.
WILLED.e:
From Middle English willen, wullen, wollen, from Old English willan (“to want”), from Proto-West Germanic *willjan, from Proto-Germanic *wiljaną, from Proto-Indo-European *welh₁- (“to choose, wish”).
Cognates
Cognate with Yola ill, weel, well, will, woul, wull (“will”), North Fri...

WILLET.d: Tringa semipalmata (or formerly Catoptrophorus semipalmatus), a large shorebird in the family Scolopacidae.

WILLOW.d: Any of various deciduous trees or shrubs in the genus Salix, in the willow family Salicaceae, found primarily on moist soils in cooler zones in the northern hemisphere.
WILLOW.e: From Middle English wilwe, welew, variant of wilghe, from Old English welig, from Proto-West Germanic *wilig, from Proto-Germanic *wiligaz, from Proto-Indo-European *welik- (compare (Arcadian) Ancient Greek ἑλίκη (helíkē), Hittite 𒌑𒂖𒆪 (welku, “grass”)), from *wel- (“twist, turn”)...

WILTED.d: Past tense of WILT: To droop or become limp and flaccid (as a dying leaf or flower).
WILTED.e: Recorded since 1691, probably an alteration of welk, itself from Middle English welken, presumed from Middle Dutch (preserved in modern inchoative verwelken) or Middle Low German welken (“to wither”), cognate with Old High German irwelhen (“to become soft”).

WIMPLE.d: A cloth which usually covers the head and is worn around the neck and chin. It was worn by women in medieval Europe and is still worn by nuns in certain orders.
WIMPLE.e: From Middle English wympel, wimpel, from Old English wimpel (“veil, an article of women's dress; a covering for the neck, a cloak, a hood”), from Proto-Germanic *wimpilaz (“wimple, scarf, veil”). Cognate with Scots wympill (“wimple”), Dutch wimpel (“streamer, pennant”), German Wi...

WINDED.d: simple past and past participle of wind

WINDER.e: From Middle English wynder; equivalent to wind + -er.

WINDOW.d: An opening, usually covered by one or more panes of clear glass, to allow light and air from outside to enter a building or vehicle.
WINDOW.e: From Middle English wyndowe, wyndown, from Old Norse vindauga (“window”, literally “wind-eye; wind-hole”), equivalent to wind + eye. Cognate with Scots windae and windock, Faroese vindeyga, Norwegian Bokmål vindu, Norwegian Nynorsk vindauge, Danish vindue, archaic Swedish vindöga...

WINERY.d: A place where wine is made, or a company that makes wine.

WINGED.d: Past tense of WING: An appendage of an animal's (bird, bat, insect) body that enables it to fly.
WINGED.e:
From Middle English winge, wenge, from Old Norse vængr ("wing of a flying animal, wing of a building"; compare vængi (“ship's cabin”)), from Proto-Germanic *wēingijaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂weh₁- (“to blow”), thus related to wind.
Cognate with Danish, Norwegian Bokmål and S...

WINING.d: Present participle of WINE: An alcoholic beverage made by fermenting grape juice, with an ABV ranging from 5.5–16%.
WINING.e: From Middle English wyn, win, from Old English wīn, from Proto-West Germanic *wīn, from Proto-Germanic *wīną, either directly or via Latin vīnum (from Proto-Italic *wīnom) from Proto-Indo-European *wóyh₁nom (“wine”). Doublet of vine and vino.

WINKED.d: Past tense of WINK: To close one's eyes in sleep.
WINKED.e: From Middle English wynken, from Old English wincian (“to wink, make a sign, close the eyes, blink”, weak verb), from Proto-West Germanic *winkōn (“to close one's eyes”), from Proto-Indo-European *weng- (“to bow, bend, arch, curve”). Cognate with Middle Low German winken (“to bli...

WINKLE.d: A periwinkle or its shell, of family Littorinidae.

WINNED.d: Past tense of WIN: To conquer, defeat.
WINNED.e: From Middle English winnen, from Old English winnan (“to labour, swink, toil,”) (compare Old English ġewinnan (“conquer, obtain, gain; endure, bear, suffer; be ill”)), from Proto-West Germanic *winnan, from Proto-Germanic *winnaną (“to swink, labour, win, gain, fight”), from Prot...

WINNER.d: Comparative form of WIN: To conquer, defeat.
WINNER.e: From Middle English winnen, from Old English winnan (“to labour, swink, toil,”) (compare Old English ġewinnan (“conquer, obtain, gain; endure, bear, suffer; be ill”)), from Proto-West Germanic *winnan, from Proto-Germanic *winnaną (“to swink, labour, win, gain, fight”), from Prot...

WINNOW.d: To subject (granular material, especially food grain) to a current of air separating heavier and lighter components, as grain from chaff.
WINNOW.e: From Middle English winewen, windewen, windwen, from Old English windwian (“to winnow, fan, ventilate”), from Proto-West Germanic *windwōn, from Proto-Germanic *windwōną, *winþijaną (“to throw about, winnow”), from Proto-Indo-European *wē- (“to winnow, thresh”). Cognate with Midd...

WINTER.d: Traditionally the fourth of the four seasons, typically regarded as spanning the months of December, January, and February in temperate and polar regions of the Northern Hemisphere or the months of June, July, and August in the Southern Hemisphere. It is the time when the sun is lowest in the sky, resulting in short days, and the time of year with the lowest atmospheric temperatures for the region.
WINTER.e: From Middle English winter, from Old English winter, from Proto-West Germanic *wintru, from Proto-Germanic *wintruz (“winter”). Cognate with West Frisian winter (“winter”), Dutch winter (“winter”), German Winter (“winter”), Danish, Swedish and Norwegian vinter (“winter”), Iceland...

WINTRY.d: Suggestive or characteristic of winter; cold, stormy.
WINTRY.e: From winter + -y; compare Old English wintriġ (a parallel formation).

WIPING.d: Present participle of WIPE: To move an object over, maintaining contact, with the intention of removing some substance from the surface. (Compare rub.)
WIPING.e: From Middle English wipen, from Old English wīpian (“to wipe, rub, cleanse”), from Proto-West Germanic *wīpōn (“to wipe”), from Proto-Indo-European *weyp- (“to twist, wind around”). Cognate with German wippen (“to bob”), Swedish veva (“to turn, wind, crank”), Gothic 𐍅𐌴𐌹𐍀𐌰𐌽 (weipa...

WIRIER.d: Comparative form of WIRY: Resembling wire.

WIRING.d: present participle and gerund of wire

WISDOM.d: An element of personal character that enables one to distinguish the wise from the unwise.
WISDOM.e: From Middle English wisdom, from Old English wīsdōm (“wisdom”), from Proto-West Germanic *wīsadōm, from Proto-Germanic *wīsadōmaz (“wisdom”), corresponding to wise + -dom. Cognate with Scots wisdom, wysdom (“wisdom”), West Frisian wiisdom (“wisdom”), Dutch wijsdom (“wisdom”), Ger...

WISENT.d: The European bison, Bison bonasus or Bos bonasus.
WISENT.e: Borrowed from German Wisent. Doublet of bison.

WISHED.d: Past tense of WISH: A desire, hope, or longing for something or for something to happen.
WISHED.e:
From Middle English wisshen, wischen, wüschen, from Old English wȳsċan (“to wish”), from Proto-West Germanic *wunskijan, from Proto-Germanic *wunskijaną (“to wish”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”).
Cognate with Scots wis (“to wish”), Saterland Frisian wonskje ...

WISHES.d: Plural of WISH: A desire, hope, or longing for something or for something to happen.
WISHES.e:
From Middle English wisshen, wischen, wüschen, from Old English wȳsċan (“to wish”), from Proto-West Germanic *wunskijan, from Proto-Germanic *wunskijaną (“to wish”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”).
Cognate with Scots wis (“to wish”), Saterland Frisian wonskje ...

WISING.d: Present participle of WISE: Showing good judgement or the benefit of experience.
WISING.e:
From Middle English wis, wys, from Old English wīs (“wise”), from Proto-Germanic *wīsaz (“wise”), from Proto-Indo-European *weydstos, *weydtos, a participle form of *weyd-.
Cognate with Dutch wijs, German weise, Norwegian vis and Swedish vis. Compare wit.

WISPED.d: Past tense of WISP: A small bundle, as of straw or other like substance; any slender, flexible structure or group.
WISPED.e: From Middle English wispe, wyspe, wips, wipse, perhaps from an unrecorded Old English *wisp, *wips. Cognate with West Frisian wisp, Dutch wisp (“bundle of hay or straw”), Norwegian bokmål/Swedish/Bornholm Danish visp (“handful or bundle of grass, hay, etc.”). Akin also to Middle ...

WITHER.d: To shrivel, droop or dry up, especially from lack of water.
WITHER.e:
From Middle English widren, wydderen (“to dry up, shrivel”), related to or perhaps an alteration of Middle English wederen (“to expose to weather”), from Old English wederian (“to expose to weather, exhibit a change of weather”).
Cognates
From Proto-Germanic: Dutch verwederen, Du...

WITTED.d: having a specified form of wit (intellectual ability)
WITTED.e: From Middle English witted, ywitted, equivalent to wit + -ed. Compare Old English witod (“appointed, ordained, assured, certain”).

WITTER.d: To speak at length on a trivial subject.

WIZARD.d: Someone, usually male, who uses (or has skill with) magic, mystic items, and magical and mystical practices.
WIZARD.e: From Middle English wysard, wysarde, equivalent to wise + -ard. A uniquely medieval Anglo-Saxon word with no known morphologically exact cognates inside the Germanic family; did not gain distinct sense of "occultist, magic user" (as opposed to a philosopher or sage) until circa 1...

WOADED.d: Past tense of WOAD: The plant Isatis tinctoria.
WOADED.e: From Middle English wode, from Old English wād (“woad”), from Proto-West Germanic *waiʀd, from Proto-Germanic *waizdaz (“woad”), from Proto-Indo-European *woydʰ-. Cognate with Old Frisian wēd (“woad”), Dutch wede (“woad”), German Waid (“woad”), and with French guède, Italian guad...

WOBBLE.e: From earlier wabble (“wobble”), probably from Low German wabbeln (“to wobble”). Compare Dutch wiebelen and wobbelen (“to wobble”), German wabbeln (“to wobble”), Old Norse vafla (“to hover about, totter”).

WOGGLE.d: A Boy Scout's neckerchief clasp or slide, originally a loop or ring of leather.
WOGGLE.e: 1923, coined in Australia by Bill Shankley, from earlier American boondoggle. Popularized from 1929 by use in Scouting for Boys, 14th edition, by Baden-Powell.

WOLFED.d: Past tense of WOLF: Canis lupus; the largest wild member of the canine subfamily.
WOLFED.e: Inherited from Middle English wolf, from Old English wulf, ƿulf, from Proto-West Germanic *wulf, from Proto-Germanic *wulfaz, from Proto-Indo-European *wĺ̥kʷos. See also Saterland Frisian Wulf, West Frisian and Dutch wolf, German Wolf, Norwegian and Danish ulv; also Sanskrit वृक ...

WOLVES.d: Plural of WOLF: Canis lupus; the largest wild member of the canine subfamily.
WOLVES.e: Inherited from Middle English wolf, from Old English wulf, ƿulf, from Proto-West Germanic *wulf, from Proto-Germanic *wulfaz, from Proto-Indo-European *wĺ̥kʷos. See also Saterland Frisian Wulf, West Frisian and Dutch wolf, German Wolf, Norwegian and Danish ulv; also Sanskrit वृक ...

WOMANS.d: Plural of WOMAN: An adult female human.

WOMBAT.d: Any of several herbivorous, burrowing marsupials, of the family Vombatidae, mainly found in southern and eastern Australia.

WOMBED.d: Past tense of WOMB: In female mammals, the organ in which the young are conceived and grow until birth; the uterus.
WOMBED.e: From Middle English wombe, wambe, from Old English womb, wamb (“belly, stomach; bowels; heart; womb; hollow”), from Proto-West Germanic *wambu, from Proto-Germanic *wambō (“belly, stomach, abdomen”). Cognate with Scots wam, wame (“womb”), Dutch wam (“dewlap of beef; belly of a fi...

WONDER.d: A sense of awe, astonishment and curiosity, inspired by unexpected events, novel experiences and inexplicable circumstances, sometimes accompanied by surprise, shock or reverence.
WONDER.e:
From Middle English wonder, wunder, from Old English wundor (“wonder, miracle, marvel”), from Proto-West Germanic *wundr, from Proto-Germanic *wundrą.
Cognate with Scots wunner (“wonder”), West Frisian wonder, wûnder (“wonder, miracle”), Dutch wonder (“miracle, wonder”), Low Germ...

WONTED.d: Past tense of WONT: One's habitual way of doing things; custom, habit, practice.
WONTED.e:
From Old English gewunod, past participle of ġewunian (“to be accustomed to, dwell”), possibly as a conflation of wone (“custom, habit, practice”) and wont (participle adjective, below).
Compare German Low German Gewohnte (“custom, habit”), Dutch gewoonte, Swedish van. Likely rel...

WOODED.d: Past tense of WOOD: The substance making up the central part of the trunk and branches of a tree. Used as a material for construction, to manufacture various items, etc. or as fuel.
WOODED.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English wode, from Old English wudu, widu (“wood, forest, grove; tree; timber”), from Proto-West Germanic *widu, from Proto-Germanic *widuz (“wood”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weydʰh₁- (“to separate”).
Cognate with Dutch wede (“wood, twig”), Middle ...

WOODEN.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From wood + -en. Dates from 1530s, gradually replaced treen (“made from a tree”), from Middle English treen, from Old English triewen.

WOODSY.d: Of, relating to, or suggestive of a wooded area.
WOODSY.e: From woods + -y (suffix meaning ‘having the quality of’ forming adjectives), to distinguish the word from woody (“made of wood, or having wood-like properties, etc.”).

WOOFED.d: Past tense of WOOF: The set of yarns carried by the shuttle of a loom which are placed crosswise at right angles to and interlaced with the warp; the weft.
WOOFED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English wof, oof, owf (“threads in a piece of woven fabric at right angles to the warp, weft, woof; also sometimes the warp; transverse filaments of a spider web”) [and other forms] (the forms beginning with w were influenced by warp and weft), fro...

WOOING.d: Present participle of WOO: To endeavor to gain someone's affection/support.
WOOING.e: From Middle English wowen, woȝen, from Old English wōgian (“to woo, court, marry”), of uncertain origin. Cognate with Scots wow (“to woo”). Perhaps related to Old English wōg, wōh (“bending, crookedness”), in the specific sense of "bend or incline (some)one toward oneself". If so...

WOOLED.d: Past tense of WOOL: The hair of the sheep, llama and some other ruminants.
WOOLED.e:
From Middle English wolle, from Old English wull, from Proto-West Germanic *wullu, from Proto-Germanic *wullō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂wĺ̥h₁neh₂.
Cognates
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Wulle, German Low German Wull, Dutch wol, German Wolle, Norwegian ull; also Welsh gwlân, L...

WOOLLY.e: From Middle English wolly, equivalent to wool + -y. Cognate with Saterland Frisian wullich (“woolly”), Dutch wollig (“woolly”), German wollig (“woolly”), Swedish ullig (“woolly”).

WORDED.d: Past tense of WORD: The smallest unit of language that has a particular meaning and can be expressed by itself; the smallest discrete, meaningful unit of language. (contrast morpheme.)
WORDED.e: From Middle English word, from Old English word, from Proto-West Germanic *word, from Proto-Germanic *wurdą, from Proto-Indo-European *wr̥dʰh₁om. Doublet of verb and verve; further related to vrata.

WORDIE.d: Someone interested in words; especially, one enthusiastic about the study of word use but not bent on being pedantic about usage prescription.
WORDIE.e: From word + -ie; the enthusiast sense is parallel in nature with foodie and was probably influenced by it.

WORKED.e: From Middle English work, werk, from Old English weorc, from Proto-West Germanic *werk, from Proto-Germanic *werką, from Proto-Indo-European *wérǵom.

WORKER.d: One who works: a person who performs labor for a living; traditionally, especially, manual labor.
WORKER.e: From Middle English werkere, worcher, wercher, equivalent to work + -er. Displaced the older term wright, from Old English wyrhta.

WORKUP.d: A general medical examination to assess a person's health and fitness.

WORLDS.d: Plural of WORLD: The Earth; all people.

WORMED.d: Past tense of WORM: A generally tubular invertebrate of the annelid phylum; an earthworm.
WORMED.e: From Middle English worm, werm, wurm, wirm, from Old English wyrm (“worm, snake”), from Proto-Germanic *wurmiz, from Proto-Indo-European *wr̥mis, possibly from *wer- (“to turn”). Doublet of vermin and wyrm, the latter of which is a fairly recent borrowing directly from the Old En...

WORMER.d: Dewormer, medicine used in deworming an animal.

WORSEN.e: From Middle English wursnen; equivalent to worse + -en.

WORTHS.d: Plural of WORTH: The value of something.

WORTHY.e: From Middle English worthy, wurthi, from Old English *weorþiġ (“worthy”), equivalent to worth + -y. Cognate with Dutch waardig (“worthy”), Middle Low German werdig (“worthy”), German würdig (“worthy”), Swedish värdig (“worthy”), Icelandic verðugt (“worthy”).

WOWING.d: Present participle of WOW: An indication of excitement, surprise, astonishment, or pleasure.
WOWING.e: Attested since the 16th century; borrowed from Scots wow; ultimately a natural exclamation.

WOYLIE.d: A species of bettong, Bettongia penicillata.

WRAITH.d: A ghost or specter, especially a person's likeness seen just after their death.
WRAITH.e:
Borrowed from Middle Scots wraith, first attested in 1513 as a translation of the Aeneid.
The word has no certain etymology; it may be a transferred use of Middle Scots wraith, wrath (nominally "anger, rage", adjectivally "angry, wrathful"), thus connecting it to writhe and makin...

WRASSE.d: Any one of numerous edible, marine, spiny-finned fishes of the family Labridae, of which several species are found in the Mediterranean and on the Atlantic coast of Europe. Many of the species are brightly colored.
WRASSE.e: Plural of dialectal (Cornwall) wrah, wraugh, wrath, from Cornish wragh (“old woman, hag; wrasse”), lenited form of gwragh.

WREATH.e: From Middle English wreth, wrethe (“coiled or rounded shape; decorative garland, wreath; chaplet, crown; ring”, noun), from Old English wrǣd, wrǣþ, wriþa (“bandage”), from Proto-West Germanic *wrīþan (“to twist; to weave”), from Proto-Germanic *wrīþaną (“to twist; to weave”), fro...

WRENCH.d: A movement that twists or pulls violently; a tug.
WRENCH.e: From Middle English wrench, from Old English wrenċ. Compare German Rank (“plot, intrigue”).

WRETCH.d: An unhappy, unfortunate, or miserable person.
WRETCH.e: From Middle English wrecche, from Old English wreċċa (“exile, outcast”), from Proto-Germanic *wrakjô (“exile, fugitive, warrior”), from Proto-Indo-European *wreg- (“to track, follow”). Doublet of garçon.

WRIEST.d: Superlative form of WRY: Turned away, contorted (of the face or body).
WRIEST.e: From Middle English wrien, from Old English wrīġian (“to go, turn, twist, bend, strive, struggle, press forward, endeavor, venture”), from Proto-Germanic *wrigōną (“to wriggle”), from Proto-Indo-European *wreyḱ- (“to turn, wrap, tie”), from *wer- (“to turn, bend”). Compare awry, ...

WRITES.d: Plural of WRITE: To form letters or words.

WRITHE.e: From Middle English writhen, from Old English wrīþan, from Proto-West Germanic *wrīþan, from Proto-Germanic *wrīþaną (“to weave, twist, turn”), from Proto-Indo-European *wreyt- (“to twist, writhe”). Cognate with Middle Dutch writen (“to turn, twist”), dialectal German reiden (“to...

WRONGS.d: Plural of WRONG: Not correct; unjust.

WRYING.d: Present participle of WRY: Turned away, contorted (of the face or body).
WRYING.e: From Middle English wrien, from Old English wrīġian (“to go, turn, twist, bend, strive, struggle, press forward, endeavor, venture”), from Proto-Germanic *wrigōną (“to wriggle”), from Proto-Indo-European *wreyḱ- (“to turn, wrap, tie”), from *wer- (“to turn, bend”). Compare awry, ...

WURZEL.d: A rural, unsophisticated person; a bumpkin.
WURZEL.e: From German Wurzel (“root”), via mangelwurzel, a root crop cultivated for livestock feed beginning in the 18th century.

WYVERN.d: A draconian creature possessing wings, only two legs and usually a barbed tail.
WYVERN.e: Alteration of Middle English wyver (“viper”), borrowed from Old Northern French wivre, from Latin vīpera (“viper; snake, serpent”). Doublet of weever and viper.

XYLENE.d: Any of a group of three isomeric aromatic hydrocarbons, found in coal and wood tar.

XYLOSE.d: One of the pentoses, C₅H₁₀O₅, a white crystalline sugar, derived from wood.

YACKED.d: Past tense of YACK: Alternative form of yak (“chatter; talk”).

YAKKED.d: Past tense of YAK: An ox-like mammal native to the Himalayas, Mongolia, Myanmar, and Tibet with dark, long, and silky hair, a horse-like tail, and a full, bushy mane.
YAKKED.e: Borrowed from Tibetan གཡག (g.yag). See there for more.

YAKKER.d: Comparative form of YAK: An ox-like mammal native to the Himalayas, Mongolia, Myanmar, and Tibet with dark, long, and silky hair, a horse-like tail, and a full, bushy mane.
YAKKER.e: Borrowed from Tibetan གཡག (g.yag). See there for more.

YAKSHA.d: A kind of supernatural being; can be a malevolent demon or a beneficent tutelary deity.

YAKUZA.e: From Japanese やくざ (yakuza). See there for more details.

YAMMER.e: From Middle English ȝameren, ȝaumeren, yemeren, ȝomeren, from Old English ġeōmrian (“to lament”), from Proto-West Germanic *jāmarōn, from Proto-Germanic *jēmarōną (“to show misery or sadness”), from Proto-Germanic *jēmaraz (“miserable, sorrowful, sad”), from Proto-Indo-European *...

YANKED.d: Past tense of YANK: A sudden, vigorous pull (sometimes defined as mass times jerk, or rate of change of force).
YANKED.e: Attested since 1822; from Scots yank. Unknown origin.

YANTRA.d: A geometrical diagram used as a meditation aid in tantric worship.

YAPPED.d: Past tense of YAP: The high-pitched bark of a small dog, or similar.
YAPPED.e: Probably of imitative origin. Alternatively, from dialectal yap, yaup, yalp (“to yap, yelp”), from Middle English ȝælpen, variant of yelpen (“to yelp”). More at yelp.

YAPPER.d: Comparative form of YAP: The high-pitched bark of a small dog, or similar.
YAPPER.e: Probably of imitative origin. Alternatively, from dialectal yap, yaup, yalp (“to yap, yelp”), from Middle English ȝælpen, variant of yelpen (“to yelp”). More at yelp.

YARDED.d: Past tense of YARD: A small, usually uncultivated area adjoining or (now especially) within the precincts of a house or other building.
YARDED.e:
From Middle English yerd, yard, ȝerd, ȝeard, from Old English ġeard (“yard, garden, fence, enclosure”), from Proto-West Germanic *gard, from Proto-Germanic *gardaz (“enclosure, yard”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰórdʰos, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰerdʰ- (“to enclose”).
See also ...

YARNED.d: Past tense of YARN: A twisted strand of fibre used for knitting or weaving.
YARNED.e:
From Middle English yarne, ȝern, yarn, from the Old English ġearn (“yarn, spun wool”), from Proto-West Germanic *garn, from Proto-Germanic *garną (“yarn”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰorn-, *ǵʰerH- (“tharm, guts, intestines”).
Cognates
Akin to West Frisian jern, Dutch garen (“yar...

YARROW.d: Any of several pungent Eurasian and North American herbs, of the genus Achillea, used in traditional herbal medicine.
YARROW.e:
From Middle English ȝarowe, yarowe, yarwe, from Old English ġearwe, from Proto-West Germanic *garwā (“yarrow, yarrow-like herbs”), perhaps derived from *garu (“prepared, ready (of food)”), as the plant was used medicinally for digestion.
Cognate with Dutch gerw (“yarrow”) and Ger...

YAWING.d: Present participle of YAW: The rotation of an aircraft, ship, or missile about its vertical axis so as to cause the longitudinal axis of the aircraft, ship, or missile to deviate from the flight line or heading in its horizontal plane.
YAWING.e: Unknown, first attested in the mid-16th century. Perhaps related to yar (“quick, agile”), or alternatively from Old Norse jaga (“to chase, drive, move back and forth”), from Middle Low German jagen (“to hunt, chase, pursue”), from Old Saxon *jagōn, from Proto-West Germanic *jagōn...

YAWLED.d: Past tense of YAWL: A small ship's boat, usually rowed by four or six oars.
YAWLED.e: Apparently from Low German and Middle Low German jolle, or Dutch jol, possibly ultimately from a Proto-Germanic derivative of Proto-Indo-European *h₂ewlos (“tube”), see also Lithuanian aulas, Norwegian aul, Hittite [script needed] (auli-, “tube-shaped organ in the neck”), Albania...

YAWNED.d: Past tense of YAWN: To open the mouth widely and take a long, rather deep breath, often because one is tired or bored, and sometimes accompanied by pandiculation.
YAWNED.e: Partly from Middle English yanen, yonen, yenen (“to yawn”), from Old English ġeonian, ġinian (“to yawn, gape”), from Proto-West Germanic *ginōn, from Proto-Germanic *ginōną (“to yawn”); and partly from Middle English gonen (“to gape, yawn”), from Old English gānian (“to yawn, gap...

YAWPED.d: Past tense of YAWP: To yelp, or utter a sharp cry, as in intense pain, or another raucous noise.
YAWPED.e: From Middle English yolpen, of imitative origin.

YEARED.d: Past tense of YEAR: A period of time akin to the time taken for the Earth to undergo a full cycle of seasons.
YEARED.e:
From Middle English yeer, yere, from Old English ġēar (“year”), from Proto-West Germanic *jār, from Proto-Germanic *jērą (“year”), from Proto-Indo-European *yóh₁r̥ (“year, spring”). Doublet of hora and hour.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots year (“year”), North Frisian iir, Jaar, juar...

YELLED.d: Past tense of YELL: To shout; holler; make a loud sound with the voice, especially to express intense emotions such as anger or excitement.
YELLED.e: From Middle English ȝellen, yellen, from Old English ġiellan, from Proto-Germanic *gellaną. Cognate with Saterland Frisian gälje (“to yell”), Dutch gillen (“to yell”), German Low German gellen (“to yell”), German gellen (“to yell”).

YELLOW.d: The color of sunflower petals and lemons; the color obtained by mixing green and red light, or by subtracting blue from white light; the color evoked by light of wavelength around 580 nm; one of the three primary colors in subtractive color systems.
YELLOW.e:
From Middle English yelwe, yelou, from Old English ġeolwe, oblique form of Old English ġeolu, from Proto-West Germanic *gelu, from Proto-Germanic *gelwaz, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰelh₃wos, from *ǵʰelh₃- (“gleam, yellow”).
Cognate with Scots yella (“yellow”), North Frisian gööl...

YELPED.d: Past tense of YELP: An abrupt, high-pitched noise or utterance.
YELPED.e: From Middle English ȝelp, yelp, from Old English ġielp (“boasting, arrogance, pride”), from Proto-West Germanic *gelp, from Proto-Germanic *gelpą (“boasting”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰel- (“to shout”).

YENNED.d: Past tense of YEN: The unit of Japanese currency (symbol: ¥) since 1871, divided into 100 sen.
YENNED.e: From Medhurst and Hepburn’s romanizations, under the influence of earlier Portuguese romanizations, of Japanese 圓(えん) (en, “round; a round object”) as ye or yen, now 円(えん) (en), from Chinese 銀圓 /银圆 (yínyuán, “round silver object(s), especially a piece of eight”): 銀 /银 (yín, “silv...

YEOMAN.d: An official providing honorable service in a royal or high noble household, ranking between a squire and a page. Especially, a yeoman of the guard, a member of a ceremonial bodyguard to the UK monarch (not to be confused with a Yeoman Warder).
YEOMAN.e: From Middle English yoman, yeman, from Old English *ġēamann, from Proto-West Germanic *gauwjamann (compare Old Frisian gāman (“villager”), Middle High German göuman (“peasant”)), compound of Proto-West Germanic *gawi (“shire, district”) (compare Old English -ġē, -ġēa (“district, ...

YIPPED.d: Past tense of YIP: a sharp, high-pitched bark
YIPPED.e: Possibly from dialectal yip (“to cheep like a bird”), from Middle English ȝyppe, probably imitative.

YOGINI.e: Borrowed from Sanskrit योगिनी (yoginī), feminine of योगिन्.

YOGURT.d: A milk-based product stiffened by a bacterium-aided curdling process, and sometimes mixed with fruit or other flavoring.
YOGURT.e: Borrowed from Ottoman Turkish یوغورت (yoğurt). Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *yogrut.

YOKING.d: Present participle of YOKE: Senses relating to a frame around the neck.
YOKING.e:
From Middle English yok, yoke, ȝok from Old English ġeoc (“yoke”), from Proto-Germanic *juką (“yoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *yugóm (“yoke”), from *yewg- (“to join; to tie together, yoke”). Doublet of yuga, jugum, yoga and possibly yogh.
Senses 3.1 (“area of arable land”) and ...

YOLKED.d: Past tense of YOLK: The yellow, spherical part of an egg that is surrounded by the white albumen, and serves as nutriment for the growing young.
YOLKED.e: From Middle English yolke, yelke, ȝolke, ȝelke, from Old English ġeolca, ġeoloca, ġioleca (“the yellow part, yolk”), from ġeolu (“yellow”).

YONDER.d: At or in a distant but indicated place.
YONDER.e:
From Middle English yonder, yondre, ȝondre, ȝendre, from Old English ġeonre (“thither; yonder”, adverb), equivalent to yond (from ġeond, from Proto-Germanic *jainaz) + -er, as in hither, thither.
Cognate with Scots ȝondir (“yonder”), Saterland Frisian tjunder (“over there, yonder...

YOUNGS.d: Plural of YOUNG: In an early period of life.

YOUTHS.d: Plural of YOUTH: The period of being young.

YOWLED.d: Past tense of YOWL: A prolonged, loud cry, like the sound of an animal; a wail; a howl.
YOWLED.e: From Middle English youlen, goulen, from Old Norse gaula (“to low, bellow, howl, scream”), related to Icelandic gaula (“to yell, howl, roar”), Faroese geyla (“to bawl, squall, shout, yell, bellow”), Norwegian gaule (“to roar, howl, whine, weep noisily”), dialectal Swedish gjöla, ...

YUCKED.d: Past tense of YUCK: Uttered to indicate disgust usually toward an objectionable taste or odour.
YUCKED.e: Perhaps imitative. Akin to Dutch jakkes (“disgusting”). First appeared in the 1960s. Compare also Scots yeuk (“anything that disgusts”), Middle English yuke (“an itchy skin disease" akin to middle Dutch "joke" and modern Dutch "jeuk"”) .

YUKKED.d: Past tense of YUK: An exuberant laugh.
YUKKED.e: Imitative, similar to the variant yuck.

YUPPIE.d: A young upwardly mobile urban professional person with an affluent lifestyle.
YUPPIE.e: Originally an acronym for young upwardly mobile professional or young urban professional, + -ie (suffix forming noun signifying person associated with suffixed noun).

ZAGGED.d: Past tense of ZAG: One of a series of sharp turns or reversals.

ZANDER.d: A European freshwater fish in the family Percidae, closely related to the perch, Sander lucioperca.
ZANDER.e: Borrowed from German Zander, from a Slavic language, perhaps via Middle Low German sandāt. Pfeifer states that the first German attestation is East Central German czandas (in the Marienburger Treßlerbuch) circa 1400, which he derives from Pomeranian *sądač (compare Slovincian sãd...

ZANIER.d: Comparative form of ZANY: Unusual and awkward in a funny, comical manner; outlandish; clownish.
ZANIER.e: From Middle French zani, zanni, from Italian zanni (“a kind of masked clown character”), from Zanni, a dialectal form of Giovanni. Doublet of Zanni, John, and Giovanni.

ZANIES.d: Plural of ZANY: Unusual and awkward in a funny, comical manner; outlandish; clownish.
ZANIES.e: From Middle French zani, zanni, from Italian zanni (“a kind of masked clown character”), from Zanni, a dialectal form of Giovanni. Doublet of Zanni, John, and Giovanni.

ZAPPED.d: Past tense of ZAP: A sound made by a sudden release of electricity or some similar energy.

ZEALED.d: Past tense of ZEAL: The fervour or tireless devotion for a person, cause, or ideal and determination in its furtherance; diligent enthusiasm; powerful interest.
ZEALED.e: From Middle English zele, from Old French zel, from Late Latin zēlus, from Ancient Greek ζῆλος (zêlos, “zeal, jealousy”), from Proto-Indo-European *yeh₂- (“to search”). Related to jealous.

ZEALOT.d: One who is zealous, one who is full of zeal for their own specific beliefs or objectives, usually in the negative sense of being too passionate; a fanatic.
ZEALOT.e: Initially only found as Middle English zelote, an epithet of Simon the Zealot, acquiring its current senses in the 16th and 17th centuries. The Middle English derives from Latin zēlōtēs, from Ancient Greek ζηλωτής (zēlōtḗs, “emulator, zealous admirer, follower”), from ζηλόω (zēló...

ZENANA.d: Synonym of harem (“area of house or palace for high-caste women or wives of a wealthy man; the women thus kept; the system of segregating women in this way”).
ZENANA.e: From Hindi ज़नाना (zanānā), Urdu زنانه (zanānah), from Classical Persian زنانه (zanāna, “womanly”), from زن (zan, “woman”). Related to Old English cwene (“woman”). More at quean.

ZENITH.d: The point in the sky vertically above a given position or observer; the point in the celestial sphere opposite the nadir.
ZENITH.e: From Middle English cenyth, from Medieval Latin cenit, from Arabic سَمْت (samt, “direction, path”), from the fuller form سَمْت اَلرَّأْس (samt ar-raʔs, “direction of the head”). The -ni- for -m- is sometimes thought to be due to a misreading of the three strokes, which is plausib...

ZEPHYR.d: A light wind from the west.
ZEPHYR.e: From Latin zephyrus (“west wind”), from Ancient Greek Ζέφυρος (Zéphuros). Doublet of zefir, zéphire, Zephyr, and Zephyrus. The confectionery sense is a semantic loan from Russian зефи́р (zefír).

ZEROED.d: Past tense of ZERO: The cardinal number occurring before one and that denotes no quantity or amount at all, represented in Arabic numerals as 0.
ZEROED.e: Collectively borrowed from Early Modern Spanish zero, Middle French zero, and (their etymon) Old Italian zero, from Medieval Latin zēphirum, from Arabic صِفْر (ṣifr, “nothing; cipher”), itself calqued from Sanskrit शून्य (śūnyá, “void; nothingness”). Doublet of cipher and chiffre...

ZESTED.d: Past tense of ZEST: The outer skin of a citrus fruit, used as a flavouring or garnish.

ZEUGMA.d: The act of using a word, particularly an adjective or verb, to apply to more than one noun when its sense is appropriate to only one.
ZEUGMA.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek ζεῦγμα (zeûgma, “yoking; a bond, a band”), from ζεύγνυμι (zeúgnumi, “to yoke; to join”), from ζεῦγος (zeûgos, “a yoke”).

ZIGZAG.d: A line or path that proceeds by sharp turns in alternating directions.
ZIGZAG.e: Attested from 1712. Borrowed from French zigzag (attested from 1662), possibly from a Germanic source via Walloon ziczac (although German Zickzack is attested only from 1703). Also, possibly from the shape of the letter Z, which appears twice in the word. Sense “drunk” from the z...

ZILLAH.d: A female given name from Hebrew.

ZINCED.d: Past tense of ZINC: A chemical element (symbol Zn) with an atomic number of 30, a blue-silvery metal that is slightly brittle at room temperature and tarnishes slightly in moist air.
ZINCED.e: Borrowed from German Zink, related to Zinke (“point, prong”), from Middle High German zinke, from Old High German zinko (“prong, tine”), allied to zint (“a jag, point”), from Proto-Germanic *tindaz (“prong, pinnacle”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃dónts (“tooth, projection”). Cogn...

ZINGED.d: Past tense of ZING: A short high-pitched humming sound, such as that made by a bullet or vibrating string.

ZINNIA.d: A female given name from English from the flower

ZIPPED.d: Past tense of ZIP: The high-pitched sound of a small object moving rapidly through air.

ZIPPER.d: Comparative form of ZIP: The high-pitched sound of a small object moving rapidly through air.

ZIRCON.d: A mineral occurring in tetragonal crystals, usually of a brown or grey colour and consisting of silica and zirconia.
ZIRCON.e: From German Zirkon, possibly via French zircon, formed in the 1780s from Arabic زَرْقُون (zarqūn). Doublet of jargoon.

ZITHER.d: A musical instrument consisting of a flat sounding box with numerous strings placed on a horizontal surface, played with a plectrum or fingertips.
ZITHER.e: Borrowed from German Zither, from Old High German zithara, from Latin cithara, from Ancient Greek κιθάρα (kithára, “a kind of harp”). Doublet of cithara, cither, and guitar.

ZITTER.e: Uncertain origin, first attested as 1960s North American English teenagers' slang. Compare English chit (“pimple, wart”), German Zitze (“teat, nipple”).

ZODIAC.d: The belt-like region of the celestial sphere, approximately eight degrees north and south of the ecliptic, which includes the apparent path of the sun, moon, and visible planets.
ZODIAC.e: From Middle English zodiak (late 14th century), from Old French zodiaque, from Latin zōdiacus, from Ancient Greek ζῳδιακός [κύκλος] (zōidiakós [kúklos], “[circle] of little animals”), from ζῴδιον (zōídion), the diminutive of ζῷον (zōîon, “animal”).

ZOMBIE.d: A person, usually undead, animated by unnatural forces (such as magic), with no soul or will of his or her own.
ZOMBIE.e:
First attested in 1871.
From a Bantu language. Compare Kongo nzambi (“god”), zumbi (“fetish”), and Kimbundu nzumbi (“ghost”) (see Portuguese zumbi, Sranan Tongo dyumbi), and Caribbean folklore's jumbee (“a spirit or demon”).
Origin from Spanish sombra (“shadow, phantom”) has also...

ZONING.d: Present participle of ZONE: Each of the five regions of the earth's surface into which it was divided by climatic differences, namely the torrid zone (between the tropics), two temperate zones (between the tropics and the polar circles), and two frigid zones (within the polar circles).
ZONING.e: From Latin zōna, from Ancient Greek ζώνη (zṓnē, “girdle, belt”).

ZOOMED.d: Past tense of ZOOM: A humming noise from something moving very fast.
ZOOMED.e: Uncertain. The verb was first attested c. 1892, as a noun in 1918 and as an interjection in 1942. Apparently related to Scots soom (“to buzz, hum”), dialectal English and Scots soom, swoom, sweem (“to spin or twirl at high speed”). Compare also dialectal English sweem (“to swoon,...

ZOSTER.d: An ancient Greek waist-belt for men.
ZOSTER.e: From Latin zōstēr, from Ancient Greek ζωστήρ (zōstḗr).

ZYDECO.d: A form of Louisiana Creole music, characteristically performed by accordion and washboard bands, that combines Cajun and Creole roots music with elements of African American music.
ZYDECO.e: From Louisiana Creole zydéco, compare French zarico; possibly from a metanalysis of French les haricots (“beans”) as French le zarico (“beans”) in a dance-tune title.

ZYGOTE.d: A eukaryotic cell formed from the fusion of two gametes (“reproductive cells”) during a fertilization process.
ZYGOTE.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek ζῠγωτός (zŭgōtós, “yoked”) + English -ote (suffix meaning ‘having [the thing to which it is attached]’). Ζῠγωτός (Zŭgōtós) is derived from ζῠγόω (zŭgóō, “to join or yoke together”) + -τός (-tós, suffix forming adjectives of possibility); and ζ...

ZYTHUM.d: An unfermented kind of Egyptian malt beer.
ZYTHUM.e: From Latin zȳthum, from Ancient Greek ζῦθος (zûthos).
